title: Kaufman, Texas
complex: Kaufman is a city in Kaufman County, Texas, United States. <s> The population was 6,703 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Kaufman County. <s> Kaufman was founded as "Kings Fort", named after Dr. William P. King who established the fort in 1840 after purchasing 2.5 sqmi of land where the city is now located.
simple: Kaufman is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Kaufman County.

title: Celeste Yarnall
complex: Celeste Jeanne Yarnall (July 26, 1944 – October 7, 2018) was an American actress primarily of the 1960s and 1970s. <s> She started her career on television before moving to feature film roles. <s> Yarnall died in Westlake Village, California on October 7, 2018, aged 74, from ovarian cancer which she had been diagnosed with in 2014.

title: Ken Kercheval

title: Aneuploidy
complex: Aneuploidy is the presence of an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell, for example a human cell having 45 or 47 chromosomes instead of the usual 46. <s> It does not include a difference of one or more complete sets of chromosomes. <s> A cell with any number of complete chromosome sets is called a "euploid" cell. <s> An extra or missing chromosome is a common cause of genetic disorders, including some human birth defects. <s> Some cancer cells also have abnormal numbers of chromosomes. <s> Aneuploidy originates during cell division when the chromosomes do not separate properly between the two cells. <s> Most cases of aneuploidy result in miscarriage and the most common extra autosomal chromosomes among live births are 21, 18, and 13. <s> Most embryos cannot survive with a missing or extra autosome (numbered chromosome) and are spontaneously aborted. <s> The most frequent aneuploidy in humans is trisomy 16, although fetuses affected with the full version of this chromosome abnormality do not survive to term (it is possible for surviving individuals to have the mosaic form, where trisomy 16 exists in some cells but not all). <s> The most common aneuploidy that infants can survive with is trisomy 21, which is found in Down syndrome, affecting 1 in 800 births. <s> Trisomy 18 (Edwards syndrome) affects 1 in 6,000 births, and trisomy 13 (Patau syndrome) affects 1 in 10,000 births.
simple: Aneuploidy is a condition where the nucleus of a cell has one or a few chromosomes more or less than the usual number in the species. <s> It is a common cause of genetic disorders. <s> Some cancer cells also have abnormal numbers of chromosomes. <s> Aneuploidy occurs during cell division when the chromosomes do not separate properly between the two cells. <s> Aneuploidy often causes birth defects and miscarriages. <s> Among those who survive birth, Down syndrome is the most common form of aneuploidy.

title: Cachapoal Province
complex: Cachapoal Province is one of three provinces of the central Chilean region of O'Higgins (VI). <s> Its capital is the city of Rancagua (pop. <s> According to the 2002 census by the National Statistics Institute ("INE"), the province spans an area of 7384.2 sqkm and had a population of 542,901 inhabitants (271,226 men and 271,675 women), giving it a population density of 73.5 PD/sqkm . <s> It is the fifth most populated province in the country. <s> Between the 1992 and 2002 censuses, the population grew by 13.8% (65,871 persons). <s> As a province, Cachapoal is a second-level administrative division of Chile, governed by a provincial governor who is appointed by the president.
simple: Cachapoal Province is one of three provinces of the central Chilean region of Libertador General Bernardo O'Higgins (VI). <s> Its capital is the city of Rancagua. <s> s of 2002 (last national census), there were 542,901 people living in the province, giving it a population density of 73.52197936133908 /km2 inhabitants/km2. <s> As a province, Cachapoal is a second-level administrative division, consisting of 17 communes ("comunas"). <s> The province is administered by a governor.

title: Icosahedron
complex: There are infinitely many non-similar shapes of icosahedra, some of them being more symmetrical than others. <s> The best known is the (convex, non-stellated) regular icosahedron—one of the Platonic solids—whose faces are 20 equilateral triangles. <s> There are two objects, one convex and one nonconvex, that can both be called regular icosahedra. <s> Each has 30 edges and 20 equilateral triangle faces with five meeting at each of its twelve vertices. <s> Both have icosahedral symmetry. <s> The term "regular icosahedron" generally refers to the convex variety, while the nonconvex form is called a "great icosahedron". <s> The convex regular icosahedron is usually referred to simply as the "regular icosahedron", one of the five regular Platonic solids, and is represented by its Schläfli symbol {3, 5}, containing 20 triangular faces, with 5 faces meeting around each vertex. <s> Its dual polyhedron is the regular dodecahedron {5, 3} having three regular pentagonal faces around each vertex. <s> The great icosahedron is one of the four regular star Kepler-Poinsot polyhedra. <s> Its Schläfli symbol is {3, }. <s> Like the convex form, it also has 20 equilateral triangle faces, but its vertex figure is a pentagram rather than a pentagon, leading to geometrically intersecting faces. <s> The intersections of the triangles do not represent new edges. <s> Its dual polyhedron is the great stellated dodecahedron { , 3}, having three regular star pentagonal faces around each vertex. <s> Stellation is the process of extending the faces or edges of a polyhedron until they meet to form a new polyhedron. <s> It is done symmetrically so that the resulting figure retains the overall symmetry of the parent figure. <s> In their book "The Fifty-Nine Icosahedra", Coxeter et al. enumerated 58 such stellations of the regular icosahedron. <s> Of these, many have a single face in each of the 20 face planes and so are also icosahedra. <s> The great icosahedron is among them. <s> Other stellations have more than one face in each plane or form compounds of simpler polyhedra. <s> These are not strictly icosahedra, although they are often referred to as such.

title: Sol Invictus
complex: Sol Invictus ("Unconquered Sun") was the official sun god of the later Roman Empire and a patron of soldiers. <s> On 25 December AD 274, the Roman emperor Aurelian made it an official cult alongside the traditional Roman cults.
simple: Sol Invictus ("the Unconquered Sun") or, more fully, Deus Sol Invictus ("the Unconquered Sun God") was a religious title applied to at least three distinct deities during the later Roman Empire: El Gabal, Mithras, and Sol.

title: Wikipedia administrators
complex: On Wikipedia, trusted users may be appointed as administrators (also known as admins, sysops, and janitors), following a successful request for adminship. <s> As of 2019, there are administrators on the English Wikipedia. <s> Administrators have additional technical privileges compared with other editors. <s> On Wikipedia, becoming an admin is often referred to as being "given or taking up the mop", a term which has also been used elsewhere. <s> In 2006, "The New York Times" reported that administrators on Wikipedia, of whom there were then about 1,000, were "geographically diverse". <s> In July 2012, it was widely reported that Wikipedia was "running out of administrators", because in 2005 and 2006, 40 to 50 people were often appointed administrators each month, but in the first half of 2012, only nine in total were appointed. <s> However, Jimmy Wales, Wikipedia's co-founder, denied that this was a crisis or that Wikipedia was running out of admins, saying, "The number of admins has been stable for about two years, there's really nothing going on." <s> Wales had previously (in a message sent to the English Wikipedia mailing list on February 11, 2003) stated that being an admin is "not a big deal", and that "It's merely a technical matter that the powers given to sysops are not given out to everyone." <s> In his book "Wikipedia – The Missing Manual", John Broughton states that while many people think of administrators on Wikipedia as judges, that is not the purpose of the role. <s> Instead, he says, admins usually "delete pages" and "protect pages involved in edit wars". <s> While the first Wikipedia administrators were appointed by Jimmy Wales in October 2001, administrator privileges on Wikipedia are now granted through a process known as requests for adminship (RfA). <s> Any registered editor may nominate themselves, or may request another editor to do so. <s> The process has been said to be "akin to putting someone through the Supreme Court" by Andrew Lih, a scientist and professor who is himself an administrator on the English Wikipedia. <s> Lih also said, "It's pretty much a hazing ritual at this point", in contrast to how the process worked early in Wikipedia's history, when all one had to do to become an admin was "prove you weren't a bozo". <s> Candidacy for the role is normally considered only after "extensive work on the wiki". <s> While any editor may vote in an RfA, the outcome is not determined by a majority vote, but rather by whether or not consensus has been reached that the candidate would make a good administrator, a decision which can only be made by a bureaucrat, a Wikipedia editor who is also appointed by the community through a "request" process, though the process is much stricter for them than for administrators. <s> This may have been implemented as a result of RfAs attracting increasing levels of attention: Stvilia et al. quoted that "Prior to mid-2005, RfAs typically did not attract much attention. <s> Since then, it has become quite common for RfAs to attract huge numbers of RfA groupies who all support one another". <s> Once granted administrator privileges, a user has access to additional functions in order to perform certain duties. <s> These include "messy cleanup work", deletion of articles deemed unsuitable, protecting pages (restricting editing privileges to that page), and blocking the accounts of disruptive users. <s> Blocking a user must be done according to Wikipedia's policies and a reason must be stated for the block, which will be permanently logged by the software. <s> Use of this privilege to "gain editing advantages" is considered inappropriate. <s> A scientific paper by researchers from Virginia Tech and Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute found that after editors are promoted to administrator status, they often focus more on articles about controversial topics than they did before. <s> The researchers also proposed an alternative method for choosing administrators, in which more weight is given to the votes of experienced editors. <s> Another paper, presented at the 2008 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, analyzed data from all 1,551 requests for adminship from January 2006 to October 2007, with the goal of determining which (if any) of the criteria recommended in Wikipedia's "Guide to requests for adminship" page were the best predictors of whether the user in question would actually become an admin. <s> In December 2013, a similar study was published by researchers from the Polish-Japanese Institute of Information Technology in Warsaw which aimed to model the results of requests for adminship on the Polish Wikipedia using a model derived from Wikipedia's edit history. <s> They found that they could "classify the votes in the RfA procedures using this model with an accuracy level that should be sufficient to recommend candidates."

whether the user in question would actually become an admin. <s> In December 2013, a similar study was published by researchers from the Polish-Japanese Institute of Information Technology in Warsaw which aimed to model the results of requests for adminship on the Polish Wikipedia using a model derived from Wikipedia's edit history. <s> They found that they could "classify the votes in the RfA procedures using this model with an accuracy level that should be sufficient to recommend candidates."

title: Thanjavur Taluk
complex: Thanjavur is a taluk of Thanjavur district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Thanjavur, which is also the seat of the district administration. <s> It has two revenue blocks: Budalur and Thanjavur. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Thanjavur had a population of 510,411 with 253,723 males and 256,688 females. <s> There were 1012 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 78.51%. <s> Of the children less than six years of age, 23,251 were male and 21,749 were female.
simple: Thanjavur Taluk is a tehsil or taluk or administrative division of the Thanjavur district, Tamil Nadu, India. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Thanjavur, which is also the district headquarters. <s> It itself has been further divided into two revenue blocks: Budalur block and Thanjavur block. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Thanjavur had a population of 510,411 with 253,723 males and 256,688 females. <s> There were 1012 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 78.51%. <s> Of the children less than six years of age, 23,251 were male and 21,749 were female.

title: County Cavan
complex: County Cavan is a county in Ireland. <s> It is in the province of Ulster and is part of the Border Region. <s> It is named after the town of Cavan and is based on the historic Gaelic territory of East Breffny ("Bréifne"). <s> Cavan County Council is the local authority for the county, which had a population of 76,176 at the 2016 census. <s> Cavan borders six counties: Leitrim to the west, Fermanagh and Monaghan to the north, Meath to the south-east, Longford to the south-west and Westmeath to the south. <s> Cavan shares a 70 km border with County Fermanagh in Northern Ireland. <s> Cavan is the 19th largest of the 32 counties in area and the 25th largest by population. <s> The county is characterised by drumlin countryside dotted with many lakes and hills. <s> The north-western area of the county is sparsely populated and mountainous. <s> The Breifne Mountains contain the highest point, Cuilcagh, at 665 m . <s> Cavan is the source of many rivers. <s> Shannon Pot on the slopes of Cuilcagh is the source of the River Shannon, the longest river in Ireland at 386 km . <s> The River Erne is a major river which rises from Beaghy Lough, two miles (3 km) south of Stradone in Cavan and flows for 120 km to Lough Erne. <s> Other rivers in the county include the Blackwater River, which rises near Bailieborough and flows through Lough Ramor, joining the River Boyne at Navan; the Dee which springs near Bailieborough; the River Annalee which flows from Lough Sillan and joins the Erne; and the Cladagh river which rises from Cuilcagh and flows into Fermanagh. <s> The Glyde and the Owenroe also source in Cavan. <s> Cavan is known as 'The Lakeland County' and is reputed to contain 365 lakes. <s> At 18.8 km2 , Lough Sheelin is the county's largest lake; it is situated in the south of the county and forms a three way border on its waters between counties Meath, Westmeath and Cavan. <s> A large complex of lakes form in the north and west of Cavan into designated Specially Protected Areas (SPA); an example is Lough Oughter. <s> Other important wildlife protected lakes such as Lough Gowna and Lough Ramor are in the south and east of the county. <s> Cavan has a mainly hilly (drumlin) landscape and contains just under 7000 ha of forested area, 3.6% of Cavan's total land area. <s> The county contains forests such as Bellamont Forest near Cootehill, Killykeen Forest Park at Lough Oughter (a Coillte state forest concern), Dún na Rí Forest Park and the Burren Forest. <s> In medieval times, the area of Cavan was part of the petty kingdom of East Bréifne or Brefney O'Reilly after its ruling Gaelic family. <s> This in turn was a division of the 11th century Kingdom of Bréifne. <s> For this reason the county is colloquially known as the Breffni County. <s> A high degree of defence was achieved by using the natural landscape of drumlin hills and loughs. <s> The poorly drained heavy clay soils contributed as an obstacle against invasion. <s> Historically, Cavan was part of the western province of Connacht, but was transferred to Ulster in 1584 following the composition of Breifne. <s> In the south, the Lough Sheelin area was part of Leinster until the late 14th century. <s> Parts of Cavan were subjected to Norman influence from the twelfth century and the remains of several motte and bailie fortifications are still visible mainly in the east of the county, as well as the remains of stronger works such as Castlerahan and Clogh Oughter castle. <s> The influence of several monastic orders also owes its origins to around this time with abbey remains existent in locations such as Drumlane and Trinity Island. <s> The Plantation of Ulster from 1610 saw the settlement and origins of several new towns within the county that include Bailieborough, Cootehill, Killeshandra and Virginia. <s> Existing towns such as Cavan and Belturbet became over time more important as trading centres. <s> Wars during the mid-seventeenth century aimed at trying to unsettle the Plantation only led to further plantations of English and Scottish settlers into the county and the beginnings of a thriving flax and linen industry. <s> Agriculture is the largest industry in the county, especially dairy milk processing as well as pig and beef farming. <s> Much of Cavan's land consists of clay soils, which are rich in minerals, but heavy and poorly drained, making pasture farming the dominant farming system in the county. <s> There is a total farmed area of 144269 ha in the county, and there are approximately 219,568 cattle in Cavan. <s> Lakeland Dairies Group, which is based in Killeshandra and has manufacturing sites located throughout Cavan, is Ireland's second largest dairy co-operative with an annual revenue of €545 million. <s> Cavan is one of Ireland's leading counties for pig production, with the county's farms raising a fifth of the national pig herd. <s> Pig farming regulations have put pressure on the industry, which is highly dependent on affordable credit. <s> Traditionally an agricultural economy, Cavan has since expanded in other industries, chiefly quarrying, energy production and manufacturing facilities. <s> As of April 2012, Cavan produces 122.02 megawatts of wind energy. <s> The largest wind farm is at Bindoo, which produces 48 megawatts of energy. <s> Peat cutting exists in the northwest of the county, in the Cuilcagh range. <s> Major industries such as Quinn Quaries and Gypsum Industries are also important employers within the county.
simple: County Cavan (in Gaelic, ) is a county in Ireland. <s> It is part of the Border Region as it is on the border with Northern Ireland. <s> It is part of the province of Ulster. <s> It is named after the town of Cavan. <s> Cavan borders six other counties: Leitrim to the west, Fermanagh and Monaghan to the north, Meath to the south-east, Longford to the south-west and Westmeath to the south. <s> The county has a lot of countryside with many lakes and small hills called drumlins. <s> Not many people live in the north-western area of the county as there are many mountains. <s> The highest point of the county is in the Breifne mountains, mount Cuilcagh at 665 m. <s> Many rivers in Ireland start in County Cavan. <s> The Shannon Pot is the source of the River Shannon, the longest river in Ireland at 386 km. <s> The River Erne is a major river which rises from Beaghy Lough south of Stradone in Cavan and flows for 120 km to Lough Erne. <s> Cavan is known as 'The Lakeland County' and it is said it has 365 lakes, one for every day of the year. <s> At 18.8 km2, Lough Sheelin is the county's largest lake situated in the south of the county. <s> A large area of lakes in the north and west of Cavan are marked as Specially Protected Areas (SPA), example of this being Lough Oughter. <s> Other important wildlife protected lakes such as Lough Gowna and Lough Ramor are in the south and east of the county. <s> The county contains forests such as Bellamont Forest near Cootehill, Killykeen Forest Park at Lough Oughter (a Coillte state forest), Dún na Rí Forest Park and the Burren Forest. <s> In medieval times, the area of Cavan was part of East Bréifne after its ruling Gaelic family. <s> This in was a division of the 11th century Kingdom of Bréifne. <s> For this reason the county is also sometimes known as the Breffni County. <s> The natural landscape of drumlin hills and loughs made a good defence against invaders. <s> Historically, Cavan was part of the western province of Connacht, but was transferred to Ulster in 1584 when Bréifne was shired and became the county of Cavan. <s> In the south, the Lough Sheelin area was part of Leinster until the late 14th century. <s> Parts of Cavan were under Norman influence from the twelfth century. <s> The remains of several buildings from the time can still be seen at Castlerahan and Clogh Oughter castle. <s> There are also some remains of early abbeys in the county, like at Drumlane and Trinity Island. <s> The Plantation of Ulster from 1610 saw the settlement and origins of several new towns within the county like Bailieborough, Cootehill, Killeshandra and Virginia. <s> Existing towns such as Cavan and Belturbet became over time more important as trading centres. <s> Wars aimed at trying to unsettle the Plantation only led to further plantations of English and Scottish settlers into the county and the beginnings of a thriving flax and linen industry. <s> Agriculture is the largest industry in the county, especially dairy milk processing as well as pig and beef farming. <s> Much of Cavan's land is clay soils, which are rich in minerals, but heavy and poorly drained, making pasture farming the dominant farming system in the county. <s> There is a total farmed area of 144269 ha in the county, and there are approximately 219,568 cattle in Cavan. <s> Cavan has expanded in other industries, mainly quarrying, energy production and manufacturing facilities. <s> Peat cutting exists in the northwest of the county, in the Cuilcagh range.

title: Immanuel Church, Norrköping
complex: The Immanuel Church is a church building in Norrköping, Sweden. <s> Belonging to the Uniting Church in Sweden, it earlier belonged to the Mission Covenant Church of Sweden. <s> It was opened on 28 December 1884.
simple: The Immanuel Church is a church building in Norrköping, Sweden. <s> It belongs to the Uniting Church in Sweden. <s> It earlier belonged to the Mission Covenant Church of Sweden. <s> It was opened on 28 December 1884.

title: Ninigi-no-Mikoto
complex: Ninigi-no-Mikoto (Japanese: 瓊瓊杵尊 ) , also known as Ame-nigishi-kuni-nigishi-amatsuhiko-hiko-ho-no-ninigi-no-Mikoto (天邇岐志国邇岐志天津日高日子番能邇邇芸命 ) , is in Japanese mythology, the son of Ame no Oshihomimi no Mikoto (天忍穗耳尊 ) and Takuhadachiji-hime no Mikoto (栲幡千千姫命 ) , and grandson of Amaterasu, who sent him down to earth ("Tenson kōrin") to plant rice there. <s> He was the great-grandfather of Emperor Jimmu. <s> His wife was Konohanasakuya-hime. <s> Amaterasu sent him to pacify Japan by bringing the three celestial gifts used by the Emperor: the sword Kusanagi, the mirror Yata no Kagami, and the jewel Yasakani no Magatama. <s> These three gifts signify that the Emperor is the descendant of Amaterasu herself. <s> The account of Ninigi being sent to earth appears in the "Nihon Shoki".
simple: He was the great-grandfather of Emperor Jimmu. <s> Amaterasu sent him to bring peace to Japan by bringing the three gifts from Heaven used by the emperor. <s> The sword, Kusanagi, the mirror, Yata no kagami, and the jewel, Yasakani no magatama. <s> These three gifts mean to the world that the emperor is the descendant of Amaterasu herself. <s> The tale of Ninigi no Mikoto being sent to earth is told in the Nihon Shoki.

title: Carrie (2013 film)
complex: Carrie is a 2013 American supernatural horror film directed by Kimberly Peirce, and is the third film adaptation (the others were in 1976 and 2002) of Stephen King's 1974 novel of the same name. <s> The film was produced by Kevin Misher, with a screenplay by Lawrence D. Cohen and Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa. <s> The film stars Chloë Grace Moretz as the titular character Carrie White, alongside Julianne Moore as Margaret White. <s> The cast also features Judy Greer, Portia Doubleday, Gabriella Wilde, Ansel Elgort and Alex Russell.
simple: Carrie is an American teen horror movie. <s> Moore plays Carrie's mother Margaret White in this 2013 adaptation. <s> Starring in this are Chloë Grace Moretz, Julianne Moore and Judy Greer; Moretz plays Carrie White.

title: Nick Buoniconti
complex: Nicholas Anthony Buoniconti (December 15, 1940 – July 30, 2019) was an American professional football player who was a middle linebacker in the American Football League (AFL) and National Football League (NFL). <s> He played for the Boston Patriots and Miami Dolphins, winning two Super Bowls with the Dolphins. <s> Buoniconti was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Buoniconti died on July 30, 2019, in Bridgehampton, New York, at the age of 78.
simple: Nicholas Anthony Buoniconti (December 15, 1940 – July 30, 2019) was an American professional football player. <s> He was a middle linebacker in the American Football League (AFL) and National Football League (NFL). <s> He played for the Boston Patriots and Miami Dolphins. <s> He won two Super Bowls with the Dolphins. <s> Buoniconti was added into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Buoniconti died on July 30, 2019, in Bridgehampton, New York, at the age of 78.

title: Ben Smith (ice hockey, born 1988)
complex: Benjamin Alexander Smith (born July 11, 1988) is an American professional ice hockey player currently playing for Adler Mannheim in the Deutsche Eishockey Liga (DEL). <s> He previously played in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the Chicago Blackhawks, San Jose Sharks, Toronto Maple Leafs and the Colorado Avalanche. <s> Smith graduated from Westminster School in 2006 and played four seasons at Boston College. <s> While playing for Boston College, Smith was drafted by the Chicago Blackhawks 169th overall in the sixth round of the 2008 NHL Entry Draft. <s> On October 29, 2010 the Blackhawks recalled Smith from the AHL's Rockford IceHogs to make his NHL debut in a home game against the Edmonton Oilers. <s> He scored his first NHL goal on April 8, 2011 against Jimmy Howard of the Detroit Red Wings. <s> On April 15, 2011, Smith scored 2 goals against the Vancouver Canucks in a 4–3 loss in only his second NHL playoff game. <s> On Sunday, April 24, 2011, during Game 6 of the Western Conference quarterfinals, Smith scored the overtime goal on a rebound against the Vancouver Canucks' goaltender, Roberto Luongo, to force a Game 7 in Vancouver after the Canucks had previously been leading the series 3–0. <s> The Blackhawks ended up losing Game 7 in overtime. <s> On June 17, 2013, Smith was called up to play his first Stanley Cup Finals game, a 2–0 loss to the Boston Bruins, to fill in over the injured Marián Hossa. <s> The Blackhawks won the Cup on June 24, 2013, when they defeated the Bruins in Game 6. <s> On June 27, 2014, the Blackhawks signed him to a two-year contract extension. <s> In the following season, Smith scored four goals in 19 playoff games to help the Blackhawks advance to the Western Conference finals. <s> On March 2, 2015, Smith was traded by the Blackhawks to the San Jose Sharks in exchange for Andrew Desjardins. <s> He scored his first goal with the Sharks the same day in their shutout game against the Montreal Canadiens, but remained for most of the season with the Sharks' AHL affiliate San Jose Barracuda.
simple: Ben Smith (born July 11, 1988) is an American professional ice hockey right winger. <s> He currently plays for the San Jose Sharks of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> He has also played for the Chicago Blackhawks. <s> He has also played ice hockey in college at Boston College with the Eagles. <s> He made his NHL debut with the Blackhawks on October 29, 2010 against the Edmonton Oilers. <s> He scored 2 goals on April 15, 2011 against the Vancouver Canucks in his second NHL playoff game. <s> On April 24, 2011, Smith scored the overtime goal on a rebound by Niklas Hjalmarsson against the Vancouver Canucks' goaltender, Roberto Luongo, to force a Game 7 in Vancouver. <s> On June 24, 2013, He won the Stanley Cup with the Blackhawks after they defeated the Boston Bruins 4 games to 2 in the 2013 Stanley Cup Finals. <s> On March 2, 2015, the Blackhawks traded Smith to the San Jose Sharks in exchange for Andrew Desjardins.

title: 916 America
complex: 916 America is a minor planet orbiting the Sun in the main belt between Mars and Jupiter. <s> It was discovered on 7 August 1915 by the Russian astronomer Grigory Nikolaevich Neujmin at Simeis, Russian Empire. <s> Originally designated 916I, it was renamed '916 America' on 24 February 1923 after the Council of Astronomers at Pulkovo Observatory decided to commemorate "the friendly relations of the astronomical observatories and astronomers". <s> Another possible reason for the name was as a mark of appreciation for the help given during the 1921 Russian famine by the American Relief Administration under the later President Herbert Hoover. <s> In 1986, assuming that the asteroid was of S-type and that it had a diameter of 15 km, the rotational period was measured to be 38 hours. <s> Observations by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite have since shown that it has a diameter of 33.2±1.3 km, with an absolute magnitude of 11.20 and an albedo of 0.053±0.004.
simple: 916 America is a minor planet that is orbiting the Sun in the main belt between Mars and Jupiter. <s> It was discovered on 7 August 1915 by the Soviet astronomer Grigory Nikolaevich Neujmin at Simeis, Ukraine. <s> It was originally called 916I, but was renamed "916 America" on 24 February 1923 after the Council of Astronomers at Pulkovo Observatory decided to pay tribute to "the friendly relations of the astronomical observatories and astronomers". <s> Another possible reason for the name was as a mark of thankfulness for the help given during the famine in Crimea by the American Relief Administration under President Herbert Hoover. <s> In 1986, believing that the asteroid was of S-type and that it had a diameter of 15 km, the length of 916 America's day was thought to be 38 hours. <s> Observations by the Infrared Astronomical Satellite have since shown that it has a diameter of 33.2±1.3 km, with an absolute magnitude of 11.20 and an albedo (the extent to which it reflects light) of 0.053±0.004.

title: Pak Hon-yong
complex: Pak Hon-yong (Hangul: 박헌영, Hanja:朴憲永, 28 May 1900 – 18 December 1955 ) was a Korean independence activist, politician, philosopher and Communist activist. <s> One of the main leaders of the Korean communist movement during Japan's colonial rule (1910–45). <s> His nickname was Ijong (이정) and Ichun (이춘), his courtesy name being Togyong (덕영). <s> In September 1948, while keeping his role as secretary of the Workers' Party of South Korea, he became Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister of North Korea.
simple: Pak Hon-Yong (: ; : , May 28, 1900 - December 5, 1956) was a Korean independence activist, politician, thinker, Communist, and leader of the Korean Chosen Communist Party. <s> He served in North Korea as the Foreign Minister and Vice Prime Minister, August 1948 to 1953.

title: Cook County, Minnesota
complex: Cook County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> Around 1.8 million visitors travel to Cook County each year. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 5,176, making it the fifth-least populous county in Minnesota. <s> Its county seat is Grand Marais. <s> The Grand Portage Indian Reservation is entirely within the county.
simple: Cook County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> As of 2010, 5,176 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Grand Marais.

title: Black Friday (Lil' Kim mixtape)
complex: Black Friday is the second mixtape by American rapper Lil' Kim, released on February 14, 2011 through PayPal. <s> The title track is a response to Nicki Minaj's song "Roman's Revenge". <s> The mixtape also contains the track "Grindin' Makin' Money", a collaboration which features rappers Birdman and Nicki Minaj, which Kim claims ignited the feud between her and Minaj, as well as another diss song towards Minaj titled "Pissin' on 'Em".
simple: Black Friday is the second mixtape by American rapper Lil' Kim, released on February 14, 2011. <s> The title track also is a diss song aimed at Minaj as Kim imitates Minaj talking about Kim on her song "Roman's Revenge" in an interview.

title: Division of Warringah
complex: The Division of Warringah is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> The division is named after the Warringah area of Sydney, which itself is named by an Aboriginal Australian word which translates into English as "rain", "waves" or "sea". <s> The Division was proclaimed at the redistribution of 13 September 1922, and was first contested at the 1922 federal election. <s> Centred on Mosman and the Northern Beaches region of Sydney, it covers most of the land between Middle Harbour and the Tasman Sea. <s> It extends from Port Jackson in the south to the suburb of Dee Why in the north. <s> It includes the suburbs of Allambie, Allambie Heights, Balgowlah, Balgowlah Heights, Balmoral, Beauty Point, Brookvale, Clifton Gardens, Clontarf, Cremorne Point, Curl Curl, Fairlight, Freshwater, Killarney Heights, Kurraba Point, Manly, Manly Vale, Mosman, North Balgowlah, North Curl Curl, North Head, North Manly, Queenscliff, Seaforth, and Wingala; as well as parts of Beacon Hill, Cremorne, Dee Why, Forestville, Frenchs Forest, Narraweena, and Neutral Bay.
simple: The Division of Warringah is a Federal Electoral Division for the Australian House of Representatives in the state of New South Wales. <s> The Division was named after the Warringah area of Sydney. <s> This is an Aboriginal Australian word which means "rain", "waves" or "sea". <s> The Division was created on 13 September 1922, for the 1922 Federal election. <s> It is located in the Northern Beaches region of Sydney. <s> It covers most of the land between Middle Harbour and the Pacific Ocean. <s> It extends from Port Jackson in the south to the suburb of Dee Why in the north. <s> It includes the suburbs of Mosman, Balgowlah, Manly, Brookvale, Beacon Hill and Forestville.

title: Meulles
complex: Meulles is a former commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into the new commune of Livarot-Pays-d'Auge.
simple: Meulles is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Luís de Camões
complex: Luís Vaz de Camões (] ; sometimes rendered in English as Camoens or Camoëns, e.g. by Byron in "English Bards and Scotch Reviewers", ; c. 1524 or 1525 – 20 June O.S. 10 June 1580 ) is considered Portugal's and the Portuguese language's greatest poet. <s> His mastery of verse has been compared to that of Shakespeare, Vondel, Homer, Virgil and Dante. <s> He wrote a considerable amount of lyrical poetry and drama but is best remembered for his epic work "Os Lusíadas" ("The Lusiads"). <s> His collection of poetry "The Parnasum of Luís de Camões" was lost in his lifetime. <s> The influence of his masterpiece "Os Lusíadas" is so profound that Portuguese is sometimes called the "language of Camões".
simple: Luís Vaz de Camões (c. 1524 – June 10, 1580) was Portugal's greatest poet. <s> He has been compared to Homer, Virgil, Dante, Cervantes or Shakespeare. <s> He wrote lyrical poetry (in Portuguese and in Spanish) and drama but is best remembered for his epic work "Os Lusíadas". <s> (His philosophical work "The Parnasum of Luís Vaz" was lost, stolen with part of "Os Lusíadas" by envious enemies while he was staying at Mozambique.)

title: J. B. S. Haldane
complex: John Burdon Sanderson Haldane ( ; 5 November 18921 December 1964) was a British-Indian scientist known for his work in the study of physiology, genetics, evolutionary biology, and mathematics. <s> He made innovative contributions to the fields of statistics and biostatistics. <s> Between 1919 and 1922 he was a Fellow of New College, Oxford, where he researched physiology and genetics. <s> He then moved to the University of Cambridge, where he accepted a readership in Biochemistry and taught until 1932. <s> From 1927 until 1937 he was also Head of Genetical Research at the John Innes Horticultural Institution. <s> During his nine years at Cambridge, Haldane worked on enzymes and genetics, particularly the mathematical side of genetics. <s> He was the Fullerian Professor of Physiology at the Royal Institution from 1930 to 1932 and in 1933 he became full Professor of Genetics at University College London, where he spent most of his academic career. <s> Four years later he became the first Weldon Professor of Biometry at University College London. <s> In 1956, Haldane left University College London, and joined the Indian Statistical Institute (ISI) in Kolkata, India, where he headed the biometry unit. <s> Officially he stated that he left the UK because of the Suez Crisis, writing: "Finally, I am going to India because I consider that recent acts of the British Government have been violations of international law." <s> He believed that the warm climate would do him good, and that India shared his socialist dreams. <s> The university had sacked his wife Helen for excessive drinking and refusing to pay a fine, triggering Haldane's resignation. <s> He declared he would no longer wear socks, "Sixty years in socks is enough." <s> and always dressed in Indian attire. <s> He was one of the three major figures to develop the mathematical theory of population genetics, along with Ronald Fisher and Sewall Wright. <s> He thus played an important role in the modern evolutionary synthesis of the early 20th century. <s> He re-established natural selection as the central mechanism of evolution by explaining it as a mathematical consequence of Mendelian inheritance.
simple: John Burdon Sanderson Haldane FRS (3 November 1892 – 1 December 1964), known as Jack (but who used 'J.B.S.' in his printed works), was a British geneticist and evolutionary biologist who emigrated to India towards the end of his life. <s> Between 1919 and 1922 he was a Fellow of New College, Oxford University, then moved to Cambridge University, where he accepted a Readership in Biochemistry at Trinity College and taught there until 1932. <s> During his nine years at Cambridge, Haldane worked on enzymes and genetics, particularly the mathematical side of genetics. <s> He then accepted a position as Professor of Genetics and moved to University College London where he spent most of his academic career. <s> Four years later he became the first Weldon Professor of Biometry at University College London. <s> Haldane's move to India, initially to the Indian Statistical Institute (ISI) was influenced by a number of factors. <s> Officially he stated that his chief political reason was in response to the Suez Crisis. <s> He wrote: "Finally, I am going to India because I consider that recent acts of the British Government have been violations of international law." <s> His interest in India was also because of his interest in biological research, belief that the warm climate would do him good and that India offered him freedom and shared socialist dreams. <s> He was one of the founders (along with Ronald Fisher and Sewall Wright) of population genetics. <s> His major professional work was his contribution of mathematical papers on the theory of evolution, which assisted the modern evolutionary synthesis.

title: Trenton, Kentucky
complex: Trenton is a city in Todd County, Kentucky, United States. <s> The population was 384 at the 2010 census.
simple: Trenton is a city of Kentucky in the United States. <s> It is in Todd County.

title: Narita Airport Terminal 1 Station
complex: Narita Airport Terminal 1 (Narita Airport) Station (成田空港駅 , Narita Kūkō eki ) is an underground train station located beneath Terminal 1 of Narita International Airport in Narita, Chiba, Japan. <s> The station is shared between East Japan Railway Company (JR East) and the private railway operator Keisei Electric Railway.
simple: Narita Airport Station (成田空港駅, Narita Kūkō eki) is a train station of East Japan Railway Company(JR East) and Keisei Electric Railway. <s> It is in Narita, Chiba Prefecture, Japan. <s> This station is the main access point of Narita International Airport.

title: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961
complex: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961 was a scheduled flight serving the route Addis Ababa–Nairobi–Brazzaville–Lagos–Abidjan. <s> On 23 November 1996, the aircraft serving the flight, a Boeing 767-200ER, was hijacked en route from Addis Ababa to Nairobi by three Ethiopians seeking asylum in Australia. <s> The plane crash-landed in the Indian Ocean near Grande Comore, Comoros Islands, due to fuel exhaustion; 125 of the 175 passengers and crew on board, including the three hijackers, died. <s> The crash was captured on video. <s> Of the 175 passengers and crew members, 125 were killed, including the three hijackers. <s> According to the accident report, all six surviving crew members and 38 passengers received serious injuries, two passengers received minor injuries, and four passengers received no injuries.
simple: Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961 was a domestic passenger flight from Addis Ababa to Nairobi, with stopovers at Brazzaville, Lagos, and Abidjan. <s> On November 23, 1996 the Boeing 767 was hijacked by three Ethiopians that were seeking asylum in Australia. <s> However the plane ran out of fuel, and crash-landed in the Indian Ocean near the Comoros Islands. <s> Of the 175 occupants on-board 125 people including the hijackers were killed, and 50 people survived.

title: Bara Subdivision
complex: Bara Subdivision is a subdivision located in Khyber District, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan. <s> In the 2000s, Bara achieved some mention in worldwide media with the founding of Lashkar-e-Islam, founded in the area by Mufti Munir Shakir, and later passed to Mangal Bagh, a local driver.
simple: Bara is a tehsil in Khyber Agency, Federally Administered Tribal Areas, Pakistan. <s> In the 2000s, Bara achieved some mention in worldwide media with the founding of Lashkar-e-Islam, founded in the area by Mufti Munir Shakir, and later passed to Mangal Bagh, a local driver.

title: Pete Geren
complex: Preston Murdoch Geren, III, known as Pete Geren (born January 29, 1952) served as the 20th United States Secretary of the Army from July 16, 2007 to September 16, 2009. <s> He is a Democratic former member of the United States House of Representatives from Texas's 12th congressional district. <s> He is currently president of the Sid W. Richardson Foundation in Fort Worth, Texas and chair of the Institute for Defense Analyses in Alexandria, Virginia. <s> On July 29, 2005, Bush appointed Geren the acting United States Secretary of the Air Force, a position he served in until the confirmation of his successor Michael Wynne in November 2005.
simple: Preston M. Geren, III (born January 29, 1952 in Fort Worth, Texas) was the 20th United States Secretary of the Army from 16 July 2007 to 16 September 2009. <s> Geren was also a member of the United States House of Representatives from Texas. <s> He had already been acting United States Secretary of the Air Force, between 29 July 2005 and position he served in until the confirmation of his successor Michael Wynne on 4 November 2005.

title: Going Solo
complex: Going Solo is a book by Roald Dahl, first published by Jonathan Cape in London in 1986. <s> It is a continuation of his autobiography describing his childhood, "Boy" and detailed his travel to Africa and exploits as a World War II pilot.
simple: Going Solo is a non-fiction book by Roald Dahl.

title: Wild Orchid (film)
complex: Wild Orchid is a 1989 American erotic film directed by Zalman King and starring Mickey Rourke, Carré Otis, Jacqueline Bisset, Bruce Greenwood, and Assumpta Serna. <s> The film was shot in Salvador, Bahia, and Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. <s> King's original version of the film was deemed too sexually graphic for an R-rating and the MPAA threatened to release it with an X-rating, limiting its commercial potential. <s> King reluctantly removed part of a love scene between Otis and Rourke to comply with the R-rating. <s> The scene was widely rumored in the media to have shown the two actors—who had become romantically involved during production of the film—actually having intercourse.
simple: Wild Orchid is an 1989 erotic suspense movie. <s> It was directed by Zalman King. <s> The movie stars Mickey Rourke, Carré Otis, Jacqueline Bisset, Bruce Greenwood, Oleg Vidov and Assumpta Serna. <s> The first version of the movie was too sexual for an R rating. <s> The MPAA threatened give the movie an X rating. <s> King edited the movie down to get the R rating.

title: Deaths in June 2018
complex: The following is a list of notable deaths in June 2018.
simple: The following is a list of deaths that should be noted in June 2018.

title: Dress shirt
complex: In the UK, the term "dress shirt" is reserved for a particular type of formal shirt. <s> There are formal day shirts for wearing with morning dress, and the white dress shirts used as eveningwear.
simple: In England, this is a term for a shirt that is worn with a tuxedo.

title: Trannyshack
complex: Trannyshack is a monthly drag club that takes place at DNA Lounge in San Francisco. <s> It was started by drag queen Heklina in 1996 as an offshoot of Klubstitute, and was a weekly fixture at The Stud bar in San Francisco for 12 years, drawing large crowds on a regular basis. <s> The Tuesday night performances at The Stud ended on 12 August 2008, with Trannyshack resuming as a monthly event at DNA Lounge in March 2010. <s> The Trannyshack stage has hosted celebrities including Lady Gaga, Gwen Stefani, RuPaul, Charo, Michelle Visage, Mary Wilson and many of the contestants from "RuPaul's Drag Race" among others. <s> In the early years of the club, Ana Matronic of the Scissor Sisters lived in San Francisco and performed frequently at Trannyshack before moving to New York in 1999. <s> Trannyshack also holds the annual Trannyshack Reno bus trip.
simple: Trannyshack is a San Francisco drag club started by drag queen Heklina, and takes place at The Stud Bar. <s> This club has hosted many celebrities from Mary Wilson of the Supremes to Charo, RuPaul, Gwen Stefani, Alaska Thunderfuck, Lady Bunny, and more. <s> At one time, Ana Matronic of the Scissor Sisters lived in San Francisco, where she performed at Trannyshack and was the first and only female to reach the finals of the Miss Trannyshack pageant.

title: Keita Goto (footballer)
complex: Keita Goto (後藤 圭太, born 8 September 1986) is a Japanese football player. <s> He plays for Fagiano Okayama.
simple: Keita Goto (born 8 September 1986) is a Japanese football player. <s> He plays for Fagiano Okayama.

title: Yoram Globus
complex: Yoram Globus (Hebrew: יורם גלובוס ; born 7 September 1943) is an American-Israeli film producer, cinema owner, and distributor. <s> He is most known for his association with The Cannon Group, Inc., an American film production company, which he co-owned with his cousin Menahem Golan.
simple: Yoram Globus (born 21 October 1943), is an Israeli movie producer. <s> He is most famous for his association with Cannon Films Inc., a company he ran with his cousin Menahem Golan.

title: Diene
complex: In organic chemistry a diene (diolefin or alkadiene) is a covalent compound that contains two double bonds, usually among carbon atoms. <s> They thus contain two alk"ene" units, with the standard prefix "di" of systematic nomenclature. <s> As a subunit of more complex molecules, dienes occur in naturally occurring and synthetic chemicals and are used in organic synthesis. <s> Conjugated dienes are widely used as monomers in the polymer industry. <s> Polyunsaturated fats are of interest to nutrition. <s> Compounds that contain more than two double bonds are called polyenes. <s> Polyenes and dienes share many properties. <s> An important reaction for conjugated dienes is the Diels–Alder reaction. <s> Many specialized dienes have been developed to exploit this reactivity for the synthesis of natural products (e.g., Danishefsky's diene).
simple: In organic chemistry, a diene or diolefin is a hydrocarbon that contains two carbon pi bonds. <s> Dienes occur occasionally in nature but are widely used in the polymer industry. <s> Compounds that contain more than two double bonds are called polyenes. <s> Polyenes and dienes, share many of their properties. <s> An important reaction for conjugated dienes is the Diels–Alder reaction. <s> Many specialized dienes have been developed to exploit this reactivity for the synthesis of natural products, e.g. Danishefsky’s diene.

title: Write Anywhere File Layout
complex: The Write Anywhere File Layout (WAFL) is a proprietary file system that supports large, high-performance RAID arrays, quick restarts without lengthy consistency checks in the event of a crash or power failure, and growing the filesystems size quickly. <s> It was designed by NetApp for use in its storage appliances like NetApp FAS, AFF, Cloud Volumes ONTAP and ONTAP Select.
simple: Write Anywhere File Layout (WAFL) is a file system.

title: The Battle for Wesnoth
complex: The Battle for Wesnoth is a turn-based strategy video game with a fantasy setting, designed by Australian developer David White and first released in June 2003. <s> In "Wesnoth", the player attempts to build a powerful army by controlling villages and defeating enemies for experience. <s> The game is loosely based on the Sega Genesis games "Master of Monsters" and "Warsong". <s> "The Battle for Wesnoth" is free software, available under the GPLv2 license in source form and for a variety of computer operating systems. <s> The game is programmed in C++. <s> It is cross-platform, and runs on AmigaOS 4, BeOS, FreeBSD, Linux (including OS flavors running on GP2X and Nokia n800, n810, and n900 handheld devices), OS X/Darwin, Windows, MorphOS, NetBSD, OpenBSD, RISC OS, iOS, Solaris/illumos, Android, Playbook and Google Native Client running under Google Chrome. <s> Even when not counting this community content, the list of contributors to the official version of the game as displayed in-game contains over 550 unique entries (May 2010). <s> Developers of the game also include well-known authors from the free software and open source scene, like the co-founder of the Open Source Initiative and core Linux kernel developer Eric S. Raymond, or Linux kernel programmer Rusty Russell. <s> As of April 2010, The Battle for Wesnoth is available in about 50 languages, 9 of which have more than 90% of messages translated. <s> The first development release of "Wesnoth" 0.1 happened on June 18, 2003. <s> In October 2005, the game reached its 1.0 milestone release. <s> On January 29, 2012, version 1.10 was released. <s> On May 2, 2018, version 1.14.0 was released.
simple: The Battle for Wesnoth (or just Wesnoth) is a strategy video game. <s> It is designed by David White and the first released was made in June 2003. <s> The game is available under the GPL license. <s> The game is programmed in C++. <s> It is cross-platform and runs on AmigaOS 4, BeOS, FreeBSD, Linux, Mac OS X, Microsoft Windows, MorphOS, NetBSD, OpenBSD, RISC OS, iOS, Solaris and Android. <s> Some developers are well-known authors of other free and open-source projects. <s> The game is translated in more than 50 languages. <s> In 10 of them, the game is very well translated (These languages have more than 95% of messages translated). <s> The 1.14.5 version is the last release and was made the 18 September 2018.

title: Natural history
complex: Natural history is a domain of inquiry involving organisms including animals, fungi and plants in their environment; leaning more towards observational than experimental methods of study. <s> A person who studies natural history is called a naturalist or natural historian. <s> Definitions from biologists often focus on the scientific study of individual organisms in their environment, as seen in this definition by Marston Bates: "Natural history is the study of animals and Plants – of organisms.
simple: Natural history is the study of plants and animals in the wild, and the environments they live in. <s> People who study natural history are called naturalists. <s> "Naturalist" is short for "natural historian".

title: Militia
complex: Beginning in the late 20th century, some militias (in particular officially recognized and sanctioned militias of a government) act as professional forces, while still being "part-time" or "on-call" organizations. <s> For instance, the members of some U.S. Army National Guard units are considered professional soldiers, as they are trained to maintain the same standards as their "full-time" (active duty) counterparts.
simple: At the beginning in the late 20th century, some militias acted as professional forces, while still being "part-time" or "on-call" organizations.

title: Snape, Suffolk
complex: Snape is a small village in the English county of Suffolk, on the River Alde close to Aldeburgh. <s> It has about 600 inhabitants, measured at 611 at the 2011 Census.
simple: Snape is a village and civil parish in Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England.

title: Finger
complex: A finger is a limb of the human body and a type of digit, an organ of manipulation and found in the hands of humans and other primates. <s> Normally humans have five digits, the bones of which are termed phalanges, on each hand, although some people have more or fewer than five due to congenital disorders such as polydactyly or oligodactyly, or accidental or medical amputations. <s> The first digit is the thumb, followed by index finger, middle finger, ring finger, and little finger or pinkie. <s> According to different definitions, the thumb can be called a finger, or not. <s> The palm has five bones known as metacarpal bones, one to each of the five digits. <s> Human hands contain fourteen digital bones, also called phalanges, or phalanx bones: two in the thumb (the thumb has no middle phalanx) and three in each of the four fingers. <s> These are the distal phalanx, carrying the nail, the middle phalanx, and the proximal phalanx.
simple: A finger is a type of digit attached to the hand. <s> Our type of fingers are similar to those of other primates. <s> Humans have five digits, the bones of which are termed phalanges. <s> The first digit is the thumb, followed by the index finger, middle finger, ring finger, and little finger or 'pinky'. <s> According to different definitions, the thumb can be called a finger, or not. <s> The four fingers have three phalanges each; the thumb has two.

title: Muhammad Habibur Rahman
complex: Muhammad Habibur Rahman (3 December 1928 – 11 January 2014) was a Chief Justice of Bangladesh Supreme Court in 1995. <s> He was the Chief Adviser of the 1996 caretaker government which oversaw the Seventh parliamentary elections in Bangladesh. <s> A language activist and advocate of the Bengali language, he wrote extensively and published eight books on the subject. <s> He played a significant role to implement Bengali in the Supreme Court of Bangladesh. <s> He wrote "Jathashabdo" (1974), the first thesaurus in the Bengali language. <s> Rahman was awarded Bangla Academy Literary Award in 1984 and Ekushey Padak in 2007 by the Government of Bangladesh. <s> He served as a Fellow of Bangla Academy, Asiatic Society of Bangladesh and Worcester College, Oxford. <s> Rahman began his career as a lecturer in history of Dhaka University in 1952. <s> Later he joined Rajshahi University where he subsequently held the office of Dean of the Faculty of Law (1961) and of Reader in History (1962–64). <s> He changed his profession in 1964 when he took to law and joined the Dhaka High Court Bar. <s> In his legal career, he held the offices of Assistant Advocate General (1969), Vice President of High Court Bar Association (1972) and member of Bangladesh bar council(1972). <s> Rahman was an author of seventy books in Bengali on law, language, literature, poetry and religion and five books in English, including two books of verse. <s> Law of Requisition (1966), Rabindra Prabandhey Sanjna O Parthakya Bichar (1968), Jatha-sabda (1974), Matri-bhashar Sapakshey Rabindranath (1983), Qur'an-sutra (1984), Bachan O Prabachan (1985), Gangariddhi thekey Bangladesh (1985), Rabindra Rachanar Rabindra-byaksha (1986), Rabindra-kabyey Art, Sangeet O Sahitya (1986), Koran-shorif Sorol Banganubad, On Rights and Remedies, Amara ki Jabo-na Tader Kachhey Jara Shudhu Banglai Katha Baley (1996). <s> On 11 January 2014, at the age of 85, Rahman died at United Hospital, Gulshan, Dhaka.
simple: Muhammad Habibur Rahman (December 3, 1928 – January 11, 2014) was a Bangladeshi politician and jurist. <s> Justice Habibur Rahman retired from service as the Chief Justice of Bangladesh in 1995. <s> He was also the first Chief Advisor of the Caretaker Government of Bangladesh for a month in 1996. <s> Justice Rahman was conferred a Bangla Academy award for his contribution to literature in 1984 and the Ekushey Padak in 2007. <s> He is a fellow of the Asiatic Society of Bangladesh; Fellow of the Bangla Academy; Honorary Bencher, Lincoln's Inn. <s> Habibur Rahman began his career as a temporary Lecturer in History of Dhaka University on May 1, 1952. <s> Later he joined Rajshahi University where he subsequently held the office of Dean of the Faculty of Law (1961) and of Reader in History (1962-64). <s> Habibur Rahman changed his profession in 1964 when he took to law and joined the Dhaka High Court Bar. <s> In his legal career he held the offices of Assistant Advocate General (1969), Vice President of High Court Bar Association (1972) (now Supreme Court Bar Association) and member of Bangladesh Bar Council (1972). <s> Some of his literary and other noted publications are as follows: Law of Requisition (1966), রবীন্দ্র প্রবন্ধেসঞ্জনা ও পার্থক্য বিচার (Rabindra Prabandhey Sanjna O Parthakya Bichar) (1968), যথা-শব্দ (Jatha-sabda) (1974), মাতৃভাষার স্বপক্ষেরবীন্দ্রনাথ (Matri-bhashar Sapakshey Rabindranath) (1983), কোরআন সূত্র (Qoran-sutra) (1984), বচন ও প্রবাচন (Bachan O Prabachan) (1985), গঙ্গারিদ্ধী থেকে বাংলাদেশ (Gangariddhi thekey Bangladesh) (1985), রবীন্দ্র রচনার রবীন্দ্র ব্যাখ্যা (Rabindra Rachanar Rabindra-byaksha) (1986), রবীন্দ্র কাব্যে, শীল্পে, সঙ্গীত ও সাহিত্যে(Rabindra- kabyey Art, Sangeet O Sahitya) (1986), On Rights and Remedies, আমরা কি যাবো না তাদের কাছে যারা শুধু বাঙলায় কথা বলে (Amara ki Jabo-na Tader Kachhey Jara Shudhu Banglai Katha Baley) (1996). <s> On 11 January 2014, doctors declared him dead on arrival at United Hospital,Dhaka at the age of 84.

title: Yaakov Neeman
complex: Yaakov Neeman ( , 16 September 1939 – 1 January 2017) was an Israeli lawyer who also served as Minister of Justice and Minister of Finance. <s> Neeman was born to a religious Zionist family in Tel Aviv during the Mandate era. <s> He was educated at the Midrashiat Noam high-school yeshiva and completed his military service in the Golani Brigade.
simple: Yaakov Neeman (‎ , 16 September 1939 – 1 January 2017) was an Israeli lawyer and academic. <s> He was born in Tel Aviv.

title: Óscar López (footballer, born 1980)
complex: Óscar López Hernández (born 11 May 1980) is a Spanish retired footballer. <s> A defender, he played in all the back-four positions (mainly left back).
simple: Óscar López Hernández (born 11 May 1980) is a Spanish football player.

title: Second Epistle to Timothy
complex: In the New Testament, the Second Epistle of Paul to Timothy, usually referred to simply as Second Timothy and often written 2 Timothy or II Timothy, is one of the three pastoral epistles traditionally attributed to Paul the Apostle. <s> The three epistles are called "pastoral" because they relate to the conduct of church leaders, thought of as pastors (literally shepherds).
simple: This book is believed to a letter from the Apostle Paul to Timothy.

title: Pieve Ligure
complex: Pieve Ligure ( , locally ) is a "comune" (municipality) in the Metropolitan City of Genoa in the Italian region Liguria, located about 13 km southeast of Genoa.
simple: Pieve Ligure is an Italian town in the region of Liguria in the province of Genoa in Italy.

title: Ellen Muth
complex: Ellen Muth (born March 6, 1981) is an American actress, known for her role as Georgia "George" Lass in Showtime's series "Dead Like Me". <s> Muth was born in Milford, Connecticut, the daughter of Rachel and Erich Muth. <s> After a brief stint as a model with Ford Models and Rascal's Agency, Muth pursued a career in acting, studying at the Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute in New York City, and getting her first professional experience doing commercials in 1993.
simple: Ellen Muth (born March 6, 1981) is an American actress. <s> Muth was born in Milford, Connecticut.

title: Cumberland, Maine
complex: Cumberland is a town in Cumberland County, Maine, United States. <s> The population was 7,211 at the 2010 census. <s> It is part of the Portland–South Portland–Biddeford, Maine Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> Cumberland is one of the wealthiest municipalities in the state.
simple: Cumberland is a town in Cumberland County, Maine, United States. <s> The population was 7,211 at the 2010 census. <s> It is part of the Portland–South Portland–Biddeford, Maine Metropolitan Statistical Area.

title: Grumman F6F Hellcat
complex: The Grumman F6F Hellcat is an American carrier-based fighter aircraft of World War II. <s> Designed to replace the earlier F4F Wildcat and to counter the Japanese Mitsubishi A6M Zero, it was the United States Navy's dominant fighter in the second half of the Pacific War.
simple: The F6F Hellcat was a United States Navy fighter aircraft made by Grumman during World War II.

title: Dole, Jura
complex: Dole was the capital of Franche-Comté until Louis XIV conquered the region; he shifted the "parlement" from Dole to Besançon. <s> The university, founded by Duke Philippe le Bon of Burgundy in 1422, was also transferred to Besançon at that time.
simple: It was the capital of the Free County until Louis XIV conquered the region, which from then on became Besançon.

title: Fatima Bhutto
complex: Fatima Bhutto ( ; born 29 May 1982) is a Pakistani writer. <s> Born in Kabul, she is daughter of Murtaza Bhutto, niece of former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and granddaughter of former Pakistani Prime Minister Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto. <s> She is a critic of her aunt Benazir Bhutto and her husband Asif Ali Zardari, whom she accused of being involved in her father's murder.
simple: Fatima Bhutto (born 1982) is a young Pakistani poet and writer. <s> She is the niece of former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and grand-daughter of former Prime Minister Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto.

title: Hocquinghen
complex: Hocquinghen is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Hocquinghen is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Judd Nelson
complex: Judd Asher Nelson (born November 28, 1959) is an American actor best known for his roles as John Bender in "The Breakfast Club", Alec Newbary in "St. Elmo's Fire", Hot Rod / Rodimus Prime in "" and "", Joe Hunt in "Billionaire Boys Club", Nick Peretti in "New Jack City", Billy Beretti in "Empire", and Jack Richmond in the television series "Suddenly Susan".
simple: Judd Asher Nelson (born November 28, 1959) is an American actor, screenwriter, and producer. <s> He is best known for his roles as John Bender in "The Breakfast Club", Alec Newbary in "St. Elmo's Fire", Hot Rod and Rodimus Prime in "" and Jack Richmond in "Suddenly Susan".

title: Odia language
complex: Odia ( ; formerly romanized as Oriya) is an Indo-Aryan language spoken in the Indian state of Odisha.
simple: Odia (ଓଡ଼ିଆ oṛiā), formerly known as Oriya, is an Indian Dravidian language, mainly spoken in the Indian state of Odisha.

title: Banner County, Nebraska
complex: Banner County is a county in the western part of the state of Nebraska in the Great Plains region of the United States. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, its population was 690. <s> Its county seat is the unincorporated community of Harrisburg; there are no incorporated municipalities within the county. <s> When Nebraska became a state in 1867, a single county encompassed the entire Panhandle. <s> In 1870, the Panhandle's southern half was organized as Cheyenne County. <s> The arrival of increasing numbers of settlers led to the partitioning of the county in 1888: the eastern third became Deuel County; the middle third became present-day Cheyenne County; and the western third became Kimball, Scotts Bluff, and Banner Counties. <s> The last of these was named by citizens who declared it would become the state's "banner county", and "the brightest star in the constellation of Nebraska counties".
simple: Banner County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, 690 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Harrisburg. <s> It was founded in 1888.

title: Hultsfred Municipality
complex: Hultsfred Municipality ("Hultsfreds kommun") is a municipality in Kalmar County, in south-eastern Sweden. <s> The seat is in the town of Hultsfred.
simple: Hultsfred Municipality is a municipality in Kalmar County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Hultsfred.

title: Archduchess Maria Maddalena of Austria
complex: Maria Maddalena of Austria (Maria Magdalena; 7 October 1589 – 1 November 1631) was Grand Duchess of Tuscany from the accession of her husband, Cosimo II, in 1609 until his death in 1621. <s> With him, she had eight children, including a duchess of Parma, a grand duke of Tuscany, and an archduchess of Further Austria. <s> Born in Graz, she was the youngest daughter of Charles II, Archduke of Inner Austria, and his wife Maria Anna of Bavaria. <s> During the minority of her son, Grand Duke Ferdinando, she and her mother-in-law acted as regents from 1621 to 1628. <s> She died on 1 November 1631 in Passau.
simple: Maria Magdalena of Austria or Maria Maddalena of Austria (7 October 1589 – 1 November 1631) was Grand Duchess of Tuscany from her husband's accession in 1609 until his death in 1621. <s> With him, she had eight children, including a duchess of Parma, a grand duke of Tuscany, and an archduchess of Further Austria. <s> She was the youngest daughter of Charles II, Archduke of Inner Austria, and his wife Maria Anna of Bavaria. <s> During the minority of her son, Grand Duke Ferdinando II, she and her mother-in-law Christina of Lorraine acted as regents.

title: Rheda-Wiedenbrück
complex: Rheda-Wiedenbrück is a town in the district of Gütersloh, in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.
simple: Rheda-Wiedenbrück is a town in the district of Gütersloh, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.

title: Lesse
complex: The Lesse is a river in the Ardennes, in the Walloon region of Belgium. <s> It is a right tributary to the river Meuse. <s> The source of the Lesse is near Libramont-Chevigny, in the Belgian province of Luxembourg. <s> The Lesse flows roughly in north-western direction. <s> Near Han-sur-Lesse (municipality of Rochefort) the entire river goes underground, flowing through limestone caves. <s> Many of the caves along the banks of the Lesse are important archaeological sites; these include the Trou de Chaleux (by the Cirque de Chaleux), and the Trou des Nutons and Trou du Frontal at Furfooz. <s> The Lesse flows into the river Meuse in the village of Anseremme, municipality of Dinant. <s> Towns along the Lesse are Daverdisse, Han-sur-Lesse, Houyet and Anseremme.
simple: The Lesse (Walloon: Aiwe di Lesse) is a river in the Ardennes, in the Walloon region of Belgium. <s> It is a right tributary to the river Meuse. <s> Its source is near Libramont-Chevigny, in the Belgian province of Luxembourg. <s> It flows roughly in a northwestern direction. <s> Near Han-sur-Lesse (commune of Rochefort), by the "Gouffre de Belvaux", the entire river goes underground, flowing through limestone caves. <s> Many of the caves along the banks of the Lesse are important archaeological sites - these include the Trou de Chaleux (by the Cirque de Chaleux), and the Trou des Nutons and Trou du Frontal at Furfooz. <s> The Lesse flows into the river Meuse in the town of Anseremme, commune of Dinant, Namur province.

title: David H. Gambrell
complex: David Henry Gambrell (born December 20, 1929) is an American attorney who represented Georgia in the United States Senate from 1971 through 1972.
simple: David Henry Gambrell (born December 20, 1929) is a American politician. <s> Gambrell served in the United States Senate representing Georgia from 1971 through 1972.

title: Freshly-Picked Tingle's Rosy Rupeeland
complex: Freshly-Picked Tingle's Rosy Rupeeland is an adventure video game developed by Vanpool and published by Nintendo for the Nintendo DS handheld game console. <s> It was first released in Japan, and was released in Europe on September 14, 2007, a year after its Japanese release.
simple: Freshly-Picked Tingle's Rosy Rupeeland (もぎたてチンクルのばら色ルッピーランド, Mogitate Chinkuru no Barairo Ruppīrando) is an action role-playing video game made by Vanpool for the Nintendo DS game console.

title: Georgetown, Guyana
complex: Georgetown is a city and the capital of Guyana, located in Region 4, which is also known as the Demerara-Mahaica region. <s> It is the country's largest urban centre. <s> It is situated on the Atlantic Ocean coast at the mouth of the Demerara River and it was nicknamed the 'Garden City of the Caribbean.'
simple: Georgetown is the capital city of Guyana. <s> It is located in the Demerara-Mahaica region. <s> It is the country's largest city.

title: Caitlin
complex: Caitlin (pronounced ] ) is a female given name of Irish origin. <s> It is the Irish version of the Old French name "Cateline" ] , which comes from Catherine, which in turn comes from the Ancient Greek Αἰκατερίνη (Aikaterine).
simple: Caitlin is a female given name. <s> The name is of Irish origin.

title: Samuel W. Kinnaird
complex: Samuel W. Kinnaird (May 2, 1840 – April 20, 1923) was a Union Navy sailor in the American Civil War and a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the Medal of Honor, for his actions at the Battle of Mobile Bay. <s> Born on May 2, 1840, in New York City, Kinnaird was still living in the state of New York when he joined the Navy. <s> He served during the Civil War as a landsman on the . <s> At the Battle of Mobile Bay on August 5, 1864, "Lackawanna" engaged the at close range and Kinnaird displayed "presence of mind and cheerfulness" which helped maintain his shipmates' morale. <s> For this action, he was awarded the Medal of Honor four months later, on December 31, 1864. <s> Kinnaird's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Served as a landsman on board the U.S.S. "Lackawanna" during successful attacks against Fort Morgan, rebel gunboats and the ram "Tennessee" in Mobile Bay, 5 August 1864. <s> Showing a presence of mind and cheerfulness that had much to do with maintaining the crew's morale, Kinnaird served gallantly through the action which resulted in the capture of the prize rebel ram "Tennessee" and in the destruction of batteries at Fort Morgan. <s> Kinnaird died on April 20, 1923, at age 82 and was buried in the New York City neighborhood of Woodside, Queens.
simple: Samuel W. Kinnaird (May 2, 1840 – April 20, 1923) was a Union Navy sailor in the American Civil War. <s> He was a recipient of the U.S. military's highest decoration, the Medal of Honor. <s> He got it for his actions at the Battle of Mobile Bay. <s> He was born on May 2, 1840, in New York City. <s> Kinnaird was still living in the state of New York when he joined the Navy. <s> He served during the Civil War as a landsman on the . <s> At the Battle of Mobile Bay on August 5, 1864, "Lackawanna" engaged the . <s> They fought at close range and Kinnaird displayed "presence of mind and cheerfulness" which helped maintain his shipmates' morale. <s> For this action, he was presented the Medal of Honor four months later on December 31, 1864. <s> Kinnaird's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Served as a landsman on board the U.S.S. "Lackawanna" during successful attacks against Fort Morgan, rebel gunboats and the ram "Tennessee" in Mobile Bay, 5 August 1864. <s> Showing a presence of mind and cheerfulness that had much to do with maintaining the crew's morale, Kinnaird served gallantly through the action which resulted in the capture of the prize rebel ram "Tennessee" and in the destruction of batteries at Fort Morgan. <s> Kinnaird died on April 20, 1923. <s> He was 82 and was buried in the New York City neighborhood of Woodside, Queens.

title: Waterloo Wind Farm
complex: Waterloo wind farm is east of Manoora, South Australia. <s> It is the largest wind farm operated by EnergyAustralia. <s> The wind farm is positioned along a rocky north-south ridge on privately owned property at Waterloo. <s> The 111 megawatt wind farm spreads across five acres of land and cost about $350 million, it began construction in November, 2008 and has been operational since October 2010. <s> Each wind turbine produces on average 24 megawatt hours of power each day. <s> On a windy day three wind turbines can power the whole of Clare and the whole wind farm can power up to 163,000 homes or 5 to 10% of South Australia.
simple: Waterloo Wind Farm is based east of Manoora, South Australia. <s> It is the largest wind farm operated by EnergyAustralia. <s> The 111 megawatt wind farm spreads across five acres of land and cost about $350 million, it began construction in November, 2008 and has been operational since October 2010. <s> On a windy day three wind turbines can power the whole of Clare and the whole wind farm can power up to 163,000 homes or 5 to 10% of South Australia.

title: Paul Eisler
complex: Paul Eisler (1907 – 26 October 1992, London) was an Austrian inventor born in Vienna. <s> Among his innovations were the printed circuit board. <s> In 2012, "Printed Circuit Design & Fab" magazine named its Hall of Fame after Eisler. <s> He graduated in engineering from Vienna University of Technology in 1930. <s> Being Jewish, antisemitic German-Nationalist organizations prevented him from getting an engineering job in Vienna, so he obtained employment with the English recording technology firm (Gramaphone Company, EMI from March 1931) operating under its His Master's Voice brand in Belgrade. <s> His task there was to eliminate radio interference on the music broadcast system on trains running from Belgrade to Niś. <s> The project was a technical success but a financial failure because the Serbian railroad could only pay HMV by barter in grain, not pounds sterling, due a foreign exchange crisis.
simple: Paul Eisler (1907 - 26 October 1992) was an Austrian inventor. <s> Eisler was born in Vienna, Austria. <s> He invented the modern circuit board. <s> He invented the modern circuit board. <s> He was a student at Vienna University of Technology. <s> German nationalists would not let Eisler get a job in Vienna, because he was Jewish. <s> He got a job with an English company (Gramaphone Company, EMI from March 1931). <s> He removed interference from music broadcast on trains.

title: Space Shuttle Columbia disaster
complex: On February 1, 2003, the "Columbia" disintegrated during atmospheric entry, killing all seven crew members. <s> The disaster was the second fatal accident in the Space Shuttle program, after "Challenger" , which broke apart 73 seconds after liftoff and killed the seven-member crew in 1986.
simple: The Space Shuttle Columbia disaster occurred when "Columbia" broke up when it was reentering the atmosphere on February 1, 2003.

title: Albert (given name)
complex: Albert is a masculine given name. <s> It is derived from the Germanic "Adalbert", containing the words "adal" ("noble") and "beraht" ("bright"). <s> It is also less commonly in use as a surname.
simple: The name Albert is a masculine given name. <s> It comes from the Germanic words "adal" and "beraht", meaning "bright" and "noble".

title: Dnieper
complex: The Dnieper is one of the major rivers of Europe, rising in the Valdai Hills near Smolensk, Russia, before flowing through Belarus and Ukraine to the Black Sea. <s> It is the longest river of Ukraine and Belarus and the fourth-longest river in Europe. <s> The total length is approximately 2200 km with a drainage basin of 504000 km2 . <s> Historically, the river was an important barrier, dividing Ukraine into right and left banks. <s> Nowadays, the river is noted for its dams and hydroelectric stations. <s> The Dnieper is an important navigable waterway for the economy of Ukraine and is connected via the Dnieper–Bug Canal to other waterways in Europe. <s> In antiquity, the river was known to the Greeks as the Borysthenes and was part of the Amber Road. <s> The total length of the river is variously given as 2145 km or 2201 km , of which 485 km are within Russia, 700 km are within Belarus, and 1095 km are within Ukraine. <s> Its basin covers 504000 km2 , of which 289000 km2 are within Ukraine, 118360 km2 are within Belarus. <s> The river is part of the quagga mussel's native range. <s> The mussel has been accidentally introduced around the world where it has become an invasive species.
simple: The Dnieper River is one of the major rivers in Europe. <s> It flows from Russia, through Belarus and Ukraine, to the Black Sea. <s> It is fourth largest by length in Europe. <s> In antiquity, it was known to the Greeks as the Borysthenes. <s> 485 km is in Russia, 595 km is in Belarus, and 1095 km is in Ukraine. <s> Its basin covers 504000 km2. <s> 289000 km2 is in Ukraine. <s> The river is part of the Quagga mussel's native range.
