title: Chemnitzer Land
complex: Chemnitzer Land is a former district in the Free State of Saxony, Germany. <s> It was bounded by (from the north and clockwise) the district of Mittweida, the city of Chemnitz, the districts of Stollberg and Zwickauer Land and the state of Thuringia (district Altenburger Land). <s> The history of the region is largely influenced by the neighbouring cities of Chemnitz and Zwickau. <s> In medieval times the town of Glauchau, today the capital of the district, was the centre of the county of Schönburg-Glauchau. <s> The East German government attempted to turn the region into a huge industrial complex, which is the reason for the dense population. <s> The district was established in 1994 by merging the former districts of Glauchau and Hohenstein-Ernstthal. <s> In August 2008, as a part of the district reform in Saxony, the districts of Zwickauer Land, Chemnitzer Land and the urban district Zwickau were merged into the new district Zwickau.
simple: Chemnitzer Land is a district in the Free State of Saxony, Germany. <s> The district has a very big population because the East German government tried to make the area very industrial. <s> The district was created in 1994 by joining the old districts of Glauchau and Hohenstein-Ernstthal. <s> In 2008, part of city of Zwickau will become part of the district.

title: Nin'an
complex: Nin'an (仁安 ) , also known as Ninnan, was a Japanese era name (年号, , "nengō", , lit. <s> "year name") after "Eiman" and before "Kaō." <s> This period spanned the years from August 1166 through April 1169. <s> The reigning emperors were Rokujō"-tennō" (六条天皇 ) and Takakura"-tennō" (高倉天皇 ) .
simple: Nin'an (仁安), also known as Ninnan, was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Eiman" and before "Kaō." <s> This period started in August 1166 ended in April 1169. <s> The reigning emperors were Rokujō"-tennō" (六条天皇) and Takakura"-tennō" (高倉天皇).

title: The Ark (Swedish band)
complex: The Ark was a Swedish glam rock band formed in 1991 by Mikael Jepson (better known as "Jepson") and Lasse ("Leari") Ljungberg, Ola Salo and Leari being only fourteen years old at the time. <s> In 1996 The Ark released an EP featuring four songs, of those "Racing With The Rabbits" being the most known.
simple: The Ark was a rock band from Rottne in Sweden, active between 1991 and 2011.

title: Livery company
complex: The livery companies of the City of London, currently 110 in number, comprise London's ancient and modern trade associations and guilds, almost all of which are styled the 'Worshipful Company of...' their respective craft, trade or profession. <s> London's livery companies play a significant part in City life, not least by providing charitable-giving and networking opportunities. <s> Liverymen retain voting rights for the senior civic offices, such as the Lord Mayor, Sheriffs and City of London Corporation, its ancient municipal authority with extensive local government powers. <s> Most livery companies still maintain contacts with their original trade, craft or professional roles. <s> Some still exercise powers of regulation, inspection and enforcement, while others are awarding bodies for professional qualifications. <s> The Scriveners' Company admits senior members of legal and associated professions, the Apothecaries' Company awards post-graduate qualifications in some medical specialties, and the Hackney Carriage Drivers' Company comprises licensed taxi drivers who have passed the "Knowledge of London" test. <s> Several companies restrict membership only to those holding relevant professional qualifications, "eg." <s> the City of London Solicitors' Company and the Worshipful Company of Engineers. <s> Other companies, whose trade died out long ago, such as the Longbow Makers' Company, have evolved into being primarily charitable foundations. <s> In 1515, the Court of Aldermen of the City of London settled an order of precedence for the 48 livery companies then in existence, based on those companies' contemporary economic or political power. <s> The 12 highest-ranked companies remain known as the Great Twelve City Livery Companies. <s> Today there are 110 City livery companies, all post-1515 companies being ranked by seniority of creation. <s> The Merchant Taylors and the Skinners have long disputed their precedence, so once a year (at Easter) they swap between sixth and seventh places. <s> This mix-up is a favourite theory for the origin of the phrase "at sixes and sevens", as has been pointed out by at least one Master Merchant Taylor; however, it is possible that the phrase may have been coined before these two companies (Taylors and Skinners) resolved their dispute, which arose from their both receiving Charters in 1327 with no proof surviving as to which was granted first. <s> Neither the "Company of Parish Clerks" nor the "Company of Watermen" have applied or intend to apply for livery status, which remains a long-standing City tradition. <s> This is granted by the City Corporation in effect to control a company.
simple: The City of London Livery Companies began as trade associations or trade guilds, which controlled who could carry out certain jobs in the City of London. <s> Some still have a statutory role. <s> The order of precedence was first set down in 1515 by the Aldermen of the City of London. <s> The list was based on the companies' economic or political power. <s> The first twelve livery companies are known as the "Great Twelve City Livery Companies". <s> There are now 108 livery companies, some very new, so the Order of Precedence is sometimes reviewed. <s> The Merchant Taylors and the Skinners have always disputed their precedence, so once a year (at Easter) they exchange sixth and seventh place. <s> This is one of the theories for the origin of the phrase "at sixes and sevens", as the master of the Merchant Taylors has said a number of times, although the first use of the phrase may have been before the Taylors and the Skinners decided to alternate their position. <s> Two old companies do not intend applying for a grant of the right to wear the special costume or uniform known as a livery. <s> Three groups intend applying for livery.

title: Saint-Pont
complex: Saint-Pont is a commune in the Allier department in Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes in central France. <s> The poet Alain Borne (1915–1962), winner of the 1954 Prix Antonin-Artaud was born in Saint-Pont.
simple: Saint-Pont is a commune. <s> It is found in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: S/2004 S 6
complex: S/2004 S 6 is the provisional designation of a dusty object seen orbiting Saturn very close to the F ring. <s> It is not clear whether it is only a transient clump of dust, or if there is a solid moonlet at its core. <s> It was first seen by scientists in images taken by the Cassini-Huygens probe on October 28, 2004 and announced on November 8 that year. <s> It appears to be the best tracked object in this region with at least five probable sightings in the period to late 2005. <s> In comparison, two objects in the F ring's vicinity (S/2004 S 3 and S/2004 S 4 ) that were first seen several months earlier have not been recovered with any confidence. <s> Nevertheless, it continues to be unclear whether there is a solid core to S/2004 S 6 or whether it is just a transient dust clump that will dissipate on a timescale of years or months. <s> Notably, an imaging sequence covering an entire orbital period at 4 km resolution taken on November 15, 2004 (soon after S/2004 S 6 's discovery) failed to recover the object, while it has been seen again later. <s> The lighting conditions in S/2004 S 6 's part of the orbit were different during these two observations, however, with the discovery being made when the region was strongly backlit by the sun. <s> A suggested resolution of the absence in November is that S/2004 S 6 's visibility is primarily due to a diffuse cloud of fine dust that is much brighter in forward scattered light (the conditions of the discovery image), and that the solid core (if any) is small. <s> S/2004 S 6 has been seen both inside and outside the main F ring, and its orbit must cross the ring. <s> Careful calculations show that the object periodically plows through the ring material, coming within 1.5 km of the densest core e.g. on 9 April 2005. <s> It has been suggested that a spiral structure in the tenuous material surrounding the F ring may have been a consequence of this. <s> The dusty halo seen in images is sizeable, being around 2000 km in lengthwise extent. <s> The solid object, if any, would be no greater than 3–5 km in diameter based on brightness.
simple: S/2004 S 6 is the designation of a dusty object seen orbiting Saturn very close to the F ring. <s> It is not clear whether it is only a clump of dust, or if there is a solid small moon at its core. <s> It was first seen by scientists in pictures taken by the Cassini-Huygens probe on October 28, 2004, and announced on 8 November that year. <s> It appears to be the best tracked object in this area with at least five possible sightings in the period till late 2005. <s> In comparison, two objects in the F ring's area (S/2004 S 3 and S/2004 S 4) that were first seen months earlier have not been found again with any confidence. <s> Nevertheless, it continues to be unclear whether there is a solid core to S/2004 S 6 or whether it is just a dust clump that will disappear in years or months. <s> Notably, an imaging sequence covering an entire orbital period at 4 km resolution taken on 15 November, 2004 (soon after S/2004 S 6's discovery) failed to find the object, while it has been seen again later. <s> The lighting conditions in S/2004 S 6's part of the orbit were different during these two sightings, however, with the discovery being made when the area was strongly backlit by the sun. <s> A suggested resolution of the absence in November is that S/2004 S 6's visibility is primarily due to a diffuse cloud of fine dust that is much brighter in forward scattered light (the conditions of the discovery image), and that the solid core (if any) is small. <s> S/2004 S 6 has been seen both inside and outside the main F ring, and its orbit must cross the ring. <s> Careful calculations show that the object periodically plows through the ring material, coming within 1.5 km of the densest core e.g. on 9 April, 2005. <s> It has been suggested that a spiral structure in the thinnest material around the F ring may have been a result of this. <s> The dusty halo seen in pictures is big, being around 2000 km in lengthwise extent. <s> The solid object, if any, would be no bigger than 3−5 km in diameter based on brightness.

title: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement
complex: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement ( ; , "Chăvash Surăm yal tărăkhĕ") is an administrative and municipal division (a rural settlement) of Alikovsky District of the Chuvash Republic, Russia. <s> It is located in the eastern part of the district. <s> Its administrative center is the rural locality (a "selo") of Chuvashskaya Sorma. <s> Rural settlement's population: 1,758 (2006 est.). <s> Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement comprises sixteen rural localities. <s> The Cheboksary–Yadrin highway crosses the territory of the rural settlement.
simple: Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement or Chuvash-Sorma Rural Settlement (; , "Chăvash Surăm yal tărăkhĕ") is an administrative and municipal division (a rural settlement) of Alikovsky District of the Chuvash Republic, Russia. <s> It is located in the eastern part of the district. <s> Its administrative center is the locality (a "selo") of Chuvashskaya Sorma. <s> Rural settlement's population: 1,758 (2006 est.). <s> Chuvashsko-Sorminskoye Rural Settlement comprises sixteen rural localities. <s> The Cheboksary–Yadrin highway crosses the territory of the rural settlement.

title: A
complex: A (named , plural "As", "A's", "a"s, "a's" or "aes" ) is the first letter and the first vowel of the modern English alphabet and the ISO basic Latin alphabet. <s> It is similar to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives. <s> The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar. <s> The lowercase version can be written in two forms: the double-storey a and single-storey ɑ. <s> The latter is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type. <s> The earliest certain ancestor of "A" is aleph (also written 'aleph), the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet, which consisted entirely of consonants (for that reason, it is also called an abjad to distinguish it from a true alphabet). <s> In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended. <s> By 1600 BC, the Phoenician alphabet letter had a linear form that served as the base for some later forms. <s> Its name is thought to have corresponded closely to the Paleo-Hebrew or Arabic aleph. <s> When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter to represent the glottal stop—the consonant sound that the letter denoted in Phoenician and other Semitic languages, and that was the first phoneme of the Phoenician pronunciation of the letter—so they used their version of the sign to represent the vowel /a/ , and called it by the similar name of alpha. <s> In the earliest Greek inscriptions after the Greek Dark Ages, dating to the 8th century BC, the letter rests upon its side, but in the Greek alphabet of later times it generally resembles the modern capital letter, although many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set. <s> The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to their civilization in the Italian Peninsula and left the letter unchanged. <s> The Romans later adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write the Latin language, and the resulting letter was preserved in the Latin alphabet that would come to be used to write many languages, including English. <s> In algebra, the letter "a" along with other letters at the beginning of the alphabet is used to represent known quantities, whereas the letters at the end of the alphabet ("x", "y", "z") are used to denote unknown quantities. <s> In geometry, capital A, B, C etc. are used to denote segments, lines, rays, etc. <s> A capital A is also typically used as one of the letters to represent an angle in a triangle, the lowercase a representing the side opposite angle A.
simple: A is the first letter of the English alphabet. <s> The same letter of the Greek alphabet is named alpha. <s> The earliest letter 'A' has appeared was in the Phoenician alphabet's aleph. <s> The Greeks later modified this letter and used it as their letter alpha. <s> The Greek alphabet was used by the Etruscans in northern Italy, and the Romans later modified the Etruscan alphabet for their own language. <s> In algebra, the letter "A" along with other letters at the beginning of the alphabet is used to represent known quantities. <s> In geometry, capital A, B, C etc. are used to label line segments, lines, etc. <s> Also, A is typically used as one of the letters to label an angle in a triangle.

complex: Salmonella enterica (formerly Salmonella choleraesuis) is a rod-shaped, flagellate, facultative aerobic, Gram-negative bacterium and a species of the genus "Salmonella". <s> A number of its serovars are serious human pathogens.
simple: Salmonella enterica is a rod-shaped bacterium. <s> It is a member of the genus "Salmonella".

title: French Stewart
complex: Milton French-Stewart (born February 20, 1964), known professionally as French Stewart, is an American actor and dancer, known for his role as Harry Solomon on the 1990s sitcom "3rd Rock from the Sun" and for his role as Chef Rudy on the sitcom "Mom".
simple: Milton French-Stewart (born February 20, 1964), known professionally as French Stewart, is an American actor and comedian. <s> He is best known for his role as Harry Solomon on the 1990s sitcom "3rd Rock from the Sun" and for his role as Chef Rudy on the sitcom "Mom".

title: 70 Virginis b
complex: 70 Virginis b (abbreviated 70 Vir b) is an extrasolar planet approximately 60 light-years away in the constellation of Virgo. <s> Announced in 1996 by Geoffrey Marcy and R. Paul Butler, 70 Virginis was one of the first stars confirmed to have planets orbiting it. <s> When first announced, 70 Virginis b was considered to be within its star's habitable zone (preferably in the "Goldilocks zone"), but it was later confirmed that the planet has an eccentric orbit, closer to its parent. <s> 70 Virginis b is a gas giant extrasolar planet that is 7.5 times the mass of Jupiter and is in an eccentric 116-day orbit about its host. <s> Its surface gravity is expected to be about six to eight times that of Jupiter's. <s> At the time of discovery in January 1996, it was believed that the star was only 29 ly away resulting in the star being less luminous based on its apparent magnitude. <s> As a result, the planet's orbit was thought to be in the habitable zone and the planet was nicknamed Goldilocks (not too cold or too hot). <s> The Hipparcos satellite later showed that the star was more distant from Earth and therefore brighter resulting in the planet being too hot to be in the habitable zone.
simple: 70 Virginis b is an extrasolar planet that is around 60 light-years away from the Earth in the constellation of Virgo. <s> The finding of this planet was announced in 1996 by astronomers Geoffrey Marcy and R. Paul Butler. <s> 70 Virginis was one of the first stars that was known to have planets orbiting it. <s> When first announced, 70 Virginis b was thought to be inside its star's habitable zone, but proof was later found that the planet has an eccentric orbit, closer to its parent. <s> 70 Virginis b is a Jupiter-type extrasolar planet that orbits around 70 Virginis every 116 days. <s> It has 7.5 times the mass of Jupiter. <s> Its surface gravity is thought to be about two to three times that of Jupiter's. <s> At the time that it was found in January 1996, it was thought that the star was only 29 light years away from the Earth. <s> As a result, the planet's orbit was thought to be in the habitable zone and the planet was given the nickname "Goldilocks" (not too cold or too hot). <s> The Hipparcos satellite later showed that the star was farther away from 70 Virginis and therefore its brightness was a result of the planet being too hot to be in the habitable zone.

title: Dennison, Minnesota
complex: Dennison is a city in Goodhue and Rice counties in the U.S. state of Minnesota. <s> The population was 212 at the 2010 census. <s> Most of Dennison is in Goodhue County, with only a small part that extends into Rice County.
simple: Dennison is a city in Goodhue County and Rice County, Minnesota. <s> It has a population of 212 residents in 2010. <s> Most of it is in Goodhue.

title: Charles Ranhofer
complex: Charles Ranhofer (November 7, 1836 in Saint-Denis, France – October 9, 1899 in New York) was the chef at Delmonico's Restaurant in New York from 1862 to 1876 and 1879 to 1896. <s> Ranhofer was the author of "The Epicurean" (1894), an encyclopedic cookbook of over 1,000 pages, similar in scope to Escoffier's "Le Guide Culinaire". <s> Ranhofer was sent to Paris at the age of 12 to begin his training by studying pastry-making, and at 16 became the private chef for the prince d'Hénin, comte d'Alsace. <s> In 1856 he moved to New York to become the chef for the Russian consul, and later worked in Washington, D.C. and New Orleans. <s> He returned to France in 1860 for a short time, where he arranged balls for the court of Napoleon III at the Tuileries Palace, but then came back to New York to work at what was then a fashionable location, "Maison Dorée". <s> In 1862, Lorenzo Delmonico hired him for Delmonico's, and it was there that Ranhofer made his real fame, though others say that he made the fame of the restaurant as well. <s> At that time, Delmonico's was considered the finest restaurant in the United States. <s> He was the chef at Delmonico's until his retirement in 1896, except for a short hiatus from 1876 to 1879 when he owned the Hotel American at Enghien-les-Bains. <s> Ranhofer is credited (often on slim evidence) with inventing or making famous a number of dishes that Delmonico's was known for, such as Lobster Newberg, and had a talent for naming dishes after famous or prominent people—particularly those who dined at Delmonico's—as well as his friends, and events of the day. <s> Examples include: Others may be found under List of foods named after people. <s> Ranhofer did not invent baked Alaska, nor do the menus he provides in "The Epicurean" mention anything similar, not even his own Alaska-Florida (the term he himself used for his similar dessert). <s> He also experimented with new foods, acquainting New Yorkers with the "alligator pear" (avocado) in 1895, among other things. <s> Ranhofer and his wife Rose had five children: three sons and two daughters. <s> He died at home of Bright's Disease in 1899 and was buried at Woodlawn Cemetery in The Bronx, New York City.
simple: Charles Ranhofer (November 7, 1836, Saint-Denis, France — October 9, 1899, New York) was the chef at the famous Delmonico's Restaurant in New York from 1862 to 1876 and 1879 to 1896. <s> Ranhofer wrote "The Epicurean", (1894), a cookbook of over 1,000 pages, similar in scope to Escoffier's "Le Guide Culinaire". <s> Ranhofer was sent to Paris at the age of 12 to begin his training by studying pastry-making, and at 16 became the private chef for the prince d'Hénin, comte d'Alsace. <s> In 1856 he moved to New York to become the chef for the Russian consul, and later worked in Washington, D.C. and New Orleans. <s> He returned to France in 1860 for a short time, where he arranged balls for the court of Napoleon III at the Tuileries Palace, but then came back to New York to work at what was then a fashionable location, "Maison Dorée". <s> In 1862, Lorenzo Delmonico hired him for Delmonico's Restaurant, and it was there that Ranhofer made his real fame, though others say that he made the fame of the restaurant as well. <s> At that time, Delmonico's was considered the finest restaurant in the United States. <s> He was the chef at Delmonico's until his retirement in 1896, except for a short break from 1876 and 1879 when he owned the "Hotel American" at Enghien-les-Bains. <s> Ranhofer invented or made famous a number of dishes that Delmonico's was known for, such as Lobster Newberg, and had a talent for naming dishes after famous or prominent people—particularly those who dined at Delmonico's--as well as his friends, and events of the day. <s> Examples include: "Many others may be found under "List of foods named after people."" <s> Ranhofer did not invent baked Alaska, but he popularized it in 1876 when he named it in honor of the newly acquired Alaskan territory. <s> Ranhofer and his wife Rose had five children: three sons and two daughters. <s> He died at home of Bright's Disease in 1899. <s> He was buried at Woodlawn Cemetery.

title: Huacho

title: Lawrence Gonzi
complex: Lawrence Gonzi, KUOM (born 1 July 1953) is a Maltese politician, retired Nationalist politician and lawyer, who served for twenty-five years in various critical roles in Maltese politics. <s> Gonzi was Prime Minister of Malta from 2004 to 2013, and leader of the Nationalist Party. <s> He also served as speaker of the House from 1988 to 1996, and Minister of Social Policy from 1998 to 2004, as well as Deputy Prime Minister from 1999 to 2004. <s> He served in practically all positions in Parliament, being also Leader of the House, an MP and Leader of the Opposition.
simple: Lawrence Gonzi KUOM (born 1 July 1953) is a Maltese politician. <s> He served for twenty-five years in Maltese politics. <s> Gonzi was Prime Minister of Malta from 2004 to 2013, and leader of the Nationalist Party. <s> He also served as speaker of the House from 1988 to 1996, and Minister of Social Policy from 1998 to 2004, as well as Deputy Prime Minister from 1999 to 2004.

title: Ferdinand Lemaire
complex: Ferdinand Lemaire (1832–1879) was a French librettist and poet, best known for writing the libretto of Camille Saint-Saëns's opera "Samson et Dalila". <s> Lemaire was a creole, originally from Martinique, and had married a cousin of Saint-Saëns's wife. <s> Saint-Saëns had previously set two of his poems, “Souvenance” and “Tristesse”, for voice and piano. <s> Approached by the composer to write an oratorio on the story of Samson and Delilah, Lemaire agreed, but only if the work was to be an opera.
simple: Ferdinand Lemaire was a librettist and writer. <s> He was a creole. <s> He married into Saint-Saëns's family. <s> He agreed to write "Samson" but only as opera, rather than as an oratorio as the composer first intended.

title: Florent Malouda
complex: Florent Johan Malouda (] ; born 13 June 1980) is a French football coach and former professional player.
simple: Florent Malouda (born 13 June 1980) is a French football player.

title: Facta (encyclopedia)
complex: Facta is an encyclopedia in Finnish. <s> It was published as a series of 11 volumes between 1969 and 1974. <s> It describes subjects from a Finnish point of view. <s> Chief editor was Veli Valpola and publisher, Tietosanakirja Oy.
simple: Facta is an encyclopedia in Finnish. <s> It was published as a series of 11 volumes between 1969 and 1974. <s> It describes subjects from a Finnish point of view.

title: Halifax Explosion
complex: The Halifax Explosion was a maritime disaster in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada, which happened on the morning of 6 December 1917. <s> The Norwegian vessel collided with , a French cargo ship laden with high explosives, in the Narrows, a strait connecting the upper Halifax Harbour to Bedford Basin, causing a large explosion on the French freighter, devastating the Richmond district of Halifax. <s> Approximately 2,000 people were killed by the blast, debris, fires or collapsed buildings, and an estimated 9,000 others were injured. <s> The blast was the largest man-made explosion at the time, releasing the equivalent energy of roughly 2.9 ktonTNT .
simple: The Halifax explosion took place on December 6, 1917 when the SS "Mont-Blanc", a French cargo ship loaded with explosives collided with the SS "Imo", a Norwegian ship in the harbour in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada. <s> 2,000 people were killed and over 9,000 people were injured.

title: Neoteny
complex: Neoteny in humans is the slowing or delaying of body development, compared to non-human primates, resulting in features such as a large head, a flat face, and relatively short arms and legs. <s> These neotenic changes may have been brought about by sexual selection in human evolution.
simple: Neoteny is a type of heterochrony where bodily development is slowed, but sexual development goes on at the same rate. <s> These are some of the neotenous traits in humans: flattened face, broadened face, large brain, hairless body, hairless face, small nose, reduction of brow ridge, small teeth, small upper jaw (maxilla), small lower jaw (mandible), thinness of skull bones, limbs proportionately short compared to torso length, longer leg than arm length, larger eyes, and upright stance.

title: Jason Bonham
complex: Jason John Bonham (born 15 July 1966) is an English drummer. <s> He is the son of the late Led Zeppelin drummer John Bonham and Patricia "Pat" Bonham (née Phillips).
simple: Jason John Bonham (born 15 July 1966) is an English rock drummer who is noted for being the son of Led Zeppelin drummer John Bonham, as well for his own music.

title: Jean-Marie Girault
complex: Jean-Marie Girault (9 February 1926 – 1 May 2016) was a French politician and former mayor of Caen.
simple: Jean-Marie Girault (9 February 1926 – 1 May 2016) was a French politician. <s> Girault died in Caen, France on 1 May 2016, aged 90.

title: Mab (moon)
complex: Mab , or Uranus XXVI (26), is an inner satellite of Uranus. <s> It was discovered by Mark R. Showalter and Jack J. Lissauer in 2003 using the Hubble Space Telescope. <s> It was named after Queen Mab, a fairy queen from English folklore who is mentioned in William Shakespeare's play "Romeo and Juliet". <s> Because the moon is small and dark, it was not seen in the heavily scrutinized images taken by "Voyager 2" during its Uranus flyby in 1986. <s> However, it is brighter than another moon, Perdita, which was discovered from Voyager's photos in 1997. <s> This led scientists to re-examine the old photos again, and the satellite was finally found in the images. <s> The size of Mab is not known exactly. <s> If it is as dark as Puck, it is about 24 km in diameter. <s> On the other hand, if it is brightly coloured like the neighbouring moon Miranda, it would be even smaller than Cupid and comparable to the smallest outer satellites. <s> Mab is heavily perturbed. <s> The actual source for perturbation is still unclear, but is presumed to be one or more of the nearby orbiting moons. <s> Following its discovery, Mab was given the temporary designation S/2003 U 1. <s> The moon is also designated Uranus XXVI.
simple: It was found by Mark R. Showalter and Jack J. Lissauer in 2003 using the Hubble Space Telescope. <s> It was named after Queen Mab, a fairy queen from English folklore who is noted in William Shakespeare's play "Romeo and Juliet". <s> Because the moon is small and dark, it was not seen in the images taken by "Voyager 2" during its Uranus flyby in 1986. <s> However, it is brighter than another moon, Perdita, which was discovered from "Voyager's" photos in 1997. <s> This led scientists to look at the old photos again, and the moon was finally found in the images. <s> If it is as dark as Puck, then it is about 24 km in diameter. <s> On the other hand, if it is brightly coloured like the neighbouring moon Miranda, then it would be even smaller than Cupid and comparable to the smallest farther moons. <s> Mab is heavily perturbed, meaning its movement is not only caused by the gravity of another large thing. <s> The actual source for perturbation is still unclear, but is probably one or more of the nearby orbiting moons. <s> Following its discovery, Mab was given the code name S/2003 U 1. <s> The moon is also known as Uranus XXVI.

title: The Exorcism of Emily Rose
complex: The Exorcism of Emily Rose is a 2005 American supernatural horror crime film directed by Scott Derrickson and starring Laura Linney and Tom Wilkinson. <s> The film is loosely based on the story of Anneliese Michel and follows a self-proclaimed agnostic (Linney) who acts as defense counsel representing a parish priest (Wilkinson), accused by the state of negligent homicide after he performed an exorcism.
simple: The Exorcism of Emily Rose is a horror-drama movie of 2005.

title: Eiji Ueda
complex: Eiji Ueda (上田 栄治 , Ueda Eiji , born December 22, 1953) is a former Japanese football player and manager. <s> He managed the Japan women's national team. <s> After retirement, Ueda became coach for Fujita Industries. <s> In 1999, he became manager for Bellmare Hiratsuka.
simple: Eiji Ueda (上田栄治, Ueda Eiji, born 22 December 1953) is a Japanese sportsman. <s> Ueda was the head coach of the Japan women's national football team in 2004-2006. <s> After retirement as a coach, Ueda became Chairman of the Japan Football Association Women’s Football Committee.

title: Fernando Gómez Doblas
complex: Fernando Gómez Doblas (born October 16, 1965 in Málaga) is a track and field athlete from Spain with cerebral palsy. <s> He competes as a T36 type athlete. <s> He competed at the 1996 Summer Paralympics in Atlanta, Georgia, winning a silver in the 400 meter T34-T35 race, the 200 meter T34-T35 race and the 100 meter T35 race. <s> He competed at the 2000 Summer Paralympics in Sydney, Australia, where he did not meal in any of his races.
simple: Fernando Gómez Doblas (born October 16, 1965 in Málaga) is a track and field athlete from Spain. <s> He has a disability: He has cerebral palsy and a T36 type athlete. <s> He raced at the 1996 Summer Paralympics in Atlanta, Georgia. <s> He finished second in the 400 meter T34-T35 race, the 200 meter T34-T35 race and the 100 meter T35 race. <s> He raced at the 2000 Summer Paralympics in Sydney, Australia. <s> He did not finish 1, 2 or 3 in any race he raced in at the 2000 Games.

title: Cornish Assembly
complex: A Cornish Assembly is a proposed devolved law-making assembly for Cornwall along the lines of the Scottish Parliament, the National Assembly for Wales and the Northern Ireland Assembly in the United Kingdom.
simple: A Cornish Assembly is a law making parliament that some Cornish people and politicians argue should exist as part of a devolution agreement with the United Kingdom.

simple: Michihiro Yasuda (安田 理大, Yasuda Michihiro, born December 20, 1987) is a Japanese football player.

title: Baltoro Kangri
complex: Baltoro Kangri ( ; also known as the Golden Throne) is a mountain of the Karakoram mountain range in Gilgit-Baltistan, Pakistan. <s> Baltoro Kangri is the 82nd highest mountain in the world with an elevation of 7312 m . <s> It lies to the south of the Gasherbrums and east of Chogolisa Peak (7,665 m). <s> The huge Baltoro Glacier (which is one of the largest glaciers outside polar regions) rises from the foot of Baltoro Kangri. <s> In the north of Baltoro Kangri is the Abruzzi Glacier.
simple: Baltoro Kangri (or Golden Throne) is a mountain in the Karakoram mountain range in the Northern Areas of Pakistan. <s> It lies to the south of the Gasherbrums and east of Chogolisa Peak (7,665 m). <s> The huge Baltoro Glacier, which is one of the largest glaciers outside polar regions, rises from the foot of Baltoro Kangri. <s> In the north of Baltoro Kangri is the Abruzzi Glacier.

title: Palace of Culture and Science
complex: Palace of Culture and Science ( ; abbreviated PKiN), is a notable high-rise building in central Warsaw, Poland. <s> With a total height of 237 m it is the tallest building in Poland, the 6th-tallest building in the European Union (including spire) and one of the tallest on the European continent.
simple: Palace of Culture and Science is the tallest building in Poland (230 meters). <s> It is in Warsaw.

title: Mitchell County, Kansas
complex: Mitchell County (standard abbreviation: MC) is a county located in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the county population was 6,373. <s> The largest city and county seat is Beloit. <s> In 1854, the Kansas Territory was organized, then in 1861 Kansas became the 34th U.S. state. <s> In 1867, Mitchell County was established. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 719 sqmi , of which 702 sqmi is land and 17 sqmi (2.4%) is water. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 6,373 people, 2,790 households, and 1,725 families residing in the county. <s> The population density was 8.8 people per square mile (3.4/km2). <s> There were 3,296 housing units at an average density of 4.6 per square mile (1.7/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the county was 97.97% White, 0.20% Black or African American, 0.37% Native American, 0.29% Asian, 0.07% Pacific Islander, 0.26% from other races, and 0.80% from two or more races. <s> 1.14% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race. <s> Prior to 1940, Mitchell County was a swing county, backing the national winner in every presidential election from 1900 to 1936. <s> Since 1940, it has become a Republican stronghold, with only George H. W. Bush in 1992 failing to win a majority in the county due to Ross Perot's strong showing in Kansas.
simple: Mitchell County (standard abbreviation: MC) is a county in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> In 2010, 6,373 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Beloit. <s> Beloit is also the biggest city in Mitchell County. <s> In 1867, Mitchell County was created. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau says that the county has a total area of 719 sqmi. <s> Of that, 702 sqmi is land and 17 sqmi (2.4%) is water. <s> Before 1940, Mitchell County was a swing county. <s> They voted for the national winner in every presidential election from 1900 to 1936. <s> Since 1940, it has become very Republican. <s> Only George H. W. Bush in 1992 failed win a majority in the county due to Ross Perot's strong showing in Kansas.

title: Minos Kyriakou
complex: Minos Xenophon "Minas" Kyriakou ( , ] ; 31 May 1942 – 2 July 2017) was a Greek media and shipping magnate and businessman. <s> He was the president of the Hellenic Olympic Committee and was the President of the International Olympic Academy (IOA, 2004-2009). <s> He was elected to the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) council in August 2003. <s> Kyriakou died of a heart attack on 2 July 2017, at the Athens Medical Center. <s> He was twice divorced and was survived by his three children from his first marriage.
simple: Minos Xenophon "Minas" Kyriakou (; 31 May 1942 – 2 July 2017) was a Greek media and shipping magnate and businessman. <s> He was the president of the Greek Olympic Committee and was the President of the International Olympic Academy (IOA, 2004-2009). <s> He was elected to the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) council in August 2003. <s> Kyriakou died of a heart attack on 2 July 2017 at a hospital in Athens, aged 75.

title: Askham, Cumbria
complex: Askham is a village and civil parish in the Eden District of Cumbria, England. <s> It is in the historic county of Westmorland. <s> According to the 2001 census the parish had a population of 360, decreasing slightly to 356 at the 2011 Census. <s> It is situated in the eastern edge of the Lake District National Park, about 5 mi south of Penrith.
simple: Askham is a village and civil parish in Eden, Cumbria, England. <s> In 2001 there were 360 people living in Askham.

title: Hans Nowak
complex: Hans Nowak (9 August 1937 – 19 July 2012) was a German football player. <s> He played in four matches at the 1962 FIFA World Cup.
simple: Hans Nowak (born 9 August, 1937) is a former German football player.

title: Apollo 9
complex: Apollo 9 was a March 1969 human spaceflight, the third crewed mission in the United States Apollo program. <s> Flown in low Earth orbit, it was the second crewed Apollo mission to be launched by a Saturn V rocket, and the first flight of the full Apollo spacecraft: the command and service module (CSM) with the Lunar Module (LM). <s> The mission was flown to qualify the LM for lunar orbit operations by demonstrating its descent and ascent propulsion systems, showing that its crew could fly it independently, then rendezvous and dock with the CSM again, as would be required for the first crewed lunar landing. <s> Other objectives of the flight included firing the LM descent engine to propel the spacecraft stack as a backup mode (as would be required on the Apollo 13 mission), and use of the Portable Life Support System backpack outside of the LM cabin. <s> The three-person crew consisted of Commander James McDivitt, Command Module Pilot David Scott, and Lunar Module Pilot Rusty Schweickart. <s> During the ten-day mission, they tested systems and procedures critical to landing on the Moon, including the LM engines, backpack life support systems, navigation systems and docking maneuvers. <s> After launching on March 3, 1969, the crew performed the first crewed flight of a lunar module, the first docking and extraction of the same, one two-person spacewalk (EVA), and the second docking of two crewed spacecraft—two months after the Soviets performed a spacewalk crew transfer between Soyuz 4 and Soyuz 5. <s> The mission concluded on March 13 and was a complete success.
simple: Apollo 9 was a mission in NASA's Apollo program. <s> It was the third manned mission in the Apollo program and was the first flight of the Command/Service Module (CSM) with the Lunar Module (LM). <s> The crew was Commander James A. McDivitt, Command Module Pilot David R. Scott, and Lunar Module Pilot Russell L. Schweickart. <s> The mission tested several things which were important for landing on the Moon, including the LM engines, backpack life support systems, navigation systems, and docking maneuvers. <s> The mission was launched on March 3, 1969.

title: Allen Crabbe
complex: Allen Lester Crabbe III (born April 9, 1992) is an American professional basketball player for the Atlanta Hawks of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> He played college basketball for the California Golden Bears. <s> He earned third-team All-American honors as a junior, when he was also named the conference player of the year in the Pac-12.
simple: Allen Lester Crabbe III (born April 9, 1992) is an American professional basketball player. <s> He plays for the Portland Trail Blazers of the National Basketball Association (NBA). <s> He played college basketball for the California Golden Bears.

title: British Rail Class D3/11
complex: British Rail Class D3/11 was a locomotive commissioned by the Great Western Railway, but delivered to its successor British Rail in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.
simple: British Rail Class D3/11 was a locomotive commissioned by the Great Western Railway, but delivered to its successor British Rail in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.

title: Denise DuBarry
complex: Denise DuBarry Hay (March 6, 1956 – March 23, 2019) was an American actress, businesswoman, film producer, and philanthropist. <s> She co-founded Thane International Inc., a direct response industry company along with her husband, Bill Hay, in 1990. <s> She served as its Chief Creative Officer for 15 years, from 1990–2005. <s> As an actress, she is best known for her role as nurse Lieutenant Samantha Green, on the television series "Black Sheep Squadron", and as Johanna Franklin in the film "Being There". <s> DuBarry was born in Killeen, Texas, at Fort Hood Army Base, to Adrian Pierre DuBarry and his wife, Betty Louise (née King). <s> Her parents moved back to Louisiana where they were from so that her father could finish his master's degree at LSU in Baton Rouge. <s> The family later moved to Honduras, Mexico, Guatemala and Costa Rica, where DuBarry grew up from ages 2 to 10, and learned to speak fluent Spanish. <s> The family moved throughout California, eventually settling in Granada Hills, California, where Denise attended middle school and high school. <s> A child of divorce and the eldest of five children, at 14 she watched after her siblings while her mother worked. <s> DuBarry Hay died at UCLA Medical Center on March 23, 2019, seventeen days after her 63rd birthday. <s> Her husband Bill Hay confirmed that DuBarry Hay died after contracting a rare illness Candida Auris.
simple: Denise DuBarry (March 6, 1956 – March 23, 2019) was an American actress, businesswoman, movie producer, and philanthropist. <s> In business, she co-founded Thane International, Inc.. <s> She was its Chief Creative Officer for 15 years, from 1990 to 2005. <s> She was known for her roles as nurse Lieutenant Samantha Green, on the television series "Black Sheep Squadron", and as Johanna Franklin in the movie "Being There". <s> She was born in Killeen, Texas. <s> DuBarry died from a fatal fungal infection on March 23, 2019 in Los Angeles, California, aged 63.

title: Citric acid cycle
complex: The citric acid cycle (CAC) – also known as the" TCA cycle (tricarboxylic acid cycle) " or the" Krebs cycle "– is a series of chemical reactions used by all aerobic organisms to release stored energy through the oxidation of acetyl-CoA derived from carbohydrates, fats, and proteins, into adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and carbon dioxide. <s> In addition, the cycle provides precursors of certain amino acids, as well as the reducing agent NADH, that are used in numerous other reactions. <s> Its central importance to many biochemical pathways suggests that it was one of the earliest established components of cellular metabolism and may have originated abiogenically. <s> Even though it is branded as a 'cycle', it is not necessary for metabolites to follow only one specific route; at least three segments of the citric acid cycle have been recognized. <s> Because two acetyl-CoA molecules are produced from each glucose molecule, two cycles are required per glucose molecule. <s> Therefore, at the end of two cycles, the products are: two GTP, six NADH, two QH, and four CO.
simple: Its other names are the citric acidity cycle, and the tricarboxylic acid cycle (TCA cycle). <s> It is the series of chemical reactions used by all aerobic organisms to generate energy. <s> It is important to many biochemical pathways. <s> This suggests that it was one of the earliest parts of cellular metabolism to evolve. <s> Because two acetyl-CoA molecules are produced from each glucose molecule, "two cycles are required per glucose molecule". <s> Therefore, at the end of two cycles, the products are: two ATP, six NADH, two FADH two QH (ubiquinol) and four CO.

title: Nemanja Vidić
complex: Nemanja Vidić (, ] ; born 21 October 1981) is a Serbian retired professional footballer. <s> He most notably played for Manchester United from 2006 to 2014, and was part of the Serbia national team from 2002 to 2011. <s> In his prime, Vidić was regarded as one of the best defenders in the world.
simple: Nemanja Vidić (born 21 October 1981) is a Serbian football player. <s> He plays for Manchester United and Serbia national team.

title: Antonio Juliano
complex: Antonio Juliano (] ; born 1 January 1943) is a former Italian footballer who played as a midfielder. <s> A dedicated, hardworking, influential, and creative playmaker, he was renowned in particular for his leadership, technical ability, and ball control, as well as for his outstanding vision, stamina, and passing range.
simple: Antonio Juliano (born 1 January 1943) is a former Italian football player.

title: Montalchez
complex: Montalchez is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipalities of Bevaix, Saint-Aubin-Sauges, Gorgier, Vaumarcus, Montalchez and Fresens merged into the new municipality of La Grande-Béroche.
simple: Montalchez is a former municipality in the district of Boudry in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipalities of Bevaix, Saint-Aubin-Sauges, Gorgier, Vaumarcus, Montalchez and Fresens merged into the new municipality of La Grande-Béroche.

title: Dhṛtarāṣṭra
complex: Dhṛtarāṣṭra (Sanskrit; Pali: "Dhataraṭṭha") is a major deity in Buddhism and one of the Four Heavenly Kings. <s> His name means "Upholder of the Nation." <s> The name "Dhṛtarāṣṭra" is a Sanskrit compound of the words "dhṛta" (possessing; bearing) and "rāṣṭra" (kingdom; territory). <s> Dhṛtarāṣṭra is the guardian of the eastern direction. <s> He lives on the eastern part of Sumeru. <s> He is leader of the gandharvas and piśācas. <s> Most East Asian depictions of Dhṛtarāṣṭra show him playing a stringed instrument, but the presence of this motif varies. <s> In the Pāli Canon of Theravāda Buddhism, Dhṛtarāṣṭra is called Dhataraṭṭha. <s> Dhataraṭṭha is one of the Cātummahārājāno, or "Four Great Kings." <s> each of whom rules over a specific direction. <s> He has many sons who go by the title "Indra, as well as a daughter named "Sirī". <s> In Japan, Jikokuten (持国天) is commonly depicted with a fierce expression. <s> He is clad in armor, often brandishing a sword or trident spear while trampling a jaki.
simple: Dhritarashtra (Sanskrit: धृतराष्ट्र, "Dhṛtarāṣṭra") or Dhatarattha (Pali: धतरट्ठ "Dhataraṭṭha") is one of the Four Heavenly Kings and an important person in Buddhism. <s> The name Dhṛtarāṣṭra comes from two Sanskrit words: "dhṛta" (possessing; bearing) and "rāṣṭra" (kingdom; territory). <s> Dhṛtarāṣṭra is the guardian god of the East. <s> He lives on the eastern part of Mount Sumeru. <s> He is leader of the gandharvas and the pishacas. <s> He is often shown in art playing a stringed instrument. <s> In the Pāli writings of the Theravada Buddhist tradition, Dhṛtarāṣṭra is called "Dhataraṭṭha". <s> Dhataraṭṭha is one of the Four Great Kings, each one of which rules over a direction. <s> He has many sons called "Indra." <s> He also has a daughter named "Sirī". <s> In Japan, Jikokuten (持国天) is often shown wearing a suit of armor. <s> He usually holds a sword and a trident while standing on top of a demon called a "jaki".

title: Toni Ucci
complex: Antonio "Toni" Ucci (13 January 1922 – 16 or 19 February 2014) was an Italian actor and comedian. <s> He appeared in 86 films between 1948 and 2000.
simple: Antonio "Toni" Ucci (13 January 1922 – 19 February 2014) was an Italian actor and comedian from Rome. <s> Ucci died from natural causes on 19 February 2014, aged 92, in his hometown of Rome. <s> He appeared in 86 movies between 1948 and 2000.

title: Eastern religions
complex: The Eastern religions are the religions that originated in East, South and Southeast Asia and thus have dissimilarities with Western religions. <s> This includes the East Asian religions (Shintoism, Sindoism, Taoism and Confucianism), Indian religions (Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism) as well as animistic indigenous religions.
simple: Eastern religions is the name for a number of religions that had their origins in India, China, Japan and Southeast Asia.

title: Humphrey Mijnals
complex: Humphrey August Mijnals (21 December 1930 – 27 July 2019) was a footballer who played international football for both the Netherlands and Suriname. <s> Then he played 45 times in the Suriname national football team. <s> In 1999, he was elected Surinamese footballer of the century. <s> On 24 August 2008, Mijnals also received Sports Medal of the city of Utrecht.
simple: Humphrey Mijnals (21 December 1930 – 27 July 2019) was a Surinamese-Dutch footballer. <s> He played international football for both the Netherlands and Suriname. <s> Mijnals died on 27 July 2019 in Utrecht at the age of 88. <s> Then he played 45 times in the Suriname national football team. <s> In 1999, he was elected Surinamese footballer of the century. <s> On 24 August 2008, Mijnals also received Sports Medal of the city of Utrecht.

title: John Andretti
complex: John Andrew Andretti (born March 12, 1963) is an American race car driver. <s> He is the older brother of racer Adam Andretti, nephew of Indianapolis 500 winner Mario Andretti, and first cousin to IndyCar champion Michael and Jeff Andretti. <s> He is also the first cousin once-removed to IndyCar driver Marco Andretti. <s> His father Aldo Andretti, Mario's twin brother, retired from driving a race car after he nearly died in an accident. <s> He has won in CART, IMSA GTP, Rolex Sports Car Series, and NASCAR. <s> In April 2017, Andretti disclosed that he is battling stage four colon cancer. <s> His cancer battle, originally misdiagnosed as Stage III-A cancer, was widely publicized, with him starting a Twitter hashtag called #CheckIt4Andretti, as far as getting a colonoscopy.
simple: John Andrew Andretti (born March 12, 1963) is an American race car driver. <s> He is the older brother of racer Adam Andretti and the nephew of Indianapolis 500 winner Mario Andretti. <s> He has won in CART, IMSA GTP, Rolex Sports Car Series, and NASCAR. <s> In April 2017, Andretti said that he was diagnosed with stage four colon cancer.

title: Michael Somare
complex: Sir Michael Thomas Somare (born 9 April 1936) is a Papua New Guinean politician. <s> He was a pivotal politician in the coming of independence. <s> His political career spanned from 1968 until his retirement in 2017. <s> He has been the longest serving prime minister (17 years). <s> Besides that he has been minister of foreign affairs, leader of the opposition and governor of East Sepik.
simple: Sir Michael Thomas Somare (born 9 April 1936) is a Papua New Guinean politician. <s> His career lasted from 1968 until his retirement in 2017. <s> He has been the longest serving Prime Minister of Papua New Guinea (17 years). <s> He was the country's first Prime Minister.

title: Hungerford Bridge and Golden Jubilee Bridges
complex: The Hungerford Bridge crosses the River Thames in London, and lies between Waterloo Bridge and Westminster Bridge. <s> Owned by Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd (who use its official name of Charing Cross Bridge) it is a steel truss railway bridge flanked by two more recent, cable-stayed, pedestrian bridges that share the railway bridge's foundation piers, and which are named the Golden Jubilee Bridges. <s> The north end of the bridge is Charing Cross railway station, and is near Embankment Pier and the Victoria Embankment. <s> The south end is near Waterloo station, County Hall, the Royal Festival Hall, and the London Eye. <s> Each pedestrian bridge has steps and lift access. <s> The first Hungerford Bridge, designed by Isambard Kingdom Brunel, opened in 1845 as a suspension footbridge. <s> It was named after the then Hungerford Market, because it went from the South Bank to Hungerford Market on the north side of the Thames. <s> The two new 4 m wide footbridges were completed in 2002. <s> They were named the Golden Jubilee Bridges, in honour of the fiftieth anniversary of Queen Elizabeth II's accession, although in practice they are often still referred to as the "Hungerford Footbridges".
simple: Hungerford Bridge, often called Charing Cross Bridge, is a railway bridge.It crosses the River Thames in London from Charing Cross station across to the south, near Waterloo station. <s> The bridge lies between Waterloo Bridge and Westminster Bridge. <s> It is a steel bridge with two more recent pedestrian bridges on either side. <s> The north end of the bridge is Charing Cross station. <s> It is near Embankment Pier and the Victoria Embankment. <s> The south end is near Waterloo station, County Hall, the Royal Festival Hall, and the London Eye. <s> Each footpath has steps and lift access. <s> The first version of the bridge was designed by Isambard Kingdom Brunel, and opened in 1845. <s> These were named the Golden Jubilee Bridges, but are really just footpaths alongside the railway bridge.

title: Petrykivka painting
complex: Petrykivka painting (or simply "Petrykivka") is a traditional Ukrainian decorative painting style, originating from the village of Petrykivka in Dnipropetrovsk oblast of Ukraine, where it was traditionally used to decorate house walls and everyday household items. <s> The earliest known examples of this style date from the 17th century, but it continues to thrive and develop as a modern art form. <s> In 2012, the Ministry of Culture of Ukraine recognized Petrykivka painting as a part of intangible cultural heritage of Ukraine, and it was included in the UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity in 2013. <s> Petrykivka painting has become a "brand" in Ukrainian popular culture, and a "Petrykivka" trademark belonging to the artisans of Petrykivka village has been created.
simple: Petrykivka painting is a traditional Ukrainian decorative painting. <s> It originates from the Petrykivka village in Dnipropetrovsk oblast of Ukraine. <s> In 2013 it was included to the UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.

title: Sandy Silver

title: WebKit
complex: WebKit is a browser engine used in Apple's Safari browser and other products. <s> WebKit is also the basis for the experimental browser included with the Amazon Kindle e-book reader, and for the default browser in Apple iOS, BlackBerry Browser in OS 6 and above, and Tizen mobile operating systems. <s> WebKit's C++ application programming interface (API) provides a set of classes to display Web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the user, managing a back-forward list, and managing a history of pages recently visited. <s> WebKit's JavaScriptCore and WebCore components are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, while the rest of WebKit is available under a BSD-style license.
simple: WebKit is a layout engine made to let web browsers show web pages. <s> WebKit was first made to be used as the layout engine for Safari, and is portable to many other computing platforms. <s> The WebKit engine has a set of classes to display web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the person using the web browser (the user), managing a back-forward list, and keeping a history of pages recently visited. <s> WebKit's WebCore and JavaScriptCore parts are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, and the rest of WebKit is available under a BSD-style license.

title: Bearded vulture
complex: The bearded vulture ("Gypaetus barbatus"), also known as the lammergeier (or lammergeyer) or ossifrage, is a bird of prey and the only member of the genus "Gypaetus". <s> Traditionally considered an Old World vulture, it actually forms a minor lineage of Accipitridae together with the Egyptian vulture ("Neophron percnopterus"), its closest living relative. <s> It is not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to, for example, hawks, and differs from the former by its feathered neck. <s> Although dissimilar, the Egyptian and bearded vulture each have a lozenge-shaped tail—unusual among birds of prey. <s> The bearded vulture is the only known vertebrate whose diet consists almost exclusively (70 to 90 percent) of bone. <s> It lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern Europe, the Caucasus, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, and Tibet, laying one or two eggs in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring.
simple: The bearded vulture ("Gypaetus barbatus"), also known as the lammergeier or lammergeyer, is a bird of prey. <s> It is the only member of the genus Gypaetus. <s> An Old World vulture, it forms a minor line of the Accipitridae with the Egyptian vulture, its closest living relative. <s> They are not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to hawks. <s> They differ from Old World vultures by their feathered neck. <s> It eats mainly carrion and lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern Europe, the Caucasus, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, and Tibet. <s> The females lay one or two eggs in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring.

title: Clay County, Iowa
complex: Clay County is a county located in the U.S. state of Iowa. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 16,667. <s> Its county seat is Spencer. <s> Its name is in honor of Henry Clay, Jr., a colonel who died in action in the Mexican–American War, and son of Henry Clay, famous American statesman from Kentucky.
simple: Clay County is a county in the U.S. state of Iowa. <s> In the 2010 census, 16,667 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Spencer.

title: Bioleaching
complex: Bioleaching is the extraction of metals from their ores through the use of living organisms. <s> This is much cleaner than the traditional heap leaching using cyanide. <s> Bioleaching is one of several applications within biohydrometallurgy and several methods are used to recover copper, zinc, lead, arsenic, antimony, nickel, molybdenum, gold, silver, and cobalt.
simple: Bioleaching is getting metals from their ores by using living organisms. <s> Bioleaching uses certain types of bacteria to produce a solution called a "leachate". <s> This is much cleaner than the traditional method using cyanide. <s> Bioleaching is one of several methods used to recover copper, zinc, lead, arsenic, antimony, nickel, molybdenum, gold, silver, and cobalt.

Grant, 18th President of the United States.

title: Martin Milner
complex: Martin Sam Milner (December 28, 1931 – September 6, 2015) was an American film, stage, radio, and television actor. <s> Milner is known for his performances on two television series: "Route 66", which aired on CBS from 1960 to 1964, and "Adam-12", which aired on NBC from 1968 to 1975. <s> On September 6, 2015, Milner died of heart failure at his home in Carlsbad, California, at age 83. <s> Milner's remains were cremated by Eternal Hills Memorial Park's mortuary in Oceanside, California..
simple: Martin Sam Milner (December 28, 1931 – September 6, 2015) was an American movie, stage, radio and television actor. <s> Milner was best known for his performances in two popular television series: "Route 66", which aired on CBS from 1960 to 1964, and "Adam-12", which aired on NBC from 1968 to 1975. <s> Milner died at his home in Carlsbad, California at the age of 83.

title: Defenceman
complex: Defence (defense in the USA) in ice hockey is a player position whose primary responsibility is to prevent the opposing team from scoring. <s> They are often referred to as defencemen, D, D-men or blueliners (the latter a reference to the blue line in ice hockey which represents the boundary of the offensive zone; defencemen generally position themselves along the line to keep the puck in the zone). <s> They were once called cover-point. <s> A good defenceman is both strong in defensive and offensive play and for defenceman pairing also need to be good at defending and attacking. <s> In regular play, two defencemen complement three forwards and a goaltender on the ice. <s> Exceptions include overtime during the regular season and when a team is shorthanded (i.e. has been assessed a penalty), in which two defencemen are typically joined by only two forwards and a goaltender; in National Hockey League play in overtime effective with the 2015-16 season the teams have only three position players and a goaltender on the ice and may use either two forwards and one defenceman (typically), or conversely, two defencemen and one forward.
simple: Defence (defense in the U.S.) in ice hockey is a player position whose main job is to stop the other team from scoring. <s> They are often called defencemen, defensemen, D, or "blueliners" (a reference to the blue line in ice hockey which is boundary of the offensive zone; defencemen generally stay along the line to keep the puck in the zone). <s> In regular play, two defencemen play with three forwards and a goaltender on the ice. <s> Exceptions include overtime and when a team is shorthanded (i.e. has been assessed a penalty), in which two defencemen are typically joined by only two forwards and a goaltender.

complex: Patricia Gallerneau (9 September 1954 – 7 July 2019) was a French politician representing the Democratic Movement. <s> She was elected to the French National Assembly on 18 June 2017, representing the department of Vendée. <s> Patricia Gallerneau was born in the 20th arrondissement of Paris to a Finisterian mother and a Correzian father. <s> The latter was elected by the Rassemblement pour la République in Angers.

title: Duke of Noailles
complex: The title of Duke of Noailles was a French peerage created in 1663 for Anne de Noailles, Count of Ayen. <s> Noailles is the name of a prominent French noble family, derived from the castle of Noailles in the territory of Ayen, between Brive and Turenne in Limousin, and claiming to date back to the 11th century. <s> The family did not obtain fame until the 16th century, when its head, Antoine de Noailles (1504–1562), became admiral of France and was ambassador in England during three important years (1553–1556), maintaining a gallant but unsuccessful rivalry with the Spanish ambassador, Simon Renard. <s> Henri de Noailles (1554–1623), son of Antoine, was a commander in the religious wars and was made comte d'Ayen by Henry IV of France in 1593.
simple: The title of Duke of Noailles was a French peerage created in 1663 for Anne de Noailles, Count of Ayen. <s> The title of Duke of Ayen was also given to the family. <s> Noailles is the name of a great French family, derived from the castle of Noailles in the territory of Ayen, between Brive and Turenne in the Limousin, and claiming to date back to the 11th century. <s> It did not obtain fame until the 16th century, when its head, Antoine de Noailles (1504–1562), became admiral of France and was ambassador in England during three important years, 1553–1556, maintaining a gallant but unsuccessful rivalry with the Spanish ambassador, Simon Renard. <s> Henri (1554–1623), son of Antoine, was a commander in the religious wars and was made Count of Ayen by Henry IV of France in 1593.

title: Aulis Rytkönen
complex: Taavi Aulis Rytkönen (5 January 1929 – 16 April 2014) was a Finnish footballer. <s> He became the country's first professional player when he signed for France's Toulouse FC in 1952. <s> Rytkönen earned 37 caps for the Finnish national team, scoring seven goals. <s> He played for Finland at the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki. <s> He also worked as national coach from 1975 to 1978. <s> He was chosen Finland's Player of the Year in 1949, 1950, and 1952.
