title: Balochistan, Pakistan
complex: Balochistan ( ; ) is one of the four provinces of Pakistan. <s> It is the largest province in terms of land area, forming the southwestern region of the country, but is the least populated. <s> Its provincial capital and largest city is Quetta. <s> The main ethnic groups in the province are the Baloch people and the Pashtuns, who constitute 52% and 36% of the population respectively (according to the preliminary 2011 census). <s> The remaining 12% comprises smaller communities of Brahuis, Hazaras along with other settlers such as Sindhis, Punjabis, Uzbeks and Turkmens. <s> The name "Balochistan" means "the land of the Baloch". <s> Largely underdeveloped, its provincial economy is dominated by natural resources, especially its natural gas fields, estimated to have sufficient capacity to supply Pakistan's demands over the medium to long term. <s> Aside from Quetta, the second-largest city of the province is Turbat in the south, while another area of major economic importance is Gwadar Port on the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is situated in the southwest of Pakistan and covers an area of 347,190 km2 . <s> It is Pakistan's largest province by area, constituting 44% of Pakistan's total land mass. <s> The province is bordered by Afghanistan to the north and north-west, Iran to the south-west, Punjab and Sindh, and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and the Federally Administered Tribal Areas to the north-east. <s> To the south lies the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is located on the south-eastern part of the Iranian plateau. <s> It borders the geopolitical regions of the Middle East and Southwest Asia, Central Asia and South Asia. <s> Balochistan lies at the mouth of the Strait of Hormuz and provides the shortest route from seaports to Central Asia. <s> Its geographical location has placed the otherwise desolate region in the scope of competing global interests for all of recorded history. <s> The capital city Quetta is located in a densely populated portion of the Sulaiman Mountains in the north-east of the province. <s> It is situated in a river valley near the Bolan Pass, which has been used as the route of choice from the coast to Central Asia, entering through Afghanistan's Kandahar region. <s> The British and other historic empires have crossed the region to invade Afghanistan by this route. <s> Balochistan is rich in exhaustible and renewable resources; it is the second major supplier of natural gas in Pakistan. <s> The province's renewable and human resource potential has not been systematically measured or exploited due to pressures from within and without Pakistan. <s> Local inhabitants have chosen to live in towns and have relied on sustainable water sources for thousands of years. <s> In common with the other provinces of Pakistan, Balochistan has a parliamentary form of government. <s> The ceremonial head of the province is the Governor, who is appointed by the President of Pakistan on the advice of the provincial Chief Minister. <s> The Chief Minister, the province's chief executive, is normally the leader of the largest political party or alliance of parties in the provincial assembly. <s> The unicameral Provincial Assembly of Balochistan comprises 65 seats of which 11 are reserved for women and 3 reserved for non-Muslims. <s> The judicial branch of government is carried out by the Balochistan High Court, which is based in Quetta and headed by a Chief Justice.
simple: Balochistan is a province in Pakistan. <s> The capital of Balochistan is Quetta. <s> There are also relatively smaller communities of Iranian Baloch, Hazaras, Sindhis and other settlers, including Punjabis, Uzbeks, and Turkmens. <s> The name Balochistan means "the land of the Baloch" in many regional languages. <s> Balochistan has a population of about 10 million people and an area of 134,051 mi or (347,190 km). <s> Balochistan is situated in the south-west of Pakistan and covers an area of 347,190 km2. <s> It covers 45% of Pakistani territory; in terms of area the province of Balochistan is greater in area than Republic of the Congo but smaller than Germany. <s> It is Pakistan's largest province by area constituting 44% of Pakistan's total land mass. <s> The province is bordered by Afghanistan to the north and north-west, Iran to the south-west, Punjab and Sindh, and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa and the Federally Administered Tribal Areas to the north-east. <s> To the south lies the Arabian Sea. <s> Balochistan is located on the south-eastern part of the Iranian plateau. <s> It borders the geopolitical regions of the Greater Middle East and Southwest Asia, Central Asia and South-central Asia. <s> Balochistan lies at the mouth of the Strait of Hormuz and provides the shortest route from seaports to Central Asia. <s> Its geographical location has placed the otherwise desolate region in the scopes of competing global interests like Afghanistan for all of recorded history. <s> The capital city Quetta is located in a densely populated portion of the Sulaiman Mountains in the north-east of the province. <s> It is situated in a river valley near the Bolan Pass which has been used as the route of choice from the coast to Central Asia, entering through Afghanistan's Kandahar region. <s> The British and other historic empires have crossed the region to invade Afghanistan by this route. <s> Balochistan is rich in exhaustible and renewable resources; it is the second major supplier of natural gas in Pakistan. <s> The province's renewable and human resource potential has not been systematically measured nor exploited due to pressures from within and without Pakistan. <s> Local inhabitants have chosen to live in towns and have relied on sustainable water sources for thousands of years. <s> In common with the other provinces of Pakistan, Balochistan has a parliamentary form of government. <s> The ceremonial head of the province is the Governor, who is appointed by the President of Pakistan on the advice of the provincial Chief Minister. <s> The chief executive of the province is the Chief Minister who is normally the leader of the largest party or alliance in the provincial assembly. <s> The unicameral Provincial Assembly of Balochistan comprises 65 seats of which 4% are reserved for non-Muslims and 16% for women only. <s> The judicial branch of government is carried out by the Balochistan High Court, based in Quetta, and headed by a Chief Justice.

title: Network File System
complex: Network File System (NFS) is a distributed file system protocol originally developed by Sun Microsystems in 1984, allowing a user on a client computer to access files over a computer network much like local storage is accessed. <s> NFS, like many other protocols, builds on the Open Network Computing Remote Procedure Call (ONC RPC) system. <s> The NFS is an open standard defined in a Request for Comments (RFC), allowing anyone to implement the protocol.
simple: Network File System (NFS) is a file system protocol. <s> It was originally developed by Sun Microsystems in 1984. <s> Using NFS, a user on a client computer can access files over a network in the same way as if they were attached to its local disks. <s> NFS uses the Open Network Computing Remote Procedure Call (ONC RPC) system. <s> The Network File System is an open standard defined in RFCs. <s> That way, anyone can implement the protocol.

title: Wolfgang Völz
complex: Wolfgang Otto Völz (16 August 1930 – 2 May 2018) was a German actor. <s> He is known for his roles in theatre plays, TV shows, feature films (especially German films based on Edgar Wallace works) and taped radio shows. <s> He was also a very prolific voice actor. <s> As a voice actor he dubbed American stars such as Walter Matthau, Peter Falk and Mel Brooks and people or animals in animated films like "Impy's Island".
simple: Wolfgang Otto Völz (16 August 1930 – 2 May 2018) was a German actor. <s> He was known for his roles in theatre plays, television shows, feature movies (especially German movies based on Edgar Wallace works) and taped radio shows. <s> He was also a very prolific voice actor. <s> He dubbed American stars such as Walter Matthau, Peter Falk and Mel Brooks and people or animals in animated movies like "Impy's Island".

title: Channel 5 (Singapore)
complex: Channel 5 is a 24-hour Singapore English free-to-air nationwide terrestrial television channel. <s> Its programming mainly consists of English language dramas, movies, sports, reality show, variety show, news, current affairs and game shows. <s> Local editions of imported programmes such as "Singapore Idol", "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?" <s> and "Deal or No Deal" have also been aired on the channel.
simple: MediaCorp Channel 5 or Channel 5 (Chinese: 五频道, Before 1 January 2005: 第五波道) is a 24-hour free-to-air English television channel based in Singapore. <s> Programmes on Channel 5 normally include English language drama (both foreign imports and locally-made), movies, sports, reality show, variety show, news, current affairs and game show programmes. <s> Local editions of overseas programmes like Singapore Idol, Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?, <s> , and Deal or No Deal have also been produced.

title: Aten
complex: Aten (also Aton, ) is the disc of the sun in ancient Egyptian mythology, and originally an aspect of the god Ra. <s> The deified Aten is the focus of the monotheistic religion of Atenism established by Amenhotep IV, who later took the name Akhenaten (died ca. 1335 BCE) in worship and recognition of Aten. <s> In his poem "Great Hymn to the Aten", Akhenaten praises Aten as the creator, giver of life, and nurturing spirit of the world. <s> Aten does not have a Creation Myth or family but is mentioned in the Book of the Dead. <s> The worship of Aten was eradicated by Horemheb.
simple: Aten is the disk of the Sun in ancient Egyptian mythology, and an aspect of the Sun-god Ra. <s> The deified Aten is the focus of the monotheistic religion of Atenism established by Amenhotep IV, who later took the name Akhenaten in worship and recognition of the Aten. <s> In his poem "Great Hymn to the Aten", Akhenaten praises Aten as the creator, and giver of life. <s> The worship of Aten was eradicated by Horemheb.

title: Kim Wilson
complex: Kim Wilson (born January 6, 1951) is an American blues singer and harmonica player. <s> He is best known as the lead vocalist and frontman for the Fabulous Thunderbirds on two hit songs of the 1980s, "Tuff Enuff" and "Wrap It Up." <s> Wilson wrote "Tuff Enuff," the group's only Top 40 hit. <s> Wilson was born in Detroit, Michigan, in 1951, but he grew up in Goleta, California, where he sometimes went by the stage name of "Goleta Slim." <s> He started with the blues in the late 1960s and was tutored by people like Muddy Waters, Jimmy Rogers, Eddie Taylor, Albert Collins, George "Harmonica" Smith, Luther Tucker and Pee Wee Crayton and was influenced by harmonica players such as Little Walter, James Cotton, Big Walter Horton, Slim Harpo and Lazy Lester. <s> Before he moved to Austin, Texas, in 1974, he was the leader of the band Aces, Straights and Shuffles in Minneapolis, Minnesota; the band released one single. <s> In Austin he formed the Fabulous Thunderbirds with guitarist Jimmie Vaughan. <s> They became the house band at Antone's, a blues club owned by Clifford Antone. <s> Wilson continues to perform up to 300 concert dates per year at blues music festivals and clubs all over the world, both as leader of the Fabulous Thunderbirds and with Kim Wilson's Blues Allstars.
simple: Kim Wilson (born January 6, 1951 in Detroit, Michigan) is an American blues singer and harp player. <s> He is best known as the harp player and singer of The Fabulous Thunderbirds. <s> In the 1980s they had two hits with "Tuff Enuff" and "Wrap It Up." <s> He started with the blues in the late 1960s whenhe was a senior at High school. <s> Wilson was tutored by people like Muddy Waters, Jimmie Rogers, Eddie Taylor, Albert Collins, George "Harmonica" Smith, Luther Tucker and Pee Wee Crayton. <s> He was influenced by harmonica players like Little Walter, James Cotton, Big Walter Horton, Slim Harpo and Lazy Lester. <s> 1974 he went to Austin, Texas where he and the guitarist Jimmie Vaughan formed The Fabulous Thunderbirds. <s> They became the house band at the blues club, Antone's. <s> He is doing more than 200 concerts in a year playing in blues clubs and at Festivals around the world.

title: Kariapatti taluk
complex: Kariapatti taluk is a taluk of Virudhunagar district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Kariapatti. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Kariapatti had a population of 105,329 with 52,875 males and 52,454 females. <s> There were 992 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 68.46. <s> Child population in the age group below 6 was 5,736 Males and 5,513 Females.
simple: Kariapatti taluk is a taluk of Virudhunagar district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters of the taluk is the town of Kariapatti. <s> According to the 2011 census, the taluk of Kariapatti had a population of 105,329 with 52,875 males and 52,454 females. <s> There were 992 women for every 1000 men. <s> The taluk had a literacy rate of 68.46. <s> Child population in the age group below 6 was 5,736 Males and 5,513 Females.

title: Vesanto
complex: Vesanto is a municipality of Finland. <s> Neighbour municipalities are Keitele, Konnevesi, Rautalampi, Tervo, Viitasaari and Äänekoski.
simple: Vesanto is a municipality in Northern Savonia, Finland. <s> The municipalities next to it are Keitele, Konnevesi, Rautalampi, Tervo, Viitasaari and Äänekoski.

title: Determinism
complex: Determinism is the philosophical belief that all events are determined completely by previously existing causes. <s> Deterministic theories throughout the history of philosophy have sprung from diverse and sometimes overlapping motives and considerations. <s> The opposite of determinism is some kind of indeterminism (otherwise called nondeterminism) or randomness. <s> Determinism is often contrasted with free will.
simple: In philosophy, determinism is the thesis that there are conditions that make future events happen the way they happen. <s> The opposite position to this idea is called indeterminism.

title: Iris (plant)
complex: Iris is a genus of 260–300 species of flowering plants with showy flowers. <s> It takes its name from the Greek word for a rainbow, which is also the name for the Greek goddess of the rainbow, Iris. <s> Some authors state that the name refers to the wide variety of flower colors found among the many species. <s> As well as being the scientific name, "iris" is also widely used as a common name for all "Iris" species, as well as some belonging to other closely related genera. <s> A common name for some species is 'flags', while the plants of the subgenus "Scorpiris" are widely known as 'junos', particularly in horticulture. <s> It is a popular garden flower. <s> The three, sometimes reduced, petals stand upright, partly behind the sepal bases. <s> They are called "standards". <s> Some smaller iris species have all six lobes pointing straight outwards, but generally limb and standards differ markedly in appearance.
simple: Iris is a genus of 260–300 species of flowering plants with showy flowers. <s> It takes its name from the Greek word for a rainbow. <s> This refers to the wide variety of flower colors found among the many species. <s> The scientific name, "iris" is also very widely used as a common name for all "Iris" species, as well as some belonging to other closely related genera. <s> A common name for some species is 'flags'. <s> Plants of the subgenus "Scorpiris" are widely known as 'junos', particularly in horticulture. <s> It is a member of the Iridaceae family It is a popular garden flower. <s> They have three inner petals called "standards".

title: Goole
complex: Goole is a town, civil parish and inland port located at junction 36 off the M62 via the A614 and approximately 45 mi from the North Sea at the confluence of the rivers Don and Ouse in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England, although historically within the West Riding of Yorkshire. <s> Goole lies 19 mi south of York and 29 mi west of Hull.
simple: Goole is a town and inland port in the East Riding of Yorkshire of England, UK.

title: Txillardegi
complex: José Luis Álvarez Enparantza (27 September 1929 – 14 January 2012), better known by his pseudonym Txillardegi, was a Basque linguist, politician and writer from Spain. <s> Born in San Sebastián (Basque Country, Spain), he did not learn the Basque language until the age of 17, but came to be considered one of the most influential figures in Basque nationalism and culture in the second half of the 20th century. <s> After becoming disillusioned with the PNV, Txillardegi was one of the founders of ETA in 1959, together with a group of young nationalists and was the visible leader of the cultural branch of the movement. <s> In 1961 he fled into exile, in Paris and Brussels, returning in 1967.
simple: José Luis Álvarez Enparantza (27 September 1929 – 14 January 2012) was a Basque linguist, politician and writer. <s> When writing he used the pseudonym Txillardegi. <s> He was born in Donostia, which is called "San Sebastian" in Spanish. <s> Even though he did not learn the Basque language until he was 17, he came to be seen as one of the most influential figures in Basque nationalism and culture in the second half of the 20th century. <s> Together with some friends he started ETA in 1959, and became responsible for their social and cultural activities.

title: Wii Party U
complex: Wii Party U (Japanese: Wiiパーティ・U , Hepburn: Wī Pāti Yū ) is a party video game developed and published by Nintendo for the Wii U in 2013. <s> It was announced in a January 2013 Nintendo Direct, and later detailed at E3 2013 and the October 2013 Nintendo Direct. <s> It is the sequel to the 2010 Wii game "Wii Party". <s> "Wii Party U" is a multiplayer video game consisting of a standard board game with mini-games, similar to "Mario Party". <s> Over 80 different new mini-games are available. <s> Multiple people can play mini-games using the Wii U GamePad. <s> Wii Party U also includes a new accessory, a stand for the Wii U GamePad to allow support for the tabletop games.
simple: Wii Party U is a party video game for the Wii U game console. <s> It is the sequel to "Wii Party". <s> "Wii Party U" is a party video game which takes elements from the "Mario Party" series. <s> It has over 80 minigames. <s> Players are able to play minigames with the Wii U GamePad.

title: Cashew
complex: The cashew tree ("Anacardium occidentale") is a tropical evergreen tree that produces the cashew seed and the cashew apple. <s> It can grow as high as 14 m , but the dwarf cashew, growing up to 6 m , has proved more profitable, with earlier maturity and higher yields. <s> While the cashew plant is native to northeast Brazil, the Portuguese took it to Goa, India, between 1560 and 1565. <s> From there, it spread throughout Southeast Asia and eventually Africa.
simple: The cashew is a tropical tree in the flowering plant. <s> The plant is native to northeastern Brazil.

title: Elena Anaya
complex: Elena Anaya Gutiérrez (born 17 July 1975) is a Spanish actress whose career started in 1995. <s> She starred alongside Antonio Banderas in Pedro Almodóvar's "The Skin I Live In", for which she won the Goya award for Best Actress. <s> She is also known for her roles in "Van Helsing", "Habitación en Roma" "(Room in Rome)" and "Wonder Woman". <s> In November 2016, it was announced that Anaya was expecting her first child with her partner, Tina Afugu Cordero, a costume designer. <s> In February 2017, Anaya gave birth to their son.
simple: Elena Anaya Gutiérrez (born July 17, 1975) is a Spanish actress. <s> Her career dates back to 1995. <s> She starred alongside Antonio Banderas in Pedro Almodóvar's "The Skin I Live In", for which she won the Goya award for Best Actress. <s> She is also known for her roles in "Habitación en Roma" "(Room in Rome)" and "Wonder Woman" as Doctor Poison. <s> In November 2016, it was announced that Anaya was expecting her first child with her partner, Tina Afugu Cordero, a costume designer. <s> In February 2017, Anaya gave birth to their son.

title: John Howes
complex: John Forman Howes (June 19, 1924 – February 4, 2017) was a Professor of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia (UBC) for over three decades. <s> Howes began his studies of the Japanese language in 1944 at the I.T.S. Naval School of Oriental Languages, and served as a translator in the general headquarters of the Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers Occupation of Japan. <s> Returning to the United States, he obtained an undergraduate degree at Oberlin College, and then an MA from Columbia University with a thesis entitled "Uchimura Kanzō; a biographical sketch", followed by a 1965 Ph.D for "Japan's enigma, the young Uchimura Kanzō". <s> Even before completing his doctoral work, in 1961, he joined the Department of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia, rising to the rank of Professor, and then Emeritus Professor. <s> After retirement from UBC, he taught at Obirin University, near Tokyo. <s> In 2003, Howes was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun by the Emperor of Japan for his contributions to the Canada-Japan community.
simple: John Forman Howes ORS (June 19, 1924 – February 4, 2017) was an American educator. <s> He was the Professor of Asian Studies at the University of British Columbia (UBC) for over 30 years. <s> Howes died on February 4, 2017 in Vancouver, British Columbia, aged 92. <s> After retirement from UBC, he taught at Obirin University, near Tokyo. <s> In 2003, Howes was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun by the Emperor of Japan for his outstanding contributions to the Canada-Japan community.

title: Fractional distillation
complex: Fractional distillation is the separation of a mixture into its component parts, or fractions. <s> Chemical compounds are separated by heating them to a temperature at which one or more fractions of the mixture will vaporize. <s> It uses distillation to fractionate. <s> Generally the component parts have boiling points that differ by less than 25 C from each other under a pressure of one atmosphere. <s> If the difference in boiling points is greater than 25 °C, a simple distillation is typically used. <s> Fractional distillation is the most common form of separation technology used in petroleum refineries, petrochemical and chemical plants, natural gas processing and cryogenic air separation plants. <s> In most cases, the distillation is operated at a continuous steady state.
simple: Fractional distillation is a process of separating a mixture of chemical compounds. <s> Fractional distillation is done by heating the mixture so that each fraction evaporates and then condenses in its own compartment. <s> Generally, the component parts boil at less than 25°C from each other under a pressure of one atmosphere (atm). <s> If the difference in boiling points is greater than 25°C, a simple distillation is used. <s> Fractional distillation is the main activity of oil refineries.

title: Burdwan division
complex: Burdwan Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.
simple: Burdwan Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.

title: Interstate 74
complex: Interstate 74 (I-74) is an Interstate Highway in the midwestern and southeastern United States. <s> Its western end is at an interchange with Interstate 80 in Davenport, Iowa (Quad Cities); the eastern end of its Midwest segment is at an interchange with Interstate 75 in Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> The major cities that I-74 connects to includes Davenport, Iowa; Peoria, Illinois; Champaign, Illinois; Indianapolis, Indiana; and Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> I-74 also exists as several disconnected sections of highways in North Carolina. <s> Two sections of I-74 in North Carolina are currently under construction. <s> These include building the first part of a bypass of Rockingham with Interstate 73 by reconstructing US 220 to interstate standards for 4 miles south of Ellerbe and is scheduled to be completed in 2018 and the first segment of the Eastern Half of the Winston-Salem Northern Beltway which is constructing 4 mi of the future I-74 freeway between Business 40/US 421 and U.S. 158, this project should also be completed by 2018.
simple: Interstate 74 is an Interstate Highway in the United States. <s> The main part of it goes from Davenport, Iowa east to Cincinnati, Ohio. <s> There are three parts of Interstate 74 that are in North Carolina, with no part being connected. <s> All four parts of Interstate 74 will become part of one road.

title: Pietà (Michelangelo)
complex: The Pietà (] ; ; 1498–1499) is a work of Renaissance sculpture by Michelangelo Buonarroti, housed in St. Peter's Basilica, Vatican City. <s> It is the first of a number of works of the same theme by the artist.
simple: The Pieta is a statue by Michelangelo. <s> It is now in the first temple on the right of Saint Peter's Basilica in the Vatican City.

title: Throat culture
complex: A throat culture is a laboratory diagnostic test that evaluates for the presence of a bacterial or fungal infection in the throat. <s> A sample from the throat is collected by swabbing the throat and placing the sample into a special cup (culture) that allows infections to grow.
simple: A throat culture is a medical test which looks for bacteria or fungus that cause infections in the throat.

title: Koror City
complex: Koror City is the largest city in Palau, home to about half of the country's population. <s> It was formerly the capital until it was replaced by Ngerulmud in 2006.

title: Grigoriy Bronza
complex: Grigoriy Zakharovich Bronza ( ; 30 April 192730 January 2010) was a prominent artist of Transnistria (Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic). <s> He was an art restorer and an honorary member of the Transnistria Union of Artists. <s> Bronza was a designer of postage stamps of Transnistria and Moldova. <s> He also helped create a number of museums in the former Soviet Union. <s> During World War II, Grigoriy Bronza served in the Red Army and was awarded the following Soviet military decorations: Bronza is the author of the first stamps of Moldova issued in June 1991. <s> He designed the first stamps of the Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic issued in December 1993. <s> Bronza designed the third definitive stamp issue of Transnistria (1997). <s> He also created a series of stamps for the 5th anniversary of the events in Bendery (1997), a series of stamps "Historical and modern coats of arms of cities of Transnistria" (1999), the 200th anniversary of Alexander Pushkin issue (1999), etc.
simple: Grigoriy Zakharovich Bronza (30 April 192730 January 2010) was an artist of Transnistria (Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic). <s> He was an art restorer and an honorary member of the Transnistria Union of Artists. <s> Bronza was a designer of postage stamps of Transnistria and Moldova. <s> He also helped create a number of museums in the former Soviet Union. <s> During World War II, Grigoriy Bronza served in the Red Army and was awarded the following Soviet military decorations: Bronza is the author of the first stamps of Moldova issued in June 1991. <s> He designed the first stamps of the Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic issued in December 1993. <s> Bronza designed the third definitive stamp issue of Transnistria (1997). <s> He also created a series of stamps for the 5th anniversary of the events in Bender (1997), a series of stamps "Historical and modern coats of arms of cities of Transnistria" (1999), and the 200th anniversary of Alexander Pushkin issue (1999).

title: Lillehammer
complex: Lillehammer (] ) is a town and municipality in Oppland county, Norway. <s> It is part of the traditional region of Gudbrandsdal.

title: Manfred Porsch
complex: Manfred Maria Porsch (born 14 April 1950 in Vienna) is a composer of Austrian contemporary worship music and a teacher. <s> Manfred Porsch comes from the Focolare Movement. <s> In 1971 and 1972 he toured with Gen Rosso. <s> In 1983 he won the first prize at the "World Festival of the Religious Song", the "Rassegna Mondiale della Canzone Religiosa Populare" in Rom. <s> In 1987 Porsch founded "Musica e Vita Österreich" and initiated the festival series "Fest der Lieder". <s> He published about 200 songs on more than 20 albums. <s> After a long musical break, in 2012 Porsch published new songs together with the producer Thomas Raber.
simple: Manfred Maria Porsch (born 14 April 1950 in Vienna) is an Austrian composer and teacher. <s> He composes Austrian contemporary worship music. <s> Manfred Porsch comes from the Focolare Movement. <s> In 1971 and 1972, he toured with Gen Rosso. <s> In 1983, he won first prize at the "Worldfestival of religious Song", the "" in Rome. <s> In 1987, Porsch founded "" and started the festival series "Fest der Lieder". <s> He has published about 200 songs. <s> In 2012, after a long break from writing music, Porsch published new songs with the producer Thomas Raber.

title: Hana Orgoníková
complex: Hana Orgoníková (8 December 1946 – 5 June 2014) was a Czech politician. <s> She was an MP for the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSDP) from 1989 until her death. <s> Orgoníková was born in Přibyslav, Czechoslovakia. <s> She was divorced and had two children, Vladimír and Lucie. <s> Orgoníková died following a long illness on 5 June 2014 in Hradec Králové, Czech Republic, aged 67.
simple: Hana Orgoníková (8 December 1946 – 5 June 2014) was a Czech politician. <s> She was an MP for the Czech Social Democratic Party (CSDP) from 1989 until her death. <s> Orgoníková was born in Přibyslav, Czechoslovakia. <s> She was divorced and had two children, Vladimír and Lucie. <s> Orgoníková died after a long illness on 5 June 2014 in Hradec Králové, Czech Republic, aged 67.

title: Wood Buffalo National Park
complex: Wood Buffalo National Park is the largest National Park of Canada at 44807 sqkm . <s> It is located in northeastern Alberta and the southern Northwest Territories. <s> Larger in area than Switzerland, it is the second-largest national park in the world. <s> The park was established in 1922 to protect the world's largest herd of free roaming wood bison, currently estimated at more than 5,000. <s> It is one of two known nesting sites of whooping cranes. <s> This area was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 for the biological diversity of the Peace-Athabasca Delta, one of the world's largest freshwater deltas, as well as the population of wild bison. <s> Wood Buffalo National Park contains a large variety of wildlife species, such as moose, bison, great grey owls, black bears, hawks, spotted owls, timber wolves, lynxes, beavers, snowy owls, marmots, bald eagles, martens, wolverines, peregrine falcons, whooping cranes, snowshoe hares, sandhill cranes, ruffed grouses, and the world's northernmost population of red-sided garter snakes, which form communal dens within the park. <s> Wood Buffalo Park contains the only natural nesting habitat for the endangered whooping crane. <s> Known as Whooping Crane Summer Range, it is classified as a Ramsar site.
simple: Wood Buffalo National Park is a national park and the largest one in Canada. <s> The park is located in northeastern Alberta and southern Northwest Territories. <s> It was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983 because of it's biological diversity of the Peace-Athabasca Delta, which is one of the world's largest freshwater deltas, as well as the population of wild bison. <s> The park is also populated by moose, wood bison, black bear, wolf, lynx, beaver, brown bear, snowshoe hare, Sandhill Crane, Ruffed Grouse, and the world's northernmost population of Red-sided Garter Snakes. <s> Inside the park is the only natural nesting habitat for the endangered Whooping Crane.

title: Beersel
complex: Beersel (] ) is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant. <s> The municipality comprises the towns of Alsemberg, Beersel proper, Dworp, Huizingen and Lot.
simple: Beersel is a municipality in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant.

title: Liberal Party (UK)
complex: The Liberal Party was one of the two major parties in the United Kingdom with the opposing Conservative Party in the 19th and early 20th centuries. <s> The party arose from an alliance of Whigs and free trade Peelites and Radicals favourable to the ideals of the American and French Revolutions in the 1850s. <s> By the end of the 19th century, it had formed four governments under William Gladstone. <s> Despite being divided over the issue of Irish Home Rule, the party returned to government in 1905 and then won a landslide victory in the following year's general election. <s> Under Prime Ministers Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman (1905–1908) and H. H. Asquith (1908–1916), the Liberal Party passed the welfare reforms that created a basic British welfare state. <s> Although Asquith was the party's leader, its dominant figure was David Lloyd George. <s> Asquith was overwhelmed by the wartime role of coalition Prime Minister and Lloyd George replaced him as Prime Minister in late 1916, but Asquith remained as Liberal Party leader. <s> The pair fought for years over control of the party, badly weakening it in the process. <s> The government of Lloyd George was dominated by the Conservative Party, which finally deposed him in 1922. <s> By the end of the 1920s, the Labour Party had replaced the Liberals as the Conservatives' main rival. <s> The party went into decline after 1918 and by the 1950s won no more than six seats at general elections. <s> Apart from notable by-election victories, its fortunes did not improve significantly until it formed the SDP–Liberal Alliance with the newly formed Social Democratic Party (SDP) in 1981. <s> At the 1983 general election, the Alliance won over a quarter of the vote, but only 23 of the 650 seats it contested. <s> At the 1987 general election, its share of the vote fell below 23% and the Liberal and Social Democratic parties merged in 1988 to form the Liberal Democrats. <s> A splinter group reconstituted the Liberal Party in 1989.
simple: It was one of the two big political parties in the United Kingdom in the 19th and early 20th century. <s> The party came from an alliance of Whigs and free-trade Peelites and radicals in the 1850s. <s> In the next 50 years it formed four governments under William Gladstone. <s> The party split over the issue of Irish Home Rule. <s> They introduced the welfare reforms that created a basic British welfare state. <s> H. H. Asquith was Liberal Prime Minister between 1908 and 1916. <s> He was followed by David Lloyd George, whose premiership lasted until 1922. <s> By the end of the 1920s, the Labour Party had replaced the Liberals as the Conservatives' main rival. <s> The party went into decline. <s> By the 1950s, it won no more than six seats at general elections. <s> Apart from notable by-election victories, the party's fortunes did not improve significantly until it formed the SDP-Liberal Alliance with the newly formed Social Democratic Party (SDP) in 1981. <s> At the 1983 General Election, the Alliance won over a quarter of the vote, but only 23 of the 650 seats it contested. <s> At the 1987 General Election, it won less than 23% of the vote. <s> The Liberal and Social Democratic parties merged in 1988 to form the Liberal Democrats.

title: Quranism
complex: Quranism ( ; "al-Qur'āniyya") comprises views that Islamic law and guidance should only be based on the Qur'an, thus opposing the religious authority, reliability, and/or authenticity of hadith literature. <s> Quranists believe that God's message in the Quran is clear and complete as it is, and that it can therefore be fully understood without referencing the Hadith. <s> Quranists affirm that the Hadith literature which exists today is apocryphal, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet Muhammad; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. <s> Adherents of Quranic Islam are referred to as "Quranists" , or "People of the Quran" . <s> This should not be confused with Ahle-e-Quran, which is an organisation formed by Abdullah Chakralawi.
simple: Quranism (; "al-Qur'āniyya") is the belief that the Quran is the only source for Islam. <s> Quranists reject the Hadiths as they believe that the Hadith literature which exists today is apocryphal, as it had been written three centuries after the death of the Islamic prophet Muhammad; thus, it cannot have the same status as the Quran. <s> Followers of the group are called Quranist Muslims, or Quran alone Muslims or Quraniyoon.

title: John Abbot (poet)
complex: John Abbot (1587/1588 – c. 1650) was an English Roman Catholic clergyman and poet. <s> Abbot's birthplace is uncertain, but may have been London or Leicester. <s> He is believed to be the nephew both of George Abbot, the Archbishop of Canterbury and Robert Abbot, the bishop of Salisbury. <s> He was thus from a strongly Protestant family. <s> After being educated at Balliol College, Oxford, he travelled to the continent where he converted to Roman Catholicism. <s> On returning to England he was in Jesuit orders for a while, before working as a secular priest. <s> In 1635 he was imprisoned in the Gatehouse at the Palace of Westminster. <s> He was released within a year, but in 1637 he was again arrested, and seems to have spent the rest of his life in prison. <s> He was, along with other Catholic priests, condemned to death in 1641, but the conviction was never executed, and he appears to have died in prison in 1650. <s> Abbot's best known work is his poem "Devout Rhapsodies" (2 vols., 1647), about the war in heaven and the temptation and fall of man. <s> The work can be seen as a precursor of Milton's "Paradise Lost".
simple: John Abbot (1587/1588 – c. 1650) was an English Roman Catholic priest and poet. <s> Nobody knows where he was born, he might have been from either London or Leicester. <s> Abbot was from a strongly Protestant family because he was the nephew of George Abbot, the Archbishop of Canterbury, but after being educated at Balliol College, Oxford, he travelled to the European continent where he was converted to Roman Catholicism. <s> On returning to England he was in Jesuit orders for a while, before working as a priest. <s> In 1635 he was put in jail. <s> He was released within a year, but in 1637 he was again arrested, and spent the rest of his life in prison. <s> His best known work is his poem "Devout Rhapsodies" (2 vols., 1647), about the war between Good and Evil and the temptation and fall of man.

title: Paul Petersen
complex: Paul William Petersen (born September 23, 1945) is an American actor, singer, novelist, and activist. <s> Petersen began his show business career at the age of ten as a Mouseketeer on the "Mickey Mouse Club". <s> He appeared in the 1958 movie "Houseboat" with Sophia Loren and Cary Grant, but achieved stardom playing teenager Jeff Stone from 1958 to 1966 on the ABC family television sitcom "The Donna Reed Show".
simple: William Paul Petersen (born September 23, 1945) is an American actor and comedian, best known for portraying Jeff Stone on "The Donna Reed Show". <s> He began his show business career at the age of 10 as a Mouseketeer on the "Mickey Mouse Club".

title: Anthony Mamo
complex: Sir Anthony Joseph Mamo, KUOM OBE QC (9 January 1909 – 1 May 2008) was the first President of Malta and previously served as the last Governor-General of the State of Malta before the country became a republic. <s> He was also the first Maltese citizen to be appointed Governor-General, and before independence, briefly served as acting Governor. <s> Mamo died on 1 May 2008 at the age of 99, at Casa Arkati Home for Elderly.
simple: Sir Anthony Joseph Mamo, KUOM OBE QC (9 January 1909 – 1 May 2008) was a Maltese politician. <s> He was the first President of Malta. <s> He was the last Governor-General of the State of Malta before the country became a republic. <s> Mamo died on 1 May 2008 at the age of 99, at Casa Arkati Home for Elderly.

title: Syd Ward (cricketer)
complex: Sydney William "Syd" Ward (5 August 1907 – 31 December 2010) was an Australian-born New Zealand cricketer. <s> Ward was a right-handed batsman who bowled right-arm medium pace. <s> He was born in Sydney, New South Wales, and, from the death of Frank Shipston on 6 July 2005 until his death, was considered the oldest living first-class cricketer and the second oldest ever, behind Jim Hutchinson. <s> Following his death, Cyril Perkins became the oldest living first-class cricketer.
simple: Sydney William Ward (born 5 August 1907 – died 31 December 2010) ) was an Australian-born New Zealand cricketer. <s> Ward was a right-handed batsman who bowled right-arm medium pace. <s> He was born in Sydney, New South Wales. <s> He is the second longest-lived cricketer, behind England's Jim Hutchinson, who at the time of his death was 103 years and 344 days old.

complex: Lixy is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Lixy is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

simple: Versonnex is a commune.

title: Dax, Landes
complex: Dax (] ; "Dacs" in Occitan) is a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in southwestern France, sub-prefecture of the Landes department. <s> It is known as a spa, specialising in mud treatment for rheumatism and similar ailments. <s> It was first established by the Romans, and its reputation is supposed to date from a visit by Julia, the daughter of the first Emperor Octavian Augustus. <s> Its Roman name was "Civitas Aquensium". <s> In the Middle Ages, it was administered by viscounts until 1177. <s> With the acquisition of Aquitaine by Henry II Plantagenet, later King of England, Dax remained under English rule until 1451, when it was conquered by French troops before the end of the Hundred Years' War. <s> It successfully withstood a Spanish siege in 1521-1522.
simple: Dax ("Dacs" in Gascon) is a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in south-western France, sub-prefecture of the Landes department. <s> It is well-known spa town, specialising in mud treatment for rheumatism and similar medical problems. <s> Dax was first established by the Romans, and its name was "Civitas Aquensium". <s> In the Middle Ages, it was administered by viscounts until 1177. <s> when Henry II Plantagenet, later King of England, got the Aquitaine. <s> Dax remained under the English rule until 1451, when it was conquered by the French troops before the end of the Hundred Years' War.

title: John McLaughlin (host)
complex: John Joseph McLaughlin ( ; March 29, 1927 – August 16, 2016) was an American television personality and political commentator. <s> He created, produced, and hosted the political commentary series "The McLaughlin Group." <s> He also hosted and produced "John McLaughlin's One on One" which ran from 1984 to 2013. <s> McLaughlin was originally a supporter of the Democratic Party and opposed the Vietnam War, but then became a war supporter and changed his party affiliation to Republican. <s> In 1970 he sought permission from the Jesuit order to run for a seat in the United States Senate, representing Rhode Island. <s> They had given permission to fellow Jesuit Father Robert Drinan who ran successfully for the United States House of Representatives in Massachusetts.
simple: John McLaughlin (March 29, 1927 – August 16, 2016) was an American television personality and producer, politician, writer, and political commentator. <s> He created and hosts the long-running political commentary series "The McLaughlin Group" as well as "John McLaughlin's One On One". <s> He also ran for senator of Rhode Island in 1970, but lost the election to incumbent John O. Pastore.

title: Bass Highway, Tasmania
complex: The Bass Highway is a highway in Tasmania, Australia. <s> It is a part of the National Highway, designated as National Highway 1 and connects the major cities across the north of the state - Burnie, Devonport and Launceston. <s> The road was named due to its proximity to the Bass Strait. <s> Other bypasses have included Carrick and Hadspen in the late 1980s and the longest stretch of highway, the Hagley-Westbury bypass, which was completed in 2001. <s> The 'old' highway alignment between Deloraine and Hadspen is now known as Meander Valley Road, and is promoted as a tourist route. <s> The Bass Highway is, like Bass Strait, named for explorer George Bass.
simple: The Bass Highway is a highway in Tasmania, Australia. <s> It is a part of the National Highway, named National Highway 1. <s> It joins the major cities across the north of the state - Burnie, Devonport and Launceston. <s> Between Launceston and Deloraine, this had included Carrick and Hadspen in the 1980s and Deloraine in the early 1990s. <s> The longest stretch of highway, the Hagley-Westbury bypass, was completed in 2001. <s> The 'old' highway, now known as the Meander Valley Highway, is promoted as a tourist route. <s> The Bass Highway is, like Bass Strait, named for explorer George Bass.

title: Strait of Magellan
complex: The Strait of Magellan , also called the "Straits of Magellan", is a navigable sea route in southern Chile separating mainland South America to the north and Tierra del Fuego to the south. <s> The strait is the most important natural passage between the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
simple: It is just south of mainland South America and north of Tierra del Fuego. <s> The Strait of Magellan is a passageway from the Atlantic Ocean to the Pacific.

title: Ashurbanipal
complex: Ashurbanipal ( ; 'Ashur is the creator of an heir'), also spelled Assurbanipal or Ashshurbanipal, was King of the Neo-Assyrian Empire from 668 BC to c. 627 BC, the son of Esarhaddon and the last strong ruler of the empire, which is usually dated between 934 and 609 BC. <s> He is famed for amassing a significant collection of cuneiform documents for his royal palace at Nineveh. <s> This collection, known as the Library of Ashurbanipal, is now in the British Museum, which also holds the famous "Lion Hunt of Ashurbanipal" set of Assyrian palace reliefs. <s> In the Hebrew Bible he is called Asenappar ( - ). <s> Roman historian Justinus identified him as Sardanapalus, although the fictional Sardanapalus is depicted as the last king of Assyria and an ineffectual, effete and debauched character, whereas four further kings succeeded Ashurbanipal, who was in fact an educated, efficient, highly capable and ambitious warrior king.
simple: Ashurbanipal (685 BC – 627 BC), the son of Esarhaddon, was the last great king of the Neo-Assyrian Empire. <s> In the Bible he is called Asenappar. <s> Roman historian Justinus identified him as Sardanapalus, and describes him as effeminate.

title: Electrical substation
complex: A substation is a part of an electrical generation, transmission, and distribution system. <s> Substations transform voltage from high to low, or the reverse, or perform any of several other important functions. <s> Between the generating station and consumer, electric power may flow through several substations at different voltage levels. <s> A substation may include transformers to change voltage levels between high transmission voltages and lower distribution voltages, or at the interconnection of two different transmission voltages.
simple: An electrical substation is a subsidiary station of an electricity generation, transmission and distribution system where voltage is transformed from high to low or the reverse using transformers. <s> Electric power may flow through several substations between generating plant and consumer, and may be changed in voltage in several steps.

title: House of Representatives
complex: House of Representatives is the name of legislative bodies in many countries and sub-national entitles. <s> In many countries, the House of Representatives is the lower house of a bicameral legislature, with the corresponding upper house often called a "Senate". <s> In some countries, the House of Representatives is the sole chamber of a unicameral legislature.
simple: A House of Representatives is a part of some legislatures, which are law-making bodies. <s> In a House of Representatives, the members are called representatives. <s> One of these parts is called the House of Representatives and the other one is called the Senate. <s> Many state legislatures in the United States also have Houses of Representatives.

title: Skyland (Washington, D.C.)
complex: Skyland is a neighborhood in Southeast Washington, D.C. <s> It is bounded by Good Hope Road to the northeast, Alabama Avenue to the southeast, and Fort Stanton Park to the south and west. <s> Also see article on Anacostia. <s> The District is in the midst of redeveloping the 18 acre Skyland Shopping Center at Alabama Avenue and Naylor Road, SE in Ward 7 into a mixed-used town center. <s> The District is working with the Rappaport Cos. and the William S. Smith Cos. on a master plan for the site. <s> Initial plans for Skyland Town Center call for more than 320000 sqft of retail space—a combination of high-quality, large format national-brand retailers and neighborhood serving shops and restaurants. <s> The project will also include 420 to 470 units of housing, about 80 percent of the units will be condos and 20 percent will be apartments. <s> The development team expects to have its master plan completed and a Planned Unit Development (PUD) application filed with the Zoning Commission by the spring of 2008. <s> The District and development team are negotiating the business terms of their agreement. <s> The DC Council has already approved a Tax Increment Financing (TIF) package to provide gap financing for the project. <s> Skyland is within the Good Hope neighborhood and borders Hillcrest to the east and Naylor Gardens to the southeast.
simple: Skyland is a neighborhood in Southeast Washington, D.C. <s> It is next to Good Hope Road to the northeast, Alabama Avenue to the southeast, and Fort Stanton Park to the south and west. <s> The District government wants to rebuild the 18 acre Skyland Shopping Center at Alabama Avenue and Naylor Road, SE in Ward 7 into a mixed-used town center. <s> The District is working with the Rappaport Cos. and the William S. Smith Cos. on a new plan for Skyland. <s> They want to build 320000 sqft of retail space. <s> They hope that the new buildings will be filled with high-quality, national stores and locally-owned shops and restaurants. <s> The project will also include 420 to 470 units of housing. <s> About 80 percent of the housing units will be owned by the people who live there and 20 percent will be rented. <s> Rappaport and Smith filed a Planned Unit Development (PUD) application with the Zoning Commission in 2008. <s> The DC Council approved a Tax Increment Financing (TIF) package to loan money for the new buildings. <s> Skyland is a part of the Good Hope neighborhood. <s> Hillcrest to the east and Naylor Gardens to the southeast of the Good Hope neighborhood.

title: Paul Mebus
complex: Paul Mebus (9 June 1920 – 11 December 1993) was a German footballer. <s> He was part of the West German team that won the 1954 FIFA World Cup. <s> He earned six caps for West Germany and played twice for the German 'B-team'. <s> During his club career he played for VfL 06 Benrath and 1.
simple: Paul Mebus (9 June 1920 - 12 December 1993) was a German football player. <s> He played for West Germany national team.

complex: Fedio (also spelled Fedyo; ) is a Syrian village located in Latakia Governorate. <s> Fedio had a population of 4,065 in the 2004 census.

complex: Saint-Nicolas or Saint-Nicolas-lez-Arras is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Saint-Nicolas, Pas-de-Calais is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Sorry I'm Late
complex: Sorry I'm Late is the second studio album by English recording artist Cher Lloyd. <s> It was released on 27 May 2014, by Epic Records, Syco Music, and Mr. Kanani. <s> Lloyd herself co-wrote five songs on the album, working with new producers and songwriters such as Beth Ditto and Tove Lo. <s> It is her last album released through Epic and Syco. <s> On 16 October 2013, Lloyd told "Billboard" that the title of her second studio album is "Sorry I'm Late". <s> She explained, "I think it has two meanings. <s> ... It's been a long time since I've actually done anything new, but for me, it's as a person. <s> I mean, I've spent a whole lot of time trying to figure out who I am, and I think everybody goes through that." <s> In November 2013, during an interview with Larry King, Lloyd confirmed that she had left Syco Music after she and Cowell disagreed about her career path in music. <s> Lloyd also confirmed that "Sorry I'm Late", which was originally due for release in November, was pushed back until early 2014, despite the record being done. <s> She remarked, "My album got pushed back and I'm not happy about it. <s> It's all done, but I am currently in the studio for the rest of this week to try and find some more magic. <s> ... It was meant to be coming out in November. <s> Now I think it's going to be early next year." <s> The explicit version of the album artwork depicts Lloyd smoking while sitting in a bathtub; censored pressings of the record remove the smoke. <s> On 20 May 2014, one week before the release, Lloyd made the album available for online stream on MTV.com.
simple: Sorry I'm Late is the second studio album by English recording artist Cher Lloyd. <s> It was released on 23 May 2014 by Epic Records, Syco Music and Mr. Kanani. <s> Lloyd herself co-wrote five songs on the tracklist, working with new producers and songwriters such as Beth Ditto and Tove Lo. <s> It is her last album released through Epic and Syco. <s> On 16 October 2013, Lloyd told "Billboard" that the title of her second studio album is "Sorry I'm Late". <s> She explained, "I think it has two meanings. <s> ... It's been a long time since I've actually done anything new, but for me, it's as a person. <s> I mean, I've spent a whole lot of time trying to figure out who I am, and I think everybody goes through that." <s> Lloyd confirmed that "Sorry I'm Late", which was originally due for release in November, was pushed back until early 2014, despite the record being done. <s> The explicit version of the album artwork depicts Lloyd smoking while sitting in a bathtub; censored pressings of the record remove the smoke.

title: Eagle Pass, Texas
complex: Eagle Pass is a city in and the county seat of Maverick County in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> The population was 26,255 as of the 2010 census (2013 estimate 27,708).
simple: Eagle Pass is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Maverick County.

title: Ruslan Salei
complex: Ruslan Albiertavič Saliej (Belarusian: Руслан Альбертавіч Салей; November 2, 1974 – September 7, 2011), better known as Ruslan Salei (Russian: Руслан Альбертович Салей), was a Belarusian professional ice hockey player. <s> Salei played 14 seasons in the National Hockey League (NHL) for the Detroit Red Wings, Colorado Avalanche, Florida Panthers and the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, the latter of which selected him ninth overall in the 1996 NHL Entry Draft. <s> On September 7, 2011, at 4:02 PM local time, the Yakovlev Yak-42 passenger aircraft, carrying nearly the entire Lokomotiv Yaroslavl hockey team crashed near Yaroslavl, Russia, en route to Minsk, Belarus, to begin the 2011–12 season. <s> Salei was 1 of the 44 passengers and crew to die in the crash.
simple: Ruslan "Rusty" Salei (Belarusian: Руслан Салей; November 2, 1974 – September 7, 2011) was a Belarusian professional ice hockey player. <s> During 14 seasons in the National Hockey League (NHL) he played for the Detroit Red Wings, Colorado Avalanche, Florida Panthers and the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim. <s> On September 7, 2011, the Yakovlev Yak-42 passenger aircraft, carrying the entire Lokomotiv team including Salei crashed near Yaroslavl on its way to Minsk, Belarus.

title: Maurane
complex: Claudine Luypaerts, better known as Maurane (] ; 12 November 1960 – 7 May 2018), was a Belgian singer and actress. <s> Claudine Luypaerts was born on 12 November 1960 in Ixelles, Brussels, to Guy-Philippe Luypaerts, a composer and director of Académie de Musique of Verviers, and Jeannie Patureaux, a piano teacher. <s> When she was a teenager she took part in several musical contests. <s> In 2012, she became a member of the Jury in "Nouvelle Star" broadcast on television station D8. <s> She and singer Pablo Villafranca had a daughter. <s> On 7 May 2018 Maurane was found dead at the age of 57 beside her bathtub at her home in Schaerbeek in the area of Brussels, Belgium.. <s> The following day, the magistrate of the Brussels public prosecutor's office confirms the opening of a judicial inquiry, although the death of the singer is not considered as suspect.
simple: Maurane (born Claudine Luypaerts; 12 November 1960 – 7 May 2018) was a Belgian singer and actress. <s> She was born in Ixelles, Belgium. <s> In 2012, she became a member of the Jury in "Nouvelle Star" broadcast on television station D8. <s> Maurane died in Schaerbeek, Belgian on 7 May 2018 of suspected cardiac arrest at the age of 57.

title: Pell City, Alabama
complex: Pell City is a city in St. Clair County, Alabama, United States. <s> The city is the county seat of St. Clair County along with Ashville. <s> At the 2000 census the population was 9,565. <s> At the 2010 census, the city-limit population jumped to 12,695.
simple: Pell City is a city in St. Clair County, Alabama, United States. <s> The city is the county seat of St. Clair County along with Ashville. <s> At the 2010 census the population was 12,695.

title: The Maccabees (band)
complex: The Maccabees were an English indie rock band, formed in 2004 in London. <s> They released four albums: "Colour It In" in 2007, followed by "Wall of Arms" in 2009, "Given to the Wild" which was released on 9 January 2012 and their last album "Marks to Prove It" released on 31 July 2015. <s> The band announced that they decided to disband in August 2016, with farewell gigs in 2017. <s> The band came up with the name by flicking through the Bible and picking out a random word. <s> Despite adopting a name with perceived religious connotations, lead singer Orlando Weeks has more recently affirmed, in an interview on Steve Lamacq's BBC 6 Music show, that none of the band is religious. <s> Notwithstanding, Maccabees are referred to in the Bible. <s> Their debut single, "X-Ray", was released on Promise records on 28 November 2005, and received some evening play on London radio station Xfm London. <s> They received little significant exposure, however, until six months later, when they released their second single, "Latchmere", the subject of which is the wave machine at the Latchmere Leisure Centre in Battersea, South London, on Fierce Panda Records in April 2006. <s> This was championed by Radio 1 DJ Steve Lamacq and received airtime on MTV2. <s> The video, directed by Hugh Frost and Samuel Bebbington, also proved an internet hit after it was posted on YouTube. <s> They had their first taste of festivals by playing on the Carling stage of the Leeds/Reading festival in 2006. <s> The band were signed to major label Fiction Records, and released their debut album "Colour It In" in May 2007. <s> Because an early copy of the album appeared on the "New York Times" website, "Colour It In" became available to download exclusively from iTunes on 16 December, before its physical release on 14 May, in an effort to combat the leak. <s> The single "First Love" was their first to chart in the UK top 40, and was followed by "About Your Dress", which peaked at No. 33. <s> Their album received positive reviews, and charted at No. 24. <s> They then toured the United States with fellow indie group Bloc Party. <s> A full UK tour followed from October 2007, culminating in a sell-out show at the Roundhouse venue in London.
simple: The Maccabees are a English indie band based in Brighton. <s> The band thought of the name 'The Maccabees' by opening the Bible to a random page. <s> Even though the name has religious meaning, lead singer Orlando Weeks said that none of the band are religious in an interview on Steve Lamacq's BBC Radio 1 show. <s> The Maccabees' debut single, 'X-Ray', was released on the Promise record label on 28 November 2005. <s> It was played a little in the evenings on London radio station Xfm London. <s> The band got very attentiong until six months later, when they released their second single, 'Latchmere'. <s> It was released on Fierce Panda Records in April 2006. <s> This song was talked about by Radio 1 DJ Steve Lamacqu and was played on MTV2. <s> The video, directed by Hugh Frost and Samuel Bebbington, also became a hit after it was put on YouTube. <s> The band are currently signed to Fiction Records, and released their debut album 'Colour It In' in May 2007. <s> Because the album had been leaked, or accidentally put, on the internet, 'Colour It In' became available to download exclusively from iTunes on 17 April before its release on 14 May. <s> The song First Love was the Maccabees' first to chart in the UK top 40. <s> It was followed by 'About Your Dress', which charted at #33. <s> Their next album was released to positive reviews, and charted at #24. <s> They toured the USA with fellow Indie group Bloc Party. <s> A UK tour happened in October 2007, ending in a show at the Roundhouse venue in London, where all the tickets were sold.

title: Ghats (mountains)
complex: Ghats refer to two converging mountain ranges in south-eastern India, called the Eastern Ghats and Western Ghats, running along the eastern and western seaboards of the country.
simple: The Ghats are two mountain ranges at the eastern and western edges of the Deccan Plateau in southern India.

title: Radio drama
complex: Radio drama (or audio drama, audio play, radio play, radio theatre, or audio theatre) is a dramatised, purely acoustic performance. <s> With no visual component, radio drama depends on dialogue, music and sound effects to help the listener imagine the characters and story: "It is auditory in the physical dimension but equally powerful as a visual force in the psychological dimension."
simple: A radio drama ("audio" or "radio play", "dramatized audiobook") is a live or recorded performance of actors without visual elements.

title: Zee Bangla
complex: Zee Bangla (জি বাংলা) is a Bengali language Cable television channel in India and Bangladesh. <s> It is offered by Zee Network, part of the Essel Group. <s> The first Bengali-language television channel in India, Zee Bangla was launched in 1996 by Zee's TV chairman. <s> It aired the comedy show "Raja and Gaja" before the show switched stations. <s> It has its own YouTube Channel and has over 4 million subscribers.
simple: Zee Bangla is a leading Bengali language cable television channel in India. <s> It is offered by Zee Network, part of the Essel Group. <s> The first Bengali-language television channel in India, Zee Bangla was launched in 1996 by Zee's TV chairman. <s> It aired the comedy show "Raja and Gaja" before the show switched stations. <s> It has its own YouTube Channel and becomes the 1st Bengali-content channel to cross 1 million subscribers.

title: Anne Holton
complex: Anne Bright Holton (born February 1, 1958) is an American lawyer and judge who served as the Secretary of Education for the Commonwealth of Virginia from 2014 to 2016. <s> On August 1, 2019, she assumed the role of interim president of George Mason University. <s> She is the wife of United States Senator and former Virginia Governor Tim Kaine, who was the vice-presidential running mate of Hillary Clinton in the 2016 U.S. presidential election. <s> Holton served as First Lady of Virginia from 2006 to 2010.
simple: Anne Bright Holton (born February 1, 1958) is an American politician and educator. <s> She served as the Virginia Secretary of Education from 2014-2016. <s> She is also the wife of United States Senator and former Governor Tim Kaine. <s> She served as First Lady of Virginia from 2006 to 2010.

title: Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld
complex: Prince Bernhard of Lippe-Biesterfeld (later Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands; German: "Bernhard Friedrich Eberhard Leopold Julius Kurt Carl Gottfried Peter Graf von Biesterfeld"; 29 June 1911 – 1 December 2004) was a Dutch prince who was the consort of Queen Juliana of the Netherlands; they were the parents of four children, including Princess Beatrix, who was Queen of the Netherlands from 1980 to 2013. <s> Bernhard was born Bernhard Leopold Friedrich Eberhard Julius Kurt Karl Gottfried Peter, Count of Biesterfeld in Jena, Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach, German Empire on 29 June 1911, the elder son of Prince Bernhard of Lippe and his wife, Armgard von Cramm. <s> He was a grandson of Ernest, Count of Lippe-Biesterfeld, who was regent of the Principality of Lippe until 1904. <s> He was also a nephew of the principality's last sovereign, Leopold IV, Prince of Lippe. <s> Prince Bernhard died of cancer at the age of 93 at University Medical Center Utrecht in Utrecht on 1 December 2004; until his death he suffered from malignant lung and intestinal tumors. <s> On 11 December 2004, he was interred with a lavish state funeral at the Nieuwe Kerk, Delft.
simple: Prince Bernhard of the Netherlands (29 June 1911 – 1 December 2004) was the prince consort of Queen Juliana of the Netherlands. <s> He was born in Jena, Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach, German Empire. <s> He died of lung cancer in Utrecht, Netherlands at the age of 93.

title: Mary Wells Lawrence
complex: Mary Wells Lawrence (born Mary Georgene Berg on May 25, 1928 in Youngstown, Ohio, United States) is a retired American advertising executive. <s> She was the founding president of Wells, Rich, Greene, an advertising agency known for its creative work. <s> Lawrence was the first female CEO of a company listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
simple: Mary Wells Lawrence (born Mary Georgene Berg on May 25, 1928) is a retired American advertising executive. <s> She was the founding president of Wells Rich Greene, an advertising agency. <s> Lawrence was the first female CEO of a company listed on the New York Stock Exchange.

title: Takeoff
complex: Takeoff is the phase of flight in which an aerospace vehicle goes from the ground to flying in the air. <s> For aircraft that take off horizontally, this usually involves starting with a transition from moving along the ground on a runway. <s> For balloons, helicopters and some specialized fixed-wing aircraft (VTOL aircraft such as the Harrier), no runway is needed. <s> Takeoff is the opposite of landing.
simple: Takeoff is the part of flight in which an aircraft goes from moving along the ground (taxiing) to flying in the air, usually on a runway. <s> For balloons, helicopters and some special aircraft (such as the Harrier), no runway is needed. <s> Takeoff is the opposite of landing.

title: George Clements
complex: George H. Clements is an American Roman Catholic priest who, in 1981, became the first Catholic priest in the Chicago area to adopt a child. <s> Through his founding of several programs, including "one church-one child", "one church-one addict", and "one church-one inmate", he brought greater recognition to social problems and encouraged the adoption of African-American children. <s> In June 1969, Father Clements became the first black pastor of Holy Angels Catholic Church on the South Side of Chicago. <s> He is also well known for his involvement in civil rights activities during a period that extended from the late 1960s to present. <s> In August 2019, Cardinal Blase Cupich asked Clements to step aside from ministry, while the Church investigates allegations that he sexually abused a minor in 1974.
simple: George H. Clements (born January 26, 1932) is an American Roman Catholic priest. <s> In 1981, became the first Catholic priest in the Chicago area to adopt a child. <s> In June 1969, Father Clements became the first black pastor of Holy Angels Catholic Church on the South Side of Chicago. <s> He is also well known for his involvement in civil rights activities since the 1960s.

title: Blest Pair of Sirens
complex: Blest Pair of Sirens is a short work for choir and orchestra by the English composer Hubert Parry, setting John Milton's ode "At a solemn Musick". <s> It was first performed at St James's Hall, London on 17 May 1887, conducted by its dedicatee, Charles Villiers Stanford. <s> The piece is about 11 minutes in duration. <s> Stanford had originally intended to perform an existing work of Parry's, the 1885 cantata "The Glories of our Blood and State". <s> As the concert was to mark the Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria, it was thought that such lines in the text as "Sceptre and crown must tumble down" made the work unsuitable for the occasion. <s> Asked to write a new piece, Parry turned, at the suggestion of his colleague George Grove, to Milton's ode, which he had been considering setting for many years.
simple: Blest Pair of Sirens is a short work for choir and orchestra by Hubert Parry. <s> It is a setting of an ode called "At a solemn Musick" by John Milton. <s> "Blest Pair of Sirens" was first performed by the Bach Choir conducted by Charles Villiers Stanford. <s> George Grove suggested Milton’s "Ode at a Solemn Music" would be a good poem for Parry to set. <s> The first performance of "Blest Pair of Sirens" at St James’s Hall took place on 17 May 1887. <s> At first Stanford wanted to perform another work by Parry: "The Glories of Our Blood and State". <s> However, the performance was going to be part of Queen Victoria’s Golden Jubilee celebrations.

title: 2003–04 Tampa Bay Lightning season
complex: The 2003–04 Tampa Bay Lightning season was the 12th National Hockey League season in Tampa, Florida. <s> The Lightning won their first Stanley Cup over the Calgary Flames this season, after the Flames were attempting to be the first Canadian team to win a Stanley Cup since the 1993 Montreal Canadiens. <s> The Lightning's first Stanley Cup victory came just a year after their NFL (National Football League) counterparts, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, won Super Bowl XXXVII, also their first championship title. <s> The Lightning did not have a first-round pick. <s> For their first pick, they chose Mike Egener in the second round, 35th over-all. <s> On Saturday, December 27, 2003, the Lightning scored three short-handed goals in a 4-2 win over the Boston Bruins. <s> The Lightning finished the regular season having tied the Detroit Red Wings for the most short-handed goals scored, with 15. <s> Divisions: "AT" – Atlantic, "NE" – Northeast, "SE" – Southeast <s> Z – "Clinched Conference"; Y – "Clinched Division"; X – "Clinched Playoff spot" <s> "Note: GP= Games played; G= Goals; A= Assists; PTS = Points; PIM = Points" "Note: GP= Games played; G= Goals; A= Assists; PTS = Points; PIM = Points" "Note: GP= Games played; W= Wins; L= Losses; T = Ties; SO = Shutouts; GAA = Goals Against"

simple: Lestrem is a commune.

title: Division of Martin
complex: The Division of Martin was an Australian Electoral Division in the state of New South Wales. <s> It was located in the inner western suburbs of Sydney, and initially included the suburbs of Concord and Mortlake, although by the time it was abolished in 1955, it had moved to cover Abbotsford, Balmain and Drummoyne. <s> The Division was named after Hon Sir James Martin, a former Premier of New South Wales. <s> It was proclaimed at the redistribution of 13 September 1922, and was first contested at the 1922 Federal election. <s> It was abolished at the redistribution of 30 August 1955. <s> The seat was at one stage held by William Holman, a former Premier of New South Wales.
simple: The Division of Martin was a Australian Electoral Division for the Australian House of Representatives in the state of New South Wales. <s> It was located in inner western Sydney. <s> It was also located in Concord and Mortlake. <s> By the time it was abolished, the division of Martin had spread to Abbotsford, Balmain and Drummoyne. <s> It was named after Sir James Martin, former Premier of New South Wales. <s> It was abolished in 1955.

title: Harry Tjutjuna
complex: Harry Tjutjuna is an Aboriginal artist from central Australia. <s> He belongs to the Pitjantjatjara people. <s> Tjutjuna began painting in 2005. <s> He held his first solo exhibition in 2007, in Darwin. <s> His work is now held in several major public galleries in Australia, including the Art Gallery of New South Wales, the National Gallery of Victoria, and the National Gallery of Australia. <s> His painting " " (Bilby Dreaming Story) was a finalist for the Togard Contemporary Art Award in 2009. <s> In 2010 and 2011, another of Tjutjuna's paintings, " ", was chosen as a finalist in both the Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards, and the National Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander Art Award (NATSIAA). <s> Tjutjuna was born around 1930. <s> He was born in the bushland close to what is now the community of Pipalyatjara in the north-west corner of South Australia. <s> Sources disagree on where exactly he was born. <s> Some say he was born at Walytjatjara, a place to the north-east of Pipalyatjara, just over the border in the Northern Territory. <s> Others say that he was born at Mount Davies, a hill that overlooks Pipalyatjara. <s> When Tjutjuna was still young, his family settled at Ernabella. <s> He went to school on the mission there and later worked as a labourer for the community. <s> He later moved back west to live in the communities of Irrunytju and Pipalyatjara after they were established. <s> He moved there with his wives and children to be closer to his homeland. <s> In his later life, Tjutjuna became known as an important traditional healer (" ") and law man (" ") for the Pitjantjatjara. <s> Tjutjuna began painting in late 2005, when he was aged in his mid-seventies. <s> He was living again at Ernabella, and began to paint for the community's art company Ernabella Arts. <s> His work at Ernabella depicted "Tjukurpa" (traditional law or stories from the Dreamtime). <s> It supported a shift in subject matter for the centre's artists, from quite secular to more spiritual subjects. <s> In 2008, Tjutjuna moved back to Pipalyatjara and began work for Ninuku Arts. <s> Tjutjuna paints concepts and stories from his Dreaming. <s> His main personal totem is a spider (" "), and his Dreaming revolves around the (Spider Man Dreaming). <s> According to his Dreaming, which was passed on to him from previous generations, Tjutjuna's ancestor is a powerful being known as the Spider Man. <s> This creature is said to have created Tjutjuna's country in the Dreamtime, and so Tjutjuna associates his country, his heritage and himself with this set of beliefs. <s> In this way, the paintings are autobiographical in addition to depicting traditional stories. <s> Tjutjuna identifies himself as the Spider Man, and his paintings are often seen to symbolise his work as a " " (healer). <s> Because his totem is a spider, he uses spider webs to treat wounds on people's skin. <s> Tjutjuna also paints figures from several other Dreaming stories associated with his country, such as the "Wati Maḻu" (Red Kangaroo Man) and the "Kungka Mingkiri" (Mice Women). <s> Many of the paintings have sexual themes. <s> One of Tjutjuna's most famous paintings, " ", is a composition of two Dreaming stories. <s> It depicts the story of the Kungkarungkara (Seven Sisters), which is about the constellations of Pleiades (the Sisters) and Orion. <s> Tjutjuna painted it from the male's perspective. <s> , a shape-shifting man, chases the seven sisters and catches the youngest, raping her. <s> The other story depicted is from the Spider Man Dreaming. <s> The painting was chosen as a finalist for the Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards in 2010, and the National Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander Art Award in 2011. <s> Tjutjuna paints in the typical style of the Western Desert, which can be seen as very abstract. <s> The figures in his paintings, ancestral beings, are obscured and encoded for cultural reasons. <s> He uses fields of dots to represent their interactions, and lines to represent their journeys across the landscape. <s> The landscape is depicted with the earthly colours of the desert (reds, oranges, ochres and white). <s> In his works depicting , he often paints circular patterns across the background. <s> This motif is used to represent both a spider's web and the spider man's many women. <s> Tjutjuna is also known for drip paintings.
