simple: Besny-et-Loizy is a commune.

title: Epic Movie
complex: Epic Movie is a 2007 American parody comedy film directed and written by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer and produced by Paul Schiff. <s> It was made in a similar style to "Date Movie", Friedberg and Seltzer's previous film, but as a spoof of the "Epic" style of films, hence the name. <s> The film mostly references "", the "Harry Potter" films, Tim Burton's version of "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory", "Pirates of the Caribbean", and "". <s> The song "Ms. New Booty" by Bubba Sparxxx gained commercial attention for being featured in "Epic Movie". <s> Many have considered this to be one of the worst films of all time. <s> "Epic Movie" debuted at number one at the box office with a gross of $18.6 million over the opening weekend. <s> As of May 8, 2007, the film has grossed $86,865,564, with $39,739,367 of that amount earned domestically, despite negative reviews from critics. <s> The film was an economic success for its producers not least because it had a comparatively low budget, estimated at $20 million (the same as "Date Movie").
simple: Epic Movie is a 2007 American parody movie directed and written by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer. <s> It was made by Paul Schiff. <s> It was made in a similar style to "Date Movie", Friedberg and Seltzer's movie before they made this one. <s> The movie mostly references "" and Tim Burton's version of "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory". <s> "Epic Movie" started at number 1 at the box office. <s> It made $18.6 million over the first weekend. <s> As of May 8, 2007 the movie made $86,865,564 and received generally negative reviews.

title: Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home
complex: The Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home is the house located at 816 South Hennepin Avenue, Dixon, Illinois, in which the 40th President of the United States Ronald Reagan lived as a youth beginning in 1920. <s> The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
simple: The Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home is the house located at 816 South Hennepin Street, Dixon, Illinois, in which the late former President of the United States Ronald Reagan lived as a youth beginning in 1920. <s> The building was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982.

title: Ryohei Yamazaki
complex: Ryōhei Yamazaki (山崎 亮平 , Yamazaki Ryōhei , born 14 March 1989) is a Japanese footballer who plays for Kashiwa Reysol in the J1 League.
simple: Ryohei Yamazaki (born 14 March 1989) is a Japanese football player.

title: Make Way for Ducklings
complex: Make Way for Ducklings is a children's picture book written and illustrated by Robert McCloskey. <s> First published in 1941, the book tells the story of a pair of mallards who decide to raise their family on an island in the lagoon in Boston Public Garden, a park in the center of Boston. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" won the 1942 Caldecott Medal for McCloskey's illustrations, executed in charcoal then lithographed on zinc plates. <s> As of 2003, the book had sold over two million copies. <s> The book's popularity led to the construction of a statue by Nancy Schön in the Public Garden of the mother duck and her eight ducklings, which is a popular destination for children and adults alike. <s> In 1991, Barbara Bush gave a duplicate of this sculpture to Raisa Gorbachev as part of the START Treaty, and the work is displayed in Moscow's Novodevichy Park. <s> The book is the official children's book of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. <s> Praise for the book is still high over 70 years since its first publication, mainly for the enhancing illustrations and effective pacing. <s> It was criticised for having a loose plot, however. <s> The book is popular worldwide. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" has been continuously in print since it was first published.
simple: Make Way for Ducklings is a children's picture book written and illustrated by Robert McCloskey. <s> The book is about two mallard ducks who decide to raise their family on an island in the lagoon in Boston Public Garden, a park in the middle of Boston, Massachusetts. <s> "Make Way for Ducklings" won the 1942 Caldecott Medal for McCloskey's pictures, drawn in charcoal, then lithographed on zinc. <s> In 2003, the book had sold more than two million copies. <s> The book was so popular a statue of a mother duck and her eight ducklings were set up in the Public Garden. <s> In 1991, Barbara Bush gave a copy of this statue to Raisa Gorbachev as part of the START Treaty, and the work is in Moscow's Novodevichy Park. <s> The book is the official children's book of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. <s> The book is still highly praised for over 60 years because of its pictures and pace. <s> However, it was criticised for having a loose plot (story) and weak characters. <s> The book is very popular around the world.

title: Indravati River, Nepal
complex: The Indravati River in Nepal is a tributary of the Sun Koshi River. <s> It used to be called "Melamchi" or "Melamchu" until the 19th century.
simple: The Indravati River is a river in Nepal. <s> It is a tributary of Sun Kosi river which later joins Koshi River.

title: Pontoon Dock DLR station
complex: Pontoon Dock is a station on the Docklands Light Railway (DLR) in Silvertown in east London, which is on the Woolwich Arsenal branch, opened on 2 December 2005. <s> It is located in the east of Silvertown in the London Borough of Newham, in the redevelopment zone known as Silvertown Quays, and is in Travelcard Zone 3.
simple: Pontoon Dock DLR station, on the Woolwich Arsenal branch of the DLR, opened on 2 December 2005. <s> It is in the east of Silvertown in the London Borough of Newham, and is in Travelcard Zone 3.

title: Mona Sahlin
complex: Mona Ingeborg Sahlin (] née Andersson; born 9 March 1957) is a Swedish politician who was leader of the opposition and leader of the Swedish Social Democratic Party from 2007 to 2011. <s> Sahlin was born Mona Ingeborg Andersson in Sollefteå, Västernorrland County, Sweden.
simple: Mona Ingeborg Sahlin (born Andersson on March 9, 1957 in Sollefteå, Sweden) is a former leader for the Swedish Social Democratic Party, when she replaced Göran Persson after his ten years as leader, she was the first woman to do so.

title: Jean-Noël Rey
complex: Jean-Noël Rey (23 December 1949 – 16 January 2016) was a Swiss manager and politician of the Social Democratic Party. <s> He was director-general of the Swiss public post and telecommunications service (PTT) from 1990 to 1998, and a member of the National Council of Switzerland from 2003 to 2007. <s> Born in Siders, Valais, Rey graduated with a doctorate in social sciences from the University of Geneva in 1978. <s> He worked as a personal assistant to Federal Councillor Otto Stich and was elected director-general of PTT in 1990. <s> When PTT was split into Swisscom and Swiss Post in 1998, Rey was the subject of allegations of cronyism and resigned as CEO of the new postal service, but was acquitted of criminal charges. <s> Rey was killed in the terror attacks in Burkina Faso in 2016, together with another former Swiss politician, Georgie Lamon. <s> They had been visiting a school built by a Swiss charity founded by Lamon, "Association Yelen", for which Rey had helped raise money.
simple: Jean-Noël Rey (23 December 1949 – 16 January 2016) was a Swiss socialist politician. <s> He was a member of the National Council of Switzerland between 2003 and 2007. <s> He was also the CEO of the national postal service Swiss Post. <s> Rey was shot and killed by terrorists on 16 January 2016 in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.

title: Kevin Keegan
complex: Joseph Kevin Keegan, OBE (born 14 February 1951) is an English former football player and manager. <s> A forward, he played for several clubs, including Newcastle United, Southampton, Liverpool and Hamburger SV.
simple: Kevin Keegan (born 14 February 1951) is a former English football player.

title: Second Party System
complex: Historians and political scientists consider the Second Party System to be a term of periodization to designate the political party system operating in the United States from about 1828 to 1854, after the First Party System ended. <s> The system was characterized by rapidly rising levels of voter interest, beginning in 1828, as demonstrated by Election Day turnouts, rallies, partisan newspapers, and high degrees of personal loyalty to parties. <s> Two major parties dominated the political landscape: the Democratic Party, led by Andrew Jackson, and the Whig Party, assembled by Henry Clay from the National Republicans and from other opponents of Jackson. <s> Minor parties included the Anti-Masonic Party, an important innovator from 1827 to 1834; the abolitionist Liberty Party in 1840; and the anti-slavery expansion Free Soil Party in 1848 and 1852. <s> The Second Party System reflected and shaped the political, social, economic and cultural currents of the Jacksonian Era, until succeeded by the Third Party System. <s> Historian Richard P. McCormick is most responsible for defining the term. <s> Among the best-known figures on the Democratic side were: Andrew Jackson, Martin Van Buren, John C. Calhoun, James K. Polk, Lewis Cass, and Stephen Douglas. <s> On the Whig side were John Quincy Adams, Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, William H. Seward, and Thurlow Weed. <s> The 1824 presidential election operated without political parties and came down to a four-man race. <s> Each candidate (Henry Clay, William Crawford, Andrew Jackson, and John Quincy Adams), all of whom were nominally Democratic Republicans, had a regional base of support involving factions in the various states. <s> With no electoral college majority, the choice devolved on the United States House of Representatives. <s> Clay was not among the three finalists, but as Speaker of the House he negotiated the settlement. <s> Jackson, despite having won the most popular votes and the most electoral votes, was not elected. <s> John Quincy Adams, son of former President John Adams, was elected, and he immediately chose Clay as Secretary of State. <s> Jackson loudly denounced this "corrupt bargain." <s> Campaigning vigorously he launched a crusade against the corruption he saw in Washington. <s> Appealing both to local militia companies (as the most famous of the nation's Indian fighters, and a hero of the War of 1812) and to state political factions, Jackson assembled a coalition, the embryonic Democratic Party, that ousted Adams in 1828. <s> Martin Van Buren, brilliant leader of New York politics, was Jackson's key aide, bringing along the large electoral votes of Virginia and Pennsylvania. <s> His reward was appointment as Secretary of State and later nomination and election to the vice presidency as heir to the Jacksonian tradition. <s> The Adams-Clay wing of the Democratic-Republican Party became known as the National Republicans, although Adams never considered himself a loyal member of the party. <s> Jackson considered himself a reformer, but he was committed to the old ideals of Republicanism, and bitterly opposed anything that smacked of special favors for special interests. <s> While Jackson never engaged in a duel as president, he had shot political opponents before and was just as determined to destroy his enemies on the battlefields of politics. <s> The Second Party System came about primarily because of Jackson's determination to destroy the Second Bank of the United States. <s> Headquartered in Philadelphia, with offices in major cities around the country, the federally chartered Bank operated somewhat like a central bank (like the Federal Reserve System a century later). <s> Local bankers and politicians annoyed by the controls exerted by Nicholas Biddle grumbled loudly. <s> Jackson did not like any banks (paper money was anathema to Jackson; he believed only gold and silver "specie" should circulate.) <s> After Herculean battles with Henry Clay, his chief antagonist, Jackson finally broke Biddle's bank. <s> Jackson continued to attack the banking system. <s> His "Specie Circular" of July 1836 rejected paper money issued by banks (it could no longer be used to buy federal land), insisting on gold and silver coins. <s> Most businessmen and bankers (but not all) went over to the Whig party, and the commercial and industrial cities became Whig strongholds. <s> Jackson meanwhile became even more popular with the subsistence farmers and day laborers who distrusted bankers and finance. <s> Jackson systematically used the federal patronage system, what was called the "Spoils System". <s> Jackson not only rewarded past supporters; he promised future jobs if local and state politicians joined his team. <s> As Syrett explains: When Jackson became President, he implemented the theory of rotation in office, declaring it "a leading principle in the republican creed." <s> He believed that rotation in office would prevent the development of a corrupt civil service. <s> On the other hand, Jackson's supporters wanted to use the civil service to reward party loyalists to make the party stronger. <s> In practice, this meant replacing civil servants with friends or party loyalists into those offices. <s> The spoils system did not originate with Jackson. <s> It originated under Thomas Jefferson when he removed Federalist office-holders after becoming president. <s> Also, Jackson did not out the entire civil service. <s> At the end of his term, Jackson had only dismissed less than twenty percent of the original civil service. <s> While Jackson did not start the spoils system, he did encourage its growth and it became a central feature of the Second Party System, as well as the Third Party System, until it ended in the 1890s. <s> As one historian explains: "Although Jackson dismissed far fewer government employees than most of his contemporaries imagined and although he did not originate the spoils system, he made more sweeping changes in the Federal bureaucracy than had any of his predecessors.
simple: It is a phrase used by historians and political scientists to describe the time period between 1828 and 1854. <s> People quickly became more interested in voting starting in 1828. <s> One was the Democratic Party, led by Andrew Jackson. <s> The other was the Whig Party, started by Henry Clay. <s> The Whig party was made up of members of the National Republican Party and other people who opposed Jackson. <s> The Anti-Masonic Party (1827-34) was important in developing political ideas and laws. <s> The United States Free Soil Party in 1848 and 1852 was another anti-slavery party. <s> The Second Party System was an important part of the politics, society, economics, and culture of the Jacksonian Era. <s> The phrase "second party system" was defined by the historian Richard P. McCormick. <s> Some famous democrats were: Andrew Jackson, Martin Van Buren, John C. Calhoun, James K. Polk, Lewis Cass, and Stephen Douglas. <s> Some famous Whigs were: Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, William H. Seward, and Thurlow Weed. <s> The United States presidential election in 1824 did not have any political parties. <s> There were four main candidates for president: Henry Clay, William Crawford, Andrew Jackson, and John Quincy Adams. <s> The three final candidates were Adams, Crawford, and Jackson. <s> At the end of the race, none of the candidates had enough votes in the electoral college to win, and the United States House of Representatives had to choose the winner. <s> Even though Clay was not one of these finalists, he was the Speaker of the House, and it was his job to negotiate who would become president. <s> Jackson had the most popular votes (votes cast by citizens) and the most electoral votes (votes cast by the electoral college), but was not elected. <s> Instead, John Quincy Adams was elected president. <s> He immediately chose Clay to be his Secretary of State. <s> Jackson loudly declared this to be a "corrupt bargain." <s> Jackson was a very popular politician, the most famous fighter of the American Indian Wars, and a hero of the War of 1812. <s> Martin Van Buren, a brilliant leader in New York politics, was Jackson's most important supporter. <s> Van Buren was popular in Virginia and Pennsylvania, and he had the support of their electoral college votes. <s> Van Buren became the Secretary of State, and later Vice President. <s> Adams, Clay, and their supporters in the Democratic-Republican Party became known as the National Republicans. <s> Andrew Jackson opposed (was against) the idea of giving special favors to special interest groups. <s> He strongly opposed the Second Bank of the United States. <s> The Bank was a federal institution that worked somewhat like a central bank. <s> Jackson did not like any banks, and he did not believe in paper money. <s> (He believed that money should only be gold and silver.) <s> Jackson continued to attack the banking system. <s> He issued his "Specie Circular" in July 1836. <s> The Circular said that only gold and siver coins, and not paper money, could be used to buy federal land. <s> This made most businessmen and bankers join the Whig party. <s> Also, cities that depended on commerce (trade) and industry became supporters of the Whig party. <s> Jackson became more popular with subsistence farmers (farmers who grow crops to eat, but not to sell) and day laborers. <s> Jackson used the spoils system a lot when he was president. <s> He rewarded his supporters and promised future jobs if local and state politicians joined his team. <s> He believed in the theory of rotation in office, where people would only remain in a position for a short time. <s> He believed that this would keep the civil service from becoming corrupt. <s> In total, Jackson dismissed less than twenty percent (20%) of the original civil service. <s> As president, Jackson encouraged the use of the spoils system. <s> It became an important part of the Second Party System and the Third Party System. <s> The spoils system was ended in the 1890s.

title: Polyhydroxyalkanoates
complex: Polyhydroxyalkanoates or PHAs are polyesters produced in nature by numerous microorganisms, including through bacterial fermentation of sugar or lipids. <s> When produced by bacteria they serve as both a source of energy and as a carbon store.
simple: Polyhydroxyalkanoate (PHA) is a biopolymer that is made by bacteria.

title: Manganese(II) oxide
complex: Manganese(II) oxide is an inorganic compound with chemical formula MnO. <s> It forms green crystals.
simple: Manganese(II) oxide is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is MnO. <s> It is made by reduction of manganese(IV) oxide by hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or methane.

title: Jönköping Concert Hall
complex: The Jönköping Concert Hall is a concert hall in Jönköping, Sweden. <s> It was opened in September 1990. <s> There are two halls, the Hammaskjöld Hall and the Rydberg Hall .
simple: The Jönköping Concert Hall is a concert hall in the town of Jönköping in Sweden. <s> It was opened in September 1990. <s> There are two halls. <s> They are the Hammaskjöld Hall and the Rydberg Hall .

title: Armand Gatti
complex: Armand Gatti (] ; 26 January 1924 – 6 April 2017) was a French playwright, poet, journalist, screenwriter, filmmaker and World War II resistance fighter. <s> His debut film "Enclosure" was entered into the 2nd Moscow International Film Festival where he won the Silver Prize for Best Director. <s> Two years later, his film "El Otro Cristóbal" was entered into the 1963 Cannes Film Festival. <s> In 2013 he was awarded the Grand prix du théâtre de l'Académie française. <s> He died on 6 April 2017.
simple: Armand Gatti (]; January 26, 1924 – April 6, 2017) was a Monegasque-born French playwright, poet, journalist, screenwriter, filmmaker and World War II resistance fighter. <s> Gatti's first movie, "Enclosure", was entered into the 2nd Moscow International Film Festival where he won the Silver Prize for Best Director. <s> Two years later, his movie "El Otro Cristóbal" was entered into the 1963 Cannes Film Festival. <s> In 2013 he was awarded the Grand prix du théâtre de l'Académie française. <s> Gatti died on April 6, 2017 in Saint-Mandé, France, aged 93.

title: River Adur
complex: The Adur ( or ) is a river in Sussex, England; it gives its name to the Adur district of West Sussex. <s> The river, which is 20 miles long, was once navigable for large vessels up as far as Steyning, where there was a large Saxon port, but by the 11th century the lower river became silted up and the port moved down to the deeper waters at the mouth of the river in Shoreham-by-Sea.
simple: The River Adur is a river in the county of Sussex, in England.

title: Lake Morat
complex: Lake Morat or Lake Murten (French: "Lac de Morat"; German: "Murtensee") is a lake located in the cantons of Fribourg and Vaud in the west of Switzerland. <s> It is named after the small bilingual town of Murten/Morat on its southern shore.
simple: Lake Morat or Lake Murten (; ) is a lake in the cantons of Fribourg and Vaud in the west of Switzerland. <s> It is named after the small bilingual town of Murten/Morat on its southern shore.

title: Hidden Hills, California
complex: Hidden Hills is a city and gated community in Los Angeles County, California. <s> It is located next to the city of Calabasas and is located in the west San Fernando Valley. <s> It is notable for being home to many actors and celebrities. <s> The 2010 United States Census reported that Hidden Hills had a population of 1,856. <s> The population density was 1,099.1 people per square mile (424.4/km2).
simple: Hidden Hills is a city in Los Angeles County, California, United States, and a gated community. <s> It is in the San Fernando Valley region. <s> The population was 1,856 at the 2010 census.

title: Jim B. Tucker
complex: Jim B. Tucker is a child psychiatrist and Bonner-Lowry Professor of Psychiatry and Neurobehavioral Sciences at the University of Virginia School of Medicine. <s> His main research interests are children who claim to remember previous lives, and natal and prenatal memories. <s> He is the author of "Life Before Life: A Scientific Investigation of Children’s Memories of Previous Lives", which presents an overview of over four decades of reincarnation research at the Division of Perceptual Studies. <s> Tucker worked for several years on this research with Ian Stevenson before taking over upon Stevenson’s retirement in 2002. <s> Since taking over the research into claimed past-life memories from Ian Stevenson in 2002, Tucker has been interviewed about reincarnation in print and broadcast media in the United States, United Kingdom and Canada.
simple: Jim B. Tucker is medical director of the Child and Family Psychiatric Clinic, and associate professor at the Division of Perceptual Studies, at the University of Virginia. <s> His main research interests are reincarnation research, and prenatal and birth memories. <s> Tucker is the author of "Life Before Life: A Scientific Investigation of Children’s Memories of Previous Lives". <s> Tucker, a child psychiatrist, worked for several years on this research with Ian Stevenson before taking over upon Stevenson’s retirement in 2002. <s> He has been interviewed about reincarnation in print and broadcast media in the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada.

title: List of counties in South Dakota
complex: There are 66 counties in the U.S. state of South Dakota with FIPS codes. <s> Todd County and Oglala Lakota County are the only counties in South Dakota which do not have their own county seats. <s> Hot Springs in Fall River County serves as the administrative center for Oglala Lakota County. <s> Winner in Tripp County serves as the administrative center for Todd County. <s> These are two of five counties in South Dakota which are entirely within an Indian reservation. <s> (The other three counties are Corson, Dewey, and Ziebach.) <s> South Dakota's postal abbreviation is SD and its FIPS state code is 46.
simple: There are 66 counties in the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> Todd County and Oglala Lakota County are two counties in South Dakota that do not have their own county seat. <s> Hot Springs in Fall River County is the administrative center of Oglala Lakota County. <s> Winner in Tripp County is the administrative center of Todd County. <s> South Dakota's postal abbreviation is SD and its FIPS state code is 46.

title: Mary Ellis (pilot)
complex: Mary Ellis (née Wilkins; 2 February 1917 – 24 July 2018) was a British ferry pilot, and one of the last surviving British women pilots from the Second World War. <s> Mary Wilkins was born on 2 February 1917, in Leafield, Oxfordshire, to a farming family. <s> She developed a fascination with aviation from a young age, as her family home was located near Royal Air Force bases at Bicester Airfield and Port Meadow. <s> At the age of 11 her father paid for her to have a joy ride in a biplane at a flying circus, and she decided she wanted to learn to fly. <s> When she was 16 she started having lessons at a flying club in Witney, successfully gained a private pilot's licence and flew for pleasure until the start of the Second World War in 1939, when all civilian flying was banned. <s> Ellis died at her home in Sandown, Isle of Wight, on 24 July 2018 at the age of 101.
simple: Mary Ellis (née Wilkins; 2 February 1917 – 24 July 2018) was a British ferry pilot. <s> She was one of the last surviving British women pilots from the Second World War. <s> She was born in Leafield, Oxfordshire. <s> Ellis died on 24 July 2018 in Sandown, Isle of Wight, aged 101.

title: Arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot
complex: The arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is an arrondissement of France in the Lot-et-Garonne department in the Nouvelle Aquitaine région. <s> It has 92 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is an arrondissement of France. <s> It is part of the Lot-et-Garonne "département" in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region. <s> When the Lot-et-Garonne department was created on 17 February 1800, the "arrondissement" of Villeneuve-sur-Lot was part of that original department. <s> The "arrondissement" of Villeneuve-sur-Lot is in the northeast of Lot-et-Garonne, with an area of 1559.7 km2, the largest "arrondissement" of the department.

title: Herbert Kretzmer
complex: Herbert Kretzmer, OBE (born 5 October 1925) is an English journalist and lyricist. <s> He is best known as the lyricist for the English-language musical adaptation of "Les Misérables" as well as for his long-time collaboration writing the English-language lyrics to the songs of French songwriter Charles Aznavour.
simple: Herbert Kretzmer, OBE (born 5 October 1925) is a South African-born English journalist and lyricist. <s> He is best known as the lyricist for the English-language musical adaptation of "Les Misérables" as well as for his long-time writing works with the French singer Charles Aznavour.

title: Syunik Province
complex: Syunik ( , ] ) is the southernmost province of Armenia. <s> It is bordered by the Vayots Dzor Province from the north, Azerbaijan's Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic exclave from the west, the "de facto" independent Nagorno-Karabakh Republic from the east, and Iran from the south. <s> Its capital and largest city is the town of Kapan. <s> The National Statistical Service of the Republic of Armenia (ARMSTAT) reported its population was 141,771 in the 2011 census, down from 152,684 at the 2001 census. <s> Historically, Syunik is supposed to be one of the 15 provinces of the ancient Kingdom of Armenia. <s> At various times, the region of present-day Syunik was also known by other names such as "Syunia", "Sisakan" and "Zangezur" (or "Zangadzor"). <s> However, the present-name of the province is derived from the ancient Armenian Siunia dynasty, who were the Nakharar (governors) of the historic province of Syunik since the 1st century. <s> According to the 2011 official census, Syunik has a population of 141,771 (69,836 men and 71,935 women), forming around 4.7% of the entire population of Armenia. <s> The urban population is 95,170 (67.13%) and the rural is 46,601 (32.87%). <s> The province has 7 urban and 102 rural communities. <s> The largest urban community is the provincial center of Kapan, with a population of 43,190. <s> The other urban centres are Goris, Sisian, Kajaran, Meghri, Agarak and Dastakert.
simple: Syunik is the southernmost province of Armenia. <s> It borders Iran to the south. <s> The capital is Kapan. <s> The National Statistical Service of the Republic of Armenia (ARMSTAT) reported its population was 152,900 in 2010. <s> Historically, Syunik was one of the 15 provinces of the Kingdom of Armenia. <s> There are 7 urban communities and 102 rural communities. <s> Other important cities and towns include Goris, Sisian, Meghri, Agarak, and Dastakert.

title: Turriff
complex: Buckley’s in Turriff has been closed since August 25 2019 due to heath and safety issues Turriff is a town and civil parish in Aberdeenshire in Scotland. <s> It lies on the River Deveron, about 166 ft above sea level, and has a population of 5,708. <s> In everyday speech it is often referred to by its Scots name, Turra, which is derived from the Scottish Gaelic pronunciation. <s> The Knights Templar appear to have had a base in the area, and a nearby site is still known as "Temple Brae". <s> Turriff was notable as the scene of the very first engagements of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms (1639–51). <s> Early in 1639, the Marquis of Huntly assembled his forces here, and thereafter went to Kintore in lower Aberdeenshire, eventually marching from there to Aberdeen itself. <s> The Marquis — being informed shortly after his arrival in Aberdeen that a meeting of Covenanters was to be held in Turriff on the fourteenth of February — resolved to disperse them, by occupying the town with 2000 men. <s> The incident was known as the "Raid of Turriff" and was followed a few days later by a minor engagement known as the "Trot of Turriff".
simple: Turriff is a town and parish in Aberdeenshire, Scotland. <s> It is approximately 166 feet above sea level. <s> It is known locally as Turra in the Doric dialect of Scots. <s> The Knights Templar appear to have had a base in the area, and a nearby site is still known as "Temple Brae". <s> Early in 1639, the Marquis of Huntly assembled his forces here, and thereafter went to Kintore in lower Aberdeenshire, eventually marching from there to Aberdeen itself. <s> The Marquis — being informed shortly after his arrival in Aberdeen that a meeting of Covenanters was to be held in Turriff on the fourteenth of February — resolved to disperse them, by occupying the town with 2000 men. <s> The incident was known as the "First raid of Turray".

title: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery
complex: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery, or the full title, A Philosopher giving a Lecture on the Orrery in which a lamp is put in place of the Sun, is a 1766 painting by Joseph Wright of Derby depicting a lecturer giving a demonstration of an orrery to a small audience. <s> It is now in the Derby Museum and Art Gallery The painting preceded his similar "An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump" (National Gallery, London). <s> In both of these works, the candlelit setting had a realist justification. <s> Viewing sculpture by candlelight, when the contours showed well, and there might even be an impression of movement from the flickering light, was a fashionable practice described by Goethe. <s> In the orrery demonstration the shadows cast by the lamp representing the Sun were an essential part of the display. <s> But there seems no reason other than heightened drama to stage the air pump experiment in a room lit by a single candle, and in two later paintings of the subject by Charles-Amédée-Philippe van Loo the lighting is normal. <s> An anonymous review from the time called Wright "a very great and uncommon genius in a peculiar way". <s> "The Orrery" was painted without a commission, probably in the expectation that it would be bought by Washington Shirley, 5th Earl Ferrers, an amateur astronomer who had an orrery of his own, and with whom Wright's friend Peter Perez Burdett was staying while in Derbyshire. <s> Figures thought to be portraits of Burdett and Ferrers feature in the painting, Burdett taking notes and Ferrers seated with a youth next to the orrery. <s> Ferrers purchased the painting, which was exhibited in 1766, for £210, but the 6th Earl auctioned it off, and it is now in the Derby Museum and Art Gallery, where it is on permanent display, close to a working replica of a full-sized mechanical Grand Orrery. <s> A biographer of Wright, Benedict Nicolson, argued in 1968 that John Whitehurst was the model for the lecturer, while another commentator points out the figure's resemblance to "a painting of Isaac Newton by Godfrey Kneller". <s> Close observation of the adult faces in the picture reveals that each one demonstrates one or other of the main phases of the Moon – new moon, half moon, gibbous moon and full moon.
simple: A Philosopher Lecturing on the Orrery is an 18th-century oil painting by Joseph Wright of Derby. <s> Wright later created his similar "An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump" (National Gallery, London) in 1768. <s> In the orrery demonstration, the shadows created by the lamp mimic the sun, and it is a part of the display of heliocentrism. <s> In two later paintings, the lighting is normal. <s> One person called Wright "a very great and uncommon genius in a peculiar way". <s> "The Orrery" was painted without payment. <s> Wright expected that Washington Shirley, 5th Earl Ferrers, an amateur astronomer, will buy the painting, because Shirley had his own orrery, and Wright's friend Peter Perez Burdett was staying with him. <s> Figures are considered to be portraits of Burdett and Ferrers. <s> In the picture, Burdett is taking notes and Ferrers is seated with his son next to the orrery. <s> Ferrers purchased the painting for £210, but the 6th Earl sold it at an auction. <s> It is now held by Derby Museum and Art Gallery as its permanent display. <s> However, other people say the figure is similar to "a painting of Isaac Newton by Godfrey Kneller".

title: Eddie Vedder
complex: Eddie Jerome Vedder (born Edward Louis Severson III; December 23, 1964) is an American musician, multi-instrumentalist and singer-songwriter best known as the lead vocalist and one of three guitarists of the American rock band Pearl Jam. <s> He is known for his powerful baritone vocals.
simple: Eddie Vedder (born Edward Louis Severson III; December 23, 1964) is an American musician, singer and songwriter. <s> He is best known for being the lead singer and one of three guitarists of the alternative rock band Pearl Jam.

title: The Stinky Cheese Man and Other Fairly Stupid Tales
complex: The Stinky Cheese Man and Other Fairly Stupid Tales is a postmodern children's book written by Jon Scieszka and illustrated by Lane Smith. <s> Published in 1992 by Viking, it is a collection of twisted, humorous parodies of famous children's stories and fairy tales, such as "Little Red Riding Hood", "The Ugly Duckling" and "The Gingerbread Man". <s> Illustrated in a unique style by Lane Smith, the book won "The New York Times" Best Illustrated Book award, was a Caldecott Honor book, and has won numerous other awards in various countries. <s> The book was re-released in a 10th anniversary edition in 2002 and included a new story, a parody of "The Boy Who Cried Wolf" on the dust jacket. <s> The foreword includes a parody of "Goldilocks and the Three Bears" as an example of a "Fairly Stupid Tale". <s> Also, the table of contents includes the title, "The Boy Who Cried Cow Patty", a story found nowhere in the book. <s> The latter story was printed on the back of the dust jacket for the book's 10th anniversary edition (whereas the original edition had the Little Red Hen complaining about buying this book, while asking who "this ISBN guy" is and complaining that she is only in three of the pages as a book gag).
simple: The Stinky Cheese Man and Other Fairly Stupid Tales is a children's book by Jon Scieszka. <s> It was published in 1992 by Viking. <s> It is a collection of stories which make fun of famous children's stories and fairy tales, such as "Chicken Licken", "The Gingerbread Man" (changed to The Stinky Cheese Man of the title), "The Ugly Duckling", and others. <s> It was illustrated by Lane Smith, who won the Caldecott Honor for his illustrations. <s> This book also won the New York Times Best Illustrated Book award, among numerous awards in many countries. <s> The book was also re-released in a new edition in 2002 to celebrate its tenth anniversary. <s> This story was printed on the back of the dust jacket.

title: Child abuse
complex: Child abuse or child maltreatment is physical, sexual, and/or psychological maltreatment or neglect of a child or children, especially by a parent or a caregiver. <s> Child abuse may include any act or failure to act by a parent or a caregiver that results in actual or potential harm to a child, and can occur in a child's home, or in the organizations, schools or communities the child interacts with. <s> The World Health Organization (WHO) defines "child abuse" and "child maltreatment" as "all forms of physical and/or emotional ill-treatment, sexual abuse, neglect or negligent treatment or commercial or other exploitation, resulting in actual or potential harm to the child's health, survival, development or dignity in the context of a relationship of responsibility, trust or power." <s> In the United States, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) uses the term "child maltreatment" to refer to both acts of commission (abuse), which include "words or overt actions that cause harm, potential harm, or threat of harm to a child", and acts of omission (neglect), meaning "the failure to provide for a child's basic physical, emotional, or educational needs or to protect a child from harm or potential harm". <s> The United States federal Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act defines "child abuse and neglect" as, at minimum, "any recent act or failure to act on the part of a parent or caretaker which results in death, serious physical or emotional harm, sexual abuse or exploitation" or "an act or failure to act which presents an imminent risk of serious harm". <s> Many children who have been abused in any form develop some sort of psychological problem. <s> These problems may include: anxiety, depression, eating disorders, OCD, co-dependency, or even a lack of human connections. <s> There is also a slight tendency for children who have been abused to become child abusers themselves. <s> In the U.S. in 2013, of the 294,000 reported child abuse cases only 81,124 received any sort of counseling or therapy. <s> Treatment is greatly important for abused children.
simple: Child abuse is the abuse, mistreatment or hurt done by adults to children. <s> It often means abuse done by a child's parents or another caregiver. <s> The World Health Organization (WHO) defines "child abuse" and "child maltreatment" as "all forms of physical and/or emotional ill-treatment ... or other exploitation, resulting in actual or potential harm to the child's health, survival, development or dignity in the context of a relationship of responsibility, trust or power." <s> In the United States, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) uses the term "child maltreatment" to refer to both acts of absue and neglect. <s> According to the WHO, the term abuse includes "words or overt actions that cause harm, potential harm, or threat of harm to a child"; neglect means "the failure to provide for a child's basic physical, emotional, or educational needs or to protect a child from harm or potential harm". <s> The United States federal Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act defines "child abuse and neglect" as, at minimum, "any recent act or failure to act on the part of a parent or caretaker which results in death, serious physical or emotional harm, sexual abuse or exploitation" or "an act or failure to act which presents an imminent risk of serious harm". <s> Talking about these things and helping children who suffer from child abuse is very important, but some people do not believe it could happen in their country, neighbourhood or family.

title: Amoeboid movement
complex: Amoeboid movement is the most common mode of locomotion in eukaryotic cells. <s> It is a crawling-like type of movement accomplished by protrusion of cytoplasm of the cell involving the formation of pseudopodia ("false-feet") and posterior uropods. <s> One or more pseudopodia may be produced at a time depending on the organism, but all amoeboid movement is characterized by the movement of organisms with an amorphous form that possess no set motility structures. <s> Movement occurs when the cytoplasm slides and forms a pseudopodium in front to pull the cell forward. <s> This type of movement has been linked to changes in action potential, though the exact mechanism is still unknown. <s> Some examples of organisms that exhibit this type of locomotion are the amoeboids, slime molds and some protozoans such as "Naegleria gruberi", as well as some cells in humans such as leukocytes. <s> Sarcomas, or cancers arising from connective tissue cells, are particularly adept at amoeboid movement, thus leading to their high rate of metastasis.
simple: Amoeboid movement is the most common type of movement in eukaryotic cells. <s> It is a crawling type of movement got by pushing out cell cytoplasm in the form of pseudopodia ("false feet"). <s> The cytoplasm slides and forms a pseudopodium in front to move the cell forward. <s> The exact mechanism is still unknown. <s> This type of movement is observed in amoebae, slime molds and some other protozoans such as "Naegleria gruberi", as well as some cells in humans such as white blood cells. <s> Sarcomas, or cancers arising from connective tissue cells, are particularly good at amoeboid movement, thus leading to their high rate of metastasis.

title: Harold Lederman
complex: Harold Lederman (January 26, 1940 – May 11, 2019) was an American boxing judge and analyst. <s> He began his career as a boxing judge in 1967 and joined the cast of HBO World Championship Boxing in 1986, and was there until HBO dropped boxing in 2018. <s> Lederman was inducted into the International Boxing Hall of Fame in the class of 2016. <s> Lederman died on May 11, 2019 at 79 years of age, from cancer.
simple: Harold Lederman (January 26, 1940 – May 11, 2019) was an American professional boxing judge and analyst. <s> He began his career as a boxing judge in 1967 and joined the cast of "HBO World Championship Boxing" in 1986. <s> He stayed in this role until HBO dropped boxing in 2018. <s> He was added to the International Boxing Hall of Fame in 2016. <s> Lederman died of cancer on May 11, 2019, at the age of 79.

title: Ned Zelic
complex: Nedjeljko "Ned" Zelic (] ; born 4 July 1971) is an Australian former footballer. <s> He has played for the Australia youth, Olympic and senior teams, but made himself unavailable in November 1999 after disagreements with coach Frank Farina. <s> Zelic was captain of the Australian team that competed and finished 4th at the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona.

title: IRCd
complex: An IRCd, short for Internet Relay Chat daemon, is server software that implements the IRC protocol, enabling people to talk to each other via the Internet (exchanging textual messages in real time). <s> It is distinct from an IRC bot that connects outbound to an IRC channel. <s> The server listens to connections from IRC clients on a set of TCP ports. <s> When the server is part of an IRC network, it also keeps one or more established connections to other servers/daemons. <s> The term "ircd" originally referred to only one single piece of software, but it eventually became a generic reference to any implementation of an IRC daemon. <s> However, the original version is still distributed under the same name, and this article discusses both uses.
simple: An IRCd, meaning Internet Relay Chat server program, is a program, server software that uses the IRC protocol. <s> They exchange textual messages in real time. <s> The server accepts connections from IRC clients on a group of TCP ports. <s> When the server is part of an IRC network, it also keeps one or more connections with other servers/daemons. <s> The word "ircd" once referred to only one piece of software.

title: Frogs in captivity
complex: Frogs have recently become very popular exotic pets as they are generally undemanding, often visually appealing, and can be kept under fairly basic conditions. <s> Many frogs, especially common ones, can be inexpensive, but some specimens can cost several hundreds of Dollars/Pounds. <s> Their food is in most cases easily purchased. <s> Commonly kept pet frogs include ranids, hylids, bufonids, leptodactylids, and dendrobatids. <s> Pet frogs can be fed a wide variety of live foods, from pinhead crickets to mice and rats, depending on the size of the frog. <s> Particularly small pet frogs, like those of "Dendrobates" and "Phyllobates" species, will generally feed on small crickets, fruit flies, springtails, and other small arthropods. <s> Medium-sized pet frogs can be fed larger crickets, mealworms, butterworms, silkworms, grasshoppers, and even small fish. <s> Large pet frogs, like those in the genus "Ceratophrys" can be fed small fish, other frogs, reptiles, and small mammals such as mice or rats.
simple: Frogs have become a popular exotic pet. <s> They can be kept in basic conditions, compared to reptiles. <s> They are not expensive and their food is easily purchased. <s> Common pet frogs includes ranids, hylids, bufonids, leptodactylids, and dendrobatids. <s> Pet frogs can be fed a lot of different live foods. <s> Small pet frogs will only eat crickets, fruit flies, springtails and other small arthropods. <s> Medium-sized pet frogs can be fed larger crickets, mealworms, butterworms, silkworms, grasshoppers and small fish. <s> Large pet frogs like Ceratophrys frogs, can be fed small fish, other frogs, reptiles, and small mammals such as mice or rats.

title: Lyceum (Classical)
complex: It was best known for the Peripatetic school of philosophy founded there by Aristotle in 334 / 335 BCE . <s> Aristotle fled Athens in 323 BCE , but the school continued to function under a series of leaders until the Roman general Sulla destroyed it during his assault on Athens in 86 BCE. <s> In 335 BCE, Athens fell under Macedonian rule and Aristotle, aged 50, returned from Asia. <s> Upon his return, Aristotle began teaching regularly in the morning in the Lyceum and founded an official school called "The Lyceum". <s> After morning lessons, Aristotle would frequently lecture on the grounds for the public, and manuscripts of his compiled lectures were eventually circulated. <s> The group of scholars who followed the Aristotelian doctrine came to be known as the Peripatetics due to Aristotle's tendency to walk as he taught. <s> Aristotle's main focus as a teacher was cooperative research, an idea which he founded through his natural history work and systematic collection of philosophical works to contribute to his library. <s> His students were assigned historical or scientific research projects as part of their studies. <s> The school was also student run. <s> The students elected a new student administrator to work with the school leadership every ten days, allowing all the students to become involved in turn. <s> Before returning to Athens, Aristotle had been the tutor of Alexander of Macedonia, who became the great conqueror Alexander the Great. <s> Throughout his conquests of various regions, Alexander collected plant and animal specimens for Aristotle's research, allowing Aristotle to develop the first zoo and botanical garden in existence. <s> It is also suspected that Alexander donated what would be the equivalent of more than 4 million dollars to the Lyceum. <s> In 322 BCE , Aristotle was forced to flee Athens with his family when the political leadership reacted against the Macedonians again and his previously published works supporting Macedonian rule left him a target. <s> He passed on his Lyceum to Theophrastus and died later that year in Chalcis, near his hometown.

title: Gary Weiss
complex: Gary Weiss is an American investigative journalist, columnist and author of two books that critically examine the ethics and morality of Wall Street. <s> He was also a contributing editor for "Condé Nast Portfolio". <s> His "Businessweek" articles exposed organized crime on Wall Street and the Salomon Brothers bond trading scandal in the 1990s, and more recently he has covered the 2008 financial crisis and its aftermath. <s> Weiss is co-founder of The Mideast Reporter.

title: Doug Wilson (rugby union)
complex: Douglas Dawson Wilson (30 January 1931 – 18 May 2019) was a New Zealand rugby union player. <s> A first and second five-eighth, Wilson represented Canterbury and Wellington at a provincial level, and was a member of the New Zealand national side, the All Blacks, on their 1953–54 tour of Britain, Ireland, France and North America. <s> On that tour, he played 14 matches, including two internationals, and scored five tries and one drop goal. <s> He died in Kowhanui Hospital, Whanganui. <s> He had been married to Janice for 64 years.

title: Pebibyte
complex: The pebibyte is closely related to the petabyte (PB), its corresponding unit in the decimal set of multiples defined in the International System of Units (SI), and which represents 10 bytes = . <s> It follows that one pebibyte (1 PiB) is approximately equal to 1.13 PB. <s> One thousand twenty-four pebibytes (1024 PiB) is equal to one exbibyte (1 EiB).
simple: It is related to the petabyte which is 10 bytes. <s> 1024 pebibytes make one exbibyte.

title: Ike Turner
complex: Izear Luster "Ike" Turner Jr. (November 5, 1931 – December 12, 2007) was an American musician, bandleader, songwriter, arranger, talent scout, and record producer. <s> An early pioneer of fifties rock and roll, he is best known for his work in the 1960s and 1970s with his then-wife Tina Turner in the Ike & Tina Turner Revue. <s> Turner was born in Clarksdale, Mississippi, on November 5, 1931, to Beatrice Cushenberry, a seamstress, and Izear Luster Turner Sr., a Baptist minister. <s> The youngest of their two children, Turner had a sister named Lee Ethel Knight who was "some ten years" his senior.
simple: Ike Turner (November 5, 1931 – December 12, 2007) was an American singer, songwriter and recording artist. <s> He was born in Clarksdale, Mississippi, although he later moved to St. Louis, Missouri then to California.

title: Gymnastics at the 1972 Summer Olympics
complex: At the 1972 Summer Olympics, fourteen different artistic gymnastics events were contested, eight for men and six for women. <s> All events were held at the Sports Hall in Munich from 27 August through 1 September.

title: Macromolecule
complex: A macromolecule is a very large molecule, such as protein, commonly created by the polymerization of smaller subunits (monomers). <s> They are typically composed of thousands of atoms or more.
simple: A macromolecule is a molecule with a large number of atoms. <s> The word is usually used only when describing polymers, molecules which are made up of smaller molecules called monomers.

title: Yuri Lyubimov
complex: Yuri Petrovich Lyubimov ( ; 30 September O.S. 17 September 1917 5 October 2014) was a Soviet and Russian stage actor and director associated with the internationally renowned Taganka Theatre, which he founded in 1964. <s> He was one of the leading names in the Russian theatre world. <s> After service in the Red Army during World War II, Lyubimov joined the Vakhtangov Theatre (founded by Yevgeny Vakhtangov). <s> In 1953, he received the USSR State Prize. <s> Lyubimov started teaching in 1963 and formed the Taganka Theatre the following year. <s> His celebrated production of Bertold Brecht's "The Good Person of Setzuan" with Anna Orochko's class at the Schukin Theatre Institute earned him the artistic directorship of the Taganka Theatre. <s> With Meyerhold, Stanislavsky, Vakhtangov and Brecht as his spiritual guides, Lyubimov eschewed Soviet drama for the more imaginative worlds of poetry and narrative fiction, which he dramatized, and the classics, which he broke apart, reconstituted and presented from a pronounced critical perspective. <s> Under Lyubimov, the theatre rose to become the most popular in Moscow, with Vladimir Vysotsky and Alla Demidova as the leading actors. <s> In 1971 Shakespeare's "Hamlet" became one of Lyubimov's highly successful and much acclaimed productions. <s> In 1976 he was awarded by the BITEF First Prize for "Hamlet". <s> After Vysotsky's death in 1980, all of Lyubimov's productions were banned by the Communist authorities. <s> In 1984, he was stripped of Soviet citizenship. <s> Thereupon he worked abroad before returning to the Taganka Theatre in 1989. <s> His staging of "Eugene Onegin" premiered in the Taganka on his 85th birthday to much critical acclaim. <s> While in the West he maintained a busy directing career. <s> In the United States he directed "Crime and Punishment" at Arena Stage and "Lulu" at the Lyric Opera of Chicago. <s> In 1983 he directed Crime and Punishment in London, winning the Evening Standard Award for Best Director, in 1985 he directed St Matthew Passion at La Scala. <s> His effort to re-stage his famous "The Master and Margarita" at the American Repertory Theater failed to materialize because of a disagreement with the management of that company. <s> In 1989, his Russian citizenship was restored. <s> In June 2011, before a performance of Bertolt Brecht's play "The Good Person of Szechwan" in Czech, the actors of Taganka refused to rehearse unless they were paid first. <s> Lyubimov paid the money and left the theatre. <s> "I've had enough of this disgrace, these humiliations, this lack of desire to work, this desire just for money", he said. <s> Lyubimov retired from the theatre the following week. <s> Two leading actors of theatre, Dmitry Mezhevich and Alla Smirdan, as well as some administrative assistants, followed Lyubimov. <s> His dramatization of Dostoyevsky's "Demons" premiered the next year. <s> Lyubimov, a director who dominated Russian theatre for half a century, died at 97, after being admitted to the Botkin Clinic in Moscow with heart failure.
simple: Yuri Petrovich Lyubimov (September 30, 1917 – October 5, 2014) is a Soviet and Russian actor and director, founder of the internationally-renowned Taganka Theatre. <s> He is one of the leading names in the Russian theatre world. <s> After service in the Soviet Army during the World War II, Lyubimov joined the Vakhtangov Theatre. <s> In 1953, he received the "USSR State Prize". <s> Lyubimov started teaching in 1963 and formed the Taganka Theatre the following year. <s> Under Lyubimov, the theatre became the most popular in Moscow, with Vladimir Vysotsky and Alla Demidova as the leading actors. <s> After Vysotsky's death in 1980, all of Lyubimov's productions were banned by the Communist authorities. <s> In 1984, he was stripped of Soviet citizenship. <s> Thereupon Lyubimov worked abroad before returning to the Taganka Theatre in 1989. <s> His staging of "Eugene Onegin" premiered in the Taganka on his 85th birthday to much critical acclaim. <s> While in the West he maintained a busy directing career. <s> In the US he directed "Crime and Punishment" at Arena Stage and "Lulu" at the Lyric Opera of Chicago. <s> In 1983 he directed "Crime and Punishment" in London, winning the Evening Standard Award for Best Director. <s> In June, 2011 Lyubimov left the Taganka theatre. <s> Lyubimov died at 97 after being admitted to the Botkin Clinic in Moscow with heart failure.

title: Burt, Iowa
complex: Burt is a city in Kossuth County, Iowa, United States. <s> The population was 533 at the 2010 census.

title: Chicagoland (TV series)
complex: Chicagoland is a documentary series that debuted its pilot episode at the 2014 Sundance Film Festival on January 19, 2014. <s> It was aired on CNN in eight successive weekly broadcasts beginning March 6, 2014, and ending April 24, 2014. <s> It is executive produced by Robert Redford and Laura Michalchyshyn and created by Mark Benjamin and Marc Levin. <s> During its production, the documentary received assistance from the office of Chicago mayor Rahm Emanuel.
