title: Denis Leary
complex: Denis Colin O'Leary (born August 18, 1957) is an American actor, comedian, singer, writer and producer. <s> Leary was the star and co-creator of "Rescue Me", which ended its seventh and final season on September 7, 2011. <s> He has starred in many films including playing Captain George Stacy in Marc Webb's film, "The Amazing Spider-Man", Cleveland Browns Head Coach Vince Penn in Ivan Reitman's film, "Draft Day", and as the voice of Francis in "A Bug's Life" and Diego in the "Ice Age" franchise.
simple: Denis Colin Leary (born August 18, 1957 in Worcester, Massachusetts) is an American actor, comedian, producer, singer and writer. <s> He is the star and co-creator of the television show "Rescue Me".

title: Wolfgang Schäuble
complex: Wolfgang Schäuble (] ; born 18 September 1942) is a German lawyer and politician of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party whose political career has spanned more than four decades. <s> He is one of the most experienced and longest serving politicians in German history and since 2017 has been the President of the Bundestag. <s> On 27 September 2017 the CDU/CSU group in the Bundestag announced Schäuble's nomination as President of the Bundestag. <s> He was elected to that position on 24 October 2017.
simple: Wolfgang Schäuble (] born 18 September 1942) is a German lawyer and politician. <s> He is a member of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU). <s> His political career has spanned more than forty years. <s> On 27 September 2017 the CDU/CSU group in the Bundestag announced Schäuble’s nomination as President of the Bundestag and assumed office on 24 October 2017.

title: James Corden
complex: James Kimberley Corden (born 22 August 1978) is an English actor, singer, comedian, and television host. <s> He hosts "The Late Late Show with James Corden", a late-night television talk show on CBS. <s> Along with Welsh actress Ruth Jones, Corden co-created, co-wrote and starred in the critically acclaimed BBC sitcom "Gavin & Stacey" (2007–2010; 2019) for which he won the BAFTA Television Award for Best Comedy Performance.
simple: James Kimberley Corden, OBE (born 22 August 1978) is an English actor, writer, producer, comedian, and television host. <s> He currently hosts the late-night television talk show "The Late Late Show with James Corden" on CBS.

title: Bologna massacre
complex: The Bologna massacre was a terrorist bombing of the Bologna Centrale railway station in Bologna, Italy, on the morning of 2 August 1980 which killed 85 people and wounded over 200. <s> Several members of the neo-fascist terrorist organization Nuclei Armati Rivoluzionari (Armed Revolutionary Nuclei) were sentenced for the bombing, although the group denied involvement.
simple: The Bologna massacre was the bombing of Bologna Centrale railway station in Bologna, Emilia-Romagna, Italy by Nuclei Armati Rivoluzionari. <s> It happened on 2 August 1980. <s> It killed 85 people and injured over 200 others.

title: What Are You Waiting For? (FM Static album)
complex: What Are You Waiting For? <s> is the first album by the pop punk band FM Static. <s> As of the end of 2006, it has sold more than 60,000 copies.
simple: What Are You Waiting For? <s> Although not a bestseller or anything really great, "What Are You Waiting For?" <s> is the debut album from FM Static, a Canadian pop punk band. <s> did manage to sell around 60,000 copies in three and a half years.

title: Information commissioner
complex: In the United Kingdom, the Information Commissioner's Office is responsible for regulating compliance with the Data Protection Act 1998, Freedom of Information Act 2000 and the Environmental Information Regulations 2004. <s> The Freedom of Information (Scotland) Act 2002 is the responsibility of the Scottish Information Commissioner.
simple: In the United Kingdom these are laws such as the Data Protection Act.

title: Larry Craig
complex: Larry Edwin Craig (born July 20, 1945) is a retired American politician from the state of Idaho. <s> He served 18 years as a Republican in the United States Senate (1991–2009), preceded by 10 years in the U.S. House of Representatives, representing Idaho's 1st District (1981–91). <s> His 28 years in Congress rank as the second-longest in Idaho history, trailing only William Borah, who served over 32 years in the Senate.
simple: Larry Edwin Craig (born July 20, 1945) is an American politician. <s> He is a former Republican politician from the U.S. state of Idaho. <s> He served 18 years in the U.S. Senate (1991–2009), preceded by 10 years in the U.S. House, representing Idaho's first district (1981–91).

title: Interstate 68
complex: Interstate 68 (I-68) is a 112.9 mi Interstate Highway in the U.S. states of West Virginia and Maryland, connecting I-79 in Morgantown, West Virginia, to I-70 in Hancock, Maryland. <s> I-68 is also Corridor E of the Appalachian Development Highway System.
simple: Interstate 68 is an Interstate Highway in the United States. <s> It goes from Morgantown, West Virginia east to Hancock, Maryland. <s> The route is 112.9 mi long.

title: Walter Pidgeon
complex: Walter Davis Pidgeon (September 23, 1897 – September 25, 1984) was a Canadian-American actor. <s> He earned two Academy Award for Best Actor nominations for his roles in "Mrs. Miniver" (1942) and "Madame Curie" (1943). <s> Pidgeon also starred in many films such as "How Green Was My Valley" (1941), "The Bad and the Beautiful" (1952), "Forbidden Planet" (1956), "Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea" (1961), "Advise & Consent" (1962), "Funny Girl" (1968), and "Harry in Your Pocket" (1973). <s> Born in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada, Pidgeon was the son of Hannah (née Sanborn), a housewife, and Caleb Burpee Pidgeon, a haberdasher. <s> His brother, Larry, was an editorial writer for the "Santa Barbara News-Press". <s> Pidgeon died on September 25, 1984 in Santa Monica, California, two days after his 87th birthday following a series of strokes. <s> He bequeathed his body to the University of California, Los Angeles School of Medicine for the furtherance of medical science.
simple: Walter Pidgeon (September 23, 1897 – September 25, 1984) was a Canadian actor. <s> He starred in many movies, including "Forbidden Planet". <s> He was born in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada. <s> He died in Santa Monica, California.

title: Amalgam (chemistry)
complex: An amalgam is an alloy of mercury with another metal, which may be a liquid, a soft paste or a solid, depending upon the proportion of mercury. <s> These alloys are formed through metallic bonding, with the electrostatic attractive force of the conduction electrons working to bind all the positively charged metal ions together into a crystal lattice structure. <s> Almost all metals can form amalgams with mercury, the notable exceptions being iron, platinum, tungsten, and tantalum. <s> Silver-mercury amalgams are important in dentistry, and gold-mercury amalgam is used in the extraction of gold from ore. <s> Dentistry has used alloys of mercury with metals such as silver, copper, indium, tin and zinc. <s> Aluminium can form an amalgam through a reaction with mercury. <s> Aluminium amalgam may be prepared by either grinding aluminium pellets or wire in mercury, or by allowing aluminium wire or foil to react with a solution of mercuric chloride.
simple: An amalgam is a solution of a metal in mercury. <s> Many metals can dissolve in mercury. <s> Platinum and iron cannot form amalgams. <s> Amalgams are used in tooth fillings. <s> Aluminum forms an amalgam which can react with water because the thin oxide coating on the aluminum is dissolved.

title: Edwards Barham
complex: Erle Edwards Barham (July 10, 1937 – October 17, 2014) was an American businessman, farmer, and conservationist in Oak Ridge, a village in Morehouse Parish in North Louisiana. <s> He was the first Republican elected — by a 29-vote margin — to the Louisiana State Senate since the era of Reconstruction. <s> Barham represented the agricultural District 33 from 1976 to 1980. <s> Barham was narrowly unseated in the 1979 nonpartisan blanket primary by a Democrat, David 'Bo' Ginn of Bastrop, who held the seat until 1988. <s> Like his father, Edwards Barham died in a plane crash. <s> On October 17, 2014, Barham, a certified flight instructor, was taxiing back to the hangar after a flight at Rayville Municipal Airport in Richland Parish when his Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft struck a perimeter fence. <s> He died airborne en route to Shreveport for medical attention.
simple: Erle Edwards Barham (July 10, 1937 – October 17, 2014) was an American farmer and conservationist. <s> He was the first Republican elected—by a 29-vote margin—to the Louisiana State Senate since the era of Reconstruction. <s> Barham represented the agricultural District 33 from 1976 to 1980. <s> He was narrowly unseated in the 1979 nonpartisan blanket primary by the Democrat David "Bo" Ginn of Bastrop, who held the seat until 1988. <s> Barham died in a plane crash on October 17, 2014. <s> He was attempting to take off at Rayville Municipal Airport when his Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft struck a perimeter fence.

title: Star Trek: Enterprise
complex: Star Trek: Enterprise, titled simply Enterprise for its first two seasons, is an American science fiction television series created by Rick Berman and Brannon Braga. <s> It originally aired from September 26, 2001, to May 13, 2005, on UPN, spanning . <s> The sixth series in the "Star Trek" franchise, it served as a prequel to "". <s> The show is set in the 22nd century, a hundred years before the events of "The Original Series" and just prior to the formation of the United Federation of Planets. <s> The series follows the adventures of the "Enterprise", Earth's first starship capable of traveling at warp five, as it explores the galaxy and encounters various alien species. <s> "Star Trek: Enterprise" follows the adventures of the crew of the starship "Enterprise", designation NX-01.
simple: Enterprise (retitled Star Trek: Enterprise at the start of its third season) is a science fiction television program created by Brannon Braga and Rick Berman. <s> It aired from 2001 to 2005. <s> The series follows the adventures of humanity's first "Warp" 5 starship, the "Enterprise", ten years before the United Federation of Planets shown in previous "Star Trek" series.

title: Bee Cave, Texas
complex: Bee Cave is a city located in Travis County, and within the United States state of Texas. <s> The population was estimated at 6,535 as of 2016.
simple: Bee Cave is a city in Travis County, Texas, United States.

title: SEAT León
complex: The SEAT León (] , also spelled Leon outside of Spain) is a hatchback compact car built by the Spanish car manufacturer SEAT since October 1998. <s> The second generation León, "Typ" 1P, was released in 2005, with factory production commencing May 2005. <s> It is based on the Volkswagen Group A5 (PQ35) platform, most notably used by the Volkswagen Golf Mk5.
simple: The SEAT León is a 5-door hatchback automobile produced by SEAT in three generations since 1999. <s> After launching the second generation in 2005, the first generations continues as "León Torro" until 2006.

title: Milt Pappas
complex: Milton Steven Pappas (May 11, 1939 – April 19, 2016) was a professional baseball pitcher. <s> A 17-year veteran, Pappas, nicknamed "Gimpy", pitched for the Baltimore Orioles (1957 –1965 ), Cincinnati Reds (1966 –1968 ), Atlanta Braves (1968 –1970 ) and Chicago Cubs (1970 –1973 ). <s> Pappas was born to Greek parents, and his birth name was Miltiades Stergios Papastergios. <s> A control specialist, Pappas pitched in 520 games, starting 465, with 209 wins, 164 losses, 43 shutouts, 1,728 strikeouts and a 3.40 ERA in 3,186 innings pitched. <s> Pappas died of natural causes on April 19, 2016.
simple: Milton Steven "Milt" Pappas (May 11, 1939 – April 19, 2016) was an American professional baseball pitcher. <s> Pappas, nicknamed "Gimpy", pitched for the Baltimore Orioles (1957–1965), Cincinnati Reds (1966–1968), Atlanta Braves (1968–1970) and Chicago Cubs (1970–1973). <s> Pappas was born to Greek parents in Detroit, Michigan, and his birth name was Miltiades Stergios Papastergios. <s> Pappas pitched in 520 games, starting 465, with 209 wins, 164 losses, 43 shutouts, 1,728 strikeouts and a 3.40 ERA in 3,186 innings pitched. <s> Pappas died of natural causes on April 19, 2016 in Beecher, Illinois, aged 76.

title: Interregnum
complex: In some monarchies, such as the United Kingdom, an "interregnum" is usually avoided due to a rule described as "The King is dead. <s> Long live the King", i.e. the heir to the throne becomes a new monarch immediately on his predecessor's death or abdication. <s> This famous phrase signifies the continuity of sovereignty, attached to a personal form of power named "Auctoritas". <s> This is not so in other monarchies where the new monarch's reign begins only with coronation or some other formal or traditional event. <s> In the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth for instance, kings were elected, which often led to relatively long interregna. <s> During that time it was the Polish primate who served as an interrex (ruler between kings). <s> In Belgium the heir only becomes king upon swearing before the parliament. <s> A "Papal interregnum" occurs upon the death or resignation of the Catholic Church's Pope, though this is generally known as a "sede vacante" (literally "when the seat is vacant"). <s> The interregnum ends immediately upon election of a new Pope by the College of Cardinals.
simple: In some monarchies, such as the United Kingdom, an "interregnum" is usually avoided due to a rule described as "the king is dead, long live the King", i.e. the heir to the throne becomes a new monarch immediately on his predecessor's death or abdication. <s> This famous phrase signifies the continuity of sovereignty. <s> This is not so in other monarchies where the new monarch's reign begins only with coronation or some other formal or traditional event. <s> An "interregnum" occurs also upon the death of the Roman Catholic Pope, though this is generally known as a "sede vacante" (vacant seat). <s> The interregnum ends immediately upon election of the new Pope by the College of Cardinals.

title: Carl Vinson
complex: Carl Vinson (November 18, 1883 – June 1, 1981) was a powerful United States Representative from Georgia. <s> He was a Democrat and served for more than 50 years in the United States House of Representatives. <s> He was known as "The Father of the Two-Ocean Navy". <s> He is the longest-serving member of the United States House of Representatives from the state of Georgia.
simple: Carl Vinson (November 18, 1883 – June 1, 1981) was an American politician. <s> He served as a Representative from Georgia. <s> He was a Democrat. <s> He was the first person to serve for more than 50 years in the United States House of Representatives. <s> He was known as "The Father of the Two-Ocean Navy".

title: 1958 FIFA World Cup
complex: The 1958 FIFA World Cup, the sixth staging of the World Cup, was hosted by Sweden from 8 to 29 June. <s> The tournament was won by Brazil, who beat Sweden 5–2 in the final in the Stockholm suburb of Solna for their first title.
simple: The 1958 FIFA World Cup was a football sporting event that was held in Sweden.

title: Redlands, California
complex: Redlands is a city in San Bernardino County, California, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 68,747, up from 63,591 at the 2000 census. <s> The population was estimated at 69,999 in 2013. <s> The city is located approximately 10 mi east of downtown San Bernardino.
simple: Redlands (Serrano: "Tukut") is a city in San Bernardino County, California, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 68,747. <s> The city is located about 10 mi east of San Bernardino.

title: Timeline of Christianity
complex: The purpose of this timeline is to give a detailed account of Christianity from the beginning of the current era (AD) to the present. <s> on dates indicate approximate dates. <s> The year one is the first year in the "Christian calendar" (there is no year zero), which is the calendar presently used (in unison with the Gregorian calendar) almost everywhere in the world. <s> Traditionally, this was held to be the year Jesus was born; however, most modern scholars argue for an earlier or later date, the most agreed upon being between 6 BC and 4 BC. <s> Jesus begins his ministry after his baptism by John and during the rule of Pilate, preaching: "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is near" . <s> While the historicity of the gospel accounts is questioned to some extent by some critical scholars and non-Christians, the traditional view states the following chronology for his ministry: Temptation, Sermon on the Mount, Appointment of the Twelve, alleged Miracles, Temple Money Changers, Last Supper, Arrest, Trial, Passion, Crucifixion on Nisan 14th ( , , Gospel of Peter) or Nisan 15th (Synoptic Gospels), entombment by Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus, professed Resurrection by God and claimed Resurrection appearances of Jesus to Mary Magdalene and other women , Simon Peter , and others, , Great Commission, Ascension, Second Coming Prophecy to fulfill the rest of Messianic prophecy such as the Resurrection of the dead, the Last Judgment, and establishment of the Kingdom of God and the Messianic Age. <s> Shortly after the death and resurrection of Jesus (Nisan 14 or 15), the Jerusalem church is founded as the first Christian church with about 120 Jews and Jewish Proselytes , followed by Pentecost (Sivan 6), the Ananias and Sapphira incident, Pharisee Gamaliel's defense of the Apostles , the stoning of Saint Stephen (see also Persecution of Christians) and the subsequent dispersion of the Apostles ( , also ) which leads to the baptism of Simon Magus in Samaria , and also an Ethiopian eunuch . <s> Paul's "Road to Damascus" conversion to "Apostle to the Gentiles" is first recorded in , cf. . <s> Peter baptizes the Roman Centurion Cornelius, who is traditionally considered the first Gentile convert to Christianity . <s> The Antioch church is founded, it was there that the term Christian was first used . <s> Constantine called the First Council of Nicaea in 325 to unify Christology, also called the first great Christian council by Jerome, the first ecumenical, decreed the Original Nicene Creed, but rejected by Nontrinitarians such as Arius, Theonas, Secundus of Ptolemais, Eusebius of Nicomedia, and Theognis of Nicaea who were excommunicated, also addressed Easter controversy and passed 20 Canon laws such as Canon VII which granted special recognition to Jerusalem.
simple: This timeline is to show the history of Christianity from the beginning to the present. <s> Question marks on dates mean that dates are not exact. <s> The Gregorian calendar is now used almost everywhere in the world (except for calculating the holy days of other religions). <s> There is no year zero. <s> The exact date is not certain, but most agree that it was between 6 BC and 4 BC. <s> Jesus began his ministry after his baptism by John and during the rule of Pilate, preaching: "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is near" (Matt 4:12–17). <s> While the historicity of the gospel accounts is questioned to some extent by most critical scholars and non-Christians, the traditional view states the following chronology for his ministry: Temptation, Sermon on the Mount, Appointment of the Twelve, Miracles, Temple Money Changers, Last Supper, Arrest, Trial, Passion, Crucifixion on Good Friday (Mark 15:42, John 19:42), Nisan 14th (John 19:14, Mark 14:2, Gospel of Peter) or Nisan 15th (Synoptic Gospels), (7 Apr 30, 3 Apr 33, 30 Mar 36, possible Fri-14-Nisan dates – Meier), entombment by Pharisees Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus of the Sanhedrin, Resurrection by God on Easter Sunday, appearances to Paul of Tarsus (1Cor 15:3–9), Simon Peter (Luke 24:34), Mary Magdalene (Mark 16:9, John 20:10–18), and others, Great Commission, Ascension, Second Coming Prophecy to fulfill the rest of Messianic prophecy such as the Resurrection of the dead, the Last Judgment, and establishment of the Kingdom of God and the Messianic Age. <s> Shortly after the Crucifixion of Jesus (Nisan 14 or 15), the Jerusalem church was founded as the first Christian church with about 120 Jews and Jewish proselytes (Acts 1:15), followed by Pentecost, the Ananias and Sapphira incident, Pharisee Gamaliel's defense of the Apostles (5:34–39), the stoning of Saint Stephen (see also Persecution of Christians) and the subsequent dispersal of the church (7:54–8:8) which led to the baptism of Simon Magus in Samaria (8:9–24), and also an Ethiopian eunuch (8:26–40). <s> Paul's conversion to "Apostle to the Gentiles" is first recorded in (9:13–16, cf. Gal 1:11–24). <s> Peter baptized the Centurion Cornelius, who is traditionally considered the first Gentile convert to Christianity (10). <s> The Antioch church was founded. <s> It was there that the term Christian was first used (11:26). <s> Constantine called the First Council of Nicaea in 325 to unify Christology, also called the first great Christian council by Jerome, the first ecumenical, decreed the Original Nicene Creed, but rejected by Nontrinitarianism such as Arius, Theonas, Secundus, Eusebius of Nicomedia, and Theognis who were excommunicated, also addressed Easter controversy and passed 20 Canon laws.

title: Skin Yard
complex: Skin Yard was an American grunge band from Seattle, Washington, who were active from 1985 to 1993. <s> The group never gained a mainstream audience, but were an influence on several of their grunge contemporaries, including Soundgarden, Screaming Trees, and Green River.
simple: Skin Yard was a rock band from Seattle, Washington, who were active from 1985 to 1992. <s> The group never gained any mainstream audience, but were an influence on their contemporaries – most notably Soundgarden, The Melvins, and Green River – alongside whom they are considered the early pioneers of the sound that would later be called grunge.

title: Water Lilies (Monet series)
complex: Water Lilies (or Nymphéas, ] ) is a series of approximately 250 oil paintings by French Impressionist Claude Monet (1840–1926). <s> The paintings depict his flower garden at his home in Giverny, and were the main focus of his artistic production during the last thirty years of his life. <s> Many of the works were painted while Monet suffered from cataracts. <s> The paintings are on display at museums all over the world, including the Princeton University Art Museum, Musée Marmottan Monet, the Musée d'Orsay in Paris, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Museum of Modern Art in New York, the Art Institute of Chicago, the Saint Louis Art Museum, the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City, Missouri, the Carnegie Museum of Art, the National Museum of Wales, the Musée des Beaux-Arts de Nantes, the Cleveland Museum of Art, the Portland Art Museum and the Legion of Honor.
simple: Water Lilies (or Nymphéas, ]) is a series of about 250 oil paintings by French Impressionist Claude Monet. <s> The paintings are of Monet's flower garden at Giverny. <s> They were the main focus of Monet's work during the last thirty years of his life. <s> Many of the works were painted while Monet suffered from cataracts. <s> The paintings are on display in museums all over the world, including the Musée Marmottan Monet and the Musée d'Orsay in Paris, the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the Art Institute of Chicago, the Carnegie Museum of Art and the National Museum of Wales, among others.

title: Seychelles at the Olympics
complex: Seychelles first participated at the Olympic Games in 1980, and has sent athletes to compete in most Summer Olympic Games since then, missing only the 1988 Games when Seychelles did not respond to the invitation sent by the IOC. <s> The nation has never participated in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> To date, no Seychellois athlete has ever won an Olympic medal. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Seychelles was created in 1979 and recognized by the International Olympic Committee that same year.
simple: Seychelles was first at the Olympic Games in 1980. <s> They have been in most Summer Olympic Games since then, missing only the 1988 Games in support of North Korea. <s> The nation has never been in the Winter Olympic Games. <s> As of 2011, no Seychellois athlete has won an Olympic medal. <s> The National Olympic Committee for Seychelles was created in 1979. <s> They were recognized by the International Olympic Committee that same year.

title: Marin Marais
complex: Marin Marais (] ; 31 May 1656, Paris – 15 August 1728, Paris) was a French composer and viol player. <s> He studied composition with Jean-Baptiste Lully, often conducting his operas, and with master of the bass viol Monsieur de Sainte-Colombe for six months. <s> In 1676 he was hired as a musician to the royal court of Versailles and was moderately successful there, being appointed in 1679 as "ordinaire de la chambre du roy pour la viole," a title he kept until 1725. <s> Marin Marais was a master of the viol, and the leading French composer of music for the instrument. <s> He wrote five books of "Pièces de viole" (1686–1725) for the instrument, generally suites with basso continuo. <s> These were quite popular in the court, and for these he was remembered in later years as he who "founded and firmly established the empire of the viol" (Hubert Le Blanc, 1740). <s> His other works include a book of "Pièces en trio" (1692) and four operas (1693–1709), "Alcyone" (1706) being noted for its tempest scene. <s> As with Sainte-Colombe, little of Marin Marais' personal life is known after he reached adulthood. <s> Marin Marais married a Parisian, Catherine d'Amicourt, on 21 September 1676. <s> They had 19 children together. <s> Facsimiles of all five books of Marais' "Pièces de viole" are published by Éditions J.M. Fuzeau. <s> A complete critical edition of his instrumental works in seven volumes, edited by John Hsu, is published by Broude Brothers.
simple: Marin Marais (31 May 1656, Paris – 15 August 1728, Paris) was a French composer and viol player. <s> He then learnt from Monsieur de Sainte-Colombe, a famous bass viol player. <s> Marais often conducted the operas Lully had written. <s> Marais was hired as a musician in 1676 to play at the royal court of Versailles. <s> In 1679 he was appointed "ordinaire de la chambre du roy pour la viole", a title he kept until 1725. <s> He was a master of the basse de viol. <s> He wrote a lot of music for that instrument, he was the most important French composer for it. <s> He wrote five books of "Pièces de viole" (1686-1725). <s> Most of the pieces in the book are suites with basso continuo. <s> These were quite popular in the court, and for these he was remembered in later years as he who "founded and firmly established the empire of the viol" (Hubert Le Blanc, 1740). <s> His other works include a book of "Pièces en trio" (1692) and four operas (1693-1709). <s> "Alcyone" (1706) is well known for its storm scene. <s> He married Catherine d'Amicourt, on 21 September 1676. <s> They had 19 children together. <s> Facsimiles of all five books of Marais' "Pièces de viole" are published by Éditions J.M. Fuzeau. <s> A complete critical edition of his instrumental works in seven volumes, edited by John Hsu, is published by Broude Brothers.

title: Molucca Sea
complex: The Moluccan Sea (Indonesian: "Laut Maluku") is located in the western Pacific Ocean, around the vicinity of Indonesia, specifically bordered by the Indonesian Islands of Celebes (Sulawesi) to the west, Halmahera to the east, and the Sula Islands to the south. <s> The Molucca Sea has a total surface area of 77,000 square miles (200,000 square km). <s> The Molucca Sea is rich in coral and has many diving sites due to the deepness of its waters. <s> The deepness of the water explains the reasoning behind dividing the sea into three zones, which functions to transport water from the Pacific Ocean to the shallower seas surrounding it. <s> The deepest hollow in the Molucca Sea is the 15,780-foot (4,810-meter) Batjan (Indonesian: "Bacan") basin. <s> This region is known for its periodic experiences of earthquakes, which stems from the sea itself being a micro plate, in which the Molucca Sea is being subducted in two opposite directions: one in the direction of the Eurasian Plate to the west and the other in the direction of the Philippines Sea Plate to the east. <s> The Molucca Sea borders the Banda Sea to the south and the Celebes Sea to the west. <s> To the north is Philippine Sea and to the east is Halmahera Sea. <s> The islands bordering the Moluccan Sea include Halmahera to the north east, Buru and Ceram in the centre, and Sulawesi to the west. <s> The Talaud Islands to the north are considered to be the northern border the sea, though the Molucca Sea Plate, the tectonic plate named after the sea, extends further north.
simple: The Molucca Sea is in the western Pacific Ocean, within the country of Indonesia. <s> The region is rich in coral and has many diving sites. <s> The Molucca Sea borders the Banda Sea to the south and the Celebes Sea to the north. <s> The islands bordering the Molucca Sea include Halmahera to the north east, Buru and Ceram in the centre, and Sulawesi to the west. <s> The Talaud Islands to the north are the general limit of the sea. <s> The Molucca Sea Plate, the tectonic plate named after the sea, goes further north.

title: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt
complex: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt is a "Kreis" (district) in the south of Thuringia, Germany. <s> Neighboring districts are (from the north clockwise) the districts Weimarer Land, Saale-Holzland, Saale-Orla, the district Kronach in Bavaria, and the districts Sonneberg, Hildburghausen and Ilm-Kreis. <s> The district dates back to the "Landratsamt" Saalfeld, which was created in 1868, and in 1922 it was converted into the "Landkreis". <s> Also in 1922 the district Rudolstadt was created, the second historical root of the district as of today. <s> Both districts were merged in the communal reform of 1994. <s> The main rivers in the district is the Saale.
simple: Saalfeld-Rudolstadt is a "Landkreis" (district) in the south of Thuringia, Germany. <s> The district dates back to the "Landratsamt" Saalfeld, which was created in 1868, and in 1922 it was converted into the "Landkreis". <s> Also in 1922 the district Rudolstadt was created. <s> Both districts were merged in the local government changes of 1994.

title: Thomas L. Kane
complex: Thomas Leiper Kane (January 27, 1822 – December 26, 1883) was an American attorney, abolitionist, philanthropist, and military officer who was influential in the western migration of the Latter-day Saint movement and served as a Union Army colonel and general of volunteers in the American Civil War. <s> He received a brevet promotion to major general for gallantry at the Battle of Gettysburg. <s> Kane came in contact with members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints during a Philadelphia conference in May 1846. <s> Kane offered them his advice and help in their conflicts with the US government and in their efforts to emigrate to western territories. <s> Jesse C. Little, presiding LDS elder in the East, was soliciting support for the Latter-day Saints' westward migration. <s> Politically well-connected through his father, Kane provided letters of recommendation and later joined Little in Washington, D.C. <s> The two called on the secretary of state, secretary of war, and President James K. Polk. <s> As a result of their negotiations, the United States agreed to enlist up to 500 LDS men, in five companies of 75 to 100 men each, as the Mormon Battalion, to serve in the Mexican–American War. <s> With the help of his father, Kane obtained US government permission for the refugee Mormons to occupy Pottawattamie and Omaha Indian lands along the Missouri. <s> After carrying dispatches relating to the land agreements and battalion criteria to Fort Leavenworth, Kane sought out Little in the Latter-day Saint encampments on the Missouri River. <s> On July 17, 1846, a meeting was held with Kane, LDS leaders and Army Captain James Allen to create the Mormon Battalion. <s> Kane met many leaders of the church, and became a popular figure among Mormon emigrants. <s> Miller's Hollow, the principal Iowa settlement of the LDS group at the site of present-day Council Bluffs, was renamed Kanesville in recognition of his service. <s> During this stay, Kane became seriously ill. <s> Although good care from both an army physician from Fort Leavenworth and church members helped him recover, he suffered poor health the rest of his life. <s> Kane became a personal friend of Brigham Young, and stayed in contact with the church leader for many years. <s> Kane visited Utah several times, advising Young on dealing with the federal government.
simple: Thomas L. Kane (January 27, 1822 – December 26, 1883) was an American lawyer. <s> Kane met with members of the LDS Church at a meeting in Philadelphia in May 1846. <s> Kane gave them his advice (told them what he thought they should do) and helped with their conflicts (arguments) with the U.S. government. <s> He also helped them when they tried to emigrate (move) to western areas (places) in the US. <s> , an LDS religious leader in the East, was asking for help with the Latter-day Saints' move to the West. <s> Kane was able to get letters of recommendation (letters that say Kane can be trusted) from people who knew his father. <s> Kane later joined Little in , and they met the secretary of state, secretary of war, and President . <s> After they negotiated (shared and talked about ideas), the United States agreed to send 500 LDS men, in five groups of 75 to 100 men each, called the , to help in the . <s> With his fathers help, Kane got U.S. government permission for the refugee (people who have lost or had to leave their homes) Mormons to occupy Pottawattamie and Omaha Indian lands along the Missouri. <s> Kane carried letters to , and looked for Little in the Latter-day Saint camps on the . <s> On July 17, 1846, Kane met with LDS leaders and Army Captain to make the Mormon Battalion. <s> Kane met many leaders of the Church, and became a popular figure among Mormon emigrants (people who moved). <s> Miller's Hollow, the main Iowa settlement (colony) of the LDS group at what is now , was renamed Kanesville to honor Kane for his help. <s> During this time, Kane became really ill with a fever. <s> Although he got help from both an army physician (doctor) from Fort Leavenworth and church members, his health was not good for the rest of his life. <s> He was friends with Brigham Young, a leader in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, or Mormon church, or LDS Church. <s> Kane helped Brigham Young and the Mormons travel to Utah.

title: Fernando Gago
complex: Fernando Rubén Gago (] ; born 10 April 1986) is an Argentine footballer who last played for Boca Juniors as a defensive midfielder and deep-lying playmaker. <s> He is also a former Argentina national team player.
simple: Fernando Gago (born 10 April 1986) is an Argentine football player. <s> He plays for Real Madrid and Argentina national team.

title: Prince of Orange
complex: Prince of Orange (or Princess of Orange if the holder is female) is a title originally associated with the sovereign Principality of Orange, in what is now southern France. <s> Under the Treaty of Utrecht of 1713, Frederick William I of Prussia ceded the Principality of Orange to King Louis XIV of France (while retaining the title as part of his dynastic titulature). <s> After William III of England died without children, a dispute arose between Johan Willem Friso and Frederick I of Prussia, which was settled in the Treaty of Partition (1732); consequently, Friso's son, William IV had to share use of the title "Prince of Orange" (which had accumulated prestige in the Netherlands and throughout the Protestant world) with Frederick William I of Prussia. <s> With the emergence of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, the title is traditionally borne by the heir apparent of the Dutch monarch. <s> Originally only worn by men, since 1983 the title descends via absolute primogeniture, which means that the holder can be either Prince or Princess of Orange. <s> The Dutch royal dynasty, the House of Orange-Nassau, is not the only family to claim the dynastical title. <s> Rival claims to the title have been made by German emperors and kings of the House of Hohenzollern and by the head of the French noble family of Mailly. <s> The current users of the title are Princess Catharina-Amalia of the Netherlands (Orange-Nassau), Georg Friedrich, Prince of Prussia (Hohenzollern), and Guy, Marquis de Mailly-Nesle (Mailly). <s> The title originally referred to Orange in the Vaucluse department in the Rhone valley of southern France, which was a property of the House of Orange, then of the House of Baux and the House of Châlon-Arlay before passing in 1544 to the House of Orange-Nassau. <s> The last descendant of the original princes, René of Châlon, left the principality to his cousin William the Silent, who was not a descendant of the original Orange family but the heir to the principality of Orange by testament, however in violation against the inheritance pattern enacted by the last will of Marie des Baux, the Princess of Orange through kinship to whom Prince René derived his own right thereto. <s> In 1673, Louis XIV of France annexed all territory of the principality to France and to the royal domain, as part of the war actions against the stadtholder William III of Orange — who later became King William III of Great Britain. <s> Orange ceased to exist as a sovereign realm, de facto. <s> After the marquis (who died in 1713), the next holder was , marquis de Nesle (1689–1764). <s> Although no longer descended from Louis-Charles, a branch of the Mailly family still claim the title today. <s> In 1714 Louis XIV bestowed the usufruct of the principality on his kinsman, Louis Armand of Bourbon, Prince de Conti. <s> After his death in 1727 the principality was deemed merged in the Crown by 1731. <s> Because William III died without legitimate children, the principality was regarded as having been inherited by his closest cognate relative on the basis of the testament of Frederic-Henry, Frederick I of Prussia, who ceded the principality — at least the lands, but not the formal title — to France in 1713. <s> France supported his claim. <s> In this way, the territory of the principality lost its feudal and secular privileges and became a part of France. <s> The Treaty of Utrecht allowed the King of Prussia to erect part of the duchy of Gelderland (the cities of Geldern, Straelen and Wachtendonk with their bailiwicks, Krickenbeck, Viersen, the land of Kessel, the lordships of Afferden, Arcen-Velden-Lomm, Walbeck-Twisteden, Raay and Klein-Kevelaer, Well, Bergen and Middelaar) into a new "Principality of Orange". <s> The kings of Prussia and the German emperors styled themselves Princes of Orange till 1918. <s> An agnatic relative of William III, John William Friso of Nassau, who was also cognatically descended from William the Silent, was designated the heir to the princes of Orange in the Netherlands by the last will of William III. <s> Several of his descendants became stadtholders. <s> They claim the principality of Orange on the basis of agnatic inheritance, similar to that of William the Silent, who had inherited Orange from his cousin René of Châlon. <s> They did however have a claim, albeit distant, to the principality itself due to John William Friso's descent from Louise de Coligny, who was a descendant of the original Princes of Orange. <s> (Louise's great grandmother, Anne Pot, Countess of St. Pol, was a descendant of Tiburge d'Orange, who married into the des Baux family) <s> They also claimed on the basis of the testament of Philip William, Maurice and William III. <s> Finally, they claimed on the basis that Orange was an independent state whose sovereign had the right to assign his succession according to his will. <s> France never recognized any of this, nor allowed the Orange-Nassaus or the Hohenzollerns to obtain anything of the principality itself. <s> The Oranje-Nassaus nevertheless assumed the title and also erected several of their lordships into a new principality of Orange. <s> From that derivation of the title comes the tradition of the house of Nassau-Dietz, the later stadtholders of the Netherlands, and the present-day royal family of the Netherlands, of holding this title. <s> They maintain the tradition of William the Silent and the house of Orange-Nassau. <s> Until 1340, it was customary for all sons of the prince of Orange to inherit the title. <s> Only the direct line of descent to Raimond V is shown here. <s> William of Nassau inherited the principality of Orange from his cousin René.
simple: Prince of Orange is a title of nobility. <s> The title was at first related to a self-ruling state called the Principality of Orange. <s> At the moment, the title is used by Prince Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands (Orange-Nassau), Georg Friedrich, Prince of Prussia (Hohenzollern) and Guy, Marquis de Mailly-Neslé, Prince d'Orange. <s> The land was the property of the house of Orange and from 1544 of the house of Orange-Nassau. <s> The last of the original princes, René of Nassau, left the principality to his cousin William the Silent after he died. <s> William the Silent was not related to the original house of Orange, but was the legal heir. <s> In a war in 1673, Louis XIV of France took over the lands of the principality and added them to his own royal domain. <s> This was part of the war against the stadtholder William III of Orange. <s> His descendant still claims the title today. <s> In 1714, Louis XIV allowed Prince Louis Armand of Bourbon-Conti to use the land of the Principality to make money. <s> Prince Louis Armand died in 1727 and the principality was merged in the Crown in 1731. <s> William III died without legitimate children. <s> This meant that the principality was seen as inherited by his closest cognate relative on the basis of the testament of Frederic-Henry, Frederick I of Prussia . <s> He handed over the principality's lands but not the title to France in 1713. <s> France supported his claim. <s> In this way, the territory of the principality was no longer a separate state, but became a part of France. <s> Through the Treaty of Utrecht. <s> The kings of Prussia and the German emperors styled themselves Princes of Orange till 1918. <s> John William Friso of Nassau was chosen as the heir to the princes of Orange in the Netherlands by the last will of William III. <s> Several of his descendants became stadtholders. <s> They claim the principality of Orange on the basis of agnatic inheritance (inheritance of lands to the brother rather than the sons of the king) . <s> This way of inheriting is similar to the way William the Silent inherited from his cousin René. <s> The claim to the title is also on basis of the testament of Philips William, Maurice and William III. <s> Although they claimed the title "Prince of Orange", France never allowed them to obtain anything of the lands of the principality itself. <s> It is from this tradition that later stadtholders of the Netherlands, and the present-day royal family of the Netherlands, also hold the title. <s> Until 1340, it was customary for all sons of the prince of Orange to inherit the title. <s> Only the direct line of descent to Raimond V is shown here.

title: Tuvan People's Republic
complex: The Tuvan People's Republic (TPR); ; Uniform Turkic Alphabet: "Tьʙа Arat Respuʙlik" , ] , known as the Tannu Tuva People's Republic until 1926, was a partially recognized socialist republic that existed between 1921 and 1944. <s> The country was located in the same territory as the former Tuvan protectorate of Imperial Russia known as Uryankhay Krai.
simple: Tuvan People's Republic was a partially recognized state that existed from 1921 to 1944. <s> Until 1926, it was also known as People's Republic Tannu-Tuva.

title: AK-47
complex: In 1974, the Soviets began replacing their AK-47 and AKM rifles with a newer design, the AK-74, which uses 5.45×39mm ammunition. <s> This new rifle and cartridge had only started to be manufactured in Eastern European nations when the Soviet Union collapsed, drastically slowing production of the AK-74 and other weapons of the former Soviet bloc. <s> The AK-47 was designed to be a simple, reliable fully automatic rifle that could be manufactured quickly and cheaply, using mass production methods that were state of the art in the Soviet Union during the late 1940s. <s> The AK-47 uses a long stroke gas system that is generally associated with great reliability in adverse conditions. <s> The large gas piston, generous clearances between moving parts, and tapered cartridge case design allow the gun to endure large amounts of foreign matter and fouling without failing to cycle. <s> The AK-47 and its variants have been and are made in dozens of countries, with "quality ranging from finely engineered weapons to pieces of questionable workmanship." <s> As a result, the AK-47 has a service/system life of approximately 6,000, to 10,000, to 15,000 rounds. <s> The AK-47 was designed to be a cheap, simple, easy to manufacture assault rifle, perfectly matching Soviet military doctrine that treats equipment and weapons as disposable items. <s> As units are often deployed without adequate logistical support and dependent on "battlefield cannibalization" for resupply, it is actually more cost-effective to replace rather than repair weapons. <s> In the pro-communist states, the AK-47 became a symbol of the Third World revolution. <s> They were utilized in the Cambodian Civil War and the Cambodian–Vietnamese War. <s> During the 1980s, the Soviet Union became the principal arms dealer to countries embargoed by Western nations, including Middle Eastern nations such as Iran, Libya, and Syria, which welcomed Soviet Union backing against Israel. <s> After the fall of the Soviet Union, AK-47s were sold both openly and on the black market to any group with cash, including drug cartels and dictatorial states, and more recently they have been seen in the hands of Islamic groups such as Al-Qaeda, ISIL, and the Taliban in Afghanistan and Iraq, and FARC, Ejército de Liberación Nacional guerrillas in Colombia. <s> The proliferation of this weapon is reflected by more than just numbers. <s> The AK-47 is included in the flag of Mozambique and its emblem, an acknowledgment that the country gained its independence in large part through the effective use of their AK-47s. <s> It is also found in the coats of arms of East Timor and the revolution era Burkina Faso, as well as in the flags of Hezbollah, Syrian Resistance, FARC-EP, the New People's Army, TKP/TIKKO and the International Revolutionary People's Guerrilla Forces.
simple: It was later replaced by the AK-74. <s> The AK-47 uses gas-operated reloading. <s> The AK-47 and its successors continue to be used by many of the world's armies. <s> It is a cheap, reliable, and easy-to-use weapon. <s> In the pro-communist states, the AK-47 became a symbol of the Third World revolution. <s> They were used in the Cambodian Civil War and the Cambodian–Vietnamese War. <s> During the 1980s, the Soviet Union became the principal arms dealer to countries embargoed by Western nations. <s> This included Middle Eastern nations such as Iran, Libya, and Syria, which welcomed Soviet Union backing against Israel. <s> After the end of the Soviet Union (1989/90), AK-47s were sold openly and on the black market to any group with cash, including drug cartels and dictatorial states. <s> More recently they have been seen in the hands of Islamic groups such as Al-Qaeda, ISIL, and the Taliban in Afghanistan and Iraq, and FARC, Ejército de Liberación Nacional guerrillas in Colombia. <s> The proliferation of this weapon is shown by more than just numbers. <s> The AK-47 is included in the flag of Mozambique, an acknowledgment that the country gained its independence in large part through the effective use of their AK-47s. <s> It is also found in the coats of arms of East Timor and the revolution era Burkina Faso, as well as in the flags of Hezbollah, FARC-EP, the New People's Army in the Phillipines, TKP/TIKKO and other "Revolutionary Peoples" groups.

title: Parliamentary opposition
complex: Parliamentary opposition is a form of political opposition to a designated government, particularly in a Westminster-based parliamentary system. <s> This article uses the term "government" as it is used in Parliamentary systems, i.e. meaning "the administration" or "the cabinet" rather than "the state". <s> The title of "Official Opposition" usually goes to the largest of the parties sitting in opposition with its leader being given the title "Leader of the Opposition".
simple: Parliamentary opposition is a political position. <s> It is a type of opposition to the government. <s> They are called the "Official Opposition" sometimes.

title: Jeffery Dench
complex: Jeffery Danny Dench (29 April 1928 – 27 March 2014) was an English actor, best known for his work with the Royal Shakespeare Company. <s> He was the older brother of actress Judi Dench. <s> On 27 March 2014 it was announced that Jeffery Dench had died. <s> Writing after his death, Sylvia Morris said: When not playing grotesque old men, he brought humour, warmth and integrity to his parts.
simple: Jeffery Dench (29 April 1928 – 27 March 2014) was an English actor. <s> He is best known for his work with the Royal Shakespeare Company. <s> He was the older brother of actress Judi Dench. <s> Dench died on 27 March 2014, aged 85.

title: Florence Bjelke-Petersen
complex: Florence Isabel Bjelke-Petersen (née Gilmour; 11 August 1920 – 20 December 2017) was an Australian politician and writer. <s> She was a member of the Australian Senate from 1981 to 1993, and was the wife of the longest-serving Premier of Queensland, Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen. <s> She was styled as Lady Bjelke-Petersen upon her husband's knighthood, and was also known informally as Lady Flo. <s> She was re-elected at the 1983 and 1987 elections (both double dissolutions), and her term expired on 30 June 1993. <s> Bjelke-Petersen died in Kingaroy, Queensland, at Orana Aged Care, where she had resided since August 2014, at the age of 97, after suffering a short illness. <s> Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull and Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk offered to hold a state funeral which was accepted by their son John Bjelke-Petersen.
simple: Florence Isabel Bjelke-Petersen (née Gilmour; 11 August 1920 – 20 December 2017) was an Australian politician and writer. <s> She was a member of the Australian Senate from 1981 to 1993. <s> Bjelke-Petersen was the wife of the longest-serving Premier of Queensland, Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen. <s> She was styled as Lady Bjelke-Petersen upon her husband's knighthood, and was also known informally as Lady Flo. <s> She was re-elected at the 1983 and 1987 elections (both double dissolutions), and her term expired on 30 June 1993. <s> Lady Bjelke-Petersen died in Kingaroy, Queensland on 20 December 2017 of cardiopulmonary arrest at the age of 97, after suffering a short illness.

title: John Finnegan (actor)
complex: John P. "J.P." Finnegan (August 18, 1926 – July 29, 2012) was an American film and television actor, mostly known for his recurrent role on the American crime fiction series "Columbo". <s> He voiced the villainous character Warren T. Rat in the 1986 Don Bluth film "An American Tail". <s> Finnegan died on July 29, 2012 at his home in Palm Desert, California from complications of pneumonia, aged 85.
simple: John P. Finnegan (August 18, 1926 – July 29, 2012) was an American television, voice, stage, and movie actor. <s> He died on July 29, 2012 from pneumonia and old age in his home in Palm Desert, California, aged 85.

title: María Antonieta de las Nieves
complex: María Antonieta Gómez-Rodríguez (born 22 December 1950), more commonly known by her stage name María Antonieta de las Nieves, is a Mexican actress, comedian, and singer. <s> Her best remembered role is that of La Chilindrina, one of the main characters of the Televisa sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho". <s> De las Nieves became famous as La Chilindrina in the Televisa sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho".
simple: María Antonieta Gómez Rodríguez (born 22 December 1950), more commonly known by her stage name María Antonieta de las Nieves, is a Mexican actress, comedienne, and singer. <s> She is known for her role as La Chilindrina in the Mexican sitcom "El Chavo del Ocho".

title: Jette
complex: Jette (] ; ] ) is one of the nineteen municipalities located in the Brussels-Capital Region of Belgium. <s> In common with all the Brussels municipalities, it is legally bilingual (French–Dutch).
simple: Jette is a municipality in the Belgian Brussels-Capital Region.

title: Pat Patterson (wrestler)
complex: Patrick Patterson (born Pierre Clermont on January 19, 1941) is a Canadian–American professional wrestler. <s> He is currently employed by the professional wrestling promotion WWE as a creative consultant and producer. <s> He is the inaugural WWE Intercontinental Champion and creator of the Royal Rumble match, Patterson was inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame class of 1996. <s> In 2019, Patterson became the oldest person to ever win a title in WWE history, after winning the WWE 24/7 Championship at 78 years old. <s> He has been described by journalist Dave Meltzer as "Vince McMahon's right-hand man" and "one of the chief architects of the WWE, playing an integral role in helping it become a global phenomenon.". <s> Patterson is openly gay. <s> He first came out in the early 1970s, and although Jim Ross made several jokes about it on commentary, his sexuality was not acknowledged publicly or in WWE storylines until the season finale of "WWE Legends' House", which aired June 12, 2014.
simple: Pierre Clermont (born March 19, 1941) is a Canadian retired professional wrestler. <s> He is better known by the ring name Pat Patterson. <s> He currently works as a creative consultant for the WWE. <s> Patterson was inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame in 1996. <s> Patterson is openly gay.

title: Nobuo Kawakami
complex: Nobuo Kawakami (川上 信夫 , Kawakami Nobuo , born October 4, 1947) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Nobuo Kawakami (川上 信夫, Kawakami Nobuo, born October 4, 1947) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Joseph Yobo
complex: Joseph Phillip Yobo (born 6 September 1980) is a former Nigerian professional footballer who played as a centre back. <s> He was the captain of the Nigerian national team until his international football retirement in June 2014, and is Nigeria's joint record appearance holder. <s> Yobo left Nigeria to join Standard Liège in 1998. <s> He made his first team debut in 2000, and went on to appear 46 times. <s> In 2001, he was bought by Marseille.
simple: Joseph Yobo (born 6 September 1980) is a Nigerian football player who plays for Everton in the Premier League. <s> Yobo is also captain of the national Nigerian side. <s> He signed from French side Olympique Marseille in 2001 and has become a favourite at Everton ever since.

title: Miss USA
complex: Miss USA is an American beauty pageant that has been held annually since 1952 to select the entrant from United States in the Miss Universe pageant. <s> The Miss Universe Organization operates both pageants, as well as Miss Teen USA.
simple: The Miss USA pageant is a beauty contest. <s> It has been held every year since 1952. <s> The Miss Universe Organization operates both pageants. <s> It also operates Miss Teen USA.

title: Cunt
complex: Cunt is a vulgar word for the vulva or vagina and is also used as a term of disparagement. <s> Reflecting different national usages, "cunt" is described as a "usually disparaging and obscene" term for a woman or an "offensive way to refer to a woman" in the United States by the Merriam-Webster dictionary, but "an unpleasant or stupid person" in the "Compact Oxford English Dictionary", and "a contemptible person" in the "Macquarie Dictionary" of Australian English.
simple: Cunt is an abusive word that is used against people as an insult. <s> It can also be slang for the vagina or vulva.

title: Optare Alero
complex: The Optare Alero is a low-floor integral minibus that was built by Optare between 2001 and 2008. <s> It was built as an alternative to van-derived buses such as the Mercedes-Benz Sprinter. <s> Around 300 were built in the first five years of production. <s> The primary markets for the Alero have been community transport groups and rural demand responsive bus routes.
simple: The Optare Alero was a low-floor minibus that was built by Optare between 2001 and 2008. <s> Around 300 were built in the first five years of being built.

title: Gustav Adolf Church, Liverpool
complex: Gustav Adolf Church or the Scandinavian Seamen's Church is a historical building located in Park Lane, Liverpool, Merseyside, England. <s> It consists of a church, built between 1883 and 1884, and an attached minister's house, and provides a centre for the Liverpool International Nordic Community. <s> The combined church and minister's house is recorded in the National Heritage List for England as a designated Grade II* listed building.
simple: The Gustav Adolf Church or the Scandinavian Seamen's Church is located in Park Lane, Liverpool, Merseyside, England. <s> It consists of a church, built between 1883-1884, and an attached minister's house, and provides a centre for the Liverpool International Nordic Community. <s> The combined church and minister's house is designated by English Heritage as a Grade II* listed building.

title: Memè Perlini
complex: Amelio "Memè" Perlini (8 December 1947 – 5 April 2017) was an Italian actor and film director. <s> His directorial debut, "Italian Postcards", was screened in the "Un Certain Regard" section at the 1987 Cannes Film Festival. <s> Perlini died in Rome on 5 April 2017, at the age of 69. <s> He seems to have committed suicide by jumping from the fifth floor of his house.
simple: Amelio "Memè" Perlini (8 December 1947 – 5 April 2017) was an Italian actor and movie director. <s> His debut movie as a director, "Italian Postcards", was screened in the Un Certain Regard section at the 1987 Cannes Film Festival. <s> Perlini died in Rome on 5 April 2017, aged 69. <s> He committed suicide, by jumping from the fifth floor of his house.

title: Keble College, Oxford
complex: Keble College is one of the constituent colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Its main buildings are on Parks Road, opposite the University Museum and the University Parks. <s> The college is bordered to the north by Keble Road, to the south by Museum Road, and to the west by Blackhall Road. <s> Keble was established in 1870, having been built as a monument to John Keble, who had been a leading member of the Oxford Movement which sought to stress the Catholic nature of the Church of England. <s> Consequently, the college's original teaching focus was primarily theological, although the college now offers a broad range of subjects, reflecting the diversity of degrees offered across the wider university. <s> In the period after the Second World War the trends were towards scientific courses (proximity to the university science area east of the University Museum influenced this). <s> As originally constituted, it was for men only and the fellows were mostly bachelors resident in the college. <s> Like many of Oxford's men's colleges, Keble admitted its first mixed-sex cohort in 1979. <s> It remains distinctive for its still-controversial neo-gothic red-brick buildings designed by William Butterfield. <s> The buildings are also notable for breaking from Oxbridge tradition by arranging rooms along corridors rather than around staircases, in order that the scouts could supervise the comings and goings of visitors. <s> (Girton College, Cambridge, similarly breaks this tradition.) <s> Keble is one of the larger colleges of the University of Oxford, with 433 undergraduates and 245 graduate students in 2011/12. <s> Keble's sister college at the University of Cambridge is Selwyn College.
simple: Keble College is one of the colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Its main buildings are on Parks Road, opposite the University Museum and the University Parks. <s> Keble was founded in 1870, having been built as a monument to John Keble, a leading member of the Oxford Movement. <s> In the period after the second World War the trends were towards scientific courses (the major area devoted to science east of the University Museum influenced this) and eventually co-education for men and women from 1979 onwards. <s> As originally constituted it was for men only and the fellows were mostly bachelors resident in the college. <s> It remains distinctive for its once-controversial neo-gothic red-brick buildings designed by William Butterfield. <s> Keble is one of the larger colleges, with 435 undergraduates and 245 graduate students.

title: Zaventem
complex: Zaventem (] ) is a Belgian municipality in the province of Flemish Brabant. <s> It is located in the Dijleland area, one of the three large recreational areas which together form the "Groene Gordel" ("Green Belt") around the Brussels-Capital Region.
simple: Zaventem is a municipality in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant.

title: Duck Commander
complex: Duck Commander is both the brand of a duck call and the name of the company in West Monroe, Louisiana, United States. <s> The company manufactures these calls and other duck-hunting merchandise, as well as deer-hunting merchandise under the Buck Commander brand. <s> Phil Robertson, a football quarterback at Louisiana Tech University, founded the company. <s> He began his business in a dilapidated boat, where he spent 25 years making duck calls from Louisiana cedar trees. <s> Robertson's third son, Willie Robertson, currently serves as the company's chief executive officer and has expanded it into a multimillion-dollar enterprise. <s> The Robertson family and business are the subjects of "Duck Dynasty", a reality television series on A&E. <s> Before that, they were featured in the "Duck Commander" television show on the Outdoor Channel.
simple: Duck Commander is a company that makes duck calls. <s> They also make duck and deer hunting equipment Their main office is in West Monroe, Louisiana, United States. <s> Phil Robertson, an American football quarterback at Louisiana Tech University, was originally going to play professional football in the NFL. <s> He began his business in a dilapidated shed. <s> He spent 25 years there making duck calls from Louisiana cedar trees. <s> Phil's third son, Willie Robertson, is the company's chief executive officer. <s> Willie expanded it into a multi-million dollar enterprise. <s> The Robertson family and business are the subjects of "Duck Dynasty", a reality television series on A&E. <s> Before that, they were featured in the "Duck Commander" television show on the Outdoor Channel.

Blackhawks and Columbus Blue Jackets. <s> Duclair was born in Laval, Quebec, and grew up in Pointe-Claire, Quebec. <s> He is of Haitian descent. <s> As a youth, he played in the 2008 Quebec named to the QMJHL First All-Star Team. <s> On January 2, 2014, Duclair signed a three-year, entry-level contract with the New York Rangers. <s> Duclair impressed the Rangers with his performance in the 2014–15 pre-season, leading the team with five points in five games. <s> On October 6, 2014, defenceman Steven Kampfer and centre Andrew Yogan were traded to the Florida Panthers in exchange for forward Joey Crabb, securing an opening-night roster position for Duclair. <s> Duclair scored his first NHL goal on October 27, 2014, against Darcy Kuemper of the Minnesota Wild. <s> On January 6, 2015, Duclair was assigned to the Quebec Remparts for the remainder of the 2014–15 season. <s> On March 1, 2015, while playing with the Remparts, Duclair was traded to the Arizona Coyotes (along with John Moore and two draft picks) in exchange for Keith Yandle and Chris Summers. <s> On October 14, 2015, Duclair scored his first career NHL hat-trick in a 4–0 shut-out win against the Anaheim Ducks. <s> Fellow rookie Max Domi pitched in a goal of his own and an assist on one of Duclair's goals.

title: Pygmy rabbit
complex: The pygmy rabbit ("Brachylagus idahoensis") is a North American rabbit, and is one of only two rabbit species in America to dig its own burrow. <s> The pygmy rabbit differs significantly from species within either the "Lepus" (hare) or "Sylvilagus" (cottontail) genera and is generally considered to be within the monotypic genus Brachylagus. <s> One isolated population, the Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit, is listed as an endangered species by the U.S. Federal government, though the International Union for Conservation of Nature lists the species as lower risk. <s> The pygmy rabbit is the world's smallest leporid, which means adult weights from 375 to about , and a body length from 23.5 to ; females are slightly larger than males. <s> The pygmy rabbit is distinguishable from other leporids by its small size, short ears, gray color, small hind legs, and lack of white fur on the tail. <s> The last male purebred Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit, found only in the Columbia Basin of Washington State, died March 30, 2006, at the Oregon Zoo in Portland. <s> The last purebred female died in 2008. <s> A crossbreeding program conducted by the Oregon Zoo, Washington State University and Northwest Trek is attempting to preserve the genetic line by breeding surviving females with the Idaho pygmy rabbit. <s> Weasels ("Mustela" spp.) are the principal predators of pygmy rabbits. <s> Coyotes ("Canis latrans"), red foxes ("Vulpes vulpes"), badgers, bobcats ("Felis rufus"), great horned owls ("Bubo virginianus") and northern harriers (Circus hudsonius) also prey on pygmy rabbits.

title: Pattazhy
complex: Pattazhy, also Pattazhiis a village located in Pathanapuram taluk in the eastern part of the Kollam District, Kerala state, India. <s> It is best known as the site of an ancient Bhagavathy temple, Pattazhy Devi Temple. <s> The name Pattazhy has an uncertain etymology. <s> Pattazhy may stem from an imperfect Malayalam portmanteau fusing Patt ("Soft") and Aazhy ("Ocean"). <s> Thus the word Pattazhy represents the compassion and affection of Pattazhy Devi to her beloved devotees and depth of her grace. <s> The name Pattazhy may have also derived from the word "Bhattarika" which means a virtuous and pious woman. <s> Pattazhy is a temple village situated in Pathanapuram Taluk of Kollam District in Kerala. <s> The land of Pattazhy comprising two panchayat areas (Pattazhy and Pattazhy vadakekara) was given as a gift to Pattazhy Devi by the King of Travancore for the help and shelter given in the fierce fight against the king of Kayamkulam. <s> When the king was extending his kingdom by winning war with the neighboring kingdoms with the help of Ramayyan Dalawa, Kambithan, a hardcore worshipper of Pattazhy Devi helped the king to take over Kayamkulam Kingdom. <s> As a symbol of his gratitude the king ordered to let Pattazhy be named and dedicated to Devi by issuing a royal order. <s> The annual festival at Pattazhy Devi Temple is one of the famous temple festivals in central Travancore.The Kumbhathiruvathira and Meenathiruvathira were the famous festivals of Pattazhy. <s> The festival is known for Kambam (fire works), Aalpindi Vilakku Ezhunnallathu (Procession of small structure made out of plantain kernel and germinating leaves of coconut tree with numerous lamps on it), Ponnin Thirumudi (Devi's idol carved out of pure gold and rare precious stones) Ezhunnallathu. <s> Pattazhy also got a place in the Guinness Book of world records for the 'Longest bamboo'.
simple: Pattazhy, also Pattazhi is a village in Pathanapuram taluk, Kollam district, Kerala, India. <s> The name Pattazhy has an uncertain etymology. <s> Pattazhy may stem from an imperfect Malayalam portmanteau fusing Patt ("Soft") and Aazhy ("Ocean"). <s> Thus the word Pattazhy represents the compassion and affection of Pattazhy Devi to her beloved devotees and depth of her grace. <s> The name Pattazhy may have also derived from the word "Bhattarika" which means a virtuous and pious woman. <s> The annual festival at Pattazhy Devi Temple is one of the famous temple festivals in central Travancore.The Kumbhathiruvathira and Meenathiruvathira were the famous festivals of Pattazhy. <s> The festival is known for Kambam (fire works), Aalpindi Vilakku Ezhunnallathu (Procession of small structure made out of plantain kernel and germinating leaves of coconut tree with numerous lamps on it), Ponnin Thirumudi (Devi's idol carved out of pure gold and rare precious stones) Ezhunnallathu. <s> Pattazhy also got a place in the Guinness Book of world records for the 'Longest bamboo'.
