title: Obdurodon tharalkooschild
complex: Obdurodon tharalkooschild is an extinct species of monotreme in the genus "Obdurodon". <s> It is known from a single tooth found at the Miocene-aged Two Tree Site fossil beds in Riversleigh in Queensland, Australia. <s> The type material, a single tooth, was discovered in 2012 by a team from the University of New South Wales including Mike Archer, Suzanne Hand, and Rebecca Pian. <s> The description, published in the same year, was the fourth species of the family Ornithorhynchidae to be described, the second from the Riversleigh site, and estimated to have been the largest. <s> The specific name was chosen in honour of an indigenous Australian creation story for the platypus, where a duck named Tharalkoo gives birth to a chimeric creature after being ravished by a rakali. <s> An ornithorhynchid-like monotreme with a bill resembling the modern aquatic forager, the platypus, but a much larger animal that was probably up to one metre long. <s> The species was estimated to have been present in the middle and upper Miocene (5–15 million years ago). <s> The wear patterns on the tooth are suggestive of crushing, perhaps by consuming hard-shelled animals such as turtles, rather than using a shearing action. <s> "Obdurodon tharalkooschild" is believed to have been carnivorous and estimated to be twice the size of the modern platypus at one metre long.
simple: Obdurodon tharalkooschild is an extinct species of platypus in the genus "Obdurodon". <s> Only one single tooth has been found. <s> This was at the Miocene fossil beds in Riversleigh in Queensland, Australia. <s> The tooth was discovered in 2012 by a team from the University of New South Wales including Mike Archer, Suzanne Hand, and Rebecca Pian. <s> Its name was chosen in honour of an indigenous Australian creation story for the platypus, where a duck named Tharalkoo gives birth to a strange and fantastic creature after being ravished by a water-rat. <s> The species lived during in the middle and upper Miocene about 5–15 million years ago. <s> Wear on the tooth shows that it probably crushed hard shells such as those of turtles. <s> Because of this, scientists believe that "O. tharalkooschild" was carnivorous. <s> They also believe that it was twice the size of the modern platypus at one metre long.

title: River Dart
complex: The River Dart is a river in Devon, England which rises high on Dartmoor, and releases to the sea at Dartmouth. <s> The river's name is presumed to be Brythonic Celtic meaning 'river where oak trees grow' due to the banks of the lower Dart being covered in ancient woods of native oak. <s> The Cornish word for oak is "derow"; alternatively the word for water is "dowr", the probable source of other British hydronyms such as Derwent Water. <s> Bray notes in 1832 that the name was occasionally spelled 'Darant'. <s> The river begins as two separate branches (the East Dart and West Dart), which join at Dartmeet. <s> The paths along these rivers offer very attractive walking, and there are several small waterfalls. <s> The rivers are crossed by a number of clapper bridges, notably at the hamlet of Postbridge. <s> After leaving the moor, the Dart flows southwards past Buckfast Abbey and through the towns of Buckfastleigh, Dartington and Totnes. <s> At Totnes, where there is a seventeenth-century weir (rebuilt in the 1960s), it becomes tidal, and there are no bridges below the town. <s> The Dart estuary is a large ria and is popular for sailing. <s> The village of Kingswear and town of Dartmouth are on the east and west sides of the estuary, and are linked by two vehicle ferries and a passenger ferry. <s> The Kingswear Regatta is held each year. <s> The deep water port of Dartmouth is a sheltered haven. <s> The entrance to the river from the sea is a rocky entrance with cliffs either side. <s> On the East side Kingswear Castle sits very close to the water's edge, and on the west side Dartmouth Castle is built on a rocky promontory at sea level. <s> The castles once operated a defensive chain across the estuary, which was raised at dusk to destroy enemy ships attempting to attack the harbour. <s> The remains of the operating mechanisms for the chain are still visible in Dartmouth castle. <s> The flooded ria that forms the lower reaches of the Dart, with its deep water and steeply sloping valley sides, is a considerable barrier to crossing traffic. <s> There are no bridges below Totnes. <s> The lower section of the River Dart forms Dartmouth Harbour, a deep water natural harbour with a long history of maritime usage. <s> In modern times, the port's commercial activity has declined, but it is still a busy port for local fishing vessels and a wide variety of yachts and other private boats. <s> Several local companies specialise in shipbuilding and repairs to small tonnage craft.
simple: The River Dart is an English river in Devon. <s> It rises on Dartmoor, and reaches the English Channel at Dartmouth. <s> The river's name may be Celtic meaning 'river where oak trees grow'. <s> The banks of the lower Dart are covered in ancient woods of native oak. <s> The Dart begins at Dartmeet where the separate rivers East Dart and West Dart flow into each other. <s> The East and West Dart are crossed by a number of "clapper bridges" which are big slabs of stone laid on the river bed. <s> At Totnes the river becomes tidal, and there are no bridges below the town. <s> The Dart estuary is a large 'ria' (coastel inlet). <s> It is popular for sailing. <s> The entrance to the river from the sea is rocky with cliffs either side. <s> On the East side Kingswear Castle sits very close to the water's edge, and on the west side Dartmouth Castle is built on a rocky promontory at sea level. <s> The castles once operated a defensive chain across the estuary. <s> It was raised at dusk to destroy enemy ships attempting to attack the harbour. <s> The remains of the operating mechanisms for the chain are still visible in Dartmouth castle. <s> The lower section of the River Dart forms Dartmouth Harbour, a deep water natural harbour with a long history. <s> It is still a busy port for local fishing boats and a variety of yachts and other private boats. <s> Several local companies do shipbuilding and repairs to small tonnage craft.

title: Northwest Arctic Borough, Alaska
complex: Northwest Arctic Borough is a borough located in the U.S. state of Alaska. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 7,523. <s> The borough seat is Kotzebue. <s> The borough was formed on June 2, 1986.
simple: Northwest Arctic Borough is a borough in the U.S. state of Alaska. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 7,523. <s> The borough seat is Kotzebue. <s> The borough was created on June 2, 1986.

title: Univerzitet u Prištini Faculty of Arts
complex: The Faculty of Arts of Pristina ( or ) is the faculty of arts of the University of Pristina in North Kosovo . <s> The Faculty was founded in Pristina in 1973 as the Academy of Arts and got the present name in 1986. <s> During the Kosovo War of 1999 it was moved, first to Varvarin and later to Zvečan and Kosovska Mitrovica, where it is now. <s> It is part of the University of Pristina, provisionally relocated to Kosovska Mitrovica.
simple: The Faculty of Arts of Priština (Serbian: Факултет уметности у Приштини or Fakultet umetnosti u Prištini) is the faculty of arts of the University of Priština in Kosovo, Serbia. <s> The Faculty of Arts of Pristina was founded in 1973 as the Academy of Arts, and got its present name in 1986. <s> Because of Albanian terrorist attacks it was moved in 1999. <s> It first moved to Varvarin and later to Zvečan, where it is now. <s> It is part of the University of Priština temporarily relocated in Kosovska Mitrovica.

title: Alan Trask
complex: Alan Trask (June 26, 1933 – January 9, 2019) was an American politician in the state of Florida. <s> Trask was born in Bartow, Florida. <s> He attended the University of Florida and Florida Southern College. <s> He was elected to the State Senate for the 27th district in 1968 and served until 1971. <s> He was redistricted to the 13th district in 1973, and served until 1982. <s> He was a former president pro tempore of the senate and was a member of the Democratic Party. <s> In 1981, he and Florida Representative Tom Bush successfully attached an amendment to the state budget that would deny funding to any state university that advocated sexual activity between unmarried adults. <s> Within months, Florida's Supreme Court unanimously ruled the provision an unconstitutional violation of the First Amendment. <s> Shortly thereafter, several ethics allegations were made against Senator Trask, and he resigned from office in July 1982. <s> He later switched to the Republican Party. <s> Trask died on January 9, 2019.
simple: Alan Trask (June 26, 1933 – January 9, 2019) was an American politician. <s> He was born in Bartow, Florida. <s> He was elected to the Florida State Senate for the 27th district in 1968 until 1971. <s> He was redistricted to the 13th district in 1973, and represented it until 1982. <s> He was a former president pro tempore of the senate and was a member of the Democratic Party. <s> He later switched to the Republican Party. <s> Trask died on January 9, 2019 at a hospital in Lakeland, Florida from respiratory failure, aged 85.

title: Pelecanimimus
complex: Pelecanimimus (meaning "pelican mimic") is a genus of basal ("primitive") ornithomimosaurian theropod dinosaur from the Early Cretaceous of Spain. <s> It is notable for possessing more teeth than any other member of the Ornithomimosauria (or any other theropod), most of which were toothless.
simple: Pelecanimimus (meaning "pelican mimic") is a primitive theropod dinosaur from Spain. <s> It is notable for possessing more teeth than any other member of the Ornithomimosauria (or any other theropod), most of which were toothless.

title: Eugène Gigout
complex: Eugène Gigout (] ; 23 March 1844 – 9 December 1925) was a French organist and a composer, mostly of music for his own instrument. <s> Gigout was born in Nancy, and died in Paris. <s> A pupil of Camille Saint-Saëns, he served as the organist of the French capital's Saint-Augustin Church for 62 years. <s> He became widely known as a teacher and his output as a composer was considerable. <s> Renowned as an expert improviser, he also founded his own music school. <s> His nephew by marriage was Léon Boëllmann, another distinguished French composer and organist. <s> The "10 pièces pour orgue" (composed 1890) include the "Toccata in B minor", Gigout's best-known creation, which turns up as a frequent encore at organ recitals. <s> Also fairly often played, and to be found in the same collection, is a "Scherzo in E major". <s> Other notable pieces by Gigout are "Grand chœur dialogué", which dates from 1881, and "Marche religieuse". <s> Gigout's works are now available on several commercial recordings.
simple: Eugène Gigout (23 March 1844 – 9 December 1925) was a French organist and composer of European late-romantic music for organ. <s> Gigout was born in Nancy, and died in Paris. <s> A student of Camille Saint-Saëns, he served as the organist of Saint-Augustin Church in Paris for 62 years. <s> He became known as a teacher. <s> Also, his output as a composer was large and of high quality. <s> Renowned as an expert improviser, he also founded his own music school. <s> His nephew-by-marriage, Leon Boëllmann, became another fine organist and composer for the organ (but died at the very young age of 35). <s> The "10 pièces pour orgue", composed in 1890, are Gigout's most famous compositions. <s> They are the "Toccata in B minor", his best-known composition, which turns up as a common encore at organ concerts. <s> Also fairly often performed, and to be found in the same collection, is a "Scherzo in E major". <s> Other compositions by Gigout sometimes played nowadays are "Grand Choeur Dialogué" and "Marche Religieuse". <s> Gigout's works are now available on many commercial recordings.

title: Pickup truck
complex: Modified pickups can be used as improvised, unarmoured combat vehicles called technicals.
simple: A pickup truck can be turned into an improvised military vehicle by installing a machine gun or a light cannon on the cargo bed.

title: National Portrait Gallery, London
complex: The National Portrait Gallery (NPG) is an art gallery in London housing a collection of portraits of historically important and famous British people. <s> It was the first portrait gallery in the world when it opened in 1856. <s> The gallery moved in 1896 to its current site at St Martin's Place, off Trafalgar Square, and adjoining the National Gallery. <s> It has been expanded twice since then. <s> The National Portrait Gallery also has regional outposts at Beningbrough Hall in Yorkshire and Montacute House in Somerset. <s> It is unconnected to the Scottish National Portrait Gallery in Edinburgh, with which its remit overlaps. <s> The gallery is a non-departmental public body sponsored by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. <s> The gallery houses portraits of historically important and famous British people, selected on the basis of the significance of the sitter, not that of the artist. <s> The collection includes photographs and caricatures as well as paintings, drawings and sculpture. <s> One of its best-known images is the Chandos portrait, the most famous portrait of William Shakespeare although there is some uncertainty about whether the painting actually is of the playwright. <s> Not all of the portraits are exceptional artistically, although there are self-portraits by William Hogarth, Sir Joshua Reynolds and other British artists of note. <s> Some, such as the group portrait of the participants in the Somerset House Conference of 1604, are important historical documents in their own right. <s> Often, the curiosity value is greater than the artistic worth of a work, as in the case of the anamorphic portrait of Edward VI by William Scrots, Patrick Branwell Brontë's painting of his sisters Charlotte, Emily and Anne, or a sculpture of Queen Victoria and Prince Albert in medieval costume. <s> Portraits of living figures were allowed from 1969. <s> In addition to its permanent galleries of historical portraits, the National Portrait Gallery exhibits a rapidly changing selection of contemporary work, stages exhibitions of portrait art by individual artists and hosts the annual BP Portrait Prize competition. <s> In addition to the busts of the three founders of the gallery over the entrance, the exterior of two of the original 1896 buildings are decorated with stone block busts of eminent portrait artists, biographical writers and historians. <s> These busts, sculpted by Frederick R. Thomas, depict James Granger, William Faithorne, Edmund Lodge, Thomas Fuller, The Earl of Clarendon, Horace Walpole, Hans Holbein the Younger, Sir Anthony van Dyck, Sir Peter Lely, Sir Godfrey Kneller, Louis François Roubiliac, William Hogarth, Sir Joshua Reynolds, Sir Thomas Lawrence and Sir Francis Chantrey.
simple: The National Portrait Gallery (NPG) is an art gallery in London. <s> It holds a collection of portraits of historically important and famous British people. <s> It was the first portrait William Shakespeare although there is some uncertainty about whether the painting actually is of the playwright. <s> Not all of the portraits are exceptional artistically, although there are title: Xinyang
complex: Xinyang (; postal: Sinyang) is a prefecture-level city in southeastern Henan province, People's Republic of China, the southernmost administrative division in the province. <s> Its population was 6,109,106 according to the 2010 census, and 1,230,042 of them lived in 2 urban districts, Pingqiao and Shihe. <s> The prefecture-level city of Xinyang has a total land area of 18819 km2 . <s> The city is located in the southernmost part of Henan Province, on the south bank of the Huai River. <s> It borders the cities Zhumadian to the north and Nanyang to the northwest, and the provinces of Anhui and Hubei to the east and south respectively. <s> The region where Xinyang is located is considered a subtropical area and the Dabie Mountains cover most of its territory. <s> The Xinyang City is divided into two districts and eight counties. <s> According to the 2010 Census, the population of Xinyang is of 6,109,106 inhabitants, 6.39% less than the population marked on the last census of 2000, when there were 6,527,368 inhabitants in the city.
simple: Xinyang (信阳) is a prefecture-level city in southern Henan in the People's Republic of China. <s> In 2010, 6,109,106 people lived there. <s> The city is located on the south bank of the Huai River. <s> Xinyang is divided into two districts and eight counties.

title: Chakwal
complex: Chakwal (Punjabi and ) is the capital and main city of Chakwal District, Punjab, Pakistan. <s> It is located 90 kilometres south-east of the federal capital, Islamabad and 270 kilometres from the provincial capital, Lahore.
simple: Chakwal is a city in Pakistan. <s> It is in the Punjab province and is the capital of Chakwal District.

title: Mohamed Sissoko
complex: Mohamed Lamine Sissoko Gillan (born 22 January 1985) is a Malian professional footballer who plays as a defensive midfielder.
simple: Mohamed Sissoko (born 22 January 1985) is a Malian football player.

title: Union Army
complex: During the American Civil War, the Union Army referred to the United States Army, the land force that fought to preserve the Union of the collective states. <s> Also known as the Federal Army, it proved essential to the preservation of the United States as a working, viable republic.
simple: The Union Army was the name of the army that fought for the Union during the American Civil War.

title: Matthias Herget
complex: Matthias Herget (born 14 November 1955) is a retired German footballer who played as a sweeper.
simple: Matthias Herget (born 14 November, 1955) is a former German football player.

title: Bob Bennett (politician)
complex: Robert Foster "Bob" Bennett (September 18, 1933 – May 4, 2016) was an American politician and businessman. <s> He was a United States Senator from Utah as a member of the Republican Party. <s> Bennett held chairmanships and senior positions on a number of key Senate committees, including the Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee; Appropriations Committee; Rules and Administration Committee; Energy and Natural Resources Committee; and Joint Economic Committee. <s> Bennett was a popular and reliably conservative senator for most of his tenure, earning high ratings from conservative activist groups such as the National Rifle Association, U.S. Chamber of Commerce, and American Conservative Union. <s> However, in 2010 Bennett became one of the most prominent targets of the Tea Party Movement, which criticized his support of the Bush Administration's bank bailout and argued that Bennett was insufficiently conservative. <s> Despite an enthusiastic endorsement from Mitt Romney, Bennett was denied a place on the primary ballot by the 2010 Utah State Republican Convention, placing third behind two Tea-Party-backed candidates. <s> Bennett died on May 4, 2016, aged 82, at his home in Arlington, Virginia after suffering from pancreatic cancer and a stroke.
simple: Robert Foster "Bob" Bennett (September 18, 1933 – May 4, 2016) was an American politician. <s> He is the former United States Senator from Utah serving from January 3, 1993 through January 3, 2011. <s> He was a member of the Republican Party. <s> Bennett held chairmanships and senior positions on a number of key Senate committees, including the Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee, Appropriations Committee, Rules and Administration Committee, Energy and Natural Resources Committee, and Joint Economic Committee. <s> Bennett was a popular conservative senator for most of his tenure, earning high ratings from conservative activist groups such as the National Rifle Association, U.S. Chamber of Commerce, and American Conservative Union. <s> However, in 2010 Bennett became one of the most prominent targets of the Tea Party Movement, which criticized his support of George W. Bush. <s> Bennett died on May 4, 2016 at his home Arlington, Virginia after suffering from pancreatic cancer and a stroke. <s> He was 82 years old.

title: Tokyo Verdy
complex: Tokyo Verdy (東京ヴェルディ , Tōkyō Verudi ) is a Japanese professional football club, based in Tokyo, Japan, that plays in J2 League.
simple: Tokyo Verdy (東京ヴェルディ, Tōkyō Verudi) is a Japanese professional football club in Tokyo.

title: Chromium(III) chloride
complex: The hydrated chlorides are prepared by treatment of chromate with hydrochloric acid and methanol. <s> In laboratory the hydrates are usually prepared by dissolving the chromium metal or chromium(III) oxide in hydrochloric acid.
simple: It can be formed by dissolving chromium in hydrochloric acid or by dissolving chromium(III) oxide in hydrochloric acid.

title: Sofia Rotaru
complex: Sofiya Mykhaylivna Yevdokymenko-Rotaru (born 7 August 1947), known as Sofia Rotaru ( ] ; ; Romanian: "Sofia Rotaru"), is a former Soviet and Ukrainian pop singer.
simple: Sofia Mihailovna Evdokimenko-Rotaru (born in Marshintsy, Novoselitskiy Rayon, Chernivtsi Oblast, Ukraine on August 7, 1947), simply known as Sofia Rotaru, is a popular Russian, Ukrainian, Moldavian and formerly Soviet singer, actress and producer.

title: Bobby Freeman
complex: Robert Thomas "Bobby" Freeman (June 13, 1940 – January 23, 2017) was an African-American rock, soul and R&B singer, songwriter and record producer from San Francisco, best known for his two Top Ten hits, the first in 1958 on Josie Records called "Do You Want to Dance" and the second in 1964 for Autumn Records, "C'mon and Swim". <s> Freeman was born in the San Francisco Bay Area and spent much of his youth in San Francisco, California. <s> He attended Mission High School. <s> He started singing in a doo-wop group, the Romancers, in his early teens, and first recorded with them for Dootone Records in 1956. <s> Their recordings included "House Cat", included on several later rock and roll compilations. <s> However, the group soon fell apart, and Freeman started a new group, the Vocaleers (not to be confused with an earlier group of the same name who recorded "Is It a Dream"). <s> Freeman died of natural causes on January 23, 2017, aged 76.
simple: Robert Thomas "Bobby" Freeman (June 13, 1940 – January 28, 2017) was an African-American soul and R&B singer-songwriter and record producer. <s> He was best known for his two Top Ten hits, the first in 1958 on Josie Records called "Do You Want to Dance" and the second in 1964 for Autumn Records, "C'mon and Swim". <s> Freeman was born in Alameda County, California. <s> He was raised in San Francisco, California. <s> He studied at Mission High School. <s> Freeman died in San Francisco, California on January 28, 2017, aged 76.

title: Nevada Test Site
complex: The Nevada National Security Site (N2S2 or NNSS), previously the Nevada Test Site (NTS), is a United States Department of Energy reservation located in southeastern Nye County, Nevada, about 65 miles (105 km) northwest of the city of Las Vegas. <s> Formerly known as the Nevada Proving Grounds, the site was established on January 11, 1951 for the testing of nuclear devices, covering approximately 1,360 square miles (3,500 km) of desert and mountainous terrain. <s> Nuclear weapons testing at the Nevada Test Site began with a 1-kiloton-of-TNT (4.2 TJ) bomb dropped on Frenchman Flat on January 27, 1951. <s> Many of the iconic images of the nuclear era come from the NTS. <s> NNSS is operated by Mission Support and Test Services, LLC. <s> When underground explosions ended in 1992, the Department of Energy estimated that more than 300 MCi of radioactivity remained in the environment at that time, making the site one of the most radioactively contaminated locations in the United States. <s> In the most seriously affected zones, the concentration of radioactivity in groundwater reaches millions of picocuries per liter.
simple: It is in Nye County, Nevada, about 65 miles (105 km) northwest of Las Vegas. <s> The site was begun on January 11, 1951. <s> It covers an area of 1,350 square miles (3,500 km2) of desert and mountain lands. <s> Nuclear testing at the Nevada Test Site began with a one-kiloton (4 terajoule) bomb. <s> This bomb was dropped on Frenchman Flat on January 27, 1951. <s> Many of the famous photos of the nuclear age were taken at the Nevada Test Site. <s> When testing ended in 1992, the Energy Department said that more than 300 million curies of radiation remained, making the site one of the most radioactively contaminated places in the United States.

title: Kow Swamp Archaeological Site
complex: The Kow Swamp archaeological site comprises a series of late Pleistocene burials within the lunette of the eastern rim of a former lake known as Kow Swamp. <s> The site is located 10 km south-east of Cohuna in the central Murray River valley, in northern Victoria, at . <s> The site is significant for archaeological excavations by Alan Thorne between 1968 and 1972 which recovered the partial skeletal remains of more than 22 individuals. <s> The name of Kow Swamp is derived from an Aboriginal word in the Yorta Yorta language, "(Ghow)", which refers to the white gypsum soil found in the area. <s> Kow Swamp is now a permanent water body, due to its use for irrigation storage, 15 kilometres in circumference, with an average depth of 3 metres. <s> Originally a low lying swamp, it was filled when the Murray River is in flood or running at high levels, while Bendigo creek provides a smaller amount of water. <s> There is evidence of recent Aboriginal occupation of the area from canoe trees and middens, while early settlers' records describe an Aboriginal ceremonial site on the north side of the swamp. <s> The most notable evidence was the discovery in 1925, on the west side of the swamp, of the Cohuna Cranium by a local earthmoving contractor. <s> The editor of the local newspaper "Cohuna Farmers Weekly" notified authorities and the significance of the discovery was realised. <s> In the 1960s, Alan Thorne also identified archaic bone from the collection at the Museum of Victoria, and traced the find spot to Kow Swamp. <s> Archaeological excavations were undertaken between 1968 and 1972 by Thorne for the Australian National University in Canberra. <s> Further remains were found around the swamp by an interested local resident, Gordon Spark. <s> By 1972 the remains of at least forty individuals had been excavated and studied. <s> These discoveries helped establish the diversity of Aboriginal genetic history and have been interpreted as representing different waves of immigrants to Australia before European discovery. <s> Radiocarbon dates returned a wide range of ages for the burials, with 13,000 ± 280 (ANU1236) from shell in the grave of KS5 and 10,070 ± 250 (ANU-403b), from bone apatite from KS10 respectively. <s> The youngest date was approximately 6500 BP for KS1. <s> Optically stimulated luminescence (OSL) dating was undertaken of the Kow Swamp burial site in 2003 (close to KS 9, the only burial excavated in situ), which suggested that the cemetery was in use between 22 and 19 ka, rather than 15 – 9 ka. <s> Some question the OSL dates due to the difficulty of ensuring that the dated sand is contemporary with the actual burials. <s> However, the OSL dates from the burial units directly contradict the C14 dates, which were only ever minimum ages because of contamination by younger carbon. <s> The initial descriptions of the crania from Kow Swamp identified "receding frontal squama, massive supraorbital regions and a supraglabella fossae..." which were considered to be "preserving an almost unmodified eastern erectus form" displaying a ".. <s> complex of archaic characteristics not seen in recent Aboriginal crania...". <s> The features were considered to indicate "the survival of "Homo erectus" features in Australia until as recently as 10,000 years ago". <s> However, Donald Brothwell disputed this interpretation suggesting the vault size and shape at Kow Swamp had been influenced by artificial cranial deformation, particularly in Kow Swamp 5. <s> The varying morphological and metrical comparisons of the burials have distinguished them from modern Aboriginal crania and also a more gracile group of Pleistocene remains found at Lake Mungo and Keilor. <s> These differences have been used to postulate separate arrivals of distinct groups of people. <s> However, more recent comparison does not support Thorne's dual Pleistocene population model. <s> Following a campaign by Aboriginal community groups to have human remains repatriated from Australian and overseas museum collections, the Kow Swamp skeletons were returned to the area and re-interred. <s> Casts of some of the Kow Swamp crania and mandibles are held by the Archaeology and Human Sciences department at the Australian National University, with some casts (including casts of KS1 and 5) being sent to the London Natural History Museum and other institutions. <s> Despite extensive reconstruction, the Kow Swamp material was extremely fragmentary, with only two of the crania, KS1 and 5, being relatively complete.
simple: The Kow Swamp archaeological site is on the eastern side of Kow Swamp in northern Victoria. <s> A number of Pleistocene burials have been found in a sand dune, known as a lunette. <s> Archaeologist Alan Thorne dug up the skeletons of more than 22 people between 1968 and 1972. <s> Kow Swamp is named for an Aboriginal word, "Ghow", from the Yorta Yorta language. <s> It means white gypsum soil which is found in the area. <s> Kow Swamp is now a lake used to store irrigation water. <s> It is 15 kilometres in circumference and about 3 metres deep. <s> It was once a low lying swamp which only filled when the Murray River was in flood or running at high levels. <s> Early European settlers described an Aboriginal ceremonial site on the north side of the swamp. <s> In 1925 part of a skull was found on the west side of the swamp during digging works. <s> The editor of the local newspaper "Cohuna Farmers Weekly" notified authorities and the importance of the discovery was realised. <s> In the 1960s, Alan Thorne also found an ancient bone in the collection at the Museum of Victoria, and traced the find spot to Kow Swamp. <s> Archaeological excavations took place between 1968 and 1972 by Thorne for the Australian National University in Canberra. <s> Further remains were found around the swamp by a local person, Gordon Spark. <s> By 1972 the remains of at least forty individuals had been excavated and studied. <s> These discoveries helped prove the wide range of Aboriginal genetic history. <s> They have been used to show that there were different waves of immigrants to Australia before European discovery. <s> Radiocarbon dating has shown that most of the burials took place between 13,000 and 10,000 years ago. <s> The youngest burial 6500 was about 6,500 years old. <s> Optically stimulated luminesence (OSL) dating in 2003 showed the burials were between 22,000 and 19,000 years old. <s> However, these dates have been questioned due to the difficulty of making sure the dated sand is the same age as the actual burials. <s> Thorne believed that it showed "the survival of "Homo erectus" features in Australia until as recently as 10,000 years ago". <s> However, Donald Brothwell disagreed and said size and shape of the skulls at Kow Swamp had been caused by artificial cranial deformation. <s> They are also different to Pleistocene remains found at Lake Mungo and Keilor. <s> These differences have been used to suggest that different people came to Australia at different times in the past. <s> However, more recent studies do not support this theory. <s> Aboriginal community groups have asked for the human remains from Kow Swamp be returned from Australian and overseas museum collections. <s> The Kow Swamp skeletons were returned to the area and reburied. <s> Casts of some of the Kow Swamp skulls are held by the Archaeology and Human Sciences department at the Australian National University. <s> Some casts are also at London Natural History Museum and other institutions.

title: Labour and Co-operative
complex: Labour and Co-operative Party (often abbreviated Labour Co-op; ) is a description used by candidates in United Kingdom elections who stand on behalf of both the Labour Party and the Co-operative Party.
simple: Labour Co-operative or Labour and Co-operative is the name used in the United Kingdom to describe politicians who are elected as members of the Co-operative Party.

title: Ljusdal
complex: Ljusdal (] ) is a locality and the seat of Ljusdal Municipality, Gävleborg County, Sweden with 6,230 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Ljusdal is a locality in the county of Gävleborg in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Ljusdal Municipality.

title: Liqueur
complex: A liqueur is an alcoholic drink composed of distilled spirits and additional flavorings such as sugar, fruits, herbs, and spices. <s> Often served with or after dessert, they are typically heavily sweetened and un-aged beyond a resting period during production, when necessary, for their flavors to mingle. <s> Liqueurs are historical descendants of herbal medicines. <s> They were made in Italy as early as the 13th century, often prepared by monks (for example, Chartreuse). <s> Today they are produced the world over, commonly served straight, over ice, with coffee, in cocktails, and used in cooking. <s> The French word "liqueur" is derived from the Latin "liquifacere", which means "to dissolve". <s> In some parts of the United States and Canada, liqueurs may be referred to as cordials, or schnapps. <s> This can cause confusion as in the United Kingdom a cordial would refer to a non-alcoholic concentrated fruit syrup, typically diluted to taste and consumed as a non-carbonated soft drink. <s> Schnapps, on the other hand, can refer to any distilled beverage in Germany and aquavit in Scandinavian countries. <s> In the United States and Canada, where spirits are often called "liquor" , there is often confusion discerning between liqueurs and liquors, due to the many different types of flavored spirits that are available today (e.g., flavored vodka). <s> Liqueurs generally contain a lower alcohol content (15–30% ABV) than spirits and it has sweetener mixed, while some can have an ABV as high as 55%.
simple: A liqueur is a sweet-tasting alcoholic drink. <s> It is often flavored with fruits, herbs, spices, flowers, seeds, roots, plants, barks, and sometimes cream. <s> They are often served with dessert or as a dessert. <s> Liqueurs were made in Italy as early as the 13th century, and were used during signings of treaties during the Middle Ages. <s> They are commonly drank by themselves, poured over ice, with coffee, or mixed with cream or other mixers to create cocktails. <s> The word "liqueur" comes from the Latin word "liquifacere" which means "to dissolve." <s> In some parts of the world, liqueurs are sometimes called cordials. <s> Most liqueurs have 15 to 30% alcohol content but may have an alcohol content as high as 55%.

title: Rick Hendrick
complex: Joseph Riddick "Rick" Hendrick III (born July 12, 1949) is the current owner of the American NASCAR team, Hendrick Motorsports, and co owner of JR Motorsports, and founder of the Hendrick Automotive Group and Hendrick Marrow Program. <s> He attended Park View High School in South Hill, Virginia, and began his career in auto racing at age 14.
simple: Joseph Riddick Hendrick III (born July 12, 1949) is the owner of the NASCAR race team Hendrick Motorsports.

title: Anti-capitalism
complex: Anti-capitalism encompasses a wide variety of movements, ideas and attitudes that oppose capitalism. <s> Anti-capitalists, in the strict sense of the word, are those who wish to replace capitalism with another type of economic system.
simple: Anti-capitalism describes a wide variety of movements, ideas, and attitudes which oppose capitalism, toward social equality or environmentalism. <s> Anti-capitalists, in the strict sense of the word, are those who wish to completely replace capitalism with another system; however, there are also ideas which can be characterized as "partially" anti-capitalist in the sense that they only wish to replace or abolish certain aspects of capitalism rather than the entire system.

title: New Place
complex: New Place (grid reference ) was William Shakespeare's final place of residence in Stratford-upon-Avon. <s> He died there in 1616.
simple: New Place is a site in Stratford-upon-Avon, Warwickshire, England where a house once stood belonging to William Shakespeare.

title: Koji Miyata
complex: Koji Miyata (宮田 孝治 , Miyata Koji , born January 15, 1923) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Koji Miyata (宮田 孝治, Miyata Koji, born January 15, 1923) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Études (Chopin)
complex: The Études by Frédéric Chopin are three sets of études (solo studies) for the piano published during the 1830s. <s> There are twenty-seven compositions overall, comprising two separate collections of twelve, numbered Op. 10 and Op. 25, and a set of three without opus number. <s> Chopin's Études formed the foundation for what was then a revolutionary playing style for the piano. <s> They are some of the most challenging and evocative pieces of all the works in concert piano repertoire. <s> Because of this, the music remains popular and often performed in both concert and private stages. <s> Some are so popular they have been given nicknames; arguably the most popular of all is Op. 10, No. 3, sometimes identified by the names ""Tristesse"" ("Sadness") or "Farewell" (""L'Adieu""), as well as the "Revolutionary Étude" (Op. 10, No. 12). <s> No nicknames are of Chopin's original creation. <s> All twenty-seven études were published during Chopin's lifetime; Op. 10, the first group of twelve, were composed between 1829 and 1832, and were published in 1833, in France, Germany, and England. <s> The twelve études of Op. 25 were composed at various times between 1832 and 1836, and were published in the same countries in 1837. <s> The final three, part of a series called compiled by Ignaz Moscheles and François-Joseph Fétis, were composed in 1839, without an assigned opus number. <s> They appeared in Germany and France in November 1840, and England in January 1841. <s> Accompanying copies of these important early editions, there are usually several manuscripts of a single étude in Chopin's own hand, and additional copies made by his close friend, Jules Fontana, along with editions of Karol Mikuli, Chopin's student. <s> The first études of the Opus 10 set were written when Chopin was still in his teens. <s> They rank alongside the early works of Felix Mendelssohn as rare examples of extremely youthful compositions that are regarded as both innovative and worthy of inclusion in the standard canon. <s> Chopin's études elevated the musical form from purely utilitarian exercises to great artistic masterpieces.
simple: The Études by Polish composer Frédéric Chopin are three sets of études for piano. <s> Chopin's "Études" are some of the hardest pieces of all the works in concert piano repertoire. <s> Because of this, the music remain famous and are often played at concerts. <s> Some of them have been given nicknames (but not by Chopin himself) - for example, the last "Étude" from Op. 10 has been called the "Revolutionary" because it was inspired by the November 1830 Uprising, when the Poles were defeated by the Russian Empire. <s> All twenty-seven "Études" were published during Chopin's lifetime; Opus 10, the first group of twelve were written between 1829 and 1832, and were published in 1833, in France, Germany, and England. <s> The twelve "Études" of Opus 25 were composed at various times between 1832 and 1836, and were published in the same countries in 1837. <s> The final three, part of a series called "Méthode des méthodes de piano" compiled by Moscheles and Fétis, were composed in 1839 but with no opus number. <s> The first "Études" of the Opus 10 set were written when Chopin was still in his teens. <s> Chopin's "Études" elevated the musical form from purely utilitarian exercises to great artistic masterpieces.

title: Walgreens
complex: Walgreen Company or simply Walgreens is an American company that operates as the second-largest pharmacy store chain in the United States behind CVS Health. <s> It specializes in filling prescriptions, health and wellness products, health information, and photo services. <s> As of August 31, 2018, the company operated 9,560 stores in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands. <s> It was founded in Chicago, Illinois, in 1901. <s> The Walgreens headquarters office is in the Chicago suburb of Deerfield, Illinois. <s> Walgreens has its corporate headquarters in Deerfield, Illinois. <s> As of 2009, Walgreens employed 5,200 people at its headquarters. <s> In the 1980s Walgreens owned and operated a chain of casual family restaurants/pancake houses called Wag's, an attempt to compete with Woolworth's lunch counters. <s> The Wag's restaurants were very similar in concept to Denny's, IHOP, and Golden Bear. <s> At the highpoint, it had over 100 locations. <s> Walgreens sold most of these to Marriott Corp. in 1988 and by 1991, the chain was out of business.
simple: Walgreens is a pharmacy chain in the United States. <s> It was founded in 1901 in Chicago. <s> Its headquarters are in Deerfield, Illinois. <s> In the 1980s, Walgreens owned and operated a chain of casual family restaurants/pancake houses called Wag's. <s> It was very similar to Denny's, IHOP and Golden Bear. <s> In 1988, Walgreens sold most of Wag's to Marriott Corporation and by 1991 the chain was out of business.

title: Microsoft FrontPage
complex: Microsoft FrontPage (full name Microsoft Office FrontPage) is a discontinued WYSIWYG HTML editor and website administration tool from Microsoft for the Microsoft Windows line of operating systems. <s> It was branded as part of the Microsoft Office suite from 1997 to 2003. <s> Microsoft FrontPage has since been replaced by Microsoft Expression Web and SharePoint Designer, which were first released in December 2006 alongside Microsoft Office 2007, but these two products were also discontinued in favor of a web-based version of SharePoint Designer, as those three HTML editors were desktop applications. <s> As a "WYSIWYG" (What You See Is What You Get) editor, FrontPage is designed to hide the details of pages' HTML code from the user, making it possible for novices to create web pages and web sites easily.
simple: Microsoft FrontPage (Full name: Microsoft Office FrontPage) is a program made by Microsoft to help people make webpages and full websites. <s> It was one of Microsoft Office programs until 2003. <s> It was discontinued in 2006, being replaced by Microsoft Expression Web and Microsoft Office SharePoint Designer. <s> FrontPage is a WYSIWYG, "What You See Is What You Get", Web Editor.

title: Pentti Lund
complex: Pentti Alexander Lund (December 6, 1925 – April 16, 2013) was a Finnish Canadian professional ice hockey right winger who played for the Boston Bruins and New York Rangers in the National Hockey League. <s> Lund was often credited as being the first Finnish player in the National Hockey League. <s> (Albert Pudas, however, played 4 games with the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1926-1927). <s> Lund moved to Canada from Finland at the age of six. <s> He began his junior career with the local Port Arthur teams in the Thunder Bay Junior A Hockey League from 1942 to 1945.
simple: Pentti Alexander Lund (born December 6, 1925 – April 16, 2013) was a Finnish-Canadian professional ice hockey right winger who played for the Boston Bruins and New York Rangers in the National Hockey League. <s> Lund is often said to have been the first Finnish player in the National Hockey League. <s> (Albert Pudas, however, played 4 games with the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1926-1927). <s> Lund moved to Canada from Finland at the age of six.

title: Acton, London
complex: Acton is an area of west London, England, within the London Borough of Ealing. <s> It is 6.1 mi west of Charing Cross.
simple: Acton is a district of west London. <s> It is in the London Borough of Ealing.

title: Diefmatten
complex: Diefmatten is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France. <s> It is about 15 km west of Mulhouse.
simple: Diefmatten is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department of eastern France. <s> It is about 15 km west of Mulhouse.

title: The Heat (film)
complex: The Heat is a 2013 American buddy cop action comedy film directed by Paul Feig and written by Katie Dippold. <s> It stars Sandra Bullock, Melissa McCarthy, Demián Bichir, Marlon Wayans, Michael Rapaport, and Jane Curtin.
simple: The Heat is a 2013 police comedy which stars Sandra Bullock and Melissa McCarthy.

title: Kendall Jenner
complex: Kendall Nicole Jenner (born November 3, 1995) is an American model and media personality. <s> Jenner first appeared in the E! reality television show "Keeping Up with the Kardashians", and is one of the pr "the Instagirl era", where models are chosen for their online presence and social media following. <s> Jenner was born in Los Angeles, California, to retired Olympic decathlete champion Caitlyn Jenner and television personality Kris Jenner. <s> Jenner's middle name was a tribute to her mother's best friend Nicole Brown Simpson, who died just before Jenner was conceived.
simple: Kendall Nicole Jenner (born November 3, 1995) is an American model, television personality and socialite. <s> She is on the reality program "Keeping Up with the Kardashians". <s> She is the daughter of Caitlyn Jenner and Kris Jenner. <s> She was born in Los Angeles, California.

title: Squat (exercise)
complex: A squat is a strength exercise in which the trainee lowers their hips from a standing position and then stands back up. <s> During the descent of a squat, the hip and knee joints flex while the ankle joint dorsiflexes; conversely the hip and knee joints extend and the ankle joint plantarflexes when standing up. <s> Although the squat has long been a basic element of weight training, it has not been without controversy over its safety. <s> Some trainers allege that squats are associated with injuries to the lumbar spine and knees. <s> Others, however, continue to advocate the squat as one of the best exercises for building muscle and strength. <s> Some coaches maintain that incomplete squats (those terminating above parallel) are both less effective and more likely to cause injury than a full squat (terminating with hips at or below knee level).
simple: In powerlifting and bodybuilding, as well as in other sports, squat is an exercise that strengthens the muscles of the thighs, hips and buttocks, as well as the bones, ligaments and insertion of the tendons throughout the lower body. <s> Although the squat is a basic element of weight training, it has been the subject of considerable controversy in recent years. <s> Some trainers allege that squats are associated with injuries to the lumbar spine and knees. <s> As a result, many trainers suggest that the standard barbell squat be modified in various ways. <s> Others, however, reject all suggestions that the exercise be abandoned, continuing to advocate the squat.

title: Otto Arosemena
complex: Otto Arosemena Gómez (19 July 1925 – 20 April 1984) was President of Ecuador from 16 November 1966 to 1 September 1968. <s> Arosemena was born in Guayaquil to Luis Alberto Arosemena Tola and Mercedes Gómez Santistevan. <s> He came from a well-known Guayaquil family; his cousin and his cousin's father had both previously served as president. <s> He went to elementary school at San José de los Hermanos Cristianos School and to high school at Salesiano Cristóbal Colón High School and Vicente Rocafuerte High School in Guayaquil. <s> He graduated from the University of Guayaquil in 1955 with a degree in law. <s> He was already involved in public life during his education: in 1951, he was named a member of the Electoral Tribunal of Guayas. <s> Later, he became president of the tribunal. <s> Beginning in 1954, his political ascendancy was vertiginous. <s> In 1954, he was elected Deputy for Guayas Province in the National Congress; he was reelected in 1956. <s> In 1957 he was elected president of the Chamber of Deputies, in 1960 he was elected Senator and member of the Monetary Board on behalf of Congress, and in 1961 he was named President of the Monetary Board and Vice President of the Senate. <s> He fought against the military junta that in July 1963 had overthrown his cousin, President Carlos Julio Arosemena Monroy. <s> In 1965, when the country was facing one of its worst political, social, and economic crises—a result of dictatorial misrule—he founded a new political party in Quito called the Democratic Institutionalist Coalition ("Coalición Institucionalista Demócrata", CID). <s> One year later, he was elected Deputy of the Constituent Assembly held by "President" Yerovi Indaburu. <s> The Constituent Assembly elected Arosemena President of Ecuador on 16 November 1966. <s> His government, though short, greatly increased Ecuador's development and ensured the consolidation of democracy. <s> In accordance with the law, he called presidential elections, and Velasco Ibarra won for his fifth and final time. <s> Arosemena finished his term on 31 August 1968. <s> Arosemena's political adversaries later attacked his policies, particularly with respect to oil policy. <s> He responded by writing the book "Infamy and Truth" ("Infamia y verdad"), in which he addresses his administration's oil policy.
simple: Otto Arosemena Gómez (19 July 1925 – 20 April 1984) was President of Ecuador, November 16, 1966 to September 1, 1968. <s> Arosemena was born on 19 July 1925 in Guayaquil, Ecuador. <s> He studied at University of Guayaquil. <s> In 1965, when the country was facing one of its worst political, social, and economic crises—a result of dictatorial misrule—he founded a new political party in Quito called the Democratic Institutionalist Coalition (Coalición Institucionalista Demócrata, CID). <s> One year later, he was elected Deputy of the Constituent Assembly held by "President" Yerovi Indaburu. <s> The Constituent Assembly elected Arosemena President of Ecuador on November 16, 1966. <s> His government, though short, greatly increased Ecuador's development and ensured the consolidation of democracy. <s> In accordance with the law, he called presidential elections, and Velasco Ibarra won for his fifth and final time. <s> Arosemena finished his term on August 31, 1968. <s> Arosemena's political adversaries later attacked his policies, particularly with respect to oil policy. <s> He responded by writing the book Infamy and Truth (Infamia y verdad), in which he addresses his administration's oil policy.

title: Orphan
complex: An orphan (from the ) is someone whose parents have died, are unknown, or have permanently abandoned them. <s> In common usage, only a child who has lost both parents due to death is called an orphan.
simple: An orphan is a child who has lost either or both parents.

title: Trondheim Region
complex: The Trondheim Region is a statistical metropolitan region in the county of Trøndelag in Norway. <s> It is centered in the city of Trondheim.
simple: The Trondheim Region is a statistical metropolitan area in the counties of Sør-Trøndelag (population: 223,363) and Nord-Trøndelag (23,388) in Norway. <s> It is centered around the city of Trondheim.

title: Painted lady
complex: The Cynthia group of colourful butterflies, commonly called painted ladies, comprises a subgenus of the genus "Vanessa" in the family Nymphalidae. <s> They are well known throughout most of the world. <s> The lifespan of a painted lady butterfly is two to four weeks. <s> The species undergoes complete metamorphosis which has recently been investigated using microtomography. <s> This butterfly is widely distributed all over the Northern hemisphere, and can be seen in all types of habitats except dense forests. <s> Painted ladies lay their eggs on many different plants, and their larvae feed on a wider variety of plants (polyphagus) than most other butterfly species. <s> Even though they are often thought of as the thistle butterfly, and a majority of their eggs are laid on thistles, the larvae feed and can be reared on a varied number of plants and plant types, in several different families.
simple: The painted lady is a butterfly in the Cynthia group of colourful butterflies. <s> The painted lady is a subgenus of the genus "Vanessa" in the family Nymphalidae. <s> They occur in most of the world. <s> The lifespan of a painted lady imago (adult) is only about 2/3 weeks. <s> Their caterpillars feed on many different plants.

title: Kungälv Municipality
complex: Kungälv Municipality ("Kungälvs kommun") is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in western Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the city of Kungälv.
simple: Kungälv Municipality is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Kungälv.

title: Willem Janszoon
complex: Willem Janszoon (] ; 1570 – c. 1630 ), sometimes abbreviated to Willem Jansz., was a Dutch navigator and colonial governor. <s> Janszoon served in the Netherlands East Indies in the periods 16031611 and 16121616, including as governor of Fort Henricus on the island of Solor.
simple: Willem Janszoon (]; 1570 – c. 1630), sometimes abbreviated to Willem Jansz., was a Dutch navigator and colonial governor.

title: One More Time (Daft Punk song)
complex: "One More Time" is a song by French electronic music duo Daft Punk, first released as a single on 30 November 2000 and later included in the 2001 album "Discovery". <s> It is a French house song featuring a vocal performance by Romanthony that is stylistically autotuned.
simple: One More Time is a popular song by music group Daft Punk.

title: Requiem shark
complex: Requiem sharks are sharks of the family Carcharhinidae in the order Carcharhiniformes. <s> They are migratory, live-bearing sharks of warm seas (sometimes of brackish or fresh water) such as the spinner shark, the blacknose shark, the blacktip shark, the grey reef shark, the blacktip reef shark, and the Oceanic whitetip shark.
simple: Carcharhinidae, also known as the requiem sharks, is a family of sharks in the order Carcharhiniformes.

title: Wegberg
complex: Wegberg is the northernmost town in the district of Heinsberg in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany. <s> Wegberg is situated between Mönchengladbach in the northeast and Erkelenz in the southeast; the town of Rheindahlen is to the east. <s> The city lies in the "Naturpark Maas-Schwalm-Nette", a nature and wildlife park hugging the border to the Netherlands. <s> Its name derives from the three rivers that define its boundaries.
simple: Wegberg is a town in the very west of Germany, in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia. <s> Wegberg is located between Mönchengladbach and Erkelenz. <s> Wegberg is in the Naturpark Maas-Schwalm-Nette, a nature and wildlife park.

title: Oscar Ruggeri
complex: Oscar Alfredo Ruggeri (born 26 January 1962) is an Argentinian former professional footballer who played as defender. <s> Nicknamed "El Cabezón" ("The Big-Headed One"), Ruggeri achieved success at the international level with the Argentina national team, being part of the teams that won the 1986 FIFA World Cup, two editions of the Copa América and the 1992 King Fahd Cup.
simple: Oscar Ruggeri (born 26 January 1962 Rosario) is a former Argentine football player.

title: Thann, Haut-Rhin
complex: Thann (] ; Alsatian: "Dànn", ] , ) is a commune in the northeastern French department of Haut-Rhin, in Grand Est. <s> It is the "sous-préfecture" of the arrondissement of Thann-Guebwiller and part of the canton of Cernay. <s> Its inhabitants are known as "Thannois". <s> Thann is situated at the foot of the Vosges mountains, at the mouth of the valley of the Thur River. <s> The Thur runs through the middle of the town. <s> Thann is 43 km from Colmar and 21 km from Mulhouse. <s> The town is also well situated for the French autoroute network such as the A35 and A36.
simple: Thann is a commune in Alsace in north-eastern France, in the Haut-Rhin department, of which it is a subprefecture. <s> The inhabitants of Thann are known, in French, as "Thannois" (women: "Thannoises"). <s> Thann is in the southwest of the Haut-Rhin department at the foot of the Vosges mountains, at the mouth of the valley of the Thur river. <s> The Thur runs through the middle of the town. <s> Thann is at 121 km from Strasbourg, the regional capital; at 42 km from Colmar, the departamental capital; and at 21 km from Mulhouse.

title: Estréelles
complex: Estréelles is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Estréelles is a commune. <s> It is found in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais region in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Metatarsal bones
complex: The metatarsal bones, or metatarsus are a group of five long bones in the foot, located between the tarsal bones of the hind- and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes. <s> Lacking individual names, the metatarsal bones are numbered from the medial side (the side of the great toe): the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal (often depicted with Roman numerals). <s> The metatarsals are analogous to the metacarpal bones of the hand. <s> The lengths of the metatarsal bones in humans are, in descending order: second, third, fourth, fifth and first. <s> The metatarsal bones are often broken by association football players. <s> These and other recent cases have been attributed to the lightweight design of modern football boots, which provide less protection to the foot. <s> In 2010 some soccer players began testing a new sock that incorporated a rubber silicone pad over the foot to provide protection to the top of the foot. <s> Stress fractures are thought to account for 16% of injuries related to sports participation, and the metatarsals are the bones most often involved.
simple: The metatarsus or metatarsal bones are a group of five long bones in the foot. <s> They are between the tarsal bones of the hind and mid-foot and the phalanges of the toes. <s> The metatarsal bones are numbered from the side of the large toe: the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal. <s> They can be numbered with Roman numerals. <s> The metatarsals are like the metacarpal bones of the hand. <s> The metatarsal bones are often broken by soccer players. <s> This may be caused by the lightweight design of modern football boots, which give less protection to the foot. <s> In 2010 some soccer players began testing a new sock that had a rubber silicon pad over the foot to protect the top of the foot.

title: Gleb Yakunin
complex: He died at the age of 78 after a long illness on 25 December 2014.
simple: He died at the age of 80 after a long illness on 25 December 2014 in Moscow, Russia.

title: Michelangelo Antonioni
complex: Michelangelo Antonioni Cavaliere di Gran Croce OMRI ( , ] ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007), was an Italian film director, screenwriter, editor, and short story author. <s> He is best known for his "trilogy on modernity and its discontents" — "L'Avventura" (1960), "La Notte" (1961), and "L'Eclisse" (1962)—as well as the English-language films "Blowup" (1966) and "The Passenger" (1975). <s> His films have been described as "enigmatic and intricate mood pieces" that rejected action and plot in favor of contemplation, image, and design. <s> According to AllMovie, he "redefined the concept of narrative cinema" and challenged traditional approaches to storytelling, realism, and drama. <s> Antonioni died aged 94 on 30 July 2007 in Rome, the same day that another renowned film director, Ingmar Bergman, also died. <s> Antonioni lay in state at City Hall in Rome where a large screen showed black-and-white footage of him among his film sets and behind-the-scenes.
simple: Michelangelo Antonioni (29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007) was an Italian movie director and screenwriter. <s> His best known movie is "Blowup" made in 1966. <s> He died at the same day as Ingmar Bergman, another famous director.

title: Puneri Pagadi
complex: The Puneri Pagadi is a distinctive style of turban, which is considered as a symbol of pride and honor in the city of Pune. <s> It was introduced two centuries ago. <s> Though it is a symbol of honour, the use of the "pagadi" has changed over the years and now it is also used on traditional days in colleges. <s> To preserve the identity of the "pagadi", there were demands from the locals to grant it a Geographical Indication (GI) status. <s> Their demand was fulfilled and the "pagadi" became an intellectual property on 4 September 2009. <s> The "pagadi" was introduced in the 19th century by Mahadev Govind Ranade, a social reformer. <s> Later, it was worn by many leaders like Lokmanya Tilak, J.S. Karandikar, D.D. Sathye, Dr. Vitthalrao Gade, Tatyasaheb Kelkar and Datto Vaman Potdar. <s> The "pagadi" became more popular in 1973 after the Marathi play, "Ghashiram Kotwal". <s> The "pagadi" is used mostly on special occasions like wedding ceremonies and traditional days in schools and colleges. <s> Youngsters wear it while performing the "gondhal" art form. <s> The "pagadi", being a symbol of honour, is also used as a souvenir. <s> It also finds usage in period films and theatres. <s> The 10-membered "Shree Puneri Pagadi Sangh" had applied before the Geographical Indication Registry to get a Geographical Indication (GI) tag for the "pagadi". <s> Great Mission Group Consultancy, which promotes intellectual property rights filed the application on behalf of them. <s> The aim was to make the "pagadi" recognizable, preserve its identity and also that of the "Puneri" culture. <s> Consequently, on 4 September 2009, the Geographical Indication status was given to the headgear and the "pagadi" became the official cultural identity of Pune. <s> Thus, the "pagadi" got the Intellectual Property Right (IPR) and selling of any turban made outside Pune, under the name of "Puneri pagadi" became illegal. <s> Along with the "Puneri pagadi", IPR has been previously issued to Indian products like Darjeeling tea, Banarasi saris, Tirupati ladoos, among others.
simple: Puneri Pagadi is a turban, a cloth worn on the head. <s> "Puneri" means "belonging to Pune" and "pagadi" means turban. <s> The "pagadi" was introduced 200 years ago by Mahadev Govind Ranade, who was a social reformer. <s> It was also later worn by leaders like Lokmanya Tilak, J.S. Karandikar, D.D. Sathye, Tatyasaheb Kelkar and Datto Vaman Potdar. <s> The "pagadi" became more famous in 1973 after a Marathi play. <s> The "pagadi" used to be worn by people to show pride but now it is also worn on special occasions. <s> The "pagadi" is used in marriages. <s> It is also used on special events in schools and colleges (commonly on traditional days). <s> It is used by actors while performing "gondhal" art form. <s> They are the ones who applied for getting a GI tag for the "pagadi". <s> Actually, Great Mission Group Consultancy submitted the application for them. <s> The aim of this was to protect the identity of the "pagadi". <s> They also wanted to protect the "Puneri" culture. <s> In 2009, it was given the status of Geographic Indication (GI) which means that the "pagadi" will be a property of only Pune. <s> The application was accepted and on 4 September 2009, the "pagadi" became an intellectual property. <s> No one else can sell any such turban under the name of "Puneri Pagadi" outside Pune.Only Brahmins used to use this pagadi in that era. <s> Before this, the GI tag was also given to Indian products like Tirupati "ladoos", Darjeeling tea, Banarasi "saris".

title: Lappajärvi
complex: Lappajärvi is a municipality in Finland in Southern Ostrobothnia region. <s> The municipality has a population of and covers an area of km2 of which km2 is water.
simple: Lappajärvi is a municipality in Finland.

title: Presbyterian Church in Canada
complex: The Presbyterian Church in Canada is a Presbyterian denomination, serving in Canada under this name since 1875. <s> The United Church of Canada claimed the right to the name from 1925 to 1939. <s> According to the Canada 2001 Census 409,830 Canadians identify themselves as Presbyterian, that is, 1.4% of the population. <s> The Canadian roots of the Presbyterian Church in Canada can be traced to both Scottish settlers and French Huguenots, and the first Presbyterian churches formed in the late 16th and early 17th centuries, following such European Protestant Reformation theologians as John Calvin and John Knox. <s> Once the largest Christian denomination in English-speaking Canada, in 1925 some 70% of its congregations joined with the Methodist Church, Canada and the Congregationalist Union to form the "United Church of Canada." <s> The terms "Continuing Presbyterians" and "Non-Concurring Presbyterians" were then used by those who did not participate in the merger, until the legal right to use the name "Presbyterian Church in Canada" was regained in 1939. <s> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that although the institutional Presbyterian Church in Canada may legally have merged with the Methodist Church, the United Church had effectively vacated the name and it remained available to the non-concurring Presbyterians.
simple: The Presbyterian Church in Canada is a Protestant Christian denomination in Canada. <s> The four denominations merged in 1875 as the Presbyterian Church in Canada. <s> Presbyterian churches in Canada were started in the late 16th century by Scottish and French Huguenots immigrants. <s> In 1925, 70% of the Presbyterian congregations merged into the United Church of Canada. <s> The Presbyterians who did not join in the union continued using the name Presbyterian Church in Canada.

title: Amparo Rivelles
complex: María Amparo Rivelles Ladrón de Guevara (11 February 1925 – 7 November 2013), better known as Amparo Rivelles, was a Spanish actress. <s> She worked in Mexican films and telenovelas. <s> She was the daughter of actor Rafael Rivelles and actress María Fernanda Ladrón de Guevara, and the half-sister of actor Carlos Larrañaga.
simple: Amparo Rivelles, (real name: María Amparo Rivelles Ladrón de Guevara) (11 February 1925 – 7 November 2013) was a Spanish actress. <s> Rivelles was born on 11 February 1925 in Madrid, Spain. <s> In the beginning of her career, she was known as Amparito Rivelles. <s> Rivelles died on 7 November 2013 in Madrid, Spain from unknown causes, aged 88. <s> She worked in Cinema of Mexico and in telenovelas.

title: Ramat Gan
complex: Ramat Gan (Hebrew: or ) is a city in the Tel Aviv District of Israel, located east of the municipality of Tel Aviv and part of the Tel Aviv metropolitan area. <s> It is home to one of the world's major diamond exchanges, and many high-tech industries. <s> Ramat Gan was established in 1921 as a moshav, a communal farming settlement. <s> In 2018 it had a population of 159,159 . <s> The mayor of Ramat Gan is Carmel Shama. <s> The mayor of Ramat Gan is Carmel Shama.
simple: Ramat Gan (Hebrew: ; ) is a city in the Tel Aviv District of Israel, located east of Tel Aviv. <s> It is home to one of the world's major diamond exchanges, and many high-tech industries. <s> Ramat Gan was established in 1921 as a moshava, a communal farming settlement, and in 2015 it had a population of 152,596. <s> The current mayor is Carmel Shama.

title: Elmdon

title: Heart arrhythmia
complex: Heart arrhythmia (also known as arrhythmia, dysrhythmia or irregular heartbeat) is a group of conditions in which the heartbeat is irregular, too fast or too slow. <s> A heart rate that is too fast – above 100 beats per minute in adults – is called tachycardia, and a heart rate that is too slow – below 60 beats per minute – is called bradycardia. <s> Many types of arrhythmia have no symptoms.
simple: Cardiac arrhythmia (commonly called irregular heartbeat) is the name for a number of conditions, where the heartbeat is not normal. <s> It may be too fast (tachycardia); too slow (bradycardia); or the heart may not beat in its regular rhythm.

title: BandNews FM
complex: BandNews FM is a Brazilian all-news radio network owned by Grupo Bandeirantes de Comunicação. <s> First broadcast in May 20, 2005, it is the first Brazilian radio network that provides non-stop news programming 24 hours a day, considering that CBN does intersperse news with talk shows.
simple: Rádio BandNews FM is a Brazilian "all news" radio network. <s> It is owned by Grupo Bandeirantes de Comunicação. <s> It first started in 20 March 2005.

title: Gilligan's Island

simple: Gilligan's Island is a 1964 American television series.

title: Dalitstan.org
complex: Dalitstan.org was a Dalit advocacy website active until mid-2006, one of 18 websites that were blocked by the Indian government following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website claimed to be run by Dalitstan, a "Human Rights Organization working for the Upliftment of Dalits, the Untouchables of India". <s> Note that -stan is a suffix for "place of" or "country", appearing in many place names throughout Central and South Asia. <s> Dalitstan would mean "place or country of the Dalits". <s> The website claimed that the Dalits were the original people of India who created the Harappan civilization, and described the Brahmins as the descendants of the Aryan invaders who enslaved them. <s> Dibyesh Anand of the University of Westminster described Dalitstan.org as a Dalit nationalist group that also acted as a forum for anti-India Christian and Muslim advocacy. <s> Dalitistan.org was among the 18 websites that were blocked in India by the Ministry of Telecommunications of the Government in July 2006, in a bid to check terror and hate messages on the Internet following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website was launched in 1999, with the domain registered by Helen Heklund, with an address in Granbury, Texas. <s> The website was taken down sometime after May 2006. <s> The domain registration lapsed, and was subsequently purchased by an unrelated party.
simple: Dalitstan.org was a Dalit advocacy website active until mid-2006. <s> It was one of 18 websites that were blocked by the Indian government following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website claimed to be run by Dalitstan, a "Human Rights Organization working for the Upliftment of Dalits, the Untouchables of India". <s> Note that -stan is a suffix for "place of" or "country", and forms part of the name of many places throughout Central and South Asia. <s> Dalitstan would mean "place or country of the Dalits". <s> The website stated that the Dalits were the original people of India who created the Harappan civilization, and described the Brahmins as the descendants of the Aryan invaders who enslaved them. <s> Dibyesh Anand of the University of Westminster described Dalitstan.org as a Dalit nationalist group that also acted as a forum for anti-India Christian and Muslim advocacy. <s> Dalitistan.org was one of 18 websites that were blocked in India by the Ministry of Telecommunications of the Government in July 2006. <s> The purpose of the block was to try to stop terror and hate messages on the Internet following the 11 July 2006 Mumbai train bombings. <s> The website was started in 1999. <s> The domain was registered by Helen Heklund, with an address in Granbury, Texas. <s> The original version of the website was last archived on May 10, 2006. <s> The domain registration lapsed (expired), and the rights to the name were then purchased by someone else.

title: Marianne Berglund
complex: Marianne Berglund (born 23 June 1963) is a Swedish former road racing cyclist. <s> On 3 September 1983 she won the women's road race during the UCI Road World Championships in Altenrhein, Switzerland. <s> She also won the Tour of Texas. <s> She rode in the 1984 Summer Olympics and the 1988 Summer Olympics. <s> In 1990, she won the first edition of Tjejtrampet.
simple: Marianne Berglund, born 23 June 1963 in Skellefteå, Sweden is a Swedish former road racing cyclinst. <s> She won the women's road race during the UCI Road World Championships in Altenrhein, Switzerland on 3 September. <s> She has also won the Tour of Texas. <s> She won the first edition of Tjejtrampet in the year of 1990.

title: Gamlingay
complex: Gamlingay is a village and civil parish in South Cambridgeshire, England, near the border with Bedfordshire, and the traditional county of Huntingdonshire. <s> It is 14 miles (22 km) from Cambridge and the population in 2011 was 4,900 people. <s> At the time of the 2001 census, Gamlingay parish had 3,535 inhabitants living in 1,410 households. <s> The ethnic group of 99% was white, with 0.4% Asian or Asian British, 0.1% black or Black British, 0.3% mixed and 0.2% other.

title: And Now for Something Completely Different
complex: And Now for Something Completely Different is a 1971 British sketch comedy film based on the television comedy series "Monty Python's Flying Circus" featuring sketches from the show's first two series. <s> The title was taken from a catchphrase used in the television show. <s> "And Now for Something Completely Different" is the Pythons' first feature film, composed of some well-known sketches from the first two series of the Flying Circus, including the "Dead Parrot" sketch, "The Lumberjack Song", "Upperclass Twits", "Hell's Grannies", the "Nudge Nudge" sketch and others.
simple: And Now for Something Completely Different is a British movie spin-off from the comedy television series "Monty Python's Flying Circus". <s> The title was used as a catchphrase in the series.

title: Trackball
complex: A trackball is a pointing device consisting of a ball held by a socket containing sensors to detect a rotation of the ball about two axes—like an upside-down mouse with an exposed protruding ball. <s> Users roll the ball to position the on-screen pointer, using their thumb, fingers, or commonly the palm of the hand while using the fingertips to press the mouse buttons. <s> Large trackballs are sometimes seen on computerized special-purpose workstations, such as the radar consoles in an air-traffic control room or sonar equipment on a ship or submarine. <s> Modern installations of such equipment may use mice instead, since most people now already know how to use one.
simple: In computing, a trackball is a pointing input device. <s> It consists of a ball held by a socket containing sensors to detect a rotation of the ball about two axes. <s> It is like an upside-down mouse with a ball that sticks out. <s> The user rolls the ball with the thumb, fingers or the palm of the hand to move a cursor. <s> Large trackballs are sometimes seen on computerized special-purpose workstations, such as the radar consoles in an air-traffic control room or sonar equipment on a ship or submarine.
