title: Brighton College
complex: Brighton College is an independent, co-educational boarding and day school for boys and girls aged 3 to 18 in Brighton, England. <s> The school has three sites: Brighton College (the senior school, ages 11 to 18); Brighton College Preparatory School (children aged 8 to 13, located next to the senior school); and the Pre-Prep School (children aged 3 to 8). <s> Founded in 1845 by William Aldwin Soames, Brighton College was the first Victorian public school to be founded in Sussex. <s> Soames originally planned for use of the Brighton Pavilion, but after refusal by Queen Victoria, built the school in the suburb of Kemptown, Brighton.
simple: Brighton College is a boarding school in Brighton, England. <s> It is for boys and girls aged between 3 and 18. <s> It was started by William Aldwin Soames in 1845.

title: Staff (music)
complex: In Western musical notation, the staff (US) or stave (UK) (plural for either: staves) is a set of five horizontal lines and four spaces that each represent a different musical pitch or in the case of a percussion staff, different percussion instruments. <s> Appropriate music symbols, depending on the intended effect, are placed on the staff according to their corresponding pitch or function. <s> Musical notes are placed by pitch, percussion notes are placed by instrument, and rests and other symbols are placed by convention. <s> The vertical position of the notehead on the staff indicates which note to play: higher-pitched notes are marked higher on the staff. <s> The notehead can be placed with its center intersecting a line ("on a line") or in between the lines touching the lines above and below ("in a space"). <s> Notes outside the range of the staff are placed on or between ledger lines—lines the width of the note they need to hold—added above or below the staff. <s> When music on two staves is joined by a brace, or is intended to be played at once by a single performer (usually a keyboard instrument or harp), a grand staff (American English) or great stave (British English) is created. <s> Typically, the upper staff uses a treble clef and the lower staff has a bass clef.
simple: A staff (or stave) is the name given to the five horizontal lines on which we can write music. <s> The higher the pitch of the note the higher it will be on the staff. <s> Musical notes can be placed either on a line (i.e. with a line going through the middle of the note head) or in a space. <s> If two or more staves are being played at the same time the staves are joined on the left by a bracket which is called a brace.

title: Family history (medicine)
complex: In medicine, a family history (FH or FHx) consists of information about disorders from which the direct blood relatives of the patient have suffered. <s> Genealogy typically includes very little of the medical history of the family, but the medical history could be considered a specific subset of the total history of a family. <s> Accurate knowledge of a patient's family history may identify a predisposition to developing certain illnesses, which can inform clinical decisions and allow effective management or even prevention of conditions. <s> Although sometimes neglected, many healthcare professionals glean information on family morbidity of particular diseases (e.g. cardiovascular diseases, autoimmune disorders, mental disorders, diabetes, cancer) to assess whether a person is at risk of developing similar problems. <s> Some medical conditions are carried only by the female line such as X-linked conditions and some Mitochondrial diseases. <s> Tracing female ancestors can be difficult in societies that change the woman's family name when she marries.
simple: In medicine, family history means information on medical disorders the direct blood relatives of a patient may have had. <s> Many healthcare professionals look at the information on family medical problems, such as autism, diabetes, mental illness, autoimmune diseases, cancer. <s> Many medical conditions are carried only by the female line, including X-linked conditions. <s> Others are carried by the male line, including Y-linked conditions.

title: Procompsognathus
complex: Procompsognathus is an extinct genus of coelophysid theropod dinosaur that lived approximately 210 million years ago during the later part of the Triassic Period, in what is now Germany. <s> "Procompsognathus" was a small-sized, lightly built, ground-dwelling, bipedal carnivore, that could grow up to 1 m (3.3 ft) long. <s> "Procompsognathus" may have been about 1 m long, though Fraas in 1913 estimated a length of 75 cm . <s> In 2010 Gregory S. Paul gave an estimate of 1 kg for the weight with a length of 1.1 m . <s> A biped, "Procompsognathus" had long hind legs, short arms, large clawed hands, a long slender snout with many small teeth, and a stiff tail. <s> The femur discovered for the type specimen of this genus measures 93mm and the tibia, 112mm. <s> The tibia is approximately 20% longer than the femur in "Procompsognathus", an adaptation which has been strongly correlated with the development of cursorial habits in dinosaurs, suggesting that they were good runners. <s> "Procompsognathus" lived in a relatively dry, inland environment and may have eaten insects, lizards and other small prey. <s> Contemporaries of "Prompsognathus" included the coelophysoids "Halticosaurus" and "Dolichosuchus", as well as the Sauropodomorphs "Plateosaurus gracilis" and "Efraasia minor".
simple: This meat-eater lived during the late Triassic period, about 210 million years ago (mya). <s> Procompsognathus was a small, speedy theropod dinosaur. <s> "Procompsognathus" may have been about one meter long (3.3 ft), <s> A biped, "Procompsognathus" had long hind legs, short arms, large clawed hands, a long slender snout with many small teeth, and a stiff tail. <s> The tibia is approximately 20% longer than the femur in "Procompsognathus". <s> This suggests that they were good runners. <s> It probably ate insects and lizards in a relatively dry, inland environment.

title: Japanese serow
complex: The Japanese serow (, lit. <s> "coarse pelt deer" ) : ("Capricornis crispus") is a Japanese goat-antelope, an even-toed ungulate mammal. <s> It is found in dense woodland in Japan, primarily in northern and central Honshu. <s> The animal is seen as a national symbol of Japan and is subject to protection in conservation areas. <s> Adult Japanese serow stand about 32 in tall and weigh 30 – . <s> They are black to whitish, and colouring lightens in summer. <s> The fur is very bushy, especially the tail. <s> Both sexes have short, backwards-curving horns and are difficult to distinguish by sight. <s> Japanese serow are found in dense mountain forests where they eat leaves, shoots, and acorns. <s> They are diurnal and feed in early mornings and late afternoons. <s> Serows are solitary, or gather in couples or small family groups. <s> The animal marks its territory with sweet-and-sour-smelling preorbital gland secretions, and males and females have separate territories that may overlap. <s> "Capricornis crispus" is socially monogamous. <s> Females reach sexual maturity at 30 months.
simple: The Japanese serow is a mammal that lives in Japan. <s> They live in dense woodland in Japan, primarily in northern and central Honshu and are found in dense mountain forests.They live in open grassland and forests at an elevation of about 1,000 metres (3,300 ft), and uses caves to rest in. <s> The animal is seen as a national symbol of Japan and protected in conservation areas. <s> Adult Japanese serow stand about 81 centimetres (32 in) tall and weigh 30–45 kilograms (66–99 lb). <s> They are black to whitish, and colouring lightens in summer. <s> They eat leaves, shoots, and acorns. <s> Capricornis crispus is socially monogamous.

title: Cypress Hill
complex: Cypress Hill is an American hip hop group from South Gate, California. <s> Cypress Hill was the first Latino American hip hop recording group to have a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame and platinum and multi-platinum albums, selling over 20 million albums worldwide. <s> They are considered to be among the main progenitors of West Coast rap and hip hop in the early 1990s, being critically acclaimed for their first four albums. <s> The band has also advocated for medical and recreational use of cannabis in the United States. <s> After recording a demo in 1989, Cypress Hill signed a record deal with Ruffhouse Records. <s> Their self-titled first album was released in August 1991. <s> The lead single was the double A-side "The Phuncky Feel One"/"How I Could Just Kill a Man" which received heavy airplay on urban and college radio. <s> The other two singles released from the album were "Hand on the Pump" and "Latin Lingo", the latter of which combined English and Spanish lyrics. <s> The success of these singles led to the album selling two million copies in the US alone. <s> Cypress Hill contributed the song "Shoot 'Em Up" to the soundtrack of the movie "Juice". <s> The group made their first appearance at Lollapalooza on the side stage in 1992. <s> "Black Sunday", the group's second album, debuted at number one on the "Billboard" 200 in 1993, recording the highest Soundscan for a rap group up until that time. <s> Also, with their debut still in the charts, they became the first rap group to have two albums in the top 10 of the "Billboard" 200 at the same time. <s> With "Insane in the Brain" becoming a crossover hit, the album went triple platinum in the U.S. and sold about 3.25 million copies. <s> The band headlined the Soul Assassins tour with House of Pain and Funkdoobiest as support, then performed on a college tour with Rage Against the Machine and Seven Year Bitch. <s> In 1993, Cypress Hill also had two tracks on the "Judgment Night" soundtrack, teaming up with Pearl Jam (without singer Eddie Vedder) on the track "Real Thing" and Sonic Youth on "I Love You Mary Jane". <s> The group later played at Woodstock 94, introducing new member Eric Bobo, son of Willie Bobo and formerly a percussionist with the Beastie Boys. <s> "Rolling Stone" magazine named the group as the best rap group in their music awards voted by critics and readers. <s> Cypress Hill played at Lollapalooza for two successive years, topping the bill in 1995. <s> They also appeared on the "Homerpalooza" episode of "The Simpsons". <s> Prior to Bobo joining the crew, Panchito "Ponch" Gomez sat in as a percussionist when not acting. <s> Sen Dog took a break from the band to form a Los Angeles-based rap rock band, SX-10. <s> Meanwhile, in 1996, Cypress Hill appeared on the first Smokin' Grooves tour, featuring Ziggy Marley, The Fugees, Busta Rhymes and A Tribe Called Quest. <s> The band also released a nine track EP "Unreleased and Revamped" with rare mixes. <s> In 1997, band members focused on their solo careers. <s> Muggs released "Soul Assassins: Chapter 1" featuring contributions from Dr. Dre, KRS-One, Wyclef Jean and Mobb Deep. <s> B-Real appeared with Busta Rhymes, Coolio, LL Cool J and Method Man on "Hit Em High" from the multi-platinum "Space Jam Soundtrack". <s> He also appeared with RBX, Nas and KRS-One on "East Coast Killer, West Coast Killer" from Dr. Dre's "Dr. Dre Presents the Aftermath" album, and contributed to an album entitled "The Psycho Realm" with the band of the same name. <s> Though the focus that year was not on group efforts, the band played Smokin' Grooves with George Clinton and Erykah Badu. <s> Cypress Hill released "IV" in 1998 which went gold in the US, on the backs of hit singles "Tequila Sunrise" and "Dr. Greenthumb". <s> Sen Dog also released the "Get Wood" sampler as part of SX-10 on the label Flip. <s> In 1999, Cypress Hill helped with the PC crime video game "". <s> Three of the band's songs from the 1998 "IV" album were in the game ("16 Men Till There's No Men Left", "Checkmate" and "Lightning Strikes"). <s> B-Real also did voice work for some of the game's characters. <s> Also in 1999, the band released a greatest-hits album in Spanish, "Los grandes éxitos en español". <s> In 2000, Cypress Hill then fused genres with their fifth album, "Skull & Bones", which was a two-disc album. <s> The first disc, "Skull" was composed of rap tracks while "Bones" explored further the group's forays into rock. <s> The album reached the Top 5 on the Billboard 200 and number 3 in Canada. <s> The first single was "Rock Superstar" for rock radio and "Rap Superstar" for urban radio. <s> Following the release of the album, Cypress Hill (along with MxPx) landed a slot opening for The Offspring on the Conspiracy of One tour. <s> The band also released "Live at the Fillmore", a concert disc recorded at the Fillmore (in San Francisco) in 2000. <s> Cypress Hill continued their experimentation with rock on the "Stoned Raiders" album in 2001.

title: Defoliant
complex: A defoliant is any herbicidal chemical sprayed or dusted on plants to cause their leaves to fall off. <s> Defoliants are widely used for the selective removal of weeds in managing croplands and lawns.
simple: Defoliants are a type of chemical that destroys plants like trees, bushes and grass .

title: James Turrell
complex: James Turrell (born May 6, 1943) is an American artist primarily concerned with Light and Space. <s> Turrell was a MacArthur Fellow in 1984. <s> Turrell is best known for his work in progress, "Roden Crater", a natural cinder cone crater located outside Flagstaff, Arizona, that he is turning into a massive naked-eye observatory. <s> James Turrell was born in Los Angeles, California. <s> His father, Archibald Milton Turrell, was an aeronautical engineer and educator. <s> His mother, Margaret Hodges Turrell, trained as a medical doctor and later worked in the Peace Corps. <s> His parents were Quakers. <s> Turrell obtained a pilot's license when he was 16 years old. <s> Later, registered as a conscientious objector during the Vietnam War, he ended up flying Buddhist monks out of Chinese-controlled Tibet. <s> Some writers have suggested it was a CIA mission; Turrell called it "a humanitarian mission" — and that he found "some beautiful places to fly". <s> For years he restored antique airplanes to support his "art habit". <s> He received a BA degree from Pomona College in perceptual psychology in 1965 (including the study of the Ganzfeld effect) and also studied mathematics, geology and astronomy there. <s> Turrell enrolled in the graduate Studio Art program at the University of California, Irvine in 1966, where he began making work using light projections. <s> His studies at the University of California, Irvine were interrupted in 1966, when he was arrested for coaching young men to avoid the Vietnam draft. <s> He spent about a year in jail. <s> He later (1973) received an MA degree in art from Claremont Graduate University. <s> In 2004, he was awarded an honorary doctorate by Haverford College. <s> Turrell has received numerous awards in the arts including The John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Fellowship in 1984 and the National Medal of Arts in 2013.

MacArthur Foundation Fellowship in 1984 and the National Medal of Arts in 2013.

title: Ellen Hoog
complex: Ellen Marijn Hoog (] , born 26 March 1986) is a Dutch field hockey player. <s> She became part of the national team in 2004 and since then has played in 127 matches, scoring 32 goals. <s> She won Olympic gold medals in 2008 and 2012 and a silver medal in 2016. <s> She is a member of the Amsterdamsche Hockey & Bandy Club. <s> The Dutch International hockey player is sponsored by Ritual Hockey.

title: Murmansk State Technical University
complex: Murmansk State Technical University or MSTU is one of the oldest universities on the Kola peninsula. <s> The university was founded in 1950. <s> Initially it had a name of the High Marine School (HMS).
simple: The Murmansk State Technical University (Russian: Мурманский Государственный Технический Университет, "Murmanskiy Gosudarstvennyy Tekhnicheskiy Universitet"; abbreviated as MSTU in English and МГТУ in Russian) is a public university in Murmansk. <s> It was founded in 1950 as the Murmansk High Marine School (Russian: Мурманское Высшее Мореходное Училище).

complex: Kim Sung-min (Korean: 김성민, February 14, 1973June 26, 2016) was a South Korean actor.

title: Richard F. Heck
complex: Richard Frederick Heck (August 15, 1931 – October 10, 2015) was an American chemist noted for the discovery and development of the Heck reaction, which uses palladium to catalyze organic chemical reactions that couple aryl halides with alkenes. <s> The analgesic naproxen is an example of a compound that is prepared industrially using the Heck reaction. <s> For his work in palladium-catalyzed coupling reactions and organic synthesis, Heck was awarded the 2010 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, shared with the Japanese chemists Ei-ichi Negishi and Akira Suzuki. <s> Heck died on October 9, 2015 in Manila in a public hospital. <s> His wife predeceased him by 2 years.
simple: Richard Fred Heck (August 15, 1931 – October 10, 2015) was an American chemist. <s> He was known for the discovery and development of the Heck reaction, which uses palladium to catalyze organic chemical reactions that couple aryl halides with alkenes. <s> Heck was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry on October 6, 2010, with the Japanese chemists Ei-ichi Negishi and Akira Suzuki, for their work in palladium-catalyzed coupling reactions in organic synthesis. <s> Heck died on October 10, 2015 in Manila in hospital, aged 84.

title: Disney Legends
complex: The Disney Legends Awards is a hall of fame program that recognizes individuals who have made an extraordinary and integral contribution to The Walt Disney Company. <s> Established in 1987, the honor was traditionally awarded annually during a special private ceremony; since 2009, it has been awarded biennially during Disney's D23 Expo. <s> Recipients are chosen by a selection committee, formerly appointed and chaired by Disney Legend Roy E. Disney, Walt Disney's nephew, former vice chairman and director emeritus of The Walt Disney Company. <s> The committee consists of long-time Disney executives, historians, and other authorities.
simple: Disney Legends Awards are given to individuals whose work has made significant contributions to The Walt Disney Company. <s> More than 200 people have received the Disney Legends award. <s> The award was created in 1987. <s> A selection committee chooses who will receive the award.

title: Roger Nordström
complex: Roger Ola Nordström (born 27 April 1966 in Malmö, Sweden) is a Swedish former ice hockey goaltender. <s> Playing most seasons for Malmö Redhawks, he then played for German Krefeld Pinguine between 1998-2003. <s> During the 1992 Olympic tournament he was appointed for the Swedish national team.

title: Luís Miguel Rocha

title: David McAllister
complex: David James "Mac" McAllister (born 12 January 1971) is a German politician and member of the European Parliament from Germany. <s> He is a member of the Christian Democratic Union, part of the European People's Party. <s> He is the current Vice President of the European People's Party and he is also Vice Chairman of the International Democrat Union. <s> He was appointed Chair of the European Parliament Foreign Affairs Committee in February 2017. <s> On 1 July 2010 McAllister was elected Minister-President of the state of Lower Saxony, succeeding Christian Wulff, who resigned following his election as President of Germany. <s> Until his election defeat on 19 February 2013, he headed a coalition government with the liberal FDP, the Cabinet McAllister. <s> In the 2014 European elections, McAllister was elected a Member of the European Parliament as the CDU's top candidate in Lower Saxony. <s> A lawyer by profession, he served as chairman of the CDU parliamentary group in the Lower Saxon Parliament from 2003 to 2010 and was elected chairman of the state party in 2008. <s> In November 2016 he left the chairman post, and announced that he sees his political future in Europe. <s> McAllister holds both German and British citizenship. <s> McAllister was born in West Berlin on 12 January 1971 to a Scottish father and a German mother. <s> His father, James Buchanan McAllister, was a British civil servant, originally from Glasgow (where the family still has relatives), stationed in West Berlin since 1969, where he was attached to the Royal Corps of Signals. <s> His mother, Mechthild McAllister, is a music teacher. <s> David McAllister was raised bilingually and attended a British primary school in Berlin. <s> In a 2010 interview he linked his family's name to Clan MacAlister. <s> After his parents moved to the small town of Bad Bederkesa in Lower Saxony in 1982, he went to the Lower Saxon "Internatsgymnasium" (boarding school) in Bederkesa, where he took his Abitur in 1989. <s> From 1989 till 1991, McAllister served his compulsory military service in the Bundeswehr, in Panzerbataillon 74 in Cuxhaven. <s> From 1991–96 he studied law with a scholarship from the Konrad Adenauer Foundation at the University of Hanover. <s> In 1994, McAllister became local chairman of the CDU youth organisation, Junge Union, in the Cuxhaven district. <s> McAllister holds both German and British citizenship and speaks both German and English as native languages, although he has stated that he's "more or less completely German. <s> I've lived in Germany all my life. <s> I did all my school in Germany and my military service in Germany." <s> His upbringing in West Berlin, however, he describes as "very British" with "British network, British schools". <s> Holding dual citizenship, he could have relinquished his German citizenship to avoid compulsory military service in Germany (the UK does not have compulsory military service), but opted to serve instead. <s> McAllister has said that "my upbringing in West Berlin may have had an impact on my resentment towards communists. <s> I became a member of the CDU when I was 17 – it was a birthday present. <s> My parents said, ‘What do you want for your birthday?’ <s> I said I wanted to become a member of the CDU", explaining that his father was a Conservative, although neither of his parents were involved in party politics. <s> From 1996 till 2010, McAllister was a member of the Cuxhaven district council (Kreistag). <s> He served as mayor of his hometown of Bad Bederkesa from 2001 to 2002. <s> From 2002 to 2003, he also was secretary general of the CDU in Lower Saxony. <s> Since 2003, McAllister has served as the leader of the CDU parliamentary party group in the Parliament of Lower Saxony, of which he has been a member since 1998. <s> McAllister succeeded Christian Wulff as party chairman of the CDU in Lower Saxony from June 2008 until November 2016. <s> He was succeeded by Bernd Althusmann. <s> In the United Kingdom, McAllister is a supporter of the Conservative Party. <s> In 2005, Chancellor Angela Merkel offered him the position of Secretary General of the CDU, but McAllister declined, arguing he did not want to rise too far too fast. <s> He was a CDU delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2004, 2009, 2010 and 2012. <s> On 4 June 2010, McAllister was designated by his party to succeed Christian Wulff as Minister-President of Lower Saxony, if the latter were to be elected President of Germany on 30 June. <s> After the election of Wulff as President, David McAllister was elected the new Minister-President of Lower Saxony the following day. <s> He was subsequently also appointed to the supervisory board of Volkswagen, the largest company in Lower Saxony and of which the state of Lower Saxony is a major stockholder. <s> From 2010, he also served as a member of the supervisory board of Volkswagen. <s> Following the 2013 Lower Saxony state election, McAllister's CDU-FDP Coalition lost control of the Landtag, which meant that the Christian Democrats and the Free Democrats eventually lost the government role. <s> On 19 February 2013, Stephan Weil of the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) was elected Minister-President of Lower Saxony with the votes of SPD and Alliance '90/The Greens. <s> McAllister is married to Dunja McAllister, née Kolleck, who is also a lawyer. <s> They have two daughters named Jamie Elizabeth and Mia Louise. <s> He lives in Bad Bederkesa in the district of Cuxhaven. <s> McAllister proposed to his wife on the shore of Loch Ness, and married in August 2003, wearing a kilt. <s> He later explained it was a family tradition. <s> He supports Rangers FC and Hannover 96.

title: Drug tolerance
complex: Drug tolerance is a pharmacological concept describing subjects' reduced reaction to a drug following its repeated use. <s> Increasing its dosage may re-amplify the drug's effects; however, this may accelerate tolerance, further reducing the drug's effects.
simple: Drug tolerance (or physiological tolerance) is a term used to describe that the organism gets used to a given substance. <s> Drug tolerance also means that over time a drug becomes less effective and larger amounts of the substance are needed to get the same effect.

title: Park Ji-yeon
complex: Park Ji-yeon (born June 7, 1993), referred to as Jiyeon, is a South Korean singer and actress. <s> She debuted as a member of girl group T-ara in July 2009. <s> The group went on to become one of the best-selling girl groups of all time. <s> Apart from her group's activities, she has also starred in various television dramas such as "Soul" (2009), "Master of Study" (2010), "Dream High 2" (2012), "Triangle" (2014), also starred in various films such as "" (2012), "Encounter" (2015). <s> She debuted as a solo artist with her first EP, "Never Ever", on May 20, 2014, making her the first T-ara member to debut as a solo artist. <s> Park was born in Seoul, South Korea, on June 7, 1993, from a Korean family. <s> She briefly attended Hyehwa Girls' High School and graduated from Lila Art High School in 2012. <s> She didn't attend university to focus on her career. <s> She and Hahm Eun-jung are the only two members of T-ara to be trained in acting. <s> Instead, the two switched over to singing despite their original intentions. <s> Park has expressed an interest in modeling. <s> In 2008, when she was 15 years old, she was featured in several pictorials and advertisements for clothing company Smart with Korean boy band SHINee. <s> She collaborated with Davichi and SeeYa on the digital single "Women's Generation", which was released in May 2009, making her the first member "Little Kim Tae-hee" due to her close resemblance to Kim. <s> Park auditioned at the Mnet Casting System and joined the company in 2008. <s> She subsequently debuted with T-ara on July 29, 2009 as the youngest member (maknae). <s> In 2010, Park starred in "Master of Study", a Korean screen adaptation of Japanese manga "Dragon Zakura". <s> That same year, she played the leading role in horror film "" and starred in the youth drama "Jungle Fish 2". <s> In October 2010, Park became the host for MBC's "Show! <s> Music Core", alongside Bae Suzy, Choi Min-ho and Onew. <s> She also became a cast member of SBS's variety show "Heroes". <s> In 2011, Park was cast in the Korean dub of the animated film, "Gnomeo and Juliet". <s> In 2012, she was cast in the teen drama "Dream High 2", starring Kang So-ra, GOT7's JB and Jin-young, 2AM's Jinwoon, SISTAR's Hyolyn, and Park Seo-joon. <s> Park made her solo debut in May 2014, releasing the title track "Never Ever" (also known as "1 Minute 1 Second"). title: Begum Jan
complex: Begum Jan is a doctor and the founder of the Tribal Women Welfare Association, which educates tribal women in Northwest Pakistan about their rights, and gives them medical training. <s> She grew up in South Waziristan, a conservative area of Pakistan, but her father encouraged her to become a doctor. <s> She attended a school for boys as a child because there was no school for girls, and when her tribal elders forbid her to attend high school she studied with a tutor instead. <s> She received a 2008 International Women of Courage Award, making her the first Pakistani woman to receive that award.

title: Prince Regent DLR station
complex: Prince Regent DLR station is a station on the Docklands Light Railway (DLR) in Canning Town in east London. <s> The station was opened on 28 March 1994 and provides access to the eastern end of the ExCeL Exhibition Centre and ICC London. <s> The station signage is subtitled 'for ExCeL East'. <s> There is a small bus station adjoining the station with buses to Plaistow and London City Airport. <s> The station is located on the DLR's Beckton branch, between Custom House and Royal Albert stations. <s> It is in Travelcard Zone 3. <s> During major exhibitions at the adjacent Excel Centre an additional DLR shuttle service operates between Canning Town and Prince Regent stations, to supplement the normal Tower Gateway to Beckton service.

title: Sammi Smith
complex: Sammi Smith (August 5, 1943 – February 12, 2005) was an American country music singer and songwriter. <s> Born Jewel Faye Smith, she is best known for her 1971 country-pop crossover hit "Help Me Make It Through the Night", which was written by Kris Kristofferson. <s> She became one of the few women in the outlaw country movement during the 1970s. <s> Sammi Smith was born in Orange County, California, in 1943 but spent her childhood in Oklahoma, Texas, Arizona and Colorado. <s> She dropped out of school at the age of eleven and began to sing professionally in nightclubs.
simple: Jewel Faye Smith (aka Sammi Smith; August 5, 1943 – February 12, 2005) was an American country music singer and songwriter. <s> She had the 1971 hit single "Help Me Make it Through the Night". <s> She was born in Orange County, California.

title: Vahan Hovhannisyan
complex: Vahan Hovhannisyan ( ; August 16, 1956 – December 28, 2014) was an Armenian politician of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF). <s> He was Vice-President of the National Assembly of Armenia from 2007 to 2008 and was a candidate in the February 2008 presidential election. <s> A 2008 leaked confidential document by the US State Department described him as "clearly the most likeable Dashnak by public persona."
simple: Vahan Hovhannisyan (; August 16, 1956 – December 28, 2014) was an Armenian politician of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF). <s> He was Vice-President of the National Assembly of Armenia from 2007 to 2008 and was a candidate in the February 2008 presidential election.

title: Second-class citizen
complex: A second-class citizen is a person who is systematically discriminated against within a state or other political jurisdiction, despite their nominal status as a citizen or legal resident there. <s> While not necessarily slaves, outlaws or criminals, second-class citizens have limited legal rights, civil rights and socioeconomic opportunities, and are often subject to mistreatment or neglect at the hands of their putative superiors. <s> However, they are different from "less-than-whole citizens", as second-class citizens are often disregarded by the law or have it used to harass them (see police misconduct and racial profiling). <s> Systems with "de facto" second-class citizenry are generally regarded as violating human rights.
simple: A second-class citizen is a person who is discriminated by their nations system, even though they are classified as a citizen or legal resident to said nation. <s> Second-class citizenry is usually seen as a violation of human rights.

title: The Osmonds
complex: The Osmonds are an American family music group who reached the height of their fame in the early-1970s. <s> The group consists of siblings who are all members of the Osmond family, a family of musicians from Ogden, Utah, who have been in the public eye since the 1960s.
simple: The Osmonds are an American family singing group.

title: Coefficient
complex: In mathematics, a coefficient is a multiplicative factor in some term of a polynomial, a series, or any expression; it is usually a number, but may be any expression. <s> In the latter case, the variables appearing in the coefficients are often called parameters, and must be clearly distinguished from the other variables.
simple: In mathematics, a coefficient is a constant multiplicative factor of a certain object.

title: Acre-foot
complex: The acre-foot is a unit of volume commonly used in the United States in reference to large-scale water resources, such as reservoirs, aqueducts, canals, sewer flow capacity, irrigation water, and river flows. <s> An acre-foot equals approximately a 8 lane, 25 m long swimming pool. <s> Since an acre is defined as a chain by a furlong (i.e. 66 × ), an acre-foot is 43,560 cuft . <s> As a rule of thumb in U.S. water management, one acre-foot is taken to be the planned water usage of a suburban family household, annually. <s> In some areas of the desert Southwest, where water conservation is followed and often enforced, a typical family uses only about 0.25 acre-foot of water per year. <s> One acre-foot/year is approximately 893 gallons (3.38 m ) per day. <s> Water reservoir capacities in the U.S. are commonly given in thousands of acre-feet, abbreviated TAF.
simple: An acre-foot is a unit of volume used in the United States to measure large amounts of water resources. <s> An acre-foot is the amount of water it would take to cover an acre of land with water 1 ft deep. <s> It is about the same amount of water as a 8-lane, 25 m long competition swimming pool. <s> One acre-foot of water is the same as 43,560 cuft of water. <s> In some places in the deserts of the Southwestern United States, water conservation is a rule. <s> In these ares, a normal family only uses 0.25 acre-feet of water per year. <s> Large amounts of water can also be in thousands of acre-feet or TAF.

title: Álvaro Recoba
complex: Álvaro Alexánder Recoba Rivero (] ; born 17 March 1976; nickname "El Chino") is a retired Uruguayan footballer who played as a forward or midfielder. <s> Although he began and ended his footballing career in his native country, he also played for several European clubs throughout his career, most notably Italian side Inter Milan, where he spent 11 seasons. <s> Recoba started his career with Uruguay's Danubio. <s> After several years in the Danubio youth teams, he appeared on the first team at age 17 and played for two full seasons, 1994–95 and 1995–96.
simple: Álvaro Recoba (born 17 March 1976) is an Uruguayan football player. <s> He plays for Danubio.

title: 20 BC
complex: Year 20 BC was either a common year starting on Wednesday or Thursday or a leap year starting on Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar (the sources differ, see leap year error for further information) and a common year starting on Tuesday of the Proleptic Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was also known as the Year of the Consulship of Appuleius and Nerva (or, less frequently, year 734 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination 20 BC for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: Year 20 BC was either a common year starting on Wednesday or Thursday or a leap year starting on Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Appuleius and Nerva.

title: The Miserable Mill
complex: The Miserable Mill is the fourth novel of the children's novel series "A Series of Unfortunate Events" by Lemony Snicket. <s> In this novel, the Baudelaire orphans live with the owner of Lucky Smells Lumber Mill. <s> The book was published on April 15, 2000, by HarperCollins and illustrated by Brett Helquist. <s> Violet, Klaus and Sunny Baudelaire are traveling on a train heading for Paltryville, the location of the children's new home, the Lucky Smells Lumbermill. <s> Klaus breaks his own glasses when he is purposely tripped by the new foreman, Flacutono, and is sent to see Dr. Orwell. <s> When Klaus returns from the optometrist, hours later, he acts strangely, as if in a trance.
simple: The Miserable Mill is a book by Lemony Snicket. <s> It is the fourth book in a series called "A Series of Unfortunate Events". <s> Violet, Klaus, and Sunny Baudelaire go by train to Paltryville to meet their new guardian at the Lucky Smells Lumbermill. <s> After breaking his glasses, Klaus is sent to the optometrist (eye doctor) Dr. Orwell.

title: Animal coloration
complex: Animal coloration is the general appearance of an animal resulting from the reflection or emission of light from its surfaces. <s> Some animals are brightly colored, while others are hard to see. <s> In some species, such as the peafowl, the male has strong patterns, conspicuous colors and is iridescent, while the female is far less visible. <s> Animal coloration has been a topic of interest and research in biology for centuries. <s> In the classical era, Aristotle recorded that the octopus was able to change its coloration to match its background, and when it was alarmed. <s> According to Charles Darwin's 1859 theory of natural selection, features such as coloration evolved by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage. <s> For example, individuals with slightly better camouflage than others of the same species would, on average, leave more offspring. <s> Animal coloration may be the result of any combination of pigments, chromatophores, structural coloration and bioluminescence.
simple: Animal colour (or coloration) is produced by light reflecting from an animal's surface. <s> Animal colour has been a topic of interest and research in biology for a long time. <s> According to Charles Darwin's 1859 theory of natural selection, features such as colouration evolved by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage. <s> For example, individuals with slightly better camouflage than others of the same species would, on average, leave more offspring. <s> The ways animals produce colours include pigments, chromatophores and other structures, and bioluminescence.

title: Metropolitan Borough of Wirral
complex: The Metropolitan Borough of Wirral is a metropolitan borough of Merseyside, in North West England. <s> It has a population of 321,238, and encompasses 60 sqmi of the northern part of the Wirral Peninsula. <s> Major settlements include Birkenhead, Wallasey, Bebington, Heswall, Hoylake and West Kirby. <s> The city of Liverpool over the Mersey, faces the northeastern side of Wirral. <s> Bordering is the River Mersey to the east, the Irish Sea to the north and the River Dee to the west; the borough of Cheshire West and Chester occupies the remainder of the Wirral Peninsula and borders the borough of Wirral to the south. <s> The borough of Wirral has greater proportions of rural areas than the Liverpool part of Merseyside. <s> This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of Wirral at current basic prices published (pp. 240–253) by "Office for National Statistics" with figures in millions of British Pounds Sterling. <s> ^ includes hunting and forestry <s> ^ includes energy and construction <s> ^ includes financial intermediation services indirectly measured <s> ^ Components may not sum to totals due to rounding <s> In September 2006 a large scale development called Wirral Waters was unveiled by the company Peel Holdings, that if constructed as outlined may see the creation of up to 27,000 jobs.
simple: Wirral is a metropolitan borough in Merseyside, North West England, which occupies the northern part of the Wirral Peninsula, more commonly known as Wirral. <s> It faces Liverpool over the River Mersey to the east, the Irish Sea to the north and the River Dee to the west. <s> This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of Wirral at current basic prices published (pp.240–253) by the "Office for National Statistics" with figures in millions of British Pounds Sterling. <s> ^ includes hunting and forestry <s> ^ includes energy and construction <s> ^ includes financial intermediation services indirectly measured <s> ^ Components may not sum to totals due to rounding <s> In September 2006 a large scale development called Wirral Waters was unveiled by the company Peel Holdings, that if constructed as outlined may see the creation of up to 27,000 jobs.

title: Electric blues
complex: Electric blues refers to any type of blues music distinguished by the use of electric amplification for musical instruments. <s> The guitar was the first instrument to be popularly amplified and used by early pioneers T-Bone Walker in the late 1930s and John Lee Hooker and Muddy Waters in the 1940s.
simple: The electric blues is a type of blues music made different by the amplification of the guitar, the bass guitar, and/or the harmonica.

title: Jiao Ruoyu
complex: Jiao Ruoyu (; born November 7, 1915) is a retired People's Republic of China politician and diplomat. <s> He was born in Ye County, Henan. <s> He was deputy mayor of Shenyang under Huang Oudong. <s> He was Chinese Ambassador to North Korea (1965–1970), Peru (1972–1977) and Iran (1977–1979). <s> He was mayor of Beijing (1981–1983). <s> On August 14, 2012, Jiao, 97, was confirmed as the oldest member of the Communist Party of China to attend the 18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China. <s> He turned 100 in November 2015.
simple: Jiao Ruoyu (; born 7 November 1915) is a retired Chinese politician and diplomat. <s> Jiao was born in Ye County, Henan. <s> He served as deputy mayor of Shenyang under Huang Oudong. <s> He was Chinese Ambassador to North Korea (1965–1970), Peru (1972–1977) and Iran (1977–1979). <s> Jiao was also mayor of Beijing from 1981 to 1983. <s> He turned 100 in November 2015.

title: David Usher
complex: David Usher (born April 24, 1966) is a British-born Canadian musician, best-selling author, keynote speaker, and activist best known as the front man for the band Moist. <s> He has also released a number of solo albums. <s> David Usher was born in Oxford, England to Thai Buddhist artist Samphan Usher and a Jewish man from Montreal. <s> He has lived in various places such as Malaysia, New York City, California, and Thailand since early childhood, before his family settled in Kingston, Ontario. <s> He attended high school at Kingston Collegiate and Vocational Institute. <s> Usher attended Simon Fraser University in Burnaby, British Columbia, majoring in political science. <s> While studying in Vancouver, Usher helped form the second incarnation of a band called Moist, composed of Usher on vocals, Mark Makoway on guitars, Jeff Pearce on bass, Kevin Young, who, like Usher, had moved to Vancouver from Kingston, on keyboards, and Paul Wilcox on drums. <s> Usher became the principal songwriter for the band. <s> Usher has been involved in the causes War Child Canada, White Ribbon Campaign, and Amnesty International. <s> He is featured in the 2001 MuchMusic special "Musicians in the WarZone", a humanitarian documentary directed by filmmaker Liz Marshall, in which he journeys to the northern border of Thailand to visit a large Burmese refugee community. <s> Usher is on the advisory board of McGill University’s Institute for the Public Life of Art and Ideas, and is the founding director of Amnesty International’s Artists for Amnesty.
simple: David Usher (born April 24, 1966) is an British-born Canadian rock singer-songwriter. <s> Usher was born in Oxford, England. <s> He lived in many different places such as Malaysia, New York City, California and Thailand before his family decided to finally settle in Kingston, Ontario. <s> Usher attended high school at Kingston Collegiate and Vocational Institute and he attended Simon Fraser University in Burnaby, British Columbia. <s> He majored in political science. <s> While attending Simon Fraser, Usher formed Moist with guitarist Mark Makowy and keyboardist Kevin Young. <s> Usher is also a humanist, and he has been involved in causes like War Child Canada, White Ribbon Campaign and Amnesty International. <s> He was featured in the 2001 MuchMusic special "Musicians in the WarZone", a humanitarian documentary which was produced by War Child Canada and was directed by filmmaker Liz Marshall.

title: Filippo Raciti
complex: Filippo Raciti (17 January 1967–2 February 2007) was an Italian police officer ("ispettore capo di polizia") who was killed in a violent confrontation between Calcio Catania football supporters and police officers. <s> Raciti's death resulted in all of the Italian football matches, even the national team, to be suspended for a week. <s> It provoked outrage in Italy, with a great and somewhat uncommon amount of solidarity towards the Italian law enforcement forces, and massive coverage worldwide.
simple: Filippo Raciti (17 January 1967–2 February 2007) was an Italian police officer who was killed in a fight between Calcio Catania fans outside a stadium in Catania. <s> Raciti's death was in the news around the world. <s> All of the Italian football matches, even the national team, were suspended for a week.

title: Noorderhaaks
complex: Noorderhaaks (] ), also called "Razende Bol" ("Raging Bull" in Dutch), is an uninhabited Dutch island in the North Sea, a few kilometres west of the Marsdiep which separates the island of Texel from the mainland of the Netherlands. <s> The island covers an area of around five km2, although the exact area varies due to tide and the dynamic nature of the area.
simple: Noorderhaaks or "Razende Bol" is an uninhabited small island of the province of North Holland, the Netherlands. <s> It covers an area of 4 km2.

title: Lhuis
complex: Lhuis is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Lhuis is a commune.

title: Loleatta Holloway
complex: Loleatta Holloway ( , ; November 5, 1946 – March 21, 2011) was an American singer, mainly known for disco songs such as "Hit and Run" and "Love Sensation", both of which have been sampled extensively. <s> In December 2016, "Billboard magazine" ranked her as the 95th most successful dance artist of all-time. <s> Holloway died aged 64 on March 21, 2011 from heart failure and is survived by her four children.
simple: Loleatta Holloway (November 5, 1946 – March 21, 2011) was an American singer. <s> She was known mainly for disco songs, such as "Hit and Run" and "Love Sensation". <s> She died there from heart failure.

title: Mike Embley
complex: Michael Kenneth Embley (born 25 May 1955 in Sutton, Surrey) is an English broadcast journalist, best known as a presenter for BBC World News, an international news and current affairs television channel operated by the BBC. <s> He currently presents overnight Tuesday-Friday on BBC World News, BBC One and the BBC News Channel. <s> Before joining the BBC, Embley began his career training as a newspaper journalist with Thomson daily papers in Wales, on the South Wales Echo and the Western Mail. <s> He began broadcasting in 1983, working for BBC Wales' "Wales Today", followed by the consumer affairs programme "Watchdog" in 1987, and "Public Eye" in 1989. <s> Whilst working on "Public Eye", he was the first British reporter to reach San Francisco to report on the earthquake. <s> Embley later joined ITN's Channel 4 News to work as a producer and reporter, before returning to the BBC as a reporter for the flagship One O'Clock News, Six O'Clock News and Nine O'Clock News bulletins. <s> During this time, Embley also worked as a series presenter for "Nature" on BBC Two and made two films for "Panorama". <s> Embley joined BBC World in 1995, and remained there for two years until he became the main presenter of "Newsroom South East", the BBC's regional news programme for London and the South East of England. <s> After the programme was replaced by two separate regional bulletins ("BBC London" and "South East Today") in 2001, Embley rejoined BBC World as a presenter. <s> Since then, he has also presented on the domestic BBC News Channel and carried out one-on-one interviews for the BBC programme "HARDtalk", as well as reporting several series for the radio station BBC World Service.
simple: Mike Embley (born 1955 in Surrey, England) is a British broadcast journalist, best known as a presenter for BBC World News, an international news and current affairs television channel operated by the BBC. <s> Embley was born in Surrey, England in 1955. <s> Before joining the BBC, Embley began his career training as a newspaper journalist with Thomson daily papers in Wales, on the South Wales Echo and the Western Mail. <s> He began broadcasting in 1983, working for BBC Wales' "Wales Today", followed by the consumer affairs programme "Watchdog" in 1987, and "Public Eye" in 1989. <s> Whilst working on "Public Eye", he was the first news reporter with a foreign crew to reach the San Francisco to report on the earthquake. <s> Embley later joined ITN's Channel Four News to work as a producer and reporter, before returning to the BBC as a reporter for the flagship One O'Clock, Six O'Clock and Nine O'Clock News bulletins. <s> During this time, Embley also worked as a series presenter for "Nature" on BBC Two and made two films for "Panorama". <s> Embley joined BBC World in 1995. <s> After the program was replaced by two separate programs ("BBC London" and "South East Today") in 2001, Embley rejoined BBC World as a presenter. <s> Since then, he has also presented on the domestic BBC News Channel and carried out one-on-one interviews for the BBC programme "HARDtalk", as well as reporting several series for the radio station BBC World Service.

title: Hikaru Nakamura
complex: Hikaru Nakamura (ヒカル・ナカムラ (in katakana), 中村 光 (in kanji) , Nakamura Hikaru , born December 9, 1987) is a Japanese-born American chess grandmaster. <s> He is a five-time United States Chess Champion, who won the 2011 edition of Tata Steel Group A and represented the United States at five Chess Olympiads, winning a team gold medal and two team bronze medals. <s> He has also written a book about bullet chess called "Bullet Chess: One Minute to Mate". <s> Nakamura was born in Hirakata, Osaka Prefecture, Japan, to an American mother, Carolyn Merrow Nakamura, a classically trained musician and former public school teacher and Japanese father, Shuichi Nakamura. <s> When he was two years of age his family moved to the United States. <s> Nakamura's parents divorced in 1990, when he was 3 years old. <s> He began playing chess at the age of seven and was coached by his Sri Lankan stepfather, FIDE Master and chess author Sunil Weeramantry. <s> From January 14 through January 30, Nakamura competed in the Tata Steel Grandmaster A tournament in Wijk aan Zee among a field of world No. 1 and defending champion Magnus Carlsen, world champion and world No. 2 Viswanathan Anand, world No. 3 and reigning World Blitz champion Levon Aronian, world No. 4 and former world champion Vladimir Kramnik, world No. 7 Alexander Grischuk, former FIDE world champion Ruslan Ponomariov, reigning Russian champion Ian Nepomniachtchi, reigning Chinese champion Wang Hao, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, Alexei Shirov, Anish Giri, Jan Smeets, and Erwin L'Ami. <s> The average rating of the field was 2740, making this thirteen-round event a category 20 tournament.
simple: Hikaru Nakamura (中村光, Nakamura Hikaru) is the leading U.S. chess grandmaster (GM). <s> He has won the U.S. chess championship four times, and represented the United States at five Chess Olympiads. <s> He was born on 9 December 1987 in Japan (Hirakata, Osaka Prefecture). <s> His parents moved to the United States when he was two. <s> In 2011, Nakamura won the Tata Steel Grandmaster A tournament in Wijk aan Zee. <s> His opponents included world #1 and defending champion Magnus Carlsen, former world champion Viswanathan Anand, world #2 Levon Aronian, and former world champion Vladimir Kramnik,

title: Maravar
complex: Maravar (also known as Maravan and Marava) are a Tamil community in the state of Tamil Nadu. <s> These people are one of the three branches of the Mukkulathor confederacy. <s> Members of the Maravar community often use the honorific title "Thevar". <s> The term "Maravar" has diverse proposed etymologies; it may come simply from a Tamil word "maravar" (warrior), or a term meaning "bravery".
simple: Maravar is a Tamil community of the state of Tamil Nadu, southern India, and are one of the three branches of the Mukkulathor confederacy or league of caste.Members of the Maravar community often use the honorific title "Thevar".T <s> The term "Maravar" has diverse proposed etymologies; it may come simply from a Tamil word "maravar" (warrior), or a term meaning "bravery".

title: Chesterfield, South Carolina
complex: Chesterfield is a town in Chesterfield County, South Carolina, United States. <s> The population was 1,472 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Chesterfield County. <s> At the time of the 2010 census, Chesterfield was the least populous of all of South Carolina's county seats.
simple: Chesterfield is a town in Chesterfield County, South Carolina, United States. <s> The population was 1,472 at the 2010 census. <s> It is the county seat of Chesterfield County.

title: QVC
complex: QVC (an acronym for "Quality Value Convenience") is an American free-to-air television network, and flagship shopping channel specializing in televised home shopping that is owned by Qurate Retail Group. <s> Founded in 1986 by Joseph Segel in West Chester, Pennsylvania, United States, QVC broadcasts to more than 350 million households in seven countries, including channels in the UK, Germany, Japan, and Italy, along with a joint venture in China with China National Radio called CNR Mall.
simple: The name "QVC" means Quality, Value and Convenience. <s> QVC serves almost 235 million customers in six countries.

title: Angora goat
complex: The Angora goat is a breed of domesticated goat, historically known as Angora. <s> Angora goats produce the lustrous fibre known as Mohair. <s> The first Angora goats were brought to Europe by Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, about 1554, but, like later imports, were not very successful. <s> Turkey, Argentina, the United States, and South Africa are the top producers of mohair. <s> Secondary producers include New Zealand and Australia.
simple: The Angora goat is a breed of domestic goat. <s> The Angora produces fine quality white or coloured mohair which is very similar to wool. <s> Angora goats are kept mostly for their output of mohair. <s> Angoras were imported into Europe in 1554 by Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. <s> Today, the Union of South Africa is one of the world's top mohair producers.

title: Francis Dashwood, 11th Baron le Despencer
complex: Francis Dashwood, 11th Baron le Despencer, PC, FRS (December 1708 – 11 December 1781) was an English rake and politician, Chancellor of the Exchequer (1762–1763) and founder of the Hellfire Club. <s> Dashwood was born in Great Marlborough Street, London, in December 1708. <s> He was only son of Sir Francis Dashwood, 1st Baronet (died 1724), and his second wife Mary, eldest daughter of Vere Fane, 4th Earl of Westmorland. <s> Dashwood was educated at Eton College where he became associated with William Pitt the Elder. <s> Upon the death of his father on 4 November 1724, Dashwood, who was only fifteen, inherited his father's estates and the Baronetcy of Dashwood of West Wycombe.
simple: Francis Dashwood, 15th Baron le Despencer (December 1708–11 December 1781) was an English rake and politician. <s> He was Chancellor of the Exchequer (1762-1763) and founder of The Hellfire Club. <s> Dashwood was born in London. <s> He was educated at Eton College where he became associated with William Pitt the Elder.

title: Mary T. Clark
complex: Sister Mary Twibill Clark, RSCJ (October 23, 1913 – September 1, 2014) was an American academic and civil rights advocate. <s> She was best known as a scholar of the history of philosophy, and was associated especially with Augustine of Hippo. <s> She served as the President of the American Catholic Philosophical Association in 1977, of the Metaphysical Society of America, and of the Society for Medieval and Renaissance Philosophy. <s> Clark served on the Executive Committee of the Eastern Division of the American Philosophical Association, and towards the end of her life as a visiting academic at Ralston College. <s> Sister Mary Clark died on September 1, 2014, aged 100. <s> She was predeceased by her siblings, Rev. James D. Clark, George A. Clark, and Regina (Mrs. James P.) McGraney.
simple: Sister Mary T. Clark, RSCJ (October 23, 1913 – September 1, 2014) was an Americans educator and civil rights advocate. <s> She was best known as a scholar of the history of philosophy, and was associated especially with Augustine of Hippo. <s> She was formerly the President of the American Catholic Philosophical Association of the Metaphysical Society of America, and of the Society for Medieval and Renaissance Philosophy. <s> She also served on the Executive Committee of the Eastern Division of the American Philosophical Association. <s> She served as a Visitor of Ralston College. <s> Clark died in Savannah, Georgia from natural causes, aged 100.

title: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg
complex: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg is the second borough of Berlin, formed in 2001 by merging the former East Berlin borough of Friedrichshain and the former West Berlin borough of Kreuzberg. <s> The historic Oberbaum Bridge, formerly a Berlin border crossing for pedestrians, links both districts across the river Spree as the new borough's landmark (as featured in the coat of arms).
simple: Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg is a borough of Berlin. <s> It is a new borough, only made in 2001 by joining the old boroughs of Friedrichshain and Kreuzberg.

title: Brandon Roy
complex: Brandon Dawayne Roy (born July 23, 1984) is an American basketball coach and a former professional basketball player. <s> Roy played six seasons in the National Basketball Association (NBA) for the Portland Trail Blazers and Minnesota Timberwolves. <s> He was selected sixth in the 2006 NBA draft, having completed four years playing for the Washington Huskies. <s> His nickname was "B-Roy", but he was also referred to as "The Natural" by Trail Blazers announcer Brian Wheeler. <s> On December 10, 2011, Roy announced his retirement from basketball due to a degenerative knee condition, though he returned in 2012 to play five games for the Timberwolves. <s> Born in Seattle, Roy became known for his immediate impact on the Trail Blazers. <s> Zach Randolph, then the team captain, was traded to the New York Knicks at the end of Roy's first season in 2006–07, which cleared the way for Roy to take on a leadership role on the team. <s> That season, Roy won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award in a near-unanimous vote. <s> He was selected as a reserve to the 2008, 2009, and 2010 All-Star games. <s> Roy played the most minutes of any Western Conference player, and tied for the most points in the West in the 2008 season, and he played the most minutes of any player during the 2009 season.
simple: Brandon Roy (born July 23, 1984 in Seattle, Washington) is a retired professional basketball player. <s> He played for the Portland Trail Blazers of the National Basketball Association (NBA) from 2006 to 2011. <s> The Minnesota Timberwolves chose him with the sixth pick in the 2006 NBA Draft, but traded him to the Trail Blazers later that night. <s> On December 9, 2011, Roy said that he would retire from basketball because of knee problems. <s> He won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award in 2007, and was chosen as an All Star in 2008, 2009, and 2010.

title: Red Barber
complex: Walter Lanier "Red" Barber (February 17, 1908 – October 22, 1992) was an American sports commentator. <s> Barber, nicknamed "The Ol' Redhead", was primarily identified with radio broadcasts of Major League Baseball, calling play-by-play across four decades with the Cincinnati Reds (1934–1938), Brooklyn Dodgers (1939–1953), and New York Yankees (1954–1966). <s> Like his fellow sports pioneer Mel Allen, Barber also gained a niche calling college and professional American football in his primary market of New York City.
simple: Walter Lanier "Red" Barber (February 17, 1908October 22, 1992) was an American sports commentator. <s> Barber, nicknamed ""The Ol' Redhead"", by the radio broadcasts of Major League Baseball. <s> He broadcasted for forty years with the Cincinnati Reds (193438), Brooklyn Dodgers (19391953), and New York Yankees (19541966).

title: Observation deck
complex: An observation deck, observation platform or viewing platform is an elevated sightseeing platform usually situated upon a tall architectural structure such as a skyscraper or observation tower. <s> Observation decks are sometimes enclosed from weather, and a few may include coin-operated telescopes for viewing distant features.
simple: An observation deck is a place up high where people can see things.

title: Mega Man (video game)
complex: Mega Man, known as Rockman (ロックマン , Rokkuman ) in Japan, is a 1987 action-platform video game developed and published by Capcom for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES). <s> It was directed by Akira Kitamura, with Nobuyuki Matsushima as lead programmer, and is the first game of the "Mega Man" franchise and the original video game series. <s> "Mega Man" was produced by a small team specifically for the home console market, a first for Capcom, who previously focused on arcade titles. <s> The initial Western release of the game, while keeping the basic plot the same, significantly changed some details from the original Japanese manual. <s> In this version, Dr. Light and Dr. Wily (here Light's assistant turned disloyal) co-create the humanoid robot Mega Man alongside the six advanced robots, each of whom were designed for the benefit of Monsteropolis's citizens (no such place existed in the original plot). <s> Dr. Wily grows disloyal of his partner and reprograms these six robots to aid himself in taking control of the world, creating the seven empires of Monsteropolis. <s> Dr. Light sends Mega Man to destroy his fellow creations and stop Dr. Wily.
simple: Mega Man is also known as Rockman (ロックマン, Rokkuman) in Japan. <s> It is a video game developed and published by Capcom for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES). <s> It is the first game in the original "Mega Man" series. <s> Two scientists, Dr. Light and Dr. Wily, create humanoid robots; Wily goes rogue and reprograms most of the robots for world domination. <s> It's up to Mega Man, a robot created by Dr. Light, to stop Dr. Wily and his army of "Robot Masters".

title: Saint John, Barbados
complex: The parish of Saint John (St. John) is a parish of Barbados on the eastern side of the island. <s> It is home to one of its secondary schools, The Lodge School. <s> The parish is the home of many districts such as Ashford and Kendal. <s> It is home to the St. John's Parish Church, which has a scenic view of the Atlantic Ocean from its perch near Hackleton's Cliff, which overlooks the East Coast of the island. <s> In its southeastern corner, the shoreline turns northward, forming the small Conset Bay. <s> Ashford Bird Park is a bird and animal sanctuary of 197 acre .
simple: Saint John ("St. John") is a parish of Barbados. <s> It is on the eastern side of the island. <s> It is home to one of the secondary schools on the island, The Lodge School. <s> In its southeastern corner, the shoreline turns northward instead of southward, forming the small Conset Bay. <s> Ashford Bird Park is a bird and animal sanctuary.

title: La Bazouge-des-Alleux
complex: La Bazouge-des-Alleux is a commune in the Mayenne department in northwestern France.
simple: La Bazouge-des-Alleux is a commune of 262 people (1999). <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Mayenne department in the northwest of France.

title: Rafael Gordillo
complex: Rafael Gordillo Vázquez (born 24 February 1957) is a Spanish retired footballer. <s> A tremendously attacking left wingback, equally at ease as defender and midfielder and with a good effort rate, he had an unmistakable style of playing with his socks down.
simple: Rafael Gordillo (born 24 February, 1957) is a former Spanish football player.

title: James Hylton
complex: James Harvey Hylton (August 26, 1934 – April 28, 2018) was an American stock car racing driver. <s> He was a two-time winner in NASCAR Winston Cup Series (now Monster Energy Cup Series) competition and was a long-time competitor in the ARCA Racing Series. <s> Hylton finished second in points in NASCAR's top series three times. <s> Hylton was born on August 26, 1934 to a Roanoke, Virginia family farm; he was one of thirteen children. <s> Hylton's early years centered primarily around farming but he soon found himself immersed in the world of stock car auto racing. <s> On April 28, 2018, Hylton, his son James "Tweet" Hylton Jr., and the team's crew chief Terry Strange were driving home from the ARCA race at Talladega, and the team's hauler was in a traffic accident going northbound on Interstate 85 near Carnesville, Georgia. <s> Both Hyltons died in the accident, while Strange survived with severe injuries.
simple: James Harvey Hylton (August 26, 1934 – April 28, 2018) was an American stock car racing driver. <s> He was a two-time winner in NASCAR Winston Cup Series (now Monster Energy Cup Series) competition. <s> He was a long-time competitor in the ARCA Racing Series. <s> Hylton finished second in points in NASCAR's top series three times. <s> He was born in Roanoke, Virginia. <s> Hylton was killed in a car crash near Carnesville, Georgia on April 28, 2018 at the age of 83.

title: Sprint (running)
complex: In athletics and track and field, sprints (or dashes) are races over short distances. <s> They are among the oldest running competitions, being recorded at the Ancient Olympic Games.
simple: Sprints are short running races in athletics.

title: Temple of Athena Nike
complex: The Temple of Athena Nike (Greek: Ναός Αθηνάς Νίκης, "Naós Athinás Níkis") is a temple on the Acropolis of Athens, dedicated to the goddess Athena Nike. <s> Built around 420 BC, the temple is the earliest fully Ionic temple on the Acropolis. <s> It has a prominent position on a steep bastion at the south west corner of the Acropolis to the right of the entrance, the Propylaea.
simple: The Temple of Athena Nike is a temple on the Acropolis of Athens. <s> It was named after the Greek goddess, Athena Nike. <s> Built around 420BC, the temple is the earliest fully Ionic temple on the Acropolis.

title: Kazimierz Ryczan
complex: Kazimierz Ryczan (10 February 1939 – 13 September 2017) was a Polish Roman Catholic bishop. <s> Ordained to the priesthood on 16 June 1963, Ryczan was named bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Kielce, Poland on 17 July 1993.
simple: Kazimierz Ryczan (10 February 1939 – 13 September 2017) was a Polish Roman Catholic bishop. <s> He was ordained to the priesthood on 16 June 1963, Ryczan was named bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Kielce, Poland on 17 July 1993.

title: Marella Agnelli
complex: Marella Agnelli (] ; born Donna Marella Caracciolo di Castagneto ] ; 4 May 1927 – 23 February 2019) was an Italian noblewoman, art collector, socialite, style icon and widow of Fiat chairman Gianni Agnelli. <s> She often appeared in the fashion magazine "Vogue." <s> She was named to the International Best Dressed List Hall of Fame in 1963.
simple: Marella Agnelli (], born Donna Marella Caracciolo di Castagneto (]); 4 May 1927 – 23 February 2019) was an Italian noblewoman, art collector and socialite. <s> She was the widow Fiat chairman Gianni Agnelli. <s> She often appeared in the fashion magazine "Vogue." <s> She was named to the International Best Dressed List Hall of Fame in 1963.

title: Gavin Watson
complex: Gavin Joseph Watson (12 July 1948 – 26 August 2019) was a South African businessman who served as Chief Executive Officer of African Global Operations, previously known as Bosasa, from 2000 until his death in 2019. <s> His company was implicated in state capture during judicial hearings in January 2019. <s> Watson died in a car accident early on 26 August 2019 when the company Toyota Corolla he was driving struck a pillar on an approach road leading to O. R. Tambo International Airport in Johannesburg. <s> His BMW X5 was in for mechanical repairs at the time.
simple: Gavin Joseph Watson (12 July 1948 – 26 August 2019) was a South African businessman. <s> He was Chief Executive Officer of State Capture-implicated company, African Global Operations, previously known as Bosasa, from 2000 until his death in 2019. <s> Watson died in a car accident on 26 August 2019, near O. R. Tambo International Airport in Johannesburg at the age of 71.

title: Mo Collins (American football)
complex: Damon Jamal Collins (September 22, 1976 – October 26, 2014), nicknamed Mo Collins, was an American college and professional football player who was an offensive lineman in the National Football League (NFL) for six seasons during the 1990s and early 2000s. <s> Collins played college football for the University of Florida, and was a member of a national championship team. <s> The Oakland Raiders selected him in the first round of the 1998 NFL Draft, and he played his entire professional career for the Raiders. <s> Collins was hired as the head coach of the West Charlotte Lions football team of West Charlotte High School, his alma mater, on February 7, 2014. <s> Collins died Sunday, October 26, 2014; he had been receiving dialysis treatment after suffering kidney failure.
simple: Damon Jamal Collins (September 22, 1976 – October 26, 2014), nicknamed Mo Collins, was an American college and professional football player. <s> He was an offensive lineman in the National Football League (NFL) for six seasons during the 1990s and early 2000s. <s> Collins played college football for the University of Florida, and was a member of a national championship team. <s> The Oakland Raiders selected him in the first round of the 1998 NFL Draft, and he played his entire professional career for the Raiders. <s> Collins died of kidney failure in Charlotte, North Carolina, aged 38.

title: United States National Arboretum
complex: The United States National Arboretum is an arboretum in Washington, D.C., operated by the United States Department of Agriculture's Agricultural Research Service as a division of the Henry A. Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center. <s> It was established in 1927, by an act of Congress after a campaign by USDA Chief Botanist Frederick Vernon Coville.
simple: United States National Arboretum is the national arboretum of the United States.

title: Amicus curiae
complex: An amicus curiae (literally, "friend of the court"; plural, amici curiae) is someone who is not a party to a case and may or may not have been solicited by a party and who assists a court by offering information, expertise, or insight that has a bearing on the issues in the case; and is typically presented in the form of a brief. <s> The decision on whether to consider an amicus brief lies within the discretion of the court. <s> The phrase "amicus curiae" is legal Latin. <s> The "amicus curiae" figure originates in Roman law. <s> Starting in the 9th century, it was incorporated into English law, and it was later extended to most common law systems. <s> Later, it was introduced in international law, in particular concerning human rights. <s> From there, it was integrated in some civil law systems (it has recently been integrated into Argentina's law system and Honduras's 2010 civil procedures code). <s> Today, it is used by the European Court of Human Rights, the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights, the Inter-American Court of Human Rights, the Court of Justice of the European Union and the Special Tribunal for Lebanon. <s> The situation most often noted in the press is when an advocacy group files a brief in a case before an appellate court in which it is not a litigant. <s> Appellate cases are normally limited to the factual record and arguments coming from the lower court case under appeal; attorneys focus on the facts and arguments most favorable to their clients. <s> Where a case may have broader implications, "amicus curiae" briefs are a way to articulate those concerns, so that the possibly broad legal or public policy ramifications of the court's anticipated decisions will not depend solely on the positions and arguments advanced by the parties directly involved in the case. <s> In prominent cases, "amici curiae" are generally organizations with sizable legal budgets. <s> In the United States, for example, non-profit legal advocacy organizations, such as the American Civil Liberties Union, the Landmark Legal Foundation, the Pacific Legal Foundation, the Electronic Frontier Foundation, the American Center for Law and Justice or NORML, frequently submit such briefs to advocate for or against a particular legal change or interpretation. <s> If a decision could affect an entire industry, companies other than the litigants may wish to have their concerns heard. <s> In the United States, federal courts often hear cases involving the constitutionality of state laws. <s> Hence states may file briefs as "amici curiae" when their laws or interests are likely to be affected, as in the Supreme Court case "McDonald v. Chicago," when thirty-two states under the aegis of Texas (and California independently) filed such briefs. <s> "Amici curiae" who do not file briefs often present an academic perspective on the case. <s> For example, if the law gives deference to a history of legislation of a certain topic, a historian may choose to evaluate the claim from specialized expertise. <s> An economist, statistician, or sociologist may choose to do the same. <s> Newspaper editorials, blogs, and other opinion pieces arguably have the capability to influence Supreme Court decisions as "de facto amici curiae". <s> They are not, however, technically considered "amicus curiae," as they do not submit materials to the Court, do not need to ask for leave, and have no guarantee that they will be read. <s> The Supreme Court of the United States has special rules for "amicus curiae" briefs sought to be filed in cases pending before it. <s> Supreme Court Rule 37 states, in part, such a brief should cover "relevant matter" not dealt with by the parties which "may be of considerable help". <s> The cover of an "amicus" brief must identify which party the brief is supporting, or if the brief supports only affirmance or reversal. <s> The Court also requires that, "inter alia", all non-governmental amici identify those providing a monetary contribution to the preparation or submission of the brief. <s> Briefs must be prepared in booklet format, and 40 copies must be served with the Court. <s> In the United States Supreme Court, unless the "amicus" brief is being filed by the federal government (or one of its officers or agents) or a U.S. state, permission of the court (by means of motion for leave) or mutual consent of the parties is generally required. <s> Allowing an "amicus curiae" to present oral argument is considered "extraordinary". <s> The court can also appoint its own "amicus curiae" if neither party supports the decision of the lower court, which it has done at least 44 times. <s> The role of "amicus curiae" briefs in the World Trade Organization (WTO) dispute settlement system is controversial. <s> The controversy arises due to the governmental nature of WTO disputes. <s> As only WTO members have access to the system, any non-members such as non-governmental organizations (NGOs) are excluded and have no right to be heard. <s> Thus the only way for them to contribute to a WTO decision is through "amicus curiae" briefs. <s> To date there is a divergence in approaches in the WTO as to the admissibility of such briefs.

U.S. state, permission of the court (by means of motion for leave) or mutual consent of the parties is generally required. <s> Allowing an "amicus curiae" to present oral argument is considered
