title: Skatval
complex: Skatval is a village in the municipality of Stjørdal in Trøndelag county, Norway. <s> It is located on the Skatval peninsula about 8 km northwest of the town of Stjørdalshalsen.
simple: Skatval is a small village in the municipality called Stjørdal in the province Nord-Trøndelag, Norway.

title: Orbiting Carbon Observatory
complex: The Orbiting Carbon Observatory (OCO) is a NASA satellite mission intended to provide global space-based observations of atmospheric carbon dioxide . <s> The original spacecraft was lost in a launch failure on 24 February 2009, when the payload fairing of the Taurus rocket which was carrying it failed to separate during ascent. <s> The added mass of the fairing prevented the satellite from reaching orbit. <s> It subsequently re-entered the atmosphere and crashed into the Indian Ocean near Antarctica. <s> The replacement satellite, Orbiting Carbon Observatory 2, was launched 2 July 2014 aboard a Delta II rocket.
simple: The Orbiting Carbon Observatory (OCO) was a NASA satellite mission that was supposed to provide world-wide observations of atmospheric carbon dioxide from space. <s> It was lost in a launch failure on February 24, 2009, when the box of the Taurus rocket which was carrying it failed to come off during launch. <s> The added weight of the box it was in prevented the satellite from reaching its intended speed and height. <s> After that it fell back into the atmosphere and crashed into the Indian Ocean near Antarctica.

title: Argis
complex: Argis is a French commune in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of eastern France. <s> The inhabitants of the commune are known as "Argissiens" or "Argissiennes". <s> There was a lordship and a castle in the Middle Ages.
simple: Argis is a commune. <s> It is in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region of the Ain department; in the east of France. <s> The inhabitants are the "Argissiens". <s> In the Middle Ages there was a castle in Argis; but it does not exist anymore.

title: Tommy Page
complex: Thomas Alden Page (May 24, 1970 – March 3, 2017) was an American singer-songwriter, best known for his 1990 hit single "I'll Be Your Everything" and was later a music industry executive. <s> Born in Glen Ridge, New Jersey, to parents Fred and Miriam Page, he grew up in nearby West Caldwell. <s> He graduated from James Caldwell High School with the class of 1985 at the age of 15. <s> Page was found dead on March 3, 2017 at the age of 46 of an apparent suicide. <s> He had three children (Owen, Alden, and Ruby) with his husband Charlie.
simple: Thomas Alden "Tommy" Page (May 24, 1970 – March 3, 2017) was an American singer-songwriter and pianist. <s> He was best known for his 1990 hit single, "I'll Be Your Everything". <s> He later became a music industry executive for "Billboard magazine". <s> Page was born in Glen Ridge, New Jersey and raised in West Caldwell, New Jersey. <s> He studied at James Caldwell High School. <s> Page died on March 3, 2017 in New York City in an apparent suicide, aged 46. <s> Page had three children with his partner, Charlie.

title: Richea
complex: Richea is a genus of 11 species of flowering plants in the family Ericaceae. <s> Nine of the species are endemic to Tasmania and the other two are endemic to the south-east of the Australian mainland.
simple: Richea is a genus of shrubs or trees in the family Ericaceae.

title: Micro black hole
complex: Micro black holes, also called quantum mechanical black holes or mini black holes, are hypothetical tiny black holes, for which quantum mechanical effects play an important role. <s> The concept that black holes may exist that are smaller than stellar mass was introduced in 1971 by Stephen Hawking.
simple: Micro black holes are very small black holes. <s> They may exist in nature as primordial black holes.

title: Fudge
complex: Fudge is a type of sugar candy that is made by mixing sugar, butter and milk, heating it to the soft-ball stage at 240 °F , and then beating the mixture while it cools so that it acquires a smooth, creamy consistency. <s> In texture, this crystalline candy falls in between fondants and hard caramels.
simple: Fudge is a sometimes cake-like candy that can be rich and can have the flavor of cocoa. <s> It is made by putting sugar, butter, milk, and chocolate and mixing them together.

title: Scion (automobile)
complex: Scion was marketed as a youth brand and was first introduced in March 2002, at the New York Auto Show. <s> There were just two concept vehicles, the bbX (which became the xB), and the ccX (which became the tC).
simple: Scion is marketed to young car buyers.

title: Sakurai, Nara
complex: Sakurai (桜井市 , Sakurai-shi ) is a city located in Nara Prefecture, Japan. <s> Sakurai is home to Ōmiwa Shrine, traditionally considered one of the oldest Shinto shrines in Japan dedicated to the god of sake. <s> Sake dealers across Japan often hang a wooden sugi ball, made at Ōmiwa Shrine, as a talisman to the god of sake. <s> It was featured in Yukio Mishima's novel "Runaway Horses".
simple: Sakurai (桜井市, Sakurai-shi) is a Japanese city in Nara Prefecture on the island of Honshū. <s> Sakurai is home to Ōmiwa Shrine. <s> Sakurai is part of Yukio Mishima's novel, "Runaway Horses".

title: Opel Signum
complex: The Opel Signum is a large family car that was engineered and manufactured by the German automaker Opel from 2003 to 2008. <s> It was almost exclusively sold in Europe. <s> In the United Kingdom, it was rebadged and sold under the Vauxhall Signum name. <s> The Opel Signum was largely based on the Opel Vectra, and used the long wheelbase version of the GM Epsilon platform, also used by the Opel Vectra Caravan.
simple: The Opel Signum is a automobile produced by Opel. <s> It was sold in the UK as the Vauxhall Signum.

title: United States Army Corps of Topographical Engineers
complex: The U.S. Army Corps of Topographical Engineers was a branch of the United States Army authorized on 4 July 1838. <s> It consisted only of officers who were handpicked from West Point and was used for mapping and the design and construction of federal civil works such as lighthouses and other coastal fortifications and navigational routes. <s> Members included such officers as George Meade, John C. Frémont and Stephen Long. <s> It was merged with the United States Army Corps of Engineers on 31 March 1863, at which point the Corps of Engineers also assumed the Lakes Survey for the Great Lakes. <s> In the mid-19th century, Corps of Engineers' officers ran Lighthouse Districts in tandem with U.S. Naval officers.
simple: The U.S. Army Corps of Topographical Engineers was established by the United States Congress in 1838. <s> They formed the Topographical Bureau as a branch of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. <s> It was made up of only officers who were hand-picked graduates of the United States Military Academy at West Point. <s> They designed lighthouses, mapped navigational routes and worked on many other federal projects. <s> Until they were merged with the Corps of Engineers in 1863, they surveyed and built roads bridges and forts for the Union Army during the Civil War.

title: Tomonobu Hayakawa
complex: Tomonobu Hayakawa (早川 知伸 , Hayakawa Tomonobu , born July 11, 1977) is a former Japanese football player.
simple: Tomonobu Hayakawa ( born 11 July 1977) is a Japanese professional athlete.

title: Glenmore, Wisconsin
complex: Glenmore is a town in Brown County in the U.S. state of Wisconsin. <s> The population was 1,135 at the 2010 census. <s> The unincorporated communities of Glenmore and Shirley are located in the town. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 1,187 people, 375 households, and 322 families residing in the town. <s> The population density was 36.3 people per square mile (14.0/km2).
simple: Glenmore is a town in Brown County of the state of Wisconsin in the United States. <s> Shirley can be found in Glenmore. <s> 1,187 people were living in Glenmore as of 2000.

title: Calymmian
complex: The Calymmian Period (from Greek κάλυμμα "(kálymma)", meaning "cover") is the first geologic period in the Mesoproterozoic Era and lasted from round 5 Mya to round 5 Mya (million years ago). <s> Instead of being based on stratigraphy, these dates are defined chronometrically. <s> The supercontinent Columbia broke up during the Calymmian some 1500 Mya.
simple: The Calymmian is the first geological period in the Mesoproterozoic. <s> The supercontinent Columbia broke up during the Calymmian about 1.5 billion years ago.

title: Samuel J. Jones
complex: Samuel Jefferson Jones (April 16, 1827 – December 10, 1883) was a pro-slavery settler who held the position of Douglas County sheriff in Kansas Territory from late 1855 until early 1857. <s> He helped found the territorial capital of Lecompton and played a prominent role in the "Bleeding Kansas" conflict. <s> In 1858, he moved to La Mesilla, New Mexico Territory. <s> In September of that year, he was appointed the collector of customs at Paso del Norte (now Ciudad Juárez). <s> In New Mexico, he was involved with the promotion of Mowry City. <s> When that settlement's prospects collapsed, he bought a ranch near La Mesilla and died there in 1883. <s> His tombstone was later returned to Lecompton in 2013.
simple: Samuel Jefferson Jones (April 16, 1827 – December 10, 1883) was a pro-slavery man who was the Douglas County sheriff in Kansas Territory from late 1855 until early 1857. <s> He helped create the territorial capital of Lecompton. <s> He was an important person in the "Bleeding Kansas" conflict. <s> In 1858, he moved to La Mesilla, New Mexico Territory. <s> In September 1858, he was chosen to be the collector of customs at Paso del Norte (now Ciudad Juárez). <s> In New Mexico, he was involved with the of Mowry City. <s> When that town's future failed, he bought a ranch near La Mesilla and died there in 1883. <s> His grave was later returned to Lecompton in 2013.

title: Pukkila
complex: Pukkila (] ) is a municipality of Finland. <s> It is located in the Uusimaa region and it is the smallest municipality in the region in relation to its population; the municipality has a population of and covers an area of km2 of which km2 is water.
simple: Pukkila is a municipality in Finland.

title: Muppet Babies (1984 TV series)
complex: Jim Henson's Muppet Babies, commonly known by the shortened title Muppet Babies, is an American animated television series that aired from September 15, 1984 to November 2, 1991 on CBS. <s> The show portrays childhood versions of the Muppets living together in a nursery under the care of a human woman identified only as Nanny (the whereabouts of their parents are never addressed), who appears in almost every episode, but her face is never visible; only the babies' view of her pink skirt, purple sweater, and distinctive green and white striped socks is shown. <s> The idea of presenting the Muppets as children first appeared in a dream sequence in "The Muppets Take Manhattan" (1984), released two months before "Muppet Babies" debuted, in which Miss Piggy imagined what it would be like if she and Kermit the Frog had grown up together. <s> "Muppet Babies" was produced by Jim Henson Productions and Marvel Productions.
simple: Muppet Babies is an American children's animated series produced by The Jim Henson Company and Nick Jr. <s> The concept of presenting familiar Muppet characters as babies was introduced in a sequence of "The Muppets Take Manhattan".

title: Molson Brewery
complex: The Molson Brewery was formed in 1786 in Montreal by the Molson family. <s> In 2005, Molson merged with US-based Coors to form Molson Coors Brewing Company, the world's seventh-largest brewery at that time.
simple: Molson is a Canadian brewery that was created in 1786 by the founder John Molson.

title: Dumiso Dabengwa
complex: Dumiso Dabengwa (6 December 1939 – 23 May 2019) was a Zimbabwean politician. <s> He served as the head of Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army (ZIPRA) intelligence during the Rhodesian Bush War. <s> From 1992 to 2000 he served in the government as Minister of Home Affairs, and in 1991 he was appointed to the chair of the Matabeleland Zambezi Water Project. <s> He was a candidate of ZAPU for President of Zimbabwe during the 2013 general election. <s> He moved out of ZANU-PF together with Benny Ncube, whom they had trained together during the armed struggle.
simple: Dumiso Dabengwa (December 6, 1939– 23 May 2019) was a Zimbabwean politician. <s> Dabengwa died on 23 May 2019 in Harare from liver disease at the age of 79. <s> He was the head of Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army (ZIPRA) intelligence during the Rhodesian Bush War. <s> He was Minister of Home Affairs from 1992 to 2000. <s> He was a candidate of ZAPU for President of Zimbabwe during the 2013 general election.

title: Jard-sur-Mer
complex: Jard-sur-Mer is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Jard-sur-Mer is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Söderhöjdens BK
complex: Söderhöjdens BK was a sports club in Stockholm, Sweden. <s> is played three seasons in the Swedish women's bandy top division.
simple: Söderhöjdens BK was a sports club in the town of Stockholm in Sweden. <s> The club played three seasons in the Swedish women's bandy top division.

title: Cape Floristic Region
complex: The Cape Floristic Region is a floristic region located near the southern tip of South Africa. <s> It is the only floristic region of the Cape (South African) Floristic Kingdom, and includes only one floristic province, known as the Cape Floristic Province. <s> The Cape Floristic Region, the smallest of the six recognised floral kingdoms of the world, is an area of extraordinarily high diversity and endemism, and is home to over 9,000 vascular plant species, of which 69 percent are endemic. <s> Much of this diversity is associated with the fynbos biome, a Mediterranean-type, fire-prone shrubland. <s> The economical worth of fynbos biodiversity, based on harvests of fynbos products (e.g. wildflowers) and eco-tourism, is estimated to be in the region of R77 million a year. <s> Thus, it is clear that the Cape Floristic Region has both economic and intrinsic biological value as a biodiversity hotspot.
simple: The Cape flower region is a nature area near the south end of South Africa. <s> Its formal title is the Cape (South Africa) Floristic Region. <s> The region is the smallest of the six "flower kingdoms" of the world, as recognised by Ronald Good. <s> The region has very high diversity. <s> There are more than 9,000 vascular plant species. <s> Much of this diversity is because of the fynbos, a Mediterranean-type shrubland that can easily be destroyed by wildfires. <s> The economic worth of the fynbos area may be about R77 million a year from harvests of products (like wildflowers) and from eco-tourism. <s> The Cape flower region has both economic and biological value.

title: Gun Hägglund
complex: Karin Gunvor Sjöblom Hägglund (2 March 1932 – 19 August 2011), better known as Gun Hägglund, was a Swedish television host and translator. <s> Hägglund was the first female television news anchor in Sweden, hosting the Swedish national evening news show "Aktuellt" in 1958. <s> She is sometimes credited as the first female television news reader in the world, but that claim is inaccurate as British "ITN" Midday News included female bulletin presenter Barbara Mandell in 1955 and "BBC" Regional news bulletin included Armine Sandford in 1957. <s> Gun Hägglund started her career at Swedish Radio in 1955 where she worked at the foreign news desk as a secretary and program announcer. <s> She moved on to Swedish Television in 1958 to become Sweden's first female news anchor in the national news show "Aktuellt", often accompanied by pioneer news anchor Olle Björklund. <s> In addition, Hägglund was a translator of foreign motion pictures and television series. <s> In an interview from 1966, Hägglund describes the rather complicated process of translating textual versions of the dialog in films and television programs into short subtitles of text at the bottom of the screen. <s> For the general public, Hägglund is probably best known for her participation in Swedish television's entertainment programs and daily shows such as "Halvsju" ("Half Past Six O'Clock"), "Razzel", "Träna med TV" ("Workout with TV"), and "Café Sundsvall". <s> Hägglund was married to news editor Karl-Axel Sjöblom (known as "KAS") with whom she co-hosted "Halvsju", one of the most popular television shows in Swedish history. <s> They were married until his death in 1982. <s> For 30 years, until 1997, Hägglund was closely involved in the "Svenska Cykelfrämjandet" ("National Association for Promotion of Cycling"), first as Secretary-General, and later Executive Chairman. <s> In that capacity, she published a number of books about cycling. <s> In 1986, Hägglund moved from the Swedish capital of Stockholm to the Baltic island of Gotland. <s> She died in Visby after a short illness in 2011.
simple: Karin Gunvor Sjöblom Hägglund (2 March 1932–19 August 2011) was Swedish television star. <s> She is better known as Gun Hägglund. <s> Hägglund presented the national news show Aktuellt. <s> Her career started in 1955 when she started working for the Swedish radio. <s> She was a secretary and program announcer. <s> She was the news presenter of Aktuellt in 1958. <s> In 1958, she moved to television shows and became the first female in Sweden to present the news. <s> She translated movies and TV shows. <s> She was married to the Swedish news editor Karl-Axel Sjöblom. <s> Her husband died in 1982. <s> For 30 years, until 1997, Hägglund was involved in the "Swedish National Association of Promotion of Cycling". <s> First she was Secretary-General and later Executive Chairman. <s> In that position, she published some books about cycling. <s> Hägglund was born in Örnsköldsvik, Sweden and died in Visby. <s> Hägglund died in 2011 after a short illness.

title: Alanganallur
complex: Alanganallur is a panchayat town in Madurai district in the state of Tamil Nadu, India. <s> It is headquarters for the Alanganallur taluka and revenue block. <s> Agriculture is carried out in about large area around this place. <s> Paddy, Sugar cane, Coconut and Plantain are the major crops. <s> There is a sugar factory located within 1 km from Alanganallur. <s> The Jallikattu (A way to find best Bull for Breed) ceremony is conducted here during the Pongal (harvest festival) season, to choose the best breed, which occurs during the middle of January (usually 14 January) and on the first day of Tamil month Thai. <s> Tourists all over from India, even from abroad visit here during this festival to watch Jallikattu. <s> Madurai is accessible within 16 km. <s> Alagar kovil is also close by, within 18 km. <s> The Thadakai Amman falls(Kutladampatti) are located near T. Mettupatti village. <s> Kodaikanal, Vaigai dam, Kumbakarai falls
simple: Alanganallur is a panchayat town in the district of Madurai in the state of Tamil Nadu, India. <s> This town is the headquarters of Alanganallur taluk and Alanganallur revenue block. <s> Agriculture is the main occupation in the town. <s> Alanganallur town is famous for the Jallikattu ceremony conducted throughout the four days of Pongal festival. <s> The district headquarters Madurai city is 16 km away from this town. <s> Alagar kovil is also near by, within 18 km. <s> Nearby places which attracts tourist are : The Thadakai Amman falls, Kodaikanal, Vaigai dam, Kumbakarai falls and Kutladampatti.

title: Saint-Genis-sur-Menthon

simple: Saint-Genis-sur-Menthon is a commune.

title: Pat Verbeek
complex: Patrick Martin Verbeek (born May 24, 1964) is a Canadian former professional ice hockey player and current assistant general manager for the Detroit Red Wings of the National Hockey League. <s> Verbeek played for five teams over a 20 year playing career, earning a Stanley Cup ring with the Dallas Stars in 1999. <s> His nickname, "The Little Ball of Hate", was given to him in 1995 by Glenn Healy after fellow New York Rangers teammate Ray Ferraro was tagged as the "Big Ball of Hate".
simple: Patrick "The Little Ball of Hate" Verbeek (born May 24, 1964 in Sarnia, Ontario) is a former Canadian NHL ice hockey right winger who played 21 seasons in the NHL. <s> He was given the nickname "The Little Ball of Hate" by Glenn Healy because teammate Ray Ferraro was nicknamed "Big Ball of Hate".

title: Snares penguin
complex: The Snares penguin ("Eudyptes robustus"), also known as the Snares crested penguin and the Snares Islands penguin, is a penguin from New Zealand. <s> The species breeds on The Snares, a group of islands off the southern coast of the South Island. <s> This is a medium-small, yellow-crested penguin, at a size of 50 – and a weight of 2.5 – . <s> It has dark blue-black upperparts and white underparts.
simple: The Snares penguin ("Eudyptes robustus"), is a crested penguin. <s> It is a penguin from New Zealand. <s> It breeds on The Snares, a small island group south of New Zealand's South Island. <s> It has a size of 50-70 cm and a weight of 2.5-4 kg.

title: Oklahoma City Blue
complex: The Oklahoma City Blue are an NBA G League team based in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, and the minor league affiliate of the Oklahoma City Thunder. <s> The franchise began as the Asheville Altitude in 2001, before moving to Tulsa, Oklahoma, in 2005 and becoming the Tulsa 66ers. <s> After nine seasons in Tulsa, the franchise moved to Oklahoma City in 2014 and were subsequently renamed the Oklahoma City Blue.
simple: The Oklahoma City Blue are an NBA Development League team based in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma, United States. <s> They were also known as the Asheville Altitude when they played in Asheville, North Carolina from 2001 until 2005 and as the Tulsa 66ers when the team played in Tulsa, Oklahoma from 2005 until 2014.

title: B. S. Abdur Rahman
complex: Buhari Syed Abdur Rahman (15 October 1927 – 7 January 2015) was an Indian Tamil serial entrepreneur, philanthropist and educationist. <s> He had a range of business interests in the UAE and India (in Tamil Nadu) including maritime shipping, real estate, insurance etc. <s> He founded numerous schools, colleges, hospitals and university. <s> He was one of the 24 Indians to feature in "The 500 Most Influential Muslims", an annual publication which ranks the most influential Muslims in the world. <s> Abdur Rahman was the Vice-Chairperson of Emirates Trading Agency (commonly known as ETA Star) and Ascon Group, a Dubai-based conglomerate from 1973 to 2015. <s> He is the founder of B. S. Abdur Rahman University (earlier named Crescent Engineering College), one of the first private owned engineering colleges in Chennai. <s> He was the Chairman of East Coast Constructions and Industries, West Asia Exports and Imports, West Asia Maritime, Buhari Group, Amana Investments in Hong Kong and Transcar India. <s> He was also the Vice-Chairman of Coal & Oil and Coastal Energy. <s> He founded India's first stand-alone health insurer Star Health and Allied Insurance with the help of Oman Insurance Company. <s> East Coast Constructions and Industries, founded in 1962, built several landmarks in Chennai including Gemini Flyover, Kodambakkam Flyover, Chepauk Stadium, Chennai Citi Centre, Government General Hospital, Valluvar Kottam, the Marina Lighthouse and the Apollo Hospital complex in Greams Road. <s> He died on 7 January 2015 at the age of 87. <s> B. S. Abdur Rahman was born in Kilakarai, Tamil Nadu, India, in a middle-class Marakkar family, the son of Bhukari Aalim. <s> His father was a prominent Pearl Trader in South Asia.
simple: Buhari Syed Abdur Rahman (15 October 1927 – 7 January 2015) was an Indian serial entrepreneur, philanthropist and educator. <s> He had a range of business interests in the UAE and India. <s> He was one of the 24 Indians to feature in "The 500 Most Influential Muslims". <s> Rahman was the Vice-chairman of Emirates Trading Agency from 1973 to 2015. <s> He was the founder of B. S. Abdur Rahman University. <s> Rahman died in Chennai, India, aged 87. <s> Rahman was born in Kilakarai, Madras State, British India.

title: Tanah Merah MRT station
complex: Tanah Merah MRT station (EW4/CG) is an above-ground Mass Rapid Transit (MRT) interchange station located in Bedok, Singapore. <s> Other than the main service (EW4), Tanah Merah station is also the terminus for the Changi Airport branch line (CG) which is also part of the East West Line. <s> Since 2017, Tanah Merah station is officially assigned the station code "CG", in addition to the station code "EW4" which the station originally had, to differentiate the operations of the main service and the Changi Airport branch line, albeit that it is not displayed on the signage of the station. <s> The station was originally not going to be open with the rest of the East West Line in between 1988 and 1989 as there were only private houses surrounding it, but increasing pressure from Members of Parliament and the public forced SMRT to open this station. <s> When it opened, the demand was extremely stagnant, with only private houses, Bedok South housing estates and Fengshan housing estates to cater to. <s> The demand increased when Singapore Expo and the MRT line to Changi Airport opened. <s> The addition of a new platform was announced by Land Transport Authority on 25 August 2014 to allow trains to arrive and depart at shorter intervals and an improvement in waiting times with the enhancements. <s> On 26 October 2016, the Land Transport Authority awarded the civil contract to Lum Chang Building Contractors Pte. Ltd. to build a new platform at Tanah Merah station and viaducts for a contract sum of S$325 million. <s> In addition to the new platforms, the existing East West Line tracks will be extended to connect the line to the new four-in-one East Coast Integrated Depot at Changi, as well as the new underpass to be constructed, which will be Exit C to Tanah Merah Kechil Avenue and Exit D to The Glades Condominium. <s> In order to facilitate construction, the road at New Upper Changi Road will have to be realigned and the Katong Flower Shop was closed down. <s> When completed in 2024, it will be the second station to have triple island platforms after Jurong East.
simple: Tanah Merah Station (EW4/CG) is an MRT Station in Bedok, Singapore. <s> Tanah Merah MRT is also officially assigned the station code "CG", to differentiate the station's operations on the Main Line and the Changi Airport Branch Line. <s> The station was originally not going to be open with the rest of the East West Line in between 1988 and 1989 as there were only private houses surrounding it, but increasing pressure from Members of Parliament and the public forced SMRT to open this station. <s> When it opened on 4 November 1989, the demand was extremely stagnant, with only private houses, Bedok South housing estates and Fengshan housing estates to cater to. <s> The demand increased when Singapore Expo and the MRT line to Changi Airport opened. <s> The addition of a new platform was announced by Land Transport Authority on 25 August 2014 to allow trains to arrive and depart at shorter intervals and an improvement in waiting times with the enhancements. <s> On 26 October 2016, the Land Transport Authority awarded the civil contract to Lum Chang Building Contractors Pte. Ltd. to build a new platform at Tanah Merah Station and viaducts for a contract sum of S$325 million. <s> In addition to the new platforms, the existing East-West Line tracks will be extended to connect the line to the new four-in-one East Coast Integrated Depot at Changi. <s> When completed in 2024, it will be the second station to have triple island platforms after Jurong East.

title: Be Good to Me
complex: "Be Good to Me" is a song recorded by American recording artist Ashley Tisdale from her debut album, "Headstrong" (2007). <s> It was written by Kara DioGuardi, Joacim Persson and Niclas Molinder, and produced by Twin. <s> The song was released in the US as the album's lead single on December 26, 2006 and in South America in January 2007. <s> The album version features uncredited rap vocals by Swedish musician David Jassy.
simple: "Be Good to Me" is a song on Ashley Tisdale's first album, "Headstrong". <s> "Be Good to Me" was the first song released off the album. <s> It was released in the United States on December 25, 2006 and in South America in January 2007. <s> The album version has rap vocals by David Jassy.

title: Robert M. Pirsig
complex: Robert Maynard Pirsig ( ; September 6, 1928 – April 24, 2017) was an American writer and philosopher. <s> He was the author of the philosophical novels "Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance: An Inquiry into Values" (1974) and "" (1991). <s> Pirsig was born on September 6, 1928, in Minneapolis, Minnesota, the son of Harriet Marie Sjobeck and Maynard Pirsig. <s> He was of German and Swedish descent. <s> His father was a University of Minnesota Law School (UMLS) graduate who started teaching at the school in 1934. <s> The elder Pirsig served as the law school dean from 1948 to 1955, and retired from teaching at UMLS in 1970. <s> He resumed his career as a professor at the William Mitchell College of Law, where he remained until his final retirement in 1993. <s> Pirsig died aged 88, at his home in South Berwick, Maine, on April 24, 2017, after a period of failing health.
simple: Robert Maynard Pirsig (September 6, 1928 – April 24, 2017) was an American writer and philosopher. <s> They include: "" (1974) and "" (1991). <s> Pirsig was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota. <s> He died on April 24, 2017 at his home in South Berwick, Maine from a long-illness, aged 88.

title: Serbia at the 2018 Winter Paralympics
complex: Serbia sent competitors to the 2018 Winter Paralympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea. <s> One person on the team is para-Nordic skier Milos Zaric. <s> In addition to para-Nordic skier, Zaric is also a para-athlete. <s> He is the world champion in the men's F55 javelin. <s> The table below contains the list of members of people (called "Team Serbia") that participated in the 2018 Games. <s> 15 National Paralympic Committees and the International Wheelchair and Amputee Sports Federation signed a letter expressing support for the National Paralympic Committee of Russia in August 2017. <s> The countries included Armenia, Belarus, Bulgaria, Vietnam, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, China, Laos, Moldova, Mongolia, Serbia, Tajikistan, Montenegro, and South Korea. <s> They asked the IPC Governing Board to consider letting Russia compete at the 2018 Winter Paralympics. <s> The letter was signed weeks before the IPC Governing Board met in Abu Dhabi. <s> In September 2017, this decision was reviewed and upheld. <s> The International Paralympic Committee (IPC) still had concerns about doping in Russian sport. <s> All the conditions the IPC required of the Russians were not met. <s> Serbia first competed at the Winter Paralympics in 2010, and had yet to win a medal going into the 2018 edition of the Games. <s> Serbia was represented by Jugoslav Milosevic in 2014. <s> He competed in para-alpine skiing. <s> The upper limb amputee competed in the slalom and giant slalom standing events. <s> Milos Zaric competes in two sports: para-athletics and para-Nordic skiing. <s> In 2017, he won a gold medal at the 2017 IPC Athletics World Championships in the men's F55 javelin. <s> A few months later, he competed in para-Nordic skiing at the World Cup in Oberried, Germany. <s> The World Cup was the first time he was part of Team Serbia at an international sporting competition. <s> On 12 March, the 15 km race takes place, with standing and vision impaired women starting at 10:00 PM. <s> Thee sprint classic qualification takes place on 14 March from 10:00 AM - 11:25 AM for both men and women in all classes. <s> It is followed in the afternoon by the semifinals and finals. <s> The classic race takes place on 17 March. <s> The standing and visually impaired women's race takes place from 10:00 AM - 12:30.

title: Kalayaan, Palawan
complex: President Ferdinand E. Marcos created the Municipality of Kalayaan by signing "Presidential Decree 1596" into law on June 11, 1978. <s> This established what the document described as "a distinct and separate municipality of the Province of Palawan".
simple: In 1978, the Presidential Decree No. 1596 established the municipality as part of Palawan.

title: Jimmy Roy
complex: Jimmy Roy (born September 22, 1975 in Sioux Lookout, Ontario) was a Canadian ice hockey player for the Manitoba Moose of the International Hockey League and American Hockey League from 1997 to 2006. <s> Later in his career he played for Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga from 2006-2011. <s> He is currently Director of Player Development for the Winnipeg Jets of the National Hockey League. <s> Roy was drafted 254th overall by the Dallas Stars in the 1994 NHL Entry Draft but never played in the National Hockey League. <s> After spending two years at Michigan Technological University he signed with the Manitoba Moose in 1997. <s> Roy spent nine seasons with the Manitoba Moose, the first four in the International Hockey League and the rest in the American Hockey League after the Moose became members of the league when the IHL folded. <s> He holds different team records like games played and most goals. <s> For the 2006–07 season Roy signed with the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> In Iserlohn he developed to a key player, known for his leading quality on and off the ice. <s> He also helped the club to sign some former Moose players like Ryan Ready and Pat Kavanagh. <s> Roy extended his contract after his first season in Germany for two years. <s> On Christmas Day 2008 the Roosters announced again that Roy has signed for two more years. <s> As a Rooster he usually plays on a line with Ryan Ready. <s> In the 2007–08 season their center was Pat Kavanagh, the next season Bob Wren was their line mate. <s> In 2011, he retired as a player to take the position of Director of Player Development in the Winnipeg Jets organization.
simple: Jimmy Roy (born September 22, 1975 in Sioux Lookout, Ontario) is a Canadian ice hockey player currently playing for the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> Roy was drafted 254th overall by the Dallas Stars in the 1994 NHL Entry Draft but never played in the National Hockey League. <s> After spending two years at Michigan Technological University he signed with the Manitoba Moose in 1997. <s> Roy spent nine seasons with the Manitoba Moose, the first four in the International Hockey League and the rest in the American Hockey League after the Moose became members of the league when the IHL folded. <s> He holds different team records like games played and most goals. <s> For the 2006–07 season Roy signed with the Iserlohn Roosters of the Deutsche Eishockey Liga. <s> In Iserlohn he developed to a key player, known for his leading quality on and off the ice. <s> He also helped the club to sign some former Moose players like Ryan Ready and Pat Kavanagh. <s> Roy extended his contract after his first season in Germany for two years. <s> On Christmas Day 2008 the Roosters announced again that Roy has signed for two more years. <s> As a Rooster he usually plays on a line with Ryan Ready. <s> In the 2007–08 season their center was Pat Kavanagh, the next season Bob Wren was their linemate.

title: Marie-Antoine Carême
complex: Marie Antoine (Antonin) Carême (] ; 8 June 178412 January 1833) was a French chef and an early practitioner and exponent of the elaborate style of cooking known as "grande cuisine", the "high art" of French cooking: a grandiose style of cookery favoured by both international royalty and by the newly rich of Paris. <s> Carême is often considered one of the first internationally renowned celebrity chefs. <s> Abandoned by his parents in Paris in 1794 at the height of the French Revolution, he worked as a kitchen boy at a cheap Parisian chophouse in exchange for room and board. <s> In 1798, he was formally apprenticed to Sylvain Bailly, a famous "pâtissier" with a shop near the Palais-Royal. <s> The post-revolutionary Palais-Royal was a high profile, fashionable neighborhood filled with vibrant life and bustling crowds. <s> Bailly recognized his talent and ambition. <s> By the time he was prepared to leave Bailly, he could stipulate that he should be free to leave his new employer when a better offer came along. <s> Carême opened his own shop, the "Pâtisserie de la rue de la Paix", which he maintained until 1813. <s> Carême gained fame in Paris for his "pièces montées", elaborate constructions used as centerpieces, which Bailly had displayed in the pâtisserie window. <s> He made these confections, which were sometimes several feet high, entirely out of foodstuffs such as sugar, marzipan, and pastry. <s> He modeled them on temples, pyramids, and ancient ruins, taking ideas from architectural history books which he studied at the nearby Bibliothèque Nationale, thanks to the enlightened attitude of his first employer Bailly. <s> He is credited with the inventions of "gros nougats" and "grosses meringues", "croquantes", made of almonds and honey, and "solilemmes". <s> He did freelance work creating pieces principally for the French diplomat and gourmand Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord, but also other members of Parisian high society, including Napoleon. <s> While working on his confections at many private kitchens, he quickly extended his culinary skills to main courses. <s> Napoleon was famously indifferent to food, but he understood the importance of social relations in the world of diplomacy. <s> In 1804, he gave money to Talleyrand to purchase Château de Valençay, a large estate outside Paris. <s> The château was intended to act as a kind of diplomatic gathering place. <s> When Talleyrand moved there, he took Carême with him. <s> Carême was set a test by Talleyrand: to create a whole year’s worth of menus, without repetition, and using only seasonal produce. <s> Carême passed the test and completed his training in Talleyrand's kitchens. <s> After the fall of Napoleon, Carême went to London for a time and served as "chef de cuisine" to the Prince Regent, later George IV. <s> Returning to the continent, he accepted the invitation of Tsar Alexander I to come to St. Petersburg, but stayed so briefly that he prepared not even a single meal for the Tsar. <s> Upon returning to Paris, he became chef to banker James Mayer Rothschild. <s> Carême died in his Paris house on the Rue Neuve Saint Roche at the age of 48, due perhaps to many years inhaling the toxic fumes of the coal burning stoves over which he cooked. <s> He is remembered as the founder of the haute cuisine concept and is interred in the Montmartre Cemetery in Paris. <s> In his first major position, Carême worked as "chef de cuisine" to Talleyrand, who actively encouraged Carême in the development of a new refined food style using herbs, fresh vegetables, and simplified sauces with few ingredients. <s> Talleyrand became a famous host during the Congress of Vienna—by the time the congress disbanded, not only the map of Europe but also the culinary tastes of its upper classes had been thoroughly revised. <s> Carême's impact on culinary matters ranged from trivial to theoretical. <s> He is credited with creating the standard chef's hat, the "toque", he designed new sauces and dishes, and he published a classification of all sauces into groups based on four mother sauces. <s> He is also frequently credited with replacing the practice of "service à la française" (serving all dishes at once) with "service à la russe" (serving each dish in the order printed on the menu) after he returned from service in the Russian court, but others say he was a diehard supporter of "service à la française".
simple: Marie Antoine (Antonin) Carême (8 June 1784 – 12 January 1833), was a French chef and author. <s> He is well known for greatly simplifying and writing about the style of cooking known as "haute cuisine", the high art of French cooking. <s> He was known as "chef of kings and king of chefs", because he cooked for royalty, and is often thought of as the first celebrity chef. <s> Carême was born Paris, but was abandoned in 1792 because his parents were very poor. <s> He worked as a kitchen boy at a cheap Paris cafe in exchange for a room and food. <s> In 1798, he was apprenticed to Sylvain Bailly, a famous "pâtissier" (cake baker) with a shop near the Palais-Royal. <s> Carême gained fame in Paris for his cake centrepieces, which Bailly put in the pâtisserie window. <s> The centerpieces were sometimes several feet high, and were only made out of foodstuffs such as sugar, marzipan, and pastry. <s> He modelled them on temples, pyramids, and ancient ruins which he read about in the books he studied at the French national library (Bibliothéque Nationale). <s> Carême also worked for other people, for example the French diplomat and gourmand Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-Périgord, and other members of Parisian high society, including Napoleon. <s> When he worked in the private kitchens he quickly learned about main courses. <s> Napoleon was not interested in having fancy food, but he knew of social contacts that were important for diplomats. <s> In 1804, he gave Talleyrand money to buy Château de Valençay. <s> When Talleyrand moved there, he took Carême with him. <s> Carême was set a test by Talleyrand: he had to create a whole year’s worth of menus, without repeating them, and use only food that was in season. <s> Carême passed the test and finished his training in Talleyrand's kitchens. <s> When Napoléon was defeated Carême went to London for a time and served as "chef de cuisine" to the Prince Regent, later George IV. <s> He returned to Europe to work for Czar Alexander I in St. Petersburg, before returning to Paris, where he was chef to banker James Mayer Rothschild. <s> He died in Paris at the age of 48, and is buried in the Cimetière de Montmartre in Montmartre. <s> Talleyrand encouraged Carême to start a new refined style of eating. <s> Carême's is said to have started "service à la russe" (serving each course in the order printed on the menu) instead of "service à la française" (serving all dishes at once)

title: Arena da Baixada
complex: Arena Joaquim Américo Guimarães is the home stadium of Club Athletico Paranaense. <s> It is located in Curitiba, the state capital of Paraná, Brazil. <s> Known as Arena da Baixada, the football stadium was the first in Brazil to sell its naming rights. <s> It was known as "Kyocera Arena" between 2005 and 1 April 2008. <s> Additionally, the stadium is perhaps best known for being the first retractable roof stadium in South America. <s> With Curitiba selected as one of the host cities of World Cup 2014, the arena between 2012 and 2014 was rebuilt. <s> Its capacity was expanded to 42,372 seats. <s> The stadium was built at the previous location of a Brazilian Army powder depot. <s> In 1934, the stadium was renamed Estádio Joaquim Américo Guimarães. <s> In the 1970s, the original stadium was closed down. <s> After being reopened in 1984 and operating for some years, the old stadium building was demolished on March 26, 1997, right after a construction project of a new arena was announced. <s> In June 1999, the new stadium was built. <s> In 2005, the stadium was renamed "Kyocera Arena", after the Japanese company Kyocera purchased the naming rights. <s> The inaugural match of the old stadium was played on 6 September 1914, when Flamengo beat Internacional 7–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium was scored by Flamengo's Arnaldo. <s> The inaugural match of the new building was played on 24 June 1999, when Athletico Paranaense beat Cerro Porteño of Paraguay 2–1. <s> The first goal of the stadium after its reinauguration was scored by Athletico's Lucas. <s> The stadium's attendance record currently stands at 40.263, set on 12 December 2018 when Athletico defeated Junior Barranquilla on penalties, for the 2018 Sudamericana championship. <s> Although the stadium was not the venue of the 1950 FIFA World Cup, the Estádio Vila Capanema was the venue for Curitiba as a host city of the event. <s> The contract with Kyocera that gave the company naming rights expired in early 2008. <s> It was not renewed, and no new partnership was announced. <s> The stadium went back to its old name, "Arena da Baixada".

title: Pyrenees
complex: The Pyrenees ( ; ] ; ] ; ; ] ; ; ] ) is a range of mountains in southwest Europe that forms a natural border between Spain and France. <s> Reaching a height of 3404 m altitude at the peak of Aneto, the range separates the Iberian Peninsula from the rest of continental Europe, and extends for about 491 km from the Bay of Biscay (Cap Higuer) to the Mediterranean Sea (Cap de Creus).
simple: The Pyrenees (; ; ; ; ; ) are a range of mountains in southwest Europe that form a natural border between France and Spain.

title: David H. Hubel
complex: David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Canadian American neurophysiologist noted for his studies of the structure and function of the visual cortex. <s> He was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (shared with Roger W. Sperry), for their discoveries concerning information processing in the visual system. <s> For much of his career, Hubel was the John Franklin Enders University Professor of Neurobiology at Harvard Medical School. <s> In 1978, Hubel and Wiesel were awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University. <s> The Hubel and Wiesel experiments greatly expanded the scientific knowledge of sensory processing. <s> The partnership lasted over twenty years and became known as one of the most prominent research pairings in science. <s> In one experiment, done in 1959, they inserted a microelectrode into the primary visual cortex of an anesthetized cat. <s> They then projected patterns of light and dark on a screen in front of the cat. <s> They found that some neurons fired rapidly when presented with lines at one angle, while others responded best to another angle. <s> Some of these neurons responded to light patterns and dark patterns differently. <s> Hubel and Wiesel called these neurons simple cells." <s> Still other neurons, which they termed complex cells, detected edges regardless of where they were placed in the receptive field of the neuron and could preferentially detect motion in certain directions. <s> These studies showed how the visual system constructs complex representations of visual information from simple stimulus features. <s> Hubel and Wiesel received the Nobel Prize for two major contributions: firstly, their work on development of the visual system, which involved a description of ocular dominance columns in the 1960s and 1970s; and secondly, their work establishing a foundation for visual neurophysiology, describing how signals from the eye are processed by visual parcels in the neo-cortex to generate edge detectors, motion detectors, stereoscopic depth detectors and color detectors, building blocks of the visual scene. <s> By depriving kittens from using one eye, they showed that columns in the primary visual cortex receiving inputs from the other eye took over the areas that would normally receive input from the deprived eye. <s> This has important implications for the understanding of deprivation amblyopia, a type of visual loss due to unilateral visual deprivation during the so-called critical period. <s> These kittens also did not develop areas receiving input from both eyes, a feature needed for binocular vision. <s> Hubel and Wiesel's experiments showed that the ocular dominance develops irreversibly early in childhood development. <s> These studies opened the door for the understanding and treatment of childhood cataracts and strabismus. <s> They were also important in the study of cortical plasticity. <s> Hubel married Ruth Izzard in 1953; she died February 17, 2013. <s> The couple had three sons and four grandchildren. <s> He died in Lincoln, Massachusetts from kidney failure on September 22, 2013 at the age of 87.
simple: David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Canadian neurophysiologist noted for his studies of the structure and function of the visual cortex. <s> David Hunter Hubel (February 27, 1926 – September 22, 2013) was a Professor of Neurobiology Emeritus at Harvard Medical School. <s> He was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (shared with Roger W. Sperry), for their discoveries concerning information processing in the visual system. <s> Hubel was co-recipient with Torsten Wiesel of the 1981 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries about information processing in the visual system. <s> The prize was shared with Roger Sperry for his independent research on the cerebral hemispheres. <s> For much of his career, Hubel was the John Franklin Enders University Professor of Neurobiology at Harvard Medical School. <s> In 1978, Hubel and Wiesel were awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University. <s> In one experiment, done in 1959, they inserted a microelectrode into the primary visual cortex of an anesthetized cat. <s> They then projected patterns of light and dark on a screen in front of the cat. <s> They found that some neurons fired rapidly when presented with lines at one angle, while others responded best to another angle. <s> Some of these neurons responded differently to light patterns than to dark patterns. <s> Hubel and Wiesel called these neurons 'simple cells'. <s> Still other neurons, which they called 'complex cells', detected edges regardless of how they were placed in the visual field, and could detect motion in certain directions. <s> These studies showed how the visual system constructs complex pictures of visual information from simple stimulus features. <s> By depriving kittens from using one eye, they showed that columns in the primary visual cortex receiving inputs from the other eye took over the areas that would normally receive input from the deprived eye. <s> These kittens did not develop areas receiving input from both eyes, a feature needed for binocular vision. <s> Hubel and Wiesel's experiments showed that ocular dominance (dominance of one eye is normal) develops early in childhood development, and cannot be reversed. <s> They did important work in the study of cortical plasticity (flexibility). <s> Hubel died of renal failure.

title: Ettore Boiardi
complex: Ettore Boiardi (October 22, 1897 – June 21, 1985), better known by an Anglicized version of his name, Hector Boyardee, was an Italian-American chef, famous for his brand of food products, named Chef Boyardee. <s> Boiardi was born in Piacenza, Italy, in 1897, to Giuseppe and Maria Maffi Boiardi. <s> On May 9, 1914, at the age of 16, he arrived at Ellis Island aboard "La Lorraine", a ship of French registration. <s> Boiardi died of natural causes on June 21, 1985, at age 87 in his home of Parma, Ohio, survived by his wife Helen and son Mario. <s> He had two grandchildren.
simple: Ettore "Hector" Boiardi (October 22, 1897 – June 21, 1985) was an Italian-American chef. <s> He was famous for his brand of food products, named "Chef Boyardee". <s> Boiardi was born in Piacenza, Italy. <s> Boiardi was married to Helen Wroblewski from 1923 until his death in 1985. <s> He had a son, Mario Boiardi. <s> Boiardi died on June 21, 1985 in Parma, Ohio from natural causes, aged 87.

title: Shameem Ahsan
complex: Shameem Ahsan is a Bangladeshi Business leader, Venture capital investor & ICT entrepreneur. <s> He is the Chairman of eGeneration Limited and the past President of Bangladesh Association of Software and Information Services (BASIS). <s> He is the Director of Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industries (FBCCI) and state owned Agrani Bank Limited. <s> As businessman he has played a pivotal role in the implementation of all the major policy changes related to the ICT sector in last one decade. <s> Born in Dhaka, Shameem Ahsan graduated from University of Central Oklahoma. <s> Shameem Ahsan is a technology entrepreneur and the co-founder of Baagdoom.com (previously Akhoni.com Ltd.), eGeneration Ltd., Benchmark-eGeneration Ltd., and Element 5 Ltd. <s> Ahsan is a member of the Prime Minister's Digital Bangladesh Task Force, Government of Bangladesh, which is the highest policy-making body to monitor and implement the vision of building Digital Bangladesh. <s> Ahsan, General Partner of FENOX Venture Capital and The Chairman of Venture Capital and Private Equity Association of Bangladesh (VCPEAB). <s> He is currently the Chairman of BASIS Presidents' Forum and Chairman of Venture Capital & Private Equity Association of Bangladesh (VCPEAB). <s> He is the founder and President of TiE Dhaka. <s> He is also a Director of Rajshahi Kings, a popular T20 cricket team of Bangladesh Premier League (BPL), which reached the final of BPL’2016 by participating for the first time. <s> Ahsan is married to Syeda Kamrun Ahmed, a Women Business Leader and CEO of Bagdoom.com. <s> They have one daughter.

title: Finney County, Kansas
complex: Finney County (county code FI) is a county located in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the county population was 36,776. <s> Its county seat and most populous city is Garden City. <s> Finney County began about 1880 as Buffalo County and Sequoyah County, named after Sequoyah, the Cherokee Indian responsible for the development of the Cherokee alphabet. <s> The two counties were renamed Finney County in honor of then Lieutenant Governor David Wesley Finney. <s> The county grew to the current shape after Garfield County was annexed to it in 1893. <s> The northeast block, separate from the otherwise rectangular area, represents what at one time was Garfield County, which is now occupied partially by the Garfield Township. <s> Charles "Buffalo" Jones, a co-founder of Garden City, was the first member of the Kansas House of Representatives from Finney County. <s> He was known for his efforts to preserve the buffalo from extinction. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 1303 sqmi , of which 1302 sqmi is land and 0.7 sqmi (0.05%) is water. <s> It is the second-largest county in Kansas by area. <s> Finney County is included in the Garden City, KS Micropolitan Statistical Area. <s> As of the 2010 census there were 36,776 people, 12,359 households and 8,903 families residing in the county. <s> The racial makeup of the county was 77.0% White, 2.3% Black or African American, 0.9% Native American, 3.4% Asian, 0.0% Pacific Islander, 13.6% from other races, and 2.9% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 46.7% of the population. <s> Finney County has primarily supported Republican presidential candidates throughout its history. <s> In only six elections from 1888 to the present has the county not backed the Republican candidate, the last of these being in 1976 when Jimmy Carter won the county by only 102 votes.
simple: Finney County (county code FI) is a county in the U.S. state of Kansas. <s> In 2010, 36,776 people lived there. <s> Its county seat is Garden City. <s> Finney County was created around 1880. <s> It was called Buffalo County and Sequoyah County. <s> They were named after Sequoyah, the Cherokee Indian responsible for the creation of the Cherokee alphabet. <s> The two counties were renamed Finney County. <s> It was named after Lieutenant Governor David Wesley Finney. <s> Charles "Buffalo" Jones was the first member of the Kansas House of Representatives from Finney County. <s> He tried to stop the buffalo from extinction. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau says that the county has a total area of 1303 sqmi. <s> Of that, 1302 sqmi is land and 0.7 sqmi (0.05%) is water. <s> It is the second-largest county in Kansas by area. <s> Finney County is included in the Garden City, KS Micropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The 2010 census says that there were 36,776 people, 12,359 households and 8,903 families living in Finney County. <s> Finney County has often supported Republican presidential candidates. <s> This was when Jimmy Carter won the county by only 102 votes.

title: Gini coefficient
complex: In economics, the Gini coefficient , sometimes called Gini index, or Gini ratio, is a measure of statistical dispersion intended to represent the income or wealth distribution of a nation's residents, and is the most commonly used measurement of inequality. <s> It was developed by the Italian statistician and sociologist Corrado Gini and published in his 1912 paper "Variability and Mutability" . <s> The table below presents the estimated world income Gini coefficients over the last 200 years, as calculated by Milanovic. <s> More detailed data from similar sources plots a continuous decline since 1988.

title: Red Lake County, Minnesota

title: Håkan Carlqvist
complex: Håkan Carlqvist (15 January 1954 – 6 July 2017) was a Swedish professional motocross racer. <s> Carlqvist was a two-time world champion who was known for his fierce competitiveness. <s> Born in the Järfälla Municipality near Stockholm, Sweden, Carlqvist began competing in the world championships as a privateer riding an Ossa. <s> He won the F.I.M. 250cc Motocross World Championship in 1979 as a member of the Husqvarna factory racing team. <s> In 1980, he switched to Yamaha to contest the 500cc motocross world championship. <s> He finished 3rd in 1981 and 7th in 1982. <s> In 1983, he battled against Honda teammates André Malherbe and Graham Noyce to claim the 500cc world championship, on a Yamaha. <s> In 1984, an injury stopped Carlqvist from contesting the title again. <s> He raced for Yamaha until end of 1986. <s> He continued the 500 GPs in 1987 and 1988 with a privateer Kawasaki KX500. <s> His last Grand Prix victory was the Belgian Grand Prix at Namur in 1988. <s> During this race, he stunned the spectators by stopping before the end of the 2nd moto to drink a beer, while leading the race by somewhat 50 seconds, and going back into the race to win it. <s> Carlqvist died on 6 July 2017 from the effects of a brain hemorrhage he suffered the previous day.
simple: Håkan Carlqvist (15 January 1954 – 7 July 2017) was a Swedish professional motocross racer. <s> He was born near Stockholm, Sweden. <s> Carlqvist won the F.I.M. 250cc Motocross World Championship in 1979 as a member of the Husqvarna factory racing team. <s> In 1980, he switched to Yamaha to contest the 500cc motocross world championship. <s> He finished 3rd in 1981 and 1982. <s> In 1983, he battled against Honda teammates André Malherbe and Graham Noyce to claim the 500cc world championship, on a Yamaha. <s> In 1984, an injury stopped Carlqvist from contesting the title again. <s> He raced for Yamaha until end of 1986. <s> Carlqvist died in Stockholm on 7 July 2017 of a heart attack at the age of 63.

title: Angular diameter
complex: The angular diameter, angular size, apparent diameter, or apparent size is an angular measurement describing how large a sphere or circle appears from a given point of view. <s> In the vision sciences, it is called the visual angle, and in optics, it is the angular aperture (of a lens).
simple: Angular size is a measurement of how large or small something is using rotational measurement.

complex: Jean Sorel (] ; born 25 September 1934) is a French actor. <s> Born Jean Bernard de Chieusses de Combaud de Roquebrune, he worked extensively in European cinema during the 1960s and 1970s with directors such as Luis Buñuel and Luchino Visconti. <s> However, since 1980 he has worked mostly in television. <s> He was married to Italian actress Anna Maria Ferrero from 1962 until her death in 2018.

title: Nubia
complex: Around AD 350, the area was invaded by the Kingdom of Aksum and the Meroitic kingdom collapsed. <s> Eventually, three smaller Christian kingdoms replaced it: northernmost was Nobatia between the first and second cataract of the Nile River, with its capital at Pachoras (modern-day Faras); in the middle was Makuria, with its capital at Old Dongola; and southernmost was Alodia, with its capital at Soba (near Khartoum).
simple: Their true decline was around 350 AD, when the kingdom of Axum invaded and broke up the culture once again.

title: Gravitropism
complex: Gravitropism (also known as geotropism) is a coordinated process of differential growth by a plant or fungus in response to gravity pulling on it. <s> Gravity can be either "artificial gravity" or natural gravity. <s> It is a general feature of all higher and many lower plants as well as other organisms. <s> Charles Darwin was one of the first to scientifically document that roots show "positive gravitropism" and stems show "negative gravitropism". <s> That is, roots grow in the direction of gravitational pull (i.e., downward) and stems grow in the opposite direction (i.e., upwards).
simple: Gravitropism (also known as Geotropism) is a turning or growth movement by a plant, fungus, or animal in response to gravity. <s> It is a general feature of all higher and many lower plants and also in other organisms. <s> Charles Darwin was one of the first people to say that roots grow downward and stems grow upward in response to gravity.

title: Capparis decidua
complex: Capparis decidua is commonly known as karira, is a useful plant in its marginal habitat. <s> Its spicy fruits are used for preparing vegetables, curry and fine pickles and can attract helpful insectivores; the plant also is used in folk medicine and herbalism. <s> It can be used in landscape gardening, afforestation and reforestation in semidesert and desert areas; it provides assistance against soil erosion. <s> It is a small much branched tree or shrub of arid regions in Africa, Middle East and southern Asia, including the Thar desertears a mass of slender, leafless branches, the small caducous leaves being found only on young shoots. <s> It rarely exceeds a height of 5 meters (15 feet).
simple: Capparis decidua is commonly known as karir, kair, kirir, karril, etc. <s> It is either a small tree with many branches or a shrub of the Thar desert and other hot and dry regions in southern Asia. <s> It has a lot of thin, leafless branches, the small leaves being found only on young shoots. <s> It rarely grows above a height of 5 meters (15 feet).

title: List of North Carolina hurricanes (1980–1999)
complex: The list of North Carolina hurricanes from 1980 to 1999 encompasses approximately 68 tropical or subtropical cyclones that affected the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> Collectively, cyclones in North Carolina during the time period resulted in around $10 billion in damage (2007 USD), primarily from hurricanes Fran and Floyd. <s> Additionally, tropical cyclones in North Carolina were responsible for about 56 direct fatalities and at least 47 indirect casualties during the period. <s> Eight cyclones affected the state in the 1985 season, which was the year with the most tropical cyclones impacting the state. <s> Every year included at least one tropical cyclone affecting the state. <s> All but two storms were North Atlantic hurricanes; the exceptions were Eastern Pacific hurricanes Tico in 1983 and Roslyn in 1986. <s> The strongest hurricane to hit the state during the time period was Hurricane Fran in 1996, which struck near Wilmington as a Category 3 hurricane on the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale; Hurricane Emily in 1993 brushed the Outer Banks also as a Category 3 hurricane. <s> The deadliest hurricane during the period was Hurricane Floyd in 1999, which caused 35 fatalities and record-breaking flooding in the eastern portion of the state.
simple: The list of North Carolina hurricanes includes tropical cyclones that affected or struck the U.S. state of North Carolina between 1980 and 1999. <s> Tropical cyclones in North Carolina caused at least $10 billion in damage. <s> Damage is $1 billion in North Carolina. <s> These cyclones killed 56 people directly and at least 47 indirectly. <s> The strongest tropical cyclones to affect North Carolina were Hurricane Emily and Hurricane Fran.

complex: Cashville Records (formerly G-Unit South) was an American independent record label based in Nashville, Tennessee founded by rapper Young Buck. <s> Initially founded as a southern branch of 50 Cent's G-Unit Records, the label became "Cashville Records" in late 2007 after a dispute between 50 Cent and Young Buck led to Buck being banned from using the G-Unit logo or name to distribute his music. <s> The label has signed such acts as The Outlawz, C-Bo, Lil Scrappy, D4L and more.

title: MV Rachel Corrie
complex: MV "Rachel Corrie" is a 499 GT coaster owned and operated by the Free Gaza Movement. <s> The ship is named in honour of Rachel Corrie, a deceased member of the International Solidarity Movement. <s> Built by J.J. Sietas in Hamburg in 1967, she was originally named "Carsten"; she has also carried the names "Norasia Attika", "Manya" and more recently "Linda". <s> In June 2010 the vessel was intercepted by Israeli Defence Forces while attempting to break the Israeli blockade of the Gaza Strip and to deliver humanitarian aid.

title: Roger Joseph Boscovich
complex: Roger Joseph Boscovich, S.J. (; ] ; ; ; 18 May 1711 – 13 February 1787) was a physicist, astronomer, mathematician, philosopher, diplomat, poet, theologian, Jesuit priest, and a polymath from the Republic of Ragusa (modern-day Dubrovnik, Croatia). <s> He studied and lived in Italy and France where he also published many of his works. <s> Boscovich produced a precursor of atomic theory and made many contributions to astronomy, including the first geometric procedure for determining the equator of a rotating planet from three observations of a surface feature and for computing the orbit of a planet from three observations of its position. <s> In 1753 he also discovered the absence of atmosphere on the Moon. <s> Boscovich was born on 18 May 1711 in Ragusa (Dubrovnik), Republic of Ragusa, to Nikola Bošković, a Ragusan merchant, and Paola Bettera (1674–1777), daughter of a local nobleman of Italian origin. <s> He was baptised on 26 May 1711 by Marinus Carolis, "curatus et sacristia". <s> The name Ruđer/Ruggiero may have been given to him because both his great-grandfather Agostino Bettera and his mother's brother were called Ruggiero, the godparent was his uncle Ruggiero Bettera. <s> He was the seventh child of the family and the second youngest. <s> His father was born in 1642, at Orahov Do near Ravno, at the time part of the Ottoman Empire (now Bosnia and Herzegovina). <s> His father was rich in trading experience and knowledge of that part of the Ottoman Empire, but Ruđer knew him only as a bedridden invalid with paralysed legs and he died when Ruđer was 10 years old. <s> Boscovich's mother Paola, nicknamed "Pavica", was a member of a cultivated Italian merchant family established in Dubrovnik since the early 17th century, when her ancestor Pietro Bettera settled from Bergamo in northern Italy. <s> She was a robust and active woman with a happy temperament who lived to 103. <s> On 16 September 1725, Ruđer Bošković left Dubrovnik for Rome. <s> He was in the care of two Jesuit priests who took him to the Society of Jesus, famous for its education of youth and at that time having some 800 establishments and 200,000 pupils under its care throughout the world. <s> We learn nothing from Bošković himself until the time he entered the novitiate in 1731, but it was the usual practice for novices to spend the first two years not in the Collegium Romanum but in Sant'Andrea delle Fratte. <s> There, he studied mathematics and physics; and so brilliant was his progress in these sciences that in 1740 he was appointed professor of mathematics in the college. <s> Notwithstanding the arduous duties of his professorship, he found time for investigation in various fields of physical science, and he published a very large number of dissertations, some of them of considerable length. <s> Among the subjects were the transit of Mercury, the Aurora Borealis, the figure of the Earth, the observation of the fixed stars, the inequalities in terrestrial gravitation, the application of mathematics to the theory of the telescope, the limits of certainty in astronomical observations, the solid of greatest attraction, the cycloid, the logistic curve, the theory of comets, the tides, the law of continuity, the double refraction micrometre, and various problems of spherical trigonometry. <s> In 1742 he was consulted, with other men of science, by Pope Benedict XIV, as to the best means of securing the stability of the dome of St. Peter's, Rome, in which a crack had been discovered. <s> His suggestion of placing five concentric iron bands was adopted. <s> In 1745 Bošković published "De Viribus Vivis" in which he tried to find a middle way between Isaac Newton's gravitational theory and Gottfried Leibniz's metaphysical theory of monad-points. <s> He developed a concept of "impenetrability" as a property of hard bodies which explained their behaviour in terms of force rather than matter. <s> Stripping atoms of their matter, impenetrability is disassociated from hardness and then put in an arbitrary relationship to elasticity. <s> Impenetrability has a Cartesian sense that more than one point cannot occupy the same location at once. <s> A dispute arose between Francis the Grand Duke of Tuscany and the Republic of Lucca with respect to the drainage of a lake. <s> As agent of Lucca, Bošković was sent, in 1757, to Vienna and succeeded in bringing about a satisfactory arrangement in the matter. <s> In Vienna in 1758, he published the first edition of his famous work, "Philosophiæ naturalis theoria redacta ad unicam legem virium in natura existentium" ("Theory of Natural philosophy derived to the single Law of forces which exist in Nature"), containing his atomic theory and his theory of forces. <s> A second edition was published in 1763 in Venice and a third again in Vienna in 1764. <s> In 1922 it was published in London, and in 1966 in the United States. <s> Another edition was published in Zagreb in 1974.
simple: Roger Joseph Boscovich (18 May 1711 - 13 February 1787) was a Croatian polymath and Jesuit from the city of Dubrovnik in the Republic of Ragusa (modern-day Croatia). <s> He studied and lived in Italy and France, where he published many of his works. <s> He produced a precursor of atomic theory and made many contributions to astronomy. <s> In 1753 he discovered the absence of atmosphere on the Moon. <s> Boscovich was born in Dubrovnik as the youngest of seven children. <s> He joined the Jesuit school in Dubrovnik, leaving for Rome in 1725. <s> In Rome he was under the care of 2 Jesuit priests whom introduced him to the Society of Jesus. <s> There, he studied mathematics and physics and in 1740 he was appointed professor of mathematics in the college. <s> Boscovich studied the transit of Mercury, the Aurora borealis, the figure of the Earth, the observation of the fixed stars, the inequalities in terrestrial gravitation, the application of mathematics to the theory of the telescope, the limits of certainty in astronomical observations, and various problems in solid geometry and spherical trigonometry. <s> In 1742 he and other scientists were consulted by Pope Benedict XIV, as to the best way of securing the structure of the dome of St. Peter's, Rome, in which a crack had been discovered. <s> His suggested placing five iron bands and it was accepted. <s> He explained the resistance of hard bodies as due to force rather than "hardness". <s> In Vienna in 1758, he published the first edition of his famous work, "Philosophiæ naturalis theoria redacta ad unicam legem virium in natura existentium" ("Theory of natural philosophy derived to the single law of forces which exist in nature"). <s> A second edition was published in 1763 in Venice and a third again in Vienna in 1764. <s> In 1922 it was published in London, and in 1966 in the United States. <s> Another edition was published in Zagreb in 1974.

title: Schaerbeek
complex: Schaerbeek (obsolete Dutch spelling, retained in French, pronounced ] ) or Schaarbeek (Dutch, ] ) is one of the nineteen municipalities located in the Brussels-Capital Region of Belgium. <s> It is bordered by the City of Brussels, Etterbeek, Evere and Saint-Josse-ten-Noode.
simple: Schaerbeek (in French) or Schaarbeek (in Dutch) is a municipality in the Brussels-Capital Region of Belgian.

title: Premier of Tasmania
complex: The Premier of Tasmania is the head of the executive government in the Australian state of Tasmania. <s> By convention, the leader of the party or political grouping which has majority support in the House of Assembly is invited by the Governor of Tasmania to be Premier and principal adviser. <s> Since the 2014 election, the Premier of Tasmania has been Will Hodgman, leader of the Liberal Party. <s> Hodgman won a second term at the 2018 election, and now holds 13 of the 25 seats in the House of Assembly. <s> Before the 1890s, there was no formal party system in Tasmania. <s> Party labels before that time indicate a general tendency only. <s> The current convention of appointing the Premier from the House of Assembly was not generally applied prior to 1920, with Premiers often appointed from the Legislative Council.
simple: The Premier of Tasmania is the head of the government in the Australian state of Tasmania. <s> The political party which has the most support in the House of Assembly will nominate its leader to be Premier. <s> The leader is then asked by the Governor of Tasmania to act as their principal adviser. <s> The current premier is Will Hodgman of the Liberal Party of Australia, who was sworn in on 31 March 2014. <s> Before the 1890s, there was no political party system in Tasmania. <s> Before 1920 premiers were often appointed from the Legislative Council.

title: Liopleurodon
complex: Liopleurodon ( ; meaning 'smooth-sided teeth') is a genus of large, carnivorous marine reptile belonging to the Pliosauroidea, a clade of short-necked plesiosaurs. <s> The two species of "Liopleurodon" lived during the Callovian stage of the Middle Jurassic Period (c. 164 to 155 mya). <s> It was the apex predator of the Middle to Late Jurassic seas that covered Europe. <s> The largest species, "L. ferox", is estimated to have grown up to 6.4 m in length.
simple: Liopleurodon was a large species of Pliosaur. <s> It was an apex predator in the Upper Jurassic seas, around 160–155 million years ago.

title: Johnny Pesky
complex: John Michael Pesky (born John Michael Paveskovich; February 27, 1919 – August 13, 2012), nicknamed "The Needle" and "Mr. Red Sox", was an American professional baseball player, manager and coach. <s> He was a shortstop and third baseman during a ten-year major league playing career, appearing in 1,270 games played in 1942 and from 1946 to 1954 for three teams. <s> He missed the 1943–45 seasons while serving in World War II.
simple: John Michael "Johnny" Pesky (born John Michael Paveskovich; February 27, 1919 – August 13, 2012), nicknamed "The Needle" and "Mr. Red Sox", was an American professional baseball player, manager and coach. <s> He was a shortstop and third baseman during a ten-year major league playing career, appearing in 1,270 games played in 1942 and from 1946 to 1954 for three different teams.

title: Italian language in Croatia
complex: As of 2009, the Italian language is officially used in twenty cities and municipalities and ten other settlements in Croatia, according to the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages. <s> It is an officially recognized minority language in Istria County, where it is spoken by 6.83% of the population on the aggregate and closer to 50% of the population in certain subdivisions. <s> The 2011 Census in Croatia reported 17,807 ethnic Italians in the country (some 0.42% of the total population). <s> Ethnologue reported 70,000 persons whose first language is Italian or Venetian in 1998 (referring to Eugen Marinov's 1998 data). <s> This population was composed of 30,000 ethnic Italians and 40,000 ethnic Croats and persons declared regionally ("as Istrians"). <s> Native Italian speakers are largely concentrated along the western coast of peninsula Istria. <s> Because of Croatian trade and tourist relations with Italy, many Croats have some knowledge of the language (mostly in the service and tourist industries). <s> In the past the language had a much larger population than it does now: the Italian (Venetian speaking) population constituted well over half of the population of Istria and (according to the Italian linguist Bartoli) nearly one third of Dalmatians in the second half of the 18th century. <s> In Dalmatia, ethnic Italians underwent significant persecution in the 1800s, whereby, according to the Austrian census it had decreased from 22% in 1816 to 12.5% in 1853, down to a mere 2.9% in 1910. <s> For various reasons—mainly related to nationalism and armed conflict—the numbers of Italian speakers in Croatia declined during the 20th century, especially after the Second World War in a period known as the Istrian exodus, when about 90% Italian-speaking Istrians and Dalmatians left Yugoslav dominated areas in the eastern Adriatic. <s> The 2001 census in Croatia reported 19,636 ethnic Italians in the country. <s> In Istria County, local government services are provided in Croatian and Italian, including the tri-lingual (Croatian, Italian and English) official government website. <s> There are some Italian-language schools in the region of Istria: primary schools in Buje/Buie, Umag/Umago, Novigrad/Cittanova d'Istria, Poreč/Parenzo, and secondary schools in Pula/Pola and Rovinj/Rovigno.
simple: It is an officially recognized minority language in Istria County (where it is spoken by 7.69% of the population). <s> The 2001 census in Croatia reported 19,636 ethnic Italians in the country (some .44% of the total population). <s> Ethnologue reported 70,000 speakers in 1998: 40,000 ethnic Italians and 30,000 ethnic Croats and Istrian people. <s> Native Italian speakers are largely concentrated along the Adriatic coast. <s> In addition, roughly 120,000 Italian tourists visit Croatia each year, so many in the service and tourist industries have some knowledge of the language. <s> Historically, the language had a much larger population than it does now. <s> Government services are provided in Italian and Croatian in Istria County, including the official government website (which is also available in English). <s> There are four Italian-language schools in Istria: primary schools in Buje (Buie) and Novigrad (Cittanova) and secondary schools in Pula (Pola) and Rovinj (Rovigno).

title: Sadaharu Oh
