complex: Sadaharu Oh (Japanese: , "Ō Sadaharu"; born May 20, 1940), also known as Wang Chen-chih , is a retired Chinese baseball player and manager of Chinese-Japanese descent who played 22 seasons for the Yomiuri Giants in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) from 1959 to 1980. <s> Oh holds the world lifetime home run record, having hit 868 home runs during his professional career. <s> He established many NPB batting records, including runs batted in (RBIs) (2,170), slugging percentage (.634), bases on balls (2,390), and on-base plus slugging percentage (OPS) (1.080). <s> In 1977, Oh became the first recipient of the People's Honour Award. <s> He was inducted into the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame in 1994. <s> Oh played his entire professional career with the Giants and was their manager from 1984 to 1988. <s> He also managed the Fukuoka Daiei/Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks from 1995 to 2008. <s> He was the manager of the Japanese national team in the inaugural World Baseball Classic. <s> The Japanese team defeated the Cuban national team for the championship. <s> He is currently the chairman of the Hawks. <s> Oh was born in Sumida, Tokyo, the son of a Japanese mother and a Chinese father from Zhejiang. <s> Although born in Japan, he had citizenship of Republic of China which he holds today, as his father left China when the ROC governed the mainland and chose to remain a Chinese citizen. <s> Sadaharu Oh retired in 1980 at age 40, having amassed 2,786 hits (third after Isao Harimoto (Jang Hoon) and Katsuya Nomura), 2,170 RBIs, a lifetime batting average of .301, and 868 home runs. <s> Sadaharu Oh was the assistant manager of the Yomiuri Giants between 1981 and 1983.
simple: Sadaharu Oh (王貞治, Oh Sadaharu, born May 20, 1940), also known as Wang Chenchih , is a Japanese-Taiwanese professional athlete. <s> From 1984 to 1988, he was the Giants' manager. <s> He managed the Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks from 1995 to 2008. <s> In 2006, he was the manager of the Japanese national team in the World Baseball Classic. <s> Oh was born in Tokyo. <s> He is the son of a Taiwanese father and a Japanese mother. <s> Although Oh has always lived in Japan, he has always been a citizen of the Republic of China (Taiwan). <s> Oh retired from playing in 1980.

title: Economy of Pakistan
complex: The economy of Pakistan is the 24th largest in the world in terms of purchasing power parity (PPP), and 39th largest in terms of nominal gross domestic product. <s> Pakistan has a population of over 207 million (the world's 6th-largest), giving it a nominal GDP per capita of $1,357 in 2019, which ranks 154th in the world and giving it a PPP GDP per capita of 5,839 in 2019, which ranks 132th in the world for 2019.
simple: It is the 25th largest economy in the world.

title: Michael Thalbourne
complex: Michael Anthony Thalbourne, Ph.D. (24 March 1955 – 4 May 2010, Adelaide, South Australia) was an Australian psychologist who worked in the field of parapsychology. <s> He was educated at the University of Adelaide and the University of Edinburgh. <s> His books include: "A glossary of terms used in parapsychology" (2003), "The common thread between ESP and PK" (2004), and "Parapsychology in the Twenty-First Century: Essays on the future of Psychical Research" (2005). <s> He was first cousin twice removed on his mother's side of Supreme Court of South Australia judge George Coutts Ligertwood.
simple: Michael A. Thalbourne, Ph.D., (March 24 1955 – May 4 2010) was an Australian psychologist and parapsychologist. <s> He was educated at the University of Adelaide and the University of Edinburgh. <s> His books include: "A glossary of terms used in parapsychology" (2003), "The common thread between ESP and PK" (2004), and "Parapsychology in the Twenty-First Century: Essays on the future of Psychical research" (2005).

title: Divisor
complex: In mathematics, a divisor of an integer formula_1, also called a factor of formula_1, is an integer formula_3 that may be multiplied by some integer to produce formula_1. <s> In this case, one also says that formula_1 is a multiple of formula_6 An integer formula_1 is divisible by another integer formula_3 if formula_3 is a divisor of formula_1; this implies dividing formula_1 by formula_3 leaves no remainder. <s> Divisors can be negative as well as positive, although sometimes the term is restricted to positive divisors. <s> For example, there are six divisors of 4; they are 1, 2, 4, −1, −2, and −4, but only the positive ones (1, 2, and 4) would usually be mentioned. <s> 1 and −1 divide (are divisors of) every integer. <s> Every integer (and its negation) is a divisor of itself. <s> Integers divisible by 2 are called even, and integers not divisible by 2 are called odd. <s> 1, −1, "n" and −"n" are known as the trivial divisors of "n". <s> A divisor of "n" that is not a trivial divisor is known as a non-trivial divisor ( or strict divisor ) . <s> A non-zero integer with at least one non-trivial divisor is known as a composite number, while the units −1 and 1 and prime numbers have no non-trivial divisors. <s> There are divisibility rules that allow one to recognize certain divisors of a number from the number's digits. <s> The total number of positive divisors of formula_1 is a multiplicative function formula_63, meaning that when two numbers formula_3 and formula_1 are relatively prime, then formula_66. <s> For instance, formula_67; the eight divisors of 42 are 1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 14, 21 and 42. <s> However, the number of positive divisors is not a totally multiplicative function: if the two numbers formula_3 and formula_1 share a common divisor, then it might not be true that formula_66.
simple: In mathematics, a divisor of an integer "n", also called a factor of "n", is an integer which evenly divides "n" without leaving a remainder. <s> Thus, divisors can be negative as well as positive, although often we restrict our attention to positive divisors. <s> (For example, there are six divisors of four, 1, 2, 4, -1, -2, -4, but one would usually mention only the positive ones, 1, 2, and 4.) <s> 1 and -1 divide (are divisors of) every integer, every integer is a divisor of itself, and every integer is a divisor of 0, except by convention 0 itself (see also division by zero). <s> Numbers divisible by 2 are called even and numbers not divisible by 2 are called odd. <s> A divisor of "n" that is not 1, -1, "n" or -"n" is known as a non-trivial divisor; numbers with non-trivial divisors are known as composite numbers, while prime numbers have no non-trivial divisors. <s> There are properties which allow one to recognize certain divisors of a number from the number's digits. <s> For example, 7 is a divisor of 42 because 42÷7 = 6. <s> For example, the positive divisors of 42 are 1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 14, 21, 42.

title: Chitral District
complex: Chitral District is the largest district in the Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan, covering an area of 14,850 km2. <s> Part of the Malakand Division, it is the northernmost district of Pakistan. <s> It shares a border with Gilgit-Baltistan to the east, with Kunar, Badakshan and Nuristan provinces of Afghanistan to the north and west, and with the Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa districts of Swat and Dir to the south. <s> A narrow strip of Wakhan Corridor separates Chitral from Tajikistan in the north. <s> Chitral is counted amongst the highest regions of the world, sweeping from 1,094 meters at Arandu to 7,726 meters at Tirichmir, and packing over 40 peaks more than 6,100 meters in height. <s> The terrain of Chitral is very mountainous and Tirich Mir (25,289 feet) the highest peak of the Hindu Kush, rises in the north of the district. <s> Around 4.8 per cent of the land is covered by forest and 76 per cent is mountains and glaciers. <s> Chitral is connected to the rest of Pakistan by two major road routes, the Lowari Pass (el. <s> 10,230 ft.) from Dir and Shandur Top (elevation 12,200 ft.) from Gilgit. <s> Both routes are closed in winter. <s> The Lowari Tunnel is being constructed under the Lowari Pass. <s> A number of other high passes, including Darkot Pass, Thoi Pass and Zagaran Pass, provide access on foot to Chitral from Gilgit-Baltistan in Ghizer District. <s> The district has a population of about 414,000. <s> The general population is mainly of the Kho people, who speak the Khowar, which is also spoken in parts of Yasin, Gilgit, Dir and Swat. <s> Chitral is also home to the Kalash tribe, who live in Bumburet and two other remote valleys southwest of Chitral town. <s> The town of Chitral is the main town in the district and serves as its capital. <s> It is situated on the west bank of the Chitral River (also known as the Kunar River) at the foot of Tirich Mir which at 7,708 m (25,289 ft) is the highest peak of the Hindu Kush. <s> Until 1969, it served as the capital of the princely state of Chitral. <s> This district is represented by one elected MNA (Member of National Assembly) in Pakistan National Assembly. <s> Its constituency is NA-32.
simple: Chitral is a district in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan. <s> It is the largest district in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, with an area of 14,850 sq. kilometres. <s> Chitral District is the most northerly district in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province. <s> The terrain of Chitral is quite mountainous, part of the Pamir Mountains are situated here. <s> Tirich Mir which at 25,289 feet (7,708 metres) is the highest peak of the Hindu Kush, rises in the north of the district. <s> Chitral is connected to the rest of Pakistan by only two road routes, the Lowari Pass (el. <s> 10,230 ft.) from Dir and Shandur Top (el. <s> 12,200 ft.) from Gilgit. <s> Both routes are closed in winter. <s> Both are closed in winter. <s> The Lowari Tunnel is being constructed under the Lowari Pass and is opened two times a week when Lowari Top is closed due to snowfall. <s> Two other passes give access on foot to Chitral, the Broghol Pass and the Dorah Pass, both from Afghanistan. <s> The general population is mainly of the Kho people, who speak the Khowar language (or Chitrali), which is also spoken in parts of Yasin, Gilgit and Swat. <s> Chitral is also home to the Kalash tribe who live in three remote valleys southwest of Chitral town. <s> Until 1969, Chitral was a princely state, within the Malakand Agency. <s> This district is represented by one elected MNA (Member of National Assembly) in Pakistan National Assembly. <s> Its constituency is NA-32.

title: Hallstavik
complex: Hallstavik is a locality situated in Norrtälje Municipality, Stockholm County, Sweden with 4,476 inhabitants in 2010. <s> The town is famous for its papermill and the Speedway team Rospiggarna.
simple: Hallstavik is a locality in Norrtälje Municipality in Stockholm County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 4,476 people lived there. <s> The locality is known for its paper-factory and the Rospiggarna speedway team .

title: Saint-Germain-Langot
complex: Saint-Germain-Langot is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Saint-Germain-Langot is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft
complex: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft is a transport museum which specialises in the preservation of trolleybuses. <s> It is located by the village of Sandtoft, near Belton on the Isle of Axholme in the English county of Lincolnshire.
simple: The Trolleybus Museum at Sandtoft is a transport museum that has old trolleybuses. <s> It is near to the village of Sandtoft, near Belton on the Isle of Axholme in the English county of Lincolnshire.

title: Strait of Tartary
complex: Strait of Tartary or Gulf of Tartary ( ; ; ; ) is a strait in the Pacific Ocean dividing the Russian island of Sakhalin from mainland Asia (South-East Russia), connecting the Sea of Okhotsk on the north with the Sea of Japan on the south. <s> It is 900 km long, 4–20 m (13-66 ft) deep, and 7.3 km wide at the narrowest point. <s> Since 1973, Vanino-Kholmsk train ferry operates across the strait, connecting the port of Vanino, Khabarovsk Krai on the mainland with Kholmsk on Sakhalin Island.
simple: Strait of Tartary (Gulf of Tartary, Gulf of Tatary, Tatar Strait, Tartar Strait, Strait of Tartar) is a strait in the Pacific Ocean. <s> It divides the Russian island of Sakhalin from mainland Asia. <s> It connects the Sea of Okhotsk on the north with the Sea of Japan on the south. <s> It is 900 km long, 4–20 m deep, and 7.3 km wide at the narrowest point. <s> Since 1973, a rail ferry goes across the strait. <s> It connects the port of Vanino, Khabarovsk Krai on the mainland with Kholmsk on Sakhalin Island.

title: Veiled Christ
complex: The Veiled Christ (Italian: "Cristo velato") is a 1753 marble sculpture by Giuseppe Sanmartino exhibited in the Cappella Sansevero, Naples. <s> "Veiled Christ" is considered one of the world's most remarkable sculptures, and legendary thought to have been created by alchemy. <s> Sculptor Antonio Canova, who tried to acquire the work, declared that he would willingly give up ten years of his life to produce a similar masterpiece. <s> "Veiled Christ"' s production was originally assigned to the sculptor Antonio Corradini, who specialized in veiled statues. <s> However, Corradini died a short time later, having produced only a terracotta bozzetto (today displayed at the Museo nazionale di San Martino). <s> The job thus passed to Giuseppe Sanmartino, who was charged with producing "a marble statue sculpted with the greatest realism, representing Our Lord Jesus Christ in death, covered by a transparent shroud carved from the same block of stone as the statue." <s> Sanmartino produced a work with the dead Christ laid on a couch, covered by a veil which adheres perfectly to his form. <s> The mastery of the Neapolitan sculptor lies in his successful depiction, looking through the veil, of the suffering that Christ had undergone during the crucifixion. <s> Signs of Jesus's pain can be seen on his face and body. <s> Shaping further detail into the marble block, at Jesus's feet Sanmartino has carved depictions of the instruments of Christ's torture: the crown of thorns, pliers, and shackles. <s> In reality, a close analysis leaves no doubt that the work was entirely produced in marble. <s> This is also confirmed by some letters written at the time of its production. <s> A receipt of payment to Sanmartino, dated 16 December 1752 and signed by the prince, is preserved in the Historical archive of the Bank of Naples, states: In other letters, di Sangro also states that the veil was produced from the same block of stone as the statue.
simple: The Veiled Christ (Italian: "Cristo velato") is a statue made of marble. <s> It was made by Giuseppe Sanmartino. <s> It is in Cappella Sansevero, Naples. <s> Antonio Canova who once tried to acquire the work declared that he would willingly give up ten years of his own life to produce a similar masterpiece. <s> The order for the Veiled Christ was given to Antonio Corradini. <s> However, he died a short time later. <s> Sanmartino took over the work. <s> He decided to place the Christ figure on a couch, covered by a veil. <s> It was to show the suffering that Christ has undergone. <s> At the sculpture's feet, finally, the artist also carves the instruments of his torture: the crown of thorns, pliers, and some shackles. <s> An analysis shows that the work is completely made in marble. <s> A receipt of payment to Sanmartino dated 16 December 1752, signed by the prince, is preserved in the historical archive of the Bank of Naples.

title: Peter Lax
complex: Peter David Lax (born Lax Péter Dávid; 1 May 1926) is a Hungarian-born American mathematician working in the areas of pure and applied mathematics. <s> Lax has made important contributions to integrable systems, fluid dynamics and shock waves, solitonic physics, hyperbolic conservation laws, and mathematical and scientific computing, among other fields. <s> Lax was born in Budapest, Hungary to a Jewish family. <s> Lax began displaying an interest in mathematics at age twelve, and soon his parents hired Rózsa Péter as a tutor for him. <s> His parents Klara Kornfield and Henry Lax were both physicians and his uncle Albert Kornfeld (also known as Albert Korodi) was a mathematician, as well as a friend of Leó Szilárd. <s> Lax is listed as an ISI highly cited researcher. <s> According to György Marx he was one of The Martians.
simple: Peter David Lax (born 1 May 1926) is an American mathematician. <s> He is known for his works in integrable systems, fluid dynamics and shock waves, solitonic physics, hyperbolic conservation laws, and mathematical and scientific computing, among other fields. <s> Lax is of Jewish descent. <s> Lax is listed as an ISI highly cited researcher.

title: Holloway Road tube station
complex: Holloway Road is a station on the London Underground. <s> It is on the Piccadilly line between Caledonian Road and Arsenal stations, and in Travelcard Zone 2. <s> The station opened on 15 December 1906.
simple: Holloway Road is a station on the London Underground. <s> It is on the Piccadilly Line between Caledonian Road and Arsenal stations, and in Travelcard Zone 2. <s> The station opened on 15 December 1906.

title: Phyllis Vance
complex: Phyllis Vance (née Lapin) is a fictional character on the U.S. comedy television series, "The Office". <s> She is portrayed by Phyllis Smith, and has no specific counterpart in the British version of the series, instead being an amalgamation of several different office workers. <s> Phyllis Lapin is a sales representative at fictitious paper distributor Dunder Mifflin. <s> She is a quiet but friendly type who loves "girl talk" and gossip. <s> Though she has a sweet, motherly exterior, she can sometimes be very vindictive, often to Angela Martin.
simple: Phyllis Margaret Vance (née Lapin) is a fictional character on the U.S. comedy television series, "The Office". <s> She is played by Phyllis Smith. <s> The character is not based from anyone in the British version of the series. <s> Lapin is a sales representative at fictitious paper distributor Dunder Mifflin. <s> She is a quiet but friendly type who loves "girl talk" and gossip.

title: David Suzuki: The Autobiography
complex: David Suzuki: The Autobiography is the 2006 autobiography of Canadian science writer and broadcaster David Suzuki. <s> The book focuses mostly on his life since the 1987 publication of his first autobiography, "Metamorphosis: Stages in a Life". <s> It begins with a chronological account of his childhood, academic years, and broadcasting career. <s> In later chapters, Suzuki adopts a memoir style, writing about themes such as his relationship with Australia, his experiences in Brazil and Papua New Guinea, the founding of the David Suzuki Foundation, and his thoughts on climate change, celebrity status, technology, and death. <s> Throughout, Suzuki highlights the continuing impact of events from his childhood. <s> This is Suzuki's forty-third book and, he says, his last. <s> Critics have called the book candid, sincere, and charming, with insightful commentary if occasionally flat stories. <s> Suzuki's scientific background is reflected in the writing's rational and analytic style. <s> Suzuki's autobiography spent four weeks at 1 on the "Maclean's" list of non-fiction best-sellers and six weeks at No. 6 on the "Globe and Mail's" list. <s> The book won two awards in 2007: the Canadian Booksellers' Association's Libris Award for Non-Fiction Book of the Year and the British Columbia Booksellers' Choice Award. <s> The publishers, Greystone Books and Douglas & McIntyre, won the CBA Libris Award for Marketing Achievement of the Year. <s> Later chapters tell of events since "Metamorphosis."
simple: David Suzuki: The Autobiography is the 2006 autobiography of Canadian science writer and broadcaster David Suzuki. <s> The book focuses mostly on his life since the 1987 publication of his first autobiography, "Metamorphosis: Stages in a Life". <s> It begins with a chronological account of his childhood, academic years, and broadcasting career. <s> In later chapters, Suzuki adopts a memoir style, writing about themes such as his relationship with Australia, his experiences in Brazil and Papua New Guinea, the founding of the David Suzuki Foundation, and his thoughts on climate change, celebrity status, technology, and death. <s> Throughout, Suzuki highlights the continuing impact of events from his childhood. <s> This is Suzuki's forty-third book and, he says, his last. <s> Critics have called the book candid, sincere, and charming, with insightful commentary if occasionally flat stories. <s> Suzuki's scientific background is reflected in the writing's rational and analytic style. <s> Suzuki's autobiography spent four weeks at #1 on the "Maclean's" list of non-fiction best-sellers and six weeks at #6 on the "Globe and Mail's" list. <s> The book won two awards in 2007: the Canadian Booksellers' Association's Libris Award for Non-Fiction Book of the Year and the British Columbia Booksellers' Choice Award. <s> The publishers, Greystone Books and Douglas & McIntyre, won the CBA Libris Award for Marketing Achievement of the Year.

title: Wildest Dreams (Taylor Swift song)
complex: "Wildest Dreams" is a song recorded by American singer-songwriter Taylor Swift for her fifth studio album, "1989". <s> The song was released to radio by Big Machine Records and Republic Records on August 31, 2015, as the album's fifth single. <s> Swift wrote the song with its producers Max Martin and Shellback. <s> Musically, "Wildest Dreams" is a dream pop power ballad, with the lyrics describing Swift's plea for her lover to remember her. <s> Following the release of "1989", it charted in the United States, Canada, and Australia on the strength of digital downloads. <s> After its release as a single, it reached number five on the "Billboard" Hot 100, becoming the fifth consecutive top-10 song from "1989" and Swift's 19th top-10 single on the chart. <s> It also became her sixth chart topper on the Radio Songs chart. <s> On October 11, 2015 a remix by Dutch DJ R3hab was released digitally. <s> The remix received generally positive reviews from music critics.
simple: "Wildest Dreams" is a song by American singer-songwriter Taylor Swift. <s> The song was released on August 31, 2015. <s> Swift co-write the song with its producers Max Martin and Shellback. <s> The song hit #5 on the American "Billboard" Hot 100. <s> It got generally positive reviews from music critics.

title: Hamois
complex: Hamois (] ; ) is a Walloon municipality and village located in the Belgian province of Namur. <s> The village is around 25 km south-east of the city of Namur.
simple: Hamois is a municipality in the Belgian province of Namur.

title: Del Rio, Texas
complex: Del Rio is a city and the county seat of Val Verde County in southwestern Texas, United States. <s> The city is 152 miles west of San Antonio.
simple: Del Rio is a border city in and the county seat of Val Verde County, Texas, United States.

title: Phoenix (band)
complex: Phoenix is an indie pop band from Versailles, France, consisting of Thomas Mars (lead vocals), Deck d'Arcy (bass/keyboards/backing vocals), Christian Mazzalai (guitar/backing vocals) and Laurent Brancowitz (guitar/keyboards/backing vocals). <s> They are best known for their singles "If I Ever Feel Better," "Lisztomania," "Too Young" and "1901."
simple: Phoenix is a French alternative rock band that was Grammy awarded. <s> It consists of Thomas Mars (vocals), Deck D'Arcy (bass) and Laurent Brancowitz and Christian Mazzalai who play guitar.

title: USS Bunker Hill (CV-17)
complex: USS "Bunker Hill" (CV/CVA/CVS-17, AVT-9) was one of 24 "Essex"-class aircraft carrier s built during World War II for the United States Navy. <s> The ship was named for the Battle of Bunker Hill in the American Revolutionary War. <s> Commissioned in May 1943 and sent to the Pacific Theater of Operations, the ship participated in battles in the Southwest Pacific, Central Pacific and the drive toward Japan through Iwo Jima, Okinawa, and air raids on the Japanese homeland. <s> While covering the invasion of Okinawa, "Bunker Hill" was struck by two kamikazes in quick succession, setting the vessel on fire. <s> Casualties exceeded 600, including 346 confirmed dead and an additional 43 missing, the second heaviest personnel losses suffered by any carrier to survive the war after . <s> After the attack, "Bunker Hill" returned to the U.S. mainland and was still under repair when hostilities ended.
simple: USS "Bunker Hill" (CV/CVA/CVS-17, AVT-9) was one of 24 Essex Aircraft Carriers built during World War II for the United States Navy. <s> The ship was named for the Battle of Bunker Hill in the American Revolutionary War and was commissioned in May 1943. <s> While covering the invasion of Okinawa, "Bunker Hill" was struck by two kamikazes in quick succession, setting the vessel on fire. <s> Casualties exceeded 600, including 346 confirmed dead and an additional 43 missing,

title: Mira Zakai
complex: Mira Zakai ( ‎; 21 September 1942 – 20 May 2019) was an Israeli operatic contralto. <s> Zakai was born in Jerusalem as Mira Koigen, the daughter of George Koigen and his wife Eva (née Patai). <s> She studied at the University of Tel Aviv, initially in the Faculty of Humanities, and later at the Rubin Academy of Music, graduating in 1976. <s> She married Jacob Zakai and they had two daughters. <s> She appeared with Yehudi Menuhin in a concert at Castel Gandolfo for Pope John Paul II, having previously appeared at Menuhin's festival as a soloist in Bach's "Mass in B minor". <s> Her 1982 recording of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 with Georg Solti won the Grammy for Best Overall Classical Recording at the 1982 awards. <s> Zakai later moved into teaching, becoming a professor at the Buchmann-Mehta School of Music, University of Tel Aviv.
simple: Mira Zakai (‎; 21 September 1942 – 20 May 2019) was an Israeli opera singer. <s> She was a contralto. <s> On 20 May 2019, Zakai died of problems caused by a stroke she had a year before. <s> She was born in Jerusalem. <s> She studied at the University of Tel Aviv, where she later served as a professor. <s> She appeared with Menuhin at a concert in Castel Gandolfo for Pope John Paul II. <s> Before this, she appeared in Menuhin's festival as a soloist in Bach's "Mass in B minor". <s> Her recording of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 with Georg Solti won the Grammy Award for Best Overall Classical Recording in 1982.

title: Évora
complex: Évora ( , ] ; ) is a city and a municipality in Portugal. <s> The population in 2011 was 56,596, in an area of 1307.08 km2. <s> It is the seat of the Évora District. <s> The present Mayor is Carlos Pinto de Sá of the CDU coalition.
simple: Évora is a city in Portugal. <s> It has 56,596 people. <s> It is the seat of the Évora District.

title: Mara Wilson
complex: Mara Elizabeth Wilson (born July 24, 1987) is an American actress, voice actress, stage actress, and writer. <s> As a child, she rose to prominence after landing the role as Natalie Hillard in "Mrs. Doubtfire" (1993), having only acted in commercials previously. <s> Wilson also portrayed the role of Susan Walker in "Miracle on 34th Street" (1994), Matilda Wormwood in "Matilda" (1996), and Lily Stone in "Thomas and the Magic Railroad" (2000). <s> Since retiring from acting in 2000, Wilson has focused on writing and appeared in numerous podcasts. <s> Wilson was born in Burbank, California. <s> She is the oldest daughter of Mike Wilson, a television broadcast engineer at KTLA-TV News and the late Suzie Shapiro Wilson, a homemaker and Burbank PTA school volunteer.
simple: Mara Elizabeth Wilson (born July 24, 1987 in Los Angeles, California) is an American actress and playwright. <s> Her best known movies include "Mrs. Doubtfire" (1993), "Matilda" (1996) and Lily Stone in "Thomas and the Magic Railroad" (2000). <s> She was born in Los Angeles.

title: Deaths in June 2019
complex: The following is a list of notable deaths in June 2019.
simple: The following is a list of deaths that should be noted in June 2019.

title: Laxmi Prasad Devkota
complex: Laxmi Prasad Devkota ( ,(12 November 1909 – 14 September 1959) was a Nepali poet, playwright, and novelist. <s> Honored with the title of Mahakavi (literal translation: "The Great Poet" or Poet the Great) in Nepali literature, and is known as the poet with the golden heart. <s> Devkota is by and large regarded as the great poet (महाकवि) of Nepali language. <s> Some of his popular works including the best selling "Muna Madan", along with "Sulochana","Kunjini", and "Sakuntala".
simple: Laxmi Prasad Devkota was a Nepali poet, playwright, scholar, and novelist. <s> He is given the title of Mahakavi in Nepali Literature, which means The Great Poet. <s> He is known as the poet with the golden heart. <s> Some of his famous works are "Muna Madan", "Sulochana", "Kunjini", and "Sakuntala".

title: Currawong
complex: Currawongs are three species of medium-sized passerine birds belonging to the genus "Strepera" in the family Artamidae native to Australasia. <s> These are the grey currawong ("Strepera versicolor"), pied currawong ("S. graculina"), and black currawong ("S. fuliginosa").
simple: They form the genus Strepera, which belongs to the Artamidae family of birds. <s> There are three species of currawong.

title: Rod (unit)
complex: The rod or perch or pole is a surveyor’s tool and unit of length exactly equal to 5 ⁄ yards, 16 feet, of a statute mile, or one-fourth of a surveyor's chain (approximately 5.0292 meters). <s> The rod is useful as a unit of length because whole number multiples of it can form one acre of square measure. <s> The 'perfect acre' is a rectangular area of 43,560 square feet, bounded by sides of length 660 feet and 66 feet (220 yards and 22 yards) or, equivalently, 40 rods and 4 rods. <s> An acre is therefore 160 square rods. <s> Despite no longer being in widespread use, the rod is still employed in certain specialized fields. <s> In recreational canoeing, maps measure portages (overland paths where canoes must be carried) in rods; typical canoes are approximately one rod long. <s> The term is also in widespread use in the acquisition of pipeline easements, as the offers for an easement are often expressed on a "price per rod". <s> In the United Kingdom, the sizes of allotment gardens continue to be measured in square poles in some areas, sometimes being referred to simply as "poles" rather than "square poles".
simple: A rod, a perch or a pole is a unit of length in the imperial and US systems. <s> The rod is still in use as a unit of measure in certain specialised fields. <s> In recreational canoeing, overland paths where canoes must be carried are measured in rods. <s> This is probably because the length of a typical canoe is about one rod. <s> In the United Kingdom, some gardens are measured in rods.

title: Dietmar Constantini
complex: Dietmar "Didi" Constantini (born 30 May 1955) is a former Austrian football player and now coach. <s> He was appointed as head coach of the Austrian national team in March 2009 and was replaced by Marcel Koller in October 2011.
simple: Dietmar "Didi" Constantini (born 30 May, 1955 in Innsbruck, Austria) is a former Austrian football player and coach. <s> On 4 March 2009, Constantini became coach of the Austrian national football team.

title: Journans
complex: Journans is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Journans is a commune.

title: Carlos Heitor Cony
complex: Carlos Heitor Cony (March 14, 1926 – January 5, 2018) was a Brazilian journalist and writer. <s> He was a member of the Brazilian Academy of Letters (Portuguese: Academia Brasileira de Letras). <s> Cony viewed himself as center-leftist and faced persecution under the military government in the 1960s. <s> Four of his works were adapted to movies. <s> He was a columnist at the Brazilian newspaper "Folha de S.Paulo".
simple: Carlos Heitor Cony (March 14, 1926 – January 5, 2018) was a Brazilian journalist and writer. <s> Cony died in Rio de Janeiro on January 5, 2018 of multiple organ failure at the age of 91. <s> He was a member of the Brazilian Academy of Letters (Portuguese: Academia Brasileira de Letras). <s> Cony was a center-leftist and faced persecution under the military government in the 1960s. <s> Four of his works were adapted to movies. <s> He was a columnist at the Brazilian newspaper "Folha de S.Paulo".

title: Vienna Bend, Louisiana
complex: Vienna Bend is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana, United States. <s> The population was 1,251 at the 2010 census.
simple: Vienna Bend is an unincorporated community and census-designated place in Natchitoches Parish, Louisiana United States. <s> The population was 1,251 at the 2010 census.

title: Wolong National Nature Reserve
complex: Wolong National Nature Reserve , also known as Wolong Special Administrative Region , is a protected area located in Wenchuan County, Sichuan Province, People's Republic of China. <s> Established in 1963 with an initial size of about 20,000 hectares, the reserve was further expanded in 1975, covering an area of about 200,000 hectares in the Qionglai Mountains region. <s> There are over 4,000 different species recorded in the reserve. <s> According to China's Third National Giant Panda Survey, Wolong National Nature Reserve houses about 150 wild individuals of highly endangered giant pandas. <s> The reserve is also a home to many other endangered species including: snow leopards, red pandas, golden monkeys, white-lipped deer and many precious plants. <s> Before the devastating 2008 Wenchuan earthquake Wolong got up to 200,000 visitors every year. <s> Its area is superseded by the Wolong Special Administrative Region. <s> In June 1980, the China Conservation and Research Center for the Giant Panda was established at Wolong with the efforts of both World Wildlife Fund (WWF) and the Chinese government. <s> To this date, researchers have conducted many breeding research projects on giant pandas and have successfully bred 66 panda cubs. <s> A mountain stream runs through the Wolong Valley (where the reserve is); the stream is heavily armoured with boulders and smaller rounded stones. <s> Stream waters are rather alkaline with pH levels in the range of 8.91. <s> (Hogan, 2007) Water quality turbidity is quite high due to extensive sand and gravel mining in stream. <s> According to a 2001 research by Dr. Jianguo Liu of Michigan State University, the rate of destruction is higher after the reserve's creation than before its creation. <s> Using NASA's satellite images and records of population, Liu's research team concluded that due to tourism and the increase in local population, the reserve is facing an unprecedented threat. <s> "Tourists don't think they have an impact on panda habitat, but indirectly each visitor has some impact," Liu said. <s> "We don't see ourselves as a destructive force, but we are."
simple: Wolong National Nature Reserve is a national park in Sichuan Province, People's Republic of China. <s> It was established in 1963. <s> The reserve has an area of about 200,000 hectares. <s> There are over 4,000 different species recorded in the reserve. <s> Wolong National Nature Reserve houses more than 150 highly endangered giant pandas. <s> In June 1980, the China Research and Conservation Center for the Giant Panda was established. <s> The World Wildlife Fund (WWF) and the Chinese government cooperated to establish the center. <s> Researchers have made trials on how to breed the giant pandas. <s> They have successfully bred 66 panda cubs. <s> A mountain stream runs through the Wolong Valley (where the Reserve is); the stream is heavily armoured with boulders and smaller rounded stones. <s> Stream waters are rather alkaline with pH levels in the range of 8.91. <s> (Hogan, 2007) Water quality turbidity is quite high due to extensive sand and gravel mining in stream. <s> According to a 2001 research by Dr. Jianguo Liu of Michigan State University, the rate of destruction is higher after the reserve's creation than before its creation. <s> Using NASA's satellite images and records of the number of people there, Liu's research team concluded that due to tourism and the increase in the number of people, the reserve is facing an unprecedented threat. <s> "Tourists do not think they have an impact on panda habitat, but indirectly each visitor has some impact," Liu said. <s> "We do not see ourselves as a destructive force, but we are."

title: Rohit
complex: Rohit (Devanagri: रोहित), ] ) is a given name, typically male, used among Indian people. <s> It is also used in some parts of Nepal. <s> It is mostly used by Jains, Hindus, and Sikhs. <s> The word "rohit" signifies the color red. <s> It is derived from Sanskrit, meaning "the first rays of the sun". <s> The early morning sunlight usually has a reddish tint. <s> It is also said to be derived from the Sanskrit word Rohitah (रोहित:) which signifies a red coloured deer – a form which Brahma once took. ]
simple: Rohit is a given name, usually for males. <s> It is mostly used in India. <s> The word "rohit" refers to the color red. <s> It is derived from Sanskrit, meaning "the first rays of the sun". <s> The early morning sunlight usually has a reddish tint.

title: Blue-green
complex: Blue-green is a color that is a representation of the color that is between green and blue on a typical traditional old-fashioned RYB color wheel. <s> "Blue-green" belongs to the cyan family of colors.
simple: Blue-green is a color that is a deep tone of cyan.

title: Ice Road Truckers
complex: Ice Road Truckers (commercially abbreviated IRT) is an American reality television series that premiered on History Channel, on June 17, 2007. <s> It features the activities of drivers who operate trucks on seasonal routes crossing frozen lakes and rivers, in remote Arctic territories in Canada and Alaska. <s> Seasons 3–6 also featured Alaska's improved but still remote Dalton Highway, which is mainly snow-covered solid ground.
simple: Ice Road Truckers is a Canadian-American documentary-style reality television series that first appeared on television on The History Channel on June 17, 2007 (first season). <s> The show follows the activities of truck drivers which operate on routes that contain frozen lakes and rivers in the remote Arctic territories of Canada and Alaska.

title: Together Again (Sash! song)
complex: "Together Again" is a song by German production group Sash!. <s> The record was released in November 2000 via Edel Records as the fourth and final single from their third studio album "Trilenium". <s> The record features vocal parts by Danish artist Blå Øjne and was released in Denmark and Spain only. <s> The group initially planned to release the song with Danish lyrics.
simple: "Together Again" is a 2000 song by the German DJ group Sash! <s> It is the fourth and final single from Sash's third studio album "Trilenium" which was released on 22 May 2000. <s> and it features Danish singer Blå Øjne.

title: A Carnival Christmas
complex: A Carnival Christmas is the third EP by American hip hop group Insane Clown Posse, released on December 6, 1994, by Psychopathic Records. <s> It was reissued in 1997 by Island Records with alternate artwork.
simple: A Carnival Christmas is the third EP by the American Horrorcore band, Insane Clown Posse. <s> It was released on December 6, 1994. <s> The EP was a Christmas EP.

title: Michael Polakovs
complex: Michael Polakovs (23 February 1923 – 6 December 2009), born in Riga, Latvia, was a circus clown who performed in the US under the name of Coco the Clown, a moniker that his father, Nicolai Poliakoff, had made famous in Europe. <s> Michael was the eldest of Nicolai and his wife Valentina's two sons; they also had four daughters. <s> Nicolai was offered a contract to tour the UK with the Bertram Mills Circus in 1930, which allowed him to bring his wife and their two elder children, Michael and his sister Helen, to England. <s> The rest of the family joined them in 1934. <s> Michael joined his father in the circus ring, clowning and stiltwalking. <s> Many circuses were closed following the outbreak of the Second World War in 1939, and during the early part of the war Michael was employed by the Ascot Gas Board to dig holes in roads, for £2 16s 6d a week. <s> Nicolai and his family succeeded in finding employment with the Blackpool Tower Circus after it was decided that it would remain open during the war. <s> Michael and his sister Tamara appeared in each summer season until 1946, and toured during the winter months with stage circuses organised by impresario Tom Arnold. <s> Michael joined Billy Smart's Circus in 1951, and toured the US with the Mills Brothers Circus in 1953. <s> He returned to the US in the late 1950s, performing under his father's name of Coco the Clown with the Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus. <s> He was hired by the McDonald's fast-food chain in 1966 to revamp the character of Ronald McDonald, for whom he designed the outfit and make-up still in use today. <s> Michael also appeared in the first eight television commercials featuring the new character. <s> Michael retired to Catlettsburg, Kentucky with his second wife, Hazel, with whom he had one son and one daughter. <s> He also had four children from his first marriage, one of whom, Graham, also became a clown. <s> Died in 6 December 2009
simple: Michael Polakovs, known in America as Coco the Clown, (born Riga, Latvia 23 February 1923; died USA, 6 December 2009) was a famous clown. <s> His father was known as Coco the Clown in Britain. <s> Michael played the part of Coco the Clown in America. <s> Michael Polakovs was born in Riga. <s> Nikolai was known as Coco the Clown. <s> Michael was the eldest of six children. <s> In 1951 he went with a brother and a sister to work for Billy Smart’s circus. <s> There he became known as Coco the Clown. <s> He started the popularity of the character Ronald McDonald, advertising for the fast food chain. <s> He designed Ronald’s clothes and make-up and appeared in the first eight of his television commercials. <s> Later he settled with his second wife in Kentucky. <s> He had four children by his first wife and two children by his second wife. <s> He died aged 86 in 2009.

title: Seven (1995 film)
complex: Seven (stylized as SE7EN) is a 1995 American neo-noir crime thriller film directed by David Fincher and written by Andrew Kevin Walker. <s> It stars Brad Pitt, Morgan Freeman, Gwyneth Paltrow, John C. McGinley, R. Lee Ermey, and Kevin Spacey. <s> It tells the story of David Mills, a detective who partners with the retiring William Somerset to track down a serial killer who uses the seven deadly sins as a motif in his murders. <s> Somerset and Mills investigate a set of murders inspired by the seven deadly sins: a man forced to eat until his stomach ruptured, representing gluttony, and a defense attorney killed after a pound of flesh was taken from him, representing greed. <s> Clues at the murder scenes lead them to a suspect's apartment, where they find a third victim, a drug dealer and child molester, strapped to a bed, emaciated but alive, representing sloth.
simple: Seven is a 1995 American neo-noir crime horror thriller movie. <s> It stars Brad Pitt as David Mills and Morgan Freeman as William Somerset, police detectives who are working together to catch serial killer John Doe, played by Kevin Spacey. <s> Doe murders people he believes are guilty of the seven deadly sins.

title: Division of Cowan
complex: The Division of Cowan is an Australian Electoral Division in Western Australia. <s> The division was created in 1984 and is named for Edith Cowan, the first woman elected to an Australian Parliament. <s> It is located in the northern suburbs of Perth, including the suburbs of Girrawheen, Greenwood, Landsdale and Marangaroo. <s> It is a marginal seat, changing hands between the Australian Labor Party and the Liberal Party.
simple: The Division of Cowan is an Australian Electoral Division in Western Australia. <s> It was created in 1984 and is named for Edith Cowan, the first woman elected to an Australian Parliament. <s> It covers the northern suburbs of Perth, including Girrawheen, Greenwood, Kingsley, Landsdale, Woodvale and Marangaroo.

title: Elisabeth Moss
complex: Elisabeth Singleton Moss (born July 24, 1982) is an American actor. <s> She is known for her work in several television dramas, earning such accolades as two Primetime Emmy Awards and two Golden Globe Awards, which led "Vulture" to name her the "Queen of Peak TV". <s> Elisabeth Moss was born and raised in Los Angeles, California, the daughter of Ron and Linda Moss, both of whom were musicians. <s> Moss has one younger brother.
simple: Elisabeth Moss (born 24 July 1982) is an American actress. <s> Moss was born in Los Angeles.

title: John Law (economist)
complex: John Law ("baptised" 21 April 1671 – 21 March 1729) was a Scottish economist who believed that money was only a means of exchange that did not constitute wealth in itself and that national wealth depended on trade. <s> He was appointed Controller General of Finances of France under the Duke of Orleans, who served as regent for the youthful king, Louis XV.
simple: John Law ("baptized" 21 April 1671 - 21 March 1729) was a Scottish economist who believed that money was only a means of exchange that did not have wealth in itself, and that national wealth depended on trade.

title: DuPage County, Illinois
complex: DuPage County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois, and one of the collar counties of the Chicago metropolitan area. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 916,924, making it Illinois' second-most populous county. <s> Its county seat is Wheaton. <s> DuPage County has become mostly developed and suburbanized, although some pockets of farmland remain in the county's western and northern parts. <s> The county has a high socioeconomic profile and residents of Hinsdale, Naperville and Oak Brook include some of the wealthiest people in the Midwest. <s> On the whole, the county enjoys above average median household income levels and low overall poverty levels when compared to the national average.
simple: DuPage County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 916,924, making it Illinois' second-most populous county. <s> Its county seat is Wheaton. <s> DuPage County has become mostly developed and suburbanized. <s> Residents of Hinsdale, Naperville, and Oak Brook include some of the wealthiest people in the Midwest, and in 2010, "Midwest Living" voted Hinsdale the Midwest's second-wealthiest town.

title: Serbian language
complex: Serbian ( / , ] ) is the standardized variety of the Serbo-Croatian language mainly used by Serbs. <s> It is the official language of Serbia, co-official in the territory of Kosovo, and one of the three official languages of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
simple: Serbian is South Slavic language spoken by Serbs, primarily in Serbia, Kosovo, Montenegro and some parts of neighboring countries.

title: Valery Asapov
complex: Valery Grigorievich Asapov ( ; 1 January 1966 – 23 September 2017) was Lieutenant General in the Russian Army. <s> According to the Russian Defence Ministry, he was killed on 23 September 2017 by mortar fire from ISIL militants near the city of Deir ez-Zor during the Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War in the course of the Syrian Civil War. <s> Asapov's position in Syria was described by the Ministry of Defence as the chief of the group of Russian military advisers in Syria. <s> On 23 February 2013, Col Valery Asapov, then commander of the Motor Rifle brigade, was awarded the 4th Class of the Order "For Merit to the Fatherland" by Russian president Vladimir Putin.
simple: Valery Grigorievich Asapov (; 1 January 1966 – 23 September 2017) was a Russian lieutenant general in the Russian military. <s> Asapov was killed by mortar fire from ISIL militants near the city of Deir ez-Zor during the Syrian Civil War, according to the Russian Defence Ministry. <s> Asapov has been described as one of the senior Russian military advisers in Syria. <s> Asapov, then commander of an army motorised rifle brigade, was awarded the 4th Class of the Order "For Merit to the Fatherland" by President Vladimir Putin on 23 February 2013.

title: John Mayall
complex: John Mayall, OBE (born 29 November 1933) is an English blues singer, guitarist, organist and songwriter, whose musical career spans over sixty years. <s> In the 1960s, he was the founder of John Mayall & the Bluesbreakers, a band which has counted among its members some of the most famous blues and blues rock musicians.
simple: John Mayall, OBE (born 29 November 1933) is an English blues singer, guitarist, organist and songwriter, whose musical career spans over fifty years. <s> In the 1960s, he was the founder of John Mayall & the Bluesbreakers, a band which has included some of the most famous blues and blues rock musicians.

title: Maple syrup urine disease
complex: Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is an autosomal recessive metabolic disorder affecting branched-chain amino acids. <s> It is one type of organic acidemia. <s> The condition gets its name from the distinctive sweet odor of affected infants' urine, particularly prior to diagnosis, and during times of acute illness. <s> Infants with this disease seem healthy at birth but quickly deteriorate, often with severe brain damage, which may be permanent. <s> Death often occurs within the first five months in severe cases of the disease, when left untreated. <s> Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is a rare, inherited metabolic disorder. <s> Its prevalence in the United States population is approximately 1 newborn out of 180,000 live births. <s> However, in populations where there is a higher frequency of consanguinity, such as the Mennonites in Pennsylvania or the Amish, the frequency of MSUD is significantly higher at 1 newborn out of 176 live births. <s> In Austria, 1 newborn out of 250,000 live births inherits MSUD. <s> It also is believed to have a higher prevalence in certain populations due in part to the founder effect since MSUD has a much higher prevalence in children of Amish, Mennonite, and Jewish descent.
simple: Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is a genetic medical disorder. <s> Maple syrup urine disease affects about 1 in 185,000 infants worldwide. <s> The most noticeable symptom of the disorder is an infant with sweet-smelling urine. <s> Infants with this disease seem healthy at birth. <s> The urine of infants with this disease has a very sweet odor, much like burned caramel or maple syrup. <s> MSUD is much more common in children of Amish and Mennonite descent.

title: Attalla, Alabama
complex: Attalla is a city in Etowah County, Alabama, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 6,048.
simple: Attalla is a city in Etowah County, Alabama, United States.

title: Atsushi Natori
complex: Atsushi Natori (名取 篤 , Natori Atsushi , born November 12, 1961) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Atsushi Natori (名取 篤, Natori Atsushi, born November 12, 1961) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: ZDF
complex: Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen (] ; ), usually shortened to ZDF (] , stylized as 2DF), is a German public-service television broadcaster based in Mainz, Rhineland-Palatinate. <s> It is run as an independent nonprofit institution, which was founded by all federal states of Germany ("Bundesländer").
simple: Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen is the second public broadcasting coorparation that was founded in Germany.

title: Ray Mathews
complex: Raymond Dyral Mathews (February 26, 1929 – December 20, 2015) was an American football halfback and end in the National Football League (NFL) for the Pittsburgh Steelers and the Dallas Cowboys. <s> He played college football for Clemson University.
simple: Raymond Dyral Mathews (February 26, 1929 – December 20, 2015) was an American football running back and wide receiver in the National Football League for the Pittsburgh Steelers (1951-59) and the Dallas Cowboys (1960). <s> He played college football for Clemson University.

title: New Orleans blues
complex: As a style New Orleans blues is primarily driven by piano and horn, enlivened by Caribbean rhythms and Dixieland music. <s> It is generally cheerful in delivery regardless of the subject matter, with a laid back tempo and complex rhythms falling just behind the beat.
simple: New Orleans blues is a mix of Dixieland music and rhythms from Caribbean music.

title: Decapoda
complex: The Decapoda or decapods (literally "ten-footed") are an order of crustaceans within the class Malacostraca, including many familiar groups, such as crayfish, crabs, lobsters, prawns, and shrimp. <s> Most decapods are scavengers. <s> The order is estimated to contain nearly 15,000 species in around 2,700 genera, with around 3,300 fossil species. <s> Nearly half of these species are crabs, with the shrimp (about 3000 species) and Anomura including hermit crabs, porcelain crabs, squat lobsters (about 2500 species) making up the bulk of the remainder. <s> The earliest fossil decapod is the Devonian "Palaeopalaemon". <s> Decapods can have as many as 38 appendages, arranged in one pair per body segment. <s> As the name Decapoda (from the Greek , " ", "ten", and , "-pod", "foot") implies, ten of these appendages are considered legs. <s> They are the pereiopods, found on the last five thoracic segments. <s> In many decapods, one pair of these "legs" has enlarged pincers, called chelae, with the legs being called chelipeds. <s> In front of the pereiopods are three pairs of maxillipeds which function as feeding appendages. <s> The head has five pairs of appendages, including mouthparts, antennae, and antennules. <s> There are five more pairs of appendages on the abdomen. <s> They are called pleopods. <s> There is one final pair called uropods, which, with the telson, form the tail fan. <s> Classification within the order Decapoda depends on the structure of the gills and legs, and the way in which the larvae develop, giving rise to two suborders: Dendrobranchiata and Pleocyemata. <s> The Dendrobranchiata consist of prawns, including many species colloquially referred to as "shrimp", such as the "white shrimp", "Litopenaeus setiferus". <s> The Pleocyemata include the remaining groups, including "true shrimp". <s> Those groups which usually walk rather than swim (Pleocyemata, excluding Stenopodidea and Caridea) form a clade called Reptantia.
simple: Decapoda is an order of crustaceans in the class Malacostraca. <s> Many familiar groups, such as crayfish, crabs, lobsters, prawns and shrimp are in this order. <s> Many decapods are scavengers - they eat dead plants and animals. <s> As their name suggests, all decapods have ten appendages. <s> In many decapods, the front pair of appendages carry large pinching claws. <s> The claws are called "chelae", so these appendages may be called "chelipeds". <s> The front three pairs of appendages on the thorax are used as jaws, and called "maxillipeds". <s> On the abdomen are swimming appendages called "pleopods", and the body ends in a tail fan. <s> Classification of the order Decapoda depends on the structure of the gills and legs, and the way in which the larvae develop. <s> There are two suborders: Dendrobranchiata and Pleocyemata. <s> Prawns (including many so-called "shrimp", such as the Atlantic white shrimp) make up the Dendrobranchiata. <s> The other groups, including true shrimp, are the Pleocyemata.

title: Eino Leino
complex: Eino Leino (birth name Armas Einar Leopold Lönnbohm) (6 July 1878 – 10 January 1926) was a Finnish poet and journalist and is considered one of the pioneers of Finnish poetry. <s> His poems combine modern and Finnish folk elements. <s> The style of much of his work is like the "Kalevala" and folk songs. <s> Nature, love, and despair are frequent themes in Leino's work. <s> He is beloved and widely read in Finland today.
simple: Eino Leino (6 July 1878 – 10 January 1926) was a Finnish poet and journalist. <s> He is considered to be one of the pioneers of Finnish poetry. <s> His poems combine modern and Finnish folk elements. <s> The style of much of his work is like the "Kalevala" and folk songs. <s> He was known for writing about love, sadness, and about nature.

title: Yurik Vardanyan
complex: Yuri Norayrovich Vardanyan ( ; , also transliterated Yurik Vardanian, 13 June 1956 – 1 November 2018) was a Soviet weightlifter. <s> Vardanyan won a gold medal at the 1980 Summer Olympics, becoming the world's first weightlifter to achieve a 400 kilogram total in the 82.5 kg weight category. <s> During his career he set several world records. <s> He trained at Lokomotiv in Leninakan, Armenia. <s> He earned the title Honoured Master of Sports of the USSR in 1977 and was awarded the Order of Lenin in 1985. <s> In 1994 he was elected a member of the International Weightlifting Federation Hall of Fame. <s> Vardanyan was born on 13 June 1956 in Leninakan, Armenian SSR (now Gyumri, Armenia), a city well known for its weightlifters. <s> He began weight training in 1970 under the guidance of his uncle Sergey Vardanyan. <s> Yuri Vardanyan died on 1 November 2018 at the age of 62. <s> On 2 April 2009 Vardayan was appointed as an advisor to President Serzh Sargsyan.
simple: Yuri Norayrovich Vardanyan (; , also transliterated Yurik Vardanian, 13 June 1956 – 1 November 2018) was a Soviet-Armenian weightlifter. <s> Vardanyan won a gold medal at the 1980 Summer Olympics, becoming the world's first weightlifter to win a 400 kilogram total in the 82.5 kg weight category. <s> During his career he set several world records. <s> In 1994 he was elected member of the International Weightlifting Federation Hall of Fame. <s> He was born in Leninakan, Soviet Union (now Gyumri, Armenia). <s> Vardanyan in Yerevan, Armenia on 1 November 2018 from a pulmonary embolism at the age of 89. <s> On 2 April 2009 he was appointed as President Serzh Sargsyan's adviser.

title: Chapel Hill, North Carolina
complex: Chapel Hill is a town in Orange, Chatham, and Durham counties in the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> Its population was 57,233 in the 2010 census, making Chapel Hill the 15th-largest city in the state. <s> Chapel Hill, Durham, and the state capital, Raleigh, make up the corners of the Research Triangle (officially the Raleigh–Durham–Chapel Hill combined statistical area), with a total population of 1,998,808. <s> Chapel Hill is located in the southeast corner of Orange County. <s> It is bounded on the west by the town of Carrboro and on the northeast by the city of Durham.
simple: Chapel Hill is a town in the U.S. state of North Carolina. <s> It is in an area called The Triangle, because it is next to Raleigh and Durham. <s> Chapel Hill is in southeastern Orange County.

title: Fuzzy Knight
complex: John Forrest "Fuzzy" Knight (May 9, 1901 – February 23, 1976) was an American film and television actor. <s> He was also a singer, especially in his early career. <s> He appeared in more than 180 films between 1928 and 1967, usually as a cowboy hero's comic sidekick. <s> Knight became famous to a new generation when he co-starred as Buster Crabbe's sidekick (using his own name as Private Fuzzy Knight) on the 1955 television series "Captain Gallant of the Foreign Legion". <s> In semi-retirement thereafter, Knight continued to make occasional appearances in films and TV shows through 1967. <s> He died in his sleep at the Motion Picture Country House and Hospital in Woodland Hills, California, and was survived by his wife, actress Patricia Ryan (née Thelma de Long). <s> He was buried in Valhalla Memorial Park Cemetery in Burbank, California.
simple: John Forrest "Fuzzy" Knight (May 9, 1901 – February 23, 1976) was an American actor. <s> He appeared mostly in westerns, usually as the hero's friend. <s> He also appeared in the 1950s television series, "Captain Gallant of the Foreign Legion". <s> He married actress Patricia Ryan (née Thelma de Long).

title: The Butler
complex: The Butler (full title Lee Daniels' The Butler) is a 2013 American historical drama film directed and co-produced by Lee Daniels and with a screenplay by Danny Strong. <s> It is inspired by Wil Haygood's "Washington Post" article "A Butler Well Served by This Election". <s> Loosely based on the real life of Eugene Allen, who worked in the White House for decades, the film stars Forest Whitaker as Cecil Gaines, an African-American who is a witness of notable political and social events of the 20th century during his 34-year tenure serving as a White House butler. <s> In addition to Whitaker, the film's all-star cast also features Oprah Winfrey, John Cusack, Jane Fonda, Alex Pettyfer, Cuba Gooding Jr., Terrence Howard, Lenny Kravitz, James Marsden, David Oyelowo, Vanessa Redgrave, Alan Rickman, Liev Schreiber, Robin Williams, Minka Kelly, Mariah Carey, and Clarence Williams III. <s> It was the last film produced by Laura Ziskin, who died in 2011.
simple: Lee Daniels' The Butler is a 2013 American historical drama movie directed by Lee Daniels. <s> The fictional Cecil Gaines is based on Eugene Allen who worked at the White House during eight presidential terms from 1952 to 1986. <s> It was the last movie produced by Laura Ziskin.

title: Čejov
complex: Čajev is a small village near Humpolec in the Pelhřimov District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> 473 people live there and it covers 7,98 km2 of land.
simple: Čajev is small village near Humpolec in the Havlíčkův Brod District, Vysočina Region of the Czech Republic. <s> 473 people live there and it has 7,98 km2.

title: Beatrice Mintz
complex: Beatrice Mintz (born January 24, 1921 in New York City) is an American embryologist who has contributed to the understanding of genetic modification, cellular differentiation and cancer, particularly melanoma.Mintz was a pioneer of genetic engineering techniques, and was among the first scientists to generate both chimeric and transgenic mammals. <s> In 1996 she shared the inaugural March of Dimes Prize in Developmental Biology with Ralph L. Brinster for their work in developing transgenic mice. <s> Much of her career has been spent at the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia where, in 2002, she was named to the Jack Schultz Chair in Basic Science. <s> Mintz is a member of both the United States National Academy of Sciences and the Pontifical Academy of Sciences.
simple: Beatrice Mintz (born January 24, 1921) is an American embryologist who has helped to the understanding of genetic modification, cellular differentiation and cancer, particularly melanoma. <s> Mintz was a pioneer of genetic engineering techniques, and was among the first scientists to generate both chimeric and transgenic mammals. <s> Mintz was born on January 24, 1921 in New York City. <s> In 1996 she shared the inaugural March of Dimes Prize in Developmental Biology with Ralph L. Brinster for their work in developing transgenic mice. <s> Much of her career has been spent at the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia where, in 2002, she was named to the Jack Schultz Chair in Basic Science. <s> Mintz is a member of both the United States National Academy of Sciences and the Pontifical Academy of Sciences.

title: Museum for Architectural Drawing
complex: The Museum for Architectural Drawing is a private museum in Berlin, Germany run by the Tchoban Foundation. <s> It was opened in June 2013. <s> Three to four exhibitions are shown each year, made up of drawings from the Tchoban Foundation’s collection and from works on loan in cooperation with other museums and institutions.
simple: Museum for Architectural Drawing (in German: Museum für Architekturzeichnung) is a private museum in Berlin, Germany dedicated to Architectural Drawing around the world. <s> the museum was open in 2013.

title: Mansfield
complex: Mansfield is a market town in Nottinghamshire, England, the main town in the District of Mansfield and Mansfield Urban Area. <s> Nestling in the Maun Valley surrounded by hills, it lies 12 mi north of Nottingham in a largely urban district, most of whose 106,556 population live in Mansfield (including Mansfield Woodhouse), with Market Warsop a secondary centre.
simple: Mansfield is a town in Nottinghamshire, England.

title: AD 19
complex: AD 19 (XIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Silanus and Balbus (or, less frequently, year 772 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination AD 19 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: It was a common year starting on Sunday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Silanus and Balbus.

title: Laura Chinchilla
complex: Laura Chinchilla Miranda (] ; born 28 March 1959) is a Costa Rican politician who was President of Costa Rica from 2010 to 2014. <s> She was one of Óscar Arias Sánchez's two Vice-Presidents and his administration's Minister of Justice. <s> She was the governing PLN candidate for President in the 2010 general election, where she won with 46.76% of the vote on 7 February. <s> She was the eighth woman president of a Latin American country and the first woman to become President of Costa Rica. <s> She was sworn in as President of Costa Rica on May 8, 2010. <s> Chinchilla was born in Carmen Central, San José in 1959. <s> She is the daughter of Rafael Ángel Chinchilla Fallas, a former comptroller of Costa Rica, and Emilce Miranda Castillo. <s> She married Mario Alberto Madrigal Díaz on 23 January 1982 and divorced on 22 May 1985. <s> Chinchilla met her second husband, José María Rico Cueto, a Spanish lawyer who held Canadian citizenship, in 1990 while both were working as consultants for the Center for the Administration of Justice at the University of Florida in Miami, Florida. <s> The couple had a son, José María Rico Chinchilla, in 1996. <s> Chinchilla married Rico on 26 March 2000. <s> Chinchilla graduated from the University of Costa Rica and received her master's degree in public policy from Georgetown University. <s> Prior to entering politics, Chinchilla worked as an NGO consultant in Latin America and Africa, specializing in judicial reform and public security issues. <s> She went on to serve in the José María Figueres Olsen administration as vice-minister for public security (1994–1996) and minister of public security (1996–1998). <s> From 2002 to 2006, she served in the National Assembly as a deputy for the province of San José. <s> Chinchilla was one of two vice-presidents elected under the second Arias administration (2006–2010). <s> She resigned the vice-presidency in 2008 in order to prepare her run for the presidency in 2010. <s> On 7 June 2009 she won the Partido Liberación Nacional (PLN) primary with a 15% margin over her nearest rival, and was thus endorsed as the party's presidential candidate.
simple: Laura Chinchilla Miranda (born 28 March 1959) served as the President of Costa Rica from 2010 to 2014. <s> She was one of Óscar Arias Sánchez's two vice presidents. <s> She was his administration's Minister of Justice. <s> She was the governing PLN candidate for President in the 2010 general election. <s> She won with 46.76% of the vote. <s> She is Costa Rica's first female president. <s> She is the sixth woman to be elected president of a Latin American country. <s> Chinchilla was born in Carmen Central, San José in 1959. <s> Her father was Rafael Ángel Chinchilla Fallas. <s> Her mother was Emilce Miranda Castillo. <s> She married Mario Alberto Madrigal Díaz on 23 January 1982 and divorced on 22 May 1985. <s> She had a son in 1996 with José María Rico Cueto, a Spanish lawyer who has a Canadian citizenship; Chinchilla married him on 26 March 2000. <s> Chinchilla graduated from the University of Costa Rica. <s> She received her master's degree in public policy from Georgetown University. <s> Before politics, Chinchilla worked as a NGO consultant in Latin America and Africa. <s> She specialized in judicial reform and public security. <s> She served in the José María Figueres Olsen administration as vice-minister for public security (1994–1996) and minister of public security (1996–1998). <s> From 2002 to 2006, she served in the National Assembly as a deputy for the province of San José. <s> Chinchilla was one of two vice-presidents elected under the second Arias administration (2006–2010). <s> She resigned the vice-presidency in 2008 in order to prepare her run for the presidency in 2010. <s> On 7 June 2009 she won the Partido Liberación Nacional (PLN) primary with a 15% margin over her nearest rival, and was thus endorsed as the party's presidential candidate.

title: 2028 Summer Olympics
complex: The 2028 Summer Olympics, officially known as the Games of the XXXIV Olympiad, and commonly known as Los Angeles 2028/LA 2028, is a forthcoming international multi-sport event that is scheduled to take place from July 21 to August 6, 2028, in Los Angeles, California, United States. <s> The process of bidding for the host city was originally scheduled to begin in 2019, with the winning bid due to be announced in 2021. <s> However, following the withdrawal of a number of cities from the bidding process for both the 2022 Winter Olympics and the 2024 Summer Olympics, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) resolved in July 2017 to jointly award both the 2024 and 2028 Games. <s> Thus on July 31, 2017, an agreement was reached wherein Los Angeles would bid for the 2028 Games with $1.8 billion of additional funding from the IOC, which then cleared the way for Paris to be confirmed as host of the 2024 Games. <s> Both cities were formally announced as winners of their respective Games at the 131st IOC Session in Lima, Peru, on September 13, 2017. <s> The bid was praised by the IOC for using a record-breaking number of existing and temporary facilities and relying on corporate money.
simple: The 2028 Summer Olympics, which will be officially known as the Games of the XXXIV Olympiad, is a sporting event that will happen from July 21 to August 6 in Los Angeles, California, United States. <s> Applying to host the games was supposed to begin in 2019. <s> The host city was supposed to be announced in 2021. <s> In July 2017, The International Olympic Committee decided to award 2024 and 2028 Games at the same time. <s> On July 31, 2017, an agreement was announced that Los Angeles would apply to host the 2028 Summer Olympics. <s> On September 13, 2017, the hosts for both Olympic games was announced at the 131st IOC Session in Lima, Peru.

title: Austral thrush
complex: The austral thrush ("Turdus falcklandii") is a medium-sized thrush from southern South America. <s> There are two subspecies, the Magellan thrush ("T. f. magellanicus") from south Argentina and south and central Chile, and the Falkland thrush ("T. f. falcklandii") from the Falkland Islands.
simple: Austral thrush ("Turdus falcklandii magellanicus") is a common bird found in southern South America.

title: Ottmarsheim
complex: Ottmarsheim is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France, on Highway 9 just across the Rhein River from its terminus at the German Autobahn Steinenstadt interchange.
simple: Ottmarsheim is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France, on Highway 9 just across the Rhine River from its terminus at the German Autobahn Steinenstadt interchange.

title: Lake Mweru
complex: Lake Mweru (also spelled "Mwelu", "Mwero") is a freshwater lake on the longest arm of Africa's second-longest river, the Congo. <s> Located on the border between Zambia and Democratic Republic of the Congo, it makes up 110 km of the total length of the Congo, lying between its Luapula River (upstream) and Luvua River (downstream) segments. <s> Mweru means 'lake' in a number of Bantu languages, so it is often referred to as just 'Mweru'. <s> The move of the boma from Chiengi to Kalungwishi had the effect of leaving the Belgian boma at Pweto a free rein at the northern end of the lake, leading a hundred years later to about 33 km2 of Zambian territory next to Pweto being ceded to the DR Congo (then Zaire). <s> See the Luapula Province border dispute for further details and references.
simple: Lake Mweru is a freshwater lake on the Congo River. <s> It is on the border between the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Zambia. <s> The lake makes up 110 km of the border. <s> 'Mweru' means 'lake' in many Bantu languages, so the lake is often just called Mweru. <s> This border dispute is known as Luapula Province border dispute.

title: Prajñā (Buddhism)
complex: Prajñā (Sanskrit) or paññā (Pāli) "wisdom" is insight in the true nature of reality, namely primarily anicca (impermanence), dukkha (dissatisfaction or suffering), and anattā (non-self). <s> In addition, Abhidharma and later Mahāyāna text may include suññatā (Skt; Eng: emptiness).
simple: Prajna is a Buddhist word meaning wisdom.

title: Line of succession to the Bahraini throne
complex: Succession to the Bahraini throne is determined by primogeniture amongst the male descendants of Sheikh Isa bin Ali Al Khalifa (1848 – 1932). <s> However, the ruling King of Bahrain has the right to appoint any of his other sons as his successor if he wishes to. <s> The current ruler of Bahrain is King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifah. <s> After Isa bin Muhammad Al Khalifa come firstly the descendants of Hakim Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, and then last in line the descendants of Hakim Isa bin Ali Al Khalifa.
simple: Succession to the Bahraini throne is done by primogeniture from the male descendants of Sheikh Isa bin Ali Al Khalifa (1848 – 1932). <s> However, the ruling King of Bahrain can select any of his other sons as his successor if he wishes to. <s> The current ruler of Bahrain is King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifah. <s> After Sheikh Isa bin Muhammad Al Khalifa come firstly the descendants of Hakim Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, and then last in line the descendants of Hakim Isa bin Ali Al Khalifa.

title: Leulinghem
complex: Leulinghem is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Leulinghem is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Marjoram
complex: Marjoram ( ; Origanum majorana) is a somewhat cold-sensitive perennial herb or undershrub with sweet pine and citrus flavors. <s> In some Middle Eastern countries, marjoram is synonymous with oregano, and there the names sweet marjoram and knotted marjoram are used to distinguish it from other plants of the genus "Origanum". <s> It is also called pot marjoram, although this name is also used for other cultivated species of "Origanum".
simple: Whoa Black Betty Marjoram ("Origanum majorana", Lamiaceae) is a somewhat cold-sensitive perennial herb or undershrub with sweet pine and citrus flavours. <s> In some middle-eastern countries, marjoram is synonymous with oregano, and there the names sweet Black Betty had a child marjoram and the damn thing gone wild knotted marjoram are used to distinguish it from other plants.

title: Sunny Murray
complex: James Marcellus Arthur "Sunny" Murray (September 21, 1936 – December 7, 2017) was one of the pioneers of the free jazz style of drumming. <s> Murray was born in Idabel, Oklahoma and spent his youth in Philadelphia before moving to New York City where he began playing with Cecil Taylor: "We played for about a year, just practicing, studying — we went to workshops with Varèse, did a lot of creative things, just experimenting, without a job" He was featured on the influential 1962 concerts in Denmark released as "Nefertiti the Beautiful One Has Come". <s> He later recorded under his own name for ESP-Disk and then when he moved to Europe for BYG Actuel. <s> Murray died on December 7, 2017 from unspecified causes at the age of 81.
simple: James Marcellus Arthur "Sunny" Murray (September 21, 1936 – December 8, 2017) was an American jazz drummer. <s> He was one of the pioneers of the free jazz style of drumming. <s> He was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. <s> He later recorded under his own name for ESP-Disk and then when he moved to Europe for BYG Actuel. <s> Murray died on December 8, 2017 from unspecified causes at the age of 81.

title: Caitlin McHugh
complex: Caitlin Maureen McHugh (born May 13, 1986) is an American actress, writer, and model. <s> McHugh is signed with Wilhelmina Models. <s> In 2016, she appeared in television commercials for Colgate toothpaste and the following year, for the Buick "Encore". <s> On October 23, 2017, McHugh announced her engagement to actor John Stamos after a year of dating. <s> In December 2017, the couple announced they were expecting their first child, due in the spring of 2018. <s> Stamos and McHugh married in February 2018. <s> On April 15, 2018, Stamos announced the birth of their first son, Billy, named after John's father.
simple: Caitlin McHugh (born May 13, 1986) is an American actress, writer and model. <s> McHugh is signed with Wilhelmina Models. <s> In 2016, she appeared in television commercials for Colgate toothpaste. <s> On October 23, 2017, McHugh announced her engagement to actor John Stamos after a year of dating. <s> Stamos and McHugh married in February 2018.

title: Jacques Marquette
complex: Father Jacques Marquette S.J. (June 1, 1637 – May 18, 1675), sometimes known as Père Marquette or James Marquette, was a French-American Jesuit missionary who founded Michigan's first European settlement, Sault Ste. Marie, and later founded St. Ignace, Michigan. <s> In 1673, Father Marquette and Louis Jolliet were the first Europeans to explore and map the northern portion of the Mississippi River Valley.
simple: Father Jacques Marquette S.J. (June 1, 1637 – May 18, 1675), sometimes known as Père Marquette or James Marquette, was a French Jesuit missionary. <s> He founded Michigan's first European settlement, Sault Ste. Marie, and later founded St. Ignace, Michigan. <s> In 1673 Father Marquette and Louis Jolliet were the first Europeans to explore and map the northern portion of the Mississippi River Valley.

title: Aharon Lichtenstein
complex: Aharon Lichtenstein (May 23, 1933 – April 20, 2015) was a noted Orthodox rabbi and rosh yeshiva. <s> He was an authority in Jewish law ("Halakha"). <s> Rabbi Lichtenstein was born in Paris, France, but grew up in the United States, studied in Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin under Rabbi Yitzchok Hutner. <s> He earned a BA and "semicha" ("rabbinic ordination") at Yeshiva University under Rabbi Joseph B.
