Soloveitchik, whose daughter, Tovah, he would later marry, and a PhD in English Literature at Harvard University, where he studied under Douglas Bush. <s> In 2005, he and his wife Dr. Tovah (née Soloveitchik) moved to Alon Shvut, where Yeshivat Har Etzion is located. <s> They were married in 1960 and had six children. <s> Lichtenstein was awarded the Israel Prize for Jewish Literature on Israeli Independence Day: May 6, 2014. <s> He died on April 20, 2015. <s> He was a source of inspiration for a wide circle of Jewry, for both his educational attainments and his intellectual and spiritual leadership.
simple: Aharon Lichtenstein (23 May 1933 – 20 April 2015) was a French-born American-Israeli Orthodox rabbi, rosh yeshiva and writer. <s> He was an authority of Jewish law ("Halacha"). <s> Lichtenstein was born in Paris and grew up in New York, United States. <s> He studied at Yeshiva University and Harvard University. <s> He married in 1960 and had six children. <s> He won the Israel Prize in 2014. <s> Lichtenstein died on 20 April 2015 in Jerusalem, aged 81.

title: Nebling
complex: Nebling is a small village in the municipality of Untergriesbach in the District of Passau in Lower Bavaria, Germany.
simple: Nebling is a small village in Passau, Lower Bavaria, Germany.

title: Casualty (person)
complex: A casualty, as a term in military usage, is a person in military service, combatant or non-combatant, who becomes unavailable for duty due to several circumstances, including death, injury, illness, capture or desertion. <s> In civilian usage, a casualty is a person who is killed, wounded or incapacitated by some event; the term is usually used to describe multiple deaths and injuries due to violent incidents or disasters. <s> It is sometimes misunderstood to mean "fatalities", but non-fatal injuries are also casualties. <s> In military usage, a "casualty" is a person in service killed in action, killed by disease, disabled by injuries, disabled by psychological trauma, captured, deserted, or missing, but not someone who sustains injuries which do not prevent them from fighting.
simple: A casualty in military usage is a person in military service, who becomes unavailable for duty due to death or injury. <s> It also includes illness, capture, desertion, etc.; or a civilian casualty. <s> In civilian usage the word "casualty" is properly used for a person who is killed, wounded or injured by some event. <s> It is usually used to describe multiple deaths and injuries due to violent incidents or disasters. <s> "Casualties" is sometimes loosely used to mean "fatalities", but non-fatal injuries are also casualties.

title: Egypt Standard Time
complex: On 21 April 2011, the interim government abolished summer time. <s> The standard time was used the whole year round, with no change in summer.
simple: EET was then used all year, with no summer time change.

title: Patrice Talon
complex: Patrice Guillaume Athanase Talon (born 1 May 1958) is a Beninese businessman and politician who has been President of Benin since 6 April 2016.
simple: Patrice Guillaume Athanase Talon (born 1 May 1958) is a Beninese businessman and politician. <s> He has been President of Benin since 6 April 2016.

title: Aurangzeb
complex: Muhi-ud-Din Muhammad (3 November 16183 March 1707), commonly known by the sobriquet Aurangzeb (Persian: "Ornament of the Throne") or by his regnal title Alamgir (Persian: "Conqueror of the World"), was the sixth Mughal emperor, who ruled over almost the entire South Asia for a period of 49 years. <s> Widely considered to be the last effective major ruler of the Mughal Empire, Aurangzeb compiled the Fatawa-e-Alamgiri, and was among the few monarchs to have fully established Sharia law and Islamic economics throughout the Indian subcontinent. <s> He was an accomplished military leader whose rule has been the subject of praise, though he has also been described as the most controversial ruler in Indian history. <s> He was a notable expansionist; during his reign, the Mughal Empire reached its greatest extent, ruling over nearly all of the Indian subcontinent. <s> During his lifetime, victories in the south expanded the Mughal Empire to 4 million square kilometres, and he ruled over a population estimated to be over 158 million subjects, with an annual revenue of $450 million (more than ten times that of his contemporary Louis XIV of France), or £38,624,680 (2,879,469,894 rupees) in 1690. <s> Under his reign, India surpassed Qing China to become the world's largest economy and biggest manufacturing power, worth nearly a quarter of global GDP and more than the entirety of Western Europe, and its largest and wealthiest subdivision, the Bengal Subah, signaled the proto-industrialization. <s> By 1689, the conquest of Golconda, Mughal victories in the south expanded the Mughal Empire to 4 million square kilometres, with a population estimated to be over 158 million. <s> But this supremacy was short-lived. <s> Jos Gommans, Professor of Colonial and Global History at the University of Leiden, says that "... the highpoint of imperial centralisation under emperor Aurangzeb coincided with the start of the imperial downfall." <s> Many Indian historians consider his death year 1707 as the one which marks the end of Medieval Indian history and the start of Modern Indian history when classifying Indian history. <s> This is because of the start of decline of the Mughal empire and the start of domination of European powers in India.
simple: Muhi-ud-Din Muhammad also known as Aurangzeb or by his title Alamgir was the sixth emperor of the Mughal Empire. <s> His reign lasted for 49 years from 1658 until his death in 1707. <s> He compiled the Fatawa Alamgiri, which served as the Islamic law of India. <s> During this time, Aurangzeb greatly expanded the territory of the Mughal Empire. <s> Victories in the south expanded the Empire to more than 3.2 million square kilometres. <s> His empire was the world's largest economy, valued 25% of world's GDP. <s> After his death, the power of the Mughal Empire declined quickly.

title: Jim Whittaker
complex: James W. Whittaker (born February 10, 1929), also known as Jim Whittaker, is an American mountaineer and mountain guide. <s> Born and raised in Seattle, Washington, on May 1, 1963 he became the first American to reach the summit of Mount Everest as a member of the American Mount Everest Expedition led by Norman Dyhrenfurth, alongside the Sherpa Nawang Gombu (a nephew of Tenzing Norgay). <s> They ran out of oxygen but managed to reach the summit. <s> Once there, Whittaker planted a U.S. flag at the top.
simple: James W. Whittaker (born February 10, 1929), also known as Jim Whittaker, is an American mountaineer, autobiographer and mountain guide. <s> On May 1, 1963 he became the first American to reach the summit of Mount Everest as a member of the American Mount Everest Expedition led by Norman Dyhrenfurth. <s> They ran out of oxygen but managed to reach the summit. <s> Once there, Whittaker planted a U.S. flag at the top.

title: Sugarland
complex: Sugarland is an American country music duo consisting of singer-songwriters Jennifer Nettles (lead vocals) and Kristian Bush (vocals, guitar, mandolin). <s> Sugarland was founded in 2002 by Kristen Hall (vocals, guitar) with Bush and became a trio after hiring Jennifer Nettles.

title: Alfons Schuhbeck
complex: Alfons Schuhbeck (born on May 2, 1949) is one of Germany's top chefs, as well as being a restaurateur, celebrity chef, author and businessman. <s> Born "Alfons Karg", he trained as a telecommunications technician, but soon became disenchanted with this profession. <s> While playing with his band in the Bavarian holiday resort of Waging am See, he ran into the restaurateur Sebastian Schuhbeck. <s> This man committed Alfons in a career in the hospitality business and became his mentor. <s> Sebastian Schubeck later adopted Alfons and made him his heir. <s> He studied at the "College of Hotel Management Bad Reichenhall" in Bavaria. <s> After that he went through practical training in Salzburg, Geneva, Paris, London and Munich (in Eckart Witzigmanns three stars awarded "Aubergine"). <s> He finally took the "Kurhausstüberl" from his mentor in 1980. <s> Alfons was the driving force in Sebastian Schuhbeck's business. <s> His chef skills impressed the guests of the "Kurhausstüberl" in a way, that this former village inn became a favourite restaurant for the upper society of Munich and Salzburg. <s> In 1983 he was awarded with one star in the French Michelin Guide, as the third chef outside France at this time. <s> The also French Gault Millau restaurant guide gave him 17 points and 3 hoods and elected him "Cook of the year" in 1989. <s> Since 1990 Schubeck has operated a catering service and supplied many first-class events like the Federal Chancellor’s celebration, the "Ball des Sports" and the German music industry's "ECHO" award ceremony. <s> In 2003 he established a new restaurant, the "Südtiroler Stuben" in Munich. <s> There he won his second Michelin star in December 2003. <s> In November 2005 he was awarded with the "Five Star Diamond Award" by the American Academy of Hospitality Sciences. <s> German TV-Station Bayerischer Rundfunk has broadcast his show "Schuhbecks" since 1993. <s> His popularity in Germany results in this as well as publishing more than 20 books about cooking. <s> He is also a regular guest in other German TV shows. <s> During the 1990s Schuhbeck amassed up to DM 60 million from business partners for capital investments. <s> Dubious practices such as being solely responsible for several millions of DM invested in an account with the Citibank Monte Carlo resulted in court proceedings, Schuhbeck being indicted for fraud. <s> The court found the business practices unusual but not illegal, and he was exonerated. <s> At the end of the 1990s he set up "Schuhbecks GmbH". <s> This company now includes the restaurant "Südtiroler Stuben", a wine bistro, the catering service, a cookery school, a spice shop and an ice-cream parlour, all based in Munich. <s> "Schuhbeck Check Inn GmbH" was formed in 2001 to manage the "Check Inn restaurant and bar" in Egelsbach (south Hesse).

title: John J. Farrell
complex: John J. Farrell (1872 - July 22, 1946) was the Dairy and Food Commissioner of Minnesota in 1917 and president of the National Creamery Buttermakers' Association. <s> By 1921 he was the secretary of National Dairy Products. <s> He was the unsuccessful Democratic candidate in the United States Senate elections of 1924 for senator from Minnesota. <s> He was the Minnesota Democratic state chair in 1931. <s> He was born in 1872 in Ohio to Daniel Farrell and Mary Guyton, both Irish immigrant parents. <s> They migrated to Minnesota in 1886. <s> He married in August 1901 Mabel Sanborn of Faribault, Minnesota, a daughter of W. title: Jack Welch
complex: John Francis "Jack" Welch Jr. (born November 19, 1935) is an American business executive, author, and chemical engineer. <s> He was chairman and CEO of General Electric between 1981 and 2001. <s> During his tenure at GE, the company's value rose 4,000%. <s> In 2006, Welch's net worth was estimated at $720 million. <s> When he retired from GE he received a severance payment of $417 million, the largest such payment in history.
simple: John Francis "Jack" Welch Jr. (born November 19, 1935) is an American retired business executive, author, and chemical engineer. <s> He was chairman and CEO of General Electric between 1981 and 2001. <s> In 2006, Welch's net worth was estimated at $720 million. <s> When he retired from GE he received a severance payment of $417 million, the largest such payment in history.

title: Jorge Mendonça (footballer, born 1954)
complex: Jorge Pinto Mendonça (June 6, 1954 – February 17, 2006) was a famous Brazilian footballer during the 1970s and 1980s, playing in a striker role.

title: Alexander Varshavsky
complex: Alexander Jacob Varshavsky ( ; born 8 November 1946) is a Russian-American biochemist, noted for his discovery of the N-end rule of ubiquitination. <s> A native of Moscow, he is currently researching at Caltech. <s> In 2014 he was awarded the $3 million Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences for his work and also the Albany Medical Center Prize.

title: Ronald Paulson
complex: Ronald Howard Paulson (born May 27, 1930 in Bottineau, North Dakota) is an American professor of English, a specialist in English 18th-century art and culture, and English artist William Hogarth. <s> Paulson has taught and held various administrative positions at several universities in the United States, including the University of Illinois from 1959 to 1963 and Rice University from 1963 to 1967. <s> He was the Chairman of the Johns Hopkins University English Department from 1967 to 1975. <s> From 1975 to 1984 he was a professor at Yale University and served as the Director of Graduate Studies in the English Department from 1976 to 1983 and the Director of the British Studies Program from 1976 to 1984. <s> He has been a member of the editorial board of the academic journal "ELH: English Literary History" and was senior editor from 1985 to 2004; he served on the editorial boards of the journals "Studies in English Literature"; PMLA; "Eighteenth-Century Studies"; and the Johns Hopkins University Press.
simple: Ronald Paulson (born May 27, 1930) is an American professor of English, a specialist in English 18th-century art and culture, and English artist William Hogarth. <s> Paulson was born in Bottineau, North Dakota. <s> Paulson has taught and held many administrative positions at several universities in the United States, including the University of Illinois from 1959 to 1963 and Rice University from 1963 to 1967. <s> He was the Chairman of the Johns Hopkins University English Department from 1967 to 1975. <s> From 1975 to 1984 he was a professor at Yale University and served as the Director of Graduate Studies in the English Department from 1976 to 1983 and the Director of the British Studies Program from 1976 to 1984. <s> He has been a member of the editorial board of the academic journal "ELH: English Literary History" and was senior editor from 1985 to 2004; he served on the editorial boards of the journals "Studies in English Literature"; PMLA; "Eighteenth-Century Studies"; and the Johns Hopkins University Press.

title: 2016 Nice truck attack
complex: On the evening of 14 July 2016, a 19-tonne cargo truck was deliberately driven into crowds of people celebrating Bastille Day on the Promenade des Anglais in Nice, France, resulting in the deaths of 86 people and the injury of 458 others. <s> The driver was Mohamed Lahouaiej-Bouhlel, a Tunisian resident of France. <s> The attack ended following an exchange of gunfire, during which Lahouaiej-Bouhlel was shot and killed by police.
simple: The 2016 Nice attack happened on 14 July 2016 in Nice, France. <s> A truck drove into people celebrating Bastille Day, the national day of France. <s> The driver, Tunisian truck driver Mohamed Lahouaiej-Bouhlel, was killed by police.

title: Jared Martin
complex: Jared Christopher Martin (December 21, 1941 – May 24, 2017) was an American film and television actor. <s> He was best known for his role as Steven "Dusty" Farlow in the 1978 series "Dallas" and for roles on two science fiction TV series, "The Fantastic Journey" and "War of the Worlds". <s> Martin was born in Manhattan to Charles Elmer Martin, a cover artist and cartoonist for "The New Yorker", and his wife, Florence Taylor, an artist and homemaker. <s> He began acting at the age of ten in a local children's theater group. <s> After graduating from the Putney School and Columbia University, where his roommate was Brian De Palma, he spent a summer apprenticing with Joseph Papp's Shakespeare in the Park. <s> After graduating, he worked for a couple of years at "The New York Times" as a copy boy and thumbnail book reviewer for the Sunday edition. <s> Martin died from pancreatic cancer on May 24, 2017 at his home in Philadelphia at age 75.
simple: Jared Christopher Martin (December 21, 1941 – May 24, 2017) was an American movie and television actor. <s> He was best known for his role as Steven "Dusty" Farlow in the 1978 series "Dallas" and for roles on two science fiction TV shows, "The Fantastic Journey" and "War of the Worlds". <s> He was born in Manhattan, New York. <s> Martin died on May 24, 2017 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania from pancreatic cancer at the age of 75.

title: Plummer, Idaho
complex: Plummer is a city in Benewah County, Idaho, United States. <s> The population was 1,044 at the 2010 census, up from 990 in 2000. <s> It is the largest city within the Coeur d'Alene Reservation, and is accessed by U.S. Route 95, the state's primary north-south highway. <s> Plummer is located at (47.333423, -116.884393), at an elevation of 2743 ft above sea level. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 1.25 sqmi , all of it land. <s> The median age in the city was 31.4 years. <s> 32.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.6% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22.3% were from 25 to 44; 24.8% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. <s> The gender makeup of the city was 51.1% male and 48.9% female. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 990 people, 336 households, and 257 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 875.2 people per square mile (338.3/km2). <s> There were 380 housing units at an average density of 335.9 per square mile (129.8/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the city was 55.86% White, 0.71% African American, 39.29% Native American, 0.10% Asian, 0.10% Pacific Islander, 0.81% from other races, and 3.13% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.93% of the population. <s> There were 336 households out of which 38.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.4% were married couples living together, 17.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 23.5% were non-families. <s> 19.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. <s> The average household size was 2.95 and the average family size was 3.33. <s> In the city, the population was spread out with 33.3% under the age of 18, 12.2% from 18 to 24, 26.6% from 25 to 44, 17.6% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older. <s> The median age was 29 years. <s> For every 100 females, there were 96.8 males. <s> For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.6 males. <s> The median income for a household in the city was $28,438, and the median income for a family was $31,806. <s> Males had a median income of $26,583 versus $20,357 for females. <s> The per capita income for the city was $10,564. <s> About 17.3% of families and 22.0% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.8% of those under age 18 and 18.8% of those age 65 or over.
simple: Plummer is a city in Idaho in the United States. <s> Plummer is located at (47.333423, -116.884393). <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the area of the city is 1.1 square miles (2.9 km2). <s> During the census of 2000, there were 990 people in the city. <s> 336 households, and 257 families were present there. <s> The population density was 875.2 people per square mile (338.3/km2). <s> There were 380 housing units. <s> The average density of 335.9/sq mi (129.8/km2). <s> 55.86% were White, 0.71% African American, 39.29% Native American, 0.10% Asian, 0.10% Pacific Islander, 0.81% from other races, and 3.13% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.93% of the population. <s> Of the 336 households, 38.4% had children under 18 living with them. <s> 49.4% were married couples living together. <s> 17.3% had a female resident with no husband present. <s> 19.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.0% had someone living alone who was over 65 years of age. <s> The average household size was 2.95 and the average family size was 3.33. <s> 33.3% people in the city were under the age of 18, 12.2% from 18 to 24, 26.6% from 25 to 44, 17.6% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older. <s> The average age was 29 years. <s> For every 100 females there were 96.8 males. <s> For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.6 males. <s> The median income for a household in the city was $28,438, and the median income for a family was $31,806. <s> Males had a median income of $26,583 versus $20,357 for females. <s> The per capita income for the city was $10,564. <s> About 17.3% of families and 22.0% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.8% of those under age 18 and 18.8% of those age 65 or over.

title: Ray Phiri
complex: Raymond Chikapa Enock Phiri (23 March 1947 – 12 July 2017) was a South African jazz, fusion and mbaqanga musician born in Mpumalanga to Thabethe Phiri, a Malawian immigrant worker, and South African guitarist nicknamed "Just Now" Phiri. <s> He collaborated with Paul Simon and Ladysmith Black Mambazo on Simon's Graceland (album) project in 1985, and became founding member of the Cannibals in the 1970s. <s> When the Cannibals disbanded Ray founded Stimela, with whom he conceived gold and platinum-selling albums like "Fire, Passion and Ecstacy " (1982), "Look, Listen and Decide" (1986). <s> Phiri was involved in a series of car accidents which affected his personal life and musical career. <s> Phiri was badly injured in 1987 in a crash that claimed the lives of his band manager and six others. <s> In 2003, his wife was killed in a car accident, with Ray escaping serious injury. <s> Phiri was diagnosed with lung cancer and died at the age of 70 on 12 July 2017 at a Nelspruit hospital. <s> A memorial service for Phiri was held at the Mbombela Stadium in Nelspruit on 20 July, and the funeral service took place at the same venue on 22 July.
simple: Raymond Chikapa Enock Phiri (23 March 1947 – 12 July 2017) was a South African jazz guitarist, singer, fusion and mbaqanga musician. <s> He was born in Mpumalanga to Malawian immigrant worker and South African guitarist nicknamed "Just Now" Phiri. <s> Phiri became founding member of the Cannibals in the 1970s. <s> When the Cannibals disbanded Ray founded Stimela, with whom he conceived gold and platinum-selling albums like "Fire, Passion and Ecstasy" (1991), "Look, Listen and Decide" (1992) as well as the controversial "People Don't Talk So Let's Talk". <s> Phiri died at the age of 70 on 12 July 2017 at a Nelspruit hospital from lung cancer.

title: TV Tokyo
complex: TV Tokyo Corporation (or TX) (株式会社テレビ東京 , Kabushiki-gaisha Terebi Tōkyō ) is a television station headquartered in Roppongi, Minato, Tokyo, Japan. <s> Also known as "Teleto" (テレ東 , Teretō ) , a blend of "terebi" and "Tokyo", it is the flagship station of TX Network. <s> It is one of the major Tokyo television stations, particularly specializing in anime. <s> The station is partly owned by the "Nihon Keizai Shimbun".
simple: TV Tokyo is a television station in Tokyo, Japan. <s> It is also known as "Teleto," a portmanteau of "terebi," the Japanese word for "television," and "Tokyo." <s> Its main owner is Nihon Keizai Shimbun.

title: Cayman Islands
complex: The Cayman Islands ( or ) are an autonomous British Overseas Territory in the western Caribbean Sea. <s> The 264 km2 territory comprises the three islands of Grand Cayman, Cayman Brac and Little Cayman, which are located to the south of Cuba and northeast of Honduras, between Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatán Peninsula. <s> As of spring 2018 , the population of the Cayman Islands was estimated to be 64,420 making it the second-most populated British overseas territory after Bermuda. <s> The capital city is George Town, situated on Grand Cayman, by far the most populous of the three islands. <s> The islands are in the western Caribbean Sea and are the peaks of an undersea mountain range called the Cayman Ridge (or Cayman Rise).
simple: The Cayman Islands are a territory of the United Kingdom in the Caribbean Sea. <s> The three islands are Grand Cayman, Little Cayman, and Cayman Brac. <s> Its capital, George Town, is on the main island (Grand Cayman).

title: Ivan Korsak
complex: Ivan Feodosiyovych Korsak ( ; 15 September 1946 – 7 December 2017) was a Ukrainian writer and journalist. <s> Ivan Korsak was born on 15 September 1946 in Zabolottya (in the Ratne district of Volyn region). <s> As an undergraduate in college he studied agronomy and journalism. <s> Korsak worked as an editor of the newspaper "Radyans'ke Polissya" in Kamin-Kashyrsky (1975–90), and also for "Narodna trybuna" in Lutsk (1990–95). <s> In 1996, he became the chief editor of the newspaper "Simya i Dim". <s> Korsak has been a member of the National Union of Writers of Ukraine and an editorial board member of the newspaper "Literary Ukraine" since 2011.
simple: Ivan Feodosiyovych Korsak (; 15 September 1946 – 7 December 2017) was a Ukrainian writer and journalist. <s> Korsak died on 7 December 2017 in Lutsk, Volyn Oblast, at the age of 71. <s> He was born in Zabolottya, Volyn Oblast. <s> He was also worked at newspapers such as "Radyans'ke Polissya", "Narodna trybuna" and "Literary Ukraine". <s> He was best known as chief editor of the newspaper "Simya i Dim".

complex: This is a list of the main towns and cities in Turkmenistan. <s> For a full list of settlements see the list of cities, towns and villages in Turkmenistan.

title: Ingonish
complex: Ingonish is a Canadian rural community in northeastern Victoria County, Nova Scotia. <s> Located along the northeast coast of Cape Breton Island, Ingonish is situated on the Cabot Trail approximately 60 kilometres from the shire town of Baddeck. <s> Ingonish lies at the eastern entrance to Cape Breton Highlands National Park. <s> The regional economy is tied to the seasonal tourism and fishing industries. <s> The community is in the federal electoral district of Sydney—Victoria. <s> Ingonish was one of the first areas settled on Cape Breton Island, and is home to the "Keltic Lodge" resort, downhill skiing at Cape Smokey, and a public golf course, the Highlands Links.
simple: Ingonish is a Canadian rural community in northeastern Victoria County, Nova Scotia. <s> Ingonish is on the northeast coast of Cape Breton Island along the Cabot Trail. <s> It is about 60 km from the shire town of Baddeck. <s> Ingonish is located at the eastern entrance to Cape Breton Highlands National Park. <s> The regional economy is tied to the seasonal tourism and fishing industries. <s> The community is in the federal electoral district of Sydney—Victoria. <s> Ingonish was one of the first areas settled on Cape Breton Island.

title: Unicellular organism
complex: A unicellular organism, also known as a single-celled organism, is an organism that consists of only one cell, unlike a multicellular organism that consists of more than one cell. <s> Unicellular organisms fall into two general categories: prokaryotic organisms and eukaryotic organisms. <s> Prokaryotes include bacteria and archaea. <s> Many eukaryotes are multicellular, but the group includes the protozoa, unicellular algae, and unicellular fungi. <s> Unicellular organisms are thought to be the oldest form of life, with early protocells possibly emerging 3.8–4 billion years ago. <s> Some organisms are partially unicellular, like "Dictyostelium discoideum".
simple: Unicellular organisms are organisms that have one cell. <s> Unicellular organisms can be found everywhere. <s> Almost all unicellular organisms are microorganisms but you can observe eukaryotes and many prokaryotes by using a compound microscope. <s> The oldest forms of life existed 3.8 billion years ago, if not longer.

title: Financial regulation
complex: Financial regulation is a form of regulation or supervision, which subjects financial institutions to certain requirements, restrictions and guidelines, aiming to maintain the integrity of the financial system. <s> This may be handled by either a government or non-government organization. <s> Financial regulation has also influenced the structure of banking sectors by increasing the variety of financial products available. <s> Financial regulation forms one of three legal categories which constitutes the content of financial law, the other two being market practices, case law. <s> In the early modern period, the Dutch were the pioneers in financial regulation. <s> The first recorded ban (regulation) on short selling was enacted by the Dutch authorities as early as 1610.
simple: Financial regulation is supervision of financial institutions to certain rules and guidelines. <s> Regulation may be done by either a government or non-government organization. <s> Also, financial regulation has increased the variety of financial products available. <s> In the early modern period, the Dutch were the pioneers in financial regulation. <s> The first recorded regulation was a ban on short selling done by the Dutch authorities in 1610.

title: Hispanic
complex: The term Hispanic ( or ) refers to the people that originate from, or reside in, a former Spanish Empire viceroyalty. <s> "Hispanus" was the Latin name given to a person from Hispania during Roman rule. <s> The ancient Roman Hispania, which roughly comprised what is currently called the Iberian Peninsula, included the contemporary states of Spain, Portugal, and Andorra, and the British Overseas Territory of Gibraltar. <s> In English, the term "Hispano-Roman" is sometimes used.

title: Janet Seidel
complex: Janet Seidel (28 May 1955 – 7 August 2017) was an Australian jazz vocalist and pianist. <s> Seidel's 18 CD albums, recorded with musicians including her brother, bassist David Seidel, have been nominated for prizes such as the ARIA Music Awards. <s> Her album "Moon of Manakoora" won the Bell Award for Best Australian Jazz Vocal Album in 2006. <s> Seidel was described as a "virtual institution" in her country. <s> She was a music teacher at the Sydney Girls High School. <s> Seidel died on 7 August 2017 from ovarian cancer in Sydney at the age of 62. <s> Some newspapers mistakenly reported her death as 8 August.

title: José Plácido Caamaño
complex: José María Plácido Caamaño y Gómez-Cornejo (5 October 1837 – December 31, 1900) was President of Ecuador 23 November 1883 to 1 July 1888. <s> Caamaño was born in Guayaquil. <s> He was the grandson of Spanish explorer Jacinto Caamaño. <s> He studied law and theology in the seminary of his native city, and was educated in Quito. <s> Subsequently he was mayor of Guayaquil, and chief of the custom-house service. <s> He was a member of the Progresistas, a liberal Catholic party. <s> An attempt was made to assassinate him in 1886, and he narrowly escaped death by throwing himself into a river. <s> Under his administration telegraphs, railways, an institute of sciences, several Colleges, and many new schools were added to the resources of Ecuador. <s> After his term ended, he served as ambassador to US from 1889 to 1890.

title: Taeyeon discography
complex: Kim Tae-yeon, better known by the mononym Taeyeon, is a South Korean singer. <s> Her discography consists of one studio album, four extended plays (EPs), thirty two singles (including six as featured artist), and three promotional singles. <s> She debuted as a member of South Korean girl group Girls' Generation in August 2007 and initially gained some popularity as a singer upon recording soundtrack songs "If" for "Hong Gil Dong" and "Can You Hear Me" for "Beethoven Virus" (2008). <s> She subsequently established herself as one of the most renowned vocalists on the South Korean music scene with further soundtrack recordings, notably "I Love You" for "" (2010), "Missing You like Crazy" for "The King 2 Hearts", "Closer" for "To the Beautiful You" (2012), and "And One" for "That Winter, the Wind Blows" (2013), all of which managed to enter the top ten of South Korea's Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Apart from soundtrack recordings, Taeyeon has also recorded duets with other artists, most notably "Like a Star" with The One and "Different" with Kim Bum-soo, which peaked at numbers one and two on the Gaon Digital Chart, respectively. <s> Her career as a soloist began in 2015 with the release of her debut extended play "I". <s> The EP was a commercial success in South Korea, where it peaked at number two on the country's Gaon Album Chart and has since sold over 150,000 physical copies. <s> The title track of the same name peaked atop the Gaon Digital Chart and has sold over 1.8 million digital units. <s> In February 2016, Taeyeon released "Rain" as the opening single for S.M. Entertainment's digital music project SM Station. <s> The single peaked atop the Gaon Digital Chart and charted at number three on the "Billboard" World Digital Songs. <s> Her second EP "Why" was released in June 2016 to similar success, peaking atop the Gaon Album Chart and having sold over 110,000 physical copies. <s> It produced two Gaon Digital Chart top-ten singles–"Starlight" and "Why". <s> She subsequently released a digital single titled "" in November, which charted at number two on the Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Taeyeon released her first studio album, "My Voice", in February 2017. <s> The album peaked atop the Gaon Album Chart and has sold over 200,000 physical copies in South Korea. <s> It yielded a single titled "Fine", which was a number one on the Gaon Digital Chart and peaked at number seven on the World Digital Songs. <s> It subsequently yielded the single "Make Me Love You" off the deluxe edition, which charted at number four on the Gaon Digital Chart.
simple: Taeyeon's discography consists of a studio album, two EPs, twenty singles and ten soundtracks. <s> The singer debuted in girl group Girls' Generation in August 2007 and then in Girls' Generation-TTS in May 2012. <s> Her solo career began in 2015 with the release of her debut mini-album entitled "I". <s> The EP was a commercial success in South Korea, where it reached number two on Gaon Album Chart and since then has sold more than 140,000 physical copies. <s> The single of the same name managed to position itself in the first position of Gaon Digital Chart and has sold more than 1,8 million digital copies. <s> In February 2016, Taeyeon published "Rain" as the first single from SM Station. <s> The single reached the maximum position in Gaon Digital Chart and was ranked number three in Billboard World Digital Songs. <s> His second EP, Why, was released in June 2016, reaching the top in Gaon Album Chart and managed to sell more than 110,000 physical copies. <s> He produced two singles that were included in the mini album, "Starlight" and "Why". <s> Subsequently, he released a digital single titled "" in November, which was ranked second in Gaon Digital Chart. <s> Taeyeon released her first studio album, "My Voice", in February 2017. <s> The album won first place in Gaon Album Chart and sold more than 109,000 physical copies in its first month of release. <s> He produced the single "Fine", which was number one on Gaon Digital Chart and reached number seven on Billboard World Digital Songs.

title: L. L. Zamenhof
complex: Ludwik Lejzer Zamenhof (15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 – 14 April O.S. 1 April 1917 ), often credited as L. L. Zamenhof, was a Polish ophthalmologist and the inventor of the international language Esperanto, the most widely-used constructed international auxiliary language in the world. <s> Zamenhof was born on 15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 , the son of Markus Zamenhof (27 January O.S. 15 January 1837 - 29 November O.S. 16 November 1907 ) and Rozalia Zamenhof (1839 - 1 September O.S. 20 August 1892 ), in the multi-ethnic city of Belostok in Russian Empire (now Białystok in Poland). <s> At that time the city was in the Grodno Governorate of the Russian Empire as a result of the 1807 Treaties of Tilsit. <s> His parents were of Litvak Jewish descent. <s> This group inhabited the former Grand Duchy of Lithuania. <s> He appears to have been natively bilingual in Yiddish and Russian. <s> His father was a teacher of German and French. <s> From him, Zamenhof learned German, French and Hebrew. <s> He also spoke some major language of Białystok: Polish, a Yiddish, Belarusian, and German. <s> Polish became the native language of his children in Warsaw. <s> In school he studied the classical languages Latin, Greek, Hebrew, and Aramaic. <s> He later learned some English, though in his own words not very well. <s> He had an interest in Lithuanian and Italian, and learned Volapük when it came out in 1880. <s> By that point his international language project was already well developed. <s> As a student at secondary school in Warsaw, Zamenhof attempted to create an international language with a grammar that was rich, but complex. <s> When he later studied English, he decided that the international language must have a simpler grammar. <s> Apart from his parents' native languages Russian and Yiddish and his adopted language Polish, his projects were also aided by his mastery of German, a good passive understanding of Latin, Hebrew and French, and a basic knowledge of Greek, English and Italian. <s> Zamenhof's grandson, Louis-Christophe Zaleski-Zamenhof (Adam's son), has lived in France since the 1960s. <s> Zamenhof was nominated 12 times for the Nobel Peace Prize.
simple: Ludwik Lejzer Zamenhof (; , ; 15 December O.S. 3 December 1859 – 14 April O.S. 1 April 1917), credited as L. L. Zamenhof and sometimes as the pseudonymous Dr. Esperanto, was an eye doctor, linguist (who creates a language), and scholar who created the international language Esperanto. <s> Zamenhof was born in 1859 in the town of Białystok, Poland. <s> His parents spoke Russian and Yiddish at home. <s> His father was a German teacher, so Zamenhof learned that language from an early age and spoke the language fluently. <s> Later he learned French, Latin, Greek, Hebrew and English. <s> He also had an interest in Italian, Spanish and Lithuanian. <s> He attempted to create the international language with a grammar that was rich, and complex. <s> Zamenhof decided that the international language must have a simple grammar and be easier to learn than Volapük, an earlier international language. <s> His grandson, Louis-Christophe Zaleski-Zamenhof, has lived in France since the 1960s. <s> He was 14 times nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize between 1907 and 1917.

title: Stanleycaris
complex: Stanleycaris is an extinct, monotypic genus of anomalocaridid which existed in Canada, during the middle Cambrian (Miaolingian). <s> The type species is "Stanleycaris hirpex". <s> "Stanleycaris" was described from the Stephen Formation near the Stanley Glacier Burgess Shale locality and also informally reported from Odaray Mountain. <s> Putative lobopodian species "Aysheaia prolata" from the Cambrian Wheeler Formation (Utah, United States) was reinterpreted as an isolated frontal appendage of a member of the genus "Stanleycaris" by Pates, Daley & Ortega-Hernández (2017).
simple: Stanleycaris (meaning "crab of Stanley Glacier") is an extinct, monotypic genus of anomalocaridid which existed in Canada, during the middle Cambrian. <s> Its fossils were found in the Burgess Shale in and also informally reported from Mount Odaray. <s> Putative lobopodian species "Aysheaia prolata" from Utah, United States were reinterpreted as an isolated frontal appendage of a member of the genus "Stanleycaris" by Pates, Daley & Ortega-Hernández (2017).

title: William M. Jennings Trophy
complex: The William M. Jennings Trophy is an annual National Hockey League (NHL) award given to "the goaltender(s) having played a minimum of 25 games for the team with the fewest goals scored against it ... based on regular-season play." <s> From 1946 until 1981, the Vezina Trophy had been awarded under that definition, but it was later changed and replaced by the Jennings Trophy. <s> It is named in honor of William M. Jennings, the longtime governor and president of the New York Rangers. <s> Since its beginnings in 1982, it has been awarded at the end of 32 seasons to 53 different players; mostly in tandems of two goaltenders. <s> The most recent winners are Thomas Greiss and Robin Lehner of the New York Islanders, which had a league-low 191 team goals-against in the 2018–19 NHL season. <s> From 1946 until the 1980–81 season, the Vezina Trophy was awarded to the goaltender(s) of the National Hockey League (NHL) team allowing the fewest goals during the regular season. <s> However, it was recognized that this system often meant the trophy went to the goaltender of the better team rather than the individual and was changed to offer the trophy to the most outstanding goaltender, as voted by the NHL general managers. <s> The William M. Jennings Trophy was created as a replacement and is awarded to the starting goaltender(s) playing for the team with the fewest goals against. <s> The Jennings Trophy was donated by the NHL's board of governors and first presented at the conclusion of the 1981–82 season. <s> It is named in honor of the late William M. Jennings, who was a longtime governor and president of the New York Rangers and a builder of ice hockey in the United States. <s> Normally the minimum number of games a goaltender must play to be eligible for the trophy is 25, but for the lockout shortened 1994–95 season, the required minimum was fourteen games. <s> Seven players have won both the Jennings and Vezina Trophy for the same season: Patrick Roy ( and ), Ed Belfour ( and ), Dominik Hasek ( and ), Martin Brodeur , Miikka Kiprusoff , Tim Thomas , and Carey Price . <s> Roy and Brodeur have won the trophy five times each, the most of any goaltenders. <s> Belfour is third, having won four times. <s> The Montreal Canadiens have the most wins, with six, followed by the New Jersey Devils and the Chicago Blackhawks with five each, and the Buffalo Sabres with three. <s> Bold Player with the fewest goals ever scored against in a season.
simple: The William M. Jennings Trophy is an award in the National Hockey League (NHL) given each year to "to the goalkeeper(s) having played a minimum of 25 games for the team with the fewest goals scored against it. <s> Winners are selected based on regular-season play." <s> Up until 1981, the Vezina Trophy had been awarded under that definition, but it was later changed and replaced by the Jennings Trophy. <s> Since it began in 1982, it has been awarded at the end of 25 seasons to 27 different players. <s> The most recent winners are Corey Crawford of the Chicago Blackhawks and Carey Price of the Montreal Canadiens, who both allowed only 189 team goals against for their teams in the 2014–15 NHL season. <s> Until the 1980–81 season, the Vezina Trophy was awarded to the goaltender(s) of the team allowing the fewest goals during the regular season. <s> However, it was discovered that this often meant the trophy went to the goaltender of the better team rather than the individual, so they changed it to offer the Vezina to the most outstanding goaltender, as voted by the NHL General Managers. <s> The William M. Jennings Trophy was created as a replacement and is given to the goaltender(s) playing for the team with the fewest goals scored against them. <s> The Jennings Trophy was donated by the NHL's board of governors and first handed out at the end of the 1981–82 season. <s> It is named for the late William M. Jennings, who was a governor and president of the New York Rangers and who helped build ice hockey in the United States. <s> Normally the lowest number of games a goaltender must play to be eligible for the trophy is 25, but for the lockout shortened 1994–95 season, the lowest was fourteen games. <s> Five players have won both the Jennings and Vezina Trophy for the same season: Patrick Roy (1988–89 and 1991–92), Ed Belfour (1990–91 and 1992–93), Dominik Hasek (1993–94 and 2000–01), Martin Brodeur (2002–03 and 2003–04) and Miikka Kiprusoff (2005–06). <s> Roy has won the trophy five times, the most of any goaltender. <s> Belfour and Brodeur are tied for second, having each won the trophy four times. <s> It has been won most often by the Montreal Canadiens, on 5 occasions. <s> The New Jersey Devils have won four times, and Buffalo Sabres and Chicago Blackhawks have three wins each. <s> Player is still active in the NHL Player's team won the Stanley Cup Bold Player with the fewest goals ever scored against in a season.

title: Statue
complex: A statue is a free-standing sculpture in which the realistic, full-length figures of persons or animals or non-representational forms are carved in a durable material like wood, metal, or stone. <s> Typical statues are life-sized or close to life-size; a sculpture that represents persons or animals in full figure but that is small enough to lift and carry is a statuette or figurine, while one more than twice life-size is a colossal statue.

title: Carson Cistulli
complex: Carson Cistulli (born December 23, 1979) is an American poet, Wikipedia editor, essayist and sabermetrician. <s> His works of poetry include "Some Common Weaknesses Illustrated", "Assorted Fictions," and "A Century of Enthusiasm." <s> Carson Cistulli was born December 23, 1979, in Concord, New Hampshire, to Philip Cistulli Jr. and Holly Young. <s> Carson passed his early childhood in a middle class Italian-American household until his parents' divorce in 1994. <s> Cistulli attended boarding school at Milton Academy in Massachusetts.

title: Heinz Hall for the Performing Arts
complex: Heinz Hall is a performing arts center and concert hall located at 600 Penn Avenue in the Cultural District of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <s> Home to the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra (PSO) and the Pittsburgh Youth Symphony Orchestra, the 2,676 seat hall presents about 200 performances each year. <s> Originally built in 1927 as Loew's Penn Theatre, the former movie palace was renovated and reopened as Heinz Hall in 1971.

title: Branislav Ivanović
complex: Branislav Ivanović ( , ; born 22 February 1984) is a Serbian professional footballer who plays for Russian club Zenit Saint Petersburg and the Serbia national team. <s> A versatile defender, Ivanović plays as a right back, although he can also play as a centre back. <s> Ivanović was born into a family with a sporting history, his father Rade played for local team FK Srem as a defender.

title: Black Dahlia
complex: Elizabeth Short (July 29, 1924 – January 14 or 15, 1947), known posthumously as the "Black Dahlia", was an American woman who was found murdered in the Leimert Park neighborhood of Los Angeles, California. <s> Her case became highly publicized due to the graphic nature of the crime, which included her corpse having been mutilated and bisected at the waist. <s> Short's unsolved murder and the details surrounding it have had a lasting cultural intrigue, generating various theories and public speculation. <s> Her life and death have been the basis of numerous books and films, and her murder is frequently cited as one of the most famous unsolved murders in American history, as well as one of the oldest unsolved cases in Los Angeles County. <s> It has likewise been credited by historians as one of the first major crimes in post-World War II America to capture national attention. <s> Short's severely mutilated body was completely severed at the waist and drained entirely of blood, leaving her skin a pallid white. <s> Medical examiners determined that she had been dead for around ten hours prior to the discovery, leaving her time of death either sometime during the evening of January 14, or the early morning hours of January 15.
simple: Elizabeth Short (July 29, 1924 – January 14 or 15, 1947), known as "the Black Dahlia", was an American woman who was found murdered in a neighborhood of Los Angeles, California. <s> Her case became highly publicized due to the graphic nature of the crime. <s> Short's unsolved murder and the details surrounding it have had caused many theories and public speculation. <s> It is one of the oldest unsolved cases in Los Angeles County. <s> Her corpse was chopped into pieces and severed at the waist.

title: Promotional recording
complex: A promotional recording, or promo, or plug copy, is an audio or video recording distributed free, usually in order to promote a recording that is or soon will be commercially available. <s> Promos are normally sent directly to broadcasters, such as music radio and television stations, and to tastemakers, such as DJs and music journalists, in advance of the release of commercial editions, in the hope that airplay, reviews, and other forms of exposure will result and stimulate the public's interest in the commercial release. <s> Promos are often distributed in plain packaging, without the text or artwork that appears on the commercial version. <s> Typically a promo is marked with some variation of the following text: "Licensed for promotional use only. <s> It may also state that the promo is still the property of the distributor and is to be "returned upon demand." <s> However, it is not illegal to sell promotional recordings, and recalls of promos are extremely rare and unenforced. <s> Because promos are produced in smaller quantity than releases made available to the general public, they are sometimes considered valuable collectors' items. <s> They are never intended for sale in record stores. <s> In music, a buzz single or advance single is a track or promotional song, released by the label (typically) preceding the album's release. <s> The song(s) are released in order to bring attention to an album's release. <s> Buzz singles are not typically issued to radio as promotional singles, due to the fact that they are only intended to attract minor attention compared to a regular single.
simple: A promotional recording (or promo), is an audio or video recording that is released for free. <s> Promos are sent to broadcasters, such as music radios, television stations, tastemakers, DJs, and music journalists. <s> Promos are often released in plain packaging. <s> Most promos are marked with "Licensed for promotional use only. <s> However, it is not against the law to sell promotional recordings. <s> There has been recalls of promos, but this is rare and not forced by recording labels. <s> Because promos are released in smaller quantities than CD singles, they are sometimes considered a collectors item. <s> They are never released in record stores. <s> They are released to promote a song that will be released through an album.

title: Bredbury
complex: Bredbury is a suburban town in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport, Greater Manchester, England, 7.9 mi south-east of Manchester, 1.8 mi east of Stockport and 3.2 mi south-west of Hyde. <s> At the 2011 census, it had a population of 13,593.
simple: Bredbury is a village in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport, in Greater Manchester, England. <s> Bredbury is found 7 mi southeast of the city of Manchester, and 2 mi east-northeast of Stockport.

title: Arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse
complex: The arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse is an arrondissement of France in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> Since the January 2017 reorganization of the arrondissements of Ain, it has 199 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Bourg-en-Bresse is an arrondissement of France in the Ain department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> When the Ain department was created on 1800, the "arrondissement" of Bourg-en-Bresse was part of that original department. <s> The "arrondissement" of Bourg-en-Bresse is bordered to the northwest by the Saône-et-Loire department, to the northeast by the Jura department, to the west by the "arrondissements" of Nantua and Belley, and to the southwest by the Rhône department.

title: Smedjebacken
complex: Smedjebacken is a locality and the seat of Smedjebacken Municipality, Dalarna County, Sweden, with 5,100 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Smedjebacken is an urban area in the county of Dalarna in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Smedjebacken Municipality.

title: Arlöv
complex: Arlöv (] ) is the seat of Burlöv Municipality, Skåne County, Sweden. <s> It is statistically not defined as a locality of its own, but forms part of the contiguous city of Malmö, 5 km northeast of downtown Malmö.
simple: Arlöv is a place in the county of Skåne in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Burlöv Municipality.

title: Bartow, Georgia
complex: Bartow is a town in Jefferson County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 286. <s> Initially the town was known as "Spier's Turnout", but was changed to honor the first Confederate officer to die in battle, Colonel Francis S. Bartow of Savannah, Georgia, who was killed at the Battle of Manassas, Virginia on July 21, 1861.
simple: Bartow is a town in Jefferson County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 286. <s> The town was originally named "Spier's Turnout", but was changed to honor the first Confederate officer to die in battle, Colonel Francis S. Bartow of Savannah, Georgia.

title: Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department
complex: The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department, or Port Authority Police Department (PAPD), is a law enforcement agency in New York and New Jersey, the duties of which are to protect and to enforce state and city laws at all the facilities, owned or operated by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey (PANYNJ), the bi-state agency running airports, seaports, and many bridges and tunnels within the Port of New York and New Jersey. <s> Additionally, the PAPD is responsible for other PANYNJ properties including three bus terminals (the Port Authority Bus Terminal, the George Washington Bridge Bus Station and Journal Square Transportation Center), the World Trade Center in lower Manhattan, and the PATH train system. <s> The PAPD is the largest transit-related police force in the United States. <s> On February 26, 1993, the Port Authority's World Trade Center complex was the target of a terrorist attack bombing. <s> On September 11, 2001, the complex was the target of terrorist attacks for a second time. <s> The complex housed over 50,000 employees and accommodated 70,000 visitors per day; the efforts of the Port Authority Police, the New York City Police Department (NYPD), the New York City Fire Department (FDNY), New York City Sheriff's Office, New York State Court Officers, and federal law enforcement officers, along with countless others, helped to minimize the loss of life. <s> The Port Authority Police suffered the worst loss of police personnel in a single event in American history: 37 police officers, along with one police K-9 named Sirius, were killed on September 11.
simple: The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department, or Port Authority Police Department (PAPD), is a police department in New York and New Jersey. <s> It protects all the property owned by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, and it enforces state and city laws. <s> The PAPD is owned by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, a two-state agency that runs the bridges, tunnels, airports, and seaports along the New York - New Jersey border. <s> The PAPD is one of the largest police departments in the United States, with 1,660 members. <s> On February 26, 1993 the Port Authority's World Trade Center was the target of a terrorist attack, and of the more successful September 11 attacks in 2001. <s> The area had over 50,000 employees and 70,000 visitors per day; the work of emergency personnel including the Port Authority Police, the New York City Police Department, the New York City Fire Department, New York City EMS, New York State Court Officers, Federal Agents and many others helped to lower the deaths from the attack. <s> The Port Authority Police had the biggest loss of police personnel at a single time in American history: 37 police officers along with one police dog were killed on September 11th.

title: Minter City, Mississippi
complex: Minter City is an unincorporated community located in Leflore County and in Tallahatchie County, Mississippi. <s> It is part of the Greenwood, Mississippi micropolitan area, and is within the Mississippi Delta.
simple: Minter City is an unincorporated community located in Leflore County and in Tallahatchie County, Mississippi. <s> It is part of the Greenwood, Mississippi micropolitan area, and is within the Mississippi Delta.

title: How to Train Your Dragon (film)
complex: How to Train Your Dragon is a 2010 American computer-animated action fantasy film loosely based on the 2003 book of the same name by British author Cressida Cowell, produced by DreamWorks Animation and distributed by Paramount Pictures. <s> The film was directed by Chris Sanders and Dean DeBlois from a screenplay by Will Davies, Sanders, and DeBlois, and stars the voices of Jay Baruchel, Gerard Butler, Craig Ferguson, America Ferrera, Jonah Hill, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, T. J. Miller, and Kristen Wiig. <s> The story takes place in a mythical Viking world where a young Viking teenager named Hiccup aspires to follow his tribe's tradition of becoming a dragon slayer. <s> After finally capturing his first dragon, and with his chance at last of gaining the tribe's acceptance, he finds that he no longer wants to kill the dragon and instead befriends it. <s> The film premiered at the Gibson Amphitheater on March 21, 2010, and was released in the United States five days later on March 26. <s> The film was a critical and commercial success, earning praise from film critics and audiences and earning nearly $500 million worldwide. <s> It was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature and Best Original Score at the 83rd Academy Awards, but lost to "Toy Story 3" and "The Social Network", respectively. <s> "How to Train Your Dragon" also won ten Annie Awards, including Best Animated Feature. <s> Two sequels, "How to Train Your Dragon 2" and "", were released on June 13, 2014, and February 22, 2019, respectively. <s> Much like their predecessor, both sequels were widely praised and became box office successes.
simple: How to Train Your Dragon is a 2010 computer animated fantasy-comedy movie from DreamWorks Animation. <s> It is based on the 2003 book of the same name. <s> It was produced by Bonnie Arnold, Doug Davison, Roy Lee, Michael Connolly and Tim Johnson and was directed by Chris Sanders and Dean DeBlois. <s> The movie was released on March 26, 2010. <s> The movie was nominated for two Academy Awards for Best Animated Feature and Best Original Score. <s> A sequel How To Train Your Dragon 2 released on June 13, 2014. <s> A third film How To Train Your Dragon 3 will be released in 2019.

title: Bergsjö
complex: Bergsjö is a locality and the seat of Nordanstig Municipality, Gävleborg County, Sweden with 1,266 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Bergsjö is an urban area in the county of Gävleborg in Sweden. <s> It is the seat of Nordanstig Municipality.

title: Konstantyn K. Kuzminsky
complex: Konstantin Konstantinovich Kuzminsky (16 April 1940 – 2 May 2015) was a Russian performance poet. <s> Born in Leningrad, Kuzminsky emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1978. <s> He published "The Blue Lagoon Anthology of Modern Russian Poetry". <s> Other publications include a collection of Russian poetry "The Living Mirror". <s> He appeared in several documentary films, among them two by Andrei Zagdansky: Vasya, a portrait of a close friend and Russian/Soviet nonconformist artist Vasily Sitnikov and Konstantin and Mouse a.k.a. "Kostya and Mouse", a double-portrait of Konstantin Kuzminsky and his wife Emma, nicknamed Mouse. <s> Kuzminsky died in the United States on 2 May 2015.
simple: Konstantin Konstantinovich Kuzminsky (; 16 April 1940 – 2 May 2015) was a Russian-American performance poet. <s> Kuzminsky was born in Leningrad (now called Saint Petersburg). <s> He moved to the United States from the Soviet Union in 1978. <s> He published "The Blue Lagoon Anthology of Modern Russian Poetry" as well as other publications including a collection of Russian poetry "The Living Mirror". <s> He also appeared in many documentary movies, including two by Andrei Zagdansky. <s> Kuzminsky died on 2 May 2015 in New York City, aged 75.

title: Union County, Arkansas
complex: Union County is a county located on the central southern border of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 41,639. <s> The county seat is El Dorado. <s> The county was formed on November 2, 1829, and named in recognition of the citizens' petition for a new county, which said that they were petitioning "in the spirit of Union and Unity." <s> The county is directly adjacent to the south to Union Parish in the state of Louisiana.
simple: Union County is a county of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 41,639. <s> The county seat is El Dorado. <s> It was founded on November 2, 1829.

title: Frits Thors
complex: Alexander Frederik Paul "Frits" Thors (13 September 1909 – 19 April 2014) was a Dutch journalist and news anchor. <s> Thors was best known as the newscaster of the NTS-Journaal from 1965 until 1972.
simple: Alexander Frederik Paul "Frits" Thors (13 September 1909 – 19 April 2014) was a Dutch journalist and television and news anchor. <s> Thors died from natural causes on 19 April 2014 in Laren, North Holland. <s> He was best known for being the newscaster of the NTS-Journaal from 1965 until 1972.

title: Treasure Coast
complex: The Treasure Coast is a region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> It is located on the state's Atlantic coast, comprising Indian River, St. Lucie, and Martin, and in some definitions, Palm Beach counties. <s> The region, whose name refers to the Spanish Treasure Fleet lost in a 1715 hurricane, evidently emerged from residents' desire to distinguish themselves from Miami and the Gold Coast region to the south. <s> The area has long been inhabited, but like other of Florida's vernacular regions, a popular identity for the area did not emerge until the area saw its initial population boom in the 20th century.
simple: Treasure Coast is a region in the US state of Florida. <s> It is found on the state's Atlantic coast. <s> The name "Treasure Coast" refers to the Spanish Treasure Fleet lost in a 1715 hurricane.

title: Eli Thayer
complex: Eli Thayer (June 11, 1819 – April 15, 1899) was a member of the United States House of Representatives from 1857 to 1861. <s> He was born in Mendon, Massachusetts. <s> He graduated from Worcester Academy in 1840, from Brown University in 1845, and in 1848 founded Oread Institute, a school for young women in Worcester, Massachusetts. <s> He is buried at Hope Cemetery, Worcester. <s> Local leagues were established whose members emigrated to Kansas and established towns. <s> The Company provided hotels for temporary accommodation (such as the Free State Hotel in Lawrence) and provided sawmills and other improvements. <s> Settlements were established at Manhattan, Lawrence, Topeka, and Osawatomie. <s> The clash of these settlers and other "Free-Stater" Northerners with pro-slavery settlers spawned the violence of Bleeding Kansas.
simple: Eli Thayer (June 11, 1819 – April 15, 1899) was an educator, reformer, legislator and founder of the New England Emigrant Aid Company. <s> He was a member of the United States House of Representatives from 1857-1861. <s> Thayer died in Worcester, Massachusetts on April 15, 1899. <s> Thayer was elected as a Republican to the U.S. House of Representatives where he served two terms (March 4, 1857-March 3, 1861). <s> Thayer was born in Mendon, Massachusetts on June 11, 1819. <s> He attended the Academy of Amherst and in 1840 graduated from Worcester Academy. <s> In 1845 he graduated from Brown University as salutatorian. <s> The towns of Lawrence, Topeka, Manhattan and Osawatomie, Kansas were all settled by or with help from the Emigrant Aid Company.

title: Rotselaar
complex: Rotselaar (] ) is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Flemish-Brabant, near the convergence of the Demer and the Dijle. <s> Since January 1, 1977 the municipality comprises the towns of Rotselaar proper, Werchter and Wezemaal.
simple: Rotselaar is a municipality in the Belgian province of Flemish Brabant.

title: Grâce-Hollogne
complex: Grâce-Hollogne is a municipality of Belgium. <s> It lies in the country's Walloon Region and Province of Liege.
simple: Grâce-Hollogne is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare
complex: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare is a 1991 American slasher film and the sixth installment in the "Nightmare on Elm Street" series. <s> It is the sequel to "" and was originally supposed to be the concluding chapter of the series; "Wes Craven's New Nightmare" was released after "The Final Nightmare" but takes place outside the series canon. <s> A canonical sequel, "Freddy vs. Jason", was released later. <s> This was New Line Cinema's first 3D film release. <s> Critical reception to the film was very negative upon release. <s> The release of the film was timed for September 13 in 1991 being a friday the 13th, as is the practice for fellow slasher franchise "Friday the 13th". <s> Robert Englund reprises his role as Freddy Krueger. <s> The film stars Lisa Zane, Yaphet Kotto, Breckin Meyer, Shon Greenblatt, Ricky Dean Logan, Lezlie Deane, and Tobe Sexton. <s> Additionally, several well-known actors make cameo appearances in the film, including Johnny Depp (whose screen debut was in the original "A Nightmare on Elm Street"), Roseanne Barr, Tom Arnold, and Alice Cooper. <s> Iggy Pop sings the title song, which plays during the end credits over a montage of scenes from the previous "Nightmare" films. <s> "Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare" made $12,966,525 in its opening weekend, which was the highest opening weekend for the series until the release of "Freddy vs. Jason". <s> After its initial run, the film grossed a total of $34,872,033 in the United States, making it the fifth-highest-grossing film in the series. <s> The soundtrack for the film was released on September 24, 1991, by Warner Bros. <s> Although not included on the soundtrack, the song "In-a-Gadda-Da-Vida" by Iron Butterfly is featured in the film.
simple: Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare is a 1991 American comedy horror slasher movie and the sixth movie in the "Nightmare on Elm Street" series. <s> It is the sequel to "" and is followed by "Wes Craven's New Nightmare". <s> This was New Line Cinema's first movie released in 3-D. <s> Upon its release, the movie received a poor critical reception. <s> Robert Englund reprises his role as Freddy Krueger; Lisa Zane, Yaphet Kotto, Breckin Meyer, Shon Greenblatt, Ricky Dean Logan, Lezlie Deane and Tobe Sexton also star. <s> The movie made $34.9 million in the box office. <s> It was released on September 13, 1991.

title: Carcassonne and Trèbes attack
complex: On 23 March 2018, there was a series of Islamist terrorist attacks in the towns of Carcassonne and Trèbes in southern France. <s> Redouane Lakdim, a 25-year-old French-Moroccan (born 11 April 1992 in Taza, Morocco), shot the two occupants of a car in Carcassonne, killing the passenger and hijacking it. <s> He then opened fire on four police officers, seriously wounding one. <s> Lakdim drove to nearby Trèbes, where he stormed a Super U supermarket, killing two civilians, wounding others, and taking at least one hostage. <s> He swore allegiance to the Islamic State and demanded the release of Salah Abdeslam, the only surviving suspect of the November 2015 Paris attacks. <s> A senior gendarmerie officer, Lieutenant Colonel Arnaud Beltrame, voluntarily swapped places with a hostage. <s> After a three-hour stand-off, Lakdim shot and fatally stabbed Beltrame. <s> A police tactical unit immediately stormed the building and killed Lakdim. <s> He was named a "soldier of the Islamic State" by the Amaq News Agency, and the President of France called the attacks an act of Islamist terrorism. <s> Five people were killed in the attacks, including the perpetrator, and fifteen were wounded.
simple: On 23 March 2018, there was a series of Islamist terrorist attacks in the towns of Carcassonne and Trèbes in southern France. <s> Redouane Lakdim, a 25-year-old French-Moroccan, shot the two occupants of a car in Carcassonne, killing the passenger and hijacking it. <s> He then opened fire on four police officers, seriously wounding one. <s> Lakdim drove to nearby Trèbes, where he stormed a Super U supermarket, killing two civilians, wounding others, and taking at least one hostage. <s> Lakdim swore allegiance to the Islamic State and demanded the release of Salah Abdeslam, the only surviving suspect of the November 2015 Paris attacks. <s> A senior gendarme, Lt. Col. Arnaud Beltrame, voluntarily swapped places with a hostage. <s> After a three-hour stand-off, Lakdim fatally shot and stabbed Beltrame. <s> A police tactical unit immediately stormed the building and killed Lakdim. <s> He was named a "soldier of the Islamic State" by the Amaq News Agency, and the President of France called the attacks an act of Islamist terrorism. <s> Five people were killed in the attacks, including the perpetrator, and fifteen were wounded.

title: Potassium bromate
complex: Potassium bromate (KBrO), is a bromate of potassium and takes the form of white crystals or powder. <s> It is a strong oxidizing agent. <s> Potassium bromate is produced when bromine is passed through a hot solution of potassium hydroxide. <s> This first forms unstable potassium hypobromite, which quickly disproportionates into bromide and bromate: Electrolysis of potassium bromide solutions will also give bromate. <s> Both processes are analogous to those used in the production of chlorates. <s> Potassium bromate is typically used in the United States as a flour improver (E number E924). <s> It acts to strengthen the dough and to allow higher rising.
simple: Potassium bromate is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is KBrO. <s> It contains potassium and bromate ions. <s> Potassium bromate is a white solid. <s> It is a strong oxidizing agent. <s> It can be made by dissolving bromine in hot potassium hydroxide. <s> Normally when the bread is baked the potassium bromate is broken down. <s> It can also be made by electrolysis of potassium bromide solution. <s> Potassium bromate is used to make wheat flour better.

title: Villarvolard
complex: Villarvolard is a former municipality in the district of Gruyère in the canton of Fribourg in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2011 it was merged with the municipality of Corbières.
simple: Villarvolard is a former municipality of the district Gruyère in the canton of Fribourg in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2011 the former municipality of Villarvolard merged into the municipality of Corbières.

title: Giorgi Margvelashvili
complex: Giorgi Margvelashvili (Georgian: ; born 4 September 1969) is a Georgian academic and politician who was the fourth President of Georgia, in office from 17 November 2013 to 16 December 2018.
simple: Giorgi Margvelashvili (Georgian: ; born 4 September 1969) is a Georgian educator and politician. <s> He served as President of Georgia from 17 November 2013 to 16 December 2018.

title: Savonlinna
complex: Savonlinna ( , ] , ; ) is a town and a municipality of inhabitants in the southeast of Finland, in the heart of the Saimaa lake region.
simple: Savonlinna is a town in Finland.

title: Tulare County, California
complex: Tulare County is a county in the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 442,179. <s> Its county seat is Visalia. <s> The county is named for Tulare Lake, once the largest freshwater lake west of the Great Lakes.
simple: Tulare County is a county in the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 442,179. <s> The county seat is Visalia.

title: Marie Severin
complex: Marie Severin ( ; August 21, 1929 – August 29, 2018) was an American comics artist and colorist best known for her work for Marvel Comics and the 1950s' EC Comics. <s> She was inducted into the Will Eisner Comics Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Marie Severin was born in East Rockaway, New York, on Long Island, the second and last child of John Edward Severin, born in Oslo, Norway, who immigrated to the United States at age 3, and a mother, Marguerite (Powers) Severin, from Syracuse, New York, whose heritage was Irish. <s> Her older brother, John Severin, was born in 1922.
simple: Marie Severin (; August 21, 1929 – August 29, 2018) was an American comics artist and colorist. <s> She was best known for her work for Marvel Comics such as on "Spider-Man", "Thor", and "Iron Man" and the 1950s' EC Comics. <s> Severin died in Massapequa, New York on August 29, 2018 from a stroke at the age of 89. <s> Severin was added into the Will Eisner Comics Hall of Fame in 2001. <s> Severin was born in East Rockaway, New York.

title: Dr. Seuss
complex: Theodor Seuss Geisel ( or ; March 2, 1904 – September 24, 1991) was an American children's author, political cartoonist, illustrator, poet, animator, screenwriter, and filmmaker. <s> He is known for his work writing and illustrating more than 60 books under the pen name Doctor Seuss ( or abbreviated Dr. Seuss). <s> His work includes many of the most popular children's books of all time, selling over 600 million copies and being translated into more than 20 languages by the time of his death. <s> Geisel died of oral cancer on September 24, 1991 at his home in La Jolla, California at the age of 87. <s> He was cremated and his ashes were scattered. <s> On December 1, 1995, four years after his death, University of California, San Diego's University Library Building was renamed Geisel Library in honor of Geisel and Audrey for the generous contributions that they made to the library and their devotion to improving literacy. <s> Geisel wrote more than 60 books over the course of his long career. <s> Most were published under his well-known pseudonym Dr. Seuss, though he also authored more than a dozen books as Theo LeSieg and one as Rosetta Stone. <s> His books have topped many bestseller lists, sold over 600 million copies, and been translated into more than 20 languages. <s> In 2000, "Publishers Weekly" compiled a list of the best-selling children's books of all time; of the top 100 hardcover books, 16 were written by Geisel, including "Green Eggs and Ham", at number 4, "The Cat in the Hat", at number 9, and "One Fish, Two Fish, Red Fish, Blue Fish", at number 13. <s> In the years after his death in 1991, two additional books were published based on his sketches and notes: "Hooray for Diffendoofer Day!" <s> "My Many Colored Days" was originally written in 1973 but was posthumously published in 1996. <s> In September 2011, seven stories originally published in magazines during the 1950s were released in a collection titled "The Bippolo Seed and Other Lost Stories".
simple: Theodor Seuss Geisel (; March 2, 1904 – September 24, 1991) was an American writer and cartoonist from Springfield, Massachusetts. <s> Theodor Seuss Geisel is one of the most popular children's authors of all time. <s> He was better known by his pen name, Dr. Seuss. <s> Dr. Seuss died from oral cancer in La Jolla, California, aged 87. <s> In his long life Geisel wrote more than 60 books. <s> Though most of them were published as Dr. Seuss, he also wrote 13 books as Theo. <s> His books have sold over 222 million copies and been translated into more than 15 languages. <s> In the years after his death in 1991, several books have been published based on his sketches and notes; these include "Hooray for Diffendoofer Day!" <s> Though they were all published under the name Dr. Seuss, only "My Many Colored Days", originally written in 1973, was entirely by Geisel.

title: Easton, Minnesota
complex: Easton is a city in Faribault County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The population was 199 at the 2010 census.
simple: Easton is a city in Faribault County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The population was 199 at the 2010 census.

title: Dengie
complex: Dengie is a village and civil parish in the Maldon district of Essex, England, with a population of 119 at the 2011 census.
simple: Dengie is a village and civil parish in Maldon District, Essex, England.

title: Mason, Texas
complex: Mason is a city in, and the county seat of, Mason County, Texas, United States. <s> The city is an agricultural community on Comanche Creek southwest of Mason Mountain, on the Edwards Plateau and part of the Llano Uplift.
simple: Mason is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> It is the county seat of Mason County.

title: Bakerhill, Alabama
complex: Bakerhill or Baker Hill is a town in Barbour County, Alabama, United States, near Eufaula. <s> According to the 2010 U.S. Census, the town had a population of 279. <s> Although it existed as an unincorporated village since before 1860, the town was officially incorporated in 1997. <s> Bakerhill is located at 31.88 degrees north, 85.15 degrees west (31.88495, -85.15390).
simple: Bakerhill or Baker Hill is a city in Barbour County, Alabama, United States, near Eufaula. <s> Although it existed as an unincorporated village since before 1860, the city was officially incorporated in 2000. <s> Bakerhill is located at 31.88 degrees north, 85.15 degrees west (31.88495, -85.15390).

title: Bukit Timah Hill
complex: Bukit Timah Hill is a hill located within the planning area of Bukit Panjang in Singapore. <s> The hill stands at an altitude of 163.63 metres (537 ft.) above ground level (approx. 44 storey building) and 182 metres (597 ft.) above sea level, making it the highest natural point in the city-state.
simple: Bukit Timah is an area in Singapore and a hill in that area. <s> The Bukit Timah area is a particularly prominent location with a high land value. <s> Bukit Timah Hill stands at an altitude of 163.63 m and is the highest point in the city-state of Singapore.

title: Keith Birdsong
complex: Keith Birdsong (July 14, 1959 – June 4, 2019) was a Muscogee Creek-Cherokee illustrator, known best for illustrating covers of "Star Trek" novels, usually depicting the various actors of the "Star Trek" television series and movies in a realistic manner. <s> Birdsong died on June 4, 2019, as a result of injuries sustained in a car crash.
simple: Keith Birdsong (July 14, 1959 – June 4, 2019) was a Muscogee Creek-Cherokee illustrator. <s> Birdsong was best known for illustrating covers of "Star Trek" novels. <s> Birdsong was killed in a car crash on June 4, 2019 at the age of 59.

title: Willerval
complex: Willerval is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Willerval is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Bucklesham
complex: Bucklesham is a village and civil parish in the East Suffolk district of Suffolk, England, a few miles east of Ipswich.
simple: Bucklesham is a village and civil parish in Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England.

title: Meslay-du-Maine
complex: Meslay-du-Maine is a commune in the Mayenne department in north-western France.
simple: Meslay-du-Maine is a commune of 2 616 people (1999).

title: Veneridae
