complex: The Veneridae or venerids, common name: venus clams, are a very large family of minute to large, saltwater clams, marine bivalve molluscs. <s> Over 500 living species of venerid bivalves are known, most of which are edible, and many of which are exploited as food sources.
simple: Veneridae is a family of clams, with over 500 described species, in twelve subfamilies. <s> They are commonly called Venus clams. <s> They are bivalve molluscs. <s> Many are edible and used as seafood.

title: Bucov
complex: Bucov (] ) is a commune in Prahova County, Romania, just east of Ploieşti, the county seat. <s> It is composed of five villages: Bighilin, Bucov, Chițorani, Pleașa and Valea Orlei.
simple: Bucov is a commune in the Prahova County, Romania.

title: Vaiśravaṇa
complex: The name is a derivative (used, e.g., for patronymics) of the Sanskrit proper name from the root "hear distinctly", (passive) "become famous". <s> The name is derived from the Sanskrit " " which means "son of Vishrava", a usual epithet of the Hindu god Kubera. <s> is also known as Kubera and Jambhala in Sanskrit and Kuvera in Pāli. <s> The character of is founded upon the Hindu deity Kubera, but although the Buddhist and Hindu deities share some characteristics and epithets, each of them has different functions and associated myths. <s> Although brought into East Asia as a Buddhist deity, has become a character in folk religion and has acquired an identity that is partially independent of the Buddhist tradition (cf. the similar treatment of Guanyin and Yama). <s> He is often portrayed with a yellow face. <s> He carries an umbrella or parasol (chatra) as a symbol of his sovereignty. <s> He is also sometimes displayed with a mongoose, often shown ejecting jewels from its mouth. <s> The mongoose is the enemy of the snake, a symbol of greed or hatred; the ejection of jewels represents generosity. <s> In the Pāli Canon of Theravāda Buddhism, is called . <s> is one of the "Cāturmahārājika deva" or "Four Great Heavenly Kings", each of whom rules over a specific direction. <s> 's realm is the northern quadrant of the world, including the land of Uttarakuru. <s> According to some suttas, he takes his name from a region there called ; he also has a city there called Ālakamandā which is a byword for wealth. <s> governs the yakshas – beings with a nature between 'fairy' and 'ogre'. <s> As with all the Buddhist deities, is properly the name of an office (filled for life) rather than a permanent individual. <s> Each is mortal, and when he dies, he will be replaced by a new . <s> Like other beings of the Cātummahārājika world, his lifespan is 90,000 years (other sources say nine million years). <s> has the authority to grant the yakkhas particular areas (e.g., a lake) to protect, and these are usually assigned at the beginning of a 's reign. <s> When Gautama Buddha was born, became his follower, and eventually attained the stage of sotāpanna, one who has only seven more lives before enlightenment. <s> He often brought the Buddha and his followers messages from the gods and other humans, and protected them. <s> He presented to the Buddha the verses, which Buddhists meditating in the forest could use to ward off the attacks of wild yakkhas or other supernatural beings who do not have faith in the Buddha. <s> These verses are an early form of paritta chanting. <s> In Japan, Bishamonten (毘沙門天), or just Bishamon (毘沙門) is thought of as an armor-clad god of war or warriors and a punisher of evildoers. <s> Bishamon is portrayed holding a spear in one hand and a small pagoda in the other hand, the latter symbolizing the divine treasure house, whose contents he both guards and gives away. <s> In Japanese folklore, he is one of the Seven Lucky Gods. <s> In Tibet, is considered a lokapāla or dharmapāla in the retinue of Ratnasambhava. <s> He is also known as the King of the North. <s> As guardian of the north, he is often depicted on temple murals outside the main door. <s> He is also thought of as a god of wealth. <s> As such, is sometimes portrayed carrying a citron, the fruit of the "jambhara" tree, a pun on another name of his, Jambhala. <s> The fruit helps distinguish him iconically from depictions of Kuvera. <s> He is sometimes represented as corpulent and covered with jewels.
simple: The name Vaiśravaṇa comes from the Sanskrit viśravaṇa which means "Great Fame". <s> Vaiśravaṇa is also known as Kubera in Sanskrit or Kuvera in Pāli. <s> The character of Vaiśravaṇa is set up on the Hindu god Kubera, but although the Buddhist and Hindu deities share some characteristics, both of them have different functions and myths. <s> He is often shown with a yellow face. <s> He carries an umbrella as a sign of his power. <s> He is also sometimes shown with a mongoose, often shown spitting out jewels. <s> The mongoose is the enemy of the snake, which is a symbol of greed or hatred; the spitting out of jewels shows generosity. <s> In the Pāli writings of the Theravāda Buddhist tradition, Vaiśravaṇa is called Vessavaṇa. <s> Vessavaṇa is one of the Four Great Kings, each one of which rules over a direction. <s> Vessavaṇa's direction is the northern quarter of the world. <s> As with all the Buddhist deities, Vessavaṇa is properly the name of a person who has the god inside him rather than a permanent individual. <s> Each Vessavaṇa is a human, and when he dies, he will be replaced by a new Vessavaṇa. <s> Like other beings of the Cātummahārājika world, his lifespan is 90,000 years, but other sources say nine million years. <s> When the Buddha was born, Vessavaṇa became his follower. <s> He often brought the Buddha and his followers messages from the gods and other humans, and protected them. <s> In Japan, Bishamonten (毘沙門天), or just Bishamon (毘沙門) is thought of as a god of war or warriors who wears armor, and a punisher of people who do evil things, a view that is very strange when compared with the more peaceful Buddhist king described above. <s> Bishamon is shown holding a spear in one hand and a small pagoda in the other hand. <s> The Pagoda symbolises the divine treasure house, which holds things that he guards and gives away. <s> In Japanese folklore, he is one of the Japanese Seven Lucky Gods. <s> He is also known as the King of the North. <s> As guardian of the north, he is often shown on temple wall paintings outside the main door. <s> He is also a god of wealth. <s> Vaiśravaṇa is sometimes shown carrying a citron, the fruit of the "jambhara" tree. <s> The fruit helps pick him out from depictions of Kuvera.

title: Pedro Zaballa
complex: Pedro Zaballa Barquín (29 July 1938 – 4 June 1997) was a Spanish footballer who played for FC Barcelona between 1961 and 1967, and scored the 2000th goal for Barcelona in La Liga.
simple: Pedro Zaballa (29 July 1938 – 4 June 1997) is a former Spanish football player.

title: Vulvar cancer
complex: Vulvar cancer is a cancer of the vulva, the outer portion of the female genitals. <s> It most commonly affects the outer vaginal lips.
simple: Vulvar cancer is a disease in which cells in the body grow out of control in or on the vulva. <s> The vulva is the outer part of the female genital organs. <s> Vulvar cancer most often occurs on the inner edges of the labia. <s> When vulvar cancers are found early, treatment works best.

title: Sondersdorf
complex: Sondersdorf is a commune in the Haut-Rhin department in Alsace in north-eastern France.
simple: Sondersdorf is a commune. <s> It is found in the Haut-Rhin department of eastern France.

title: Uptown Girls
complex: Uptown Girls is a 2003 American comedy-drama film directed by Boaz Yakin, who was working from a screenplay which Julia Dahl, Mo Ogrodnik and Lisa Davidowitz had adapted from the story by Allison Jacobs. <s> It stars Brittany Murphy as a 22-year-old living a charmed life as the daughter of a famous rock and roll musician.
simple: Uptown Girls is a movie starring Brittany Murphy and Dakota Fanning.

title: Cairo, Georgia
complex: Cairo is a city in Grady County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 9,607. <s> The city is the county seat of Grady County.
simple: Cairo is a city in Grady County, Georgia, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city had a population of 9,607. <s> The city is the county seat of Grady County.

title: National Museum of Mongolia
complex: The National Museum of Mongolia ; formerly the National Museum of Mongolian History is located in Ulaanbaatar. <s> This museum is a cultural, scientific, and educational organization, which is responsible for the collection, conservation and interpretation of the objects under its curation.
simple: The National Museum of Mongolia has exhibitions about archaeology, history and Mongolian culture.

title: Tarn (river)
complex: The Tarn ( , , possibly meaning 'rapid' or 'walled in') is a 381 km long river in southern France ("régions" Languedoc-Roussillon and Midi-Pyrénées), right tributary of the Garonne.
simple: The Tarn is a river in southern France, tributary of the Garonne river. <s> The Tarn river has a length of 380.6 km and a drainage basin with an area of 15700 km2.

title: Hot n Cold
complex: "Hot n Cold" is a song by American singer Katy Perry. <s> The song was written by Perry, Dr. Luke, and Max Martin and produced by Dr. Luke and Benny Blanco for her second studio album, "One of the Boys" (2008). <s> The track was released as the album's second single on September 9, 2008. <s> The lyrics address an unstable romantic relationship caused by a partner's mood swings. <s> The song reached number three on the "Billboard" Hot 100, becoming Perry's second consecutive top three single, following "I Kissed a Girl". <s> It also became Perry's second top five single in the United Kingdom, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand, and topped the charts in Finland, Germany, Canada, Norway, Spain, and Denmark, among others. <s> To date, "Hot n Cold" has sold over 5.7 million copies in the US, making it one of Perry's highest-selling singles in the nation.
simple: "Hot N Cold" is a single by pop singer Katy Perry. <s> The song came from the album "One of the Boys". <s> The single was released on September 30, 2008. <s> The song reached number one in Canada, Denmark, Norway, Finland, Switzerland, Germany, Austria, and Belgium (Wallonia). <s> It climbed to the top three in the US and the top five in the UK, Australia, and New Zealand.

title: Raghbir Singh Bhola
complex: Raghbir Singh Bhola (21 August 1927 – 21 January 2019) was an Indian Airforce Officer and international hockey player who represented India in the 1956 Melbourne and 1960 Rome Olympics, winning a gold and silver medal respectively for the country. <s> Bhola, was born in a middle-class family in Multan (now Pakistan); his ancestors belonged to Pind Dadan Khan and his grandparents moved to Multan around the end of the 18th Century. <s> He went to the Government Model High School, in Khanewal, Pakistan.
simple: Raghbir Singh Bhola (21 August 1927 – 22 January 2019) was an Indian Airforce Officer and a former India hockey player. <s> He represented India in the 1956 Melbourne and 1960 Rome Olympics, winning a gold and silver medal respectively for the country. <s> He was born in Multan, Pakistan.

title: Nickelodeon Movies
complex: Nickelodeon Movies is the theatrical motion picture production arm of the Nickelodeon TV channel. <s> Founded in 1996, the company released its first film "Harriet the Spy" in 1996.
simple: Nickelodeon Movies is the motion picture production arm of children's cable channel Nickelodeon, originally launched in 1996.

title: Dison
complex: Dison is a Walloon municipality located in the Belgian province of Liège. <s> On January 1, 2006, Dison had a total population of 14,243.
simple: Dison is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: Ulricehamn Municipality
complex: Ulricehamn Municipality ("Ulricehamns kommun") is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in western Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the city of Ulricehamn.
simple: Ulricehamn Municipality is a municipality in Västra Götaland County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Ulricehamn.

title: Great power
complex: A great power is a sovereign state that is recognized as having the ability and expertise to exert its influence on a global scale. <s> Great powers characteristically possess military and economic strength, as well as diplomatic and soft power influence, which may cause middle or small powers to consider the great powers' opinions before taking actions of their own. <s> International relations theorists have posited that great power status can be characterized into power capabilities, spatial aspects, and status dimensions.
simple: A great power is a nation or state that is able to influence other states in most of the world. <s> That is possible because it has great economic, political and military strength.

title: Lauterpacht Centre for International Law
complex: The Lauterpacht Centre for International Law (LCIL) at the Faculty of Law, Cambridge, England, was founded in 1985 by Sir Elihu Lauterpacht under the name "The Research Centre for International Law". <s> It was renamed in 1997 "to honour the achievements of his father Sir Hersch Lauterpacht and himself". <s> The purpose of the centre is to "promote international law by a combination of individual and group research, whether undertaken privately by scholars or funded externally, and by the publication of monographs and collections of primary materials".
simple: The Lauterpacht Centre for International Law (LCIL) at the Faculty of Law, Cambridge, England, was founded in 1985 by Sir Elihu Lauterpacht under the name The Research Centre for International Law. <s> It was renamed in 1997 “to honour the achievements of his father Sir Hersch Lauterpacht and himself”. <s> The purpose of the centre is to "promote international law by a combination of individual and group research”.

title: Playback singer
complex: A playback singer is a singer whose singing is pre-recorded for use in movies. <s> Playback singers record songs for soundtracks, and actors or actresses lip-sync the songs for cameras; the actual singer does not appear on the screen. <s> South Asian movies produced in the Indian subcontinent are particularly known for using this technique. <s> A majority of Indian movies as well as Pakistani movies typically include six or seven songs. <s> After "Alam Ara" (1931), the first Indian talkie film, for many years singers made dual recordings for a film, one during the shoot, and later in the recording studio, until 1952 or 1953. <s> Popular playback singers in India enjoy the same status as popular actors, and music directors, and they also receive wide public admiration. <s> Most of the playback singers are initially trained in classical music, but they later often expand their range. <s> Mohammed Rafi and Ahmed Rushdi are regarded as two of the most influential playback singers in South Asia. <s> The sisters Lata Mangeshkar and Asha Bhosle, who have mainly worked in Hindi films, are often referred to as two of the best-known and prolific playback singers in India.
simple: A playback singer is a singer whose singing is pre-recorded for use in movies. <s> Playback singers record songs for soundtracks. <s> The actors or actresses lip-sync the songs for cameras. <s> The actual singer does not appear on screen. <s> South Asian movies produced in the Indian subcontinent are particularly known for using this technique. <s> A majority of Indian movies as well as Pakistani movies typically include six or seven songs. <s> Popular playback singers in India enjoy the same status as popular actors. <s> Most of the playback singers are initially trained in classical music. <s> Mohammed Rafi and Ahmed Rushdi are regarded as two of the most influential playback singers in South Asia.

title: Hesdin
complex: Hesdin (] ) is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in northern France.
simple: Hesdin is a commune.

title: Waterbury, Connecticut
complex: Waterbury (nicknamed "The Brass City") is a city in the U.S. state of Connecticut on the Naugatuck River, 33 miles southwest of Hartford and 77 miles northeast of New York City. <s> Waterbury is the second-largest city in New Haven County, Connecticut.
simple: Waterbury is a town in the state of Connecticut.

title: Equivalence relation
complex: In mathematics, an equivalence relation is a binary relation that is reflexive, symmetric and transitive. <s> As a consequence of the reflexive, symmetric, and transitive properties, any equivalence relation provides a partition of the underlying set into disjoint equivalence classes. <s> Two elements of the given set are equivalent to each other if and only if they belong to the same equivalence class.
simple: The equivalence relation is a mathematical relation that is symmetric, transitive and reflexive. <s> Using this relation, it is possible to partition a set into (non-empty) subsets, which are called "equivalence classes".

title: Joe P. Tolson
complex: Joe Pat Tolson (April 15, 1941 – February 3, 2019) was a Democratic member of the North Carolina General Assembly representing the state's twenty-third House district, including constituents in Edgecombe and Wilson counties. <s> A retired educator from Pinetops, North Carolina, Tolson retired after the 2013-2014 session, serving his ninth term in the state House. <s> He was replaced by Shelly Willingham. <s> Tolson died in 2019 from respiratory failure at a hospital in Tarboro, North Carolina.
simple: Joe Pat Tolson (April 15, 1941 – February 3, 2019) was an American Democratic politician. <s> Tolson died on February 3, 2019 from respiratory failure at a hospital in Tarboro, North Carolina, aged 77.

title: Viveca Lärn
complex: Viveca Lärn, earlier Viveca Sundvall, born 6 April 1944 in Örgryte Parish in Gothenburg, Sweden, is a Swedish writer. <s> She is mostly famous for writing the Mimmi and the Eddie children's books series. <s> She has also written books for an adult audience, and many of those books formed the basis for the TV series "Saltön".
simple: Viveca Lärn, earlier Viveca Sundvall, born 6 April 1944 in Örgryte Parish in Gothenburg, Sweden, is a Swedish writer. <s> She is mostly famous for writing the Mimmi and the Eddie children's books series. <s> She has also written books for adults. <s> Her books for adults have led to the TV series "Saltön".

title: Richard II, Duke of Normandy
complex: Richard II (died 28 August 1026), called the Good (French: "Le Bon"), was the eldest son and heir of Richard I the Fearless and Gunnor. <s> He was a Norman nobleman of the House of Normandy. <s> He was the paternal grandfather of William the Conqueror. <s> Richard succeeded his father as Duke of Normandy in 996. <s> During his minority, the first five years of his reign (suggesting he was born between 980 and 990), his regent was Count Rodulf of Ivry, his uncle, who wielded the power and put down a peasant insurrection at the beginning of Richard's reign. <s> Richard had deep religious interests and found he had much in common with Robert II of France, who he helped militarily against the duchy of Burgundy. <s> He forged a marriage alliance with Brittany by marrying his sister Hawise to Geoffrey I, Duke of Brittany and by his own marriage to Geoffrey's sister, Judith of Brittany. <s> In 1000–1001, Richard repelled an English attack on the Cotentin Peninsula that was led by Ethelred II of England. <s> Ethelred had given orders that Richard be captured, bound and brought to England. <s> But the English had not been prepared for the rapid response of the Norman cavalry and were defeated at the Battle of Val-de-Saire. <s> Richard attempted to improve relations with England through his sister Emma of Normandy's marriage to King Ethelred. <s> This marriage was significant in that it later gave his grandson, William the Conqueror, the basis of his claim to the throne of England. <s> The improved relations proved to be beneficial to Ethelred when in 1013 Sweyn Forkbeard invaded England. <s> Emma with her two sons Edward and Alfred fled to Normandy followed shortly thereafter by her husband king Ethelred. <s> Soon after the death of Ethelred, Cnut, King of England forced Emma to marry him while Richard was forced to recognize the new regime as his sister was again Queen. <s> Richard had contacts with Scandinavian Vikings throughout his reign. <s> He employed Viking mercenaries and concluded a treaty with Sweyn Forkbeard who was en route to England. <s> Richard II commissioned his clerk and confessor, Dudo of Saint-Quentin, to portray his ducal ancestors as morally upright Christian leaders who built Normandy despite the treachery of their overlords and neighboring principalities. <s> It was clearly a work of propaganda designed to legitimize the Norman settlement, and while it contains numerous historically unreliable legends, as respects the reigns of his father and grandfather, Richard I and William I it is basically reliable. <s> In 1025 and 1026 Richard confirmed gifts of his great-grandfather Rollo to Saint-Ouen at Rouen. <s> His other numerous grants to monastic houses tends to indicate the areas over which Richard had ducal control, namely Caen, the Éverecin, the Cotentin, the Pays de Caux and Rouen. <s> Richard II died 28 Aug 1026. <s> his eldest son, Richard becoming the new duke.
simple: Richard II († 1026), called the Good (French: "Le Bon"), was the Duke of Normandy from 996 to 1026. <s> Richard II was the oldest son of Richard I the Fearless and Gunnora. <s> He succeeded his father as Duke of Normandy in 996. <s> During his minority, which was the first five years of his reign, his was his uncle Count Ralph of Ivrea. <s> Ralph put down a peasant revolt at the start of Richard's reign. <s> Richard was very religious like his overlord king Robert II of France. <s> Richard used his army to support the king against the duchy of Burgundy. <s> He formed a marriage alliance with Brittany by marrying his sister Hawise of Normandy to Geoffrey I, Duke of Brittany. <s> It became a double alliance when he married Geoffrey's sister, Judith of Brittany. <s> In 1000-1001 the English attacked Normandy on the Cotentin Peninsula. <s> Ethelred had given orders that Richard be captured, shackled and brought to England. <s> But the English were not prepared for the rapid response of the Norman cavalry and were quickly defeated. <s> He gave his sister Emma of Normandy in marriage to King Ethelred. <s> This turned out to be an important marriage as it later gave Richard's grandson, William the Conqueror, a claim to the throne of England. <s> In 1013 when Sweyn Forkbeard invaded England, Emma with her two sons Edward and Alfred fled to Normandy. <s> After losing his throne King Ethelred followed shortly. <s> Soon after the death of Ethelred, Cnut, King of England forced Emma to marry him. <s> Duke Richard was forced to recognize the new regime as his sister was again Queen. <s> He commissioned Dudo of Saint-Quentin to write a detailed history of the Norman Dukes showing their and Christian patronage. <s> Richard II commissioned Dudo of Saint-Quentin, his clerk and priest, to write about his ancestors. <s> He wanted them shown to be good and upright leaders who built Normandy despite the bad behavior of their Frankish neighbors. <s> In 1025 and 1026 Richard confirmed gifts of his ancestor Rollo to Saint-Ouen at Rouen. <s> He gave many other gifts to Monasteries. <s> Their names show the areas over which Richard had ducal control: Caen, the Éverecin, the Cotentin, the Pays de Caux and Rouen. <s> Richard II died 28 Aug 1026.

title: Grunerite
complex: Grunerite is a mineral of the amphibole group of minerals with formula FeSiO(OH). <s> It is the iron endmember of the grunerite-cummingtonite series.
simple: It has the chemical formula FeSiO(OH).

title: Bradenton, Florida
complex: Bradenton is a city in Manatee County, Florida, United States. <s> The U.S. Census Bureau estimated the city's 2018 population to be 57,644. <s> Bradenton is a principal city of the North Port–Sarasota–Bradenton metropolitan statistical area, which had a 2018 estimated population of 821,573. <s> It is the county seat.
simple: Bradenton is a city of Florida in the United States. <s> It is the county seat of Manatee County.

title: Adile Naşit
complex: Adile Naşit (17 June 1930 – 11 December 1987) was a Turkish actress, who is best known for being the partner of Münir Özkul in movies like "Happy Days" and in "Hababam Sınıfı" (Hababam Class). <s> She also starred in many plays, movies, and a children's programme called "Uykudan Önce" (Before Sleep) as a storyteller.
simple: Adile Naşit (June 17, 1930 – December 11, 1987) was a Turkish movie actress. <s> She played in many Turkish movies.

title: Recess (album)
complex: Recess is the debut and currently only studio album by American record producer Skrillex, released on March 18, 2014 by Owsla, Big Beat Records, and Atlantic Records. <s> It was recorded between 2013 and 2014 whilst Skrillex was touring around the world. <s> "Try It Out (Neon Mix)" with Alvin Risk was released as the album's lead single on October 14, 2013 alongside two more mixes of the song.
simple: Recess is the debut studio album by American electronic music producer, Skrillex. <s> "Recess" was released on March 14, 2014. <s> It was released through Big Beat Records, Asylum Records, and Atlantic Records. <s> Skrillex recorded the album while he was touring around the world, through countries such as the United States, Canada, South Korea, and the United Kingdom.

title: David Pall
complex: David Boris Pall (2 April 1914 – 21 September 2004), founder of Pall Corporation, was the chemist who invented the Pall filter used in blood transfusions. <s> Born in 1914 in Thunder Bay, Ontario of Russian immigrant parents, he grew up on a farm in Saskatchewan. <s> He attended McGill University, from which he was granted a bachelor's degree in chemistry and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry. <s> He moved to New York City in 1938 and became a part of the Manhattan Project. <s> Pall worked on the design a filter to separate uranium 235 from uranium 238 using sintered stainless steel mesh. <s> In 1946, he established Pall Corporation. <s> The company's initial focus was on the development of filters for use in aircraft hydraulics. <s> However, in 1959, when Dr. Pall's first wife, Josephine, died of aplastic anemia, he began to work on the "Pall filter". <s> Mrs. Pall had undergone multiple blood transfusions in the course of an illness, which were ultimately unsuccessful. <s> His Pall filter was designed to make blood transfusions significantly safer by filtering out white blood cells, thereby reducing the incidence of transfusion reactions and viral infections. <s> Pall expanded the business, adding additional products. <s> Today, Pall Corporation has sales in excess of $2.0 Billion. <s> In his lifetime, Dr. Pall received over 180 patents and in 1990, he received the United States National Medal of Technology from President George H.W. Bush. <s> Pall died of complications of Alzheimer's disease at his last home in Roslyn Estates, New York.
simple: David Boris Pall (2 April 1914 - 21 September 2004), founder of Pall Corporation, was the chemist who invented the Pall filter used in blood transfusions. <s> Born in Thunder Bay, Ontario of Russian immigrant parents, he grew up on a farm in Saskatchewan, and attended McGill University, from which he was granted a bachelor's degree in chemistry and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry. <s> He moved to New York in 1938 and became a part of the Manhattan Project. <s> In 1946, he established Pall Corporation. <s> The company's initial focus was on the development of filters for use in aircraft hydraulics. <s> However, in 1959, when Dr. Pall's first wife, Josephine, died of aplastic anemia, he began to work on the Pall filter. <s> Mrs. Pall had undergone multiple blood transfusions in the course of an illness, which were ultimately unsuccessful. <s> The Pall filter makes blood transfusions significantly safer by filtering out white blood cells, thereby reducing the incidence of transfusion reactions and viral infections. <s> Today, Pall Corporation has sales in excess of $2.0 Billion. <s> In his lifetime, Dr. Pall received over 180 patents and in 1990, he received the United States National Medal of Technology from President George H.W. Bush. <s> Pall, a trustee of the North Shore University Hospital, died of complications of Alzheimer's disease at his last home in Roslyn Estates, New York.

title: Graphical user interface
complex: Graphical user interface (GUI) wrappers find a way around the command-line interface versions (CLI) of (typically) Linux and Unix-like software applications and their text-based user interfaces or typed command labels. <s> While command-line or text-based application allow users to run a program non-interactively, GUI wrappers atop them avoid the steep learning curve of the command-line, which requires commands to be typed on the keyboard.
simple: Computers can display information and let the user give commands to it using two methods: a command line interface (CLI) or a graphical user interface (GUI).

title: Joel Daly
complex: Joel Daly (born August 21, 1934) is an American former news anchor. <s> Daly is most known for serving as an anchor for WLS-TV (an ABC-affiliate) in Chicago, Illinois for 38 years from 1967–2005. <s> Daly served as co-anchor on the 4PM news broadcast alongside Linda Yu from January 1985 until his retirement in May 2005. <s> Daly was inducted into the Silver Circle, a group of elite Chicago broadcasters, in 2003. <s> Since his retirement from news broadcasting in 2005, From March 2007 until October 2013, Daly served as spokesperson for Chicago's Cook County Federal courthouse.
simple: Joel Daly (born August 21, 1934) is an American former news anchor. <s> Daly is most known for serving as an anchor for WLS-TV (an ABC-affiliate) in Chicago, Illinois for 38 years from 1967–2005. <s> Daly served as co-anchor alongside Linda Yu from January 1985 until his retirement in May 2005. <s> From March 2007 until October 2013, Daly served as spokesperson for Chicago's Cook County Federal courthouse.

title: Mastung, Pakistan
complex: Mastung , the capital of Mastung District, is a town in the Balochistan province of Pakistan. <s> It is located at 29°48'0N 66°50'60E and has an altitude of 1701 metres (5583 feet). <s> The town is also the administrative centre of Mastung Tehsil, an administrative subdivision of the district – the town itself is administratively subdivided into two Union Councils.
simple: Mastung, the capital of Mastung District, is a town in the Baluchistan province of Pakistan. <s> It is located at 29°48'0N 66°50'60E and has an altitude of 1701 metres (5583 feet). <s> The town is also the administrative centre of Mastung Tehsil, an administrative subdivision of the district - the town itself is administratively subdivided into two Union Councils of Pakistan

title: The Statesman (India)
complex: The Statesman is an Indian English-language broadsheet daily newspaper founded in 1875 and published simultaneously in Kolkata, New Delhi, Siliguri and Bhubaneswar. <s> It incorporates and is directly descended from The Friend of India, founded in 1818.
simple: The Statesman is a English language newspaper published in India. <s> It is published simultaneously from Kolkata, New Delhi, Siliguri and Bhubaneshwar.

title: Piroska Oszoli
complex: Piroska Oszoli (21 January 1919 – 22 March 2017) was a Hungarian painter, is known as "The lover of the Danube and the beautiness". <s> She worked especially as applied to plein air landscape painting. <s> Piroska Oszoli (née Névery) was born in Dunaföldvár, Hungary in a Roman Catholic baron family on 21 January 1919. <s> After finishing her studies, she taught literature and history in Budapest. <s> Her master as an amateur artist was the note Transylvanian painter "Ferenc Doór" (1918–2015). <s> From 1947, after having returned in her native village to teach painting for schoolchildren, she completed her art studies as well. <s> Her husband was István Oszoli, a high school biology and chemistry teacher from 1949 until his death in 2003. <s> They have two sons, István (b. 1950) and András (b. 1953). <s> After teaching she became a pensioner, and started her painting as an individual artist. <s> She worked all around her village and neighborhood, after in Hungary, at Lake Balaton for example, and also in some beautiful places of Europe, from Italy to Norway, and from Germany to Croatia. <s> She had numerous expositions in her Country. <s> Her paintings are present around the World from Austria to New Zealand. <s> She died in her home in Dunaföldvár at the age of 98 years on 22 March 2017.
simple: Piroska Oszoli (21 January 1919 – 22 March 2017) was a Hungarian painter, is known as "The lover of the Danube and the beautiness". <s> She made especially as applied to plein-air landscape painting. <s> She was born and also dead in Dunaföldvár, Hungary. <s> Her master as an amateur artist was the famous Transylvanian painter Ferenc Doór (1918–2015). <s> After teaching she became a pensioner, and started her painting as an individual artist. <s> Oszoli worked all around her village and neighborhood, after in Hungary, at Balaton. <s> She painted natural surroundings in Italy, Croatia, Germany and Norway. <s> Her paintings are present from Austria to New Zealand. <s> Oszoli died on 22 March 2017 in Dunaföldvár, aged 98.

title: Plomb du Cantal
complex: The Plomb du Cantal is the highest summit of Mounts of Cantal in the Massif central, France. <s> It's the second highest summit of the Massif central after the mountain of puy de Sancy.
simple: Plomb du Cantal is a French mountain, the highest summit of Mounts of Cantal in the "Massif Central", France. <s> Plomb du Cantal is in the Mounts of Cantal, a chain of volcanic mountains in the Massif Central, in the centre of the Cantal department. <s> It is the highest mountain of the Cantal department and the second highest in the Massif Central, after Puy de Sancy that is 1885 m high.

title: Salim Ahmed Salim
complex: Salim Ahmed Salim ( , Urdu: , , born 23 January 1942) is a Tanzanian politician and diplomat who has worked in the international diplomatic arena since the early 1960s.
simple: Salim Ahmed Salim (, Urdu: , , born 23 January 1942) is a Tanzanian diplomat.

title: The Destruction of Sodom And Gomorrah
complex: The destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah is a painting by the English painter John Martin from 1852. <s> John Martin's painting, shows the biblical story of the destruction of the two cities of Sodom and Gomorrah, which was God's punishment for the two cities for people's immoral behavior. <s> Only Lot and his daughters were saved. <s> Lot's wife disobeyed God's instruction not to look back, and was turned into a pillar of salt. <s> The fiery red color is characteristic of John Martin's dramatic scenes of destruction. <s> The swirling storm in heaven was also a frequent feature of his paintings. <s> It is 136.3 x 212.3 cm. <s> It is in the collection of the Laing Art Gallery in Newcastle upon Tyne.
simple: The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah is a painting by John Martin (1789-1854). <s> Martin painted it in 1852. <s> "The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah" was the last painting that Martin finished. <s> The painting shows the destruction of the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah from the Bible. <s> Lot's wife looked back and became a pillar of salt. <s> The painting has a red color and a storm in the sky, typical of Martin's work. <s> "The Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah" is in the Laing Art Gallery in Newcastle, England.

title: Kaltag, Alaska
complex: Kaltag (KAL-tag) ("Ggaał Doh" in Koyukon) is a city and village in Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska, United States. <s> At the 2010 census the population was 190, down from 230 in 2000. <s> Kaltag was a Koyokon Athabascan area used as a cemetery for surrounding villages. <s> It is located on an old portage trail which led west through the mountains to Unalakleet. <s> The Athabascans had seasonal camps in the area and moved as the wild game migrated. <s> There were 12 summer fish camps located on the Yukon River between the Koyukuk River and the Nowitna River. <s> Kaltag was named by Russians for a Koyokon man named Kaltaga. <s> There was a smallpox epidemic in 1839 that killed a large part of the population of the area. <s> After the Alaska Purchase, a United States military telegraph line was constructed along the north side of the Yukon River. <s> A trading post opened around 1880, just before the gold rush of 1884-85. <s> Steamboats on the Yukon, which supplied gold prospectors ran before and after 1900 with 46 boats in operation on the river in the peak year of 1900. <s> A measles epidemic and food shortages during 1900 reduced the population of the area by one-third. <s> The village Kaltag was established after the epidemic when survivors from three nearby villages moved to the area. <s> There was a minor gold rush in the area in the 1880s. <s> In 1906, gold seekers left for Fairbanks or Nome; however, the galena lead mines began operating in 1919. <s> Kaltag was downriver from the mines and grew as a point on the transportation route for the mines. <s> It declined in the 1940s as mining declined. <s> The old cemetery caved into the river around 1937. <s> An airport and clinic were constructed during the 1960s. <s> Kaltag has a week long Stick Dance (memorial Potlatch) every two years that draws visitors from many neighboring villages. <s> This Potlatch is sponsored by relatives of the recently deceased, in appreciation of those who helped during their time of mourning. <s> Much of the economy around Kaltag is based on subsistence hunting and fishing. <s> Salmon, whitefish, moose, bear, waterfowl and berries are elements of the subsistence economy. <s> Kaltag is located at (64.325145, -158.727030) and is on the west bank of the Yukon River, 120 km west of Galena of 27.4 sqmi , of which, 23.3 sqmi of it is land and 4.1 sqmi of it (14.97%) is water.
simple: Kaltag is a town in Alaska. <s> They used Kaltag as a cemetery for surrounding villages. <s> It is on an old walking track which led west through the mountains to Unalakleet. <s> The Athabascans had many camps in the area. <s> They moved as the animals they hunted for food moved to different areas. <s> There were 12 summer fish camps on the Yukon River between the Koyukuk River and the Nowitna River. <s> The Russians named Kaltag after a Koyokon man named Kaltaga. <s> In 1839 smallpox killed many of the people who lived in the area. <s> When the United States took over Alaska, the army built a telegraph line along the north side of the Yukon River. <s> A trading post opened around 1880. <s> There was a gold rush in 1884-85. <s> Steamboats travelled along the river carrying supplies for the gold miners. <s> In 1900 there were 46 steamboats on the river. <s> Measles and food shortages during 1900 reduced the population of the area by one-third. <s> The village of Kaltag began after this when the people who were left in three nearby villages moved to the area. <s> By 1906, most of the people looking gold had left for Fairbanks or Nome. <s> The Galena lead mines opened 1919. <s> Kaltag was down the river from the mines and grew as a point on the transportation route for the mines. <s> It declined in the 1940s as mining declined. <s> The old cemetery was washed into the river around 1937. <s> An airport and medical clinic were built during the 1960s. <s> Kaltag has a week long Stick Dance Festival every two years that draws visitors from many other villages. <s> This festival is held by relatives of people who have died, to thank those who helped during their time of mourning. <s> Most of the people in Kaltag live by hunting and fishing. <s> Salmon, whitefish, moose, bear, waterfowl and berries are the main foods. <s> Kaltag is on the west bank of the Yukon River, 120 km (75 miles) west of Galena.

title: List of foreign-born Medal of Honor recipients
complex: The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War and is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal, it is commonly presented posthumously. <s> Although Medals of Honor can be awarded only to members of the U.S. armed forces, being a U.S. citizen is not a prerequisite for eligibility to receive the medal. <s> Since the American Civil War, hundreds of people born outside the United States have received the medal, the most recent of these recipients being Pedro Cano and Jesus S. Duran who received their medals in March 2014 for actions performed during World War II and the Vietnam War respectively. <s> The large number of foreign-born recipients during the 19th and early 20th centuries was mostly due to immigration waves from Europe.
simple: The Medal of Honor was created during the American Civil War. <s> It is the highest military decoration presented by the United States government to a member of its armed forces. <s> The recipient must have distinguished themselves at the risk of their own life above and beyond the call of duty in action against an enemy of the United States. <s> Due to the nature of this medal it is commonly presented after the recipient has been killed (posthumously). <s> Although Medals of Honor can be presented only to members of the U.S. armed forces it is not required to be a U.S. citizen. <s> Since the American Civil War hundreds of people born outside the United States have received the medal. <s> The large number of foreign-born recipients during the 19th and early 20th centuries was likely due to immigration waves from Europe.

title: Naga National Council
complex: The Naga National Council (NNC) was a political organization of Naga people, active from the late 1940s to the early 1950s. <s> Under the leadership of Angami Zapu Phizo in the 1940s, it unsuccessfully campaigned for the secession of the Naga territory from India and creation for a sovereign Naga state.
simple: The Naga National Council was a political organization of Naga people, active from the late 1940s to the early 1950s. <s> Under the leadership of Angami Zapu Phizo in the 1940s, it unsuccessfully campaigned for the secession of the Naga territory from the Republic of India and creation for a sovereign Naga state.

title: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian
complex: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian ( ; 16 December 1922 – 20 April 2019) was an Iranian artist and a collector of traditional folk art. <s> She is noted for having been one of the most prominent Iranian artists of the contemporary period, and she was the first artist to achieve an artistic practice that weds the geometric patterns and cut-glass mosaic techniques of her Iranian heritage with the rhythms of modern Western geometric abstraction. <s> In 2017, the Monir Museum in Tehran, Iran was opened in her honor. <s> Shahroudy was born on December 18, 1922, to educated parents in the religious town of Qazvin in north-western Iran. <s> Farmanfarmaian acquired artistic skills early on in childhood, receiving drawing lessons from a tutor and studying postcard depictions of western art. <s> After studying at the University of Tehran at the Faculty of Fine Art in 1944, she then moved to New York City via steamboat, when World War II derailed her plans to study art in Paris. <s> In New York, she studied at Cornell University, at Parsons The New School for Design, where she majored in fashion illustration, and at the Art Students League. <s> In 1992, Farmanfarmaian returned to Iran and later, in Tehran in 2004, she reaffirmed her place among Iran's art community, gathering both former and new employees to help create her mosaics. <s> She continued to live and work in Tehran until her death. <s> On 20 April 2019 Farmanfarmaian died at her home at the age of 96. <s> Farmanfarmaian married Iranian artist Manoucher Yektai in 1950.
simple: Monir Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian (‎; 16 December 1922 – 20 April 2019) was an Iranian artist and a collector of folk art. <s> She has been called one of the most important Iranian contemporary artists. <s> She is best known for her mosaics and glass paintings. <s> In 2017, the Monir Museum in Tehran was opened in her honour. <s> Shahroudy Farmanfarmaian was born in Qazvin. <s> She lived and worked in the United States for many years but later came back to Iran. <s> She died of natural causes in Tehran on 20 April 2019.

title: Reagan Doctrine
complex: The Reagan Doctrine was stated by United States President Ronald Reagan in his State of the Union address on February 6, 1985: "We must not break faith with those who are risking their lives--on every continent from Afghanistan to Nicaragua--to defy Soviet-supported aggression and secure rights which have been ours from birth." <s> It was a strategy implemented by the Reagan Administration to overwhelm the global influence of the Soviet Union in the late Cold War. <s> The doctrine was a centerpiece of United States foreign policy from the early 1980s until the end of the Cold War in 1991.
simple: It was about being against the global influence of the Soviet Union during the final years of the Cold War. <s> The doctrine lasted for less than a decade, it was the most important document of United States foreign policy from the early 1980s until the end of the Cold War in 1991.

title: Gignac, Vaucluse
complex: Gignac is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France. <s> Chateau d'Autet lies to the northeast of the village.
simple: It is in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Tropical Storm Beryl (2006)
complex: Tropical Storm Beryl was the third tropical storm of the 2006 Atlantic hurricane season. <s> Developing from a tropical disturbance on July 18, it tracked generally northward, and strengthened to attain peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) under generally favorable conditions. <s> After turning to the northeast, Beryl weakened over cooler waters. <s> On July 21 it struck the island of Nantucket, and shortly thereafter it became extratropical. <s> The extratropical remnants continued northeastward through Nova Scotia, and on July 22 it merged with an approaching cold front. <s> Beryl produced rough seas along the northeast United States coastline. <s> In Massachusetts, its impact was limited to light rainfall and gusty winds, with no reported damage. <s> Beryl later produced moderate rainfall and gusty winds across Atlantic Canada, resulting in some localized power outages though little damage. <s> No deaths were reported. <s> A cold front moved off the East Coast of the United States on July 16 and stalled off the coast of North Carolina. <s> It gradually decayed into a surface low pressure trough, and developed into two disturbances; one was centered 290 miles (490 km) south-southeast of Cape Cod and another was located 200 miles (320 km) south of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina. <s> The first low quickly organized into an unnamed tropical storm, and the other area initially remained broad and ill-defined. <s> However, by July 18, the system became much better organized with improved banding features, and the area developed into Tropical Depression Two while located 220 miles (355 km) south-southeast of Cape Hatteras. <s> The depression moved slowly to the north-northwest through a break in the subtropical ridge, and as convective banding features became more prominent the system intensified into Tropical Storm Beryl. <s> Throughout much of its duration, the storm tracked through an environment with light vertical wind shear and well-established upper-level outflow. <s> Shortly after becoming a tropical storm, the low-level circulation of Beryl became exposed with limited deep convection, though deep convection re-developed the following morning. <s> Outflow continued to improve, and with warm sea surface temperatures Beryl gradually intensified to attain peak winds of 60 mph (95 km/h) early on July 20 while located about 120 miles (190 km) east of Nags Head, North Carolina. <s> Beryl maintained peak winds for about 18 hours as it paralleled the Mid-Atlantic and New Jersey coasts, during which an eye-like feature developed in the center of the convection. <s> Late on July 20, it began a slow weakening trend after passing over cooler waters. <s> Steering winds ahead of an approaching mid-level trough caused Beryl to accelerate northeastward, and early on July 21 the center of the storm crossed the island of Nantucket. <s> The convection diminished as it moved through progressively colder waters, and shortly after 1200 UTC on July 21 Beryl became an extratropical cyclone a short distance east of Cape Cod. <s> Hours later, it made landfall in southwestern Nova Scotia, and on July 22 the extratropical remnants of Beryl merged with an approaching cold front over Newfoundland. <s> Forecasters initially predicted Beryl to brush the Carolinas; as such, a tropical storm watch was issued for the eastern coast of North Carolina from Cape Lookout northward to Currituck Beach Lighthouse. <s> When a more northeastward track became apparent, a tropical storm watch was issued about 33 hours prior to moving ashore from Woods Hole to Plymouth, Massachusetts, including Cape Cod, Nantucket, and Martha's Vineyard. <s> About 22 hours before landfall, the National Hurricane Center replaced the watch with a tropical storm warning for the same area, and also issued a tropical storm watch from Woods Hole, Massachusetts westward to New Haven, Connecticut and for the eastern portion of Long Island from east of Fire Island to Port Jefferson. <s> In anticipation for the storm, the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency was activated as a trial run for the hurricane season. <s> Local Red Cross chapters were opened, as well, with two volunteer teams placed on standby to assist. <s> Across southeastern Massachusetts, police departments maintained extra staff in preparation for any potential problems from the storm. <s> Many fishermen secured their boats, while some business owners boarded up windows to prevent storm damage. <s> Several days prior to the passage of Beryl through Atlantic Canada, the Canadian Hurricane Centre issued gale warnings for the coastal waters off Nova Scotia and Newfoundland. <s> In anticipation of heavy rainfall, the agency also issued heavy rainfall warnings for western Nova Scotia, including Halifax. <s> The storm caused high waves along the East Coast of the United States, with 19-foot seas (5.97 m) in the open ocean. <s> Waves along the southern coast of Nantucket reached 10 feet (3 m) in height as the storm approached the island, resulting in four people being rescued by lifeguards from rip currents. <s> High surf also occurred along the southern coast of Massachusetts, prompting the closing of the ferry between Nantucket and Boston. <s> Beryl produced a storm surge of 0.9 feet (.27 m) on Nantucket. <s> Winds across southeastern Massachusetts were fairly light, with no sustained tropical storm force winds and wind gusts peaking at 44 mph (71 km/h); unofficially gusts reached 51 mph (82 km/h). <s> Beryl dropped moderate precipitation just offshore, though the maximum precipitation total in the United States was only 0.97 inches (24.6 mm) on Nantucket. <s> Rainfall along southeastern Massachusetts reached 0.33 inches (8.38 mm) at Chatham. <s> The only reported damage were some downed telephone poles and fallen tree branches. <s> Overall impact was minor; there were no reported power outages, deaths, injuries, or maritime emergencies in association with the storm. <s> The remnants of Beryl dropped moderate precipitation in Atlantic Canada, officially peaking at 2.8 inches (71 mm) in Scots Bay, Nova Scotia with an unofficially higher total of 3.5 inches (88 mm); in some locations 1 inch of rain fell in an hour. <s> Additionally, a station in Fredericton, New Brunswick reported 1.77 inches (45 mm) in two hours. <s> The rainfall caused some flooding, with some overflown streams flooding some streets. <s> Moderate winds were reported along its path, which peaked at 60 mph (96 km/h) in southern Nova Scotia. <s> The winds downed some tree limbs and led to some power outages. <s> Overall damage was minor.

title: New Castle County, Delaware
complex: New Castle County is the northernmost of the three counties of the U.S. state of Delaware. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 538,479, making it the most populous county in Delaware, with just under 60% of the state's population of 897,936 in the same census. <s> The county seat is Wilmington. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 500,265 people, 188,935 households, and 127,153 families residing in the county. <s> The population density is 1,174 people per square mile (453/km2).
simple: New Castle County is a county in the state of Delaware in the United States. <s> The county seat is Wilmington. <s> New Castle County had 500,265 people in 2000.

title: Form classification
complex: Form classification is the classification of organisms based on their morphology, which does not necessarily reflect their biological relationships. <s> Form classification, generally restricted to palaeontology, reflects uncertainty; the goal of science is to move "form taxa" to biological taxa whose affinity is known.
simple: A form taxon is a group of organisms based on based on what they look like (their morphology). <s> Such a taxon may not reflect their biological relationships.

title: Närpes
complex: Närpes is a town and municipality of Finland.
simple: Närpes is a town in western Finland.

title: Latvian Wikipedia
complex: The Latvian Wikipedia ( ] ) is the Latvian-language edition of the free online encyclopedia Wikipedia. <s> It was created on 6 June 2003. <s> With about articles, it is currently the -largest Wikipedia as measured by the number of articles and the second-largest Wikipedia in a Baltic language.
simple: Latvian Wikipedia is the Latvian edition of Wikipedia. <s> It was started on 6 June 2003.

title: Markaryd Municipality
complex: Markaryd Municipality ("Markaryds kommun") is a municipality in south-west Kronoberg County in southern Sweden, where the town Markaryd is seat.
simple: Markaryd Municipality is a municipality in Kronoberg County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Markaryd.

title: Champs, Aisne
complex: Champs is a commune in the Aisne department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Champs is a commune.

title: List of England Test cricketers
complex: This is a list of England Test cricketers. <s> A Test match is an international two-innings per side cricket match between two of the leading cricketing nations.
simple: This is a list of cricketers that play Test cricket for England. <s> A number of cricketers have played Test match cricket for England and another Test match team.

title: Erriapus
complex: Erriapus ( ; Latin: "Erriapus, Erriappus"), also Saturn XXVIII (28), is a prograde irregular satellite of Saturn. <s> It was discovered by Brett Gladman, John J. Kavelaars and colleagues in 2000, and given the temporary designation S/2000 S 10. <s> It was named Erriapo in August 2003 after Erriapus, a giant in Gaulish mythology; the name was changed from dative "Erriapo" to nominative "Erriapus" per IAU conventions in late 2007. <s> Erriapus is about 10 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 17,3 Gm in 871 days. <s> As a member of the Gallic group of irregular satellites, which share similar orbital characteristics and a light-red colour, Erriapus is hypothesized to have its origin in the break-up of a common progenitor of the group, or to be a fragment of its largest member, Albiorix.
simple: Erriapus or Saturn XXVIII, is non-spherical moon of Saturn. <s> It was found by Brett Gladman, John J. Kavelaars, et al. in 2000, and given the designation S/2000 S 10. <s> It was named in August 2003 after Erriapo, a giant in Gaulish mythology. <s> Erriapus is about 10 kilometres in diameter, and orbits Saturn at an average distance of 17,300,000 km in 871 days. <s> Erriapus is a member of the Gallic group of non-spherical, sharing a similar orbit and displaying a similar "light-red" colour, Erriapus is thought to have been formed in a break-up of a bigger body.

title: Falkirk
complex: Falkirk ( ; ; ) is a large town in the Central Lowlands of Scotland, historically within the county of Stirlingshire. <s> It lies in the Forth Valley, 23.3 mi north-west of Edinburgh and 20.5 mi north-east of Glasgow.
simple: Falkirk is a town in Scotland.

title: Congolese rainforests
complex: The Congolese forests cover southeastern Cameroon, eastern Gabon, the northern and central Republic of the Congo, the northern and central Democratic Republic of the Congo and portions of southern and southwestern Central African Republic. <s> To the north and south, the forests transition to drier forest-savanna mosaic, a mosaic of drier forests, savannas, and grasslands. <s> To the west, the Congolese forests transition to the coastal Lower Guinean forests, which extend from western Gabon and Cameroon into southern Nigeria and Benin; these forests zones share many similarities, and are sometimes known as the Lower Guinean-Congolese forests. <s> To the east, the lowland Congolese forests transition to the highland Albertine Rift montane forests, which cover the Mountains lining the Albertine Rift, a branch of the East African Rift system. <s> The Congolese Forests are a global 200 ecoregion. <s> The Congo Rainforest is the world’s second largest tropical forest, spans six countries, and contains a quarter of the world’s remaining tropical forest. <s> With annual forest loss of 0.3% during the 2000s, the region has the lowest deforestation rate of any major tropical forest zone.
simple: The Congolese forests cover southeastern Cameroon, eastern Gabon, the northern and central Republic of the Congo, the northern and central Democratic Republic of the Congo and portions of southern and southwestern Central African Republic. <s> To the north and south, the forests transition to drier forest-savanna mosaic, a mosaic of drier forests, savannas, and grasslands. <s> To the west, the Congolese forests transition to the coastal Lower Guinean forests, which extend from western Gabon and Cameroon into southern Nigeria and Benin; these forests zones share many similarities, and are sometimes known as the Lower Guinean-Congolese forests. <s> To the east, the lowland Congolese forests transition to the highland Albertine Rift montane forests, which cover the Mountains lining the Albertine Rift, a branch of the East African Rift system. <s> The Congolese Forests are a global 200 ecoregion. <s> The tropical rainforest covers most of the eastern part of the Congo. <s> The Congo Rainforest is the world’s second largest tropical forest, spans six countries, and contains a quarter of the world’s remaining tropical forest. <s> With annual forest loss of 0.3% during the 2000s, the region has the lowest deforestation rate of any major tropical forest zone.

title: Jizz in My Pants
complex: "Jizz in My Pants" is a SNL Digital Short which aired on "Saturday Night Live" on December 6, 2008 and YouTube on the same day. <s> It serves as the music video for the first single from the Lonely Island's debut album, "Incredibad". <s> The video stars the Lonely Island members Andy Samberg, Jorma Taccone and, briefly, Akiva Schaffer, and also features guest appearances by Justin Timberlake (who had also appeared in "Dick in a Box"), Molly Sims and Jamie-Lynn Sigler. <s> The video was published first on YouTube along with most of Lonely Island's works. <s> s of February 2019 , "Jizz in My Pants" has been watched over 171 million times, making it Lonely Island's third most popular video ever, coming after "I Just Had Sex" and "Jack Sparrow".
simple: "Jizz in My Pants" (also known as "J*** in My Pants") is a comedy sketch that was performed on YouTube and the television show "Saturday Night Live" on 6 December 2008. <s> The sketch was made into the music video for a song by The Lonely Island. <s> The video stars band members Andy Samberg, Jorma Taccone and Akiva Schaffer. <s> It also features Justin Timberlake, Molly Sims and Jamie-Lynn Sigler. <s> "Jizz in My Pants" has been viewed over 117 million times on YouTube, as of 2012.

title: Luxembourg (canton)
complex: Luxembourg is a canton in the south of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg. <s> Its name, like the name of the Grand Duchy itself, derives from the name of its principal city, Luxembourg (more commonly known as Luxembourg City). <s> It is not to be confused with the former district of Luxembourg, one of three administrative units in Luxembourg abolished in October 2015. <s> It is the only canton, other than Mersch, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons and therefore to have no international boundary. <s> The capital is Luxembourg City.
simple: Luxembourg is a canton in Luxembourg. <s> It is the only canton, other than Mersch, to be entirely surrounded by other cantons, and therefore not to have an international boundary. <s> Its capital is Luxembourg.

title: Josefina Villalobos
complex: Josefina Villalobos (born August 5, 1924) is an American-born Colombian-Ecuadorian public servant. <s> She was the First Lady of Ecuador serving from August 10, 1992 through August 10, 1996 when her husband, Sixto Durán Ballén, served as President of Ecuador. <s> Ballén and Villalobos had eight children. <s> After Ballén left office, the two retired and lived in Quito, Ecuador. <s> On November 15, 2016, Ballén died at the age of 95.
simple: Josefina Villalobos (born August 5, 1924) is an American-born Colombian-Ecuadorian public servant. <s> She was the First Lady of Ecuador serving from August 10, 1992 through August 10, 1996 when her husband, Sixto Durán Ballén, served as President of Ecuador. <s> Ballén and Villalobos had eight children. <s> After Ballén left office, the two retired and lived in Quito, Ecuador. <s> On November 15, 2016, Ballén died at the age of 95.

title: Yvré-le-Pôlin
complex: Yvré-le-Pôlin is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Yvré-le-Pôlin is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Porophyllum ruderale
complex: Porophyllum ruderale is an herbaceous annual plant whose leaves can be used for seasoning food. <s> The taste has been described as "somewhere between arugula, cilantro and rue." <s> The plant is commonly grown in Mexico and South America for use in salsas. <s> When fully grown, this plant grows to about 5 feet in height and 3 feet in diameter. <s> Having been used by many cultures, Porophyllum ruderale is known by many names, including Bolivian coriander, "quillquiña" (also spelled "quirquiña" or "quilquiña"), "yerba porosa", "killi", "pápalo", "tepegua", "mampuritu" and "pápaloquelite". <s> Despite the name "Bolivian coriander", this plant is not botanically related to Coriandrum sativum.
simple: Its leaves can be used for seasoning food. <s> The taste has been described as "somewhere between arugula, cilantro and rue." <s> The plant is commonly grown in Mexico and South America. <s> There it is used in salsas. <s> When fully grown, this plant grows to about 5 feet in height and 3 feet in diameter. <s> This herb is known by many names, including "quillquiña" (also spelled "quirquiña" or "quilquiña"), "killi", "papalo", "tepegua" and "pápaloquelite". <s> Also, even though the name is "Bolivian coriander", this plant is not botanically related to the coriander.

title: Yoichiro Kakitani
complex: Yoichiro Kakitani (柿谷 曜一朗 , Kakitani Yōichirō ) (born 3 January 1990 in Osaka) is a Japanese footballer who plays as an attacking midfielder for Cerezo Osaka.
simple: Yoichiro Kakitani (born 3 January 1990) is a Japanese football player.

title: Natalia Oreiro
complex: Natalia Marisa Oreiro Iglesias (] ; born 19 May 1977) is a Uruguayan singer, actress, and fashion designer. <s> Oreiro began her career in telenovelas. <s> Since 2008 she has switched to work primarily in films. <s> Oreiro has worked on social awareness shows and events for organizations like Greenpeace and UNICEF, the latter of which designated her as ambassador for Argentina and Uruguay in September 2011. <s> She has been included in "Esquire" magazine's "The Sexiest Woman Alive Atlas" list. <s> Natalia Oreiro, daughter of Carlos Florencio Oreiro Poggio and Mabel Cristina Iglesias Bourié, was born on 19 May 1977. <s> Natalia studied drama at the age of eight and at twelve started auditioning for advertisements. <s> During her teens she appeared in more than 30 television commercials for such trade marks as Coca-Cola, Pepsi and Johnson & Johnson. <s> At the age of 16 she moved to Argentina to work there and unleash her ambition to be a star. <s> She worked as an MTV VJ and in 1995, she landed a role in the soap opera "Dulce Ana". <s> She was then cast in the TV series "90-60-90 modelos" (1996) and next in "Ricos y famosos" (1997, playing Valeria). <s> Next, she starred in the Argentinian film "Un Argentino en New York" (1998). <s> After the movie, Natalia launched her first album, "Natalia Oreiro" and the single "Cambio Dolor" became the opening theme for her next acting project, the prime time show "Muñeca Brava" (1998–1999). <s> For her performance in "Muñeca Brava", Natalia was nominated twice (1998 and 1999) for a Martín Fierro Award as best actress in a leading role. <s> In 1998, Natalia Oreiro recorded the theme "Paths of the Soul" next to Kennedy Choir2 and with more than 120 Argentine artists under the direction of Instrumental pianist and conductor Nazareno Andorno. <s> She pursued her musical career with the next album "Tu Veneno" and presentations in Gala de la Hispanidad, Gala de Murcia (both in Spain) and Festival de la Calle 8 in Miami. <s> Her most important appearance was in the prestigious Latin television show "Sábado Gigante Internacional", hosted by Don Francisco. <s> Natalia's major achievement at this time was her music performance in Chile at Viña del Mar Festival 2000 for which she was crowned Queen of that event. <s> The album scored a Latin Grammy nomination for Best Pop Female Vocal Album, but lost to Christina Aguilera's "Mi Reflejo". <s> On 1 June 2002, her third studio album "Turmalina" was released by BMG Ariola Argentina. <s> "Turmalina" was produced by Latin record producer Kike Santander and is a combination of rhythms such as rock, pop and some sort of reminiscent of the 60's and 50's sounds. <s> On this album, Oreiro write and composed the songs: "Alas De Libertad" which is inspired by kids she met some time ago in the city of Jujuy, Argentina; "Mar" tells the love story between a sailor and his girlfriend. <s> Natalia also contributed to the lyrics of "Cayendo". <s> "Que Digan Lo Que Quieran" is "Turmalina" ' s first single. <s> Official Uruguayan 2002 World Cup song "Pasión Celeste" is recorded with Fredy Bessio. <s> "Cuesta arriba, cuesta abajo" was opening song of soap opera "Kachorra" ("Runaway Lady"). <s> "Kachorra" ended with a rating lower than 20 points in Argentina.
simple: Natalia Oreiro (born May 18, 1977 in Montevideo,Uruguay) is a Latin Grammy-nominated Uruguayan singer and actress. <s> Natalia Oreiro was born in Montevideo, Uruguay on May 19, 1977. <s> She is daughter of Carlos Oreiro Poggio and the painter Mabel Iglesias Bourié. <s> She studied drama when she was eight years old than she appeared in advertisements at twelve years old such as Coca-Cola, Pepsi and Johnson & Johnson. <s> At the age of 16 she moved to Argentina to work there. <s> She worked as an MTV VJ and in 1995, she landed a role in the soap opera "Dulce Ana". <s> After that she st in the TV series "90-60-90 modelos" (1996) and "Ricos y famosos" (1997). <s> In 1998, Natalia Oreiro starred in her first movie "Un Argentino en New York" with Guillermo Francella. <s> After the movie, she released three studio albums ("Natalia Oreiro, Tu Veneno, Turmalina") and she starred many TV series and movies. <s> Than she launched her first studio album "Natalia Oreiro" (1998). <s> "Cambio Dolor" was first single from her debut album and became the opening theme for the prime time show "Muñeca Brava" (1998-1999). <s> In 2000, her second studio album, "Tu Veneno" (Your Poison) was released and was presentation in "Gala de la Hispanidad", "Gala de Murcia" (both in Spain) and "Festival de la Calle 8" in Miami. <s> She was crowned Queen of that event at Viña del Mar Festival 2000 in Chile. <s> She was nominated for Latin Grammy Awards, but lost to Christina Aguilera's "Mi Reflejo". <s> "Turmalina" was produced by Latin maker Kike Santander. <s> "Que Digan Lo Que Quieran" (Should they say whatever they want) was first single from "Turmalina". <s> Natalia made contributions with singer/songwriter Jaime Roos and Falta y Resto for the official Uruguayan 2002 FIFA World Cup song "Pasión Celeste". <s> "Cuesta Arriba, Cuesta Abajo" became the opening theme for soap opera "Kahorra".

title: Knowledge
complex: Knowledge can refer to a theoretical or practical understanding of a subject. <s> It can be implicit (as with practical skill or expertise) or explicit (as with the theoretical understanding of a subject); it can be more or less formal or systematic. <s> In philosophy, the study of knowledge is called epistemology; the philosopher Plato famously defined knowledge as "justified true belief", though this definition is now thought by some analytic philosophers to be problematic because of the Gettier problems, while others defend the platonic definition. <s> However, several definitions of knowledge and theories to explain it exist. <s> The definition of knowledge is a matter of ongoing debate among philosophers in the field of epistemology. <s> The classical definition, described but not ultimately endorsed by Plato, specifies that a statement must meet three criteria in order to be considered knowledge: it must be justified, true, and believed. <s> Some claim that these conditions are not sufficient, as Gettier case examples allegedly demonstrate. <s> There are a number of alternatives proposed, including Robert Nozick's arguments for a requirement that knowledge 'tracks the truth' and Simon Blackburn's additional requirement that we do not want to say that those who meet any of these conditions 'through a defect, flaw, or failure' have knowledge. <s> Richard Kirkham suggests that our definition of knowledge requires that the evidence for the belief necessitates its truth. <s> In many expressions of Christianity, such as Catholicism and Anglicanism, knowledge is one of the seven gifts of the Holy Spirit. <s> In Islam, knowledge (Arabic: علم, "ʿilm") is given great significance. <s> "The Knowing" ("al-ʿAlīm") is one of the 99 names reflecting distinct attributes of God. <s> The Qur'an asserts that knowledge comes from God and various "hadith" encourage the acquisition of knowledge. <s> Muhammad is reported to have said "Seek knowledge from the cradle to the grave" and "Verily the men of knowledge are the inheritors of the prophets". <s> Islamic scholars, theologians and jurists are often given the title "alim", meaning "knowledgeble".
simple: Knowledge can refer to a theoretical or practical understanding of a subject. <s> It can be implicit (as with practical skill or expertise) or explicit (as with the theoretical understanding of a subject); it can be more or less formal or systematic. <s> In philosophy, the study of knowledge is called epistemology. <s> The philosopher Plato defined knowledge as "justified true belief". <s> In many expressions of Christianity, such as Catholicism and Anglicanism, knowledge is one of the seven gifts of the Holy Spirit. <s> In Islam, knowledge has great significance. <s> "The All-Knowing" ("al-ʿAlīm") is one of the Names of God, reflecting distinct properties of God in Islam. <s> The Qur'an asserts that knowledge comes from God (2:239) and various "hadith" encourage getting knowledge. <s> Muhammad is reported to have said "Seek knowledge from the cradle to the grave" and "Verily the men of knowledge are the inheritors of the prophets". <s> Islamic scholars, theologians and jurists are often given the title "alim", meaning 'knowledgeable'.

title: Gesso
complex: Gesso (] ; "chalk", from the , from ) is a white paint mixture consisting of a binder mixed with chalk, gypsum, pigment, or any combination of these. <s> It is used in artwork as a preparation for any number of substrates such as wood panels, canvas and sculpture as a base for paint and other materials that are applied over it. <s> Gesso is used by sculptors to prepare the shape of the final sculpture (fused bronze) or directly as a material for sculpting. <s> Gesso can also be used as a layer between sculpted wood and gold leaf. <s> In this case, a layer of refined and coloured clay, called ‘bole’ is used to cover the gesso before applying the gold. <s> This is usually red in colour. <s> Modern "acrylic gesso" is a widely used ground that is a combination of calcium carbonate with an acrylic polymer, medium latex, a pigment and other chemicals that ensure flexibility, and increase archival life. <s> It is technically not "gesso" at all. <s> "The Painter's Handbook" notes a problem with using oil paints over an acrylic gesso ground instead of a traditional oil ground, citing a mismatch in flexibility over time that could cause the oil paint to delaminate.
simple: It is a white paint mixture. <s> It has a binder mixed with a pigment. <s> Gesso is used in art to prepare a surfaces (wood panels, canvas and sculpture) for painting. <s> Acrylic gesso, a widely used "ground", is a modern version which is cheaper and easier to use than the traditional type of gesso. <s> It is a combination of calcium carbonate with an acrylic polymer medium latex, a pigment and other chemicals to ensure flexibility and increase life. <s> It is technically not "gesso" at all. <s> "The Painter's Handbook" notes a problem with using oil paints over an acrylic gesso ground instead of a traditional oil ground, citing a mismatch in flexibility over time that could cause the oil paint to delaminate (flake off).

title: Katharine, Duchess of Kent
complex: Katharine, Duchess of Kent, (born Katharine Lucy Mary Worsley; 22 February 1933) is a member of the British royal family. <s> Her husband, Prince Edward, Duke of Kent, is a first cousin of Queen Elizabeth II. <s> The Duchess of Kent gained attention for her conversion to Catholicism in 1994; she was the first member of the royal family to convert publicly since the passing of the Act of Settlement 1701. <s> The Duchess of Kent is strongly associated with the world of music and has performed as a member of several choirs.
simple: Katharine, Duchess of Kent, (born Katharine Lucy Mary Worsley; 22 February 1933), is a member of the British Royal Family. <s> Her husband, Prince Edward, Duke of Kent, is a first cousin of Queen Elizabeth II. <s> The Duchess of Kent became famous her conversion to Catholicism in 1994, the first member of the Royal Family to convert publicly since 1701. <s> The Duchess of Kent is strongly associated with the world of music, and has performed as a member of several choirs.

title: Ahmed Chalabi
complex: Ahmed Abdel Hadi Chalabi ( ; 30 October 1944 – 3 November 2015) was an Iraqi politician, a founder of the Iraqi National Congress (INC) and the President of the Governing Council of Iraq (37th Prime Minister of Iraq) <s> He was interim Minister of Oil in Iraq in April–May 2005 and December 2005 – January 2006 and Deputy Prime Minister from May 2005 to May 2006. <s> Chalabi failed to win a seat in parliament in the December 2005 elections, and when the new Iraqi cabinet was announced in May 2006, he was not given a post. <s> Once dubbed the "George Washington of Iraq" by American supporters, he later fell out of favor and came under investigation by several U.S. government sources. <s> Chalabi died on 3 November 2015, four days after his 71st birthday, having apparently suffered a heart attack at his home in Kadhimiya, Baghdad. <s> When he died, he was a current Member of the Iraqi Parliament, serving as the chairman of the Finance Committee.
simple: Ahmed Abdel Hadi Chalabi (‎; 30 October 1944 – 3 November 2015) was an Iraqi politician. <s> He was interim Minister of Oil in Iraq serving from 16 April 2005 to 1 January 2006. <s> He served as Deputy Prime Minister from 1 May 2005 to 20 May 2006. <s> Chalabi failed to win a seat in parliament in the December 2005 elections. <s> Chalabi died on 3 November 2015 from a heart attack at his home in Kadhimiya, Baghdad, aged 71.

title: The Mississippi Bar
complex: The Mississippi Bar is the integrated (mandatory) bar association of the U.S. state of Mississippi. <s> The Mississippi Bar traces its lineage to a voluntary membership organization formed in 1821; however, this association lapsed after four years. <s> It was revived in 1886, but lapsed six years later. <s> In 1905 it was revived again; its first President was G.D. Shands. <s> During the Great Depression, membership dwindled amid public skepticism about lawyer ethics. <s> In response, the leading Mississippi lawyers successfully urged the passage of the state's Unified Bar Act in 1932, leading to the present-day mandatory Bar.
simple: The Mississippi Bar is the required group that attorneys in the U.S. state of Mississippi must join. <s> The Mississippi Bar was first a voluntary membership organization formed in 1821. <s> However, this association ended four years later. <s> It was restarted in 1886 but ended six years after that. <s> In 1905 it was started again. <s> During the Great Depression, membership declined because the public did not thing that the lawyers were ethical. <s> So, the main lawyers in Mississippi got the state to pass its Unified Bar Act in 1932, which led to the current required Bar assocation.

title: Probable prime
complex: In number theory, a probable prime (PRP) is an integer that satisfies a specific condition that is satisfied by all prime numbers, but which is not satisfied by most composite numbers. <s> Different types of probable primes have different specific conditions. <s> While there may be probable primes that are composite (called pseudoprimes), the condition is generally chosen in order to make such exceptions rare.
simple: In mathematics, particularly number theory, a probable prime is a whole number that is likely to be prime by having passed a probabilistic test such as Fermat's primality test. <s> Probable primes may be composite, but the tests are designed so they are really unlikely to be composite.

title: Péry
complex: Péry is part of the municipality of Péry-La Heutte in the Jura bernois administrative district in the canton of Bern in Switzerland. <s> It is located in the French-speaking Bernese Jura ("Jura Bernois"). <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Péry and La Heutte merged to form the new municipality of Péry-La Heutte.
