simple: Péry is a former municipality of the administrative district of Jura bernois in the canton of Berne in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2015 the former municipalities of Péry and La Heutte merged into the new municipality of Péry-La Heutte.

title: North Laurel, Maryland
complex: North Laurel is a census-designated place (CDP) in Howard County, Maryland, United States. <s> The published population was 4,474 at the 2010 census. <s> This population was substantially less than the CDP's population in 2000, and was the result of an error in defining the boundary prior to tabulation and publication of 2010 Census results. <s> The corrected 2010 Census population is 20,259. <s> North Laurel is adjacent to the City of Laurel, which is located across the Patuxent River in Prince George's County. <s> North Laurel is located in the southern corner of Howard County at (39.134343, −76.862690).
simple: North Laurel is a census-designated place (CDP) in Howard County, Maryland, United States. <s> The published population was 4,474 at the 2010 census. <s> North Laurel is near the City of Laurel.

title: Tim Finn
complex: Brian Timothy "Tim" Finn (born 25 June 1952) is a New Zealand singer and musician. <s> His musical career includes forming 1970s and 1980s New Zealand rock group Split Enz, a number of solo albums, temporary membership in his brother Neil's band Crowded House and joint efforts with Neil Finn as the Finn Brothers. <s> Brian Finn was born in Te Awamutu, New Zealand. <s> He went to Sacred Heart College, Auckland, a Catholic boarding school. <s> In 1971 he started a Bachelor of Arts degree at the University of Auckland. <s> There he jammed in music practice room 129 (later the name of a Split Enz song) with friends and future Split Enz bandmembers Mike Chunn, Robert Gillies, Philip Judd and Noel Crombie. <s> Music soon became more important to him than his studies. <s> In 1972 he quit university. <s> A few months later, Phil and Tim formed the group Split Ends, renamed Split Enz in 1975, shortly before they left New Zealand for Melbourne. <s> Their music moved towards a more mainstream sound in later years, with an eclecticism that incorporated influences from art rock, vaudeville, swing, punk, glam rock, rock and pop. <s> Between 1972 and 1977, Tim and Judd alternated as frontman for the band. <s> When Judd left the band, Tim Finn's younger brother Neil Finn took his place. <s> Finn had his first success away from Split Enz in 1981 when his discarded demo "They Won't Let My Girlfriend Talk to Me" became a top 10 hit for Australian band Jimmy and the Boys. <s> In 1983 Finn recorded his debut solo album, "Escapade", while still a member of Split Enz. <s> This met with major commercial success both in Australia and New Zealand, and yielded hit song "Fraction Too Much Friction", which revealed a more rhythm-based sound than Split Enz had been known for. <s> After contributing four songs to Split Enz album "Conflicting Emotions", Finn left the band permanently in June 1984, to focus on a solo career. <s> The following year he moved to London. <s> 1986 saw the release of his second solo album "Big Canoe". <s> The album utilised a wide variety of instrumentation, including guitars, orchestral backings and traditional Indian instruments - most notably on single "No Thunder, No Fire, No Rain", which was inspired by the Bhopal chemical disaster. <s> Though "Big Canoe" reached number three on the New Zealand charts, it failed to become the international breakthrough that Finn or record company Virgin had hoped. <s> During this time, Finn's focus also turned to soundtrack music, and he landed a few acting roles on-screen. <s> Finn has composed for a number of Australian films and TV productions, including 1981 teen tale "Puberty Blues" and comedy "Les Patterson Saves the World", which yielded Australian hit "You Saved the World". <s> Finn had a small part in Australian film "The Coca-Cola Kid" alongside then-girlfriend Greta Scacchi, and a larger one in her Italian-shot romance "La Donna della Luna" (The Moon Woman). <s> In late 1989, Finn was back living in Melbourne, recording his eponymous third album, "Tim Finn", for Capitol Records. <s> The album would yield strong reviews and New Zealand hit "Parihaka", based on a Maori village known for its campaign of passive resistance to European occupiers. <s> In early 1990, he began playing music with younger brother Neil, for an intended Finn brothers record. <s> After working together on some songs, Neil later proposed incorporating the tracks onto the latest album of Crowded House, the group he had formed after Split Enz dissolved. <s> Tim performed with the band to promote the band's album "Woodface", and co-wrote eight songs, including the hits "Weather with You" and "Four Seasons in One Day". <s> But some time during the tour which followed the album's American release, all concerned realised that the combination was not a good fit. <s> Finn returned to pursue his solo career. <s> Both Tim and Neil were made OBE for services to New Zealand music in the 1993 Queen's Birthday Honours List. <s> The brothers Finn collaborated on another album in 1995, playing most of the instruments themselves. <s> "Finn" was released as the first Finn Brothers release. <s> In support of this album, the brothers toured Europe, Australia and the USA. <s> Also in 1995, Finn formed the band ALT, with Irish musicians Andy White and Liam Ó Maonlaí (from band Hothouse Flowers). <s> ALT's name was formed from the initial letters of their names. <s> They released the album "Altitude" and toured Europe and Australasia. <s> 2000 also saw the release of album "", featuring Finn, and fellow New Zealand singer/songwriters Bic Runga, and Dave Dobbyn. <s> Recorded in August and September 2000 in venues around New Zealand, the album saw the three performers each equitably showcased. <s> Both the concerts and album feature all three performers providing vocal and instrumental backing on each other's songs. <s> The album spent 16 weeks in the New Zealand charts, and was finally released in the UK in May 2007. <s> In 2004, the Finn brothers released their second album, "Everyone Is Here". <s> The album was originally intended to be produced by Tony Visconti but the release has most production credits going to long-time Finn producer Mitchell Froom. <s> A "Mojo" magazine review stated that it contained "some of the most haunting music to bear the Finn imprint". <s> Finn was in a relationship with actress Greta Scacchi from 1983 to 1989. <s> He is currently married to television presenter Marie Azcona, formerly of MTV and TVNZ One's "Music Week". <s> Finn and Azcona have two children; a son, Harper, and a daughter, Elliot. <s> The pair have collaborated on several songs, some of which are featured on "Steel City", the dance show that Finn wrote. <s> Aside from co-writing two tracks with Azcona, Finn collaborated on another with former Split Enz member Mike Chunn. <s> "This discography relates to releases by Tim Finn only. <s> See Finn Brothers' discography, Crowded House discography and Split Enz discography for other related works."
simple: Brian Timothy "Tim" Finn, OBE (born 25 June 1952) is a singer-songwriter born in New Zealand. <s> Finn is most known for his music with his band Split Enz. <s> He has released solo albums, and was member of his brother Neil's band Crowded House. <s> He also released albums with Neil as the Finn Brothers. <s> Tim Finn was born in Te Awamutu, New Zealand. <s> He went to Sacred Heart College, Auckland, a Catholic boarding school. <s> In 1971 he completed a Bachelor of Arts degree at the University of Auckland. <s> It is there that he met Mike Chunn, Robert Gillies, Philip Judd and Noel Crombie. <s> Phil and Tim formed a band called Split Ends, which became Split Enz before they started to tour Australia. <s> Finn recorded his first solo album, "Escapade", in 1983. <s> This album was very successful in Australia and New Zealand. <s> Because of this, he decided to leave Split Enz in 1984. <s> In early 1985, Tim moved to London. <s> His second album "Big Canoe" was not as successful as the first album. <s> He had a bigger role in the movie "La Donna della Luna" (The Moon Woman). <s> In late 1989, he went to live in Melbourne. <s> He recorded his third album, "Tim Finn". <s> In early 1990 he joined Crowded House, the group Neil had formed after Split Enz split up. <s> Because of their success, Tim Finn and Neil Finn were made OBE for services to New Zealand music in the 1993 Queen's Birthday Honours List. <s> The album "Finn" was released in 1995. <s> Also in 1995, Finn worked with singers Andy White and Liam Ó Maonlaí. <s> They formed the band ALT. <s> They released the album "Altitude". <s> In 2000, the album "" was recorded featuring Finn, and New Zealand artists Bic Runga, and Dave Dobbyn. <s> The concerts and album have all three musicians singing and playing on each other's songs. <s> In 2004, the Finn brothers released their second album together, titled, "Everyone Is Here". <s> Finn married the television presenter Marie Azcona, formerly of MTV and TVNZ One's Music Week. <s> Finn and Azcona have two children; a son, Harper, and a daughter, Elliott. <s> They have worked together on several songs, some of which are featured on "Steel City" soundtrack. <s> "This discography relates to releases by Tim Finn only. <s> See Finn Brothers' discography, Crowded House discography and Split Enz discography for other related works."

title: Cheri Bustos
complex: Cheryl Lea Bustos (née Callahan; born October 17, 1961) is an American journalist, healthcare executive, and politician who has served as the U.S. Representative for Illinois's 17th congressional district since 2013. <s> A member of the Democratic Party, Bustos is the first woman elected to Congress from her district. <s> In 2019, Bustos assumed a leadership position among House Democrats as chair of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
simple: Cheryl Lea Bustos (née Callahan; born October 17, 1961) is an American journalist, healthcare executive, and politician. <s> Bustos has served as the U.S. Representative for Illinois's 17th congressional district since 2013. <s> She is a member of the Democratic Party. <s> Bustos is the first woman elected to Congress from her district.

title: Rusty Anderson
complex: Rusty Anderson is an American guitarist and singer-songwriter. <s> He is known as the lead guitarist for Sir Paul McCartney, though he has worked with an extensive list of artists in addition to his own solo career. <s> Now officially a band, Rusty Anderson Afternoon released their first single, “Effortless”, on April 30, 2013. <s> "Effortless" made it to #1 at Sirius Radio's “20 on 20".
simple: Rusty Anderson (born January 20, 1959) is an American guitarist, singer and songwriter from La Habra, California. <s> He has played lead guitar for Paul McCartney since 2001. <s> He also has a band called Rusty Anderson Afternoon whose first single "Effortless" hit Number One on American radio and whose first full-length record "RAA" debuted in the Top Ten Alt Chart on iTunes.

title: Joseph Engelberger
complex: Engelberger died on December 1, 2015, in Newtown, Connecticut, a little more than four months after celebrating his 90th birthday.
simple: Engelberger died in Newtown, Connecticut from complications following a stroke at the age of 90.

title: Autoimmune disease
complex: In both autoimmune and inflammatory diseases, the condition arises through aberrant reactions of the human adaptive or innate immune systems. <s> In autoimmunity, the patient's immune system is activated against the body's own proteins.
simple: Autoimmune disease: when the body's immune system attacks its own body.

title: Protective gear in sports
complex: Personal protective equipment serves an integral role in maintaining the safety of an athlete participating in a sport. <s> The usage and development of protective gear in sports has evolved through time, and continues to advance over time.
simple: Protective equipment helps sport people not get hurt.

title: Zail Singh
complex: Zail Singh ( ; born Jarnail Singh, 5 May 1916 – 25 December 1994) was the seventh President of India serving from 1982 to 1987. <s> Prior to his presidency, he was a politician with the Indian National Congress party, and had held several ministerial posts in the Union Cabinet, including that of Home Minister. <s> He also served as the Secretary-General of the Non-Aligned Movement from 1983 to 1986. <s> On 29 November 1994, Zail Singh suffered multiple injuries following a motor accident near Kiratpur Sahib in Ropar district when a truck driving down the wrong side of the road hit the car he was travelling in. <s> Singh died in Chandigarh where he had been undergoing treatment on Christmas Day in 1994, aged 78. <s> The Government of India announced seven days of official mourning following his death.
simple: Gyani Zail Singh (; born Jarnail Singh, 5 May 1916 – 25 December 1994) was an Indian politician. <s> He was the seventh President of India from 1982 to 1987. <s> He was a politician with the Indian National Congress party. <s> Singh was killed in a car crash in Chandigarh, India on 25 December 1994 at the age of 78.

title: Iwashiro Province
complex: Iwashiro Province (岩代国 , Iwashiro-no kuni ) is an old province in the area of Fukushima Prefecture. <s> It was sometimes called Ganshū (岩州 ) .
simple: Iwashiro Province (岩代国, Iwashiro-no kuni) is an old province in the area of Fukushima Prefecture on the island of Honshū. <s> It was sometimes called Ōshū (奥州).

title: Nâzım Hikmet
complex: Nâzım Hikmet Ran (15 January 1902 – 3 June 1963), commonly known as Nâzım Hikmet (] ) was a Turkish poet, playwright, novelist, screenwriter, director and memoirist. <s> He was acclaimed for the "lyrical flow of his statements". <s> Described as a "romantic communist" and "romantic revolutionary", he was repeatedly arrested for his political beliefs and spent much of his adult life in prison or in exile. <s> His poetry has been translated into more than fifty languages.
simple: Nâzım Hikmet Ran (15 January 1902 – 3 June 1963), commonly known as Nâzım Hikmet, was a Turkish poet, playwright and novelist. <s> He was well liked for the "lyrical flow of his statements". <s> Hikmet was often arrested for his political beliefs. <s> He spent much of his adult life in prison or in exile. <s> His poetry has been translated into more than fifty languages.

title: MacBook (2015–2019)
complex: The MacBook (known colloquially as the Retina MacBook or 12-inch MacBook) is a discontinued line of Macintosh portable computers introduced in March 2015 by Apple Inc. <s> The MacBook had a similar appearance to the MacBook Air, but was thinner and lighter, and was available in colors called space gray, silver, gold, and rose gold. <s> It offered a high-resolution Retina Display, a Force Touch trackpad, a redesigned keyboard, and only two ports: a headphone jack and a USB 3.1 Type-C port for charging, data transfer and video output. <s> The MacBook was designed with thinness in mind; the aluminum enclosure was 13.1 mm at its thickest point at the hinge end of the computer. <s> The MacBook includes Intel Core M processors (Kaby Lake architecture) which requires no fans or heat pipe, allowing the logic board to be much smaller than the one in the MacBook Air. <s> The storage cannot be upgraded.
simple: The MacBook Retina is a laptop computer made by Apple Inc.. <s> It was introduced in March 2015. <s> It has one USB "Type C" port, and a headphone jack. <s> The MacBook Retina is designed to be thin. <s> It is 13.1 mm at its thickest point. <s> It has an Intel Core M processor, which is designed for computers like this and does not need a fan or something else to cool it.

title: Mińsk Mazowiecki
complex: Mińsk Mazowiecki ""Masovian Minsk"" is a town in central Poland with 40,211 inhabitants (2015). <s> It is situated in the Masovian Voivodeship (since 1999), previously in Siedlce Voivodeship (1975–1998). <s> It is the capital of Mińsk County.
simple: Mińsk Mazowiecki (Minsk, miɲsk mazɔ'vi̯eʦki) is a town in Poland. <s> It is the capital of Mińsk County.

title: Corban, Switzerland
complex: Corban is a former municipality in the district of Delémont in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipality of Corban merged into the municipality of Val Terbi.
simple: Corban is a former municipality of the district of Delémont in the canton of Jura in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2018 the former municipality of Corban merged into the municipality of Val Terbi.

title: Ostend
complex: Ostend ( , ] ; ] ; ] ; ) is a coastal city and municipality, located in the province of West Flanders, Belgium. <s> It comprises the boroughs of Mariakerke, Raversijde, Stene and Zandvoorde, and the city of Ostend proper – the largest on the Belgian coast.
simple: Oostende (German / French: Ostende, English Ostend) is a city in the Belgian province of West Flanders.

title: List of colleges and universities in Vermont
complex: There are 18 currently operating colleges and universities based in the U.S. state of Vermont. <s> This figure includes one research university, six master's universities, an art school, a culinary school, a law school, and a number of undergraduate associates and baccalaureate colleges. <s> Four institutions chartered in other states offer degree programs at locations in Vermont. <s> The state's largest school is its flagship public university, the University of Vermont. <s> The other four public institutions are organized as the Vermont State Colleges system.
simple: In the state of Vermont, United States, there are 23 colleges and universities. <s> This includes one research university, six master's universities, an art school, a culinary school, a law school. <s> The state's largest school is its public university, the University of Vermont.

title: Richard II (play)
complex: The Life and Death of King Richard the Second, commonly called Richard II, is a history play by William Shakespeare believed to have been written in approximately 1595. <s> It is based on the life of King Richard II of England (ruled 1377–1399) and is the first part of a tetralogy, referred to by some scholars as the Henriad, followed by three plays concerning Richard's successors: "Henry IV, Part 1"; "Henry IV, Part 2"; and "Henry V".
simple: Richard II is a play by William Shakespeare. <s> It is a history play. <s> "Richard II" was probably first printed in 1597.

title: List of political parties in Australia
complex: This article lists political parties in Australia. <s> These are Australian political parties which are no longer registered with any federal, state or territory political bodies, and can thus no longer contest elections. <s> However, they still remain active in electoral politics through running candidates under a local government party, as independents, or as members of an electoral alliance.
simple: This is a list of Australian political parties. <s> These groups are no longer registered and can no longer take part in elections.

title: Jhando Mari
complex: Jhando Mari is a town and union council of Tando Allahyar District in the Sindh Province of Pakistan. <s> It is part of Jhando Mari Taluka and is located in the north of the district at , the Union Council has a population of 30,384.
simple: Jhando Mari is a town and Union Council of Tando Allah Yaar District in the Sindh Province of Pakistan. <s> It is part of Jhando Mari Taluka and is in the north of the district at 25°38'60N 68°54'0E. <s> The Union Council has 30,384 people.

title: Concert of Europe
complex: The Concert of Europe represented the European balance of power from 1815 to 1848 and from 1871 to 1914. <s> With the Revolutions of 1848 the Vienna system collapsed and, although the republican rebellions were checked, an age of nationalism began and culminated in the unifications of Italy (by Sardinia) and Germany (by Prussia) in 1871. <s> The German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck re-created the Concert of Europe to avoid future conflicts escalating into new wars. <s> The revitalized concert included France, Britain, Austria, Russia, and Italy with Germany as the main continental power economically and militarily.
simple: The Concert of Europe was a group of countries in Europe who worked together and agreed on policies to maintain a steady balance of power which included alliances between the great powers in 1814 and 1914. <s> The member countries were the United Kingdom, Austria, Russia, France (from 1815), Prussia (Germany from 1871) and Italy (from 1871). <s> After Napoleon, ruler of France, was no longer in power, France joined the Concert of Europe. <s> Its importance diminished with the revolutions of 1848 and subsequent wars between the big powers. <s> Otto von Bismarck re-established the Concert of Europe after the unifications of Germany and Italy.

title: Thalassomedon
complex: Thalassomedon (from Greek, "thalassa", "sea" and Greek, "medon", "lord" or "ruler", meaning "sea lord") is a genus of plesiosaur, named by Welles in 1943. <s> "Thalassomedon" is among the largest elasmosaurids, with a total length of 10.86 m for the holotype. <s> There is a larger skull however suggesting a much larger animal, potentially up to 11.7 m . <s> The neck is also very long; it comprises 62 vertebrae and is about 5.9 m - over half of the total length. <s> The skull is 47 cm long, with 5 cm long teeth. <s> The flippers were about 1.5 – long.
simple: Thalassomedon (meaning "lord of the seas") was a plesiosaur (not a dinosaur, but an extinct marine reptile from the Mesozoic Era that lived in the open oceans and breathed air). <s> The type species, "Thalassomedon haningtoni" (named by Welles in 1943). <s> It had a long neck (with 63 vertebrae), a long snout, long, sharp teeth (up to 5 cm long), a short, pointed tail and four flippers. <s> This reptile was about 40 feet (12 m) long; its skull was about 18.7 inches (47 cm) long.

title: Picardy
complex: Picardy ( ; Picard and , ] ) is a historical territory and a former administrative region of France. <s> Since 1 January 2016, it has been part of the new region of Hauts-de-France. <s> It is located in the northern part of France.
simple: Picardy used to be an administrative region of France. <s> It is now part of the administrative region of Hauts-de-France.

title: Bill Foulkes
complex: William Anthony Foulkes ( or ; 5 January 1932 – 25 November 2013) was an English footballer who played for Manchester United in the Busby Babes teams of the 1950s, and also in the 1960s. <s> His favoured position was centre-half.
simple: Bill Foulkes (5 January 1932 – 25 November 2013) was an English footballer-turned-manager.

title: Broadheath, Worcestershire
complex: Broadheath with Lower Broadheath is a civil parish officially known as "Lower Broadheath", in the Malvern Hills district of Worcestershire, England. <s> According to the 2011 census it had a population of 1,728. <s> The parish also includes Upper Broadheath. <s> The village is about 3 miles north-west of Worcester. <s> There are many housing estates in the village, including the Jacomb estate (Jacomb Road, Jacomb Drive, Jacomb Close and Rectory Close). <s> The village has a village hall, church, post office and shop, a village green (containing a football pitch, running track and many children's play areas) and a large village common. <s> There is also a primary school (Broadheath C.E. Primary School). <s> The school contains around 150 children, from the age of four up to eleven. <s> There are also three pubs in the village. <s> Broadheath is the birthplace of the English composer Edward Elgar. <s> The cottage in which he was born is now a museum.
simple: Broadheath with Lower Broadheath is a civil parish officially known as "Lower Broadheath", in the Malvern Hills district of Worcestershire, England. <s> According to the 2001 census it had a population of 1,713. <s> The parish also includes Upper Broadheath, which is about 3 miles north-west of Worcester. <s> There are many housing estates in the village. <s> The village has a village hall, church, post office and shop, a village green with a football pitch, running track and many children's play areas. <s> There is a large village common. <s> There is also a primary school (Broadheath C.E. Primary School). <s> The school has about 150 children, from the age of four up to eleven. <s> There are also three pubs in the village. <s> Broadheath is the birthplace of the English composer Edward Elgar.

title: Phi
complex: Phi ( ; uppercase Φ, lowercase φ or φ; "pheî" ] ; Modern Greek "fi" ] ) is the 21st letter of the Greek alphabet. <s> It may be that phi originated as the letter qoppa and initially represented the sound /kwh/ before shifting to Classical Greek ] . <s> In traditional Greek numerals, phi has a value of 500 or 500,000 . <s> The Cyrillic letter Ef (Ф, ф) descends from phi.
simple: Phi (uppercase/lowercase Φ φ), is the 21st letter of the Greek alphabet, used to represent the "ph" sound in Ancient Greek. <s> In the system of Greek numerals, it has a value of 500. <s> The Cyrillic letter Ф came from Phi.

title: America's Next Top Model (season 4)
complex: The winner was 20-year-old Naima Mora from Detroit, Michigan.
simple: The winner was 20-year-old Naima Mora.

title: Common year
complex: A common year is a calendar year with 365 days, as distinguished from a leap year, which has 366. <s> More generally, a common year is one without intercalation. <s> The Gregorian calendar, (like the earlier Julian calendar), employs both common years and leap years to keep the calendar aligned with the tropical year, which does not contain an exact number of days. <s> The common year of 365 days has 52 weeks and one day, hence a common year always begins and ends on the same day of the week (for example, January 1 and December 31 fell on a Sunday in 2017) and the year following a common year will start on the subsequent day of the week. <s> In common years, February has four weeks, so March will begin on the same day of the week. <s> November will also begin on this day. <s> In the Gregorian calendar, 303 of every 400 years are common years. <s> By comparison, in the Julian calendar, 300 out of every 400 years are common years, and in the Revised Julian calendar (used by Greece) 682 out of every 900 years are common years.
simple: A common year is a year that is not a leap year. <s> In the Gregorian Calendar a common year has 365 days. <s> This means a common year has 52 weeks and one day. <s> Stated differently, a common year always begins and ends on the same day of the week. <s> In the Gregorian calendar, 303 out of every 400 years are common years. <s> In the Julian calendar, 300 out of every 400 years were common years.

title: Axel Lewenhaupt
complex: Count Axel Charles Emil Lewenhaupt (27 May 1917 – 20 November 2018) was a Swedish diplomat and Grand Master of Ceremonies at the Royal Court of Sweden. <s> Lewenhaupt was born in Helsingborg, Sweden and is the son of Colonel, Count Gustaf Lewenhaupt and Baroness Elisabeth Ramel. <s> He passed "studentexamen" in 1936 and his reserve officer exam in 1938 and received a Candidate of Law degree from Uppsala University in 1942 before becoming an attaché at the Ministry for Foreign Affairs in 1943. <s> Lewenhaupt served as an attaché in Rome in 1943. <s> The Swedish legation's duties during World War II in Rome included taking special measures to protect Swedish interests and Swedish nationals (including Elizabeth Hesselblad) who was still in Rome. <s> The focus was to protect the Swedish Institute and the convent church Santa Brigida. <s> After Rome, Lewenhaupt was attaché in Berlin in 1944 and in Helsinki from 1945 to 1947. <s> He was second secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1948 to 1952 and first legation secretary in Madrid from 1952 to 1956. <s> Lewenhaupt was first secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1956 to 1958 and director at the Foreign Ministry from 1958 to 1960. <s> He was embassy counsellor in Washington, D.C. from 1960 to 1962 and ambassador in Leopoldville from 1962 to 1963. <s> Lewenhaupt was acting head of the political department at the Foreign Ministry from 1964 to 1965 and its administrative department from 1965 to 1967. <s> He was ambassador in Bangkok, Rangoon, Kuala Lumpur and Singapore from 1967 to 1970 and ambassador in New Delhi, Colombo and Katmandu from 1970 to 1975. <s> Lewenhaupt was then ambassador in Belgrade and Tirana from 1975 to 1978 and served at the Foreign Ministry from 1978 to 1979.
simple: Count Axel Charles Emil Lewenhaupt (born 27 May 1917) is a former Swedish diplomat and Grand Master of Ceremonies at the Royal Court of Sweden. <s> He was born in Helsingborg, Sweden. <s> He was second secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1948 to 1952 and first legation secretary in Madrid from 1952 to 1956. <s> Lewenhaupt was first secretary at the Foreign Ministry from 1956 to 1958 and director at the Foreign Ministry from 1958 to 1960. <s> Lewenhaupt was embassy counsellor in Washington, D.C. from 1960 to 1962 and ambassador in Leopoldville from 1962 to 1963. <s> Lewenhaupt was acting head of the political department at the Foreign Ministry from 1964 to 1965 and its administrative department from 1965 to 1967. <s> He was ambassador in Bangkok, Rangoon, Kuala Lumpur and Singapore.

title: Iran–Iraq War
complex: The Iran–Iraq War began on 22 September 1980, when Iraq invaded Iran, and it ended on 20 August 1988, when Iran accepted the UN-brokered ceasefire. <s> Iraq wanted to replace Iran as the dominant Persian Gulf state, and was worried that the 1979 Iranian Revolution would lead Iraq's Shi'ite majority to rebel against the Ba'athist government. <s> The war also followed a long history of border disputes, and Iraq planned to annex the oil-rich Khuzestan Province and the east bank of the Arvand Rud (Shatt al-Arab). <s> An estimated 500,000 Iraqi and Iranian soldiers died, in addition to a smaller number of civilians. <s> The end of the war resulted in neither reparations nor border changes. <s> The Iran–Iraq War was originally referred to as the "Persian Gulf War" until the Persian Gulf War of 1990 and 1991, after which it was known as the "First Persian Gulf War". <s> The Iraq–Kuwait conflict, which was known as the "Second Persian Gulf War," eventually became known simply as the "Persian Gulf War". <s> The Iraq War from 2003 to 2011 has been called the "Second Persian Gulf War". <s> At the war's conclusion, it took several weeks for the Armed Forces of the Islamic Republic of Iran to evacuate Iraqi territory to honor pre-war international borders set by the 1975 Algiers Agreement. <s> The last prisoners of war were exchanged in 2003. <s> Besides the United States and the Soviet Union, Yugoslavia also sold weapons to both countries for the entire duration of the conflict. <s> Likewise, Portugal helped both countries; it was not unusual to see Iranian and Iraqi flagged ships anchored at Setúbal, waiting their turn to dock.
simple: The Iran–Iraq War was a war between the armed forces of Iraq and Iran lasting from September 1980 to August 1988. <s> The war began when Iraq invaded Iran on 22 September 1980, after a long history of border disputes and demands for the overthrow of Saddam Hussein's regime. <s> About a million soldiers died and a similar number of civilians. <s> It was commonly called the "Persian Gulf War" until Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990. <s> The Iraq-Kuwait war, which the United States entered, later was called the "Persian Gulf War" or the "Gulf War". <s> Despite several calls for an end to the fighting by the United Nations Security Council, the two countries fought until 20 August 1988; the last prisoners of war were exchanged in 2003. <s> The United States sold many weapons to the Shah's government. <s> The United States had sold many weapons to Iran before the war. <s> The Soviet Union sold weapons to Iran during the war.

title: The Conjuring 2
complex: The Conjuring 2 is a 2016 American supernatural horror film, directed by James Wan. <s> The screenplay is by Chad Hayes, Carey W. Hayes, Wan, and David Leslie Johnson. <s> It is the sequel to 2013's "The Conjuring", the second installment in "The Conjuring" series, and the third installment in the Conjuring Universe franchise. <s> Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga reprise their roles as paranormal investigators and authors Ed and Lorraine Warren from the first film. <s> The film follows the Warrens as they travel to Britain to assist the Hodgson family, who are experiencing poltergeist activity at their Enfield council house in 1977 which later became referred to as the Enfield poltergeist. <s> "The Conjuring 2" had its world premiere at TCL Chinese Theatre on June 7, 2016, and was theatrically released in the United States on June 10, 2016, by Warner Bros. <s> Pictures and New Line Cinema. <s> The film received generally positive reviews from critics—who praised the performances, Wan's direction, screenplay, atmosphere and Joseph Bishara's musical score—and grossed over $320million worldwide. <s> A spin-off prequel, "The Nun", was released on September 7, 2018. <s> A sequel, "The Conjuring 3", is currently in production.
simple: The Conjuring 2 is a 2016 American horror movie directed by James Wan. <s> It is the sequel to 2013's "The Conjuring" and the third movie in "The Conjuring" series. <s> Patrick Wilson and Vera Farmiga reprise their roles as paranormal investigators and authors Ed and Lorraine Warren from the first movie. <s> The movie is about the Warrens as they travel to England to help the Hodgson family, who are experiencing poltergeist activity in Enfield council house in 1977. <s> This event became referred to as the Enfield Poltergeist. <s> "The Conjuring 2" was released in North America on June 10, 2016. <s> The movie received positive reviews from critics and has made over $320 million worldwide. <s> A spin-off prequel movie, "The Nun", is scheduled to be released in 2018.

title: White Anglo-Saxon Protestant
complex: White Anglo-Saxon Protestants (WASPs) are a social group of white Protestants in the United States, often of British descent, and typically wealthy and well-connected. <s> The group has long dominated American society, culture, and the leadership of major political parties, and had a monopoly on elite society due to intermarriage and nepotism. <s> Although the WASP hegemony on the American establishment has lessened since the World War II era, WASPs continue to be well placed in major financial, business, legal, and academic institutions.
simple: WASP: an acronym for White Anglo-Saxon Protestant. <s> They are a social group of white protestants in the United States. <s> They are often of British descent, and typically wealthy and well-connected. <s> However, WASPs are still well placed in major financial, business and legal firms, and in universities.

title: Comrade
complex: The term comrade is used to mean "mate", "colleague", or "ally", and derives from the Iberian Romance language term "camarada", literally meaning "chamber mate", from Latin "camera" "chamber" or "room". <s> Political use of the term was inspired by the French Revolution, after which it grew into a form of address between socialists and workers.
simple: It literally means "friend", "colleague", but an also mean "ally".

title: Basil Yamey
complex: Basil S. Yamey, CBE (born 4 May 1919) is a South African economist. <s> He was born in Cape Town in South Africa, and educated at the University of Cape Town. <s> For many years he was a Professor at the London School of Economics. <s> He was a part-time member of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission from 1966 to 1978, and author of many books and articles, including one on the economics of underdeveloped countries co-authored with Peter Thomas Bauer.
simple: Basil S. Yamey, CBE (born 4 May 1919) is a South African economist. <s> He was born in Cape Town in South Africa. <s> For many years he was a Professor at the London School of Economics. <s> He was a part-time member of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission from 1966 to 1978.

title: Nhundiaquara River
complex: Nhundiaquara River is a river located in the Serra do Mar, on the coast of Paraná. <s> Nhundiaquara is notable for having been the first natural route linking the Coast to the state plateaus. <s> At the start of the settling, it was named Cubatão, being considered the richest gold river, thus contributing significantly to the development of the counties.
simple: Nhundiaquara River is in the Serra do Mar, on the coast of Paraná, Brazil. <s> The historic river was the first natural route linking the coast to the state plateaus. <s> At the start of the settling, it was named Cubatão, being considered the richest gold river, thus contributing significantly to the development of the counties.

title: 40 BC
complex: Year 40 BC was either a common year starting on Thursday, Friday or Saturday or a leap year starting on Thursday or Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar (the sources differ, see leap year error for further information) and a common year starting on Friday of the Proleptic Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Calvinus and Pollio (or, less frequently, year 714 "Ab urbe condita"). <s> The denomination 40 BC for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
simple: Year 40 BC was either a common year starting on Thursday, Friday or Saturday or a leap year starting on Thursday or Friday of the Julian calendar. <s> At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Calvinus and Pollio.

title: Lou Marcon
complex: Louis Angelo Marcon (born May 28, 1935) is a Canadian retired professional ice hockey player who played 60 games in the National Hockey League for the Detroit Red Wings.
simple: Louis Angelo Marcon (born May 28, 1935 in Fort William, Ontario) is a retired Canadian professional ice hockey player. <s> His career included 60 games in the National Hockey League for the Detroit Red Wings.

title: Kälarne
complex: Kälarne is a locality situated in Bräcke Municipality, Jämtland County, Sweden with 451 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Kälarne is a locality in Bräcke Municipality in Jämtland County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 451 people lived there.

title: Loki (comics)
complex: Loki is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. <s> Created by writer Stan Lee, scripter Larry Lieber and penciller Jack Kirby, a version of the character first appeared in "Venus" #6 (August 1949). <s> The modern day incarnation of Loki first appeared in "Journey into Mystery" #85 (October 1962). <s> The character, which is based on the Norse deity of the same name, is the Asgardian god of mischief. <s> He is the adopted brother and often enemy of the superhero Thor, however over the years the character has been depicted as an antihero. <s> In 2009, Loki was ranked as IGN's 8th Greatest Comic Book Villain of All Time and in 2014 was ranked again by IGN, this time as the 4th Greatest Comic Book Villain of All Time. <s> Tom Hiddleston portrays the character in the Marvel Cinematic Universe films "Thor" (2011), "The Avengers" (2012), "" (2013), "" (2017), "" (2018), and "" (2019). <s> Hiddleston will return to portray the role in the Disney+ upcoming series "Loki" (2021).
simple: Loki is a fictional villain who appears in comic books by Marvel Comics. <s> The character first appeared historically in "Venus" No. 6 (August 1949). <s> The character was created by Stan Lee, Larry Lieber and Jack Kirby. <s> He is based on the god Loki from Norse mythology. <s> Loki is the brother and enemy of Thor. <s> In the Marvel Cinematic Universe, Loki is featured in the movies "Thor", "The Avengers" and "". <s> The character Loki is played by Tom Hiddleston.

title: Anaïs Mitchell
complex: Anaïs Mitchell ( ; born March 26, 1981) is an American singer-songwriter, musician, and playwright. <s> Mitchell has released seven albums, including "Hadestown" (2010), "Young Man in America" (2012), and "Child Ballads" (2013). <s> Mitchell's father is a novelist and college professor and named her after author Anaïs Nin. <s> She grew up on Treleven farm in Addison County, Vermont, and after traveling to the Middle East, Europe and Latin America as a child, she attended Middlebury College. <s> Having begun writing her first songs at the age of 17, Mitchell won the New Folk award in 2003 at the Kerrville Folk Festival. <s> Her album "Hymns for the Exiled" was released on Chicago's Waterbug Records label in 2004. <s> This recording attracted the attention of singer/songwriter Ani DiFranco, who signed her to the Righteous Babe Records label. <s> In 2006 Mitchell debuted a draft of her "folk opera" "Hadestown", which she wrote in collaboration with arranger Michael Chorney and director Ben T. Matchstick. <s> A revised version of "Hadestown" was staged in 2007. <s> Her third album, "The Brightness," was released that same year on Righteous Babe Records. <s> Mitchell continued quietly working on a stage version of "Hadestown" while also writing and recording new material. <s> In early 2012, she released "Young Man in America" on Wilderland Records. <s> Mitchell opened the North American leg of Bon Iver's autumn 2012 tour, which included two sold-out shows at Radio City Music Hall. <s> The album was largely praised by critics as "genre-defining" and her "second consecutive masterpiece." <s> Mitchell has received favorable reviews on her musical style, sound and performance. <s> An article in "Acoustic Guitar" magazine calls Mitchell "fearlessly emotive" and compares her to Bob Dylan, Leonard Cohen, and Gillian Welch. <s> The UK's "Independent" newspaper called her "the most engaging, and in some ways, most original artist currently working in the field of new American folk music" "The New York Times" noted that "Ms Mitchell's songs address contemporary angst with uncanny vision" and called her "a formidable songwriting talent".
simple: Anaïs Mitchell (; born March 26, 1981) is an American singer, songwriter and guitarist. <s> Anaïs Mitchell is the daughter of a novelist and a college professor. <s> As a child, she grew up on a farm in Addison County, Vermont. <s> She also traveled to the Middle East, Europe and Latin America. <s> She later studied at Middlebury College. <s> In 2003 Mitchell won the "New Folk" award at the Kerrville Folk Festival. <s> Her album, "Hymns for the Exiled", was released on Chicago's Waterbug Records label in 2004. <s> This recording caused her to be noticed by singer/songwriter, Ani DiFranco. <s> DiFranco signed Mitchell to the Righteous Babe Records label. <s> In September that same year Righteous Babe Records released "country e.p." <s> Mitchell released an album called "Young Man in America," on her Wilderland Records label in 2012. <s> Mitchell has gotten good reviews on her musical style and performance. <s> An article in "Acoustic Guitar" magazine compares her to Dylan, Cohen, and Welch.

title: SST Records
complex: SST Records is an American independent record label formed in 1978 in Long Beach, California by musician Greg Ginn. <s> The company was formed in 1966 by Ginn at age 12 as Solid State Tuners, a small business through which he sold electronics equipment. <s> Ginn repurposed the company as a record label to release material by his band Black Flag.
simple: SST Records is an American independent record label formed in 1978 in Long Beach, California by musician Greg Ginn. <s> The company was initially called Solid State Transmitters through which Ginn sold electronics equipment. <s> Ginn repurposed the company as a record label to release material by his band Black Flag.

title: Taurus Mountains
complex: The Taurus Mountains (Turkish: "Toros Dağları"), are a mountain complex in southern Turkey, separating the Mediterranean coastal region of southern Turkey from the central Anatolian Plateau. <s> The system extends along a curve from Lake Eğirdir in the west to the upper reaches of the Euphrates and Tigris rivers in the east. <s> It is a part of the Alpide belt in Eurasia. <s> A Bronze Age archaeological site, where early evidence of tin mining was found, is at Kestel. <s> The pass known in antiquity as the Cilician Gates crosses the range north of Tarsus. <s> In the Aladaglar and Bolkar mountains, limestone has eroded to form karstic landscapes of waterfalls, underground rivers, and some of the largest caves of Asia. <s> The Manavgat River originates on the southern slopes of the Beydaglari range. <s> West Taurus and Taurus Mountains form an arc around the Gulf of Antalya. <s> The East Taşeli Plateau and Goksu River divide it from the Central Taurus Mountains. <s> It has many peaks rising above 3,000 – . <s> The complex is divided into four ranges: The highest point in the central Tauruses is the summit of Mt. Demirkazık (3,756m).
simple: Taurus Mountains (Turkish: "Toros Dağları") are a mountain range in Turkey, from which the Euphrates (Turkish: Fırat) and Tigris (Turkish: Dicle) descend into Syria and Iraq. <s> This mountain range divides the Mediterranean region of southern Turkey from the central plateau. <s> The mountain range extends along a curve from Lake Eğirdir in the west to the upper reaches of the Euphrates and Tigris in the east. <s> At Kestel is a Bronze Age archaeological site where early evidence of tin mining was found. <s> Limestone has eroded to form karstic landscapes of waterfalls, underground rivers, and the largest caves of Asia. <s> The Manavgat River comes from its southern slopes. <s> It has many peaks rising above 10,000–12,000 ft (3,000–3,700 m), with the Demirkazık summit in the region known as Aladağlar, at 3,756 meters (12,322 ft.) as the highest point.

title: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie
complex: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Saint-Gilles-Croix-de-Vie is a commune. <s> It is found in the Pays de la Loire region in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Châtellerault
complex: Châtellerault (] ) is a commune in the Vienne department in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region in France. <s> It is located in the northeast of the former province Poitou, and the residents are called "Châtelleraudais".
simple: Châtellerault is a "commune" in the Vienne department in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region in western France. <s> Châtellerault is in the centre of the Vienne department.

title: Megalosauroidea
complex: Megalosauroidea (meaning 'great/big lizard forms') is a superfamily (or clade) of tetanuran theropod dinosaurs that lived from the Middle Jurassic to the Late Cretaceous period. <s> The group is defined as "Megalosaurus bucklandii" and all taxa sharing a more recent common ancestor with it than with "Allosaurus fragilis" or "Passer domesticus". <s> Members of the group include "Spinosaurus", "Megalosaurus", and "Torvosaurus". <s> Carrano, Benson & Sampson (2012) performed much larger phylogenetic analysis of the Tetanurae that includes more taxa. <s> They used the clade name Megalosauria (Bonaparte, 1850) in their analysis and defined it as the node comprising "Megalosaurus", "Spinosaurus", their most recent common ancestor, and all its descendants.
simple: Megalosauroidea is a group of carnivorous theropod dinosaurs. <s> They lived from the Middle Jurassic to the Late Cretaceous period. <s> The definition of the clade Megalosauroidea includes "Megalosaurus bucklandii" and all taxa that share a more recent common ancestor with it than they do with "Allosaurus fragilis" or the House Sparrow. <s> Members of the group include "Spinosaurus", "Megalosaurus", and "Torvosaurus". <s> It is based on a study by Carrano, Benson & Sampson (2012).

title: Kappa (folklore)
complex: The "kappa" is said to be roughly humanoid in form and about the size of a child, inhabiting the ponds and rivers of Japan. <s> It is typically greenish in color (or yellow-blue ), and either scaly or slimy skinned, with webbed hands and feet, and a turtle-like carapace on its back.
simple: The Kappa is said to be the size of a 6 to 10 year old boy.

title: Neuvy, Allier
complex: Neuvy is a commune in the Allier department in Auvergne in central France.
simple: Neuvy is a commune. <s> It is found in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Stratford Festival
complex: The Stratford Festival is a theatre festival which runs from April to October in the city of Stratford, Ontario, Canada. <s> Founded by local journalist Tom Patterson in 1952, the festival was formerly known as the Stratford Shakespearean Festival, the Shakespeare Festival and the Stratford Shakespeare Festival.
simple: The Stratford Festival, formerly called the Stratford Shakespeare Festival, is an annual theatre festival held in Stratford, Ontario, Canada. <s> It runs from April to October.

title: Moorhead, Iowa
complex: Moorhead is a city in Monona County, Iowa, United States. <s> Moorhead stands along the Soldier River.
simple: Moorhead is a city of Iowa in the United States.

title: Rockwell B-1 Lancer
complex: The Rockwell B-1 Lancer is a supersonic variable-sweep wing, heavy bomber used by the United States Air Force. <s> It is commonly called the "Bone" (from "B-One").
simple: The Rockwell B-1 Lancer is a strategic bomber in the service of the US Air Force.

title: Les Landes-Genusson
complex: Les Landes-Genusson is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Les Landes-Genusson is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Montournais
complex: Montournais is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Montournais is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France and has a population of 1,730 habitants.

title: Wabash Avenue Bridge
complex: The Wabash Avenue Bridge (officially, Irv Kupcinet Bridge) over the Chicago River was built in 1930. <s> Standing west of the Michigan Avenue Bridge and east of Marina City, the bascule bridge connects the Near North Side with "The Loop" area. <s> The single-deck, double-leaf bascule bridge was designed by Thomas Pihlfeldt and built by the Ketler and Elliot Company. <s> The American Institute of Steel Construction awarded it the "Most Beautiful" bridge in 1930.
simple: The Wabash Avenue Bridge (officially, Irv Kupcinet Bridge) over the Chicago River was built in 1930. <s> Standing west of the Michigan Avenue Bridge and southwest of the Trump International Hotel and Tower. <s> The bascule bridge connects the Near North Side with "The Loop" area. <s> The single-deck, double leaf bridge was designed by Thomas Pihlfeldt and built by the Ketler and Elliot Company. <s> The American Institute of Steel Construction awarded it the "Most Beautiful" bridge in 1930.

title: S/2003 J 9
complex: S/2003 J 9 is a retrograde irregular satellite of Jupiter. <s> It was discovered by a team of astronomers from the University of Hawaii led by Scott S. Sheppard in 2003. <s> S/2003 J 9 is about 1 kilometre in diameter, and orbits Jupiter at an average distance of 23,858 Mm in 752.839 days, at an inclination of 165° to the ecliptic (165° to Jupiter's equator), in a retrograde direction and with an eccentricity of 0.276. <s> It belongs to the Carme group, made up of irregular retrograde moons orbiting Jupiter at a distance ranging between 23 and 24 Gm and at an inclination of about 165°.
simple: S/2003 J 9 is a non-spherical moon of Jupiter. <s> It was found by a team of astronomers from the University of Hawaii led by Scott S. Sheppard in 2003. <s> S/2003 J 9 is about 1 kilometre in diameter, and orbits Jupiter at an average distance of 23,858,000 km in 752.839 days, at an inclination of 165° to the ecliptic (165° to Jupiter's equator), with an orbital eccentricity of 0.276. <s> It belongs to the Carme group, made up of non-spherical retrograde moons orbiting Jupiter at a distance ranging between 23,000,000 and 24,000,000 km and at an inclination of about 165°.

title: Volcanoes of Kamchatka
complex: The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes situated on the Kamchatka Peninsula, in eastern Russia. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, 29 of them still active. <s> The peninsula has a high density of volcanoes and associated volcanic phenomena, with 29 active volcanoes being included in the six UNESCO World Heritage List sites in the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, most of them on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The highest volcano is Klyuchevskaya Sopka (4,750 m or 15,584 ft), the largest active volcano in the Northern Hemisphere, while the most striking is Kronotsky, whose perfect cone was said by celebrated volcanologists Robert and Barbara Decker to be a prime candidate for the world's most beautiful volcano. <s> Somewhat more accessible are the three volcanoes visible from Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky: Koryaksky, Avachinsky, and Kozelsky. <s> In the center of Kamchatka is Eurasia's world-famous Geyser Valley which was partly destroyed by a massive mudslide in June 2007. <s> Owing to the Kuril-Kamchatka Trench, deep-focus seismic events and tsunamis are fairly common. <s> A pair of megathrust earthquakes occurred off the coast on October 16, 1737, and on November 4, 1952, in the magnitude of ~9.3 and 8.2 respectively. <s> A chain of more shallow earthquakes were recorded as recently as April 2006.
simple: The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes situated on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The volcanoes of Kamchatka are a large group of volcanoes on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> They are listed as the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, and most of them are on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, 29 of them still active. <s> The Kamchatka River and the surrounding central side valley are flanked by large volcanic belts containing around 160 volcanoes, including the 29 active ones. <s> The peninsula has a high density of volcanoes and associated volcanic phenomena, with 29 active volcanoes being included in the six UNESCO World Heritage List sites in the Volcanoes of Kamchatka group, most of them on the Kamchatka Peninsula. <s> 29 active volcanoes are included in six UNESCO World Heritage List sites. <s> The highest volcano is Klyuchevskaya Sopka (4,750 m or 15,584 ft), the largest active volcano in the northern hemisphere. <s> The most striking is Kronotsky, whose perfect cone was said by celebrated volcanologists Robert and Barbara Decker to be a prime candidate for the world's most beautiful volcano. <s> In the center of Kamchatka is Eurasia's world famous Geyser Valley which was partly destroyed by a massive mudslide in June 2007. <s> Deep seismic events and tsunamis are fairly common. <s> A pair of huge earthquakes occurred off the coast on October 16, 1737, and on November 4, 1952, in magnitudes ~9.3 and 8.2 respectively. <s> More shallow earthquakes were recorded as recently as April 2006.

title: VisualEditor
complex: VisualEditor (VE) is a project to provide a "visual" or "WYSIWYG-like" online rich-text editor as a MediaWiki extension to Wikipedia. <s> It was developed by the Wikimedia Foundation in partnership with Wikia. <s> In July 2013 the beta was enabled by default, with the ability to opt-out, for Mediawiki.org and several of the largest Wikipedias.
simple: It is similar to a WYSIWYG editor, and is available as a MediaWiki extension. <s> VisualEditor (VE) is a project developed by the Wikimedia Foundation together with Wikia. <s> The Beta version of this extension was enabled on Mediawiki.org and other larger Wikipedia in July 2013 by default, but users could decide to opt-out.

title: Balliol College, Oxford
complex: Balliol College is one of the constituent colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> One of Oxford's oldest colleges, it was founded around 1263 by John I de Balliol, a rich landowner from Barnard Castle in County Durham, who provided the foundation and endowment for the college. <s> When de Balliol died in 1269 his widow, Dervorguilla, a woman whose wealth far exceeded that of her husband, continued his work in setting up the college, providing a further endowment, and writing the statutes. <s> She is considered a cofounder of the college. <s> The college's alumni include the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Boris Johnson MP, as well as three former prime ministers (H. H. Asquith, who once described Balliol men as possessing "the tranquil consciousness of an effortless superiority", Harold Macmillan, and Edward Heath), Harald V of Norway, Empress Masako of Japan, five Nobel laureates, and numerous literary and philosophical figures, including Adam Smith, Gerard Manley Hopkins, and Aldous Huxley. <s> John Wycliffe, who translated the Bible into English, was Master of the college in the 1360s.
simple: Balliol College is one of the colleges of the University of Oxford in England. <s> Balliol is Oxford's most popular college. <s> It was founded in 1263 by John Balliol, father of King John Balliol of Scotland. <s> The college's alumni include several former prime ministers.

title: The Big Parade
complex: The Big Parade is a 1925 American silent war drama film directed by King Vidor, starring John Gilbert, Renée Adorée, Hobart Bosworth, Tom O'Brien, and Karl Dane. <s> Adapted by Harry Behn from the autobiographical novel "Plumes" by Laurence Stallings, with titles by Joseph W. Farnham, the film is about an idle rich boy who joins the US Army's Rainbow Division and is sent to France to fight in World War I, becomes a friend of two working class men, experiences the horrors of trench warfare, and finds love with a French girl. <s> Although other anti-war films preceded it, "The Big Parade" is an early film which neither glorified the war nor ignored its human costs. <s> It heavily influenced a great many subsequent war films, especially "All Quiet on the Western Front" (1930). <s> In 1992, "The Big Parade" was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant". <s> "The Big Parade" was one of the greatest hits of the 1920s earning gross rentals of $4,990,000 in the United States and $1,141,000 overseas on a budget of $382,000 during its initial release, with MGM recording a profit of $3.4 million, its biggest of the silent era. <s> The domestic earnings were MGM's biggest until the release of Gone With the Wind.
simple: The Big Parade is a 1925 silent movie. <s> It was directed by King Vidor. <s> It was adapted by Harry Behn and King Vidor from the play by Joseph Farnham and the autobiographical novel "Plumes" by Laurence Stallings. <s> It tells the story of an idle rich boy who joins the US Army's Rainbow Division and is sent to France to fight in World War I. <s> He becomes friends with two working class men, experiences the horrors of trench warfare, and finds love with a French girl. <s> In 1992 "The Big Parade" was selected for preservation in the United States National Film Registry by the Library of Congress as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant". <s> "The Big Parade" was one of the greatest hits of the 1920s earning gross rentals of $4,990,000 in North America and $1,141,000 overseas on a budget of $382,000 during its initial release, The film ultimately grossed $18–$22 million in worldwide rentals and is sometimes proclaimed as the most successful film of the silent era.

title: Salt mining
complex: A salt mine is a mine from which salt is extracted. <s> The mined salt is usually in the form of halite (commonly known as rock salt), and extracted from evaporite formations.
simple: A salt mine is a mine where salt is taken from the earth.

title: Francisco Pavón
complex: Francisco "Paco" Pavón Barahona (born 9 January 1980) is a Spanish retired footballer who played as a central defender.
simple: Francisco Pavón (born 9 January 1980) is a Spanish football player.

title: Fadil Vokrri
complex: Fadil Avdullah Vokrri (23 July 1960 – 9 June 2018) was a football administrator and player. <s> He was president of the Football Federation of Kosovo from 16 February 2008 until his death on 9 June 2018. <s> Vokrri scored a total of 121 goals and had 363 club appearances, he began his career at the age of 16 years old at Llapi. <s> He then moved to Prishtina in 1980 and played there until 1986, scoring 55 goals and making 172 appearances. <s> Vokrri was very successful with Partizan from Belgrade where he scored 18 goals and had 55 appearances. <s> He was key to the team's successful run in the 1988–89 Yugoslav Cup, notably scoring in the final as Partizan won 6–1 against Velež Mostar. <s> On 9 June 2018, Vokrri suffered a heart attack while he was exercising and died on his way to the emergency room. <s> Later that day, the Prishtina City Stadium was renamed to the Fadil Vokrri Stadium in his honour.
simple: Fadil Avdullah Vokrri (23 June 1960 – 9 June 2018) was a Kosovan football administrator and player. <s> He was president of Football Federation of Kosovo from 16 February 2008 until his death on 9 June 2018. <s> Vokrri scored a total of 121 goals and had 363 club appearances. <s> He moved to Pristina in 1980 and played there until 1986 scoring 55 goals and making 172 appearances. <s> On 9 June 2018, Vokrri died of cardiac arrest in Pristina, Kosovo at the age of 57.

title: Edwin Meese
complex: Edwin Meese III (born December 2, 1931) is an American attorney, law professor, author and member of the Republican Party who served in official capacities within the Ronald Reagan Gubernatorial Administration (1967–1974), the Reagan Presidential Transition Team (1980) and the Reagan White House (1981–1985), eventually rising to hold the position of the 75th Attorney General of the United States (1985–1988). <s> Meese was born in Oakland, California, the eldest of four sons born to Leone (née Feldman) and Edwin Meese, Jr. <s> He was raised in a practicing Lutheran family, of German descent.
simple: Edwin "Ed" Meese, III (born December 2, 1931) is an American attorney, law professor, and author. <s> He served under Ronald Reagan's administration back when Reagan was Governor (1967–1974), the Reagan Presidential Transition Team (1980), and under Reagan's presidential administration (1981–1985). <s> Meese was the 75th Attorney General of the United States (1985–1988), a position from which he resigned while serving in office under investigation from a special prosecutor. <s> Meese was born on December 2, 1931 in Oakland, California.

title: Williamsburg, Virginia
complex: Williamsburg is a city in the U.S. state of Virginia. <s> As of the 2010 U.S. Census, the population was 14,068.
simple: Williamsburg is a small city in Virginia in the United States.

title: Alfredo Biondi
complex: Alfredo Biondi (born June 29, 1928) is an Italian politician and lawyer. <s> In 1994 he served as Minister of Justice of the Italian Republic during the first cabinet chaired by Silvio Berlusconi.
simple: Alfredo Biondi (born June 29, 1928) is an Italian politician and lawyer. <s> In 1994 he served as Minister of Justice of the Italian Republic during the first cabinet chaired by Silvio Berlusconi.

title: Lollipop (Candyman)
complex: "Lollipop (Candyman)" is a song recorded by Danish dance-pop group Aqua. <s> It was released as the fourth overall single from their debut album "Aquarium" as the follow-up to their most successful song "Barbie Girl" in Australasia, North America and Mainland Europe (it was not released in the United Kingdom.) <s> Although it said to be one of the group's favorite songs, "Lollipop (Candyman)" failed to replicate the success of "Barbie Girl", "Doctor Jones" and "My Oh My" where it was released.
simple: "Lollipop (Candyman)" is a pop song from the group Aqua. <s> It is from their first album, "Aquarium". <s> It was not as successful as their song "Barbie Girl". <s> This song was said to be one of the group's favorite songs.

title: Aberdeen, Washington
complex: Aberdeen is a city in Grays Harbor County, Washington, United States. <s> The population was 16,896 at the 2010 census. <s> The city is the economic center of Grays Harbor County, bordering the cities of Hoquiam and Cosmopolis. <s> Aberdeen is occasionally referred to as the "Gateway to the Olympic Peninsula". <s> Aberdeen was founded by Samuel Benn in 1884 and incorporated on May 12, 1890. <s> Although it became the largest and best-known city in Grays Harbor, Aberdeen lagged behind nearby Hoquiam and Cosmopolis in its early years.
simple: Aberdeen is a city in the American state of Washington. <s> Aberdeen is sometimes called the "Gateway to the Olympic Peninsula". <s> Aberdeen was founded by Samuel Benn in 1884.

title: Töss (river)
complex: The Töss is a river of the canton of Zürich. <s> It starts with the confluence of the Vordertöss and the Hindertöss in the Zürcher Oberland, at "Tössscheidi" on 796 m on the border between the munacipalities of Wald west of the Dägelschberg (1267 m ), east of the Hüttchopf (1231 m ), and north of the Tössstock (1153 m )). <s> The Töss flows to the north before it meets the main valley of its own name, Töss Valley ("Tösstal") just before Steg im Tösstal. <s> Here, the river and its valley turns to the west in order to flow through Bauma then turns to the north again. <s> West of the village Turbenthal it turns west again, and the valley gets even more ragged than before. <s> It traverses Winterthur on its most western part of the city, just northeast of the "Töss", a city mountain. <s> After joining the Eulach on the western exit of the city, the river Töss then continues more or less westnorthwestern and joins the Rhine after about 11 km on Rhine's large southern bend called "Tössegg" west of Teufen and just before Eglisau.
simple: The Töss is a river of the canton of Zurich, Switzerland. <s> The river begins in the Zürcher Oberland. <s> It flows along the Töss Valley ("Tösstal") past Winterthur. <s> It joins the Rhine at Tössegg near Teufen.

title: 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 3
complex: The 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification UEFA Group 3 was a UEFA qualifying group for the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup. <s> The group comprised Denmark, Iceland, Israel, Malta, Serbia and Switzerland.
simple: The 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 3 was one of the European qualifying groups for the 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup.

title: Buffet
complex: A buffet ( , , from French word for "sideboard") is a system of serving meals in which food is placed in a public area where the diners serve themselves. <s> A form of "service à la française", buffets are offered at various places including hotels, restaurants, and many social events. <s> Buffet restaurants normally offer all-you-can-eat food for a set price, but some measure prices by weight or by number of dishes. <s> Buffets usually have some hot dishes, so the term cold buffet (see Smörgåsbord) has been developed to describe formats lacking hot food. <s> Hot or cold buffets usually involve dishware and utensils, but a finger buffet is an array of foods that are designed to be small and easily consumed only by hand, such as cupcakes, slices of pizza, foods on cocktail sticks, etc. <s> The essential feature of the various buffet formats is that the diners can directly view the food and immediately select which dishes they wish to consume, and usually also can decide how much food they take. <s> Buffets are effective for serving large numbers of people at once, and are often seen in institutional settings, business conventions, or large parties. <s> Many boarding schools, colleges, and universities offer optional or mandatory "meal plans", especially in connection with dormitories for students.
simple: A buffet is a serve-yourself food system. <s> Food is placed in a public area where the diners choose what they want. <s> Buffet restaurants usually offer all-you-can-eat food for a set price. <s> Buffets usually have some hot dishes. <s> The term cold buffet (see Smörgåsbord) has been developed to describe buffets lacking hot food. <s> Hot or cold buffets usually involve dishware and utensils, but a finger buffet is designed for small pieces taken by hand, such as cupcakes, slices of pizza, foods on cocktail sticks, etc. <s> The essential feature of the various buffet formats is that the diners can see the food and immediately select which dishes they wish to eat, and usually also can decide how much food they take. <s> Buffets are effective for serving large numbers of people at once, and are often seen in institutional settings, such as business conventions or large parties.

title: Ivan Grubišić
complex: Ivan Grubišić (20 June 1936 – 19 March 2017) was a Croatian Roman Catholic priest, sociologist, and politician. <s> He served in the Croatian Parliament from 2011 to 2015. <s> Ivan Grubišić was born in Dicmo in a poor family. <s> He had seven brothers and sisters.
simple: Ivan Grubišić (20 June 1936 – 19 March 2017) was a Croatian Roman Catholic priest, sociologist, and independent politician. <s> Grubišić died in Split, Croatia on 19 March 2017, aged 80. <s> He served as a representative in the Croatian Parliament representing the X electoral district from 22 December 2011 through 28 December 2015. <s> Grubišić was born in Dicmo, Kingdom of Yugoslavia.

title: Radebeul
complex: Radebeul is a town ("große Kreisstadt") in the Elbe valley in the district of Meißen in Saxony, Germany, a suburb of Dresden. <s> It is well known for its viticulture, a museum dedicated to writer Karl May, and a narrow gauge railway connecting Radebeul with the castle of Moritzburg and the town of Radeburg. <s> The Meißen area, where Radebeul is located, is one of the northeasternmost areas where wine is grown in the 21st century.
simple: Radebeul is a town ("große Kreisstadt") in the district of Meißen in Saxony, Germany, a suburb of Dresden. <s> The Meißen area, where Radebeul is located, is one of the northeasternmost areas where wine is grown today.

title: Ellen DeGeneres
complex: Ellen Lee DeGeneres ( ; born January 26, 1958) is an American comedian, television host, actress, writer, and producer. <s> She starred in the popular sitcom "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998 and has hosted her syndicated TV talk show, "The Ellen DeGeneres Show," since 2003. <s> She starred in two television sitcoms, "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998, and "The Ellen Show" from 2001 to 2002. <s> During the fourth season of "Ellen" in 1997, she came out as a lesbian in an appearance on "The Oprah Winfrey Show". <s> Her character, Ellen Morgan, also came out to a therapist played by Winfrey, and the series went on to explore various LGBT issues, including the coming-out process. <s> In 2008, she married her longtime girlfriend Portia de Rossi. <s> DeGeneres was born and raised in Metairie, Louisiana, to Elizabeth Jane (née Pfeffer, born 1930), a speech therapist, and Elliott Everett DeGeneres (c.1925–2018), an insurance agent. <s> She has one brother, Vance, a musician and producer. <s> She is of French, English, German, and Irish descent. <s> She was raised as a Christian Scientist. <s> In 1973, her parents filed for separation and were divorced the following year. <s> Shortly after, Ellen's mother married Roy Gruessendorf, a salesman. <s> Betty Jane and Ellen moved with Gruessendorf from the New Orleans area to Atlanta, Texas. <s> Vance stayed with his father. <s> On a February 2011 episode of her show, she told her studio audience of a letter from the New England Historic Genealogical Society confirming she is 15th cousin to Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge, via their shared common ancestor Thomas Fairfax. <s> When she was 15 or 16 years old, she was molested by her stepfather. <s> DeGeneres graduated from Atlanta High School in May 1976, after completing her first years of high school at Grace King High School in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She moved back to New Orleans to attend the University of New Orleans, where she majored in communication studies. <s> After one semester, she left school to do clerical work in a law firm with a cousin, Laura Gillen. <s> Her early jobs included working at J. C. Penney, and being a waitress at TGI Fridays and another restaurant, a house painter, a hostess, and a bartender. <s> She relates much of her childhood and career experiences in her comedic work. <s> A selfie orchestrated by 86th Academy Awards host Ellen DeGeneres during the broadcast is the second-most retweeted tweet ever. <s> DeGeneres said she wanted to homage Meryl Streep's record 17 Oscar nominations by setting a new record with her, and invited other Oscar celebrities to join them. <s> The resulting photo of twelve celebrities broke the previous retweet record within forty minutes and was retweeted over 1.8 million times in the first hour. <s> By the end of the ceremony it had been retweeted over 2 million times, less than 24 hours later, it had been retweeted over 2.8 million times. <s> s of May 2017 , it has been retweeted over 3.4 million times. <s> The group selfie effort was parodied by Lego and Matt Groening with The Simpsons. <s> It beat the previous record, which was held by Barack Obama, following his victory in the 2012 presidential election. <s> She is a fan of the National Football League and has shown particular support for the New Orleans Saints and the Green Bay Packers. <s> In 2011, she attended a Saints practice dressed as Packers Hall of Famer Don Hutson. <s> In 1997, DeGeneres came out as lesbian. <s> The disclosure of her sexual orientation sparked intense interest by American tabloids. <s> The contentiousness of the media coverage stunted DeGeneres' professional career and left her "mired in depression". <s> In her book "Love, Ellen", DeGeneres' mother, Betty DeGeneres describes being initially shocked when her daughter came out, but she has since become one of her strongest supporters; she is also an active member of Parents & Friends of Lesbians and Gays (PFLAG) and spokesperson for the Human Rights Campaign's Coming Out Project. <s> Since 2004, DeGeneres has had a relationship with Portia de Rossi. <s> After the overturn of the same-sex marriage ban in California, DeGeneres and de Rossi were engaged, and married in August 2008, at their home in Beverly Hills, California, where they live with their four dogs and three cats. <s> The passage of Proposition 8 cast doubt on the legal status of their marriage, but a subsequent California Supreme Court judgment validated it because it occurred before November 4, 2008. <s> On August 6, 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres. <s> The petition was granted on September 23, 2010. <s> In November 2011, Secretary of State Hillary Clinton named her a special envoy for Global AIDS Awareness. <s> On December 3, 2011, DeGeneres opened the show at the David Lynch Foundation's 3rd annual "Change Begins Within" gala at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art to raise funds to bring Transcendental Meditation to at-risk populations suffering from epidemic levels of chronic stress and stress-related disorders.
simple: Ellen DeGeneres (born January 26, 1958) is an American stand-up comedian, television host and actress. <s> She is the host of the talk show "The Ellen DeGeneres Show". <s> She starred in two television sitcoms, "Ellen" from 1994 to 1998 and "The Ellen Show" from 2001 to 2002. <s> DeGeneres was born and raised in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She is the daughter of Elizabeth Jane "Betty" Pfeffer DeGeneres, a speech therapist, and Elliott Everett DeGeneres, an insurance agent. <s> She has one brother, Vance. <s> Her brother is a musician and producer. <s> She is of French, English, German, and Irish ancestry. <s> She was raised as a Christian Scientist until age 13. <s> In 1973, her parents filed for separation and were divorced the following year. <s> Shortly after, Ellen's mother married Roy Gruessendorf, a salesman. <s> Betty Jane and Ellen moved with Gruessendorf from the New Orleans area to Atlanta, Texas. <s> Vance stayed with his father. <s> On a February 9, 2011, episode of "The Ellen DeGeneres Show", DeGeneres shared a letter from the New England Historic Genealogical Society. <s> It said that she is Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge's 15th cousin via their shared common ancestor Thomas Fairfax. <s> DeGeneres graduated from Atlanta High School in May 1976. <s> Her first years of high school were at Grace King High School in Metairie, Louisiana. <s> She moved back to New Orleans to attend the University of New Orleans, where she majored in communication studies. <s> After one semester, she left school to do clerical work in a law firm with a cousin, Laura Gillen. <s> Her early jobs included working at J. C. Penney, being a waitress at TGI Friday's and another restaurant, a house painter, a hostess, and a bartender. <s> She talks about her experiences as a child and at work in her comedic work. <s> DeGeneres took a selfie at the 86th Academy Awards in 2014 with actors such as Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie, Bradley Cooper, Jared Leto, and Lupita Nyong'o. <s> It became the most retweeted image ever on Twitter, with over 3 million retweets. <s> She is a fan of the National Football League, and has shown particular support for the New Orleans Saints and the Green Bay Packers. <s> In 2011, she attended a Saints practice dressed as Packers Hall of Famer Don Hutson. <s> During the fourth season of "Ellen" in 1997, DeGeneres came out publicly as a lesbian in an appearance on "The Oprah Winfrey Show". <s> Since 2004, DeGeneres has been in a relationship with Australian actress Portia de Rossi. <s> They were married on August 16, 2008. <s> In November 2011, then-Secretary of State Hillary Clinton named her a Special Envoy for Global AIDS Awareness.

title: Tak Province
complex: Tak ( , ] ) is one of the western provinces ("changwat") of Thailand. <s> Neighbouring provinces are (from north clockwise) Mae Hong Son, Chiang Mai, Lamphun, Lampang, Sukhothai, Kamphaeng Phet, Nakhon Sawan, Uthai Thani and Kanchanaburi. <s> The western edge of the province has a long boundary with Kayin State of Myanmar (Burma). <s> The province is divided into nine districts ("amphoes"). <s> These are further subdivided into 63 sub-districts ("tambons") and 493 villages ("mubans"). <s> Since 2003, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in Thailand has tracked progress on human development at sub national level using the Human achievement index (HAI), a composite index covering all the eight key areas of human development.Province Tak, with an HAI value of 0.5650 is "low", occupies 75th place in the ranking and that is the second-last of this rank list.
