simple: Tak is one of the northern provinces ("changwat") of Thailand. <s> Tak's neighbouring provinces are (clockwise from north) Mae Hong Son, Chiang Mai, Lamphun, Lampang, Sukhothai, Kamphaeng Phet, Nakhon Sawan, Uthai Thani and Kanchanaburi. <s> The western edge of Tak borders Kayin State of Myanmar. <s> Tak has 9 districts ("amphoe"), 63 subdistricts ("tambon") and 493 villages ("muban").

title: Kaufland
complex: Kaufland ] is a German hypermarket chain, part of the Schwarz Gruppe which also owns Lidl and Handelshof. <s> It opened its first store in 1984 in Neckarsulm and quickly expanded to become a leader in what was formerly East Germany. <s> The chain operates over 1,200 stores in Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Romania, Bulgaria and Croatia. <s> Kaufland plans to open stores in Australia, and Moldova.
simple: Kaufland ] is a German hypermarket chain, part of the Schwarz Gruppe which also owns Lidl and Handelshof. <s> In 1984, the first store was opened in Neckarsulm and quickly expanded to become a leader in what was formerly East Germany. <s> The chain operates over 1,200 stores in Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Romania, Bulgaria and Croatia. <s> Kaufland plans to open stores in Australia, and Moldova.

title: John Aloisi
complex: John Aloisi (born 5 February 1976) is a retired Australian association football player and former manager of A-League club Brisbane Roar. <s> In a professional career that spanned 20 seasons, with league totals of 459 games and 127 goals, he was the first Australian ever to play and score in La Liga, the Premier League and Serie A.
simple: John Aloisi (born 5 February 1976) is an Australian football player.

title: Carmen Silvera
complex: Carmen Dorothy Blanche Silvera (2 June 1922 – 3 August 2002) was a British comic actress. <s> Born in Canada of Spanish descent, she moved to Coventry, England, with her family when she was a child. <s> She appeared on television regularly in the 1960s, and achieved mainstream fame in the 1980s with her starring role in the British television programme, "'Allo 'Allo!" <s> Silvera first made her name as a television actress in the 1960s British police drama "Z-Cars" in 1962, going on to appear as Camilla Hope in the BBC soap opera "Compact" from 1964 to 1965. <s> She played Mrs Van Schuyler in "Lillie" in 1978, ITV's drama series about the future Edward VII's mistress, Lillie Langtry. <s> In Coventry in 1949, Silvera married John Cunliffe, an actor (not the John Cunliffe who wrote Postman Pat) she had met at repertory theatre in Tonbridge, Kent in 1941. <s> She divorced following a miscarriage and never remarried. <s> A heavy smoker, she died after a battle with lung cancer on 3 August 2002, aged 80, at the Denville Hall retirement home for actors.
simple: Carmen Silvera (3 June 1922 – 3 August 2002) was a Canadian-born British comic actress. <s> She played Camilla Hope in the soap opera "Compact". <s> She also played Mrs. Van Schuyler in Lillie in 1978. <s> She died from lung cancer at age 80 in England.

title: Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company
complex: The Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company (BRC&W) was a railway locomotive and carriage builder, founded in Birmingham, England and, for most of its existence, located at nearby Smethwick, with the factory divided by the boundary between the two places. <s> The company was established in 1854.
simple: The Birmingham Railway Carriage and Wagon Company (BRC&W) was a railway locomotive and carriage builder, founded in Birmingham, England. <s> For most of its existence, it was at nearby Smethwick, with the factory divided by the boundary between the two places. <s> The company was established in 1854.

title: Zork II
complex: Zork II: The Wizard of Frobozz is an interactive fiction video game published by Infocom in 1981. <s> It was written by Marc Blank, Dave Lebling, Bruce Daniels and Tim Anderson. <s> It was the second game in the popular Zork trilogy and was released for a wide range of computer systems. <s> It begins where "Zork I" left off and leads into "Zork III". <s> It is Infocom's second game. <s> The player begins in the Barrow from "Zork I" armed only with the trusty brass lantern and the elvish sword of great antiquity from before. <s> The objective of the game is not initially clear. <s> The Wizard of Frobozz is soon introduced. <s> The wizard was once a respected enchanter, but when his powers began to fade he was exiled by Lord Dimwit Flathead. <s> Now bordering on senility, the wizard is still a force to be reckoned with. <s> The player's goal in the wizard's realm is to avoid his capricious tricks and to learn to control his magic. <s> Like its predecessor, "Zork II" is essentially a treasure hunt. <s> Unlike the previous game, the ten treasures are tied together by a crude plot. <s> Finding the treasures does not end the game, nor are all the treasures needed to finish the game. <s> Instead, the adventurer must figure out a way to use the treasures in order to reach the game's finale.
simple: Zork II: The Wizard of Frobozz is an interactive fiction video game published by Infocom in 1981. <s> It was written by Marc Blank, Dave Lebling, Bruce Daniels and Tim Anderson. <s> It was the second game in the popular Zork trilogy. <s> It begins where "Zork I" left off and leads into "Zork III". <s> It is Infocom's second game. <s> The player starts in the Barrow from Zork I armed only with the brass lantern and the elvish sword. <s> The purpose of the game is not initially clear. <s> The Wizard of Frobozz is soon introduced. <s> The wizard was once a good sorceror, but when his powers began to go away he was exiled by Lord Dimwit Flathead. <s> Now bordering on insanity, the wizard is a force to be reckoned with. <s> Your goal, as you venture into the wizard's area, is to avoid his tricks and learn to control his magic. <s> Like its predecessor, "Zork II" is essentially a treasure hunt. <s> Unlike the previous game, the ten treasures are tied together by a crude plot. <s> Finding the treasures does not end the game, and finding all the treasures is not needed to finish the game. <s> Instead, the adventurer must figure out a way to use the treasures in order to reach the game's finale.

title: Chamely Khatun
complex: Chamely Khatun (born: 11 November 1988, is a Bangladeshi) cricketer who plays for the Bangladesh national women's cricket team. <s> She is a right handed batsman and right-arm slow bowler. <s> Chamely was part of the team that won a silver medal in cricket against the China national women's cricket team at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, China.
simple: Chamely Khatun (born 11 November 1988, is a Bangladeshi) cricketer who plays for the Bangladesh national women's cricket team. <s> She is a right handed batsman and right-arm slow bowler. <s> Chamely was part of the team that won a silver medal in cricket against the China national women's cricket team at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, China.

title: Lidgate
complex: Lidgate is a small village and a civil parish in the St Edmundsbury district, in the English county of Suffolk. <s> Lidgate is located on the B1063 road in between the towns of Newmarket and Clare.
simple: Lidgate is a village and civil parish in St Edmundsbury, Suffolk, England.

title: Peter Plympton Smith
complex: Peter Plympton Smith (born October 31, 1945) is a former member of the United States House of Representatives from the U.S. state of Vermont, the 75th Lieutenant Governor of Vermont, and an education administrator. <s> He served as the founding president of the Community College of Vermont, the founding president of California State University, Monterey Bay, and as assistant director general for education of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO). <s> From 1991 to 1994, Smith served as dean of the Graduate School of Education and Human Development at George Washington University.
simple: Peter Plympton Smith (born October 31, 1945) is a former member of the United States House of Representatives from the U.S. state of Vermont, the 74th Lieutenant Governor of Vermont, and an education administrator. <s> He served as the founding president of the Community College of Vermont, the founding president of California State University, Monterey Bay, and as assistant director general for education of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).

title: Eric Hill
complex: Eric Gordon Hill (7 September 1927 – 6 June 2014) was an English author and illustrator of children's picture books, best known for his puppy character named Spot. <s> His works have been widely praised for their contributions to child literacy. <s> He was born in Holloway, London, but was evacuated to the countryside during World War II. <s> He left school at 14 and first worked as an errand boy in an illustration studio where he was encouraged to draw cartoons and comic strips in his spare time. <s> Following National Service, he produced sketches for magazines, and later worked as a freelance designer and illustrator in advertising. <s> He was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2008 New Year Honours. <s> He died aged 86 on 6 June 2014, at his home in California. <s> He was married to second wife Gillian, and has a son named Christopher, and a daughter, Jane.
simple: Eric Gordon Hill OBE (7 September 1927 – 6 June 2014) was a British author and illustrator of children's picture books. <s> He was best known for his character Spot the Dog. <s> Hill was born in Holloway, London. <s> He was made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2008 New Year Honours. <s> Hill died after a short illness on 6 June 2014 in California, United States, aged 86. <s> He was married to Gillian and had two children, Christopher and Jane.

title: United States Secretary of Defense
complex: The secretary of defense (SecDef) is the leader and chief executive officer of the United States Department of Defense, the executive department of the Armed Forces of the U.S. <s> The secretary of defense's position of command and authority over the U.S. military is second only to that of the president. <s> This position corresponds to what is generally known as a defense minister in many other countries. <s> The secretary of defense is appointed by the president with the advice and consent of the Senate, and is by custom a member of the Cabinet and by law a member of the National Security Council. <s> Democratic Republican Political Independent / Unknown <s> The secretary of defense is sixth in the presidential line of succession, following the secretary of the treasury and preceding the attorney general.
simple: The United States Secretary of Defense (SECDEF) is the head of the U.S. Department of Defense (DoD). <s> Democratic Political Independent / Unknown Denotes an "Acting Secretary of Defense" <s> The Secretary of Defense is sixth in line to the United States presidential line of succession.

title: Abid Hamid Mahmud
complex: Lieutenant General Abid Al-Hamid Mahmud al-Tikriti ( ; ) (c. 1957 – June 7, 2012) was an Iraqi military officer under Saddam Hussein's deposed government. <s> On June 7, 2012, he was executed by hanging, according to a spokesman of the Iraqi Ministry of Justice.
simple: Abid Al-Hamid Mahmud al-Tikriti (born c. 1957; died June 7, 2012) was an Iraqi lieutenant general under Saddam Hussein's deposed regime, and he was Saddam's bodyguard. <s> He was executed on June 7, 2012.

title: Kutch district
complex: Kutch district (Kutchi and Gujarati: કચ્છ જિલ્લો; also spelled as Kachchh) is a district of Gujarat state in western India. <s> Covering an area of 45,674 km2, it is the largest district of India. <s> The population of Kutch is about 2,092,000.
simple: Kutch district (also spelled Kutch or Kachchh, ) is a formerly-independent district of Gujarat state in western Republic of India. <s> Covering an area of 45,612 km2, it is the largest district in the state of Gujarat and also the largest district of within India.

title: Al Quie
complex: Albert Harold "Al" Quie (born September 18, 1923) is an American politician who served as the 35th governor of Minnesota from January 4, 1979, to January 3, 1983. <s> Quie was born on his family's farm near Dennison, Minnesota, in Rice County. <s> Three of his grandparents were Norwegian immigrants.
simple: Albert Harold "Al" Quie (born September 18, 1923) is an American politician. <s> He was the 35th Governor of Minnesota, from January 4, 1979 to January 3, 1983. <s> Quie was born in Dennison, Minnesota.

title: Juan José Lara Ortiz
complex: Juan Jose Lara Ortiz (born November 30, 1965 in Sevilla) is a wheelchair basketball athlete from Spain. <s> He has a physical disability: he is 1 point wheelchair basketball player. <s> He played wheelchair basketball at the 1996 Summer Paralympics. <s> His team was third. <s> They beat the United States 66-60 to finish third.
simple: Juan Jose Lara Ortiz (born November 30, 1965 in Sevilla) is a wheelchair basketball athlete from Spain. <s> He has a physical disability: he is 1 point wheelchair basketball player. <s> He played wheelchair basketball at the 1996 Summer Paralympics. <s> His team was third. <s> They beat the United States 66-60 to finish third.

title: Bouvigny-Boyeffles
complex: Bouvigny-Boyeffles is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region in northern France.
simple: Bouvigny-Boyeffles is a commune.

title: Shaukat Tarin
complex: Shaukat Tarin ( ; born 1953) is a Pakistani banker and former Finance Minister of Pakistan from 2009 to 2010 in the Gillani cabinet. <s> Shaukat Tarin was appointed adviser to the finance ministry of Pakistan with a status of federal minister, on 7 October 2008.
simple: Shaukat Tarin or Shaukat Tareen (born 1953) is a senior Pakistani banker. <s> He was Pakistan's finance minister from 2009 to 2010.

title: Wikimania
complex: , the fifteenth Wikimedia conference, was held in Stockholm, Sweden from 14 to 18 August 2019, with an attendance of over 800. <s> Emna Mizouni was minted the Wikimedian of the year.
simple: , the fifteenth Wikimedia conference, will be held in Stockholm, Sweden.

title: Tsuyoshi Kunieda
complex: Tsuyoshi Kunieda (国枝 強 , Kunieda Tsuyoshi , born September 18, 1944) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Tsuyoshi Kunieda (国枝 強, Kunieda Tsuyoshi, born September 18, 1944) is a former Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Bread and salt
complex: Bread and salt is a welcome greeting ceremony in several Slavic and other European cultures and in Middle Eastern cultures. <s> The tradition, known by local Slavic names ( , Belarusian: "Хлеб і соль"; ; ; ; / "Hleb i so"; ; ; ; ; ) was also adopted by three non-Slavic nations — Lithuanians, Latvians (both Baltic) and Romanians (Latin) — all three of which are culturally and historically close to their Slavic neighbours ( . <s> It is also common in Albania , Armenia ( , "agh u hats"), the Jewish diaspora, and the Middle East. <s> This tradition has also been observed in spaceflight. <s> When important, respected, or admired guests arrive, they are presented with a loaf of bread (usually a korovai) placed on a "rushnyk" (embroidered ritual cloth). <s> A salt holder or a salt cellar is placed on top of the bread loaf or secured in a hole on the top of the loaf. <s> On official occasions, the "bread and salt" is usually presented by young women dressed in national costumes (e.g., sarafan and kokoshnik). <s> With the advent of the Soviet space program, this tradition has spread into space, where appropriately small packages of bread and salt are used nowadays.
simple: Bread and salt is a Slavic welcome greeting ceremony. <s> When this tradition is observed in spaceflight, small packages of bread and salt are used. <s> When important, respected, or admired guests arrive, they are given a loaf of bread placed on a "rushnik" (embroidered towel). <s> A salt holder or a salt cellar is placed on top of the bread loaf or secured in a hole on the top of the loaf. <s> In modern Russia, on official occasions, the "bread and salt" is presented by young women dressed in national costumes (e.g., sarafan and kokoshnik).

title: NCIS (TV series)
complex: NCIS is an American action police procedural television series, revolving around a fictional team of special agents from the Naval Criminal Investigative Service. <s> The concept and characters were initially introduced in two episodes of the CBS series "JAG" (season eight episodes 20 and 21: "Ice Queen" and "Meltdown"). <s> The show, a spin-off from "JAG", premiered on September 23, 2003, on CBS. <s> To date it has aired sixteen full seasons and has gone into broadcast syndication on the USA Network.
simple: NCIS (also called NCIS: Naval Criminal Investigative Service) is a crime-drama television series on CBS. <s> It is about a team of special agents from the Naval Criminal Investigative Service in Washington, D.C. <s> The series is a spin-off from "JAG" and has a spin-off called "".

title: Alban, Wisconsin
complex: Alban is a town in Portage County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> The population was 897 at the 2000 census. <s> The unincorporated community of Alban is located within the town.
simple: Alban is a town in Portage County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> 897 people lived there as of the year 2000.

title: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults
complex: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults is a two-hour live American television special that was broadcast in syndication on April 21, 1986. <s> Hosted by Geraldo Rivera, the special centered on the opening of a secret vault in the Lexington Hotel once owned by noted crime lord Al Capone, which turned out to be empty except for debris. <s> "The Mystery of Al Capone's Vaults" is available in its entirety on Geraldo's website.
simple: The Mystery of Al Capone's Vault was a one-time live American television special broadcast in April of 1986. <s> It was hosted by Geraldo Rivera. <s> The program was about the opening of a secret vault once owned by Al Capone.

title: Fredrik Fasting Torgersen
complex: Fredrik Ludvig Fasting Torgersen (1 October 1934 – 18 June 2015) was a Norwegian man who was convicted of murder in 1958 in a much-debated case, and released from prison in 1974. <s> Serving 16 years in prison before being released, he continuously claimed his innocence. <s> In 2013 Bjørg Njaa, a daughter of a judge in the 1958 trial said that her father was prejudiced against Torgersen even before being assigned to the trial. <s> In 2014 he was denied access to official recordings of then leader of the Norwegian Board of Forensic Medicine, Bjørnar Olaisen, answering to Criminal Cases Review Commission.
simple: Fredrik Ludvig Fasting Torgersen (1 October 1934 – 19 June 2015) was a Norwegian man who was convicted of murder in 1958. <s> Serving 16 years in prison before being released, he has claimed his innocence many times. <s> In 2013 Bjørg Njaa, a daughter of a judge in the 1958 trial said that her father was prejudiced against Torgersen even before being assigned to the trial. <s> In 2014 he was denied access to official recordings of then leader of the Norwegian Board of Forensic Medicine, Bjørnar Olaisen, answering to Criminal Cases Review Commission.

title: Tarsier
complex: Tarsiers are any haplorrhine primates of the family Tarsiidae, which is itself the lone extant family within the infraorder Tarsiiformes. <s> Although the group was once more widespread, all of its species living today are found in the islands of Southeast Asia. <s> Fossils of tarsiiform primates are found in Asia, Europe, and North America, with disputed fossils from Africa, but extant tarsiers are restricted to several Southeast Asian islands in Indonesia, Philippines, and Malaysia, The fossil record indicates that their dentition has not changed much, except in size, in the past 45 million years. <s> The genus "Tarsius" has a longer fossil record than any other primate genus, but the assignment of the Eocene and Miocene fossils to the genus is questionable. <s> Tarsiers are small animals with enormous eyes; each eyeball is approximately 16 mm in diameter and is as large as, or in some cases larger than, its entire brain. <s> The unique cranial anatomy of the tarsier results from the need to balance their large eyes and heavy head so they are able to wait silently for nutritious prey. <s> Tarsiers have a strong auditory sense, and their auditory cortex is distinct. <s> Tarsiers also have long hind limbs, owing mostly to the elongated tarsus bones of the feet, from which the animals get their name. <s> The combination of their elongated tarsi and fused tibiofibulae makes them morphologically specialized for vertical clinging and leaping. <s> The head and body range from 10 to 15 cm in length, but the hind limbs are about twice this long (including the feet), and they also have a slender tail from 20 to 25 cm long. <s> Their fingers are also elongated, with the third finger being about the same length as the upper arm. <s> Most of the digits have nails, but the second and third toes of the hind feet bear claws instead, which are used for grooming. <s> Tarsiers have soft, velvety fur, which is generally buff, beige, or ochre in color. <s> Unlike many nocturnal vertebrates, tarsiers lack a light-reflecting layer (tapetum lucidum) of the retina and have a fovea. <s> The tarsier's brain is different from that of other primates in terms of the arrangement of the connections between the two eyes and the lateral geniculate nucleus, which is the main region of the thalamus that receives visual information. <s> The sequence of cellular layers receiving information from the ipsilateral (same side of the head) and contralateral (opposite side of the head) eyes in the lateral geniculate nucleus distinguishes tarsiers from lemurs, lorises, and monkeys, which are all similar in this respect. <s> Some neuroscientists suggested that "this apparent difference distinguishes tarsiers from all other primates, reinforcing the view that they arose in an early, independent line of primate evolution." <s> Tarsiers are the only extant entirely carnivorous primates: they are primarily insectivorous, and catch insects by jumping at them. <s> They are also known to prey on birds, snakes, lizards, and bats. <s> Gestation takes about six months, and tarsiers give birth to single offspring. <s> Young tarsiers are born furred, and with open eyes, and are able to climb within a day of birth. <s> They reach sexual maturity by the end of their second year. <s> Sociality and mating system varies, with tarsiers from Sulawesi living in small family groups, while Philippine and western tarsiers are reported to sleep and forage alone. <s> Tarsiers tend to be extremely shy animals.
simple: They were once widespread, but now tarsiers live only on islands in south-east Asia. <s> Fossils are found in Asia, Europe, and North America, and some disputed fossils from Africa. <s> The fossil record shows that their teeth have not changed much, except in size, in the past 45 million years. <s> They also have the longest continuous fossil record of any primate. <s> They have large eyes. <s> Each is about 16 mm wide.They are very sensitive to touch, and weigh as much as their entire brain. <s> Unlike many nocturnal animals, tarsiers lack a light-reflecting area (tapetum lucidum) of the eye. <s> They also have a fovea, which is also not usual in nocturnal animals. <s> The tarsier's brain is different from other primates in one respect. <s> The sequence of cell layers in the lateral geniculate nucleus getting information from both eyes is different from the set-up in lemurs, lorises, and monkeys. <s> "This apparent difference distinguishes tarsiers from all other primates, and reinforces the view that they arose in an early, independent line of primate evolution". <s> Tarsiers are the only primates which are wholly carnivorous. <s> They mainly eat insects, but some are also known to eat birds and snakes. <s> Pregnancy takes about six months, which is a long time for such a small animal. <s> Tarsiers give birth to single offspring. <s> Tarsiers have incredibly good hearing.

title: National Assembly
complex: Perhaps the best known National Assembly was that established during the French Revolution in 1789, known as the "Assemblée nationale". <s> Consequently, the name is particularly common in Francophone countries.
simple: The best known National Assembly, and the first legislature to be known by this title, was established during the French Revolution in 1789, known as the "Assemblée Nationale".

title: Hélio Bicudo
complex: Hélio Pereira Bicudo (5 July 1922 – 31 July 2018) was a Brazilian jurist and politician. <s> In 1986, Bicudo was candidate to the Senate by the PT, placing 3rd, after the elected Mário Covas and Fernando Henrique Cardoso, both from the PMDB. <s> Hélio was Vice Mayor of São Paulo from 2001 to 2004, during the administration of Marta Suplicy. <s> In 2015, he filed in the Chamber of Deputies an impeachment request against president Dilma Rousseff. <s> Jurist Miguel Reale Júnior and pro-impeachment social movements decided to support Bicudo's request, which got the support of parliamentaries in the Congress and the majority of the civil society, whom organized a petition requesting the impeachment of the President of the Republic, while other parliamentaries and member of the Workers' Party positioned themselves in the defence of the defendant President. <s> Bicudo's request was, in the same year, accepted by the then President of the Chamber of Deputies Eduardo Cunha, after many meetings to instruct the claimants. <s> In 31 August 2016, the impeachment request was approved by the Federal Senate in a voting 61-20, removing Rousseff from the Presidency and officializing Michel Temer as President of Brazil. <s> Bicudo died on 31 July 2018.
simple: Hélio Pereira Bicudo (5 July 1922 – 31 July 2018) was a Brazilian jurist and politician. <s> In 1986, Bicudo was candidate to the Senate by the PT, placing 3rd, after the elected Mário Covas and Fernando Henrique Cardoso, both from the PMDB. <s> Hélio was Vice Mayor of São Paulo from 2001 to 2004, during the administration of Marta Suplicy. <s> In 2015, he filed in the Chamber of Deputies an impeachment request against president Dilma Rousseff. <s> Bicudo died on 31 July 2018 in São Paulo from a stroke, aged 96.

title: Sphere Fluidics
complex: Sphere Fluidics is a Cambridge, UK-based Life Sciences R&D company that specializes in biopharmaceutical discovery and development, cell therapy engineering, bioproduction and synthetic biology, and analysis and isolation. <s> The company is reported to own 25 patented products that include instruments, biochips, and specialist chemicals. <s> Sphere Fluidics was originally established in 2010, with two chemistry professors of Cambridge University, namely, Professor Chris Abell and Professor Wilhelm Huck, Dr. Frank F. Craig, an entrepreneur, and Dr. Maher Khaled, a Cambridge University Enterprise, as founders. <s> The total funds raised by Sphere Fluidics as of 2017, is reported to be, $13 million through various funding rounds and grants. <s> Cyto-Mine is a patented single cell analysis and characterisation system by Sphere Fluidics. <s> This technology is said to aid the development of biotherapeutics for treatment of cancer and inflammatory diseases and vaccine generation. <s> Cyto-Mine is said to be an integrated device which can automatically perform single cell analysis, sorting, imaging and dispensing into individual wells of microtiter plates in a single compact system. <s> 2015: UK's top 50 disruptive SMEs by Real Business
simple: Sphere Fluidics is an England-based Life Sciences Research and Development company specializing in developing novel tools for biopharmaceutical discovery and development, cell therapy engineering, analysis and isolation. <s> Sphere Fluidics operates in various markets including biopharmaceutical discovery and development, anti-microbial screening, synthetic biology and genome editing of single cells. <s> Sphere Fluidics Limited was originally established in 2010, by two chemistry professors of Cambridge University, namely, Professor Chris Abell and Professor Wilhelm Huck along with Dr. Frank F. Craig, an entrepreneur, and Dr. Maher Khaled, a Cambridge University Enterprise. <s> Sphere Fluidics has raised £11 million as of 2017, from investors namely, 24 Haymarket, Amadeus Capital Partners, Greenwood Way Capital, University of Cambridge Enterprise, University of Cambridge, Parkwalk Advisors, Providence Investment Company, London Business Angels, Envestors, Angels5K, Cambridge Angels, Q-Ventures and a Japanese corporate investor. <s> Cyto-Mine Technology is one of the patented products of Sphere Fluidics. <s> Cyto-Mine technology is the integrated device that is able to automatically perform single cell analysis, sorting, imaging and dispensing into individual wells of microtitre plates in a single compact system. <s> Sphere Fluidics has been named one of the UK's top 50 disruptive SMEs by Real Business in 2015.

title: Yvré-l'Évêque
complex: Yvré-l'Évêque is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Yvré-l'Évêque is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Shimon Peres
complex: Shimon Peres ( ; ] ; born Szymon Perski; 2 August 1923 – 28 September 2016) was an Israeli politician who served as the ninth President of Israel (2007–2014), the Prime Minister of Israel (twice), and the Interim Prime Minister, in the 1970s to the 1990s. <s> He was a member of twelve cabinets and represented five political parties in a political career spanning 70 years. <s> Peres was elected to the Knesset in November 1959 and except for a three-month-long hiatus in early 2006, was in office continuously until he was elected President in 2007. <s> At the time of his retirement in 2014, he was the world's oldest head of state and was considered the last link to Israel's founding generation. <s> On 13 June 2007, Peres was elected President of the State of Israel by the Knesset. <s> 58 of 120 members of the Knesset voted for him in the first round (whereas 38 voted for Reuven Rivlin, and 21 for Colette Avital). <s> His opponents then backed Peres in the second round and 86 members of the Knesset voted in his favor, while 23 objected. <s> He resigned from his role as a Member of the Knesset the same day, having been a member since November 1959 (except for a three-month period in early 2006), the longest serving in Israeli political history. <s> Peres was sworn in as President on 15 July 2007. <s> On 13 September 2016, Peres suffered a severe stroke and was hospitalized at Sheba Medical Center. <s> His condition was reported to be very serious, as he had suffered a massive brain hemorrhage and significant bleeding. <s> Two days later, he was reported as being in a serious but stable condition. <s> However, on 26 September, an examination found irreversible damage to his brainstem, indicating that it was not possible for him to recover, and the following day, his medical condition deteriorated significantly. <s> He died on 28 September at the age of 93.
simple: Shimon Peres (; born Szymon Perski; 2 August 1923 – 28 September 2016) was a Polish-born Israeli statesman. <s> He was the President of the State of Israel. <s> Peres served twice as the Prime Minister of Israel. <s> He also served as Interim Prime Minister twice. <s> Peres has been a member of 12 cabinets. <s> His political career spanned over 66 years. <s> On September 13, 2016, Peres, aged 93, suffered a severe stroke and was hospitalized in Ramat Gan, Israel. <s> He had suffered a massive brain hemorrhage. <s> Two days later, he was reported as being in a serious but stable condition. <s> However, on September 26, an examination found damage to his brainstem. <s> He died on September 28 of complications from the stroke.

title: South Magnetic Pole
complex: The South Magnetic Pole is the wandering point on Earth's Southern Hemisphere where the geomagnetic field lines are directed vertically upwards. <s> It should not be confused with the South Geomagnetic Pole described later. <s> The South Magnetic Pole is constantly shifting due to changes in Earth's magnetic field. <s> As of 2005 it was calculated to lie at , placing it off the coast of Antarctica, between Adélie Land and Wilkes Land. <s> In 2015 it lay at (est). <s> That point lies outside the Antarctic Circle. <s> Due to polar drift, the pole is moving northwest by about 10 to per year. <s> Its current distance from the actual Geographic South Pole is approximately 2860 km . <s> The nearest permanent science station is Dumont d'Urville Station. <s> Wilkes Land contains a large gravitational mass concentration.
simple: The South Magnetic Pole is the point on the southern hemisphere where the magnetic lines are directly pointing upward. <s> Because the magnetic field of the Earth changes, the exact location of ths pole does as well., placing it off the coast of Antarctica, between Adelie Land and Wilkes Land. <s> In 2015 it lies at (est). <s> That point lies outside the Antarctic Circle. <s> Due to polar drift, the pole is moving northwest by about 10 to 15 kilometers per year. <s> Its current distance from the actual Geographic South Pole is approximately 2860 km. <s> The nearest permanent science station is Dumont d'Urville Station. <s> Wilkes Land contains a large gravitational mass concentration.

title: Prince William County, Virginia
complex: Prince William County is located on the Potomac River in the Commonwealth of Virginia in the United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 402,002, on July 1, 2018, the population was estimated to be 468,011, making it Virginia's second-most populous county. <s> Its county seat is the independent city of Manassas.
simple: Prince William County is a county in Virginia. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 402,002.

title: Nathaniel Lyon
complex: Nathaniel Lyon (July 14, 1818 – August 10, 1861) was the first Union general to be killed in the American Civil War and is noted for his actions in the state of Missouri at the beginning of the conflict. <s> He fought in the Second Seminole War and the Mexican–American War, before being sent to the divided state of Kansas, where he developed strong pro-Union views. <s> In February 1861, Lyon was made commander of the Union arsenal in St. Louis, Missouri (another divided state), where Lyon forced the surrender of the pro-Confederate militia. <s> This caused a riot by civilians, with Lyon’s troops firing into the crowd (Camp Jackson Affair). <s> Lyon was promoted brigadier-general and given command of Union troops in Missouri. <s> He was killed at the Battle of Wilson’s Creek, while trying to rally his outnumbered soldiers. <s> However, Lyon’s efforts had prevented the State of Missouri from joining the Confederacy. <s> Lyon was born on a farm which was then in Ashford, Connecticut, now in the town of Eastford, the son of Amasa and Kezia Knowlton Lyon and brother of William H. Lyon. <s> As a boy he hated farming. <s> His relatives had fought in the American Revolutionary War and he was determined to follow in their footsteps. <s> In 1837 he applied to the United States Military Academy and graduated eleventh in his class of 52 cadets in 1841. <s> After being reassigned to Fort Riley, Kansas, Lyon became staunchly antislavery. <s> He did not support the radicalism of the abolitionists, and came to support the Republican Party while serving in the border wars known as "Bleeding Kansas." <s> In January 1861, he wrote about the secession crisis, "It is no longer useful to appeal to reason, but to the sword." <s> On May 10 Lyon directed the Missouri volunteer regiments and the 2nd U.S. Infantry to the camp, forcing its surrender. <s> Riots broke out in St. Louis as Lyon marched his prisoners through the city to the St. Louis Arsenal. <s> The event provoked the Camp Jackson Affair of May 10, 1861, in which Lyons' troops opened fire on a crowd of civilians injuring at least 75 and killing 28. <s> Two federals and three militia were also killed and others were wounded. <s> The source of the first shot is disputed, some witnesses claiming it was a drunken rioter, others claiming it was unprovoked. <s> Lyon was nonetheless promoted to brigadier general May 17. <s> and given command over the Union troops in Missouri May 31, 1861 as commander of the Department of the West. <s> The governor fled first to the capitol at Jefferson City (ordering the tracks destroyed behind him), and then retreated with the State Guard to Boonville. <s> Lyon moved up the Missouri River by steamer and occupied Jefferson City without a fight on June 13. <s> Lyon continued the pursuit and on June 17 he defeated a portion of the State Guard at the Battle of Boonville. <s> The governor, his administration, and the Guard retreated to the southwest. <s> Lyon was subsequently supported by the reconvened Missouri State Convention which reconvened on July 22, 1861, declared the office of Governor and other state officials "vacant", and appointed a Unionist provisional state government under former Missouri Chief Justice Hamilton Gamble. <s> Lyon assumed command of the Army of the West on July 2. <s> Lyon reinforced his army before moving southwest in pursuit of Jackson, Price and the State Guard. <s> In the confused aftermath of the Union retreat from Wilson's Creek, Lyon's body was mistakenly left behind on the battlefield and discovered by Confederate forces. <s> It was briefly buried on a Union soldier's farm outside Springfield until it could be returned to Lyon's relatives.
simple: Nathaniel Lyon (July 14, 1818 – August 10, 1861) was the first Union general to be killed in the American Civil War. <s> Lyon fought in the Second Seminole War in Florida and in the Mexican-American War. <s> He died while leading his men at the Battle of Wilson's Creek. <s> Lyon was killed while trying to rally his outnumbered soldiers. <s> However, Lyon’s efforts prevented the State of Missouri from joining the Confederacy. <s> Lyon was born on July 14, 1818, in Ashford, Connecticut. <s> He was the seventh out of nine children born to Amasa and Kezia Knowlton Lyon. <s> Lyon hated farming and wanted to be like his ancestors who fought in the American Revolutionary War. <s> On July 1, 1837, Lyon entered the United States Military Academy at West Point. <s> He graduated in 1841, 11th out of a class of 52. <s> Lyon was next sent to Fort Riley in Kansas. <s> On May 10, 1861, Lyon and his troops surrounded the pro-Confederate Missouri militia and forced them to surrender. <s> While marching his captured prisoners through St. Louis, pro-Confederate citizens began to riot. <s> The incident was called the Camp Jackson Affair. <s> On May 17, Lyon was promoted to brigadier general. <s> He was given command of the Union Army of the West. <s> Lyon moved his army to go after the rebels. <s> When the Union army retreated from Wilson's Creek, Lyon's body was mistakenly left behind on the battlefield.

title: Jenna Dewan
complex: Jenna Lee Dewan ( ; born December 3, 1980) is an American actress and dancer. <s> She started her career as a backup dancer for Janet Jackson, and later worked with artists including Pink, Missy Elliott, and Christina Aguilera. <s> She is known for her role as Nora Clark in the 2006 film "Step Up". <s> She has also starred on the short-lived NBC series "The Playboy Club" and had a recurring role on the FX series "". <s> She portrayed Freya Beauchamp on the Lifetime series "Witches of East End" and played Lucy Lane in The CW series "Supergirl". <s> Dewan hosted the NBC reality competition television series "World of Dance".
simple: Jenna Lee Dewan Tatum (born December 3, 1980) is an American actress and dancer. <s> She began her career as a backup dancer for Janet Jackson. <s> Later she worked with artists including Pink, Missy Elliott, and Christina Aguilera. <s> She is known for her role as Nora in the 2006 film "Step Up" for which she won a Teen Choice Award. <s> She has also starred on the short-lived NBC series "The Playboy Club". <s> Tatum had a recurring role on the FX series "". <s> She was Freya Beauchamp on the Lifetime series "Witches of East End".

title: Anne Marie d'Orléans
complex: Anne Marie d'Orléans (27 August 1669 – 26 August 1728) was the first Queen consort of Sardinia by marriage to Victor Amadeus II of Savoy. <s> She served as regent of Savoy during the absence of her spouse in 1686 and during the War of the Spanish Succession. <s> She is also an important figure in British history (see Jacobite Succession below). <s> She was the daughter of Philippe I, Duke of Orléans, younger brother of Louis XIV, and Henrietta of England, the youngest daughter of Charles I of England. <s> Her mother died at the "Château de Saint-Cloud" ten months after Anne Marie's birth. <s> A year later, her father married 19-year-old Elizabeth Charlotte of the Palatinate, who became very close to her stepdaughters. <s> Her half-brother Philippe II, Duke of Orléans, the future regent of France, was born of her father's second marriage. <s> Her stepmother later described her as "one of the most amiable and virtuous of women". <s> The proxy marriage of Anne Marie and Víctor Amadeus took place at Versailles on 10 April 1684, the day after the signature of the marriage contract. <s> Her husband-to-be was represented by her cousin, Louis Auguste, Duke of Maine. <s> Louis XIV gave her a dowry of 900,000 "livres". <s> The Duke of Orléans accompanied his daughter as far as Juvisy-sur-Orge (18 kilometers south of Paris), and the comtesse de Lillebonne accompanied her all the way to Savoy. <s> She met her husband Victor at Chambéry on 6 May, the nuptials being performed at the castle by the Archbishop of Grenoble. <s> Two days later, the newlyweds made their "Joyous Entry" into Turin. <s> This marriage was arranged with the assistance of the maréchal de Tessé and of Jeanne Baptiste d'Albert de Luynes, comtesse de Verrué, who was Victor's mistress from 1689 till 1700. <s> Her husband had two children with Jeanne. <s> Nonetheless, when he fell ill with smallpox, Anne Marie nursed him until his recovery. <s> Despite his marriage ties to France, Victor Amadeus joined the anti-French side in the War of the Spanish Succession. <s> Anne Marie was appointed by him to serve as regent of Savoy during his absence in the war, a task she handled with maturity and judgement. <s> In 1706, Turin was besieged by French forces under the command of Anne Marie's half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, and Spanish forces of her cousin and son-in-law Philip V. <s> She and her sons Victor Amadeus and Carlo Emanuele were forced to flee to Genoa. <s> When the war was ended in 1713 by the Treaty of Utrecht, Victor Amadeus received the Kingdom of Sicily, formerly a Spanish possession. <s> Anne Marie's stepmother wrote: "I shall neither gain nor lose by the peace, but one thing I shall enjoy is to see our Duchess of Savoy become a queen, because I love her as though she were my own child ..." When Victor Amadeus left for his coronation in Sicily, he had originally planned to leave Anne Marie behind to function as regent in his absence, but as he feared that she would let herself be directed by his mother because of her loyalty to her, he changed his mind and took her along with him instead. <s> Anne Marie was crowned with him in Sicily. <s> At the death of her eldest son in 1715, both she and Victor Amadeus fell into severe depression and left the capital to mourn, leaving Marie Jeanne to handle their official duties. <s> Victor Amadeus was forced to exchange Sicily for the less important domain of Sardinia in 1720, but retained the title of King. <s> As the Savoyard consort, Anne-Marie had the use of the Royal Palace of Turin, the vast Palazzina di caccia di Stupinigi outside the capital, and the Vigna di Madama Reale. <s> Queen Anne Marie died of heart failure at her villa on 26 August 1728, the day before her 59th birthday. <s> She is buried at the Basilica of Superga in Turin, where all her children, except Marie-Adélaïde and Maria Luisa, are also buried. <s> From 1714 to 1720, Anne Marie d'Orléans was the heiress presumptive to the Jacobite claim to the thrones of England, Scotland, and Ireland. <s> These claims were held at the time by James Francis Edward Stuart ("the Old Pretender", son of James II). <s> Anne Marie became heiress presumptive with the death of James' daughter Queen Anne in 1714. <s> She was displaced as heir by the birth of the Old Pretender's son, Charles Edward Stuart ("Bonnie Prince Charlie"), on 31 December 1720. <s> Charles Edward and his brother Henry, Cardinal Stuart, both died without legitimate issue, so the descendants of Anne Marie d'Orléans inherited the Jacobite claim, i.e. they would have inherited the British crown had it not been for the Act of Settlement, which excluded the claims of the Catholic Stuarts and d'Orléans' and settled the throne on the nearest Protestant relatives, the Hanoverians.
simple: Anne Marie d'Orléans (27 August 1669 - 26 August 1728) was a niece of Louis XIV and was the wife of Victor Amadeus II of Sardinia. <s> She was born at the Château de Saint-Cloud. <s> Her mother died when she was ten months old. <s> A year later, her father remarried Elizabeth Charlotte of the Palatinate. <s> Her half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, the future Regent of France. <s> Her stepmother described her as "one of the most amiable and virtuous of women". <s> Anne Marie d'Orléans' proxy marriage to Víctor Amadeus II took place at Versailles on 10 April 1684. <s> Louis XIV gave her a dowry of 900,000 "livres". <s> She met her husband at Chambéry the following 6 May which were followed by another wedding ceremony. <s> Her husband had two further children with Jeanne Baptiste d'Albert de Luynes, his mistress from 1689 till 1700. <s> Nonetheless, when he fell ill with smallpox, she nursed him until his recovery. <s> In 1706, during the siege of Turin by French forces under the command of her half-brother Philippe d'Orléans, and Spanish forces from her cousin Philip V of Spain, she and her sons, Victor Amadeus and Carlo Emanuele, were forced to flee the city. <s> As a result of his aid in the War of the Spanish Succession Victor Amadeus II was made King of Sicily in 1713 under the Treaty of Utrecht which ended the war. <s> However Victor Amadeus II was forced to exchange Sicily for the less important kingdom of Sardinia in 1720. <s> As queen, Anne Marie used the Royal Palace of Turin as well as the Villa della Regina which was her own property. <s> Queen Anne Marie died of heart failure at her villa on 26 August 1728, the day before her 59th birthday. <s> She is today buried at the Basilica of Superga in Turin being moved there in 1786 by her son Victor Amadeus III. <s> From 1714 to 1720, Anne Marie d'Orléans was the heiress presumptive to the Jacobite claim to the thrones of England, Scotland, and Ireland. <s> These claims were held at the time by James Francis Edward Stuart (son of James II) upon the death of his half-sister, Queen Anne. <s> Anne Marie was displaced as his heir by the birth of the Old Pretender's son, Charles Edward Stuart ("Bonnie Prince Charlie") in December 1720.

title: Rostrevor
complex: Rostrevor is a village and townland in County Down, Northern Ireland. <s> It lies at the foot of Slieve Martin on the coast of Carlingford Lough, near Warrenpoint. <s> The Kilbroney River flows through the village and Rostrevor Forest is nearby. <s> It is within Newry, Mourne and Down District. <s> Rostrevor had a population of 2,433 in the 2001 Census.
simple: Rostrevor (in Irish: "Ros Treabhair", i.e. Trevor’s Wood, also "Caislean Ruairi", i.e. Rory's Castle) is a village in County Down, Northern Ireland. <s> It is on Carlingford Lough and the hill of Slieve Martin, at the base of the Mourne Mountains and on the Kilbroney River. <s> It is in the Newry and Mourne District Council area. <s> It had a population of 2,444 in the 2001 Census.

title: Vibble
complex: Vibble is a locality in Västerhejde on the Swedish island of Gotland. <s> Sweden with 1,300 inhabitants in 2010. <s> Situated 3 km south of Visby, it is sometimes regarded as a suburb to the town of Visby.
simple: Vibble is a locality in Gotland Municipality in Gotland County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 1,286 people lived there.

title: Metropolitan-Vickers
complex: Metropolitan-Vickers, Metrovick, or Metrovicks, was a British heavy electrical engineering company of the early-to-mid 20th century formerly known as British Westinghouse. <s> Highly diversified, they were particularly well known for their industrial electrical equipment such as generators, steam turbines, switchgear, transformers, electronics and railway traction equipment. <s> Metrovick holds a place in history as the builders of the first commercial transistor computer, the Metrovick 950, and the first British axial-flow jet engine, the Metropolitan-Vickers F.2. <s> Their factory in Trafford Park, Manchester, was for most of the 20th century one of the biggest and most important heavy engineering facilities in Britain and the world.
simple: Metropolitan-Vickers, Metrovick, or Metrovicks, was a British heavy electrical engineering company of the early-to-mid 20th century formerly known as British Westinghouse. <s> Highly diversified, they were particularly well known for their industrial electrical equipment such as generators, steam turbines, switchgear, transformers, electronics and railway traction equipment. <s> Metrovick holds a place in history as the builders of the first commercial transistor computer, the Metrovick 950, and the first British axial-flow jet engine, the Metrovick F.2. <s> Their factory in Trafford Park, Manchester, was for most of the 20th century one of the biggest and most important heavy engineering facilities in Britain and the world.

title: Julio Vallejo Ruiloba
complex: Julio Vallejo Ruiloba (7 May 1945 – 14 January 2019) was a Spanish psychiatrist, medical doctor, Chairman of the Psychiatry Department at the Universitat de Barcelona, ex-President of the Spanish Psychiatry Society, and Academician of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Catalonia. <s> He wrote 56 books about psychiatry and more than 350 scientific papers.
simple: Julio Vallejo-Ruiloba (7 May 1945 – 14 January 2019) was a Spanish psychiatrist. <s> He was Chairman of the Psychiatry Departament at the University of Barcelona. <s> He was President of the Spanish Psychiatry Society, and Academician of the Royal Academy of Medicine of Catalonia. <s> Vallejo Ruiloba died on 14 January 2019 from liver cancer in Barcelona, aged 73. <s> He wrote 56 books about psychiatry and more than 350 scientific papers talking about depression.

title: Choapa Province
complex: Choapa Province is one of the provinces making up the Coquimbo Region of Chile. <s> It has an area of 10,079.8 km2 and a population of 81,681. <s> The capital of the province is the town of Illapel. <s> The current governor is Gisella Mateluna Gambo. <s> According to the 2002 census by the National Statistics Institute ("INE"), the province spans an area of 10131.6 sqkm and had a population of 81,681 inhabitants (41,578 men and 40,103 women), giving it a population density of 8.1 PD/sqkm . <s> Between the 1992 and 2002 censuses, the population grew by 4.6% (3,603 persons).
simple: Choapa Province is one of three provinces of the Chilean region of Coquimbo Region (IV). <s> Its capital is the city of Illapel <s> s of 2002 (last national census), there were 81,681 people living in the province, giving it a population density of 8.062004027004619 /km2 inhabitants/km2.

title: Thalía
complex: Ariadna Thalía Sodi Miranda (] ; born 26 August 1971) is a Mexican singer, songwriter, producer, actress and entrepreneur. <s> She is considered one of the most successful and influential Mexican artists worldwide. <s> Apart from her native Spanish, Thalía has also sung in English, French, Portuguese and Tagalog. <s> She is sometimes referred to as the "Queen of Latin Pop" by international media because of her renown within the Latin pop music scene for the last three decades. <s> She has sold over 25 million records worldwide. <s> She has received numerous accolades, including five "Billboard" Latin Music Awards (from 17 nominations), several Premios Juventud and Lo Nuestro Awards, as well as seven Latin Grammy Award nominations. <s> She has collaborated with renowned artists, such as Tony Bennett, Michael Bublé, Robbie Williams, Marc Anthony, Laura Pausini, Romeo Santos and Carlos Vives as well as with younger popular artists like Maluma, Prince Royce, Becky G, Natti Natasha, Gente de Zona and Lali.
simple: Ariadna Thalía Sodi Miranda (born August 26, 1971), known as Thalía, is a Mexican singer, songwriter and actress. <s> She has sung in Spanish, English, French, Portuguese and Tagalog. <s> She has sold over 25 million albums worldwide. <s> Thalia has been nominated for various Latin Grammy, Latin Billboard and many other awards.

title: Parole
complex: Parole is the early release of a prisoner who agrees to abide by certain conditions, originating from the French "parole" ("voice, spoken words" but also "promise"). <s> The term became associated during the Middle Ages with the release of prisoners who gave their word.
simple: Parole is the release of a prisoner before the end of his or her original sentence. <s> This is based on the prisoner accepting certain conditions.

title: Sigfrid Mattsson
complex: Sigfrid Mattsson, born 19 September 1917, dead 27 August 2009, was a Swedish cross-country skier. <s> Representing Skarpnäcks IF in club competitions, he won Vasaloppet in 1952.
simple: Sigfrid Mattsson, born 19 September 1917, dead 27 August 2009, was a Swedish cross-country skier. <s> He competed for Skarpnäcks IF in club competitions. <s> In 1952, he won the Vasaloppet event.

title: Charles Wesley Turnbull
complex: Charles Wesley Turnbull (born February 5, 1935), was the sixth elected Governor of the U.S. Virgin Islands. <s> During his tenure as governor, Turnbull served as a member of the National Governors Association, the Southern Governors' Association, and the Democratic Governors Association.
simple: Charles Wesley Turnbull (born February 5, 1935), was the 27th Governor of the U.S. Virgin Islands serving from 1999 through 2007. <s> During his tenure as governor, Turnbull served as a member of the National Governors Association, the Southern Governors' Association, and the Democratic Governors Association.

title: Data storage
complex: Data storage is the recording (storing) of information (data) in a storage medium. <s> DNA and RNA, handwriting, phonographic recording, magnetic tape, and optical discs are all examples of storage media. <s> Recording is accomplished by virtually any form of energy. <s> Electronic data storage requires electrical power to store and retrieve data. <s> A recording medium is a physical material that holds information. <s> Newly created information is distributed and can be stored in four storage media–print, film, magnetic, and optical–and seen or heard in four information flows–telephone, radio and TV, and the Internet as well as being observed directly. <s> Digital information is stored on electronic media in many different recording formats. <s> With electronic media, the data and the recording media are sometimes referred to as "software" despite the more common use of the word to describe computer software. <s> With (traditional art) static media, art materials such as crayons may be considered both equipment and medium as the wax, charcoal or chalk material from the equipment becomes part of the surface of the medium.
simple: A data storage device is a device for recording (storing) information (data). <s> Recording can be done using virtually any form of energy. <s> "Electronic data storage" is storage which requires electricity to store and get back that data. <s> A recording medium is a physical material that holds data expressed in any of the existing recording formats. <s> Most often the term is used with computers. <s> With electronic media, the data and the recording medium is sometimes referred to as "software" despite the more common use of the word to describe computer software.

title: Tetuin
complex: Tetuin is a flavone, a type of flavonoid. <s> It is the 6-O-glucoside of baicalein. <s> It can be isolated from the seeds of "Oroxylum indicum", the Indian trumpetflower, known as टेटु "tetu" in Marathi.

title: Candidatus
complex: In prokaryote nomenclature, Candidatus (Latin for candidate of Roman office, named after the white gown worn by Roman senators) is a component of the taxonomic name for a bacterium or other prokaryote, that cannot be maintained in a microbiological culture collection. <s> It is an interim taxonomic status for yet-to-be-cultured microorganisms. <s> An example would be ""Candidatus" Phytoplasma allocasuarinae". <s> This can be abbreviated to ""Ca." <s> Candidatus status may be used when a species or genus is well characterized but yet-uncultured. <s> With today's technology much information is obtained by 16S ribosomal RNA or even near-complete genomes with modern metagenomics techniques. <s> For valid publication of a species, bacteria must be isolated, cultured, described, and deposited in a bacteriology culture collection. <s> However, some bacteria require special culture conditions and cannot be maintained in such collections. <s> These include obligately intracellular pathogens and endosymbionts, insect symbionts, and populations from oceans or sludge. <s> In 1994, Murray and Schleifer published a taxonomic note in which they recommended that the new category of indefinite rank ("Candidatus") be established for certain putative taxa that could not be described in sufficient detail to warrant establishment of a new taxon. <s> It was also recommended that a "Candidatus" list should be established in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology - IJSB (now International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology).
simple: Candidatus is a term in the taxonomy (scientific classification) of bacteria. <s> An example would be ""Candidatus" Phytoplasma allocasuarinae". <s> Candidatus status may be used when a species or genus is well studied but cannot be cultured. <s> Nowadays much information is got by 16S ribosomal RNA sequence analysis. <s> For correct publication of a species, bacteria must be isolated, cultured, described, and deposited in a bacteriology culture collection. <s> However, some bacteria require special tissue culture conditions and cannot be maintained in Bacteriology Culture Collections. <s> These include obligately intracellular pathogens and endosymbionts, insect symbionts, and populations from oceans or sludge. <s> In 1994, Murray and Schleifer published a taxonomic note. <s> They recommended that the new category of indefinite rank (Candidatus) be established for certain putative taxa that could not be described in sufficient detail to warrant establishment of a new taxon. <s> It was also recommended that a Candidatus list should be established in the "International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology".

title: Fyodor Cherenkov
complex: Fyodor Fyodorovich Cherenkov (25 July 1959, Moscow – 4 October 2014, Moscow) was a Soviet and Russian football midfielder who played for Spartak Moscow (1977–90 and 1991–94) and Red Star Football Club (1990–91). <s> Cherenkov made 34 appearances for the Soviet Union national football team, scoring 12 goals. <s> Although widely regarded by Spartak's fans as team's best player ever, he was always dropped by the national team on the eve of several major tournaments, including two World Cups and a European Championship.

title: Clay County, Georgia
complex: Clay County is a county located in the U.S. state of Georgia. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 3,183, making it the fifth-least populous county in Georgia. <s> The county seat is Fort Gaines.
simple: Clay County is a county Georgia. <s> Its county seat is Fort Gaines.
